<HEADLINE>
CITY COUNCIL HEARS FROM THE CITIZENS ABOUT WTO POLICE ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HEATH FOSTER  
 and KERY MURAKAMI  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Hundreds of people packed the downtown library
Wednesday night to vent anger, frustration _ and to shed tears _ a
week after Seattle police launched their last round of tear-gas at
demonstrators opposed to World Trade Organization policies.
</P>
<P>
   In an echo of the poor planning that marked the city's response
to last week's events, the City Council failed to anticipate the
turnout. More than 400 people showed up, but only 150 could get
into the meeting room. Several hundred stood outside in the rain,
listening to testimony over loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the overflow, the Council will hold another hearing
Tuesday in a much larger room at the Seattle Center.
</P>
<P>
   Not in attendance Wednesday night was Mayor Paul Schell, who has
said he is well aware the police response to the demonstrations was
deeply disappointing in a laid-back city that prides itself on its
history of peaceful protests. Damage from the demonstrations has
been estimated at $3 million, with $12 million to $22 million in
lost sales. More than 500 people were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Council President Sue Donaldson said she discouraged Schell from
attending the public meeting, saying the Council wanted to review
the events independently.
</P>
<P>
   Each comment Wednesday night added a new wrinkle to the heavy
criticism the Schell administration and Police Department face. And
many of the points raised will be examined the Council, mayor's
office, and the American Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Richard Conlin and others said it's clear that last
week's incidents remain a major concern. He noted that council
members have received 6,000 e-mail complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's open-microphone hearing was intended as a way
to begin a healing process, and council members said it was a
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not the traditional activists that we see. It's
broader than that,'' said Councilman Nick Licata.
</P>
<P>
   In small ways, things seemed back to normal in the city that
values process in public debate. Protesters on Wednesday night
weren't controlled by pepper spray or tear gas, but by City Clerk
Theresa Dunbar's small sign advising speakers of a three-minute
limit.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council first heard from those involved in planning the
protests.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Dolan, deputy director of Public Citizen's Global Trade
Watch Program, an environmental, agricultural and faith-based
group, said he wanted to dispel suggestions that police were misled
by protest organizers who promised peaceful actions.
</P>
<P>
   He said Ruckus Society organizers made clear their goal was to
shut down the WTO, and said only a naive police department would
think that meant using only ``clever signs and powerful chants,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Seattle Police Department was not sucker-punched,'' he
insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Hilary McQuie, of the Direct Action Network, which helped
organize peaceful protests, said that Assistant Police Chief Ed
Joiner assured her before the WTO meeting that he understood Indian
independence leader Mahatma Ghandi's non-violent protest tactics
and promised to wait until television cameras arrived before
ordering mass arrests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead, the police shot tear gas before there was any
property destruction,'' McQuie said.
</P>
<P>
   Joiner has said tear gas was fired to try to open a corridor for
WTO delegates and others trying to reach the Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   After gas was used, McQuie said, Asssistant Chief Harv Ferguson
said he considered linking of arms to block a street was a violent
and illegal tactic _ contradicting what Joiner had said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It showed a complete lack of understanding of Ghandian
principles,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all speakers were opposed to police. Katherine
Coatsmilanoski said tactics of protesters also must be examined.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really what I expected,'' she said of the hearing. ``A
group whine on the side of the protesters. I saw protesters
spitting on the police ... and screaming obscenities at them. Maybe
it was non-violent, but if you saw that happening to a son or
daughter or a brother or sister you would have wanted to go down
there and kick a protester's ass.''
</P>
<P>
   D.Jennifer Whitney, a massage therapist who organized medical
workers to treat injured protesters, said reports that there were
no serious injuries were untrue. She said her volunteers pulled
glass out of the eye of a protester whose gas mask had been
shattered by a rubber bullet, witnessed dozens of serious asthma
attacks, and watched a man with multiple sclerosis in a wheelchair
shot with tear gas and rubber bullets.
</P>
<P>
   During last week's demonstrations, area hospitals reported only
a few dozen injuries, most of them from tear gas and rubber
pellets. No deaths were reported.
</P>
<P>
   She and others also questioned if military-grade tear gas, used
when police supplies ran out, had more serious and perhaps
neurological side effects. Like others at the meetings, she
demanded police give a complete accounting of the chemical agents
used.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Judd, executive secretary of the King County Labor
Council/AFL-CIO said that he considers police to be workers, and is
torn about criticizing their response. But he said police ``seemed
to be out of control'' during the protests. And like dozens of
others at the meeting, he said he couldn't understand why city
officials and police failed to anticipate events ``when we told
them this was going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Schulman, a member of the Seattle Commission on Sexual
Minorities, said, ``my friends were tear-gassed on the streets, in
restaurants and in their own apartments'' during protests in the
Capitol Hill neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Schulman said he was sitting in a Capitol Hill restaurant when
the tear-gassing started and, ``The owner locked all the doors and
turned off the lights, presumably because he was afraid the police
were going to attack the restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Cato said her husband was trying to get home when he was
stopped by police while walking through Pike Place Market.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Can I get by? I'm going home.' He got about 10 feet
and he had tear gas dropped at his feet,'' she said. ``I had to go
pick up a very angry and agitated man. We're both incredulous about
why that happened. It's bad enough that happened to peaceful
protesters, but for that to happen to someone trying to get home is
just disgusting.''
</P>
<P>
   The most raucus cheers came when speakers called for the
resignations of Schell and City Attorney Mark Sidran, who has been
criticized for backing strict ``civility laws'' governing public
conduct, but who was not involved in WTO protest management.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Norm Stamper was in command of the police, and has
said he will retire in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mayor Schell shouldn't let Stamper be his fall guy, because
he's just as responsible,'' said a woman who identified herself
only as Joyce.
</P>
<P>
   While dozens of speakers raised specific complaints Wednesday
night, many also spoke of a broader sense of loss and a feeling
that democracy itself had suffered.
</P>
<P>
   Some merchants described how they were suddenly confronted with
hordes of people banging on their windows and threatening
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost over $10,000 in business,'' said Dan Hogan of his
downtown establishment. ``Even worse, we lost faith in our city
officials.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmund Kamai summed up the testimony of many, saying ``In a real
sense, an honest innocence was stripped from our city _ not by
protesters, not by police in riot gear, not by clouds of tear gas _
but by the failure of people in whom we, the citizens of this city,
place our trust and confidence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
