u s BC-SKI-DONATE-EQUIPMENT-     12-09 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-DONATE-EQUIPMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD SKIING GEAR RECEIVES A SECOND LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is that time of year when new equipment begins showing up on
winter slopes. But what happens to all the old gear: the snowboards
with last year's nicks, the skis that look like narrow lumber next
to the new curved shapes and the poles so heavy they feel like
hammers?
</P>
<P>
   Some people get rid of them _ for a good cause.
</P>
<P>
   SnowSports Industries America, a national trade group, has
organized a program in which ski shops accept used equipment as a
charitable donation. The gear is then shipped to three collection
centers for subsequent distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Carroll, a hard-goods buyer at Paragon, a sporting goods
store in New York City, said: ``It costs us some money to implement
the program in the first place. But it gives us a chance to try and
do a good deed, and also to try and drive customers into the
store.''
</P>
<P>
   The Donate-A-Ski/Board program began Oct. 16 with a kickoff by
Billy Kidd, the 1964 Olympic ski champion who is director of skiing
at Steamboat Springs, Colo. The program ends Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Special Olympics, an organization Kidd often
works with, charitable organizations that work with disadvantaged
youths will receive the used gear.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Mattie, the donations program director, said recently
that more than 1,000 skis and 215 snowboards have be- en collected
since the October kickoff. Poles, boots and other ski accessories
are also being accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we get some awful gear as well as gear that's
hardly been used,'' Mattie said. ``But we get the bad stuff out of
the pipeline, which is probably good for safety purposes. Some of
the gear we can use for parts to fix other equipment. The rest of
it we recycle, and some goes in the trash.''
</P>
<P>
   People who drop off equipment at a participating ski shop
receive a receipt _ the donations are tax deductible _ based on the
type and age of the gear they leave.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Curley, owner of Inverness, a ski shop in Waitsfield, Vt.,
said he collected about 175 pairs of skis and 200 pairs of boots so
far.
</P>
<P>
   Avery Harper of the chain called Peter Glenn of Vermont, said
people seem grateful to have a place to pass off their old
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The resale value of skis is worse than a car,'' Harper, who
runs a Vermont store in Atlanta, said. ``So people sit on it, but
the equipment does absolutely no one any good in the basement.''
</P>
<P>
   Tina Vallin, co-owner of the Scandinavian Ski &AMP; Sports Shop in
New York, agreed. Customers in the city complain about a lack of
storage. ``They don't know what to do with their old equipment,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   At least one ski shop owner has gleaned an unexpected benefit
from the donation program. Bob Bergstrom, owner of Boarderline and
Sports Ltd., two stores in Woodland Hills, Calif., said one
customer brought in a vintage pair of Head skis, one of the first
companies in the 1950s to begin using steel in making skis.
</P>
<P>
   ``These skis have a lot of nostalgia, so we have them on
display,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For information on which ski and board shops participate in the
program, check www.snowlink.com on the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
