<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-BUCKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS TOP BUCKS, 107-90 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ With just over seven minutes left in
Wednesday night's game, the New Jersey Nets' Stephon Marbury drove
the ball along the left side of the baseline and challenged three
Milwaukee Bucks to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   The players went airborne and Marbury, the shortest of the
bunch, flew underneath the rim while cradling the ball. As the
defenders began to descend, Marbury released a reverse layup that
bounced off the backboard and then through the hoop for a dazzling
basket.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of play that forces opposing coaches to call
timeout, and Milwaukee's George Karl, his club down by 15 points
and all but done, did just that. While the Nets ran to their bench,
Keith Van Horn grabbed Marbury from behind in a jubilant bearhug
and screamed praise into his ear. As Marbury smiled, it seemed as
if all the trials and turmoil that engulfed this franchise over the
first month of the season had been forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, losers and pouters through the bulk of their first 17
games, look different now. On Wednesday night, they rolled, 107-90,
over a tired but talented Bucks team to win their second straight
game for the first time this season. The victory improved their
record to a still horrific 4-15, but their collective attitude is
no longer so sullen.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that comes about when you start winning,'' Van Horn said
of the Nets' camaraderie and exuberance. ``There's no dislike in
this locker room. I think it was just the fact that we were losing,
and losing is tough. Everyone's frustrated and it's hard to have a
smile on your face and have a great conversation with someone when
you're losing. Now that we're winning and things are going good and
people are starting to play good, the whole mentality has
completely shifted.''
</P>
<P>
   The mind-sets are not the only things that have changed for the
Nets. For the second time in two games _ they played exceptionally
well in upsetting the powerful Sacramento Kings, 109-95, on Monday
_ the Nets exhibited great ball movement, chemistry, mental
toughness, defense and shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury, playing his best ball of the season, was superb,
recording 25 points, 14 assists, 3 steals and only 1 turnover while
making 10 of 16 shots from the floor. He shattered the homecoming
plans of the former Net Sam Cassell, who two seasons ago helped
lead the Nets to one of their finest seasons. Cassell brought
averages of 19 points and 9 assists, but had only 10 points and 5
assists with 6 turnovers on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Cassell's troubles began right away as he committed two
turnovers in the first two minutes. Following its point guard's
lead, Milwaukee, playing its fourth game in five nights, committed
five turnovers in its first nine possessions. The Bucks also missed
their first eight shots, allowing the Nets to build a 16-2 lead in
under six minutes.
</P>
<P>
   With Marbury playing the playmaker's role to perfection, Kerry
Kittles putting all of his varied abilities on display, and Van
Horn finishing strongly around the rim, the Nets pushed the lead to
22 points in the second quarter. The Bucks surged at the end of the
third, pulling within 8 points entering the final period, but
Marbury took over.
</P>
<P>
   Driving to the basket almost exclusively, the Nets' point guard
scored 6 points and passed for 2 assists in a 13-6 run that ended
with his splendid reverse layup. Van Horn, shooting 7 for 13 in
making more than half of his shots for the second straight game,
followed Marbury with 20 points. In his finest game to date,
Kittles filled the box score with 18 points, 8 rebounds, 4 assists
and 3 steals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a team, the Nets, who entered shooting a league-worst 39.9
percent, made 48.1 percent of their shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost so many games this year that we have nothing to
lose,'' Kittles said of the Nets' improved play. ``We're just going
out and playing hard and letting it go. When you play that way, you
play loosey-goosey and with more confidence. And when you play with
more confidence the offense flows, the defense flows and you win
more games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
