<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3769 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-BARKLEY-HNS &LR;      12-09 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BARKLEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IT'S OVER' FOR INJURED BARKLEY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JONATHAN FEIGEN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The echoes from his standing ovations had barely
died down. Charles Barkley could no longer hear them. In the quiet
of the visitors' locker room, he wiped his tears, called his wife,
Maureen, and simply said, ``It's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley's legendary NBA career came to a crashing end Wednesday
in the city where it began.
</P>
<P>
   With 4:09 remaining in the first quarter of what turned out to
be an 83-73 loss to Philadelphia, Barkley fell hard beneath the
Houston Rockets' basket, rupturing his left quadriceps tendon.
Barkley said the injury would end his celebrated 16-year NBA
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate,'' Barkley said. ``I guess the big fella in
the sky is saying he wanted me to finish where I started. I'm
saddened and disappointed it happened. It's ironic it happened
tonight. A lot of people here saw me play my first game. Now they
saw me play my last.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mixed emotion. I cried a little. A lot. I'll probably
cry again. Sometime late tonight, sitting in my hotel room. I have
to realize it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia team physician Jack McPhilemy said the injury would
``conservatively'' require six months of rehabilitation after
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, 36, announced before the season that this one would be
his last and said the injury would not inspire him to change his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think ... it was supposed to happen here, it's supposed
to end in Philadelphia,'' Barkley said. ``I'm not going to be
stubborn and think I'm coming back. I think in my heart God sends
us subliminal messages. I think in my heart it was supposed to end
in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing but 16 years of great memories. I've been all
over the world. I've met the best actors in the world, the best
athletes in the world. I've met presidents, met Bishop (Desmond)
Tutu. I've met regular people who made a great impact on my life.
I've exceeded all my expectations. I never expected to accomplish
all the things I did the last 16 years. I have no sadness in my
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley was honored before the game. He was presented with a
LeRoy Neiman print, begun 12 years ago but left unfinished until
last week, depicting Barkley with the 76ers, the team he says he
will represent when he is inducted into the Basketball Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley received his third standing ovation of the night, a long
but almost solemn salute, late in the first half when he limped
back to the Rockets' bench using a crutch and with his leg
immobilized by a splint. He received his fourth standing ovation in
the second half when he was presented with a card, a replica of the
poster given fans before the game, that had been signed by Sixers
fans.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley spent the rest of the game sitting on a chair behind the
Rockets' coaches, joining huddles during timeouts but never seeming
to recapture his usual emotion and sometimes dropping his head into
his hands.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the third quarter, however, he was back to his
accustomed role coaching the Rockets' young guards.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley had jumped to challenge a shot by the Sixers' Tyrone
Hill, falling hard on the miss. Barkley stayed on the floor as if
he knew the severity of his injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally, this happens with a sudden, violent contraction
of the quadriceps muscle, such as a jumping motion,'' McPhilemy
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew when it happened,'' Barkley said. ``When my kneecap was
buzzing through my leg, I said, `Well, it's been fun. It's over.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew something was dead serious wrong. I knew I wasn't ever
going to play again.''
</P>
<P>
   With his mother, Charcey Glenn, and grandmother, Johnnie Mae
Mickens, who were guests of the 76ers at the game, around him,
Barkley was told almost immediately that the injury was
season-ending and under any circumstances would be
career-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley had suffered a strained quadriceps muscle to his left
leg in Monday's game against Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley was averaging 15.9 points and 11.4 rebounds, tied for
fifth in the league, this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm also glad my last game in Houston was good,'' Barkley said
of the Rockets' win on Monday in which Barkley had 25 points and 11
rebounds. ``It's their last memory of me. I played really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, twice a member of gold-medal-winning Olympic Dream
Teams, was named one of the NBA's 50 greatest players in 1997. He
was the league Most Valuable Player in 1993, when he averaged 25.6
points and 12.2 rebounds, taking the Phoenix Suns to the NBA
Finals, where Barkley was denied his only shot at an NBA title by
the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, he became only the third player in NBA history to
surpass 20,000 points, 10,000 rebounds and 4,000 assists, joining
Wilt Chamberlain and Kareem Abdul-Jabbar.
</P>
<P>
   Despite standing just 6-6, Barkley led the league in rebounding
in 1986-87, when he averaged 14.6. He was second in the NBA in
rebounding last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's tremendous,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. ``He
was one of my favorite guys when I was a scout. I love his
enjoyment of the game. As a player, he's just great. Tremendous
accomplishments. He was very good for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   A nine-time All-Star, Barkley averaged 22.2 points and 11.7
rebounds in his 16 seasons. Going into Wednesday's game, he was
averaging 16.7 points and 12.3 rebounds in his three-plus seasons
with the Rockets. They acquired him from Phoenix in a trade for Sam
Cassell, Robert Horry, Chucky Brown and Mark Bryant on Aug. 19,
1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've seen me grow from a boy to man,'' Barkley said. ``I've
done some good things, some great things, some stupid things, like
everybody. I helped the league grow. Now the young guys need to
step up.''
</P>
<P>
   When the game ended, Sixers players and coaches, including
former teammate Maurice Cheeks, rushed to Barkley to say a few
words. Barkley then made his way to the locker room, stopping to
find someone to hold his crutches, so he could sign autographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the team after the game _ appreciate,'' Barkley said.
``Being a professional athlete is the greatest thing in the world.
This can happen every single night you play. You should appreciate
every game.''
</P>
<P>
   For Barkley, there will be no more.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
