u s BC-HKN-RANGERS-OILERS-NY     12-09 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-OILERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS NIP OILERS IN OVERTIME, 2-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Coach John Muckler termed the New York Rangers' 2-1
overtime victory over the Edmonton Oilers at Madison Square Garden
on Wednesday night their most emotional performance of the season.
And the Rangers' usually mild-mannered goaltender provided the most
memorable moment of the night.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were talking about Mike Richter's pugnacious
performance long after Adam Graves had deflected a Kevin Hatcher
backhander past Tommy Salo at 3:15 of overtime. Graves' eighth goal
of the season - which was originally credited to Hatcher - gave the
Rangers their second overtime victory in as many games, and a
four-game unbeaten streak (3-0-1), a new season-high.
</P>
<P>
   Richter, on the other hand, provided his teammates with plenty
of laughs to go along with his 37 saves. And that was because
Richter uncharacteristically jumped Alexander Selivanov with 3:18
remaining in regulation and pummeled Selivanov with his blocker
after Selivanov had run Richter over.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about an uncharacteristic outburst. There was Richter,
firing at least five rights to the back of Selivanov's head, after
Selivanov had hit the far (left) post with his head after running
into Richter. Selivanov had also absorbed a Mathieu Schneider
cross-check to the neck, seconds before he collided with Richter,
one that Schneider was going to be penalized for before the melee
broke out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I had Lefebrve, John MacLean, the goal-post, the ref,
the ice,'' said Richter, when asked if any of his punches had
connected.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not that was true, Richter's pugilistic pursuits
delighted the Garden crowd, which chanted Richter's name as the
officiating crew was trying to sort all the penalties out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That blocker hurts, I know that,'' said Graves, when asked if
he would give Richter any fighting advice. ``It's not very often
you see him angry like that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have told him to uppercut with that blocker,'' said
Rich Pilon, whose defensive partner, Hatcher, has enjoyed something
of a resurgence since Muckler paired him with Pilon. ``I'd like to
have one of those things in a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   The one-sided fisticuffs overshadowed Graves' game-winner, which
soured a 33-save performance from Salo, who with Richter, provided
most of the highlights of the night. It also overshadowed Theo
Fleury's first goal in over a month, which snapped a 12 game
goal-less drought.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury had scored just one goal in his last 19 games. The
12-game drought tied the second longest of Fleury's career,
according to the Elias Sports Bureau. That was during the 1991-92
season and Fleury finished with 33 goals. In 1989-90, Fleury's
first full season in the National Hockey League, he went 16 games
without a goal and finished with 31.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty this season might be tough. Coming into Wednesday night,
Fleury was on a 15-goal pace.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old right wing had last scored on Nov. 5, in
Colorado, when he steam rolled Patrick Roy on a breakaway.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of tactic was not necessary on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Kim Johnsson _ the impressive rookie defenseman _
created a turnover at his own blue line, breaking up pass by Roman
Hamrlik. Johnsson passed to Fleury, who flew down right wing toward
Salo.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury snapped a wrist shot from the edge of the right circle.
Salo attempted to make a sliding save. Instead, the puck found its
way through Salo's five-hole at 3 minutes 18 seconds of the second
period. And Fleury had finally scored another goal, just his sixth
this season, coming in the Rangers' 28th game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised it went five-hole, because I wasn't shooting
there,'' said Fleury. ``I was trying to go far side.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleury had plenty of other chances on Wednesday night. He fired
a team-high 8 shots on goal. But Salo stopped 7, including a
breakaway with just under eight minutes to go in regulation, when
Fleury's shot bounced off his arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just fanned on my shot in the third,'' said Fleury. ``I
didn't get it up high enough.''
</P>
<P>
   As many chances as Fleury had, Edmonton's Ryan Smyth had more.
He threw a game-high 10 shots on goal. And Smyth _ who was in
Richter's face all evening _ evened the game at 4:31 with his 12th
goal of the season, by jamming a pass from Todd Marchant past
Ricther from just off the right post.
</P>
<P>
   But Richter _ who stopped Doug Weight on a breakaway as Weight
tried to beat him five-hole with a minute and a half remaining in
regulation _ did not allow another shot to get past him. He even
won a fight.
</P>
<P>
   And so the 10-14-4 Rangers, who finished off a span of five
games in eight nights, can now head into a week-long break on their
highest note of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dead tired,'' Muckler said after his Rangers had just
eked by an Edmonton team that has won once on the road this season.
``We need a rest. And it's a well-deserved rest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
