<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-GIFTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING GIFTS: WHAT BECOMES A GREEN THUMB MOST 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every year, I try mightily to suggest truly original gifts for
the garden, and every year I end up recommending the classic stuff,
because the cute, trendy things, like red rubber clogs or that
little plastic bird feeder with the suction cup that sticks to the
window do not hold up when real life crashes through the holidays
like an overweight bluejay.
</P>
<P>
   I actually loved the clogs I got one year, even though they were
too small, so I'd clomp around in them doing light chores until I
got a cramp in my toe. Besides, they are no good for digging or
venturing into some snake pit like the cellar or barn for that
perfect something or other to hold up the tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Gardeners appreciate useful things that last. I swear by my
Felco No. 7 pruners with the rotating handle, which protects me
from repetitive stress. They cost about $30. And I am loyal to
Womanswork gloves, both the soft deerskin ones ($28), which fit
like a second skin, and the tougher pigskin ones ($23) for heavy
digging, from (800) 639-2709 or at www.womansworkgloves.com.
</P>
<P>
   There are cheaper products, but in my experience cheaper pruners
break, and cheaper gloves don't fit. And avoid pretty hats. They
are usually too hot, too floppy, too stiff, too small. Hats have to
be tried on and jammed this way and that by the gardener in the
store.
</P>
<P>
   I have a friend who recently fell in love with gardening, and I
enjoy introducing her to seeds like that fabulous pumpkin that
tastes as good as it looks, Rouge Vif d'Etampes, or the old
climbing rose Mme. Gregoire Staechelin, with pink blossoms as sexy
as satin petticoats, from Heirloom Old Garden Roses, (503)
538-1576.
</P>
<P>
   I love getting seeds saved from a friend's garden, like the
poppy seeds I was given on Long Island one year, along with careful
instructions: sprinkle them over the snow in February (or bare,
frozen ground) and don't do a thing after that, even when they
germinate and grow in clumps that look in need of thinning.
</P>
<P>
   I grew glorious poppies for a few years, harvesting the seeds
from their dried pods every fall and giving them away at Christmas.
Then, somehow, I let my own poppies die out and tried to grow them
from store-bought seed the next few years. They were dull wimps
compared with the ones that were passed down to me. So last summer,
on my birthday, when an old friend in Vermont handed me a pill
bottle full of tiny black seeds, from her father, who had planted
some from me years ago, I felt the magic of a true gift.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a friend who is a serious gardener, and you want to
spend a little money, a Juwel Cold Frame is a winner, if the person
has space and the inclination to harvest salad greens in winter.
It's a sturdy German design with an automatic ventilator, about
$200 at Harris Seeds, (800) 514-4441. And the automatic vent is
nice on a sunny February day when you can't run out and let the
steam out of your mini-greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Another nice gift for salad lovers is a sprouter gizmo for the
kitchen. Adzuki beans, alfalfa, red clover, lentils, green peas and
mung beans make delicious, nutritious sprouts, and though you can
grow them in a jar with holes punched in the lid, ready-made trays
with aeration holes and covers make it easier. Territorial Seed Co.
sells a nice one, including alfalfa seeds and instructions, for
$13, (541) 942-9547.
</P>
<P>
   It's fun wooing children into the garden with a sturdy set of
child-size tools, like the rake, shovel and hoe by Brio, $11 each
at the Brooklyn Botanic Garden's shop, (718) 623-7280 or
www.bbg.org, and some seeds just for them, like Mammoth sunflowers
or moonflowers, which open at night with an enchanting fragrance.
</P>
<P>
   Giving a plant to someone has the same risks as giving a puppy.
You have to be sure the giftee has the temperament and conditions
not to kill the gift. Two plants that are good at surviving past
the holidays are Jasminum sambac Maid of Orleans, a sweetly scented
jasmine, which can do well on a windowsill, and the dwarf lemon
Citrus limon Meyer, which has fragrant blossoms and bears delicious
fruit, with proper care. About four hours of sun a day in winter
will suffice, given cool enough temperatures, from about 55 degrees
at night to 65 in the day. Then come spring, move it outside. Both
of these plants are widely available, but I often order such things
from Logee's Greenhouses in Danielson, Conn., (888) 330-8038 (toll
free), or from www.logees.com. Both plants, in four-inch pots, are
about $15.
</P>
<P>
   Don't overlook a simple gift, just because it's been given a
million times. Planting a few narcissus bulbs in a dish of pebbles
and water is as much a ritual as stuffing and gravy with the
turkey. But don't get Gallaway or Zeva, which smell as if something
died behind the walls. There are others with a far sweeter, less
musky scent, like the yellow varieties Bethlehem, Israel and
Nazareth.
</P>
<P>
   Or try some heavenly sweet Chinese sacred lilies,
www.brentandbeckysbulbs.com or (804) 693-3966. The price for these
bulbs is usually $10 for 10, but if you order before Dec. 15,
there's a 50 percent discount on all bulbs left in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Grand ideas, like trips to Italy or drip irrigation systems or
finding that one-in-a-million high school kid who can weed without
ripping up all the clematis, require more planning and money. But I
wouldn't turn up my nose at any of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 0034EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 00:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3775 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-KERNAGHAN-PROFILE-NYT     12-09 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KERNAGHAN-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USING EVERY TRICK IN FIGHTING SWEATSHOPS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Pa.)  (rk) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You know you are in the presence of a certain kind of
labor advocate when he begins to talk about the effective use of
nuns as weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies really, really hate it when the nuns get
involved and start writing letters,'' said Charles Kernaghan,
smiling maliciously from behind round glasses that reflected the
light of a solitary desk lamp he had turned on in his darkened
office one night last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, what are they going to say against nuns, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Kernaghan is the executive director of the National Labor
Committee, which, despite its name, is not national at all, but a
crowded, cluttered bunch of offices in the Garment District from
which Kernaghan and five other people direct a militant,
low-budget, much-criticized campaign against the use of sweatshop
labor by large companies.
</P>
<P>
   Kernaghan led a reporter through the offices, trying not to step
on the high school students spread on the floor painting picket
signs for an anti-sweatshop protest march planned for Thursday
along Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   He cleared tangled piles of brand new sweat pants and blouses
and baby clothes from his couch. (He lugs these clothes around the
country to use as props during speeches, comparing the retail price
to the wages paid to the foreign workers who assemble the clothes.)
</P>
<P>
   He had just returned from Seattle, where he went as a guest of
the United Steelworkers of America. But while he was there, he
broke off from the labor march and locked arms with students who
were blocking hotels to protest the meeting of the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   For a gloomy sort of man _ the kind who loves Kafka and Sartre
and describes the empty feeling he gets even after he wins public
relations wars with big companies _ Seattle was a vision of a world
the way Charles Kernaghan would like it.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the violence, which he condemned and would have liked
to stop _ ``But I was not going to get killed defending a
Starbucks,'' he says _ the protests were the kind that Kernaghan
thought died out not long after he helped shut down Loyola
University of Chicago as an undergraduate in the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Issues that no one in the United States really knew about _
except a tiny little minority of people _ now it's out there all
across the country because of Seattle,'' he says. ``It's like the
Kathie Lee thing: now people are thinking about this.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Kathie Lee thing'' _ his unlikely connection with Kathie
Lee Gifford, the talk show host _ is, in a way, the beginning of
any story about Kernaghan, a 51-year old former psychology teacher
and self-described perpetual graduate student who worked as, among
many other things, a taxi driver, a carpenter, a truck unloader and
a photographer before almost wandering into labor rights.
</P>
<P>
   But three years ago, when he told a congressional committee that
15-year-old girls were earning 31 cents an hour and working 75-hour
weeks in a Honduran factory that made Mrs. Gifford's sportswear, he
set off a makeshift publicity campaign that brought more attention
to sweatshops than any other.
</P>
<P>
   Kernaghan, who spent most of an interview this week talking
nonstop while staring at a pen he was twisting with both hands, is
the first to admit that he can be overzealous and even unfair and
that his facts can sometimes be a little off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a trained economist. I don't come from an organizing
background. I don't speak Spanish. I don't use a computer. I don't
really like talking on the phone. I can't raise money. And I can't
network.''
</P>
<P>
   He adds, ``But I often think that the reason why the work is
successful in some ways is because it was a mistake that I came
into it.''
</P>
<P>
   As he tells the brief version of his life story, though, it
becomes clear that it was not much of a mistake. He grew up in
Williamsburg, Brooklyn, and then Valley Stream, N.Y., the son of a
construction supervisor who emigrated from Scotland. His parents
were strong Catholics who took in foster children and presented
religion to him as a way of thinking about how to treat other
people. ``It made me a radical,'' he says, ``really from the time I
was a child.''
</P>
<P>
   He became interested early on in psychology, mostly to figure
out ``how the society operates and why certain people get
shafted.'' But after studying it for years and then helping to
teach it as a graduate assistant at Duquesne University in
Pittsburgh, one day he looked out the window of a classroom and
thought to himself, ``I just can't do this anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   And so he quit and got in his car and drove until he stopped
driving. He got out at a pretty town of about 50 people in
Pennsylvania called Ohiopyle, where he rented a house and dragged a
picnic table into the woods and began to read (mostly Sartre and
Kafka).
</P>
<P>
   Later, he worked just enough to earn money to wander the world,
and by the time he got to El Salvador in the mid-1980s, where he
saw working conditions firsthand, he knew what he was going to do.
(He now lives in an apartment in the East Village with Barbara
Briggs, who also helps run the campaign.)
</P>
<P>
   Where does Kernaghan go from here? He wants to get better at
raising money, so he can hire more people and go after more
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big foundations won't touch us with a 10-foot pole,'' he
says. ``And I'll tell you, if we were doing whales or penguins, we
would be funded up the gazoo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 0034EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3779 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-DIPLOMAT-ARRESTED-1ST     12-09 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIPLOMAT-ARRESTED-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN DIPLOMAT IN WASHINGTON HELD IN SPY CASE
</HEADLINE>
  (ADDS listening device found at State Department in 2nd graf; ADDS
that diplomat is likely to be expelled from the United States if he
claims diplomatic immunity in 4th graf) 
 (Eds.: This story is an added starter on The New York Times front
page) 
(rk) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON and JAMES RISEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal authorities Wednesday night arrested a
Russian diplomat believed to be an intelligence officer who had
sought classified information from the State Department, government
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The officials would not identify the diplomat, but they said
that the case involved a listening device found in a conference
room at the State Department and was linked to a substantial
Russian espionage effort aimed at pilfering sensitive information
about American activities abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said that the arrest followed a
counterintelligence investigation and that it would be announced on
Thursday. The Russian diplomat, who was employed at Moscow's
embassy in Washington, was arrested in the Washington area, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The official, detained while carrying an electronic listening
device used to detect surveillance, has immunity as a diplomat and
is expected to assert this to avoid prosecution in the United
States, the American officials said. If the official chooses that
route, he is likely to be expelled from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the arrest seemed to link it to an incident in
Moscow on Nov. 30, when the Russian authorities detained an
American diplomat who they said was a spy preparing to meet a
Russian contact.
</P>
<P>
   The American officials said that the arrest Wednesday night was
not intended as retaliation for that detention, but rather
represented the culmination of an investigation by the FBI and
other agencies that had begun before the Moscow incident.
</P>
<P>
   Former American intelligence officials familiar with
counterespionage cases said that the FBI and CIA have tended not to
engage in such retaliatory measures, at least in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   There was no indication that any Americans were detained
Wednesday night, suggesting that FBI counterintelligence agents may
have lured the Russian to a clandestine meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest of a Russian official was highly unusual. While the
practice was common at the height of the the Cold War, in recent
years the diplomatic expulsions have declined. The State Department
made no comment Wednesday night on the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The last Russian diplomat expelled from the United States was
ordered out of the country in 1994 a week after the arrest of
Aldrich H. Ames, the CIA officer who was later convicted of spying
for Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the arrest appeared certain to further strain the
already uneasy relationship between the two countries, already at
odds over Russia's offensive against its rebellious province of
Chechnya and the U.S. plan to erect a limited anti-missile defense
system.
</P>
<P>
   Since the collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991, the significance
of espionage between the United States and Russia has declined
along with Moscow's reduced global importance. Yet each country
still actively collects intelligence about its former adversary and
pursues investigations of alleged penetrations.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA continues to operate an intelligence station at the
American Embassy in Moscow, and the Russians have long conducted a
similar operation from their embassy in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   FBI and CIA officials have frequently complained, in fact, that
the SVR, the Russian foreign intelligence service that is the
successor to the Soviet KGB, has maintained a large presence in
Washington throughout the 1990s. Earlier this year, Clinton
administration officials complained to Moscow that there were too
many spies in the Russian Embassy here and demanded that the levels
be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA has also exploited the disintegration of the Soviet
Union to expand beyond Moscow and open stations in many of the
newly independent states that were once Soviet republics. In some
of those countries, the agency has established strong relationships
with the local intelligence services as well.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the American authorities have investigated a
number of cases of Russian espionage, but most have stemmed from
instances in which Americans, often motivated by money, had
volunteered to spy for the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious case to emerge in the post-Cold War era was
that of Ames, the CIA officer who was arrested in February 1994. He
was convicted and sentenced to life in prison for spying for
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Ames, a career counterintelligence officer, turned over to his
Russian handlers the identities of a number of Russian and East
European agents who were secretly supplying information to the
United States. Ames was paid nearly $2 million for his information.
More than a dozen of the agents identified by Ames were executed.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the arrest in Moscow last week, the Russians
identified the American espionage suspect as Cheri Leberknight and
said she was a CIA officer who had been working undercover as a
secretary at the American Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   When she was detained in Moscow, the Russian authorities accused
her of trying to obtain secret Russian military documents. They
said she carried a map and a number of devices designed to detect
whether she was under surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   After being detained, she was released to American Embassy
officials because she had diplomatic immunity.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest Wednesday night is the latest in a series of recent
spy incidents, confirming that espionage did not die with the end
of the Cold War. Earlier this year, Germany's internal security
service reportedly forced the CIA to withdraw three of its officers
from Germany, in a sign that German authorities want the agency to
scale back its operations on their soil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
