<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENNIS-McCARTHY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISABLED BRING CHRISTMAS JOY TO NEEDY CHILDREN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DENNIS McCARTHY 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- You could feel old St. Nick himself in the room
Wednesday morning. Oh, you couldn't see him, but he was there all
right _ probably beaming like a proud father.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his favorite children _ the physically disabled and the
poor _ were having a Christmas party in an office building over on
Gloria Avenue in Van Nuys, and you just knew St. Nick wouldn't miss
this one for the world.
</P>
<P>
   Not when it gets tougher and tougher every year to find the real
spirit of Christmas down here. The spirit that comes from the
heart, not the wallet.
</P>
<P>
   The kind of spirit that permeated every room and hallway in
United Cerebral Palsy's headquarters in the Van Nuys section of Los
Angeles Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   St. Nick was there all right. He wouldn't miss the final chapter
to this wonderful Christmas story that's been unfolding on Gloria
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   A story of how more than 40 wheelchair-using adults with
cerebral palsy decided to forego their own Christmas presents to
play Santa Claus to some needy children in the East Valley this
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   A story of how they remembered back to their own childhoods, and
what it was like to go without and always need help.
</P>
<P>
   Remembered how it felt as a kid, especially at Christmas time.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   It took less than an hour, that's all. Less than one hour for
the apprehension and fear to melt away, and the warmth and
friendship emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Less than an hour for these little kids from poor families in
the East Valley to see past the erratic, spastic movements and
sporadic yelling from the adults sitting in wheelchairs to the
loving person inside.
</P>
<P>
   The person who had made them all hand-crafted piggy banks, dolls
and stuffed toys, collected food for them, and now wanted to be
their Santa Claus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made these toys because we know how children feel if they
don't have any presents on Christmas morning,'' Valerie Wright said
in a halting voice to the children from her wheelchair, fighting
every word so she could be understood.
</P>
<P>
   The children smiled back. They understood.
</P>
<P>
   In past years, the holiday crafts that Wright and the others
make were sold to raise funds for themselves and their programs,
but not this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, they came to me and said they wanted to give their
toys to needy children because they would appreciate them more,''
said Wendy Odom, head of the center's enrichment staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``They love these kids because they share a common bond,'' she
said. ``They both know what it's like to go without and need
help.''
</P>
<P>
   The children who came to the center Wednesday were from poor
families that get help at the United Methodist Church of Sepulveda,
one of the most community-active churches in the Valley in
providing services, clothes and meals to poor families and the
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because you guys have hearts of gold, these children will have
toys to play with and food to eat,'' the Rev. Jim Hamilton told
them.
</P>
<P>
   That's when David Nichols clapped from his wheelchair, and
Kristi Arujo cried from hers.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the staff at United Cerebral Palsy began fighting
back their own tears because they were seeing something they hadn't
seen before. David never claps like this, and Kristi never cries,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see these people every day, and today we're seeing inside
them,'' said Diane Cavazos, assistant manager at the center.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing those hearts of gold.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, old St. Nick was there all right Wednesday, probably
beaming like a proud father.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his favorite children were having a Christmas party, and
you just knew he wouldn't miss this one for the world.
</P>
<P>
   He had found the real spirit of Christmas alive and well in an
office building on Gloria Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis McCarthy's column appears Tuesday, Thursday, Friday and
Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
