<HEADER>
A3788 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-ARMY-SCHOOLS-LADN     12-09 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-SCHOOLS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS WANT ARMY TO EVALUATE BELMONT LEARNING CENTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREG GITTRICH 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Los Angeles Unified's top two administrators said
Wednesday they want the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers to evaluate
the environmentally troubled Belmont Learning Center and guide the
district to a final decision on whether the nation's costliest high
school should be completed.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Operating Officer Howard Miller said he and incoming
Superintendent Ramon C. Cortines will recommend at next week's
school board meeting that the Army conduct a six-week fact-finding
mission on scandal-tainted Belmont, the nation's costliest school
project.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the Daily News' disclosure that U.S. Army
Secretary Louis Caldera had been a big backer of Belmont, Miller
said he was not worried about a potential conflict of interest
because the federal officer had no influence in the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Along with supporting Belmont while he was a state legislator
serving the downtown area, Caldera also was once employed by
O'Melveny &AMP; Myers, the law firm the district is suing for its
handling of key matters related to the project. The federal
appointee could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   After the Monday announcement the agency will manage the
district's billion-dollar school building program, Miller had
denied he and Cortines wanted to use the Army at Belmont. On
Wednesday he said the decision wasn't made until that day, and he
argued the Army's expertise is needed to give the board all the
facts before it votes on the fate of Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to engage the Army Corps of Engineers to gather
information we need to manage the decision process, so we finally
all have the same information to make a decision,'' Miller said,
announcing the planned action at a special public meeting in
Belmont's attendance area.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by the school board, the Army will be asked to
determine how much it would cost to complete the school and whether
state funding would be available. The corps also would have the
task of determining how long it would take to finish the school,
and it would investigate alternative sites for high schools in the
attendance area.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said the added time would allow the state Department of
Toxic Substances Control to give the district more detailed
information on environmental hazards at the school, which is
located atop an oil field seeping potentially deadly and explosive
gases.
</P>
<P>
   Miller added an advisory committee of students, teachers,
parents and administrators will be formed to guide the board's
final decision, which most likely would come in February.
</P>
<P>
   Standing before more than 200 students in the library of Belmont
High School, Cortines said his previous endorsements to finish
Belmont were largely based upon emotion and that more
fact-gathering is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Board President Genethia Hayes endorsed the administrators' plan
and changed her previous position on Belmont, saying the amount of
money it will take to build the school safely is no longer an
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not made up my mind,'' Hayes said, after listening to
students plead for the completion of the school. ``My only issue is
safety. It is not about money for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that is a danger, to rush. We need to have all the
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Board member Victoria Castro, an ardent Belmont supporter, said
she will be courteous and allow the Army to conduct its review but
Belmont must be completed regardless.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt in my mind this school has to be built,''
Castro said, wiping tears away from her eyes. ``We must build
this.''
</P>
<P>
   The district has sunk $170million into Belmont, but it called
off all new construction and padlocked the property last month.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Miller and Cortines broached the subject of state aid
during a private meeting with Assembly Speaker Antonio Villaraigosa
but came away without a definite answer.
</P>
<P>
   The citizens commission that reviewed the public works project
determined it would take $112million to complete the campus and
concluded the school could not open for five to eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Belmont lined up Wednesday night to denounce Miller
and Cortines' plan to involve the Army at Belmont, focusing on the
secretary's past involvement in the project.
</P>
<P>
   The critics charged that the engineering corps is in no position
to do an impartial study of Belmont since the Secretary of the Army
is a Belmont supporter who once worked for a law firm involved in
the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Army Corps cannot be considered an independent analyst
because of the conflict of interest that exists at the top,'' said
state Sen. Tom Hayden, D-Los Angeles. ``No study should begin under
the shadow of suspicion.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayden worried that the move was really an effort to pry loose
new state funding for Belmont by convincing state lawmakers the
project was in capable hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``There does seem to be an orchestrated campaign under way to
save Belmont, and it's about profits and reputations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The potential conflict of interest involving Caldera also
troubled Assemblyman Scott Wildman, D-Glendale, who chairs a state
commission that funds school construction.
</P>
<P>
   While the Army may be able to help the district build schools,
Wildman said the Army should not work on Belmont. He argued that
the district should kill Belmont now rather than search for new
ways to save it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get rid of the district's obsession with this
compromised project,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the topics Miller now wants the Army to address were
already covered by the commission that voted 4-3 to finish the
school but its decision was clouded by the opposition of its
nonvoting head, former District Attorney Ira Reiner.
</P>
<P>
   But commission member and former state Sen. Charles Calderon
said there was still room for another study to determine costs and
a timetable. &QL; 
``They're moving targets, difficult to pin down, because you have
to make a lot of assumptions about, for instance, the value of the
land if you could sell it,'' Calderon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the board feels it needs more information, I'm for whatever
it takes to get them that information.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
