<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3798 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-GAME-HNS &LR;      12-09 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-GAME-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
PHILADELPHIA _ The fire wasn't there. The usual passion was
missing. The determination was absent.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those elements were not, however, hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   They were sitting behind the Rockets' bench, immobilized in the
prone left leg of Charles Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   On a night dedicated to celebrate his last visit to
Philadelphia, Barkley ruptured a quadriceps tendon, ending his
spectacular 16-year NBA career where it began. Without him, the
Rockets put up little fight, losing 83-73 to the 76ers in a sloppy,
lifeless performance in which neither team seemed able to focus on
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously a horrible night for us, losing Charles, and just a
horrible game,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. ``We hung in
there defensively, then just got selfish. We started taking the
first option. We surrendered. Just surrendered. It was like we had
a built-in excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure would have been a nice tribute to win the game for the
guy. We were right there and turned it into a rec game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets committed 27 turnovers, more than any Sixers
opponent has in the four seasons of the First Union Center. The
Rockets did not shoot much better, making just 26 of 71 shots.
Between them, the teams combined for 49 turnovers, still finding
time to miss a combined 94 shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the ugliest games ever,'' Sixers coach Larry
Brown said. ``I think there was concern he (Barkley) wasn't coming
back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets said they immediately knew Barkley's season and
career were over. In position to see the knee as he was helped past
them, they had no doubts about the severity of the injury or chance
of a return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew when he walked off the floor,'' Rockets center Kelvin
Cato said. ``I just hope he can come back and walk right.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets, already playing without center Hakeem Olajuwon as
he rehabilitates after hernia surgery, certainly played as if they
were thinking about the leader unable to lead them.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley returned to a seat behind the coaches late in the first
half and came back to that spot for the second half. He joined
huddles and instructed the Rockets' young guards. But he was not
the same, nor were they.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurt,'' Rockets guard Steve Francis said. ``We can't use it
as an excuse. But when Charles went down, everyone knew he was
finished. I just saw everybody put their head down. Nobody was
thinking about the game. We were thinking about the rest of the
season, thinking about Charles. I couldn't stop thinking about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets finished the first half in a daze. They stayed close
in the third quarter, largely on the strength of their defense. But
without Barkley in the low post to settle them, they collapsed in
the fourth quarter without executing as they had been in recent
weeks with or without Barkley on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We let the game fall apart,'' Tomjanovich said. ``In the
fourth quarter, we get him the ball and know we'll get a good shot.
Now we've got to start thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, however, the thoughts were displaced. The Rockets
could not get the image of Barkley's misshapen knee out of their
minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him coming off the floor,'' forward Carlos Rogers said.
``To see his leg just hanging there, I never saw anything like
that. Coming in at halftime and then having to go out and play he
says a lot of crazy things and does a lot of crazy things, but he's
a good guy. Everything he says is for your benefit. Whoa, boy, it's
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets remained within three points three minutes into the
fourth quarter. But in a span of just 2{ minutes, the Sixers put
together an 11-3 run as the Rockets missed three long jumpers and
three free throws interrupted only by a Kenny Thomas 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets never challenged again. They did not get as close as
even nine points until Bryce Drew hit a jumper with 1:30 left. By
then, however, it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   Francis had 18 points and seven assists but said he ``shot
horribly.'' He made six of 15 shots. Cuttino Mobley added 14 points
in his return to Philadelphia but made just three of 10 shots.
</P>
<P>
   The 76ers were led by guards Aaron McKie and Eric Snow, who each
had 16 points and combined for 10 assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was super-hard to focus,'' Rockets forward Matt Bullard
said. ``Especially when it's Charles, it was harder if not
impossible to focus on what we were trying to do. It was almost
surreal. His last time playing here. It was surreal watching it
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley described the end of his career coming in the city where
it began as ironic. But there was another irony the Rockets must
now live with and that defeated them Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He helped the team a lot, especially with this being a young
team,'' Rogers said. ``You need a guy like that to help a young
team through tough times, times like this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 0117EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3803 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     12-09 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IT ended, perhaps fittingly, in the place where the roly-poly kid
out of Leeds, Ala., first made his transformation from the Round
Mound of Rebound into one of the greatest players in the history of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   The circle was closed in Philadelphia, the birthplace of
American independence, and nobody has ever been more fiercely
independent than Charles Wade Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary and conscientious, loud and lovable, outrageous and
outreaching, hard-headed and hard-working, profane and profound.
</P>
<P>
   He is the line from an old Kris Kristofferson song: a walking
contradiction, partly fact and partly fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody in the history of the NBA ever experienced as much
frustration or had as much fun. No championships. No regrets.
</P>
<P>
   It ended in a tangle of bodies under the Rockets' basket and
left him lying, appropriately enough, in the paint, the area where
a man of his 6-4{ stature somehow managed to survive and thrive
among the giants for so long and eventually stood taller than most.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the player who was chided throughout most of his
career for being such a weak defender was running back down the
floor at age 36 to try to make a defensive play against Tyrone Hill
of the Sixers.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley jumped sideways and landed in an awkward manner, and in
the very flash of that first moment, sprawled out on the hardwood
floor, he had the look of recognition on his face.
</P>
<P>
   It was over.
</P>
<P>
   All of the scores and all of the wars, all of the miles and all
of the smiles, all of the controversial comments and the
incontrovertible evidence by those able to get close to him that
prove he is one of the rare celebrities who in truth is a much
better person than he would dare let you believe.
</P>
<P>
   Through the '80s and the '90s, in political terms, Michael
Jordan was Slick Willie, good-looking and well-coiffed, skating
around the tough issues, dancing away from controversy while always
finding a way to win jewelry and the popular vote.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, at the same time, was the slam-dunking equivalent of
Ross Perot, perhaps crazy as a loon and always locked out of the
ultimate prize, but with so many of his own singular opinions and
never encumbered by a P.R. man's need to cover up his warts.
</P>
<P>
   Through the time of its greatest growth, the NBA _ and even Air
Jordan himself _ needed Barkley as a kind of counterweight to the
high-gloss packaging of corporate vanilla sameness. He stirred the
pot and kept them in touch with the street. He was the pea under
their mattress, never letting commissioner David Stern and the
suits get too comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   The court was his stage, and on it he was Olivier, the
consummate actor who could play any role _ warrior, joker, charmer,
villain, understanding teammate and a heckler's worst nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he broke the nose of a drunk who confronted him outside a
Milwaukee bar and, yes, he tossed a boorish little ice-throwing
fellow into the window of an Orlando nightclub. He likely spent
more time signing autographs than any high-profile athlete of his
generation, and he talks to the kids he meets, not at them or over
their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``No tears or crying or sad music for me when it's over,'' he
said just last week in a casual locker-room conversation in Los
Angeles. ``The NBA has allowed me to become Charles Barkley.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't even think about questioning his credentials, and never
mind with the numbers, which are huge.
</P>
<P>
   At the NBA's 50th anniversary celebration in 1997, when a
non-believer asked the great Elgin Baylor whether Barkley belonged
among the top 50 players in history, he was greeted by a stare.
``Maybe in the top five,'' Baylor replied. Later that same weekend,
Wilt Chamberlain pointed across a room at Barkley and said, ``I
would like to have gone to war against Russell with that boy on my
side.''
</P>
<P>
   As the horn sounded on the Rockets' 83-73 loss Wednesday night,
Carlos Rogers walked over to Barkley, who was sitting on the bench
with crutches, and kissed his bald head.
</P>
<P>
   It ended with him playing the role of teacher, mentor on a young
team that is struggling to find itself.
</P>
<P>
   After all the years of being able to physically overpower the
game, dragging the undertalented Sixers to the Eastern Conference
finals to earn the admiration of the tough Philly fans, then moving
on to Phoenix and lifting the soulless Suns to the NBA Finals, he
was playing his final days more on his wits than his muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Wade Barkley had been propping these young Rockets up in
the absence of Hakeem Olajuwon, and in the coming days we likely
will see just how much.
</P>
<P>
   Damn, I'll miss him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
