<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3804 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-LOMBARDI-AWARD-HN     12-09 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LOMBARDI-AWARD-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DEAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Corey Moore didn't go to Virginia Tech as a prize recruit. Several
colleges told the Brownsville, Tenn., native he was too small to
play on the defensive line at 6-0 and 200 pounds. Among those was
the University of Tennessee.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four years later, Moore has added 25 pounds and helped Virginia
Tech to a national championship showdown with Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Moore was named the winner of the 30th annual
Rotary Lombardi Award, honoring college football's top lineman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been a guy that's been big on individual awards. I
don't think I'll ever be,'' said Moore, who won over the Penn State
duo of linebacker LaVar Arrington and defensive end Courtney Brown
and Florida State nose guard Corey Simon. ``I'm very team-oriented
and worry about team goals, but this is nice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an honor to be in the same company of top-notch players.
I wish I could give each and every one of those guys a piece of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to thank the Virginia Tech football program for even
giving me the opportunity to play and develop me into not only the
football player I am today as well as the person I am.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lombardi Award continued a week of honors for Moore. On
Monday, he received the 1999 Bronko Nagurski Trophy, which goes to
college football's top defensive player.
</P>
<P>
   Moore was a big part of the 11-0 season that landed the Hokies a
berth in the Jan. 4 Sugar Bowl. For the second consecutive season
he led the Big East in sacks, and his 17 sacks this season
accounted for 146 yards in losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just part of Corey Moore,'' said Charley Wiles,
Virginia Tech's defensive ends coach, who accompanied Moore at the
J.W. Marriott Hotel for the presentation of the award _ 40 pounds
of granite atop a silver base.
</P>
<P>
   `` He makes everyone around him better and (sometimes) you get
those people that have a special gift that they can affect other
people in a positive manner, make them want to be better. Not only
players (but) coaches, teachers. I mean everybody he comes in
contact with, he affects them in that manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard work is what got Moore to this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't come in the door 6-foot, 230 pounds,'' said Wiles.
``He was 200 pounds, and he gained 25 pounds over the four years at
Virginia Tech. Increased his speed from 4.78 to 4.38 (in the
40-yard dash). Those are the things that happen through hard work.
This speaks for what kind of kid he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore had 59 tackles and three pass deflections and caused three
fumbles for a defense that ranked third nationally in scoring
defense and rushing defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a firm believer that size doesn't matter,'' said Moore.
``You can't measure a person's heart. I can't wait to not only show
my heart on the football field but also in society as I grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore is an outstanding student with an undergraduate degree in
finance. He is working on a second degree in management. ``He
realizes football is not the only thing in life,'' said Wiles.
``He's like, `I've got to prepare myself through education to be a
successful guy' and that's the way he works.''
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored by the Rotary Club of Houston, the Lombardi Award is
in memory of legendary coach Vince Lombardi, who died of cancer.
The Rotary Club of Houston has raised more than $2.35 million for
the American Cancer Society.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
