<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW-LOOK USC ROLLS PAST HAWAII
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC coach Henry Bibby has grown weary of being
asked when he was going to use more new players, so he took a
pre-emptive strike against the question Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby gave freshman center Kostas Charissis his first career
start and substituted more freely than usual, and it paid off in an
85-56 victory over Hawaii before 2,092 at the Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The person most surprised about the lineup change was the
6-foot-11 Charissis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect anything. I was excited,'' Charissis said. ``I
was nervous in the beginning, but after about five minutes I was in
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Charissis contributed four points and a career-high six
rebounds, but more importantly made the Trojans taller and allowed
other players to get some rest.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference was that center Brian Scalabrine moved to
small forward. He had 19 points and five rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to bang, but I'll do anything for the the team,''
Scalabrine said. ``It's not that big a difference. But defending a
small forward is a lot harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibby said previous starter David Bluthenthal was not being
demoted by the move, although Bluthenthal played 26 minutes, which
was slightly under his season average of 29.4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a different look,'' Bibby said. ``It's a nonconference
game, you see where guys fit. I told David he would play more
minutes off the bench than if he was starting.''
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Rashad Jones (22 minutes) and shooting guard Nate
Hair (10 minutes) were the other reserves given a chance to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nonconference is to see where guys are to bring them
along,'' Bibby said. ``We want to have them ready for the Pac-10
and win in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans (4-4) certainly made a case for playing more than
the usual six-man rotation. They had one of the best defensive
efforts of the season, holding Hawaii (5-2) to 38-percent shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did tonight was pick up the defensive intensity,''
Bibby said. ``We just haven't stopped people.''
</P>
<P>
   That was apparent early, as USC jumped out to an 18-8 lead and
boosted the advantage to 16 (37-21) on a layup by Jeff Trepagnier,
who had a game-high 20 points after missing last weekend's loss to
St. Bonaventure to attend his grandmother's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   The second half became mostly garbage time, with the highlights
five USC dunks, including one by Charissis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played better this game than all the games before,''
Charissis said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: USC forward Sam Clancy had his third double-double (16
points, 11 rebounds), the first Trojan with three straight since
forward Jaha Wilson in 1996. Clancy's father, Sam Sr., had 18
rebounds against Hawaii while playing for Pittsburgh in 1979.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 0155EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0025 </DOCNO>
