<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURRAY, KINGS THRASH ATLANTA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Some nights, it's good to face an expansion team,
score a few goals, hit a few people, don't think too much about
what's ahead.
</P>
<P>
   With a four-game trip looming, the Los Angeles Kings took
advantage of the Atlanta Thrashers on Wednesday with a 4-0 victory
in front of 15,210 at Staples Center. They didn't play great, but
they didn't have to.
</P>
<P>
   Luc Robitaille, who missed a month with a broken left foot,
capped the feel-good evening with his first goal in almost six
weeks. Robitaille had 10 goals in his first 15 games before the
injury.
</P>
<P>
   After a 2-3-2 stretch in their last seven games, no Ziggy Palffy
and a game Friday night against mighty Detroit, the Kings took a
3-0 lead after two periods. San Jose, which still leads them by two
points in Pacific Division, defeated Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   It might seem a little early for scoreboard watching, but every
team in the Kings' division would qualify for the playoffs if the
season ended today.
</P>
<P>
   Kings coach Andy Murray said he expects teams in the Western
Conference to spread out in the next couple of weeks. He just
doesn't want to be one of them.
</P>
<P>
   It helped that Glen Murray, the Kings hottest offensive player,
had a goal and an assist and Garry Galley scored a rare power play
goal as the club raised its record to 15-7-6. The power play goal
was just their third in the last 42 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   It also helped that Kings goalie Jamie Storr faced just 21 shots
to record the sixth shutout of his six-year NHL career.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings were lucky to take an early lead. The Thrashers
appeared to score the first goal when Shean Donovan beat Storr with
a 25-foot blast just 3:56 into his first game after being acquired
by Atlanta earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   But the goal was disallowed when Donovan's new teammate Andreas
Karlsson was whistled for holding.
</P>
<P>
   That helped because the Kings didn't play without much jump.
Palffy, the team's leading scorer with 26 points, missed the game
with a sore lower back. Palffy came out of Saturday's 3-3 tie with
Tampa Bay in the third period with the flu and could not practice
the past three days because of back spasms.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are hoping to have him back during the trip but are
happy to have Glen Murray pick up the slack.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Blake, expected to get additional playing time in Palffy's
absence, scored the game's first goal midway through the first
period. Blake, who had two goals on the Kings' last trip, was told
by Andy Murray he needed more grit and less finesse.
</P>
<P>
   Blake did just that, poking in his own rebound past Thrashers'
Norm Maracle after taking a cross-ice pass in front from Brad
Chartrand.
</P>
<P>
   Less than three minutes into the second period, it was Glen
Murray's turn. He parked in front of Maracle and scored after
taking a pass from Donald Audette. It was Murray's 12th goal and
seventh in the last six games. During that stretch, he has had
three two-goal games.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Storr was seldom tested. He faced just 13 shots in
the first two periods while the Kings fired 27 on Maracle.
</P>
<P>
   It was Murray's goal that made it clear the Kings wouldn't be
challenged. Atlanta (7-17-2) had won two straight before dropping
an overtime game to last-year's expansion team Nashville on Sunday.
The Thrashers play San Jose on Friday and the Mighty Ducks on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Less than three minutes after Murray's goal that Galley scored
on the power play. With former King Ray Farraro in the penalty box
for interfering with Storr, Galley crushed a 25-footer that sailed
between Maracle's leg for the Kings third goal.
</P>
<P>
   On the play Bryan Smolinski recorded his team-leading 19 assists
and is on a pace for a career-high 56.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the game, the Kings were 21 for 115 on the power play,
sixth best in the NHL.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 0158EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
