<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUMPEL WILL STAY HOME FOR NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Kings were hoping to take injured
Jozef Stumpel and Stephane Fiset on the team's upcoming four-city
trip, but it looks like there won't be enough practice time to make
it worthwhile for Stumpel.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' top center has been sidelined since Nov. 6 with a
hernia that required surgery. The team is hoping to have him back
by Christmas but decided the trip to Detroit, Montreal, New Jersey
and New York would not help his recovery.
</P>
<P>
   The team will not skate today before traveling to Detroit for
Friday's game against the Red Wings. The Kings fly after the game
to Montreal and will not work out before Saturday's game against
the Canadiens.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are scheduled to take Sunday off and practice Monday
in New Jersey. They play the Devils on Tuesday and the New York
Rangers on Wednesday but will not practice before that game.
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel, who has participated in two light workouts this past
week, will remain in Los Angeles and continue physical therapy at
the Iceoplex in North Hills.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings hope to have Fiset as a backup for the game against
the Canadiens. Montreal is Fiset's hometown. Quebec is home for
Marcel Cousineau, who has been the Kings' backup goalie in Fiset's
absence. Fiset, sidelined one month with a deep bone bruise on his
right hand, has been working out with the club the past week.
</P>
<P>
   __ Welcome aboard: Before Wednesday's game, Atlanta acquired
forward Shean Donovan from the Colorado Avalanche in exchange for
goaltender Rick Tabaracci. Donovan, who had one goal in 18 games
with Colorado this season, almost had one four minutes into the
first period Wednesday against the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   He beat Jamie Storr with a 25-footer, but the play was waived
off when Andreas Karlsson was whistled for holding
</P>
<P>
   __ Quick Whistles: Ziggy Palffy, the Kings' leading scorer with
26 points, tested his sore lower back Wednesday by skating for 10
minutes. He will make the trip, but the team is not sure whether he
will play Friday in Detroit. . . . With two minutes remaining in
the first period, the Kings Bryan Smolinski shot a puck into the
stands that sailed over the restaurant on the north end and into
the luxury suites on the third level. It was the first puck to land
there this season. . . . Zack Newell of Simi Valley was the Kings
honorary captain for Wednesday night's game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
