<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKENOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'NEAL PRAISES BARKLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Shaquille O'Neal's last on-court meeting
with Charles Barkley mutated into a wrestling match on the Compaq
Center floor. But the Los Angeles Lakers' O'Neal expressed nothing
but respect and sympathy Wednesday night upon hearing Barkley would
retire in the wake of a severe left-knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my eyes, he's always going to be one of the greatest
forwards ever,'' said O'Neal, a one-time Olympic teammate of
Barkley's. ``A lot of people bring up that nonsense that because he
doesn't have a ring, he's not a great player. I find that not true.
(John) Stockton and (Karl) Malone are great players also; they
don't have rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, Barkley's a good friend, good person, good player and
I'm going to miss him. I hope this is not his last year, but if it
is his last year, I'm behind him 100 percent. To me, he's one of
the greatest forwards ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played with a lot of enthusiasm, he played with a lot of
heart. That's what I liked about him.''
</P>
<P>
   The news caught the Lakers by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson called the awkward end to Barkley's career
``a sad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles has been a great player in the NBA, one of the premier
players in this league the last 12 years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Forget the medal: Speaking of the Dream Team, O'Neal said
that if he's offered one of the remaining three spots on next
year's roster, he'll pass it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``My seasons have been so rigorous, my summer has been time for
me to just get some rest. Get a lot of rest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal said the team doesn't need him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got Tim (Duncan) and Alonzo (Mourning), that should be
enough,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal won a gold medal with the 1996 U.S. Olympic team and
another with a Junior Olympics squad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I already got two gold medals,'' he said. ``I gladly
appreciate it. Thanks for picking me the first time, but this time
I'll probably decline.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if that decision was final, O'Neal hedged, saying
``probably. Most likely.'' Then he added, mysteriously, ``but
things may change.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Dribbles: Jackson gave his players the day off today,
providing another rare break in a busy week. The Lakers travel to
Vancouver on Friday for a Saturday-afternoon game, then return to
Los Angeles to play the Detroit Pistons on Sunday, completing a
stretch of five games in eight days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 0204EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
