<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3823 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-BARKLEY-CAREER-HN     12-09 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BARKLEY-CAREER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The irony is almost too great to be true.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ending his 16 years in the NBA, Charles Barkley played his last
game in the same city where his career began.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley ruptured a quadriceps tendon in his left knee Wednesday
in the first quarter of the Rockets' 83-73 loss to the Philadelphia
76ers at First Union Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the big fella in the sky wanted me to finish right
where I started,'' said Barkley. ``There were a lot of people here
tonight who saw me play my first game and saw me play my last game.
I do think it was supposed to happen like this. It was supposed to
end in Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is where it all began _ at least professionally.
</P>
<P>
   Drafted fifth overall in the 1984 NBA draft, Barkley was known
as ``Boy Gorge'' and ``the Round Mound of Rebound'' after his
spectacular career at Auburn, where he often tipped the scales at
over 300 pounds. Barkley joined a Philadelphia team that included
such NBA stars as Julius Erving and Moses Malone. Some questioned
whether the 6-6 Barkley, who played center at Auburn, could make it
as a power forward in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   He did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barkley looks like Wes Unseld, but he jumps like a young
Julius,'' said then-Knicks coach Hubie Brown, comparing Barkley to
Unseld, a former Washington Bullet who played center in the NBA
despite standing only 6-7. ``Combine that body and that
explosiveness, and you have an unstoppable force.''
</P>
<P>
   Which pretty much describes Barkley's career, both on and off
the court.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley was what NBA types like to call a 'tweener _ a player
who is between positions because of a lack of height. But he was
far from a 'tweener in the public eye. No, Barkley is one of those
players you either love or hate. There was no middle ground.
</P>
<P>
   And that's because Barkley has never been hesitant to speak his
mind on any subject. That outspoken nature is what caused Barkley
to demand trades, first to Phoenix prior to the 1992-93 season and
then to Houston before 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem I have is when a guy talks to me and disagrees
with me, then he turns around and writes bad stuff about me just
because my opinions differ from his,'' Barkley said. ``I don't like
the word controversial. What is controversial? Just because our
opinions are different, I don't look at myself as controversial. I
feel like I'm just like everyone else. Some things I say, people
agree with; some things I say, they don't agree with.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's the normal American way. But when you're famous,
you can't be like that. That's the sad thing. That's probably the
only thing I hate about being famous, that you really can't voice
your opinion and be yourself, because then you get the tag for
being outspoken and controversial. But the regular guy on the
street says something I say, then it's all right. But because I'm
in the limelight, then I'm being controversial. That bothers me.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's off the court.
</P>
<P>
   There is no denying the greatness of what he accomplished on the
court.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his relative lack of height, Barkley led the league in
rebounding once (1986-87, 14.6 rebounds), averaged less than 10
rebounds only once (his rookie year, 8.6 rebounds) and is one of
only three players to have over 20,000 points, 10,000 rebounds and
4,000 assists (Wilt Chamberlain and Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, both
7-footers, are the others). He was named the NBA's Most Valuable
Player in 1993, when he led the Phoenix Suns to the NBA Finals in
his first season in the Valley of the Sun.
</P>
<P>
   He was named one of the NBA's top 50 players of all time in 1997
and is the 13th-leading scorer in league history.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley twice won Olympic gold medals, including 1992 with the
original Dream Team that plowed through the field in Barcelona,
Spain, sparking the worldwide boom in basketball. He added his
second gold in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But Barkley is perceived to have one big void on his resume _ he
never won an NBA championship. While other greats of his generation
_ Larry Bird, Magic Johnson, Michael Jordan, Hakeem Olajuwon and
David Robinson _ have led their teams to titles, Barkley has never
captured one.
</P>
<P>
   He came close in 1993, but the Suns lost to the Bulls in six
games.
</P>
<P>
   But Barkley, contrary to his competitive nature, claims that not
winning a championship is not a concern. He looks back on his life,
which began in tiny Leeds, Ala., and is amazed at where he finds
himself today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy,'' he said. ``I feel that I've had the perfect life
because of where I came from. People keep throwing this thing out
there about the championship. Hey, let me tell you something _ you
grow up in Leeds, Ala., poor, the championship is the furthest
thing from your mind. You just want to make a success out of your
life. I have to look at the whole picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a basketball standpoint, yes, I would like to win a
championship. But I'm not going to let basketball dictate my
success or failures in life. My life, to me, has been perfect
because my only goal in life was to take care of my mother and my
grandmother. Now you can throw my wife and daughter in there, and
my two brothers. But that was my No. 1 goal in life. When I started
playing basketball, I prayed hard every night. I said, `Give me a
chance to make life better for my mother and my grandmother.'
That's it. Everything else after that has been cake. People try to
tell me what I think and what I feel. I know what I think and what
I feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``A championship would be great, but it's not the most important
thing to me. Not even close. My only goal in life was making life
better for my family because growing up really poor is not fun.
It's not fun not having things everyone else has. It's not fun
wearing hand-me-downs and things like that. That motivated me all
the time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
