<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3824 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     12-09 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WISCONSIN, DON'T WRITE OFF WILLINGHAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Russia is better equipped for Y2K than
Stanford is for Ron Dayne. Inasmuch as anybody's talking about the
Rose Bowl at all, that's what they're saying.
</P>
<P>
   If Tyrone Willingham is bothered by the public perception that
his Cardinal football team is a bug that big, bad Wisconsin is
going to wipe out on New Year's Day, he had a funny way of showing
it Wednesday during a press conference at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Willingham smiled when someone broached the matter of his team
being 10{-point underdogs in the eyes of Vegas bookmakers and more
overmatched than that in the minds of some pundits.
</P>
<P>
   To know Willingham's story is to understand why being written
off doesn't make him wrought-up or reticent. He can smile
unselfconsciously despite the braces on his lower teeth and the
lowered expectations of the public because he knows things have a
way of getting straightened out in the end.
</P>
<P>
   Few people would have bet on an African-American woman earning
her Masters degree from Columbia in the early 1950s. Fewer still
would put any money down on the slightly built boy she bore going
on to become a quarterback good enough to break down defenses and
stereotypes at a Big Ten school in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   You know what they say: Where there's a Willingham, there's a
way.
</P>
<P>
   There's an explanation other than parity or peculiarity for how
a Cardinal team that won only two Pacific-10 games in 1998 is the
king of the conference a year later: The players are passionate and
prepared and persistent and opportunistic and selfless.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, they are a reflection of their fifth-year head
coach.
</P>
<P>
   Before he was named the conference Coach of the Year, Willingham
got called all kinds of things that didn't have nearly as nice a
ring to them.
</P>
<P>
   Back-to-back losing seasons gave some Stanford boosters amnesia.
They forgot all about the back-to-back bowl seasons Willingham
presided over at the start of his Cardinal head-coaching tenure and
wondered aloud why the football team hadn't started stockpiling
conference championships like the school's tennis teams and
swimming teams and women's volleyball and basketball teams.
</P>
<P>
   After Willingham directed the Cardinal to the Liberty Bowl in
1995 and the Aloha Bowl in 1996, it didn't take someone with an IQ
of 153 to see the next logical step was the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Willingham, shut out in his efforts to get to the Rose Bowl as a
player at Michigan State, was among those who thought his third
year at The Farm would be a charm. Instead, the Cardinal lost five
Pac-10 games by an average margin of 15.4 points. The following
year was worse: six conference losses by an average of 15.7 points.
</P>
<P>
   For Willingham, those 5-6 and 3-8 campaigns were like a riddle.
He was grasping for a deeper meaning until this year supplied an
answer that made sense of everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at it now and see going to the Rose Bowl wasn't meant
to be after the first couple of years,'' he said. ``It might not
have been as rewarding as it is now, accomplishing it after two
years of difficulties.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy for Willingham, growing up a child of segregation
in the South. His mother, now deceased, worked 31 years as an
elementary-school teacher. Her influence was great but her world
relatively puny, for the longest time not extending beyond the
African-American community in Jacksonville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Boundaries of race also restricted Willingham's late father,
Nathaniel. He sold real estate but not in the wealthier, white
neighborhoods. They might as well have been on Mars for all the
access he had to them.
</P>
<P>
   The world widened for Willingham, 45, but he had to squeeze
through small cracks in existing walls to make it so. He was barely
5-6 when he finished high school and weighed 140 pounds soaking
wet.
</P>
<P>
   On the advice of his high school coach, Willingham sent out 100
letters to colleges, asking football coaches not for a free ride
but simply for a few minutes of their time. He got back two
replies, from the University of Toledo and Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   Willingham walked on at Michigan State and earned three varsity
letters each in football and baseball and one undergraduate degree.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-three years after beginning his coaching career as a
graduate assistant at his alma mater, Willingham will become the
first African-American head coach to grace the sidelines at the
Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   A funny thing happened on his way to integrating the Rose Bowl
coaching ranks. Unlike in Jacksonville, N.C., or in East Lansing,
Mich., it didn't create much of a fuss.
</P>
<P>
   Willingham answered questions for an hour Wednesday before the
topic of race first came up. Was that in itself a sign of progress,
we wondered aloud?
</P>
<P>
   Willingham flashed that all-knowing, all-teeth-showing smile
again, the one he reserves for those who go jumping to conclusions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
