<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN OLERUD SIGNING IS RELIEF FROM GRIFFEY MESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Since he was the only good news in a town where news
has been unrelievedly bad, there is an urge to build the statue of
John Olerud now, skipping the formality of his first Mariners
at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Rejected by the world and consumed with self-loathing, Seattle,
onetime national sweetheart whose makeup is messed and nylons are
backwards, desperately needed a hug.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Olerud was willing to give up New York for his
hometown team and also happens to be one of baseball's gentlemen
... well, hang on here, we're about one slobber away from bursting
into Dick Vermeil.
</P>
<P>
   Whew. OK, I'm composed now.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the baseball virtues he brings to Seattle and the
Mariners, Olerud's free-agent signing begins the local validation
of Pat Gillick as general manager, offers evidence there is passion
among ownership for something besides tax money and helps untangle
the antler-lock between the Mariners and Cincinnati Reds over Ken
Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The eagerness among all sides to get a Griffey deal done fairly
bristles. Mariners management is tired of Griffey and his demands.
Griffey is equally fed up with the club. Ohio, home to the NFL's
worst football as well as Pete Rose, the most annoying man in
sports, is eager to be lit up by the presence of Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   But the circumstances and the consequences of the deal defy
haste. So, in the meantime, the poker game is worthy of its own
admission ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Griffey's ability to force a trade via his 10-and-5
rights, the Mariners lost leverage in any trade talks. And because
Griffey a) has only one year left on his contract; b) would cost at
least $150 million in a long-term extension; and c) has the right
to refuse a trade to a team he doesn't like, only a handful of
teams could even consider trading for him.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is poor for the Mariners. It forces Gillick into
the awkward position of having to create a market for the game's
best player.
</P>
<P>
   The one automatic entry in the market was the Reds, who employ
Griffey's father and operate in his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   But one team doesn't really make a market. Although other teams
have made offers, all have been of the low-ball variety to test the
Mariners' degree of desperation.
</P>
<P>
   For six weeks, Gillick has attempted to show no hint of
desperation, rejecting all offers but maintaining there is still
serious interest from multiple clubs.
</P>
<P>
   It is classic baseball poker, heavy on the bluff. His GM
counterpart in Cincinnati, Jim Bowden, knows the game and knows
Gillick has a shaky hand. So he periodically professes in the media
that the deal is doomed, just to see if he can make sweat appear
above Gillick's upper lip.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Bowden claimed to have withdrawn all offers,
citing the need to make moves elsewhere. Wednesday, Bowden was back
dealing with Gillick.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest obstacle to a deal has been the Mariners' refusal to
let prospective trading partners negotiate a long-term extension
with Griffey prior to a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Gillick's explanation is vague, something about messing up trade
talks. More specifically, if Gillick were to allow one team the
right to talk, other bidders would fall away, presuming that a
trade is all but done. But what happens if no contract agreement is
reached between Griffey and the prospective team?
</P>
<P>
   Gillick will be left with even less leverage than before, and
perhaps no market at all, at least for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Gillick needs to have the deal he wants almost in hand before
taking the risk of allowing contract conversation. Even then, the
risk might be too great. He might choose to accept a lesser deal,
rather than chance the blow-up of the entire Griffey market.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, and perhaps as soon as the end of baseball's annual
winter meetings that begin Friday, Griffey seems destined to be
dealt to the Reds. The logic for the teams and Griffey is almost
irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   With a new stadium and its short right-field porch coming for
2003, and the generational link to the days of the Big Red Machine,
Bowden cannot help but end up with Griffey, even if he ends up
bidding only against himself. Bowden must lie awake at night
wondering what it would be like for Griffey to be chasing Hank
Aaron's home run record in another uniform, all because he wouldn't
part with a guy named Pokey Reese.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the risk for the Mariners grows a little each day. As
free agents begin to sign with new clubs, and more trades are
completed, contending teams will have patched holes and be less
tempted to rock the boat with a Griffey bid.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey is said to be growing more impatient, which could mean
that he will be uncooperative with the Mariners as far as accepting
a trade.
</P>
<P>
   And the time spent on Griffey means less time resolving the
situation of Rodriguez, the player that many more teams will bid on
than Griffey, because the Mariners control his rights.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure builds. The drama grows. Maybe a new card player at
the meetings will take the pot.
</P>
<P>
   And no matter what happens, Olerud is around to offer a hug to
the onetime sweetheart.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135 or
artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
