<HEADLINE>
CSUN LOSES FLOWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Aaron Flowers _ whose name became synonymous with
Cal State Northridge football over the past four years, first as a
player and then as a coach _ accepted an assistant's position at
Big Sky Conference rival Montana State on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough because I wanted to build something here,'' Flowers
said about moving on. ``But there's a lot of things (at CSUN) that
are uncertain.''
</P>
<P>
   Flowers, 24, will coach the Bobcats' quarterbacks, the same job
he held at CSUN this past season, when he guided sophomore Marcus
Brady to a 3,000-yard season. Flowers was contacted by new Montana
State head coach Mike Kramrer about the job two weeks ago, and he
was offered the position Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about it (Tuesday night). It's a pleasant surpise,''
Flowers said.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers played only two years at Northridge after transferring
from Valley College in the mid-1990s, but he holds school records
for passing yards in a game, season and career. He had a record 500
yards against Eastern Washington in 1996, a record 3,540 yards that
season and his 6,766 yards is the career mark.
</P>
<P>
   His six passing touchdowns in the Matadors' '97 season opener
against Division I Boise State is also a record.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers became a part-time graduate assistant coach in '98 and
was instrumental in Brady's success as a freshman; Brady threw for
2,983 yards and 26 touchdowns and was named the Newcomer of the
Year in the Big Sky.
</P>
<P>
   __ Other changes:Kearin, who is expected to have the interim
title taken away and be hired full-time within the next two weeks,
said he expects the rest of the staff to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, they're all planning on coming back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin couldn't comment upon the status of assistants Craig Wall
and Keith Borges, who were paid by the university but didn't coach
this past season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Confident QB: Rudy Camano says he's not crazy _ just
confident.
</P>
<P>
   Camano, who is attending Mt. San Antonio College, is
transferring to Cal State Northridge for the spring semester and
he's intending to become the Matadors' starting quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Camano said, he knows CSUN has Brady, who set school
records for completions and attempts this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided I didn't want to be far from home,'' said Camano,
who played at Santa Fe High in Santa Fe Springs. ``I'm just going
to go out and do what I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Camano, a 6-foot-1, 185-pound right-hander, played at Mt. SAC
last year but didn't this season, meaning he'll be an incoming
sophomore. He signed with Iowa State out of high school but never
enrolled, and he was offered scholarships by Syracuse and West
Virginia this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Brady said he's looking forward to the challenge from Camano,
who will participate in spring practice.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN has two other quarterbacks on scholarship: Mitch Ryerson,
who will be a senior next year, and Brandon Martinovic, who will be
a redshirt freshman.
</P>
<P>
   __ Swan song:Brennen Swanson, a defensive end/linebacker who
finished his career with a school-record 31{ sacks, said he was
just happy to be nominated for the Buck Buchanan Award as Division
I-AA's top defensive player. The award went to Troy State noseguard
Al Lucas on Monday in a ceremony in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was excited,'' said Swanson, a two-time first-team All-Big
Sky Conference selection. ``I'm honored just to have been
considered.''
</P>
<P>
   Swanson, who had 12{ sacks and 68 tackles this season, graduates
this month and he said he's interested in pursuing a pro career. At
6-foot-3 and 230 pounds, he's undersized but not unbowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely going to give it a shot,'' Swanson said.
</P>
<P>
   Swanson and four teammates are working out for a New York Giants
scout today. The others: defensive backs Chazz Moore and Mel
Miller, receiver Aaron Arnold and defensive lineman Shawnbay Jones.
</P>
<P>
   __ Just the stats: Arnold, a senior receiver, finished the
season as the school's all-time leader in receptions, receiving
yards and receiving touchdowns. His final career totals: 195
receptions, 2,660 yards and 26 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Brady's final total of 3,326 passing yards this season ranks
second all-time for a single season.
</P>
<P>
   Senior running back Jaumal Bradley, meanwhile, moved to sixth on
the school's single-season chart with 170 yards in the season
finale against Northern Arizona on Nov. 13. Bradley, who finished
with 907 in nine games, also had 1,281 career yards, placing him
sixth all-time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
