<HEADLINE>
KARIYA BROTHERS LONE HIGHLIGHT OF TIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Kariya brothers facing each other for the
first time might have been the feel-good story of the week, but it
didn't take long to realize that Wednesday night's game was just
another chapter in the saga of the unpredictiable and
underachieving Anaheim Mighty Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim was forced to huff and puff just to escape with a 2-2
tie versus the undermanned Vancouver Canucks before 12,488 at the
Pond.
</P>
<P>
   Both Kariyas picked up points. Steve setup Vancouver's first
goal, while Paul scored Anaheim's first. Both also picked up
penalty minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we were missing was a fight,'' quipped Paul.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Ducks' struggles against seemingly overmatched
opponents was the real story.
</P>
<P>
   They needed a special night from the special teams just to earn
a point.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 2-1 early in the third period, Anaheim's 27th-ranked
power-play unit tied the game when Steve Rucchin got in good
position in the slot and converted Teemu Selanne's pass at 5:06. It
marked only the third time this season that Anaheim has scored two
power play goals in a game and the first time since Oct. 21 in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the bright things about the night,'' said Selanne,
who assisted on both goals. ``It was a relief, we have to believe
we can score.''
</P>
<P>
   The way the game was played at even strength, power plays were
opportunities the Ducks couldn't afford to squander.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to see these kind of games,'' Selanne said.
``It was a frustrating game, there were 10 guys in the middle of
the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks' improving penalty-killing unit killed off three more
penalties and has killed 37 of the last 40 power play chances
against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``On nights like this, when nothing is happening, special teams
are so, so important,'' Selanne said.
</P>
<P>
   The Canucks, despite injuries to Mark Messier (knee), Alexander
Mogilny (back), Adrian Aucoin (groin) and Mattis Ohlund (eye
surgery), have led the Northwest Division for most of the season.
Even a roster full of rookies was more than enough to give the
Ducks all they could handle.
</P>
<P>
   The Canucks were content to play safe, conservative hockey all
night. Vancouver generated little offensive pressure, but neither
did the Ducks as the two teams did their best to lull each other
and the sparse crowd to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``To casual observers, it looks boring, but there was no room on
the ice,'' Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg said. ``We had to fight for
every inch of the ice and so did they. It wasn't pretty, but it
wasn't because of a lack of effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Guy Hebert didn't face a shot for the first 6{ minutes and
didn't look ready when he finally saw action. Steve Kariya made a
behind-the-back tip pass to Markus Naslund, who beat a
stunned-looking Hebert through the legs from the left circle at
8:32.
</P>
<P>
   Icings and offsides dominated the second period, but the Ducks'
low-voltage power play broke a 25-play drought when Paul Kariya
converted a penalty _ taken by his brother, of all people.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Kariya came into the game with only eight penalty minutes,
but he was called for elbowing Niclas Havelid and could only watch
as Paul's one-timer deflected off Peter Schaefer and past Garth
Snow at 11:24.
</P>
<P>
   Paul and Steve Kariya lined up next to each other to begin the
game, since Vancouver coach Marc Crawford started Steve at right
wing.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks lost another key member of their defense midway
through the second period when Pavel Trnka suffered a groin strain
and had to be helped to the dressing room. Anaheim is already
without Kevin Haller, who is out with a knee injury and is at least
1-2 weeks away from returning to action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
