<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS FORCED TO CHUCK CHECKING LINE
</HEADLINE>
 ... corrects newspaper affiliations (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Early in the season, the line of Mike Leclerc,
Antti Aalto and Ladislav Kohn was one of the Anaheim Mighty Ducks'
most effective, earning praise from coach Craig Hartsburg for its
aggressive forechecking and impressive work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   But it has been hard to keep the three healthy at the same time.
Leclerc had elbow surgery and missed 11 games in late October and
early November. Kohn injured his groin on Nov. 26 and has missed
the past five games. Now Aalto is expected to be out at least 1-2
weeks with a strained left elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are dropping like flies,'' joked Kohn, who hopes to return
in 1-2 weeks. ``Jimmy Mac (McKenzie) replaced Mike and he broke his
hand (and missed 10 games).''
</P>
<P>
   With Aalto and Kohn out, Hartsburg started a checking line of
Leclerc, Tony Hrkac and Jeff Nielsen on Wednesday night. He also
moved winger Ted Donato to center and played him between Jeremy
Stevenson and Stu Grimson.
</P>
<P>
   Aalto was relieved that an MRI on his elbow didn't show any torn
ligaments. The second-year center was fearful after last Saturday's
game in Phoenix that he had suffered torn ligaments, an injury that
required surgery in January, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting better everyday,'' Aalto said of his elbow. ``I
hope I can be ready in two weeks, but I have to be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Olausson sits: Fredrik Olausson has been a mainstay on the
Ducks' defense since returning to the team last season, but he sat
out his second consecutive game.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg said he sat out the veteran on Saturday in Phoenix
because it would have been his third game in four nights. Wednesday
the coach said he didn't want to change his lineup after the
Anaheim defense played so well against the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys just have to wait their turn,'' said Hartsburg, who
recently scratched Jason Marshall two games in a row. ``Last year,
we had guys banged up and struggling and we had no choice (but to
play them). This year we are going to take advantage of our
depth.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Credit McInnis: Paul Kariya, Teemu Selanne and Olausson got
most of the credit for the Ducks' powerful power play last year,
but Marty McInnis played a key role as well. The winger scored 11
of his 18 goals on the power play. This season, he has scored just
twice and is as frustrated as anybody on the unit that came into
Wednesday's game ranked 27th in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might be pressing because we know it has cost us a couple
of games,'' said McInnis, who added the Ducks must start taking
advantage of aggressive penalty killing units. ``If you can beat a
guy, you can use that aggressiveness to your advantage. . . . We
haven't been able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, McInnis remains optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't get any worse,'' he said. ``Once we get a couple of
goals our confidence will come back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
