r w BC-WTO-WARNING-SFCHRON &LR;      12-09 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-WARNING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOBBY WARNS CAPITOL HILL NOT TO OPPOSE CHINESE PACT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  WASHINGTON _ Following the meltdown of the Seattle trade talks,
the head of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce issued a blunt warning
Wednesday to members of Congress: Any opposition to admitting China
into the World Trade Organization will come at a heavy political
price.
<P>
   This spring _ just months before the November congressional and
presidential elections _ Congress will vote on whether to grant
China permanent normal trading status to clear the way for its
long-sought admission to the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   The debate is shaping up as a huge brawl between business and
environmental and labor groups that will put wavering members under
intense political pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Chamber President Thomas Donohue said the powerful business
lobby sees the China vote as critical to the U.S. economy, and
strongly implied that the chamber would withdraw campaign
contributions and other political support from members who vote
against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're absent on this China vote, it's going to get very
expensive politically,'' Donohue said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you decide that this is the place where you're going to
cost this nation dearly with regard to national security and the
national economy,'' Donohue said, then members voting no ``may find
the 2000 elections more cumbersome than they thought.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a free vote,'' Donohue added at a briefing for
reporters. ``You make this vote at your own peril.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration recently concluded an agreement _
widely viewed as highly favorable to U.S. business interests _
under which China will begin to open its huge markets as a quid pro
quo for U.S. support for its WTO admission.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional approval of China's admission into the WTO was not
considered in real danger until last week, when protests by labor
and environmental groups on the streets of Seattle preceded a
collapse of the widely touted talks among the WTO's 135 member
nations to start a new round of trade liberalization.
</P>
<P>
   These groups, joined by human rights advocates, want labor and
environmental standards incorporated into any new trade agreements,
and many consider China a top violator in each instance.
</P>
<P>
   Unions have made their opposition to China's WTO admission quite
clear already. ``It's a very, very important and consequential
fight for working people around the country,'' said Peggy Taylor,
legislative director for the AFL-CIO in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exactly how we're going to target it and what methods we'll
use are very much under discussion in the labor movement,'' Taylor
said. ``But we are coming out of Seattle with a change in the
public understanding of what's at stake in these trade fights, and
I think the China WTO will be a really important event in that
regard.''
</P>
<P>
   The chamber announced that it is targeting 66 congressional
districts, including several yet unidentified in the Bay Area, for
a grassroots business campaign to push the China pact.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no air war here, just going on the airwaves with
ads,'' said Willard Workman, the chamber's international trade
specialist. ``This will be district by district, in the streets.
This is going to be won.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, however, it's been labor that has won the grassroots
campaigns on trade, and the AFL-CIO's Taylor dismissed this latest
threat from the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't question that this is a high priority for the business
community and they'll throw a lot of resources into it,'' she said.
``I'm just not overwhelmed by their saying they're about to be out
with a big grassroots campaign, because I've heard this too many
times from them.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are split on trade, with centrist ``New Democrats''
such as Contra Costa's Ellen Tauscher and the Central Valley's Cal
Dooley strongly in favor of liberalization, while San Francisco's
Nancy Pelosi and the East Bay's George Miller side with unions and
environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle represents environmental and labor groups' latest and
largest victory in a campaign that has been steadily gaining
momentum. In 1997, unions and environmentalists dealt an enormous
blow to the Clinton administration when Congress failed to approve
the administration's request for ``fast-track'' trade negotiating
authority.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue argued that China will be different, because the China
pact offers tangible and specific benefits, promising a host of
U.S. industries increased access to China's enormous market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are they going to deny that to the e-commerce people, are they
going to deny it to the bank people, to the agriculture people, to
the car people and their workers, to the telephone people?''
Donohue asked.
</P>
<P>
   The Central Valley's Dooley agreed, adding that 110 out of 205
Democrats voted this year for renewing China's ``normal'' trade
status and predicting that next year's China vote would hold 80 to
90 of those votes.
</P>
<P>
   While conceding that unions and environmentalists have picked up
momentum, Dooley said Seattle also served as ``a call to arms for
more pro-trade forces, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a fairly high level of complacency among constituent
groups that support our engagement with China,'' Dooley said, ``and
after what took place in the streets of Seattle, I think pro-trade
factions really fully understand that they have to be engaged in
making the case to members and to the American people on why we
should welcome China into the WTO.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 0353EST &QL; 
