<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 03:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3857 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BRADLEY-INTERNET-SFCH     12-09 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-INTERNET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BRADLEY COOL TO PERMANENT BAN ON INTERNET TAXES  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTCLAIR, N.J. _ Former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, whose
presidential aspirations have been bolstered significantly by
contributors from Silicon Valley, took exception to one of their
priorities Wednesday, refusing to endorse a permanent ban on
Internet taxes.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of a campaign swing through California, Bradley said
it would be irresponsible to do what several of his Republican
counterparts have done and forever rule out Internet taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know what the world is going to look like five or 10
years from now,'' Bradley told a group of reporters during an
interview near his northern New Jersey home. ``How can anyone say
never to anything?''
</P>
<P>
   Seated at a conference table in the principal's office of
Montclair High School (with an untouched hoagie at his side),
Bradley held court for nearly an hour on issues ranging from his
opposition to gay marriage to Pete Rose's controversial campaign to
enter baseball's Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's Internet position is at odds with some high-tech
entrepreneurs who fear that taxes might dampen e-commerce.
Republican presidential hopefuls John McCain and Steve Forbes have
both endorsed a permanent ban. Front-runners George W. Bush and
Bradley's Democratic rival, Vice President Al Gore _ like Bradley _
support a temporary ban.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time in a week that Bradley has refused to
rule out future taxes, leaving him open to GOP charges that he is a
``tax-and-spend liberal.'' Last week, he told the Washington Post
that he would not foreclose the possibility of raising taxes if
needed to pay for his health care plan, though he added that he did
not foresee a any  &LR; need to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The statement also prompted an attack from Gore, which Bradley
characterized Wednesday as a ``political cheap shot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not proposed increasing taxes; I do not propose
increasing taxes,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want honesty, I believe, from their politicians,''
Bradley said. ``When you are in charge of a multitrillion (dollar)
economy, you don't know which way it's going to turn. ... It would
be irresponsible to take the George Bush `no new taxes' pledge.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley arrives in Los Angeles Thursday for a speech on race.
Friday, he will travel to Sacramento and then to the San Francisco
Bay Area for three fund-raisers, as well as an environmental event
in the East Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that Gore holds a 2-to-1 lead over Bradley in
California. But Bradley says that will change when Californians
begin to focus on the race in February, and said his campaign's
emphasis on race, the environment, free trade and technology will
serve him well.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to expound on his opposition to gay marriage, Bradley
said, ``It is not only a legal state, but also a sacrament for a
number of religions.'' He said he supports domestic partnerships to
provide gays all the ``legal, financial (and) inheritance rights
that accrue the state of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is not whether I will recognize gay union, it is how
you recognize gay union, and that is how I prefer to do it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, whose views on the issue parallel his Democratic
rival's, said he opposes the measure on California's March 7 ballot
known as the ``Knight Initiative,'' which would prohibit the state
from recognizing gay marriages, saying it is ``divisive and
contributes to stigmatization.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to distinguish himself from Gore, Bradley said there are
differences on the issues _ such as health care and gun control _
that exemplify ``different styles of leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   On both matters, Bradley said his own proposals are bolder, and
accused the vice president of being too cautious. ``In basketball,
we used to say that some people basically sit on a lead,'' he said.
``I think he's playing it too cautious.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign wasted no time responding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore has been on the court for the Democratic Party for the
last seven years, scoring points improving health care, building
schools, building a strong economy,'' Gore spokesman Chris Lehane
said. ``It's been Sen. Bradley who has been in the stands, not even
on the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   At the conclusion of the 55-minute session, Bradley, who played
professional basketball for the New York Knicks for 10 years, was
asked whether he supports a plea by Pete Rose, accused of gambling
on baseball, to be admitted to baseball's Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said with a pained, yet pensive expression.
``Probably not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
