<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3969 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-SOUTH-1210-COX     12-09 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-SOUTH-1210-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOUTHERN BLACK VOTE KEY TO A GORE VICTORY
 &HT;    880&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If Vice President Al Gore wins the Democratic
presidential nomination, it will be because of the South.
</P>
<P>
   Should he stumble in the early voting in Iowa and New Hampshire,
``Al Gore has looked at the primary calendar and has calculated,
clearly, that the South is where he either wins or stops a rout,''
said Earl Black, a political scientist at Rice University in Texas
and co-author of ``The Vital South: How Presidents Are Elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Gore campaign manager Donna Brazile outlines the primary
strategy against former Sen. Bill Bradley this way: ``Win Iowa, do
very, very well in New Hampshire, make him defend his base in the
East and force Bradley to come South, where we take him on and beat
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Gore rarely lets a week pass without tending to
his Southern political base _ especially African Americans, who
make up 40 percent of the Southern Democratic primary electorate.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, for example, Gore will be meeting with black voters
at the Auburn Avenue offices of Atlanta Life Insurance Co., the
largest African-American-controlled stockholder-owned life
insurance firm.
</P>
<P>
   At that event, Gore is expected to renew criticism that
Bradley's health care proposals could deplete the federal surplus
and jeopardize ``progressive priorities'' that are important to
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   From Atlanta, the vice president flies to Orlando to address the
Florida State Democratic Convention. Florida is one of the Southern
states where Bradley strategists believe they can make inroads, and
Bradley is set to speak to the Florida convention before Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the vice president has some advantages in the
South, but we are organizing,'' said Bradley spokesman Eric Hauser.
</P>
<P>
   The competition is likely to be intense, because whoever wins
the South is likely to win the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Now, most media attention is on the leadoff contests, in Iowa on
Jan. 24 and New Hampshire on Feb. 1. But after those states come
two ``Super Tuesday'' contests in March that could determine the
nomination winner.
</P>
<P>
   The first of these contests, on March 7, is virtually a national
primary with 14 states casting ballots, including the two largest,
California and New York. Also voting that day is Georgia, which
could provide the first indication of how the South is leaning.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later comes South Carolina, another Southern state
where Bradley strategists see possibilities of cracking Gore's
Southern strategy. Gov. Jim Hodges and Charleston Mayor Joseph
Riley, two of the state's most prominent Democrats, are neutral.
</P>
<P>
   And March 14 is the second ``Super Tuesday'' _ a Dixie fest that
features Texas, Florida, Louisiana, Mississippi and Tennessee,
Gore's home state.
</P>
<P>
   By the second Tuesday in March, about 70 percent of the
Democratic Party's convention delegates will have been allocated
between the two candidates. And more than one out of four delegates
to that point will be from the South.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's strength in the South is ``formidable'' in the Democratic
primary, said Merle Black, an Emory University professor and
co-author of ``The Vital South'' with his brother. The largely
white Democratic Party establishment ``knows him well,'' Black
added, and a majority of party officeholders have endorsed him.
</P>
<P>
   Though polls show he is the overwhelming favorite of black
voters, Gore is not taking the African American vote for granted.
His courtship of blacks has been surprisingly intense, in fact,
given the popularity of President Clinton among minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Gore started out his campaign declaring a ``personal
connection'' to the civil rights struggle led by the late Dr.
Martin Luther King Jr. Last month, in the same Memphis pulpit from
which King prophesied his own death in 1968, Gore characterized his
presidential campaign as a force for good ``against evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, the vice president is drawing criticism for such
rhetoric. His critics say he often tries to smear political
adversaries as racists.
</P>
<P>
   Gore ``has been a leader of the race-baiting pack'' in the
Democratic Party, Stuart Taylor Jr., editor of the National
Journal, wrote in the influential political magazine this week.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was incensed by Gore's often graphic descriptions of hate
crimes in his speeches and by Gore's failure to admonish two senior
campaign advisers for recent comments:
</P>
<P>
   _ Brazile, an African American, who vowed in a Washington Post
interview to defeat the ``white boys'' in the 2000 presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   _ Feminist author Naomi Wolf, who claimed last month on ABC's
``This Week'' that ``George (W.) Bush's advisers'' have ``racist''
views.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has long been popular with African Americans, largely
the result of his passion for improving race relations, born of his
long and successful career in the National Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   Only last Sunday, in a sermon to a black church in Iowa, he
promised an administration that would ``set a tone in the air''
promoting racial unity.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore, too, as a senator and congressman from Tennessee, has
a solid record of support for civil rights initiatives. ``Al Gore
has a history of being there,'' said Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., a
civil rights pioneer and Gore supporter.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   When he ran for the Democratic presidential nomination in 1988,
however, Gore ran as the great hope of white conservative Southern
Democrats after the disastrous defeat of Walter Mondale in the 1984
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Democrats engineered the Southern-dominated ``Super
Tuesday'' Democratic primary in 1988 in an effort to wrest control
of the national party from liberals and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore fell far short of expectations in 1988, winning just
under 26 percent of the vote and six of the 19 states in the
``Super Tuesday'' primary that year. The then-Tennessee senator was
hurt by the high turnout of black voters who lifted the Rev. Jesse
Jackson to victory in five states, also with 26 percent of the
primary vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The importance of 'Super Tuesday's' black vote became obvious
in 1988,'' said former Republican National Committee strategist
John Pitney, now a political science professor at Claremont McKenna
College in California. ``The big loser that night was none other
than Al Gore. He learned.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
