<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3972 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-1212-COX     12-09 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-1212-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: MICROSOFT AND THE MEDIATOR
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (f) financial categories for
release Sunday, Dec. 12.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ We are about to find out what happens when a smart
man takes on the task of settling a big antitrust case leveled
against a company co-founded by the richest man in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The brainy fellow engaged with the legal fate of Microsoft's
Bill Gates is Chicago's Richard Posner, who was named to the U.S.
Court of Appeals during the Reagan era and who has been cited by
American Lawyer magazine as ``the most brilliant judge in the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief judges of appellate circuits usually see themselves as
holding down full time jobs, although they often ask their clerks
to draft opinions. Posner is an exception: Aside from his
involvement with Microsoft, he juggles a formidable case load and
writes all his own opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Posner has also written 30 books; the most recent deals with the
impeachment of President Clinton. They include separate
path-breaking classic studies on the links between law and
economics and the links between law and literature. Each year,
dozens of articles, monographs and reviews emerge from his busy
word processor.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, Posner has taught at the University of Chicago Law
School since 1969 and continues to do so, although not full time.
Along the way, he's earned a fortune by founding a successful legal
consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   While Posner yaks it up with prosecutors and Microsoft's
attorneys at Chicago's Standard Club _ the same venue where
Attorney General Janet Reno once said: ``I don't like greedy,
indifferent lawyers'' _ you could ask, if Posner has done all that,
why hasn't he also been named to the Supreme Court?
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that there's a controversial side to Posner that
goes beyond his vaunted ability to translate Sophocles from the
original Greek when analyzing the history of legal theory in
jurisprudential drama.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Posner is the highest-ranking judge to publicly
advocate marijuana legalization as a way of reducing crime. For
another, Posner holds that newborn babies should be bought and sold
on the free market as a superior alternative to
government-regulated adoption. It could be that such views wouldn't
endear him to the Senate Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Less known is Posner's onetime role as a young lawyer on
President Johnson's Task Force on Communications Policy. He wrote a
draft chapter of the final report that advocated spinning off
Western Electric, then the manufacturing arm of the Bell System
monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   When LBJ learned off it, he hit the roof, causing the pioneering
project to receive a fatal blow. All that happened well before
Gates wrote his first litigious e-mail message.
</P>
<P>
   Consider too the matter of the William J. Brennan Jr.
Foundation, created by some of the late jurist's former law clerks
to honor his memory. In 1962, having finished first in his class at
Yale Law School, Posner became Brennan's Supreme Court clerk.
</P>
<P>
   Tax records show that the wealthy Posner has not contributed to
the charitable foundation. On the other hand, should Posner mediate
a bargain, perhaps a grateful Gates would open his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 1033EST &QL; 
