<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 10:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3987 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-GEEWAX-1212-COX     12-09 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-1212-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOOD JUDGMENT PREVAILS AS Y2K ``MOMENT OF TRUTH'' APPROACHES
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A year ago at this time, journalists were
struggling with their own Y2K problem: how to tell people about the
computer software bug without sounding overly alarmist or
complacent.
</P>
<P>
   Write too many stories about Y2K stockpiling and we might start
a stampede to the grocery store. Do too few stories about the
seriousness of the programming flaw and business owners might
ignore Y2K until it was too late to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   Now with the Midnight Moment of Truth nearly here, polls suggest
the media may have gotten the story about right. Awareness of the
Y2K bug is extremely high, with polls showing nine out of 10
Americans know about it. Considering that two years ago, most
people would have guessed that Y2K was a new and improved personal
lubricant jelly, that's a remarkable change.
</P>
<P>
   But while Y2K has become a household word, only a fraction of
households plan to take extreme action, such as yanking their
savings from the bank. A recent poll conducted by the Gallup
Organization found most people are planning to take only prudent
steps, such as making copies of financial records in case of
computer glitches caused by the bug after Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago at this time, many ``trend watchers'' insisted Y2K
stories, along with promotions for New Year's Eve parties and
concerts, would trigger all sorts wild reactions. Some forecasters
said that by mid-December 1999, federal troops would be restraining
mobs of panicky shoppers at grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   Gary North, a religious fundamentalist who started a popular
Internet site on Y2K bugs, predicted that ``months before January
1, 2000, the world's stock markets will have crashed.''
</P>
<P>
   Others who saw New Year's Eve 1999 as the ultimate party
opportunity predicted that business owners would be shutting down
factories and offices in the week's leading up to Dec. 31 because
so many employees would be missing work to party in the streets.
</P>
<P>
   But now well into December 1999, the buzz word for the month is
buzz. As in buzzzz, zzzzz, snore. Store shelves are piled high with
foods and banks operate normally.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K has stirred up a sensible concern about computer
reliability, rather than a panicky rejection of technology. And the
marketing efforts to spur lavish spending on New Year's Eve parties
seem to have rekindled a desire to stay home with loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   As the mellow millennium approaches, consumer confidence is
rising, the stock market is soaring and computers are continuing to
boost our affluence.
</P>
<P>
   The trend watchers tried hard to figure out where we would be
heading at the end of the century. But there was one mega-trend
coming that no one saw: a widespread outbreak of good judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 1046EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 10:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
