A3990 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN-COX     12-09 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Conservative challenge to Miranda threatens to
restore brutish legal system
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court has, dangerously, decided to revisit the
historic 1966 Miranda ruling. Dangerously, because it will be a
close call in the current conservative court whether this
fundamental protection against coerced confessions can survive.
</P>
<P>
   Miranda requires police to tell criminal suspects they may
refuse to answer investigators' questions and may have a lawyer
present when they are interrogated _ the familiar ``You have a
right to remain silent...'' liturgy of crime shows.
</P>
<P>
   The court established the rule to reduce the then-constant legal
wrangling over whether this confession or that was truly voluntary
or whether it had been beaten or scammed out of a suspect in
violation of the Constitution's protection against
self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   This late challenge to Miranda is based on a law Congress
enacted two years after the ruling, quashing the requirement. No
administration of either party has enforced the law, judging it
plainly unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Congress had been panicked by police and prosecutors predicting
a general collapse of criminal cases, but while Miranda has
certainly freed some criminals _ every civil-liberty protection
does, beginning with the right to a jury trial _ the fact that
prison populations are setting record highs just about annually has
proven the fear groundless.
</P>
<P>
   Police have long since accommodated to the rule. Indeed, it
forced an up-grade in police skills. And prosecutors, thanks to
Miranda, are able to win convictions that are more resistant to
appellate reversal.
</P>
<P>
   The assault on Miranda is being pushed for purely ideological
reasons, simply because conservatives hate it; always have, always
will.
</P>
<P>
   Reactionary Justice Antonin Scalia all but invited the challenge
in comments from the bench, and conservative legal activists found
a happy home for their test case in the Virginia-based,
arch-conservative 4th Circuit Court of Appeals, which bought the
argument that Miranda never really had constitutional standing and
amounted only to a court-ordered rule of evidence, reversible, as
constitutional rulings are not, by congressional act.
</P>
<P>
   This conservative sport is at the potential real-world expense
of one of the crucial elements of fairness in a criminal justice
system whose fairness is spotty even when the system is on its best
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to remember now, thanks precisely to Miranda,
the degree to which courtrooms in the past were busy with suspects
whose confessions were the product of stationhouse abuses, forced
by everything from rubber hoses to harassment, intimidation and the
denial of legal counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The disproportionate victims of that brutish system were, as
always in such matters, the poor, the ill-educated, the dim and the
rootless. There was another victim, too: the criminal justice
system itself. The broad public respect any legal system must have
to be fully effective was undermined by abuses Miranda largely
ended.
</P>
<P>
   How queer that a return to those practices is somehow deemed
``conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
