<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gunning for the governor's job
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Back in Texas' one-party Democratic days, and
even since, large ambitions have collided in primary elections. In
1982, for example, Attorney General Mark White, Railroad
Commissioner Buddy Temple and Land Commissioner Bob Armstrong all
ran for governor.
</P>
<P>
   As Republican fortunes have risen, the competition for
nominations has grown. In 1998, for instance, the candidates for
the Republican nomination for attorney general included Supreme
Court Justice John Cornyn, Railroad Commissioner Barry Williamson
and Republican State Chairman Tom Pauken.
</P>
<P>
   In 2002, the GOP ambition collision could be for governor _
between U.S. Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, up for re-election to the
Senate next year, and Lt. Gov. Rick Perry. That's particularly true
if Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who calls his current job ``the best
in the world,'' doesn't win the presidency next year.
</P>
<P>
   Perry, 49, is already raising a bankroll _ the size of which he
won't reveal before he has to _ toward running for governor in
2002, regardless of Bush's fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush wins, Perry moves up to governor, and he thinks
Hutchison would defer to him. ``Senator Hutchison has been rather
clear in her expressions of support for me and our friendship,''
Perry said recently. ``And also, if there is an incumbent governor
there, she would not consider running.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. Maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   Perry cites a report of an August interview Hutchison had with
The Dallas Morning News editorial board as an indication of her
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, she sounds reluctant to run if Perry is governor. But
Hutchison, 56,certainly doesn't rule it out.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she told the News she'd rather be governor than
senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you said to me, `You can _ in an open field with no other
issues _ run for governor or run for senator,' I'd rather be
governor,'' said Hutchison, who like Perry served in the Texas
House of Representatives and held another statewide office. Friends
say she's tired of the partisan rancor in Washington and would
rather spend more time in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Texas. I love working with people who love Texas, and
it's my area. ... But it's not an open field, and it's not a
decision that would be made in a vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   Just days before she'll file again for the Senate seat she's
held since 1993, and with $6 million plus already banked for that
race, Hutchison would sound overly ambitious if she said she's
eyeing the governorship. But some Republicans think she could win a
GOP primary, even against Perry. Meanwhile, the Democrats are still
scratching their heads about who to run against her for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But Hutchison, whose name identification will soar after
spending millions on TV ads next year, doesn't rule out a run for
governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to close the door, but it's not something I'm
looking at,'' Hutchison said last August. ``And it's not a probable
at all. ... I'm not saying I'm not going to do anything, but
probably I will serve out my term if I'm re-elected, and that'll be
that.''
</P>
<P>
   When the question was asked a few days ago, Hutchison press aide
Lisette McSoud Donnello came back with essentially the same story:
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, she cannot foresee a circumstance in which she
would challenge a Republican incumbent governor. Other than that,
she's not looking at a race for governor, but she's not closing
doors or options beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her long-term future options are open, but she is focused on
doing a good job in the Senate. She's not looking to change that
course at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   A year is a lifetime in politics. We'll see what a difference
two years makes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
