<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: Picking up their marbles
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Greeks want to pick up their marbles and go home. These
marbles are the famed Elgin ones on display in London since the 7th
Earl of Elgin picked them up at bargain Acropolis prices a couple
of hundred years ago. The deal amounted, more or less, to theft.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Elgin, British ambassador in those parts, was an admirer of
Greek antiquities. He visited the Parthenon, liked what he saw and
decided to take the best of it home. He offered the Turkish
governor a pittance and a tidy sum on the side for his trouble. The
governor, who didn't think much of the stuff, was pleased to agree.
Ergo, the ``Elgin'' Marbles!
</P>
<P>
   The phlegmatic British weren't thrilled at first, but have since
defended their ownership with high Victorian dudgeon. They've been
claiming that the marbles are in better shape than they might have
been had the Greeks kept them, an argument a petty thief couldn't
get away with. Wrong, said the Greeks recently, you messed them up
in the 1930s ``restoring'' them.
</P>
<P>
   For Pete's sake, give them back already.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
