<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4000 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-HURRICANE-FORCAST09-C     12-09 0289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-FORCAST09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Earlier hurricanes predicted next year
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Next year's hurricane season may produce
fewer storms but may start earlier, a leading forecaster said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In their annual forecast, released Wednesday, Professor William
Gray and his team at Colorado State University predicted a
``moderate'' season in 2000. They predict 11 storms will reach at
least tropical storm status and gain names, with seven becoming
hurricanes and three becoming major hurricanes with sustained winds
of at least 110 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Gray predicted 14 named storms, nine hurricanes and
four major hurricanes; there were 12 named storms, eight hurricanes
and five major hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   Gray never predicts whether or where storms will strike land.
But he did say the Atlantic Coast has a 45 percent chance of being
hit by one or more major storms next year.
</P>
<P>
   The forecast calls for fewer storms than occurred in 1995, 1996,
1998 and 1999. But the years 1995 through 1999 marked the most
active five-year stretch on record in the Atlantic, with 65 named
storms, 41 hurricanes and 20 major hurricanes. And 1999 was the
first season on record to produce five major hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   Gray, a professor of atmospheric sciences who has issued the
forecasts for 16 years, also predicted the 2000 hurricane season
will start earlier. This year, Arlene, the first named storm,
developed in June, but the next storm didn't show up until
mid-August, when four hurricanes formed.
</P>
<P>
   The season runs from June 1 to Nov. 30, reaching its height in
early September.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
