<P>
   SAVE TIME: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available for
purchase in paginated form: http://nytsyn.com/syndicate/pageex
</P>
<P>
   EMAIL _ E-mail compulsion. How many times a day do you check
your e-mail at work? How much time does it actually take? What's
the ratio of personal/work e-mail? Let's CHAT to some people who
are e-mail junkies. Maybe a psychologist will tell us that e-mail
is the obsessive/compulsive enabler of the '90s. (Gallaga, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   EMAIL-LIST _ List of places that offer free e-mail. (Gallaga,
Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   EMAIL-AVOID _ Ways to avoid e-mail. (Gallaga, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   ES-INTRO _ A cosmic-sounding intro that looks at the phenomenon
of online shopping, its future and how it is changing our lives and
our shopping habits. Written with some verve and snap. (Vejnoska,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 14. MOVED. WITH ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ES-TIPS _ Frances Katz gives her top shopping site picks. (Katz,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 5. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ES-BOTS _ A list. Online shopping is tedious and often way too
time-consuming unless you know what you want and where to get it.
You can find yourself clicking through pages endlessly. But if you
know what a ``bot'' is and how to use it, they can help do some of
the sorting for you. This is a listing of the top bots and short
intro telling you what they can do for you to save time. (Halicks,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ES-INTERNATIONAL _ The first W in WWW proves to be a boon for
e-shoppers, who can find things at international sites they can't
find at the domestic sites. How to navigate the international
sites. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ES-BESTSITES _ Some of the best online shopping sites we could
find, everything from oddball sites to luxury sites to sites that
offer products in a host of categories, including music, DVDs and
videos, books, clothing, accessories, sporting goods, cookware,
department stores, food, toys and pets. 29 categories and 157
listings in 225 inches. (Rizzo, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-FREEPORT _ FREEPORT, Bahamas _ Late-season Hurricane
Lenny churned in the Caribbean, forcing two huge cruise ships to
dock in Freeport. Passengers groaned about the unexpected change in
course to a backwater port no one knew anything about. But once on
land, they were far from irate. They roamed the duty-free shops of
the International Bazaar and Lucayan Market, found their own
private spots on more than 120 miles of white sand beaches, and
gambled at the Moroccan-style Princess Resort. But the biggest
surprise was the high style of the new Lucayan Reef Village Hotel.
These day guests were awed by the wild shapes of the
Alice-in-Wonderland furniture _ sofas with backs high enough to
accommodate Shaquille O'Neal, club chairs sporting exaggerated
curves and wind-surfer sails attached to the ceiling _ and a
two-story restaurant with chairs and wall paintings in colliding
tropical colors. (Palm Beach Post). 40. MOVED. WITH
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-FREESHOP _ FREEPORT, Bahamas _ Sidebar to
TRAVEL-FREEPORT. Of course you could do your holiday shopping at a
suburban mall, pushing your way through the crowds, paying the high
prices and, under the harsh glare offlorescent fluorescent lights,
browsing the same American merchandise in store after store. Or ...
You could go to Freeport. There, fresh from a walk on the beach and
wearing a sarong over your swimsuit, you could roam the
flower-lined lanes of the International Bazaar and Port Lucaya;
shop in more than 150 duty-free boutiques; and find European, Asian
and South American gifts that might be scarce in your local
shopping center. From Bahamian hand-blown glass figurines to
Italian perfume, Lenox fine china, aged alcohol, Cuban cigars and
Gucci and Fendi leather bags, you'll find it here. (Palm Beach
Post). 35. MOVED. TRAVEL-SEAJET _ FREEPORT, Bahamas _ Last month, I
flew over to the Bahamas. But without the airplane. I took the
SeaJet Kara, a 250-passenger Boeing JetFoil, one of only two
operating in U.S. waters. The SeaJet, a hydrofoil, flew from West
Palm Beach to Freeport going 50 mph and riding 14 to 16 feet above
the water. Palm Beach Post). 25. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet Travel page for the current week.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL 1207 -- Boston's gilded age rolled in with
horse-drawn trolleys and out with electric subways. For a ride back
to the turn of the century, just follow the tracks. (Reid, Palm
Beach Post) Art includes 5-column art headline treatment, a
2-column color-tinted photo of a line of conducters in 1917, a
color-tinted photo of a painting of a Boston scene.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: GROVE PARK CHRISTMAS -- The Grove Park Inn in Asheville,
N.C., does Christmas in big way (Langhenry, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes a 18pica color photo of singers
at the Grove Park Inn.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS -- The Center of Science and Industry in
Columbus, Ohio, has opened a new riverfront facility. (N.Y. Times
News Service.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BERMUDA _ BAILEY'S BAY, BERMUDA _ A quick walking tour of
Bermuda: Twenty-one miles of scenic right-of-way is all that's left
of the Bermuda Railway, which operated for only 17 years after
earning the dubious distinction of being the most expensive
railway, per mile, ever built. My wife and I walked the 1.75-mile
section of what's now known as the Railway Trail, one of Bermuda's
most visitor-friendly attractions. We were greeted by teenagers
sneaking smokes on the way home after school, and we stopped to
chat with farmworkers harvesting potatoes in a field. We got to see
where Bermudians work and live, close up, which was a far cry from
the confines of the beach resort where we were staying. (JDSmith,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 12.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-OPELIKA _ OPELIKA, Ala. _ A visit to Opelika, Ala.,
which is sponsoring a Victorian Front Porch Christmas event. In
addition to its charming Victorian homes, Opelika offers plenty of
Southern hospitality via its inviting antique stores and gift
shops. (MJohnson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
