<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-GREED _ When director Erich von Stroheim was a newly
arrived immigrant to America, one of the first books he read was
Frank Norris' fascinating 1899 novel McTeague. It's the story of an
amiable lug from Placer County, Calif., who becomes a dentist in
turn-of-the-century San Francisco, then begins a long, slow slide
into lethargy and degradation that culminates in him murdering his
miserly wife and dying a hunted fugitive in Death Valley. OK, so
it's not a laugh riot. But it is a virtuoso piece of naturalism, a
shock to the system of the then-prevalent Victorian style, and a
book that can still be read with pleasure. (Palm Beach Post).
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-BOOKS _ A few best bets for holiday books. (Eyman, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-VIDAL _ ``I don't like talking about myself,'' Gore Vidal
told his official biographer when their partnership began. ``And
certainly not about private matters. So I don't know how you're
going to do this because there isn't anything there.'' For his
part, Fred Kaplan preferred his subjects dead. But the academic
author of well-received biographies of Thomas Carlyle, Charles
Dickens and Henry James trudged dutifully on, and now we have
everything that isn't there in this 796-page _ not counting the
index _ biography. Gathering things that aren't there is no easy
task _ ask Edmund Morris about Ronald Reagan _ and Kaplan has done
as fine a job as anyone could fairly do, and with a good deal more
intellectual integrity than Morris. But in the end, Kaplan doesn't
fail his subject so much as his subject fails him. At 75, Gore
Vidal is a senior member of that increasingly endangered species,
the professional literary man. Beginning in 1946 with Williwaw, a
short novel based on his World War II service in the Aleutians, he
has done a bit of everything in the writing field, and not without
spirit. (Palm Beach Post). 35. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL-STORIES _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Even for a
triviaphile, John ``Blue Moon'' Odom's version of how he got his
nickname isn't an especially exciting nugget. But it becomes oddly
compelling when it's presented in Odom's own neat handwriting, with
``Oakland A's 13'' written beneath his signature and a business
card thrown in from Blue Moon Painting Service that notes the
proprietor is a ``Former Pitcher/Oakland A's.'' He is calling
attention to his past glory. Yet, in doing so, we do not see
another preening athletic ego but an ordinary man taking deserved
pride in the extraordinary moments of his past. That's often the
effect in Seth Swirsky's second disarmingly simple volume of
baseball correspondence, ``Every Pitcher Tells A Story.'' (Bennett,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-YEARSBEST _ A roundup of the year's best books: art books,
fiction, nonfiction, bios, etc. (OBriant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS (jackets and art from books).
40.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-KIDS _ Following several controversial top-book lists for
adults, Scholastic issues its 200-best-books-for kids list.
(Harris, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 8.
</P>
