<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4006 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-HOLIDAY-BOOKS10-COX     12-09 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-BOOKS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A book holiday
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ This year's contribution to the typical
seasonal mixture of pricey, shelf-busting art and design books is
something a little special, something, now that I think of it, a
little too special: books about the 100 Greatest Men and Women, 100
Greatest Artists, 100 Greatest Movie Stars, etc. _ of the century.
</P>
<P>
   They all make mildly interesting scanning, but they're more a
function of marketing and our culture's compulsive, insecure need
for self-definition than of anything organic. Did 1899 offer a
succession of books about the Greatest Men and Women of the 19th
Century?
</P>
<P>
   Doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   Now, on to the good stuff:
</P>
<P>
   ``Century'' (Phaidon) is one of the most interesting books of
the year, a massive (more than 1,000 pages) collection of
photographs, one to a page, that seem predominantly weighted toward
violence, deprivation, and other permutations of the
through-a-glass-darkly view of human existence as chosen by editor
Bruce Bernard. There are few famous photographers (the exceptions
include Mapplethorpe and Leni Riefenstahl), just a succession of
stark, often brutal photographs. A grueling but fascinating book
that comes in its own packing case, which, given its 13-pound
weight, is mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``War in the Pacific: Pearl Harbor to Tokyo Bay'' (Oklahoma) is
a beautiful book evenly split between period pictures and modern
color shots of World War II uniforms and gear. Perfect for readers
of Stephen Ambrose or Tom Brokaw.
</P>
<P>
   For those with a bent toward entertainment, ``Will Rogers: A
Photo Biography'' (Taylor) offers a good one-stop overview of the
beloved American humorist/philosopher/movie star/trick roper and
all-around good guy who once said, ``I hold only two distinctions
in the movies, being the ugliest man in 'em, and still having the
same wife I started out with.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Edward Hopper: The Watercolors'' (Norton) continues the surge
of attention devoted to one of the most idiomatic American artists,
who captured loneliness as well as anybody ever has. (I was
surprised to discover that Hopper painted the Libby House in
Portland, Maine, a fascinating, eccentric Victorian mansion that's
open to the public and very much worth a look.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Egyptian Treasures'' (Abrams) draws its material exclusively
from the Egyptian Museum in Cairo. Except for the fact that a
three-dimensional object in the museum never looks exactly like it
does in a two dimensional photograph, this is a definitive book
about a definitive collection. The book also contains an
interesting history of the museum, as well as a breakdown of the
Dynasties and Pharaohs.
</P>
<P>
   There's some inevitable overlap with ``When the Pyramids Were
Built'' (Rizzoli), but ``Pyramids'' concentrates on art of the Old
Kingdom, i.e. 2650-2150 B.C. It's actually a catalog of an exhibit
at New York's Metropolitan Museum that I'm sorry I missed. The book
offers more proof that Egyptian art of the Pharaohs remains
unsurpassed for formal beauty and craftsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   George Rodrigue's ``Blue Dog'' paintings are strangely
compelling. ``Blue Dog Man'' (Stewart, Tabori &AMP; Chang) is a sort of
autobiography and offers a wide selection of Rodrigue's noncanine
paintings, as well as dozens of the Blue Dog _ actually, his dog
Tiffany _ in various permutations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paris 360'' (Random House) continues the series by
photographer Attilio Boccazzi-Varotto of panoramic exterior photos
of a given spectacular city. Viewed strictly as photography, the
photos are nothing but calendar art, but their scope makes them
valuable. And it is Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, ``The First Time I Saw Paris'' (Times) is a
collection by photographer Peter Miller that stems from the '50s,
when he first arrived in town to assist photographer Yousuf Karsh.
Writer Stanley Karnow insists that the '50s were the last great
time in the last great city, but the truth is that the best times
in Paris are whenever you're young. The photos, all black and
white, are highly evocative. And Miller's account of his loss of
virginity is delightful.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the Crowd Goes Wild'' (Sourcebooks) is a collection of the
most celebrated sports events ever broadcast. The book comes with
two CDs (narrated by Bob Costas) in which the actual broadcasts can
be juxtaposed with the stills and analyses in the book. Hank Aaron
contributes a forward in which he says that Vin Scully is the
greatest announcer going. Smart man.
</P>
<P>
   Ever notice how much Rosie O'Donnell looks like Lou Costello?
That's just one of the random observations that occurred to me as I
leafed through Annie Leibovitz's ``Women'' (Random House).
Leibovitz often strains for effect and uses too many gimmicks _
nudity, props, costumes, white face _ but she's very good when she
keeps it simple.
</P>
<P>
   As The Hermitage in St. Petersburg, Russia, is frankly
inaccessible for most people, a book like ``French Art Treasures at
the Hermitage'' (Abrams) can be as close as you'll get. The art
involves everybody from Rodin to Matisse _ the Hermitage has a
particularly fabulous collection of Matisse _ and the presentation
is up to Abrams' high standards.
</P>
<P>
   Two photo collections of our embattled neighbor to the south are
``Havana'' (Prestel) and ``Cuba'' (National Geographic). Hans
Engel's photographs in ``Havana'' seem to have the edge for me
because of their consistent sense of desolation and absence of
humanity, the better to concentrate on the architecture. Both books
are richly evocative of that beautiful country and its charming,
vivacious people.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the most beautiful of the gift books of 1999 is ``Van
Gogh in Provence and Auvers'' (Hugh Lauter Levin). The paintings of
the artist's later period are, of course, familiar, and part of the
world's consciousness, but they have never been more luxuriously
packaged.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
