<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ES-BOTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Bots' do comparison-shopping for you
 &HT;    By Richard Halicks
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Your boyfriend insists that the Pretenders' ``Learning to
Crawl'' was the best album of the 1980s, and you want to find the
CD online for him.
</P>
<P>
   You can go to www.amazon.com or www.cdnowcom. Both have it. But
try this instead: Go to www.mysimon.com, click on the music link
and follow the search instructions. A couple of clicks later, this
site gives you a list of 23 online vendors, their prices and a
``buy'' link to each site.
</P>
<P>
   You learn that ReviewStore.com has the best price ($5.73 vs.
$11.49 at Amazon); a click on ``buy'' takes you to the site and
directly to the page on ``Learning to Crawl.'' You're ready to do
business.
</P>
<P>
   You've just used a shopping bot. Bot is short for robot _ a
search program that goes looking for what you want. Most shopping
bots are free of charge and easy to use, and they can save you time
and cash.
</P>
<P>
   Mysimon.com is only one of dozens of bots _ www.botspot.com
links you to 59. They work in different ways, but most perform the
same essential function: Bots find retailers who sell what you want
to buy, and they enable you to comparison-shop.
</P>
<P>
   A few bot cautions:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Many bots have some kind of deal with online retailers, and
that deal may limit what you get to see. Some retailers may be
paying a given bot to list them first on the results page, or a bot
may not list retailers at all if they're not being paid to do so.
You may or may not be getting the best price or selection, but you
can solve this by checking more than one bot.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bots' price lists often do not include taxes, shipping or
handling (www.jango.com and www.bottomdollar.com do), and those can
vary widely.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bots will dredge up stores you've never heard of. If a store
unknown to you has the best price, check them out: What's the
return policy? Does the store have a secure transaction server?
Does it have a toll-free customer service line? The site should
tell you all this about itself. The store's price may beat
amazon.com's, but the store itself may not even approach Amazon
when it comes to reliability and customer service.
</P>
<P>
   Some good shopping bots:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.mysimon.com: Known as the bot to beat and vilified in some
quarters as being too cute. Covers millions of products at
2,000-plus stores.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.shopfind.com: Yahoo!'s bot is one of the few that lets you
search immediately for what you want (rather than drilling down
through various categories). And it's fast.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.rusure.com: You can download its software free to your
desktop. When you push the buy button on a piece of merchandise at
any shopping site, rusure automatically goes to work in the
background, finding comparison prices at other sites and displaying
them at the top of your screen.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.jango.com: Part of the Excite network. Very fast, very
businesslike interface (few or no graphics to gum up the works).
Also lists shipping/handling costs. Doesn't offer books or music.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.dealtime.com: Enables you to choose product, price range
and time frame; searches for the period you specify and notifies
you of the results (by email, pager or by free software you install
on your desktop).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Visit www.smartbots.com or www.botspot.com for a comprehensive
listing of shopping bots.
</P>
<P>
   SITES IN THIS ARTICLE:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.amazon.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.cdnow.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.mysimon.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.reviewstore.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.botspot.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.jango.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.bottomdollar.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.shopfind.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.rusure.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.dealtime.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.smartbots.com
</P>
<P>
   Richard Halicks writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
