r f BC-ES-INTRO-COX     12-09 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ES-INTRO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Signs of the season: Americans rush to finish shoppng, but this
year they're jumping online
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ What's next, www.sitonsanta.com?
</P>
<P>
   That's about all that's missing during this holiday season, when
not a creature is stirring in many a house except for a mouse. A
computer mouse, to be precise.
</P>
<P>
   On Amazon, on e-Bay, on Egghead and Yahoo
</P>
<P>
   On AOL, on eToys, on Excite and hullabaZoo ...
</P>
<P>
   Those are but eight of some 700,000 e-commerce sites floating
around cyberspace, ready to take holiday gift orders to the tune of
(choose one, because the experts sure can't) $6 billion, $11
billion or even as much as $15 billion.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 23 percent of all Americans will shop online this
year, including, he says, President Clinton. And if you don't
believe life as we know it is about to change completely, then
consider how much we'll all miss those breathless news accounts of
the leader of the free world's last-minute dashes with the Secret
Service through a mall to buy Hillary a sweater on Christmas Eve.
</P>
<P>
   The mall still may be the only place to go to experience a few
of the more classic yuletide moments _ buying an overpriced photo
of your bawling child perched on Santa's lap, for instance, or cat
fighting over discounted cashmere. But in every other way, it's
beginning to look a lot like an Internet Christmas. Present and
Future.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't touch it when you buy it online,'' conceded Juanita
Kauffman of Dunwoody, Ga. ``But you don't have to gift wrap it
yourself, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Kauffman, her two adult daughters and 2-year-old
granddaughter were in Lenox Square on the Friday after
Thanksgiving, the traditional first Christmas shopping day of the
year. Basically, they were there to see Santa and, in at least one
daughter's case, do a little e-connaissance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to the store first and check it out and then I go home
and order it online,'' explained Megan LeBlanc, who lives in
Chicago, while her sister and niece live on St. Simons Island, Ga.
``It makes shipping gifts to them all much easier.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't even have to be Scotch tape-challenged to be tempted.
Just be 12th on line for Starbucks coffee, sixth and idling for
valet parking, or merely thisclose to smacking some surly
salesperson upside the head and suddenly, you find yourself
desperately wanting to join the Surfer in Chief and the rest of the
e-lite.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually. There's still plenty of time till the 24th, after
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``He plans to shop online as the holiday season approaches,''
Steve Boyd, a White House spokesman, said several days after
Clinton's radio broadcast about his e-commerce intentions. ``At
this point, he hasn't done any official shopping yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's beginning to look a lot like every other
Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE SALES EXPLODE
</P>
<P>
   This holiday season may well be remembered as the year online
sales, e-tailing (from retailing), e-commerce and e-shopping hit
the public consciousness big time. Here's a sampling of information
and projections for the phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Online spending last holiday season
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $5.9 billion
</P>
<P>
   (Source: Direct Marketing Association)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $8.2 billion
</P>
<P>
   (About Women &AMP; Marketing, April 1999)
</P>
<P>
   PROJECTION:
</P>
<P>
   By 2003, online sales are expected to grow to $78 billion
</P>
<P>
   (Source: Jupiter Communications)
</P>
<P>
   Average online spending by sex,
</P>
<P>
   1998 holiday season
</P>
<P>
   Females Males
</P>
<P>
   $495 average$260 average
</P>
<P>
   (Source: Infobeads.com, Jan. 26, 1999)
</P>
<P>
