A4028 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-ES-TIPS-COX     12-09 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ES-TIPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Suggestions to keep and worthwhileBy Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shopping online can be fun, it can be a timesaver, and it can
even save you money. But before you start your e-shopping
adventures, here are some key points to keep in mind.
</P>
<P>
   1. SECURITY: Most reputable Web retailers have secure ordering
forms to protect your personal information. They'll let you know
you are ordering via a secure connection. They also offer detailed
information about their security policies. If you aren't sure if a
site offers security, think twice before placing an order.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a good idea to check with your credit card companies
about security options they offer. For example, American Express
will not hold card members responsible for unauthorized charges
online. Nor are you responsible for the first $50 in unauthorized
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   2. PRIVACY POLICY: Technically, there's no law preventing any
Web site from giving out personal information about you to anyone
who asks. This includes everything from your mailing address to
your credit card number and even your shoe size. However, most
retailers are sensitive to shoppers' privacy concerns. Make sure
each site you visit has a privacy policy. Most of them do.
Companies like TrustE (www.truste.org) offer more privacy
protection tips.
</P>
<P>
   3. PRICE/ VALUE: Shopping online can save time, but not
necessarily money. Comparison shop online just as you would at the
mall. If $75 seems like too much for a sweater, shop around for the
best deal. Shopping search engines like Bottom Dollar
(www.bottomdollar.com) will help you find the best bargains.
</P>
<P>
   4. DELIVERY POLICY: Most online purchases are shipped to arrive
within five to seven days. However, if you are in a hurry, you can
have things sent overnight or for a second-day arrival. If you do
want your items delivered quickly, remember, it's going to cost
you.
</P>
<P>
   5. CUSTOMER SERVICE: Most sites have automated e-mail systems
that tell you when they received your order, when they sent it and
when it is expected to arrive. Some e-tailers will send you postal
tracking numbers for your reference if there's a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be afraid to e-mail or call a site's customer service
department to ask questions, ask for clarifications or inquire
about an order. Make sure there's an e-mail address or at least a
phone number to call in case you have questions or concerns about
your order.
</P>
<P>
   6. RETURN POLICY: It's still possible, even in the age of
technology, to purchase a sweater in the wrong size or toys that
were never on anybody's Christmas list. Don't assume the stores at
the mall will accept returns from their online counterparts; in
many cases, they won't. KBKids.com will let you bring online
purchases back to the mall, but Barnes &AMP; Noble won't. Make sure you
know the return policy before you hit that ``submit'' key.
</P>
<P>
   7. UNDERSTAND THE ORDER PROCESS: Remember, your order isn't
final until you hit the ``submit'' key. If your Internet connection
seems slow, or nothing seems to be happening, you might be tempted
to keep hitting ``submit'' as you would the buttons on an elevator
that just won't close. Don't do it! Each time you hit submit, you
could be creating another order. One click is all usually all you
need.
</P>
<P>
   SITES IN THIS ARTICLE:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.truste.org
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.bottomdollar.com
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
