<HEADER>
A4071 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-MISS-JULIE-REVIE     12-09 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MISS-JULIE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MISS JULIE' SUCCEEDS WITH FEROCIOUS PUNCH
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box at bottom) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Miss Julie,'' August Strindberg's 110-year-old play about
inter-class hanky-panky gone horribly awry, perfectly fits Mark
Twain's description of a ``classic'' as a book that everyone
praises but nobody reads. If you've read it yourself, you already
know why.
</P>
<P>
   Bleak and uncompromising, Strindberg's play ordinarily makes for
a tough 2 hours of sitting still. Neither of its two main
characters _ Miss Julie, the delusional, headstrong daughter of a
wealthy Swedish count, and Jean, the count's ruthlessly ambitious
footman with whom Miss Julie has a disastrous erotic encounter _ is
the sort of person you'd likely want for a best friend.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Strindberg's script is strewn with topical
references to 19th-century Swedish politics that have lost their
rhetorical punch over the years, to put it mildly.
</P>
<P>
   All of which makes Mike Figgis' ferociously acted, splendidly
intelligent new film version of ``Miss Julie'' triply surprising
and impressive. For my money, this intimate chamber drama, shot
entirely in Super 16mm on two roving hand-held cameras, is among
the most emotionally vital and visually sensual of all Hollywood
stage-to-screen adaptations. Ever.
</P>
<P>
   Set on the cusp of the modern age in Europe, when the rich had
electric lights and telephones but the servant classes still lived
like serfs, ``Miss Julie'' is, on one level, an upstairs-downstairs
cautionary fable about a potentially ill-fated rendezvous between
social unequals, a kind of Nietzschean, gender- and power-reversed
``Pygmalion'' by way of ``Lady Chatterley's Lover.''
</P>
<P>
   Figgis, however, has rightly decided to pare away much of the
play's period political context, which is implicit in the
characters' behavior anyway. Wisely, he keeps the movie's focus
relentlessly locked on Miss Julie (Saffron Burrows), Jean (Peter
Mullan) and a secondary yet critical third character, Christine
(the excellent Marie Doyle Kennedy), who is Jean's secret lover and
the count's cook. Like some meticulous, slightly demonic chef,
Figgis raises the movie's psychological temperature by degrees,
until the actors squirm and the audience has no choice but to
immerse itself in the perverse pleasures of Strindberg's
overheated, intriguingly sadomasochistic vision.
</P>
<P>
   Structurally similar to ``Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?'' the
action of ``Miss Julie'' takes place within a single night,
virtually all of it spent in the count's cavernous kitchen, which
Figgis, cinematographer Benoit Delhomme and production designer
Michael Howells colorize with a melancholy Scandinavian palette.
</P>
<P>
   This is where Miss Julie has come to upbraid Jean for deserting
her at the servants' dance, depicted briefly as a wild, earthy
bacchanal that represents the antithesis of the tight-corseted
propriety that is Miss Julie's birthright.
</P>
<P>
   The erotically simmering mis-en-scene is established from the
moment Miss Julie bursts in on Jean, interrupts his nuzzlings with
Christine and impulsively slaps his face. While this action is
merely a prelude to the physical and psychological brutalities that
follow, it whets the audience's appetite for a compressed evening's
worth of kinky, 19th-century variations on ``truth or dare.''
</P>
<P>
   Blessed with gorgeous, pre-Raphaelite looks and a statuesque
physique, Burrows here proves she has the actorly goods to match
her copious physical gifts. Displaying a previously untapped
emotional depth, the actress (who had minor roles in ``Deep Blue
Sea'' and Figgis' ``One Night Stand'') brings to mind a young,
reckless Liv Ullmann in her portrayal of the slumming aristocrat
who yearns for the imagined ``freedom'' of the poor but shirks from
the nitty-gritty reality.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ibsen's Hedda Gabler, Miss Julie is a pre-modern woman with
a Machiavellian streak, caught between the rock of centuries-old
sexist conditioning and the hard place of a society whose liberated
rhetoric hasn't caught up with its politics. Burrows makes Miss
Julie's dreams of escape with Jean feel as heartbreaking as they
are futile.
</P>
<P>
   Though several inches shorter and a good 10 years older than the
script implies, Mullan's calculating, intensely compacted Jean is
well-matched as Burrows' sexual adversary. This superb
Scotland-born actor, best known for his performance as a recovering
alcoholic in Ken Loach's ``My Name Is Joe,'' leaves no stone
unturned in his exploration of Jean's alternately tender and
brutal, witty and remorseless character.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of the dialogue may be difficult to follow for those
unfamiliar with Strindberg's original play, particularly in the
scene in which Jean penetrates Miss Julie while disgorging his
plans to whisk her away to Switzerland and open a hotel. Needlessly
spliced into distracting split-screen images, this crucial scene _
seduction or rape? _ is fascinating to watch, but much of its sense
gets lost amid Jean's carnal gruntings.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from such rare miscues, however, ``Miss Julie'' uses film
to take us places that Strindberg's play could only hint at. Figgis
and his team have created a ``period'' film with the stinging
immediacy of a contemporary love story. &QL; 
____ &QL; 
The film: ``Miss Julie'' (R; profanity, sexual content). &QL; 
The stars: Saffron Burrows, Peter Mullan, Maria Doyle Kennedy. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Mike Figgis. Screenplay by Helen
Cooper, adapted from the play by August Strindberg. Produced by
Figgis and Harriet Cruickshank. Released by United Artists. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 40 minutes. &QL; 
Playing: Cineplex Beverly Center in West Hollywood. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 1234EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4103 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-GREENMILE-TEX     12-09 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GREENMILE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENLIGHTENED GUARDS, RACIAL STEREOTYPES CLASH IN PRISON YARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the poster of ``The Green Mile,'' Tom Hanks looks like he's
liquefying, as if he's been greased up with 10W-40. The movie,
adapted by writer/director Frank Darabont, appears to have been
lubricated, too, to make its three-hour-plus length less painful.
(The Stephen King story that serves as the basis for ``Mile,''
serialized as six short novels a few years ago, seems to have a
layer of lard between all the lines.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Green Mile'' is death row (a mixture of death row being
known as ``the last mile'' and this prison's green floor, which
looks like ``faded limes.'') Hanks plays a prison guard in
``Mile,'' and the story has as unearthly a setting as the horror
stories that King is best known for.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks is Paul Edgecomb, a kindly head death-row guard at a
Louisiana prison in the 1930s, and the distaste he and his fellow
guards have for abuse and mistreatment of prisoners seems a little
out of place. We see it when new death row inmate John Coffey
(Michael Clarke Duncan), a hulking black man convicted for the
murder of two little white girls, is brought in.
</P>
<P>
   Simple-minded but deeply, innately good, Paul immediately
divines that Coffey doesn't belong there. It may be the only thing
that happens with any immediacy in ``Mile.''
</P>
<P>
   In the movie ``Bowfinger,'' the angry, paranoid movie star
played by Eddie Murphy rails on about the kinds of parts it takes
to get an African-American actor serious consideration: ``Black
dudes play a slave ... they get the (Oscar) nomination. White boys
play an idiot and they get the Oscar. Find me a script with a
retarded slave and then I'll get the Oscar.''
</P>
<P>
   He could've been scanning the ``Mile'' script, where the John
Coffey character is a simple-minded but good-hearted black man of
the period, who calls everybody ``boss.''
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly not inaccurate to portray black people of the
period, those from the South especially, in such a manner. But it's
a little peculiar, and insulting, to have such a depiction of a
black man while most of the prison guards _ who work ``in a
prison,'' in the South, in the 1930s _ are forward-thinkers without
a bone of racism in their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   (You half expect Paul to teach the slow-witted Coffey that
reading is fundamental before the inmate has to walk the ``Green
Mile'' to the chair.)
</P>
<P>
   Although Duncan brings an enormous amount of dignity to the
role, it's embarrassing to watch a black man play what Murphy's
character would've called ``Buck the Wonder Slave.''
</P>
<P>
   The other men awaiting the walk to the electric chair in ``The
Green Mile'' act as if extra juice is already coursing through
their veins. Michael Jeter is a lovable Cajun who, if he weren't
cute enough, is given another dollop of sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   In his last days, he takes to teaching an extra-bright mouse
tricks, and the little fellow, named Mr. Jingles, gets nearly as
much screen time performing his tricks as the humans do. (The mouse
could be the Shawshank Rodent.) Sam Rockwell is an evil inmate who insults through a set of teeth stained yellow with what
looks like a coat of Sears Best Latex, like a country-fried
Beetlejuice.
</P>
<P>
   The other prison guards, including Barry Pepper, David Morse and
Jeffrey DeMunn, are nondescript, good-hearted men. (With the
exception of Doug Hutchison as the weaselly, sadistic guard
Wetmore, who at least gets to show some enjoyment of his role. He
inflicts flamboyant punishment when he gets his chance to supervise
one of the executions.)
</P>
<P>
   What Darabont has done with his first two movies as a director
is created the smallest specialty in the history of pictures; he
turns Stephen King prison-based novellas into movies. (He made his
directing debut with ``The Shawshank Redemption,'' which came from
King's story ``Rita Hayworth and Shawshank Redemption.'')
</P>
<P>
   He's adept at working King's penchant for mixing genres and
nuggets from well-known movies and books in these stories. (Coffey
is part Lenny from ``Of Mice and Men,'' with a mystic gift that
makes him part Christ figure as well; just look at his initials, in
case you miss the point.) There's also a deep strain of sentimental
cruelty to heighten the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Coffey is revealed as a childlike figure with healing hands.
(The way he takes on suffering and expunges the rot from his system
_ it explodes in a shower of what looks like deteriorating confetti
_ is particularly photogenic.)
</P>
<P>
   Paul's instinct is right: Coffey is innocent and will die for a
crime he didn't commit. (The scenes of the crime are so cranked up,
unlike the low-key tone ``Mile'' exhibits elsewhere, that they're
cringe-inducing.) And Coffey's death continues to haunt Paul today;
he narrates ``Mile'' from a retirement home. Darabont and Hanks
team for what could be called ``Frying Private Ryan,'' a
heartwarming melodrama about sacrifice, both from the man who has
to die for others' sins and the men who have to stand by and watch,
against their better instincts.
</P>
<P>
   Darabont is a skillful filmmaker who has a hard time editing
down his embarrassment of riches. As a result, ``Mile'' seems to be
pro- and anti-capital punishment. The actors are well-handled,
though Hanks is becoming so minimal in his effects that, if this
continues, he'll do his next part in his sleep.
</P>
<P>
   The length comes partially from Darabont's intention to show the
routine of prison life, though one of the best sequences comes when
Harry Dean Stanton joins the guards for a businesslike rehearsal of
an execution. It's ironic that the most effective scenes in ``The
Green Mileeconomical. It's also ironic that you could
probably finish reading ``Mile'' before the film is over.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The Green Mile''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Frank Darabont
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Tom Hanks, Michael Clarke Duncan
</P>
<P>
   Length: 182 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ adult language and situations and violence, including
a scene of a botched electric-chair execution
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
