<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4119 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-SKI-SAFETY-BOS &LR;      12-09 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-SAFETY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEED LIMITS IN PLACE AT RESORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not too many years ago at Killington, a speeding skier or
snowboarder might get a mild reprimand from a ski patroller. It was
a somewhat casual enforcement, patrol officials acknowledge, and
whenever the question of lifting a ticket came up, ``we'd give
skiers every benefit of the doubt,'' according to Killington
spokesman Steve Wright.
</P>
<P>
   This was pretty standard policy throughout ski country: Try to
maintain safe conditions, but also let skiers have their fun. At
the sprawling twin resorts of Vail and Beaver Creek in Colorado,
the wild west spirit of point-'em-straight-down-and-go was widely
hailed as a skier's creedo for many years.
</P>
<P>
   But times change. This year at Killington, says Wright, ``the
ski patrol has the freedom to pull someone's ticket immediately if
they see the person acting recklessly.''
</P>
<P>
   And at Vail, Killington's Western counterpart, the National Ski
Patrol has added a new safety squad called the Yellow Jackets,
dedicated to busting the fast and reckless. To date this season,
they have snatched more than 50 tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for a new industry-wide campaign called Safety
Initiative 2000 or ``Heads Up'' may not have as much to do with
reality of skier safety, as public perception.
</P>
<P>
   Four agencies _ the National Ski Areas Association, Nial Ski
Patrol, Profesional Ski Instructors of America, and Snowboard
Industries _ all had a hand in creating the Heads Up campaign as a
unified effort to minimize skiing and snowboarding accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cornerstone of our safety message is that each one is
responsible for the choices (he makes) on the slopes,'' says Stacey
Gardner of the Ski Areas Association. ``Skiing is relatively
serious, and you have to be paying attention.''
</P>
<P>
   But the campaign has little to do with trends or fatality
records. Since the 1970s, reportable injuries on the slopes have
been cut nearly in half. Better grooming, wider trails, and better
equipment in the last 30 years of skiing's growth all are part of
the safety picture.
</P>
<P>
   Skier fatalities or catastrophic accidents have been relatively
steady at about .8 per million skier visits. In an average winter,
about 50 million skiers and boarders hit the slopes, and the
average of 34 fatal crashes has been fairly constant. Last year, 39
deaths occurred in US ski country, highest number in the last four
years, but the year before, there were only 26 skier/rider
fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   In part, the big safety push came because, according to National
Ski Areas of America spokesman Michael Berry, ``we're confronting
an old addage, `perception becomes reality.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, when Michael Kennedy and Sonny Bono died in ski
crashes in the Rocky Mountains, the media attention focused on
skiing as never before, Berry said. ``It didn't matter what the
safety record had been up to that time. Because they were
celebrities, there was a new focus on skier safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim White, educational directorfor the National SkAreas
Association in Denver and one of the architects o Heads Up, says
the campaign is largely aimed at people unfamiliar with figures
showing skiing to be among the safer outdoor sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that people are getting the wrong message about skiing
when all they hear about in the media is the most serious
incidents,'' said White. ``Our goal is to get our message out that
the industry has a wonderful safety record.''
</P>
<P>
   The sport has always suffered from the perennial broken leg
joke. Just this year, said White, a commerical was released showing
a busload of happy skiers showing up at the lodge. The next frame
shows the bus returning ``with the skiers in neck braces, full body
casts, and dripping IV,'' White med.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that is how perceptions are created for people outside the
sport,'' he said. ``The LA Times and Wall Street Journal printed
some negative (editorials), and that is what we're trying to
confront with Heads Up.''
</P>
<P>
   White, Berry, and members of the National Ski Patrol agree that
Heads Up is not a new approach as much as an intensification of
what has been ongoing safety policy at ski areas.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, they point out, most ski areas have established
``slow skiing'' zones, though enforcement has been uneven.
</P>
<P>
   White does not advocate a zero-tolerance policy that would
summarily tear the tickets off speeders. He would rather see
enforcement of the safety code on a case-by-case basis, and have
judgment become a part of the ski patroller's education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps for the first time (a skier or rider) breaks the
rules, he will get his ticket mark, then get it pulled on the
second offense. It's a case-by-case thing,'' said White.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real message to people is that we are on the hill with
eyes that are watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the National Ski Areas Association does not take
a definitive position on helmets, whose popularity has soared the
past two years, a fact often attributed to the Kennedy and Bono
deaths, which were caused by head injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take the position that helmets are a personal choice. A
helmet is a piece of equipment just the same as the equipment on
the feet and under them,'' said White. ``They certainly are not the
whole picture. We would be concerned if people feel a helmet is the
one answer to safety.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 1327EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4120 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-09 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ROUT LIKE THIS IS A SIGN OF HOPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ If you were an, ahem, a, um, Pete Rose kind of guy,
this was your certified Mortal Lock.
</P>
<P>
   You had the visiting team, a nice middle-of-the-road NBA entry,
coming off surprising back-to-back road victories. You know it
really isn't good enough to win three road games in a row,
especially against reasonable competition and, as a clincher, while
playing their third game in four nights.
</P>
<P>
   Then you had the home team, a nice middle-of-the-road NBA entry,
rested and well-prepped. This was a neon-lit set-up to you and me,
although not necessarily to Rick Pitino.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to expect from young people today,'' he
said. ``I really don't.''
</P>
<P>
   We do know this: In Pitino's NBA fantasy world, this bunch will
some day stroll into the Staples Center, the Delta Center, the Rose
Garden, or the Alamodome and play a game like the one they played
Wedneday night. If that ever happens, then he and his fans will
know that the Celtics have truly come all the way back.
</P>
<P>
   But you've got to start somewhere, so let the record show that
the Celtics have at least reached the point where, in their own
house, they have the power to abuse what really isn't a bad team at
all. t leads stretching as high as 36 (90-54), their wire-to-wire,
hee-hee, ho-ho, ha-ha, 115-90 demolition of the Denver Nuggets was
a pistol-whipping of the first order.
</P>
<P>
   The FleetCenter gathering of 15,730 saw the Celtics put up
season-high totals in points, field goals, steals, and assists.
Ball movement was, in fact, the key to everything. Their assist
total of 33 was the highest Celtic number in 92 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two things I love to watch,'' said Pitino, ``are good passing
and good defense.''
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of both encompassed in the inspired play of one
man _ Paul Pierce, wo had six of his game-high eight assists in the
first half, when the Celtics moved to a comfortable 62-41 lead.
Pierce's head was up and his eyes were scanning the floor,
searching for cutters, lurkers, and under-the-basket loiterers. The
Nuggets are not exactly known for their interior defense, and the
Celtics made them pay for their continual defensive sinning by
racking up six layups and/or dunks among their first seven baskets,
with Pierce setting the tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were sending two guys at me, so I knew people were
open,'' Pierce said. ``I just dribbled out of the trap and looked
around.''
</P>
<P>
   He also made sure there wouldn't be any storybook return to his
roots story for Ron Mercer by blocking his first two shots
(jumpers, too, not layups). Mercer, who only wanted to dump on
Pitino as badly as Bob Kraft wants to be a local hero, was held to
one miserable basket in 24 forgettable minutes of (in)action.
</P>
<P>
   Denver coach Dan Issel was ready for the Boston media jackals.
``We did not lose this game because of the way Ron Mercer played,''
he declard. ``That certainly was ot the case. He had plenty of
help.''
</P>
<P>
   There actually was a pretty good story lineinvolving a jilted
player. It just didn't happen to be Mercer. It was Tony Battie,
who, when he left Denver, was not exactly hailed as the second
coming of Alex English.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, he's been playing more like a poor-man's Kevin McHale,
bounding off the bench to supply inside scoring, rebounding, and
extraordinary energy. His 15 points and 12 rebounds last evening
represented his fourth consecutive powerhouse game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never had a game like that when he was in Denver,'' snorted
Issel, who was a Denver broadcaster during Battie's only season as
a Nugget.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me I had a game against Boston in which I almost
had a triple-double,'' replied Battie, ``so right away you know
that statement is false.''
</P>
<P>
   Score one for the jock. On Feb. 10, 1998, the 6-foot-10-inch
Battie had 10 points, 13 rebounds, and 8 blocks in a Denver triumph
over Pitino's Celtics. It was one of only 11 Denver victories
during that lost season and it surely must have been burned into
Pitino's consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   So we know what Battie can do. But in order for him to become a
quasi-McHale, he'll have to kep putting up these numbers on a
regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   Right now Pitino is cautiously optimistic. ``We think we have a
budding basketball player in Tony Battie,'' is as far as he's
willing to go at the present time.
</P>
<P>
   His mates are a bit more exuberant. ``He's been huge for us the
past three or four games,'' said Pierce. ``He's starting to realize
his potential. He's definitely working harder in practice. I can
see it in his eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Battie is certainly saying all the right things. Who does th
sound like? ``I'd rather come off the bench. I can study the game
and bring that excitement into the game with fresh legs and a fresh
body.'' That's what a certain Herman Munster-looking guy used to
say all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, this was an old-fashioned, crowd-pleasing, Celtic
exhibition of basketball grace and power, complete with a superb
garbage-time performance by Chauncey Billups (16 points, 3
rebounds, 3 assists in the fourth quarter alone).
</P>
<P>
   Next up: a battered Houston team missing Hakeem Olajuwon, and,
sadly, Charles Barkley. That should be another lock, right?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Rick, we know. They're kids. No one has any idea what to
expect. And that's the gospel truth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
