A4131 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-CATHOLIC-BASHING-CONG     12-09 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLIC-BASHING-CONGRESS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NO POPERY,' SAYS THE U.S. CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    In the 19th century, ``no popery'' was a popular political
slogan in the United States. Because the nation's Protestant
majority feared the power of the fast-growing Roman Catholic
minority, anti-Catholic candidates won seats in Congress by
condemning the Roman church.
 &HT;    Using political means, Protestants legally enforced
discrimination against Roman Catholics. By warning of the tyranny
of the pope and evils of the church, they often incited violence
against Catholics -- especially priests, monks, and nuns.
 &HT;    Who would have guessed that echoes of ``No Popery'' still
resound in the halls of Congress?
 &HT;    Last week, the House of Representatives chose the Rev. Charles
Parker Wright, a Presbyterian minister, as their new chaplain.
Wright was last on a list of three candidates selected by a
bipartisan committee to fill the vacancy. The first candidate, and
overwhelming choice of the selection committee, was the Rev.
Timothy J. O'Brien, a Roman Catholic priest.
 &HT;    Although the post of House chaplain was created in 1789, no
Catholic has ever served in that capacity. With the O'Brien
recommendation, Congress was set to make history.
 &HT;    Despite the committee's recommendation, however, House Speaker
Dennis Hastert (R-Ill.) and House majority leader Dick Armey
(R-Texas), both Protestants, chose Wright over O'Brien, citing
Wright as ``the one who would jell the best with the members (of
the House) and their families.''
 &HT;    Rep. Anna Eshoo (D-Calif.) stated, ``As a member of the House
and a member of the committee and as a Catholic, I'm offended and
resentful.''
 &HT;    O'Brien remarked, ``I'm not convinced that the prejudicial view
is gone, and I do believe that if I were not a Catholic priest I
would be the House chaplain.''
 &HT;    A Roman Catholic chaplain would not pose a problem for most
Americans. The majority of Protestants live in blissful ignorance
-- or embarrassed regret -- of their ancestors' discriminatory
past. Indeed, earlier this autumn, Lutherans and Roman Catholics
issued a joint statement, a kind of theological peace treaty,
proclaiming their agreement over some of the concerns that had
divided them since the 16th century Reformation. The U.S. Congress
might have celebrated this happy ecumenical moment with O'Brien's
appointment.
 &HT;    Hastert and Armey chose not to make history. Instead, they chose
to revisit America's sad history of anti-Catholicism.
 &HT;    Hastert and Armey's primary constituency is that of conservative
evangelicals and fundamentalists associated with the religious
right. Unlike their more liberal Protestant kin, they are neither
ignorant of, nor embarrassed by, past tensions between Protestants
and Roman Catholics.
 &HT;    Theologically, conservative Protestants do not believe that
Roman Catholics are ``saved.'' Catholics, so the argument runs, are
not ``born again'' (only those ``born again'' can be assured of
heaven). Instead, Roman Catholics depend on sacraments and good
works for salvation. This, conservative evangelicals believe, is
contrary to the Bible.
 &HT;    Thus, Catholics must repent of their sins (and usually their
association with the Catholic Church) in order to avoid eternal
damnation. Catholics are prime targets for evangelistic crusades.
 &HT;    Politically, however, conservative Protestants have often found
common cause with Roman Catholics. In the last 20 years, these
traditionally hostile groups worked together opposing abortion,
divorce and homosexual rights. During the heyday of the Christian
Coalition, Ralph Reed tried to form a Catholic Alliance as an arm
of the larger organization. He recognized the political power that
unity between conservative Protestants and Catholics promised.
 &HT;    But all attempts at bridge-building failed. In this case,
politics did not triumph over theology.
 &HT;    That Hastert and Armey were unable to shake anti-Catholic
prejudice should surprise no one. Hastert attended Wheaton College,
an evangelical school with few Catholic students and no Catholic
faculty members. There, Catholic doctrine -- particularly when
Hastert was a student-- would not have been presented
sympathetically.
 &HT;    Armey, even during his interview with O'Brien, confessed, ``I
was raised in North Dakota where there's lots of Lutherans, who
always complained about Catholics.''
 &HT;    During the final interview, O'Brien complained that he ran into
an ``evangelical Protestant line of questioning,'' including being
asked his favorite Bible verses and how hard it must be to be an
unmarried priest.
 &HT;    The only surprise is how ignorant these men are -- and from that
position of ignorance they are making public policy. These are the
same people who want to reinstate prayer in school and post the Ten
Commandments in classrooms?
 &HT;    To those of us with eyes to see, the O'Brien debacle reveals the
theology behind such an innocent-seeming agenda -- they want to
make all Americans into their image of what a Christian should be.
 &HT;    God help them. They really needed a Catholic priest. A rabbi, an
imam and a Buddhist monk probably wouldn't hurt, either.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.1999 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass writes a religion column for the Santa
Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious studies
at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is ``Standing
Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th Century
America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
