<SLUG> BC-WORCESTER-TRAGEDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHANGING CITY IS UNITED BY FIRE GRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ It was supposed to be part of the revival,
this giant brick warehouse half-eaten by fire.
</P>
<P>
   A short distance from the Worcester Common Outlets mall and the
shiny new medical center, the 72-year-old hulking cold storage
building would find new life as a biotechnology headquarters,
another player in this city's glossy, high-tech future.
</P>
<P>
   But many say the tragic fire that roared through the Worcester
Cold Storage and Warehouse Co., killing six firefighters, has
jolted booming Worcester back into the past, back into its
small-town, neighborly ways.
</P>
<P>
   A city with rapidly diversifying interests is connected again by
a single, tragic event.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday the city was expected to come to a virtual standstill
as more than 20,000 mourners, including President Clinton and
firefighters from around the world, gather to honor the fallen men.
People are expected to line the streets to observe a solemn
processional.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as the tribute takes place, the comrades of firefighters
Paul Brotherton, Jeremiah Lucey, Lt. Thomas Spencer, Joseph
McGuirk, and Timothy Jackson, 51, will continue to pick through the
still-smoldering building for their remains. And the sprawling
warehouse seems even more a relic of the past _ a piece of
Worcester's industrial history, the site of an outpouring of grief
and support that has made this city of nearly 170,000 feel much
smaller.
</P>
<P>
   Where it not for the disaster, the warehouse might be a fitting
symbol for a city teetering between yesterday and tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Worcester is a city dotted with red brick warehouses, bound to
its manufacturing past, but aching to reap the economic benefit of
a modern, high-tech economy. It is a city whose residents boast
about their homespun image, but grumble about their dead downtown.
</P>
<P>
   And it is a city that is changing, as medical centers fill old
warehouses, construction sites spring up around the downtown
streets, and the suburbs swell with young families.
</P>
<P>
   Signs throughout the city announce that ``Worcester Builds''; a
pristine, refurbished train station seems especially clean and
white next to an elevated highway and rusting railroad bridges.
Construction is nearly complete to give Worcester a more direct
connection to the Massachusetts Turnpike _ something New England's
second-largest city has never had.
</P>
<P>
   Residents are aware of the transformation, and some are wary of
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like living here because it's kind of low key. People are
mellow. Everybody knows each other,'' said Bill Bertel, 42, who
works at a produce market near the fire-ravaged warehouse. ``The
city's growing up, though.''
</P>
<P>
   But throughout Worcester talk of the future has come to a
temporary halt as people focus on the painful task of mourning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anywhere you go, it's the first thing people talk about,''
said Phil Niddrie, public affairs manager for the Worcester Area
Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   And Worcester, a city with no major sports teams and that boasts
few recent celebrities, now has a half dozen homegrown heros to
look up to.
</P>
<P>
   Residents are eager to pay tribute to them, to participate in
the grieving. Following the advice of a local radio station, many
turn on their headlights during the day to honor the victims.
Businesses hang signs in tribute to the six fallen firefighters,
whose pictures are displayed on a giant billboard near downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day and into the night, a constant stream of
people makes the pilgrimage to the sight of the deadly fire.
Parents bring small children, who carry flowers. Some stand across
the street from the warehouse, staring straight ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen at Worcester's Central Fire Station is overflowing
with gifts: cakes, cookies, bread, pasta, cases of soda, cards from
schoolchildren. In the station, the atmosphere is reunion-like;
current firefighters mingle with alumni and talk about days gone
by.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, they talked about the men who have been lost. Amid
the packages of food is a picture of Paul Brotherton, 41, who died
in last week's blaze. He and his six sons stand in a row on a
beach, their backs to the camera. They are bronzed by the sun, and
each one has pulled down his bathing suit just far enough to show
his tan line, and maybe a little more.
</P>
<P>
   The firefighters talk about Brotherton, how funny he was, how
crazy. But when a new colleague comes through the door to pay
respects, they stop laughing for a moment and hug each other, hard.
</P>
<P>
   At the station, emotions are heightened by exhaustion. There are
memorials to plan, and fires still to fight; Wednesday afternoon
the engines went screaming out toward a small one.
</P>
<P>
   And in between, they spend hours at the warehouse where the
search continues and the fire still burns. Half the building is
gone and yet the flames remain, fed by piles of debris inside. By
day, smoke dribbles out from the brick walls. By night, the windows
glow orange and hot.
</P>
<P>
   It's not nearly the enermous blaze the Rev. Joseph A. Coonan
watched from his rectory window at St. John's Church last Friday
night, but it is demoralizing nonetheless, he said. Because the
fire still burns, and spotlights flood the area with an eerie glow,
and the remains of the all six fallen firefighters have yet to be
found, Worcester is still grief-stricken, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The compassion of people coming together from everywhere is
the positive part of this,'' he said. But ``people are sad. Very,
very sad...There has been a cloud over the city since Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   Good can come from such sadness, Coonan said, but bad can come,
too. Because a pair of homeless people, it is alleged,
inadvertently set the fire, he fears a backlash against the other
homeless who live in vacant buildings throughout the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   And even if this fire spurs efforts to help the homeless, he
said it will come as part of a pattern that repeats itself in
Worcester: A willingness to address big problems only after tragedy
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to call it an after-the-fact city,'' he said. ``When
something terrible happens after the fact we start looking for
resolution to things.''
</P>
<P>
   Worcester may not be the only city to behave that way, Coonan
concedes but the graying long-time schoolteacher, who became a
priest 10 years ago, admits he has borne a slight grudge against
his hometown for decades. It started when city officials refused to
let the Grateful Dead play in town.
</P>
<P>
   They were fearful of ``Deadheads,'' hippies, of newness, of
change, he said, a parochialism that left him bitter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is another side to Worcester's parochialism that
leaves many residents glowing _ the friendly, know-your-neighbors
side that makes people reach out to each other. It's the impusle
that spurs the firefighters union to build wheelchair ramps for
free at the homes of disabled children in the city. It's the
impulse that has brought forth so many donations and gifts and warm
feelings this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're seeing around this fire isn't really that
remarkable,'' for Worcester, said Jim Caradonio, the city's
superintendent of schools. ``The generosity and soul is just
expanding to the enormity of the tragedy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
