<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARNER'S SITE IS BOTH FLASHY AND FRUSTRATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time Warner's new Web site, Entertaindom.com, is a gigantic
digital theme park, with flashing lights, scrolling headlines, and
throbbing graphics. Ladies and gentlemen, check out the latest
Looney Tunes! Get your horoscope here! Step right up and play ``Ask
Dr. Science,'' a new Web show where you get to send queries to a
cartoon character with a big beard, a big ego, and a big mouth.
Don't be shy! Step right up!
</P>
<P>
   After a week spent playing around in this land of sensory
overload, I have a few questions for the good doctor:
</P>
<P>
   Why doesn't ``Ask Dr. Science'' run when I press the start
button? Why does my browser keep crashing? Why do I keep getting
error messages? Why is this thing so slow? Why am I tempted to
throw this computer across the room?
</P>
<P>
   And, by the way, is this the fun part yet?
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Warner Bros. Online, the long-awaited Web site is
the biggest effort to date by a Hollywood studio to present
entertainment content on the Internet. Certainly, Warner Bros.
deserves credit for being the first major studio to launch such an
aggressive on-line experiment _ but the key word here is
experiment. All week, the much-hyped site suffered the kind of
slowdowns and snafus that have become typical with Web debuts
(remember Victoria's Secret?).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some Internet pundits have hailed the site as the
dawn of a new age in entertainment, making one wonder if they
actually looked at the content _ a collection of articles from Time
Warner publications, cartoons, animated spoofs, and clips from
``The Monkees.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros. Online president Jim Moloshok acknowledges that the
site is a work in progress and that the programming will evolve,
just as it has in other media.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are creating the first generation of the next generation of
entertainment,'' he says. ``This fits into the Warner Bros.
tradition. We were the first to go from silent movies to talkies
with `The Jazz Singer.' And when TV was coming out in the early
'50s, other studios refused to produce for television, but Warner
Bros. went out there and created a huge collection of programs.''
</P>
<P>
   But is it really possible to compare the Internet with the
invention of talking pictures and the early days of television?
Let's just take television. In the '50s, folks flocked to
neighbors' houses to watch ``The Milton Berle Show,'' with the kind
of urgency usually reserved for national disasters or the Super
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a phenomenon,'' says television historian Alex McNeil,
author of ``Total Television.'' ``People would watch test patterns
because it was a completely new medium. It was unprecedented to
have sound and pictures coming into your home. People thought it
was amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, there are things about the Internet that continue to amaze
even the most jaded of users. (For starters, the research tools
alone make it so much easier to cheat on crossword puzzles.) But
does anybody really think the ability to watch Bugs Bunny on a
computer screen is awe-inspiring? Or is anyone really bowled over
by the opportunity to wait and wait to download the free software
needed to watch a short interactive Superman saga in 3-D animation?
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, but for today's sophisticated media hounds, this stuff
just isn't amazing _ and it isn't unprecedented. Most of the
technologies used on Entertaindom.com are available in small doses
on other Web sites. And other Internet start-ups, such as Digital
Entertainment Network and Pseudo.com, have tried (somewhat
unsuccessfully) to grab viewers with on-line entertainment. Last
year, cartoonnetwork.com launched a series of Web cartoons that is
similar to some of the fare being offered on Entertaindom.com.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to get users hooked to one or more of the features
so that they come back. The show with the most potential is ``The
God and Devil Show,'' an irreverent cartoon that features the deity
and the demon as talk show hosts.
</P>
<P>
   The first ``guest'' is aging rocker Keith Richards, a Rolling
Stone who has gathered a fair share of moss. Next week's ``guest''
is Ghandi, who looks like he's auditioning for the role of
Superman.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the irreverence, the satire is predictable and not
exactly cutting-edge comedy. The idea is a good one, but the show
cries out for better writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``God and Devil'' also has some interactive elements that are
amusing for a few minutes. At the end of each Web-isode, viewers
vote whether to send the guest to heaven or hell. The show also has
a bulletin board where users can post reactions to each episode,
which lasts just a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But it takes almost as long to register for the boards than it
does to watch the show; it's hard to imagine anyone eager to have a
spirited on-line debate about a five-minute cartoon.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a toll-free number where callers can leave messages
for the Devil, a she-demon in a fetching red miniskirt. So here's
our message for the Devil: ``Hey, babe. Nice outfit. You and the
folks at Warner Bros. score points for trying. But when will
on-line entertainment be less about gimmicks and more about
gripping stories? And by the way, can you help us get in touch with
Dr. Science?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send mail to cyberlinks(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
