<HEADLINE>
A CRITIC'S CHOICE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Janet Maslin and Vincent Canby were on their way to
an early screening of ``The Godfather Part III.'' The crowd outside
the theater was filled with excitement. Maslin, who would be
reviewing the film for The New York Times, confessed to Canby that
she was, too. Her Times colleague replied, ``Actually, I'd rather
be excited on the way out.''
</P>
<P>
   Excitement on the way out might double as a description of
Maslin's life these days. In September, after nearly three decades
of reviewing movies for a living, 22 of those years at the Times,
and the last 6 as the paper's senior critic, she announced that
she'd be leaving at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday the Times named Elvis Mitchell, movie critic for the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram, and A. O. Scott, Sunday book critic for
Newsday, to succeed Maslin, thus putting to an end a minor media
tizzy that had rumors being speed-dialed from Hollywood (She's
being forced out!) to Times Square (She inherited a million
dollars!) and back again.
</P>
<P>
   The more interesting story, though, has little to do with
bold-face names in gossip columns. It's about a successful
middle-aged person who, feeling the need for a change, decided to
do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really embarrassing to be this much of a cliche,'' Maslin
says during a recent lunch at a midtown Manhattan restaurant. ``But
(this year) my father died, I turned 50, I wanted to smell the
roses. . . . It's the career equivalent of hang gliding. That's
what it is really. Most people when they do something like this
have something else in mind (for what's next). I'm just taking a
big leap.''
</P>
<P>
   What Maslin's leaping from may be the most important print
position in her profession. With television and Internet reviews
becoming an ever greater commercial force, and no one having
stepped forward in the '90s to assume the mantle of Pauline Kael
(who dominated critical discourse during her quarter-century at The
New Yorker), the institutional prominence of the Times gives its
senior critic a very high profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who writes for the Times,'' says film historian and
New York Observer critic Andrew Sarris, ``cover(s) the waterfront.
. . . They have influence in Hollywood. They have influence
overseas. It's a huge, huge responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The high profile come with a cost, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hellish job,'' Sarris says. ``You've got the whole
world jumping all over you. It's more pressure than anyone (else)
has in this business.''
</P>
<P>
   Times management would seem to agree, seeing as how they hired
two critics to take her place.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, she's reviewed 160 films. Maslin estimates she
sees an annual average of 400. Last week she reviewed three and saw
nine.
</P>
<P>
   The surprising thing, perhaps, isn't that Maslin's calling it
quits. It's that she's stuck it out so long. ``To have done this
job so well over 20 years,'' marvels Los Angeles Times film critic
Kenneth Turan, a reported finalist for the job, ``and to have so
much grace in her writing and still maintain a love for film over
that period of time is a really remarkable achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees. Maslin has her detractors _ though the
small and incestuous nature of the reviewing business means that
none of the colleagues contacted for this article was willing to go
on the record when criticizing her. Complaints, when voiced, center
on her practicing what Sarah Kerr, writing in Slate last spring,
called ``a criticism of lowered expectations'' and/or too often
going with the critical flow. Paradoxically, she's also been chided
for flouting the critical consensus in her two most-discussed
reviews this year, which praised George Lucas's ``The Phantom
Menace'' and Stanley Kubrick's ``Eyes Wide Shut.''
</P>
<P>
   Maslin stands by those reviews but concedes a larger point.
``I'm probably a little too generous. When I see good work in
something that isn't really successful, I can still sometimes
admire the intention or some part of it that did work. . . . I hope
I've brought some sense of my own enthusiasm and was able to light
that spark in other people, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason no one's willing to go on the record criticizing
Maslin is her personality. Even detractors speak fondly of her, and
friends cannot praise her enough. It was a case in point when
Charlie Rose gave her half an hour on his PBS show last month and
paid her that rarest of Charlie Rose tributes: adoring her even
more than he was adoring himself.
</P>
<P>
   Music writer and record producer James Isaacs, who worked with
Maslin when she was starting out at The Boston Phoenix, likens her
to the wisest of Golden Age screen goddesses. ``You know who Janet
always reminded me of? Myrna Loy. She has the eyes, obviously, but
also Myrna Loy's vibe: very smart, very witty, amused as well as
amusing. You can definitely see Janet in a smart-set '30s movie.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see what Isaacs means. Maslin is an engaging blend
of cool wit (her eyebrow arching is world class) and gracious
bearing. When the restaurant owner comes over to announce he has a
bit part in ``The Insider,'' the Michael Mann film starring Al
Pacino, and to inquire if she's seen it, Maslin congratulates him _
then refrains from pointing out that if he'd read her review he
wouldn't have asked that question.
</P>
<P>
   Maslin was born in Manhattan and grew up on Long Island. She
began moviegoing early: Her parents would put her in pajamas and
take her to the Whitestone Drive-In, in Queens. Her father worked
in real estate, and her mother taught mathematics. Maslin took
after mom. She was the sole girl on her high school math team. She
majored in the subject at the University of Rochester, though she
took almost as many courses in English and managed to squeeze in a
film course.
</P>
<P>
   That course was far from her mind, however, after graduation, in
1970. ``The National Lampoon had just started,'' she says. ``I
thought it was funny, so I wangled myself a job there as a
secretary filling in for two weeks. Remember how they used to run
these features with Polaroid photos? I was in one, which I'd just
as well not remember now, with (writer) Doug Kenney, and had hair
down to here.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine was full of Harvard grads, who urged her to give
Cambridge a try. ``Math was really a dead end,'' she says. ``So I
went up there and got a job at Harvard, as a secretary to (Nobel
Prize winners) J. D. Watson and Walter Gilbert at the molecular
biology lab. The other secretary was a classical pianist. But we
both needed a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our chief duty was to provide cookies for the graduate
students at teatime (Dr. Watson had spent his formative years in
England and believed in high tea), and we were not to talk because
we would distract them from their serious scientific thought. I
lasted about a month and a half doing this. But during that time,
I'd be sorting the mail and the old Boston After Dark used to come
in. It was fun to read and I just thought, `Boy, it looks like open
season there,' so that's where I went.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon enough she was writing about movies (and BAD had become The
Boston Phoenix). ``Everything was just wide open,'' Maslin recalls.
``You could write any old way you wanted, and we all learned by
doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   They learned fast, too. Writing about film for the alternative
press in Boston during the '70s was the journalistic equivalent of
playing jazz in Kansas City during the '30s _ or shortstop in the
American League in the '90s. Talent abounded. Maslin was succeeded
at the Phoenix by The New Yorker's David Denby, who was succeeded
by Stephen Schiff, who after stints at Vanity Fair and The New
Yorker now writes screenplays. Newsweek's David Ansen was at The
Real Paper, as was David Thomson, a future Esquire film columnist
and the author of ``A Biographical Dictionary of Film.''
</P>
<P>
   Maslin wrote about music as well as film. ``Singer-songwriters
were her thing,'' Isaacs says. In fact, Maslin figures in what is
surely the most celebrated review in rock history, the one in which
Jon Landau (her then husband) wrote that he had seen ``rock 'n'
roll's future'' at a Bruce Springsteen concert at the Harvard
Square Theater on May 9, 1974 in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Maslin was elsewhere on Massachusetts Avenue that evening.
``When Jon wrote the famous column,'' she explains, ``we were
already on the verge of breaking up, and he said I was home asleep.
That's not true. I went to a double feature at the Orson Welles
instead.''
</P>
<P>
   At the urging of Kael, Newsweek offered Maslin a job in 1977.
She describes her year there as ``pretty unhappy.'' Then Canby
called to see if she wanted to be his deputy at the Times.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
