<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4140 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MEDIA-MASLIN-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     12-09 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-MASLIN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NEW YORK: ... the Times.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Newsweek stint did have one happy outcome: Maslin's second
marriage. It was the result of a classic case of what screenwriters
call ``meeting cute.'' Susan Cheever, the daughter of novelist John
Cheever, had the office next door, and the two became friends. On
visits to the Cheever home, Maslin met Susan's brother Benjamin,
himself a novelist. ``We didn't like each other at first,'' she
says, ``but then we did.'' They've been married since 1981, and
have two sons, ages 13 and 10. Appropriately enough, they live in
the heart of Cheever country, Westchester County: ``Sort of between
Pleasantville and Sleepy Hollow,'' Maslin jokes, ``and it's
beginning to scare me!''
</P>
<P>
   Maslin speaks of her father-in-law with great, if slightly
baffled affection. ``He had a funny way of making everything
special,'' she says. ``Things around him took on an interesting
valence. . . . He put a charge into the world, one way or the
other.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the growing lack of a charge in Maslin's professional
world that, in part, moved her to leave the Times. ``What happened
in the last year, and one of the reasons why I felt a need to go,
was that I didn't feel as much urgency,'' she says. ``I didn't want
to stay there and just hang on past the point where I couldn't
change gears and do something else. I may go back there. I don't
know what I want to do. But I feel like anything's possible now.
Five years from now I might not have felt that way. It just seems
like a good moment to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love my kids. I love my husband. I love my life outside. But
it's not a matter of doing this so as to stay home. It's a matter
of seeking a new undertaking. Soon enough I'll be looking for
something to do, but if I had to know what it was now I wouldn't
have any kind of time out. It would just defeat the purpose. It's
great not knowing. It's terrifying, but very exciting. I could
pursue anything. The only thing I know is: no screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my big hopes is to get more conversant with computers.
Back when I was in college computers were as big as this room, and
everything was punch cards. Well, computers are rock 'n' roll now,
don't you think? The world is changing frighteningly fast. There's
a whole strange set of conventions growing up that nobody is paying
attention to. There are subversive yet powerful ways in which
that's going to change the way we process information and live our
lives and perceive popular culture. It's already changed movies
enormously, just in the narrative logic we follow. . . . I don't
know what's out there. I just sense some kind of an 800-pound
gorilla that I'd like to go look for.''
</P>
<P>
   So in between ape explorations, will Maslin be going to the
movies? Noting that there's a tenplex near her house, she says,
``Either all the time or never. I don't know which. I think for a
while it might be never.'' She takes a deep breath, then remembers
something. ``I'm going to go to Sundance (the film festival, in
January) and be on the jury, so that's 16 films I'll have to
watch.'' Those eyebrows arch, perhaps with relief, perhaps with
chagrin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Desert island (laser) discs
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Banished to a desert island, what would be on Janet Maslin's
list of must-have movies? ``I'm very bad at remembering movies off
the top of my head,'' she says. With that caveat, she offers, in no
particular order, the following titles:
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawrence of Arabia''
</P>
<P>
   ``All About Eve''
</P>
<P>
   ``Notorious''
</P>
<P>
   ``Taxi Driver'' (``And I'd be glad I was on a desert island!'')
</P>
<P>
   ``The Godfather''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some Like It Hot''
</P>
<P>
   ``Day for Night''
</P>
<P>
   ``This Is Spinal Tap''
</P>
<P>
   ``Something Wild''
</P>
</TEXT>
