<HEADLINE>
GIFTS FOR ANYONE DREAMING OF A CAR CHRISTMAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes this column can be about safe driving. Sometimes it
can be about practical cars. Sometimes it can be about esoteric
cars that most of us can only dream about ever owning. But
sometimes, especially around Christmas, it can be about what that
holiday has come to mean to so many folks: stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in sometimes specific, sometimes generic mode, is stuff it
might be fun to find in your stocking, under your tree, or in your
garage come Christmas morning.
</P>
<P>
   --A 1/5 scale Viper GTS-R from FG Modellsport of Germany. It's
remote-controlled, has a 22.5 cc two-stroke engine, independent
suspension, is 3 feet long and does 55 miles per hour. Check with
SEI Racing, 425-556-9090 or www.sei-racing.com.
</P>
<P>
   --Give your loved one, son, oraghter these things: a bag of sand
(at hardware stores), a trenching tool (Army surplus stores), wool
blanket, new jumper cables, a bag stuffed with wool mittens, wool
hat, and felt-lined boots. Have them put them in their trunk for
winter journeys. It all could come in handy.
</P>
<P>
   --For the SUVer and 4x4 enthusiast for whom the snow tire is not
enough: a rubber track conversion for 4x4 vehicles that turns them
into tracked crawlers over snow, sand, swamp, and tundra. They bolt
on where wheels bolt on and then you crawl away. They start at
$1,500 for a full set. Contact Mattracks at 218-436-7000, or
www.mattracks.com.
</P>
<P>
   --Like vintage hot rods? Own a small one you can drive. Mini
Rods come in various styles and paint jobs _ go for black with
flames on an open-top, open-wheel blast from the past _ have a
tubular chassis, fiberglass body, 5-horse motor and can handle
drivers up to 6 feet tall. Check with Autotrends at 510-251-9510 or
www.minirods.com.
</P>
<P>
   --And speaking of hot rods: The book ``Cool Cars Square Roll
Bars,'' reviewed here in the past, is a delightful verbal and
pictorial journey through New England's hot rod past. It's got the
clubs, the peple, th rods. Available through Hammershop Press,
508-543-1796; $29.95, plus shipping.
</P>
<P>
   --Driving lessons. If you are the parent of a young driver, send
them to an advanced driving school. Sure they learned how to
parallel park and watch the rearview mirror in driver's education.
That is not enough. And if you own an SUV, get yourself an advanced
lesson.
</P>
<P>
   --Ah, the Danbury Mint catalog. A veritable treasure chest of
die-cast metal works of automobile art. This year, at prices
ranging from $10-150, I'm ordering: the 1946 Chevrolet Suburban;
the Indian Four motorcycle, complete with moving brake and clutch
linkages; a 1946 Dodge Power Wagon, built because returning GIs
wanted the rig they grew to love in the war; and a 1957 Chevrolet
Bel Air convertible, all chrome trim and tail fins.
</P>
<P>
   --Straight from fantasy land, in the world of what Mobilia
magazine calls A2K (Automobilia 2000) come these items: an original
1-12.5 prototype model of the first Volkswagen Beetle. It was sold
to a private owner in 1996 for $65,000, it's worth a lot more now _
if you can find it.
</P>
<P>
   --For NASCAR fans, and I know there are a handful of you out
there despite elitists who refuse to acknowledge your intelligence
and clout, five Winston Cup drivers are offering die-cast models of
cars driven in the century's final race at Atlanta. You can get the
Rusty Wallace Miller Lite 1999 Ford Taurus; Dale Earnhardt Jr.'s
ACDelco 1999 Chevrolet Monte Carlo; Dale Earnhardt's GM Goodwrench
Service Plus 1999 Monte Carlo; Casey Atwood's Castrol GTX 1999
Monte Carlo; and Dal Jarrett's Ford Quality Care Service 1999
Taurus. They're available in 1:24 and 1:64 scales. The limited
editions can be found through Action Racing Collectables Inc.,
800-411-8404, or www.goracing.com.
</P>
<P>
   --All these dieoys under the tree. What if one breaks
down? Go fetch it with your die-cast Dodge Power Wagon 1949 Texaco
24-hour service wrecker. It's $45 from Denny's Diecast &AMP;
Collectibles, 888-919-0777.
</P>
<P>
   --And if you're on the prowl for some die-cast muscle, how about
this trio of muscle cars from 1970: a Ford Torino Cobra, a 1970
Chevy Nova SS, and an Oldsmobile 4-4-2. They're built at 1/43 scale
by wwwrtltoys.com.
</P>
<P>
   --Want to stir up controversy at your next cocktail party?
Mention that you think speed limits on many US highways are too
low, and that 100-plus miles per hour would be more realistic, as
long as the roads were upgraded. That's the basis of Mark Rask's
book, ``American Autobahn.'' He wants a high-speed highway with
full government support, and writes longingly of time spent on the
Autobahn in Germany, ``I had finally achieved what I had long been
searching for: A road and a government that permitted me _ playing
by its rules _ to drive as fast as I wanted.'' Available from
Vanguard Non-Fiction Books, PO Box 22370, Minneapolis, Minn.,
55422-0370
</P>
<P>
   --If you want a more leisurely trek through America, hop aboard
a Porsche Boxster with James Morgan in his book, ``The Distance to
the Moon.'' It's a combination of Lewis and Clark, ``Blue
Highways,'' and the old television shows ``Route 66'' (Corvette)
and ``Then Came Bronson'' (Harley-Davidson Sportster). Journey into
the body of America with the Porsche as its heartbeat, from bars to
weird art exhibits. It's all here, coast to coast. From Riverhead
Books, a member of Penguin Putnam, Inc., 375 Hudson Street, New
York, N.Y., 10014.
</P>
<P>
   --Finally, for a look into the future (10-20 years from now) and
a time when cars won't need gasoline or electric plugs, pick up
``Powering the Future,'' a look at the Ballard Fuel Cell. Tom
Koppel gives us a look at one of the leaders in the race to develop
the technology that will use hydrogen and oxygen to produce
electricity and have as its only byproduct, water. Clean,
efficient, and coming your way. From Wiley Publishers, 605 Thd
Ave., New York, N.Y., 10158.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
