<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4149 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     12-09 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELCOME TO THE TWILIGHT DOT-COM ZONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is hard to make sense of it all.
</P>
<P>
   Day after day technology stocks climb, while the rest of the
stock market mostly just hangs around. Anything remotely connected
to the new economy is hot; old-economy companies can't get the time
of day.
</P>
<P>
   Stock market veterans say it can't go on this way, that we are
in a bubble that has to burst. But what if they are wrong? What if
this is just the beginning of a golden era for stocks and
technology?
</P>
<P>
   What follows is an imaginary look at the coming year on Wall
Street. Any link between the material presented here and reality is
purely coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 8 _ Electronic retail stocks soar on news that Christmas
Internet sales rose 150 percent from the previous year. Skeptics
who suggest the big percentage gain came off a very small base are
dismissed as Luddites.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 24 _ Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan announces the
central bank will not be raising interest rates anytime in the
forseeable future. ``We've got a brand new economy. Worrying about
inflation is Wednesday's news,'' crows Greenspan, who says he will
spend the next six months working on his backhand.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 15 _ Fidelity Investments fires all of its bond and value
stock fund managers. ``We can't give this stuff away,'' explains
chairman Ned Johnson. At the same time, Fidelity announces the
launch of three new equity funds: Very Aggressive Growth, Super
Aggressive Growth, and Growth So Aggressive You Won't Believe It.
</P>
<P>
   March 8 _ The stock of Cisco Systems climbs 3 points, marking
the 80th day in a row the stock has risen. Cisco executives have no
comment. ``We'll say something if the stock ever goes down again,''
says Cisco's chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   April 9 _ Outfielder Ken Griffey Jr. turns down $20 million a
year to play for the Atlanta Braves and tells a stunned nation that
he is quitting baseball to become a venture capitalist. ``Where I'm
going, $20 million is chump change,'' says Griffey. Nike announces
it will make a set of new commercials showing Griffey on the
telephone doing deals.
</P>
<P>
   April 20 _ Responding to competitive threats, America Online
announces it will give away its Internet service. AT&AMP;T counters by
saying it will provide free long-distance telephone service. Both
companies say they will make up the lost revenue through greater
volume.
</P>
<P>
   May 1 _ CarsRUs, an Internet auto dealer, goes public. By the
end of the first day of trading, it has a greater market value than
Ford and General Motors put together. ``That's no surprise,'' says
the fledgling company's CEO. ``We don't have all those big
expensive factories to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   May 9 _ Vice President Al Gore slips in the polls after he says
he has no problem with Internet taxes. Gore later recants. ``I
thought you said clarinet taxes,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   June 12 _ Amazon.com stock rises 10 percent as the company
announces its entry into yet another new line of business: selling
rubber bands over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   July 6 _ Merrill Lynch fires its chief of equity research after
he tells clients that Nasdaq stocks, up 73 percent for the year,
may be ``fully valued.'' His successor says technology stocks still
have plenty of room to run.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 1 _ Stuart, the rockin' redheaded star of the Ameritrade
commercials, agrees to play himself in an upcoming made-for-TV
movie about his life. Seinfeld's Jason Alexander will play his bald
middle-aged boss.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 15 _ Microsoft announces it is acquiring the nation of
India in a stock swap valued at $200 billion. ``It was the cheapest
way we could find to pick up software talent,'' says chairman Bill
Gates. Microsoft says it will probably spin off the Taj Mahal in a
future deal.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 15 _ The US secretary of education reports that the best
and brightest high school students are dropping out to start
Internet companies. In most cases school districts give their
approval if the dropouts promise to let teachers and principals
participate in any future IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 11 _ Technology stocks fall 10 percent in the annual
October correction. This year, the correction lasts just four
hours. Investors who buy on the dip make a killing.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 18 _ The chairman of NBC sports announces he will save a
few advertising spots in the upcoming Super Bowl for automobile and
beer companies. ``Call me nostalgic,'' says the chairman, who
readily admits he could have sold the entire package to dot.com
firms.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 4 _ The stocks of electronic retail companies soar as an
influential Wall Street analyst predicts that December Internet
sales will be robust. When a skeptic suggests that retail sales
always rise in December, the analyst shoots back: ``Yeah, what's
your point?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
