<HEADER>
A4151 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-WELTNER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-09 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELTNER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THROUGH A BROTHER-IN-LAW'S EYES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago my sister Susan married an Irishman.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't fall in love with an Irish-American, but with an
honest-to-goodness Irishman from Waterford City named Pierce
Butler, who spoke with a brogue and hadn't set foot in the USA
until he was 20 years old. Our family embraced Pierce from the
moment we met him, but he was soft-spoken and a bit reticent, and
for some reason, in all the conversations we ever had, I never
asked him about the old country. In fact, when I wanted to learn
about what it was like to grow up in Ireland, I read ``Angela's
Ashes.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Pierce's own book, ``A Riddle of Stars,'' has just been
published by Zoland Books, and as I read it, I felt as if I were
meeting my brother-in-law for the first time. I hadn't known that
as a young boy Pierce spent his summers with relatives who lived on
the Inish, an island off the wild western coast of Ireland, or that
he remembered, with almost perfect clarity, his grandfather's house
with its outhouse and thatched roof and oil lamps glowing brightly
in the darkness of the lonely nights. There, amid lifelong grudges
and family evasions and thwarted love, the hero of Pierce's novel
plots his escape and resettlement.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, when he arrives in this land of endless promise, Matt finds
himself thwarted by that childhood, with its unpaid debts and his
grief at being abandoned by his mother. When he falls in love with
an American woman named Lily, her optimistic faith in their future
seems as far out of his reach as the ``riddle of stars'' in the
Irish sky. Lily, of course, is a fictionalized version of my
sister, whom I have never seen through the eyes of a lover before.
Her father, who in the course of the book dies of prostate cancer
while in hospice in her home, is my dad to the bone, brought back
to life by Pierce's heart-rending observations.
</P>
<P>
   My father died in Susan and Pierce's house in 1994, and although
my brother and I visited almost every day, the two of them bore the
brunt of his care. When we showed up, we'd always ask politely,
``How did it go last night?'' but to revisit my dad _ in Pierce's
re-creation of the event _ lavishing praise upon a hospice nurse
while withholding affirmation from my sister, is to reexperience my
dad's unerring ability to inflict pain on those who loved him. Yet
I can also see how my father's charm, his disarming honesty, and
his zest for life make him an inspiring figure to an Irish boy
raised on silence and pessimism and passivity. It is touching to
see how my dad provoked love and resentment in equal measure.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't only my family that's cast in a new light in Pierce's
book. Boston itself is a major character, looming out of the
headlights of Matt's car with a strange unsettling clarity as the
young Irishmen drives the streets of the city in an effort to
escape his demons.
</P>
<P>
   Take this description of the approach to the Tobin Bridge: ``In
a moment we are zooming up the expressway ramp with the Garden
rising in front of us like the Great Wall of China. To the left,
the skywalk stalks over the streets like a many-footed beast toward
the great hump of the Mystic.'' Or this one of the turnpike heading
into Boston: ``A sheer concrete retaining wall flies by on my
right; I'm below street level. The tunnel beneath the Prudential
Center rushes toward me, and I'm suddenly underground. Walls and
columns stream past, and my headlights flee across the ceiling.
(Mine) is the only car in here, beneath the unconscionable mass of
the Pru, the tons of streets, bridges, and pavements, burrowing
beneath the nighttime city, like a mole shunning the light.''
</P>
<P>
   To Matt, Lily's insistence on airing difficult feelings
represents an American mind-set that challenges his learned
hopelessness about changing himself or his fate. ``A Riddle of
Stars'' may be, as the Los Angeles Times wrote, ``an immigrant's
song,'' but when I heard Lily speaking words that might have come
from my own mouth _ ``If you don't want to talk, Matt, I can't
force you. But I can't pretend that everything's fine between us''
_ I could understand how the author's reserve had finally been
breached. And when Lily's faith in Matt's ability to understand and
overcome his history gives him the courage to say at last: ``I had
never been more aware of my love for her, not as a thought or even
as a feeling of the heart, but as a total experience of all my
being,'' I knew my brother-in-law had come home at last.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
