<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4155 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-KING-FAMILY-COX     12-09 1386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-FAMILY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    King family hails jury finding of conspiracy in assassination
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs and Mike Morris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The wife of slain civil rights leader Rev. Martin
Luther King Jr. said today that a Memphis jury's verdict that a
conspiracy led to the death of her husbandwas ``a great victory for
America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband once said, the moral arch of the universe is long,
but it bends towards justice,'' Coretta Scott King said during a
press conference at the King Center. ``Today, I feel that the
jurors's verdict clearly affirms this principle. With this faith,
we can begin the new millennium with a new spirit of hope and
healing.''
</P>
<P>
   King, along with family members and their attorney, spoke out
today in the wake of the month-long trial which found a Memphis
man, Loyd Jowers, guilty of being involved in a widespread
conspiracy to assassinate King.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury was clearly convinced that the extensive evidence
showed that a conspiracy was deeply involved,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   King attorney William Pepper presented evidence that convinced
the jury that James Earl Ray, long believed to be the gunman, did
not assassinate King. This was the first time that a jury has heard
evidence in the case. In 1969, Ray offered a plea bargain and was
sentenced to 99 years in prison. He died in 1998 in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally got what we had been asking for, the opportunity to
get evidence before a jury,'' said Dexter Scott King, director of
the King Center. ``Because of the evidence and the information that
came out in Memphis, we believe this case is over.'' ``We know now
what happened, and for us, this is the final chapter,'' Dexter King
told CNN today. ``This is a very significant event in history.
History books have to be rewritten.'' A mere three hours after they
started deliberating Wednesday, a civil trial jury of six black
people and six white people found that Jowers, the former owner of
a greasy spoon restaurant, was involved in a conspiracy to kill
King.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like triumph over tragedy,'' said Dexter King. ``The fact
that 12 independent jurors have spoken is all we've wanted and
we've ever asked for.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts a period at the end of a chapter for my family.''
</P>
<P>
   King's widow and her four children were awarded $100 in damages,
to go toward funeral costs. Dexter King said the family will donate
the money to a charity to benefit Memphis sanitation workers, since
it was their plight that brought his father to Memphis, where he
was gunned down April 4, 1968.
</P>
<P>
   But the trial was not about money, the Kings have said since
filing the civil suit against Jowers last year. Instead, the family
wanted a jury to hear evidence that King was not killed solely by
Ray, who pleaded guilty in March 1969 but recanted three days
later.
</P>
<P>
   By pleading guilty, Ray never faced a jury. He died of liver
disease in April 1998 while serving a 99-year sentence, still
insisting he was set up by a mysterious smuggler he only knew as
``Raul.''
</P>
<P>
   Although King's assassination has been investigated by federal
and Tennessee authorities, this was the first time a jury had
listened to evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.) an associate of King, told WSB-TV in
Atlanta that he will ask President Clinton and Attorney General
Janet Reno for a thorough investigation of the assassination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very gratifying to be given an opportunity before a
jury,'' said King family attorney William Pepper, who also
represented Ray in his final attempts to win a trial. ``This is all
James Earl Ray wanted. At least the family will benefit from this.
Most of the evidence that we presented would have been put forth in
a trial for Ray.''
</P>
<P>
   Juror David Morphy said he thought the assassination was too
complex to be accomplished by one person.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all thought it was a cut-and-dry case, with the evidence
that Pepper brought forth that there were a lot of people involved.
Everyone from the CIA to the military had involvement in it,''
Morphy said. ``Jowers was involved in it, we felt.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 90-minute closing statement Wednesday, Pepper talked
about conspiracies, cover-ups and Jowers' admission on nationwide
television that he was a part of a conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Jowers, who owned and operated Jim's Grill in the same building
where Ray rented a room on the day of the shooting, told ABC News
in 1993 that he received $100,000 to hire a hit man. The rear of
Jim's Grill was across the street from the Lorraine Motel, where
King was staying when he was shot.
</P>
<P>
   Jowers said he got the money from late Memphis produce dealer
Frank Liberto, who was alleged to have ties to a New Orleans
organized crime family. According to Pepper, the hit man was Earl
J. Clark, a now-deceased Memphis police officer who had won honors
at the FBI Academy for his sharpshooting skills.
</P>
<P>
   Although parts of Jowers' story have changed over the years, he
said the assassin fired his shot from behind Jim's Grill and then
handed Jowers the rifle to hide.
</P>
<P>
   Jowers' attorney, Lewis Garrison, said the lawsuit should have
been dismissed because the statute of limitations had expired.
Garrison contended the Kings should have filed the lawsuit around
the time of Jowers' TV appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Further, Garrison said, while it might be reasonable to conclude
that King was the target of a conspiracy, any role Jowers could
have played would have been minor.
</P>
<P>
   Garrison told the jury it was hard to believe that ``the owner
of a greasy spoon and an escaped convict'' could have pulled off
King's assassination. Jowers, who at 73 is suffering from cerebral
arteriosclerosis, was absent from court for most of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The jury's verdict was welcomed by some spectators, including
Charles A.L. Oliver Jr., who said he has listened to every word of
the monthlong trial since the second week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always felt there was a conspiracy,'' said Oliver, 43. ``Now
we can be free and get on with our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   For many in Memphis, the end of the trial brought closure.
</P>
<P>
   Tending his niece's gift shop on Beale Street, Lafayette Davis
said he delivered bread to the Lorraine Motel the day King was
shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are concerned about the trial because people want to
know what happened,'' said Davis, who has lived in Memphis since
1951.
</P>
<P>
   He said he missed King the morning of the assassination so he
and a friend went to the home of the Rev. Samuel B. Kyles to meet
King, who was to have dinner with the Kyles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were waiting at Kyles' house for King,'' Davis said. ``He
never made it.''
</P>
<P>
   Neady Masters never got to meet him, either. On the stormy night
of April 3, Masters' sister heard King's ``I've Been to the
Mountaintop'' sermon at the Mason Temple. She told Masters how
inspiring it was and that she felt electricity after touching King.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me I had to go see him,'' said Masters, 57, adding
that on April 4, she and a friend headed to the motel to meet King.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, traffic was bad that day, so my friend turned
around,'' Masters said. ``As we were driving back, we heard on the
radio that he had been shot. We could have been there. Had I been
driving, we would have been there.'' The trial will have
wide-ranging effects, Dexter King said.
</P>
<P>
   ``History will have to rewritten,'' he said. ``People can no
longer look the other way.'' Across town at LeMoyne-Owen College,
the only historically black college in Memphis, Clodetra McGee and
Samantha Mitchell, both freshmen, said they have been living with
theories about the assassination since birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they should find out who really killed Doctor King so
that he can rest in peace,'' said Mitchell, 19. ``I never thought
James Earl Ray did it. I always thought it was a cover-up.''
</P>
<P>
   John Campbell, a prosecutor with the Shelby County district
attorney's office who has investigated the assassination but was
not involved in the Jowers trial, said the conspiracy claims have
no merit.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said several of Jowers' friends and associates said he
was merely hoping to get a movie or book deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at this off and on for five years,'' Campbell said,
``and I've still seen nothing that would change my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
