<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Outer Space in a Dole's can
 &HT;    For release Dec. 12, 1999.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What do you get the person who has everything?, is the wail of
many holiday season shoppers. I have a suggestion: A can of Dole's
Pineapple Chunks and perhaps its Pine-Orange-Banana juice.
</P>
<P>
   You see, you've got to have two UPC bar code proofs-of-purchase
of Dole's products to be eligible to win a trip to ``outer space.''
</P>
<P>
   With the recent double failures of unmanned Mars missions, the
shutdown of the Hubble Space Telescope, as well as the frustrating
facts that the space shuttle Discovery has had six recent launch
scrubs while six unmanned rockets have gone ``boom'' in the past
year and a half, I would think a simple turbo-prop flight from
Miami to Tampa would be sufficient to meet my adventure needs.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't even have known about this chance to win a trip to
``outer space'' had not my daughter, who reads, collects and uses
those incessant store coupons that slip out of the Sunday paper,
informed me of it. Among the coupons was the Dole presentation. You
need to enter by Jan. 31, 2000 to be eligible to win and there are
other small-print rules including that you can't be unhealthy and
that you can't be under 16.
</P>
<P>
   It appears to me that the under 16 rule is unfair because the
way things are going, the child could be a highly eligible 21 years
of age _ or older _ at the time of launch.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies, both travel and aeronautical, are working on
space travel. Ask any of them when they expect to inaugurate
sub-orbital flights and you don't get a firm answer: Some say late
2002, some indicate even later. Inasmuch as I have no knowledge
that any of their space vehicles have been tested, or that
government approval has been received, I tend to think its further
rather than closer.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the Dole's random drawing gets a choice: $50,000
or the space ride in a 60-feet-long Vela Technology Space Cruiser
that, in its Web site graphic, has the look of a delta-winged
airplane but with no engine on the swept-back wings.
</P>
<P>
   From London comes the news that the World Tourism Organization
has predicted space travel will be routine by 2020 and that low
orbit trips may take place within three years.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you are suspecting a fly-by of the moon, forget it.
These are sub-orbital trips, the kind Alan Shepard took in our
first space flight. Up, then down, lickety-split. The use of the
term ``outer space'' is ambiguous in that the flight likely will
not reach higher than 63 miles. NASA space shuttles orbit several
hundred miles up, depending upon the mission.
</P>
<P>
   As far as ``outer space'' is determined, know that the U.S.
gives astronaut status to anyone who flies above 50 miles in
altitude.
</P>
<P>
   That having been said, the appeal of a flight anywhere above
where our commercial jets now fly is tantalizing. That, for
promotional purposes, you can get a chance to do it for free _
excepting a couple of cans of Dole's Pineapple Chunks _ makes it
even better.
</P>
<P>
   Proposed fares already have been established for people who
don't win the Dole's giveaway. In October 1997, Zegrahm Space
Voyages, proffered a two-minute flight for $98,000; $49,000 a
minute, which is even more than Roger Clemens gets paid to pitch
one minute for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Zegrahm was sold last month to Space Adventures but I would
assume the earlier price holds.
</P>
<P>
   I am not entering the contest inasmuch as I was born during the
Herbert Hoover administration and still bewildered about what keeps
jet planes up. But others seem to be signing up _ not necessarily
for the Dole's promotion _ but directly with the transit people.
According to a press release from Space Adventures, ``flights are
filling up already and the demand will rise quickly in anticipation
of first departures.''
</P>
<P>
   When will that be? Ask any Boston Red Sox fan when his team will
win its next World Series. The answer to when civilian space travel
will begin also lies somewhere there.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
