<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-ABC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANHATTAN'S MECCA OF MERCHANDISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI DOTEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's impossible to describe the ABC Carpet &AMP; Home
store in Manhattan's Flatiron District, the city's burgeoning
home-furnishings mecca, without resorting to the cliche ``organized
chaos.'' Any newcomer to the Broadway and 19th Street store, which
has become a destination spot for New Yorkers and out-of-towners
looking for a genuine Big Apple or holiday shopping experience,
might need a whiff of smelling salts to recover from the visual
shock of the store's ground-floor ``parlour'' and its dizzying
array of ``stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there are five more floors, it's the first one that
sets the tone, captures the imagination, and personifies first-rate
marketing, merchandising, and the art of display.
</P>
<P>
   The parlour is many things. A blown-up version of an eccentric
great-aunt's overstuffed, overlaced, overchandeliered Victorian
parlor. A pack rat's dream, albeit a rat with a large trust fund. A
theatrical, high-end flea market or a bustling South American
bazaar or a Filene's-esque bargain basement or an outsize boutique.
Or a cave filled with stalactites and stalagmites of Venetian
glass, porcelain, decorative ornaments, china figurines, and beaded
accessories.
</P>
<P>
   There's absolutely no horizontal surface without a covering of
either plates, cups, lamps, clocks, bibelots, or most every other
accessory known to man. No rafter, wall, stair or support column
without chandelier, painting, or rug. No floor space free _ except
for walkways _ of pillows, pots, planters, garden seats or small
chairs, footstools, and benches.
</P>
<P>
   Such visual madness has proven to be very lucrative. Sales
figures for the store and its satellites _ which have opened in the
Bronx, Westbury on Long Island, and Delray Beach, Fla. _ topped
$175 million this year. Employees total 1,200. Customers who visit
the more than 350,000 square feet of selling space encompassed by
the four stores average 1 million annually. And last year ABC
assumed operation of the Oriental carpet division of Harrods in
London. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pushcart origins &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The store is run by the family triumvirate of third-generation
ABC chairman Jerome Weinrib and his daughter and son-in-law,
Paulette and Evan Cole. Weinrib runs the floor-covering division,
while Paulette is creative director and Evan is president and chief
executive officer of the home division.
</P>
<P>
   The store's origins are found in the immigrant era. Sam Weinrib,
a native of Austria, sold used carpet and linoleum from a pushcart
on the Lower East Side at the turn of the century. His son, Max,
turned the pushcart into a store. Max's son, Jerome, transformed
the store into the largest rug and carpet store in the world. Today
the family owns both 881 Broadway, with its three floors of
carpets, and 888 Broadway, the ABC store and former home of W. &AMP; J.
Sloane, the premier home-furnishings store of the 1880s. That store
was part of what was called Ladies' Mile, the exclusive shopping
district for New York's upper class and birthplace of the
department store.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our vision started with the building and wanting to re-create
what was once here,'' says Evan Cole by phone during a buying trip
to Seville, Spain. ``We wanted to impart the whole feeling of a
Victorian department store and bring it into the late 20th
century.''
</P>
<P>
   With the vision in place from the start, says Cole, he and his
team worked from the ground floor up, adding more and more
merchandise with each floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're constantly evolving and refining,'' says Cole, who was a
Hollywood agent before coming to New York and ABC. ``That's why
it's always different every time a customer comes here. It's like a
moving feast. Things are constantly changing on every floor.
There's always an element of discovery.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A world of rugs &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Let's start from the top. The loftlike sixth-floor space is
impressive, with natural daylight streaming in through huge windows
onto unpainted brick walls and colorful rugs hanging from walls,
lounging across furniture, or piled in knee-high stacks. This is
the floor where handmade rugs from Tibet, Nepal, and India mingle
with antique Turkish and Persian offerings. For those without deep
pockets, there are also contemporary and cotton rag and braid rugs
along with machine-made rugs and the popular sisal.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth floor is filled with antique estate furniture,
reproductions, handpainted pieces, and upholstered items dressed in
tapestries, jacquards, velvets, and damasks. There are no so-called
vignette seating arrangements at ABC _ this is not a store for
ordering matching sofa and chairs, but more a collector's dream
house of the unusual. However, in a bow to conformity, there are
sections for Ralph Lauren and Baker furniture, because ``we don't
want any shopper to have to go anywhere else,'' says Loren Pack,
publicity and advertising director. ``Some people are looking for
these well-known brands. They've seen a Baker dining set in a
magazine and want it. They come here and order it and then end up
buying a rug upstairs and some accessories.''
</P>
<P>
   The fourth floor features less formal furniture, along with
American folk art and a bit of whimsical frog art in the Toad Hall
section. A big consumer draw is the third floor, with its 50 beds,
including cribs and bassinettes, and more than 300 sheet patterns.
There are also decorative pillows of every shape, size, and fabric,
as well as chenille throws, matelasse coverlets, silk charmeuse
duvet covers, towels, and bathroom hardware and fixtures. The
second floor features furniture from Mexico, Peru, Indonesia, and
India, along with Danish modern and American pine. And finally, in
the basement, 5,000 bolts of fabric are organized by color. &QL; 
 &QL; 
First-floor eateries &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now back to the first floor for a bite to eat.
</P>
<P>
   There are several choices. The year-old food hall offers such
specialty foods as pate, smoked fish, breads, teas, and more than
300 cheeses, along with takeout meals and made-to-order sandwiches.
Colina, a new addition to the store, serves Italian Tuscan fare in
a rustic restaurant with a direct street entrance at 35 East 18th
St. But in keeping with the store's ambience is the popular Parlour
Cafe, a microcosm of the store where the ceiling drips with glass
chandeliers of varying vintages and shoppers dine on mosaic tables
while seated on overstuffed chairs and velvet settees. Everything's
for sale here, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 1404EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4158 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-COMPUTERS-SPAM-BOS &LR;      12-09 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-SPAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECLARING WAR ON SPAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SIMSON GARFINKLE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Electronic junk mail is the scourge of the Internet. More
commonly called spam, junk e-mail wastes money and time, it turns
people away from the Internet, and most of it is just plain ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, system administrators from all over the United
States met in California at the Third Spam Roundtable to discuss
the growing problem. The results were not encouraging. Between 15
percent and 30 percent of the e-mail that America Online receives
is spam. Most large Internet service providers have a team of four
to six people dedicated to combating the problem; unsolicited
commercial e-mail is costing these companies roughly $1 million
each month, which translates to $1 to $2 per subscriber.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the real kicker: the junk e-mail problem is likely to
get worse before it gets better.
</P>
<P>
   It's the crazy economics of the Internet that created the junk
e-mail problem.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a piece of paper mail, which costs 25 cents to $1 to
send, there is no per-message charge to send e-mail: it's included
in your monthly fee. Although this works out great for people who
want to keep in touch, the economics lend themselves to abuse. All
a spammer needs to send out a million copies of a message is a
dial-up Internet account, a million e-mail addresses, and a desktop
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, a friend of mine visited an AOL chat room
called ``Parent Soup.'' A few days later, her mailbox was filled
with 40 messages directing her to gay pornographic Web sites. In
all likelihood, a spammer had been monitoring the chat room,
recorded her e-mail address, and added it to his list. If you are
an AOL user, practically the only way that you can protect yourself
from this kind of attack is to use a different screen name for chat
rooms than for e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey conducted earlier this year by
ChooseYourMail.com, pornographers are responsible for 30.2 percent
of the spam on the Internet today. Just behind the sex merchants,
29.6 percent of spam hawks get-rich-quick and work- from-home
schemes, many of them illegal. The remainder of the spam advertised
assorted products and services; a small percentage illegally offer
stock tips.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that the best way to protect yourself from being
spammed was to be cagey with your e-mail address. That is, if you
avoided putting your e-mail address on a Web page, if you didn't
participate in on-line discussion groups, if you didn't join chat
sessions, you were pretty safe.
</P>
<P>
   But hiding your e-mail address is becoming less effective every
day. At the Spam Roundtable, I learned that more and more spammers
are resorting to dictionary attacks, where they send e-mail to any
address that's likely to be valid. If the message gets through,
that's great for the spammer. If the message bounces, the spammer
doesn't care, since the bounces usually end up in some beleaguered
system administrator's mailbox.
</P>
<P>
   Although some states have passed laws that attempt to regulate
spam, none have been particularly successful. Federal attempts,
meanwhile, have been worse. Last year, Senators Frank Murkowski, a
Republican from Alaska, and Robert Torricelli, a New Jersey
Democrat, proposed legislation that would have made it illegal to
send spam to people who specifically had opted out, or asked not to
receive the junk mail, but legal to send it to everyone else.
Although the bill passed the Senate, it died in a House committee.
</P>
<P>
   Many antispam activists opposed the legislation because it
legitimized spam. For the same reason, many spammers rallied behind
it.
</P>
<P>
   But the real spam problem in the coming year won't be from
fly-by-night operations and scam artists, it will be from
legitimate companies that view unsolicited bulk e-mail as a way to
market themselves more effectively.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine how much e-mail you would get if every store where you
ever had shopped, or every store where you ever might shop, sent
you an e-mail once a week telling you about a special offer. Your
e-mail quickly would become unusable.
</P>
<P>
   This January, the Direct Marketing Association will announce an
opt-out database for electronic mail called the e-Mail Preference
Service. The database is supposed to be a list of people who do not
wish to receive marketing information by e-mail. That sounds good
at first, but many spam-fighters fear that the DMA will use its
database to legitimize e-mail marketing in general. This argument
has merit, since the DMA's two other databases, the Telephone
Preference Service and the Mail Preference Service, have been used
to legitimize telemarketing and paper junk mail.
</P>
<P>
   So what's a computer user to do?
</P>
<P>
   Today there are a number of filters that you can use to separate
the spam mail from the good mail. The best filter that I have seen
is BrightMail. Although it's designed to be used by Internet
service providers and corporations, the company recently started up
a service for individuals. You can find out more at
http://www.brightmail.com/.
</P>
<P>
   The second way to fight spam is with legislation. Write to your
lawmakers and tell them what you think about junk e-mail. The
Coalition Against Unsolicited Commercial E-mail has put up a
detailed information center about legislative attempts to stop spam
at http://www.cauce.org/.
</P>
<P>
   If you get spam e-mail, you can send it to the Spam Recycling
Center, at spamrecycle(at)ChooseYourMail.com. For information,
check out http://www.spamrecycle.com/.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you can tell the stores where you shop that you don't
want them sending you e-mail. And if catalog companies ask for your
e-mail address, don't tell them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Simson Garfinkel can be reached at http://chat.simson.net/)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
