<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW WILL TRY TO SHUT DOWN HARRISON, BROKEN HAND AND ALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Cornerback Ty Law will be on pins and
needles Sunday, and not because of the predicament of his team or
the presence of Colts wide receiver Marvin Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   When Law and the Patriots journey to Indianapolis to face the
red-hot Colts, he will be there with his broken right hand held
together by three pins and the discomfort deadened by pain-killers.
Obviously, this is not the ideal circumstance for a cornerback to
be in when facing the league's most prolific pass catcher, but that
is the circumstance Law will face after having surgery Tuesday to
stablize the hand he broke Sunday night while slamming the Cowboys'
Raghib Ismail to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The pins were inserted to stablize the hand, which means Law
will have to wear a modified hard cast wrapped in padding just to
get on the field. What it also means, he expects, is an increase in
business coming his way when Harrison and quarterback Peyton
Manning go to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what type of receiver Marvin Harrison is,'' Law said
Wednesday. ``I'm quite sure they realize what kind of competitor I
am. This is the first broken bone I ever had, but this is football.
Once you're on the field, you don't think about anything but
winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm quite sure I'll see more balls than I normally see because
I can't pick the ball off. If anything, I can just bat it down.
It's going to be frustrating to know you're going to see more balls
than I've ever seen and I can't catch them.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if that circumstance does arise, Law won't be as frustrated
as he was Sept. 19 when, with two healthy hands, he watched
Harrison catch six passes for 100 yards and three touchdowns in the
first half to help put the Colts ahead, 28-7.
</P>
<P>
   Angry over the soft defenses he was being asked to play, Law
vented his opinion at halftime. In the second half, the Patriots
played far tougher man-to-man defense and Harrison made only one
more catch for 5 yards, which helped New England catch
Indianapolis, 31-28, on Adam Vinatieri's 26-yard field goal with 35
seconds left to play.
</P>
<P>
   Law has not forgotten that game and probably neither have the
Colts, which means both will have a point to make this time. The
problem for Law is he must make his point without being able to
point his finger at anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is playing better than the Indianapolis Colts, except
maybe the Jacksonville Jaguars,'' Law said. ``But we want to let
them know when they play the Patriots, they can't beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   Having lost seven straight to New England and 10 of 12 since the
Drew Bledsoe Era began, Law has a point. But this time Law will be
at a significant disadvantage in his personal battle with Harrison,
who leads the NFL in receiving yards (1,239) and touchdowns (12).
Not only will Law be hard-pressed to catch the ball, he'll be
hard-pressed to press Harrison at the line of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I jam him and it hurts, I'll have to play a soft press,''
Law said. ``I can't wear a soft (more flexible) cast. They told me
that's totally out of the question. They told me there's no way I
can do that because the pins might break.''
</P>
<P>
   Logically, if Law can't wear a soft cast because of the severity
of the break, just how bad a break was it? ``You're talking to a
sports marketing major in college,'' Law joked. ``I have no idea. I
don't know what's going on. All I know is I got three pins in there
and it's broke straight through.''
</P>
<P>
   Be that as it may, Law understands that come Sunday no one will
want to hear about the condition of his hand. They'll only be
concerned with the condition of his feet and whether they can stay
with Harrison all over the RCA Dome. If they do, someone will be
nominating him for the Red Badge of Courage Award. If they don't,
they'll be nominating him for the Scalding of the Week Award, a
circumstance Law long ago accepted as part of the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm able to play, I got to play,'' Law said. ``(The cast)
is irrelevant. Whether we're playing man or zone I got to do the
job. If the ball comes to me, I'll try and catch it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll approach the game the same way. I'll approach Marvin
Harrison the same way. I have to play what the defense calls. Every
game against Marvin Harrison is a battle. He catches some. I catch
some. It's not one-on-one all the time, not Ty Law vs. Marvin
Harrison all the time, but it's an all-out brawl.''
</P>
<P>
   If it is, the guy with his hand in plaster would seem to be at a
unique disadvantage. Unless you talk to him about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I go to Indianapolis, I'm playing,'' Law said. ``And if I'm
on the field, don't put me away from Marvin Harrison. Don't try to
cover me up. Put me out there on that island and let me do my
thing. If I can't play that way, I don't want to play at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
