<SLUG> BC-SKI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S TALK ABOUT THE WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The vice president of a large ski company commented privately
the other day: ``This is getting scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he was talking about the current lack of snowpack in
the northern mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing new about warm autumns, or December meltdowns. Nothing
new about an upper air pattern that blocks the cold Arctic air out
while the warm soup spreads from the South all across New England .
. . and sits for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   We've seen this before. But, what if this is new?
</P>
<P>
   What if there is a permanent warming going on? So far as anyone
can tell amid all the political wrangling about global warming, no
one really knows. Or at least no one has been convincing one way or
another.
</P>
<P>
   Certain pieces of data seem unsettling _ the shrinking of the
polar ice cap; the fact that some species of migrating waterfowl
from the Canadian maritimes do not range as far south to their
ancestral wintering grounds anymore (Just ask the fifth generation
goose-hunters from Maryland's Eastern Shore who see a fraction of
the birds that used to return for winter).
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, we humans are semi-schooled at best in the long
rhythms of climate and geological evolution and do not know whether
we are dealing with a real change in the planet's climate or merely
moving through cycles heretofore unrecognized. After all, in terms
of accurate record-keeping, meteorology is a relatively new
science.
</P>
<P>
   Our long-term memory often proves untrustworthy in recreating
accurate pictures of our past. A week-long power outage caused by a
blizzard in Feburary when we were 8 years old will color our
memories of winter for a lifetime. We might conjur up images of the
Klondike, home of Sergeant Preston and King, as we remember and
long for our nostalgic past.
</P>
<P>
   In those ringing days, there was always deep fresh morning snow
after nightly blizzards. The skiing was limitless. The winter life
as gay and robust as some old David Niven movie set in a Tyrolean
resort.
</P>
<P>
   But, back to the dismal reality of this season.
</P>
<P>
   Sure there have been winters, and starts of winters, like this
one. Warm autumns, with unrelieved weeks of tepid soup that retards
natural cycles even of flower and insect. Check out your backyard.
</P>
<P>
   But no, we'll skip the global warming for now and take the easy
explanation. The warm autumn is just that, and made all the worse
because of heightened expectations of skiers with pent-up energy
carried over from last year's stingy season. And with the Christmas
week fast approaching, the collective knot in the stomach of the
ski industry is apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Peak, one of the most naturally snowy mountains in the
Northeast, intends to open its new lift, the Green Mountain Flyer,
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The 7,500-foot lift, designed to carry 2,600 skiers per hour,
was going to provide some free skiing Saturday for those attending
the opening celebration. Not now. The celebration will take place
sans the skiing and boarding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame, but with a little cold weather we'll have the
skiing going hopefully for the holidays,'' said Jay Peak spokeman
Conrad Klefos.
</P>
<P>
   The American Skiing Company, with its six New England and two
Rocky Mountain resorts, has put forth a bet with skiers. By the
holidays, says ASC chairman Les Otten boldly, ``We will have
snow.''
</P>
<P>
   ASC areas have often touted guaranteed skiing, but this year
they are making an even greater promise to vacationing skiers and
boarders: ``If we can't give our guests at least 70 percent of
their mountain, we'll activate the guarantee,'' says Otten.
</P>
<P>
   The guarantee will give guests a 25 percent price reduction on
their next visit this season and a voucher worth up to $500 toward
a vacation at The Canyons in Utah or Steamboat in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The offer is made to guests reserving a ski vacation between now
and Dec. 24 and is good for vacations between Christmas and Jan. 2,
2000.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, according to ASC spokesman Skip King, the
resorts are taking the risk out of booking a ski vacation during
the holidays. ``We know people down there are concerned with the
amount of snow they're going to find,'' said King. ``Our bottom
line is if you go skiing over the holidays you'll have a good
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The ASC guarantee applies to Sunday River, Sugarloaf/USA,
Killington, Mt. Snow, Sugarbush, and Attitash/Bear Peak.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some resorts we can open four to six trails a day,'' said
King. ``And we're looking for some natural snow, too. We'll have
the stuff. If not we'll activate the guarantee.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm, with 26 of 120 trails currently open at Sunday River, King
is hoping that the forecast for cold weather after this weekend
will come true. With about two weeks to Christmas, even at the rate
of 4-6 trails a day, 70 percent coverage seems ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question,'' says King. ``We've got our work cut out for us.
But if people get here, they'll have a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tony Chamberlain writes about the outdoors for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
