<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH CHOICE FOR SAN FRANCISCO VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco voters have a real choice in bad
choices in the Dec. 14 election.
</P>
<P>
   They can vote for an arrogant, abrasive big-time politician who
has been an underachiever in a job of high expectations _ mayor of
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Or they can vote for an arrogant, abrasive small-time politician
who has been an overachiever in a job of low expectations _ San
Francisco city supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   If those descriptions of our two candidates sound harsh, it
doesn't mean I don't like either Mayor Willie Brown or Board of
Supervisors President Tom Ammiano. I enjoy their intelligence and
wit. They are true San Francisco characters and they give good
quote.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, as my guidance counselor said about all us losers,
laggards and layabouts, they have potential.
</P>
<P>
   I don't care if they are often arrogant and abrasive. Arrogance
can be good in an elected official, as long as that official does
good and delivers the goods.
</P>
<P>
   Teddy Roosevelt was arrogant, but that quality helped him fight
monopolies. Phil Burton, the former California congressman, was as
abrasive as anyone ever seen in Congress, but he always looked out
for the poor, the environment and fought the moneyed special
interests _ which always outdo mere mortal politicians in the
arrogance department.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was Burton's protege, but you'll never see him fighting
big money.
</P>
<P>
   A mayor should serve wider, deeper and larger interests than
real estate moguls, builders and corporations. He should serve the
people who elect him.
</P>
<P>
   A mayor should get the people to and from work on time, help
them find shelter if they need it and make a city a safer, more
beautiful and more efficient place.
</P>
<P>
   The latter means spending less of the citizens' money and
getting more for it. What a concept in a city where you always pay
more and get less.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has appointed friends, political hacks and inexperienced
young people to everything from the Board of Supervisors to
solid-waste czar. It wasn't until his re-election loomed that he
brought in a professional as head of Muni to try to make the trains
and buses run on time.
</P>
<P>
   He was like a brilliant student waiting for the last minute to
do his homework.
</P>
<P>
   Brown hasn't even seriously taken on the homeless issue,
canceling a ``homeless summit,'' failing to notice homeless
encampments in the park, then threatening to call in surveillance
helicopters on them. To roust or not to roust, that was the
question he dodged.
</P>
<P>
   He's like a bright student who signed up for a very tough
course, didn't go to class and then dropped it.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has potential, but will he live up to it in the next four
years?
</P>
<P>
   You can't call him a late-bloomer, the way Barbara Bush calls
George W., because he fully bloomed as speaker of the Assembly.
Maybe he's coasting, another word my guidance counselor used.
</P>
<P>
   He's even coasting on other people's work. During the campaign,
he spent much of his time taking credit for the booming local
economy, which is just another way of claiming to have invented the
Internet, the force behind the boom.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of national stars have risen from comedy clubs in San
Francisco, but few from the perpetual open-mike night of the Board
of Supervisors. Dianne Feinstein, now the senior senator from
California, is one of those who made the big-time, perhaps because
she's as serious as they get.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano is quick with the quips, but underneath he's deadly
serious. The problem is he's often deadly serious about the
superficial, silly and irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about overachieving in a low-achievement field. This is the
man who has led the symbolically resolute Board of Supervisors in
introducing symbolic resolutions. He's championed endangered
hardwoods, downtrodden Zimbabwean gays and oppressed overweight
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   He's also been a Robin Hood trying to take from the rich and
give to the poor, although the arrows in his quiver of tax
proposals all turned out to have rubber tips and bounced off.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the Wall Street Journal wants to make fun of San
Francisco, they do a library search for ``Ammiano'' and
``resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   He's the class clown, driven by the deeper dissatisfactions of
the perpetual outsider. He's the kid always raising his hand and
making the snappy comments. He's the rebel with many causes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
