<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CUBAN SCHOOLBOY VS. AN AMERICAN BULLY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There are times as an American citizen that I
want to hang my head in shame or, better yet, fly a plane with a
message banner over a foreign country and tell its people: ``I
apologize for my government.''
</P>
<P>
   The sorry case of Elian Gonzalez, 6, of Cuba has created just
such a time.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I've missed something in this story, something that makes
the United States' inhumane manhandling of the situation excusable.
</P>
<P>
   All I keep finding is more evidence that this is bully-boy
exploitation and political posturing at its most offensive. (I find
it especially in the arrogant, patronizing smirk of State
Department spokesman James Foley, who seems to take Cuban protests
of the incident about as seriously as he might a video game.)
</P>
<P>
   So Fidel Castro postures back, visiting Elian's kindergarten
like some Hispanic Mr. Rogerarshaling hundreds of Young
Communists to take to the streets of Havana. Can you imagine what
the White House would be doing if the situation were reversed?
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that a 6-year-old boy from Kansas City was the only
survivor of a private plane crash just off the shores of Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that the boy's mother, divorced from his father but
sharing custody, had taken their son out of the United States to
live in Cuba without the father's knowledge or permission.
</P>
<P>
   Then imagine the Cuban government refusing the Kansas City
father's request to return his son to him. Imagine one of Castro's
ministers announcing that the ``most appropriate humanitarian way''
to resolve the issue was to treat it the way a Cuban custody case
would be treated and place it in the hands of a Cuban provincial
judge.
</P>
<P>
   We would have aircraft carriers heading for Havana harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Relations with communist Cuba, only 90 miles from Florida, have
grown increasingly absurd over the past decade. At the same time we
toast diplomatic and financial ties with a human rights-abusing,
totalitarian nation like China, we continue to shun and punish Cuba
as if it were the same scary, Soviet-backed maverick that pointed
missiles at us during the Kennedy administration.
</P>
<P>
   But this latest chapter lends a new meaning to absurdity.
</P>
<P>
   And to punishment.
</P>
<P>
   A little boy who just watched his mother drown in the sea has
become a kickball in a contest between the world's most powerful
capitalist nation and one of the world's few remaining Marxist
throwbacks. Everything that is wrong, stupid and wasteful about
U.S.-Cuban relations is being played out on young Elian Gonzalez's
head _ and heart.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Unites has an exclusive policy for Cuban
refugees _ if they make it to U.S. soil, they're eligible for
permanent residency _ a biological father with shared custody
rights has been told to cool his heels until a Florida family court
judge decides what is ``best'' for his son.
</P>
<P>
   And, on the boy's sixth birthday, the closest he could get to
his dad (and four grandparents, best pal and teacher) was a
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sent you a lot of little kisses so you have a happy
birthday,'' said Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, from his
home in Cardenas, Cuba. ``Are you coming back soon?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' little Elian piped back. ``Tell (my classmates) to take
care of my things.''
</P>
<P>
   Let us hope that, in the name of doing the ``most appropriate
humanitarian'' thing, the world's model of personal freedom and
democracy does not make those Cardenas kindergarteners take care
forever.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
