A4171 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-SF-MAYORAL-YOUTH-HNS &LR;      12-09 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-MAYORAL-YOUTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG ADULTS FORM BACKBONE OF AMMIANO'S SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ILENE LELCHUK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ EunYoung Lee, a 30-year-old Web page designer
with a silver ball pierced through her tongue, said she had never
volunteered for any kind of political campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Not until Tom Ammiano, the president of the governing Board of
Supervisors, won a spot in the Dec. 14 mayoral run-off election in
an unprecedented write-in campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I already know him as a person,'' Lee said Tuesday
during her first day as a political operative at Ammiano's campaign
office.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano, a former school teacher, gay activist and sometimes
stand-up comedian, has tapped into the angst and latent idealism of
Generation X in his campaign to unseat Mayor Willie Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano's campaign offices buzz with youthful energy _ a crowd
of 20- and 30-year-olds who are swept up in the excitement and hope
generated by Ammiano's surprisingly successful grass-roots
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He is 57 and hip. He is down to earth and against Big Business.
He rides public transportation and wears ink-stained shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano is considered an outsider working on the inside, an
image that disillusioned younger voters gobble up.
</P>
<P>
   The youthful group, mostly people who rent, coalesce around
Ammiano's favorite causes: rent control, protection from evictions,
a living wage and the disappearance of affordable artist lofts.
</P>
<P>
   Lee and Vivian Chang, 29, said they were volunteering because
they see a chance to make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that we are making history,'' said Chang, who as a
resident of Oakland, cannot vote in San Francisco. ``You think
about what happened on Nov. 2,'' the day of the general election
when the candidate won second place in a crowded field. ``I don't
think something like that could happen in any other U.S. city.''
</P>
<P>
   The so-called slackers are growing up. And it turns out that
despite low expectations for the much-maligned cynical generation,
they want to shape their own future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we'd be here without them. It's the engine
driving the campaign in some ways,'' said Ammiano campaign
strategist Robert Haaland, who is 35.
</P>
<P>
   Polls taken just before the Nov. 2 election showed that 56
percent of voters under age 30 supported Ammiano. One-fourth of
that age group said they supported Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Among voters 65 and older, just 6 percent supported Ammiano
while 45 percent supported Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, 65, the city's first black mayor, has spent a lifetime in
politics, earning him fund-raising power and influence with state
and federal officials. Although both men are Democrats, Brown is
seen as friendlier to the city's booming business community.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime San Francisco pollster David Binder said the trend his
poll detected in early November still holds steady.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen such an age gap,'' Binder said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an age gap. It's a generation gap,'' said political
consultant Robert Barnes, a Brown supporter who also conducted
recent polls for the Alice B. Toklas Lesbian and Gay Democratic
Club, which endorsed Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes found that among gays surveyed, the typical Ammiano
supporter is under 40, white, liberal, a renter, earns $35,000 a
year or less and has lived in San Francisco 10 or fewer years.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Brown's typical supporter in the gay community is
older, has lived here more than 10 years, owns a small business or
home and is in a steady relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced that if you are under 40 and shaved, pierced or
tattooed that you are for Ammiano,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano, asked about his appeal to young voters, said he speaks
to people who are left outside the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``My message is about grass-roots power and welcoming people
in,'' Ammiano said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
