   EDs: An early version has moved for PMs. A writethrough will
move for AMs.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-DEATHPENALTY _ Florida lawmakers have called a special
legislative session on the state's death penalty. Foes are gleeful,
saying any attempts by lawmakers to change the rules will lead to
more appeals and ultimately may mean there might not be any more
executions in the state for years. (Date, Palm Beach Post). 18-20.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANES _ The number and intensity of Atlantic storms will
ease next year, but not by much, according to professor William
Gray and his colleagues at Colorado State University in Fort
Collins. In their annual forecast, released Wednesday, they are
predicting a ``moderate'' season in 2000 with 11 named storms,
seven hurricanes and three intense hurricanes. Gray said the
residents along the U.S. Atlantic Coast, including Florida, have a
45 percent chance of being hit by one or more major storms with
winds above 100 mph. (Kleinberg, Palm Beach Post). 8. WITH CHART.
</P>
<P>
   BIBLE-SCHOOLS _ FORT MYERS, Fla._One of the first schools to
propose teaching the Bible as history is in this coastal Florida
community. We visit for an update on the debate and lawsuits the
issue has spawned. (Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   GORE-SOUTH _ WASHINGTON _ If Al Gore wins the Democratic
presidential nomination, it will be because of the South. The Old
Confederacy is his ace in the hole should he stumble in the early
voting in Iowa and New Hampshire. As a consequence, he rarely lets
a week pass without tending to his Southern political supporters _
and especially African Americans. For example, he'll be in Atlanta
this weekend for a meeting with black voters before heading to
Orlando for the Florida state Democratic convention. (Shepard, Cox
News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-DEMS _ Florida Democrats gather in Orlando today (FRI.)
where they will here from President Clinton, Vice President Gore
and Bill Bradley this weekend. Also on the agenda, is there
anything they can do to overtake the growing power of the Florida
GOP. (Crowley, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SYRIA _ JERUSALEM _ For decades, Syria has been the
Doctor No of Middle East peace, lambasting Egypt for making peace
and firmly maintaining its state of war against Israel. But, by
Thursday morning, Tel Aviv law clerk Odelia Arad, 28, could
seriously state that she hopes to someday ``eat hummos in
Damascus.'' ``I would like to see the place. It is right next
door,'' Arad said. Though attempts at bringing a peace between
Syria and Israel have ended in failure before, this week's
announcement that talks will begin again in Washington next week
raised hopes that one of the toughest obstacles to peace in the
Middle East could finally be removed. We look at key issues,
reaction in Israel and Syria, and what may have lead to the
breakthrough. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 4 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   DATELINE _ KUMASI, Ghana _ Dateline column from Kumasi, Ghana
about Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writer Don Melvin's former
neighbors and how their kids _ formerly his kids' best friends _
are adjusting to their new life. (Melvin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 18. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-HISPANICS _ WASHINGTON _The Association of Hispanic
Advertising Agencies and StarMedia Network host a news conference
and Webcast to introduce the ''first national Internet campaign
aimed at maximizing the power of the U.S. Hispanic vote.''
(Shepard, Cox News Service). 22.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-DIVIDE _ WASHINGTON _ Corporate chief executives join
Commerce Secretary William M. Daley at a ``Digital Divide''
conference to examine public and private initiatives aimed at
closing the technology gap between rich and poor. (Glass, Cox News
Service). 18.
</P>
