sentenced to 12 years in prison by a Serbian court. By Carlotta
Gall.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-SPACE-SETBACK (Tokyo) _ In the latest setback for Japan's
satellite launching efforts, the government space agency said
Thursday that it would abandon its troubled H-II rocket project,
the cornerstone of its space program, after a series of costly
failures. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   HUMAN-RIGHTS-REPORTS (Washington) _ Human Rights Watch and
Amnesty International issue annual reports. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-TV-HOLYYEAR (Rome) _ Italy, the country that perfected
housewife strip-tease quiz shows, is better known for pizazz than
piety on television. But on Dec. 25, a Roman Catholic Holy Year
begins, one that coincides with the 2,000th anniversary of the
birth of Jesus. So even on television, there will be little respite
from the Jubilee celebration. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   (Tentative; this story may be held for space reasons.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-WORKERS (Milwaukee, Wis.) _ Lots of people consider
themselves experts on this city's war on welfare, but few have
ridden its highs and lows as intensely as Michael Steinborn. A
self-deprecating man who is quick to emphasize his failures as a
caseworker, Steinborn, 31, is not one to see himself starring in a
sunny story of social progress. By Jason DeParle. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   KING-TRIAL-ASSESS (Atlanta) _ Examining the meaning of the
verdict in the King case. Meanwhile, the King family holds a news
conference offering their own views on the same subject.
</P>
<P>
   MASS-FIREFIGHTERS (Worcester, Mass.) _ President Clinton attends
memorial service for six fallen firefighters. Meanwhile, as the
city struggles with its loss, there is a remarkable amount of
compassion for the homeless couple charged with touching off the
fatal blaze. By Somini Sengupta. (With photos.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-CATHOLICS-POLL (New York) _ A New York Times poll looks at
attitudes of Catholics in the New York Archdiocese. (With a
graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-TEACHERS-CHEATING (New York) _ Not surprisingly, many of the
districts where educators cheated on standardized tests were those
with sordid histories of corruption: buying a principal's job,
stealing a school's grand piano, putting the children of Staten
Island politicians into a selective school. In that culture, many
teachers don't mind going along and looking the other way.
</P>
<P>
   MANDELA-GATES (Seattle) _ Nelson Mandela meets with Bill Gates.
Developing. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-JEWS _ Plans for a summit meeting between Baptists and
Jews, who are very angry over recent conversion tactics by Baptist,
may have fallen apart. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MARS-OCEAN _ Evidence of an ancient ocean is found on Mars.
By William J. Broad. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SPACE-HAZARD (Washington) _ A U.S. study finds big radiation
hazards in space walks, thanks to increased solar activity. By
Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENE-THERAPY (Bethesda, Md.) _ Fireworks are expected at the
second day of federal hearings on a death in a gene therapy trial.
By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BRADLEY (Washington) _ In his relentless attacks on Bill
Bradley, Vice President Al Gore is following closely to the script
written by his mentor, Bill Clinton. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   TRUMP-ASSESS (Los Angeles) _ Is Donald Trump serious? In
interviews over a few days, a reporters tries to determine whether
the New York real estate tycoon really wants to be president. By
Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-BLACKS (Los Angeles) _ Bill Bradley speaks before the
Congress of National Black Churches. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NTSB-CHALLENGES (Washington) _ A look at the challenges faced by
the National Transportation Safety Board as it seeks to carry out
its mandate. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (Moving in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-CORPORATE-DONORS _ Huge companies that once shrugged off
the United Nations as a worthy, if often ineffectual, agency now
see it as a valuable partner, one that can open doors and act as a
valuable buffer between them and the governments of countries where
they want to do business. By Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   TYCO-SEC-INQUIRY _ Tyco International Ltd., which has made more
than $30 billion in purchases in the last three years, says the
Securities and Exchange Commission is conducting an informal
inquiry relating to reserves and charges it takes for acquisitions.
Tyco shares tumble 34 percent. by Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-ASSESS _ Looking at whether the shift at the top of
Coca-Cola signals that the company will change the way it sets
targets for growth. Includes an interview with Coke's new chief
executive, Douglas Daft. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   DUTCH-PHONE-DEAL (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Royal KPN, the biggest
Dutch phone company, says it is in talks to buy a stake in E-Plus
Mobilfunk, Germany's No. 3 wireless network, which would thwart
France Telecom's plans to expand in Germany. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-GADGETS (Rome) _ Looking at new advances in European
household appliances, including a washing machine that can be
operated from a cell phone. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks are modestly higher in early trading.
The Dow Jones industrial average is up 0.92 percent, the S&AMP;P 500 is
up 0.49 percent and the Nasdaq composite index is up 0.83 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   COLLINS-COLUMN _ ``Public Interests,'' by By Gail Collins.
</P>
