<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4187 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-IVOR-JULIANNE-MOORE-I     12-09 1429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-JULIANNE-MOORE-IN-THE-END-OF-THE-AFFAIR-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JULIANNE MOORE AND ONE HOT `AFFAIR' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Julianne Moore
with Ralph Fiennes in ``The End of the Affair.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Since he starred in ``The English Patient'' (1997), Ralph
Fiennes has been acclaimed as ``the thinking woman's sex symbol.''
 &HT;    And, speaking of thinking women, independent-film veteran
Julianne Moore is widely known as one of Hollywood's most
intelligent actresses.
 &HT;    So what's it like when the two get together between the sheets
for ``The End of the Affair,'' a new adaptation of the classic
Graham Greene novel?
 &HT;    Pretty steamy, to hear Moore tell it.
 &HT;    ``The love scenes had to be torrid,'' she says unhesitatingly.
``Our characters are choked up with passion. We must show this is
no one-night stand _ they are literally consumed by the physical
passion they have for each other. It was all about sex at first,
but when they fall in love it only intensifies their sexual
appetites for one another.''
 &HT;    Not every actress would sign on for so much sex and nudity
without thinking twice, but then Moore, who will turn 39 on Dec.
30, is not every actress. Known as an extravagant risk-taker, she's
proven that she'll do whatever it takes to make a role work.
 &HT;    She shook moviegoers out of their seats by going bottomless to
deliver an extended monologue in Robert Altman's ``Short Cuts''
(1993). She was Oscar-nominated for ``Boogie Nights'' (1997), in
which she improbably made a sympathetic character out of a
drug-addicted porn star, and earlier this year she displayed
satin-smooth villainy as a scandal-mongering widow scheming to
entrap Jeremy Northam and Rupert Everett in ``An Ideal Husband.''
 &HT;    Nonetheless, she wasn't an obvious choice for ``The End of the
Affair,'' having to beat out scores of well-known British actresses
for her role as a beautiful, conflicted Englishwoman in one of
Greene's most Catholic novels, based on an actual event in the
novelist's life during World War II.
 &HT;    Fiennes plays Maurice Bendrix, a tormented novelist who falls
madly in love with Sarah Miles (Moore), who is trapped in a sexless
marriage with a boring civil servant (Stephen Rea). Adding to the
volatile situation is that her husband and Bendrix are close
friends.
 &HT;    As bombs explode over London and most sane people flee to
shelters, the couple joyously make love, until one night something
happens to shatter the affair and plunge them into a moral conflict
that brings misery to them both.
 &HT;    Moore wanted the part badly _ so badly that, having only
recently given birth to her now-2-year-old son Cal, she pumped
enough breast milk to let her leave the baby briefly to fly to
London to test for the part.
 &HT;    Hiring an American to play Fiennes' lover was a gamble, but
writer/director Neil Jordan _ best known for ``The Crying Game''
(1992) _ says he took it without hesitation.
 &HT;    ``What got Julianne the role,'' he says, ``was the instant
chemistry obvious from the first day she and Ralph worked together
_ from the moment they first met, really.''
 &HT;    Moore agrees that the two stars felt an instant attraction.
 &HT;    ``Ralph is an incredibly sexy man,'' she says, ``not because of
his looks, but because of his intelligence and the confidence he
exudes.''
 &HT;    As for the sex scenes, Jordan says, they have a quality rare in
an American movie _ they are about real, adult people.
 &HT;    ``In our movie it really looks as though they are having sex,''
Jordan says. ``It's clumsy and beautiful at the same time _ not
what you usually see in a Hollywood film.''
 &HT;    Moore's greatest asset as an actress _ the chameleon quality
that enables her to adapt so completely to each character that she
is almost unrecognizable from one role to the next _ has so far
kept her from achieving the all-important ``brand name'' star
status, despite several previous forays into consciously mainstream
films.
 &HT;    But ``End of the Affair'' could be the movie that moves her onto
the A-list. Already there's a hot Oscar buzz for the actress whom
moviegoers no longer confuse with that other screen siren named
Moore.
 &HT;    The un-Demi comes by her adaptability honestly. The daughter of
a psychiatric social worker and a military judge, she grew up as a
self-described ``geek,'' one of several actresses whose ``Army
brat'' childhoods taught them how to blend into a role. She lived
in 23 different home towns before arriving at Boston University's
School of Performing Arts, where she earned a degree in acting.
 &HT;    From Off-Broadway plays, she branched out into television with
parts on the daytime soaps ``The Edge of the Night'' (l985-l988)
and ``As the World Turns'' in the late 1980s. On the big screen,
she met a grisly end in the thriller ``The Hand that Rocks the
Cradle'' (1992), then had a small but eye-catching role as a
supportive doctor in Harrison Ford's box-office hit ``The
Fugitive'' (l993).
 &HT;    From Day 1, she adamantly resisted typecasting. She played an
actress in Louis Malle's intricate ``Vanya on 42nd Street'' (l994),
then appeared as Hugh Grant's pregnant girlfriend in the mainstream
romantic comedy ``Nine Months'' (l995). She was Picasso's troubled
mistress Dora Maar opposite Anthony Hopkins in ``Surviving
Picasso'' (l996), then turned up in Steven Spielberg's ``The Lost
World: Jurassic Park'' (l997). Last year she played a bizarre
seductress opposite Jeff Bridges in the Coen brothers' ``The Big
Lebowski'' (l998).
 &HT;    Now she has no fewer than three high-profile films coming out at
the same time. Besides ``End of the Affair,'' there's ``Map of the
World,'' which stars Sigourney Weaver, and ``Magnolia,'' in which
she plays Tom Cruise's looney stepmother for ``Boogie Nights''
director Paul Thomas Anderson.
 &HT;    But it's ``The End of the Affair'' that stands to win her star
status, not to mention possibly turning her into a sex symbol.
Predictably, she has no qualms about nudity or sex scenes in her
movies, nor any worry that they'll turn out tasteless or
gratuitous.
 &HT;    ``I don't need a nudity clause in my contract,'' she says,
``because I will only work with people I know won't exploit me.''
 &HT;    She does note that Fiennes _ who shared some passionate love
scenes with Kristin Scott Thomas in ``The English Patient'' _ went
out of his way to make sure his co-star was comfortable.
 &HT;    ``Ralph treated me with such concern and tenderness in those
nude scenes,'' the actress says. ``He was protecting me the entire
time, which allowed me to be far more liberated.
 &HT;    ``Ralph was very brave and a good sport,'' she adds with a
laugh. ``We had fun making jokes about his beautiful rear end. But
I felt like the tables were turned _ usually it's the woman who
worries about what she looks like naked.''
 &HT;    The film is very different from the l955 screen version, which
starred Van Johnson, Peter Cushing and Deborah Kerr. The story may
be set in the 1940s, she explains, but the remarkably graphic love
scenes could never have been shown to audiences of 50 years ago.
 &HT;    ``The only way you knew Deborah had sex was when you saw her
putting her earrings back on,'' she says. ``In our film, they can't
keep their hands off each other.''
 c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The End of the Affair,''
consult the official Website at www.theendoftheaffair.com. And
don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
