<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4246 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-FASHION-WEB-KANSAS-KA     12-09 1351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-WEB-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE STORES CAST A WIDE NET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JACKIE WHITE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is a Picasso painting on your holiday gift list? Are you on a
quest for an Elgin pocket watch made in 1890? What about a Prada
bag, John Hardy silver braided bracelet or maybe just one big
diamond?
</P>
<P>
   All of these may be purchased on the Internet in less time than
it takes to shower for a shopping trip. Find all the pashmina
cashmere shawls you can count and almost enough bubble bath and
bath gels to fill the Grand Canyon with suds.
</P>
<P>
   The world of cyber shopping for fashion and beauty products is
getting crowded. From basic tried-and-true catalog brands such as
Lands' End and J.Crew, the options are expanding to include a flood
of upscale indulge-yourself sites and beauty stores. One new site
is, in fact, called indulge.com.
</P>
<P>
   In this thriving economy when people with big money are spending
big money, surfing the Net is a bit like strolling down New York's
Fifth Avenue where luxury retailers such as Cartier and Bergdorf
Goodman evolve into discount camera stores and jewelers who seem to
be forever going out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Consider LuxuryFinders.com, with a Picasso painting and David
Webb's $19,000 earrings, Ashford.com with Montblanc pens and
vintage watches and buyarock.com for diamonds. Bluefly.com, the
off-price site, has Prada bags and shoes discounted up to 50
percent. The company sold out of $79 pashmina cashmere shawls in
three days. The cashmere sweaters at $750 are among the choices on
neimanmarcus.com.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of beauty sites offer everything from lipsticks, skin
care products and personal consultation to pamper-yourself
products. Check off your gift list with bath gels, skin lotions,
aroma fragrance candles and bath soaps in a few hours of clicking.
</P>
<P>
   With such a new medium growing so quickly, the big issue is
customer service. Everyone is racing to raise the level of perks to
attract shoppers from traditional stores and to set themselves
apart from their competitors. Gift suggestion lists, basic gift
wrapping and free shipping are some of the offerings. Magazines,
chatty columns, celebrity makeup items and e-mailed trend updates
are meant to enhance the experience as entertainment. Return
policies vary, but some sites allow anywhere from 30 days to
forever to send back unwanted merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that last year everyone was enamored with the idea of
the Internet,'' says Jeremy Hauser, research analyst for Lands'
End. ``This year people want more shopping aids.''
</P>
<P>
   To deal with the challenge of getting a good fit, Lands' End,
for instance, offers you the opportunity to submit measurements and
create a ``personal model'' on which to try clothes. A consultant
is available by telephone or interactive site to move you
electronically to where you want to be.
</P>
<P>
   Clothing designer Norma Kamali at omo-norma-kamali.com supplies
online personal shoppers out of her New York boutique OMO. They not
only make selections for you, but they also send clothes out on
trial to try on in your home without charge. You have 48 hours to
return.
</P>
<P>
   Webby, a cyber model compiled from a wide range of ethnic faces
from all over the world, will be helping out at beautyjungle.com in
a few months.
</P>
<P>
   And promotional efforts, including advertising campaigns in
major fashion magazines, are impressive. Actress Tracey Ullman was
recently on NBC's ``Today Show'' promoting purpledress.com.
</P>
<P>
   Location, location
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the big question these days for such a new venue is:
If they build it, will consumers come? Does anyone buy cashmere
without a feel? Will you choose a $100 fragrance without a whiff?
</P>
<P>
   Some people see the Net strictly as a replenishment source where
you go for a red lipstick, a man's dress shirt or a fleece top.
People who buy pricey goods will still want the experience of the
store, the service and the smells. Right?
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Ghive, who heads Internet services for Doneger Group, New
York retail consultants, disagrees. She says the Web is an ``added
element. If I'm going to buy Gucci, I may go to the store. But two
days later, if I decide I want a handbag, I'm not going back to the
store.'' The businesses in the best positions for the moment are
those with both sites and retail stores, she says, such as Neiman
Marcus or Nordstrom's.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed industry insiders acknowledge Web shopping is in a
fledgling stage. But Boston-based Forrester Research Inc. predicts
8.6 million household shoppers will spend $4 billion on the
Internet between Thanksgiving weekend and year's end. Forrester has
traditionally been bullish about apparel potential, urging business
to move quickly in that direction. The company anticipates that
most money will go to ``researched items'' such as electronics and
home furnishings, followed by ``convenience goods,'' such as a CD
or a J.Crew sweater.
</P>
<P>
   Overall the mood is optimistic as the holiday shopping moves
into full swing.
</P>
<P>
   At America Online Inc., sales tripled during the three-day
Thanksgiving weekend last year, says Patrick Gates, vice president
of E-commerce. Four million AOL members apparently made purchases,
600,000 for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   During the Thanksgiving weekend, sales at bluefly.com went up
700 percent over last year, says CEO Kenneth Seiff.
</P>
<P>
   QVC's iQVC.com had $1 million in sales on Sunday of Thanksgiving
weekend, with jewelry and clothing among the top sellers.
</P>
<P>
   And when beautyjungle.com launched last month, the company had
gift bags to give to the first 10,000 site visitors. Executives
expected the promotion to last two weeks. The bags were gone the
first day.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, here is a brief look at just a few new sites you
may want to scan, gather ideas or dream. Be aware that some are so
new they are not yet completed.
</P>
<P>
   - Sephora.com: Here is the superstore of cosmetics. Not only
does the store have its own beauty line with 365 lipstick colors,
but it also stocks many other brands including some from Europe
difficult to find in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Gift ideas here include Hard Candy's dog tag kit that includes
pink eye glitter, ``Hick'' nail polish and, yes, silver tags, one
the shape of a silver dog with blue crystal eyes, $30.
</P>
<P>
   You can also buy Demeter's ``Virtual Celebration'' pickup
fragrance kit including ``Fir'' and ``Gin &AMP; Tonic'' scented sprays
and ``Sugar Cookie'' travel candle.
</P>
<P>
   - indulge.com: The selection here includes pashmina cashmere
shawls at $250; tote bags from Un Apres Midi de Chien at $105;
celebrity-favorite Selina glass frames in the $200-plus range;
Stella Pace power bracelets, $30; and Gerard Yosca hair barrettes,
$23 to $34.
</P>
<P>
   - Ashford.com: Elgin vintage watches here date as far back as
the 1880s and are priced from about $275. Choose from a range of
animal print accessories, Jhane Barnes ties starting at $70 and
jewelry from designers such as Lisa Jinks and Judith Jack.
</P>
<P>
   - LuxuryFinders.com: The site lives up to its name. You'll find
ties starting at $135 by Brioni, who dressed the current James
Bond; pashmina travel pillows at $135; and Picasso's painting at
$320,000. For stocking stuffers consider Dean &AMP; Deluca's ``truffle
shaver'' and a $95 Palm Pilot case.
</P>
<P>
   - shegetsdressed.com: Linked to women.com. It's a fun site with
a magazine format and tips sure to keep you trend-savvy. The
offering includes pashmina shawls at $260, a faux fur-trimmed
sweater at $138, silk handbags at $138 and sterling drop and floret
earrings at $18.
</P>
<P>
   - neimanmarcus.com: It's one of the easiest to navigate and
packed with pricey goods such as John Hardy $395 cuff links, an
Agnona cashmere teddy bear at $240 and cashmere sweaters from $700
to $1,000. You can zoom in for closeups. Most affordable item is
Stella Pace power beads, $30.
</P>
<P>
   - bocado.com: Beaux Cadeaux in French means ``beautiful gifts,''
and the e-tailer is trying to make the name ring true. The choices
here include the likes of deco perfume bottles at $180, Trussardi
python bag at $700 and Margaretha Ley perfume for $48.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
