<HEADER>
A4252 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-GREEN-MILE-REVIE     12-09 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GREEN-MILE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GREEN MILE' TAKES LONG, ENGAGING JOURNEY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box at bottom). 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stephen King's popular serial novel ends with the lament,
``sometimes, oh God, the green mile is so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Darabont's three hour-plus film adaptation of ``The Green
Mile'' will probably elicit similar comments from many viewers _
but minus the implied sense of agony. That's because, out of all
the movies this season that take much too much time to tell their
essentially short stories, this one trudges along most engagingly.
</P>
<P>
   Everything from sensitive performances to burnished
cinematography (by ``The Phantom Menace's'' David Tattersall) to
that tough-to-nail quality of effortless tonal management is done
with deliberate, exquisite care. That doesn't disguise the fact
that Darabont and company are making a portentous mountain out of a
narrative molehill here, but it does bring an unusually high degree
of entertainment value to the enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   And for what it's worth, this ``Twilight Zone'' episode of a
tale does possess interesting resonances, although in all the time
adapter-director Darabont spent he still failed to plumb them all
fully. He gets the most obvious theme, an updated Christ story set
in a 1930s Louisiana prison, all right. And he does pretty well, if
a little too timidly, by the story's anti-death penalty subplot.
The thing's racial politics are just plain goofy, though, and
Darabont makes no effort to confront or rebut King's
paternalistic/mystical take on African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, this was a film designed to appear important and
humanistic, but one that was unwilling to challenge its perceived
mass audience in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Told in flashback by a strangely troubled old man, the movie
proper takes place over the last months, in 1935, of the remarkable
John Coffey (Michael Clarke Duncan), a gentle, childlike giant of a
man who seems utterly incapable of having raped and murdered two
little girls but has been convicted of the acts anyway.
</P>
<P>
   He's a new resident on Cold Mountain Penitentiary's Death Row,
dubbed the Green Mile for the sickly lime paint covering the floor
that leads to the execution chamber. The Mile is run by Paul
Edgecomb, the most decent fellow who has ever worked in a Southern
penal system _ we know that because he's played by a chubby, even
cuddlier-than-usual Tom Hanks _ and Edgecomb insists on running a
low-key, respectable operation. His veteran staffers _
second-in-command Brutus ``Brutal'' Howell (David Morse), old-hand
Harry Terwilliger (Jeffrey DeMunn) and nice young family man Dean
Stanton (Barry Pepper) _ are all committed to making their doomed
charges' final weeks as pleasant as circumstances permit.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, circumstances often don't. The Mile's key
roadblocks to harmony include a sadistic little weasel of a new
guard, Doug Hutchison's Percy Westmore, hated by colleagues and
inmates alike but protected by an aunt who's married to the
governor. And there's also a troublemaking sociopath, Wild Bill
Wharton (Sam Rockwell), who refuses to go into that good night, or
even sit in his cell, quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Once the good and bad people have been unmistakably delineated,
Darabont eases us, slowly of course, into the story's moral
conundrums. Edgecomb, whose younger version is introduced to us
with a bear of a urinary infection, at one point finds his crotch
clutched in Coffey's massive fist. Moments later, the big guy
exhales a mass of shimmering particles and, to the delight of both
Paul and his wonderful wife, Jan (Bonnie Hunt), the boss suddenly
feels great down there.
</P>
<P>
   Coffey's miraculous healing abilities are further demonstrated
on a little mouse the cellblock adopts _ and that we are given more
than ample opportunity to adore. Tedium gets broken by several
interestingly ritualized electric chair fire-ups, one of which goes
grotesquely awry. But the main drama here, of course, unwraps
around the question of Coffey's evident saintliness and inevitable
sacrifice. The nicer white folks, at least, feel mighty bad about
all that.
</P>
<P>
   Hanks, as he so reliably can, humanizes his paragon of penal
virtue in an earthy, unfussy and wholly satisfying way. Duncan
exudes sad sweetness towering enough to match his frame, though
little of the real angst someone forced, against their preference,
to suffer in the name of others would naturally feel. Hutchison and
Rockwell are memorably, irredeemably hissable. And as other
prisoners, Michael Jeter, Graham Greene and Harry Dean Stanton
register well.
</P>
<P>
   Darabont's only other feature directing effort was ``The
Shawshank Redemption'' five years ago. Like ``Green Mile,'' it,
too, was an overlong-Stephen King-prison story. And like that one,
the new film will certainly have its passionate champions. It's so
well-crafted that it seems like a feast, even when your brain is
telling you that this story could not possibly be stretched any
thinner. &QL; 
____ &QL; 
The film: ``The Green Mile'' (R; violence, language, nudity, sex). &QL; 
The stars: Tom Hanks, Michael Clarke Duncan, David Morse, Doug
Hutchison, Bonnie Hunt, Sam Rockwell, James Cromwell and Michael
Jeter. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Written and directed by Frank Darabont, based on
Stephen King's novel. Produced by Darabont and David Valdes.
Released by Warner Bros. &QL; 
Running time: Three hours, eight minutes. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 1529EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4254 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-TRAVEL-DUBLIN-KANSAS-     12-09 1585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-DUBLIN-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS IRISH CAPITAL PROSPERS, ITS TOURIST APPEAL GROWS RICHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN HOLDER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland _ The doors around Merrion Square line up like
the paints in a preschooler's watercolor tray: red and green and
blue and pink and yellow and black.
</P>
<P>
   I'm quite intrigued and I can't figure out why. They are just
doors, after all.
</P>
<P>
   The two quick days ahead won't allow me much time to really get
an understanding of Dublin, the complicated, now prosperous Irish
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Yet here are these doors, stealing away precious minutes. They
do that to visitors, who snap pictures by the roll. Shops sell key
chains, postcards, prints, posters, even Christmas tree ornaments,
all celebrating them. No other feature of Dublin seems quite so
omnipresent. What is it about them?
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I might have trouble finding my way home here in the
Georgian section. Many of the town houses are nearly identical.
</P>
<P>
   The vividly painted doors set each house apart, of course. But
the beauty isn't in the doors per se. It's all around them, points
out Deirdre Burns, a former schoolteacher and native Dubliner who
now helps tourists get a grasp on her city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doors often gave an indication of the status of the house,
particularly on Merrion Square, where the aristocracy lived,''
Burns said one October morning as we strolled around Merrion
Square. Most of the homes belong to businesses now.
</P>
<P>
   Notice the fanlight over the door, she said. The leaded glass
design of one might look like simple rays stretching out from the
sun, but the one next door more closely resembles the spindles of a
ship's wheel. Another looks like a spider's web. The sidelights
flanking each door are distinct, too.
</P>
<P>
   So are the boot scrapers protruding from each stoop. And how
about that mini-manhole cover on the sidewalk? Coal was once
delivered there each day. The foundries made sure these were
singularly ornamental, too.
</P>
<P>
   I knew there was something special about this place. It must
have been quite the neighborhood during Dublin's building boom of
the early 18th century.
</P>
<P>
   Some big names from Dublin's past are said to have lived here:
The poet W.B. Yeats. Irish nationalist leader Daniel O'Connell. The
writer Oscar Wilde, who was born in one house and spent some of his
adulthood in another.
</P>
<P>
   And Wilde remains, by way of a statue, reclining on a large rock
in Merrion Square, across from his home, now part of the American
College.
</P>
<P>
   It's tempting to while away the day here at Merrion Square, with
its lush, green-even-in-October lawn and schoolchildren in their
caps and plaids. But the rest of Dublin won't wait.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart
</P>
<P>
   This is a city teeming with activity, block after block after
block, and nearly perfect for exploring on foot.
</P>
<P>
   Midafternoon on a Monday, Grafton Street, the city's main
shopping and pedestrian thoroughfare, is almost shoulder to
shoulder with businesspeople, shoppers and tourists. One street
musician plays a traditional Irish tune, while down the street
another sings Elvis Presley. Tourists pose for pictures with a
statue of the mythical fishmonger Molly Malone at the end of the
street.
</P>
<P>
   The streets are jammed with cars as well. Traffic has become a
real problem, I'm told, because many residents finally have been
able to leave the buses behind for their own cars.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland is suddenly prosperous, and the last few years have
brought many immigrants _ once almost unheard of in Ireland _ to
Dublin, Burns said.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism is up, too. ``Dublin has become a very popular place for
weekend trips from the Continent over the last few years,'' Burns
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Temple Bar neighborhood, she said, is one hot spot. ``They
even have dancers on standby to teach you to riverdance, believe it
or not,'' Burns said.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few years ago Temple Bar was a neglected area in the
middle of Dublin. Now it's the bohemian section, known for music
and dance clubs, pubs and funky little shops crowded along narrow,
cobblestone streets.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly on weekends, the streets and restaurants become
packed. But even on a warm fall afternoon, it's a great place for
people watching.
</P>
<P>
   Old vs. new
</P>
<P>
   Its proximity to Trinity College, just to the east, no doubt
explains in part Temple Bar's popularity with young Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   Trinity, on the other hand, relies on the old to draw visitors.
It's also a place where you can begin to learn about the political
and religious history of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Trinity College was founded by Queen Elizabeth I in 1592 as a
Protestant college for men. Even as late as the 1960s Catholics had
to get special permission to attend _ or face excommunication.
</P>
<P>
   Trinity's must-see attraction, indeed one of Dublin's, is the
Book of Kells, an elaborately decorated edition of the four Gospels
that dates to the eighth or ninth century, maybe even earlier.
Tradition says the work was finished in the Abbey at Kells, in
County Meath. It's been at Trinity since 1661.
</P>
<P>
   Only two pages _ one a page of text from Luke, the other a
portrait of St. John _ are on display under glass in the college
library. The dimly lit, almost hushed room creates a reverential
atmosphere for this relic. It's a work that defies you to be
unimpressed _ by the craftsmanship if nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   These gospels were written on calfskin, using quill pens made
from the feathers of swans and geese. The text is impressive, to be
sure, but what really struck me was the rich detail of the
illustrations. I could have stared at St. John for hours, seeing
more and more images and details, some almost daring me to notice
them.
</P>
<P>
   Religious roots
</P>
<P>
   Like Trinity, politics and religion compete for attention at
many of this city's attractions. Walk through central Dublin and
you'll notice _ well, at least if you have a guide as savvy about
Irish history as Burns _ that only Protestant churches are on the
main thoroughfares. The English, who ruled Ireland for 700 years,
wouldn't allow anything else. Catholics, 90-plus percent of the
Irish population _ were permitted to build churches only on side
streets. Burns points out a Franciscan congregation, the Church of
Adam and Eve. Its entrance for many years was through a tavern.
</P>
<P>
   Dublin's most prominent cathedrals _ Christ Church and St.
Patrick's _ belong to the Church of Ireland. Both date to the 12th
century.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic or Protestant, the strength of Dublin's Christian roots
is undeniable. St. Patrick himself reportedly baptized
fifth-century converts at a well outside where the cathedral now
stands. Yet even Ireland's patron saint is almost overshadowed
there by another name: Swift.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Swift was the church's dean from 1713 to 1745. He's
buried in the church nave and celebrated throughout.
</P>
<P>
   Here, he is remembered for ``A Sermon on Sleeping in Church,''
not that other work, Gulliver's Travels. (But don't miss the modern
apartments across the street, where concrete medallions recall the
Lilliputians, the Houyhnhnms and the Brobdingnag giants.)
</P>
<P>
   Bad memories
</P>
<P>
   Dublin's most politically charged site may also be the place
where it traces its very origins: Dublin Castle.
</P>
<P>
   The castle garden marks the spot where the rivers Liffey and
(now underground) Poddle once joined to form a black pool or
``Dubhlinn.'' The city sprang up around the confluence of these two
rivers.
</P>
<P>
   But many Dubliners remember it for something else. ``Dublin
Castle used to be a place whose name struck great fear into the
Irish,'' Burns said. It symbolized English rule, was home to the
English viceroys and even served as a prison.
</P>
<P>
   King John ordered the building of the castle in 1204. The castle
undercroft and its Record Tower remain from those first years, but
much of the rest was built over the centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Dubliners even viewed a statue of justice atop the castle as a
sign of England's disdain. ``The woman depicting justice faces in
toward the castle, with her back toward Dublin,'' Burns said.
</P>
<P>
   Now the castle is Ireland's own, a place for important state
events, such as the inauguration of President Mary McAleese in
1997. It's even a film star: The 1996 movie ``Michael Collins,''
about Ireland's struggle for independence, was partly shot there.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring it out
</P>
<P>
   Dublin is a lot to sort out in a couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   On the way back to my hotel, I have to cross through the
Georgian section one last time. That's when I find myself at 29
Lower Fitzwilliam St.
</P>
<P>
   Another townhouse, a gray door this time. But it's open.
</P>
<P>
   Dublin's Electricity Supply Board and the National Museum of
Ireland has restored this home to the way it must have looked when
Olivia Beatty and her family lived in splendor there at the turn of
the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Delicate Italian plasterwork decorates the ceiling of the foyer.
The house is filled with Chippendale tables, Turkish rugs, a
grandfather clock made of sandalwood, huge windows with heavy
draperies, oil paintings with gilded frames and beautiful
chandeliers. A tug on the gold ropes hanging from the ceiling and
she could call any of her three servants, including a live-in
housekeeper.
</P>
<P>
   What a life, I think. Then I learn a little more. Beatty was the
widow of a wine and paper manufacturer and the mother of three
children. I decide she might even be a symbol for Dublin:
Prosperous, sure, but her life was obviously more complex than it
first seemed. And her story was worth hearing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
