<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4257 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-TRAVEL-DUBSIDE-KANSAS     12-09 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-DUBSIDE-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING TO DUBLIN, IRELAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN HOLDER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Getting there
</P>
<P>
   Round trip airfare between Kansas City and Dublin recently ran
as low as $600. If you're headed elsewhere, consider Dublin as side
trip. Round trip from London's Heathrow Airport recently started
about $175.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay
</P>
<P>
   - Holiday Inn, 97-107 Pearse St. The regular quoted rate is
about $160 for a single, but I got a package for $111 a night,
including breakfast. The hotel is within walking distance of
Trinity College, the Georgian section and most central Dublin
sites. Telephone: 01-670-3666. E-mail: info &LR; holidayinndublin.ie.
Web site: www.holidayinndublin.ie.
</P>
<P>
   - Isaacs Hostel, 2-5 Frenchmans Lane. Isaacs describes itself as
the longest established and best-known hostel in central Dublin.
Winter prices are quoted from about $9.50 to $24. Telephone:
01-855-6215. E-mail:hostel &LR; isaaces.ie.
</P>
<P>
   - Merrion, 21-24 Upper Merrion St., between Merrion Square and
St. Stephen's Green. Set in four restored Georgian town houses
dating from the 1760s. Prices start about $270. Telephone:
01-603-0600.
</P>
<P>
   - Shelbourne Hotel, 27 St. Stephen's Green. Described as one of
Europe's grand old hotels. Prices start about $225, Telephone:
01-676-6471.
</P>
<P>
   Getting around
</P>
<P>
   Dublin has no subway system, but buses are plentiful and
inexpensive. Check a map first, though. Central Dublin is fairly
compact, and most sites are within walking distance of one another.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a narrated trip aboard a Dublin City Tour bus. For
about $9.45, you can see the city's most-visited spots and get on
and off the bus as many times as you like. 01-873-4222.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   You can find anything you want in Dublin: American, Italian,
Indian, Mongolian barbecue, Chinese ... A few places even serve
genuine Irish food.
</P>
<P>
   - Bewley's Oriental Cafe, 78 Grafton St. Known for its coffees
and buns, Bewley's draws huge lunchtime crowds for cafeteria-style
food. Other locations throughout Dublin. 01-677-6761.
</P>
<P>
   - Fitzsimmons, 21-22 Wellington Quay, Temple Bar. Seafood,
steaks, chicken dishes. 01-677-9315.
</P>
<P>
   - South Street Restaurant, South Great Georges Street. A wide
variety of pasta dishes and pizzas. 01-475-2273.
</P>
<P>
   What to see
</P>
<P>
   - National Museum. Kildare Street. Free. 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.
Tuesday-Saturday, 2 to 5 p.m. Sunday. 01-677-7444. The National
Museum is home to many of Ireland's most precious treasures, from
the uniform Michael Collins wore as commander in chief of the Free
State Army to the Tara Brooch, dating to the eighth century.
</P>
<P>
   - Book of Kells and the Old Library. Trinity College. About $6.
9:30 a.m.-4:45 p.m. Monday-Saturday; noon-4:30 p.m. Sunday.
01-608-2308. After seeing the magnificent Book of Kells, look
around the Old Library, or Long Room. This 200-foot room holds
200,000 of Trinity College's collection of 3 million books. Since
1803, a copy of every book copyrighted in Britain or Ireland has
gone to Trinity. The Long Room also contains Ireland's oldest harp,
its national symbol.
</P>
<P>
   - Guinness Brewery. Crane Street, just west of Christ Church
Cathedral. About $4. Winter hours: 9:30 a.m.-4 p.m.
Monday-Saturday, noon-4 p.m. Sunday. 01-453-3645. The largest
stout-producing brewery in the world is Dublin's most popular
tourist attraction. You can't get into the brewery itself but you
can visit the hop store, a museum and shop. Admission includes a
complimentary pint of black stout.
</P>
<P>
   - St. Patrick's Cathedral, Patrick Street. About $2.70. Winter
hours: 9 a.m.-6 p.m. weekdays, 9 a.m.-4 p.m. Saturday, 10-11 a.m.,
12:45-3 p.m. Sunday. 01-475-4817. The national cathedral of the
Church of Ireland was erected on the site where St. Patrick
reputedly baptized converts in the fifth century. The church was
dedicated in 1192. It contains the tomb of Jonathan Swift, its
longtime dean and one of Dublin's most celebrated writers.
</P>
<P>
   - Christ Church Cathedral, Christ Church Place and Winetavern
Street. 10 a.m.-5:30 p.m. Monday-Saturday, between services on
Sunday. 01-677-8099. Construction of the church began in 1172. Its
crypt, which includes 12th- and 13th-century vaults, is said to be
Dublin's oldest surviving architecture.
</P>
<P>
   - Dublin Castle, Castle St. Guided tour: About $4. Open 10 a.m.
to 5 p.m. weekdays, 2-5 p.m. weekends. 01-677-7129. Dublin grew up
around the castle, site of the Black Pool that gave the city its
name. It survived seven centuries of English rule and remains of
great importance to the Irish government. In the castle undercroft
you can see excavated parts of the original castle, built in 1204.
My favorite spot was the throne room, where William of Orange's
throne sits strangely low to the ground. Queen Victoria ordered 22
centimeters cut off the legs so she could be more comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   - Ha'penny Bridge. A half-penny toll was once charged to cross
this bridge across the River Liffey. It affords a terrific view of
Dublin and is a good route from Temple Bar to the shopping area
just north of the Liffey.
</P>
<P>
   - Temple Bar. This is the place where young Dublin congregates.
It's a neighborhood filled with pubs, clubs and unusual little
shops. Plenty of good restaurants call Temple Bar home, but it's
also a great place to grab a slice of pizza at midday and
people-watch.
</P>
<P>
   - Number Twentynine, 29 Lower Fitzwilliam St. About $3.40.
01-702-6165. Restored town house in Dublin's Georgian section. Open
10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Tuesday-Saturday, 2-5 p.m. Sunday. Closed Mondays
and the two weeks before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   - Oscar Wilde House, No. 1 Merrion Square. About $2.70. 10
a.m.-noon, Monday, Wednesday and Thursday. 01-662-0281. Tours of
ground and first floors.
</P>
<P>
   Money
</P>
<P>
   The Irish pound, or punt, recently exchanged for about $1.28.
</P>
<P>
   Telephones
</P>
<P>
   Ireland's country code is 353. From the United States, dial
011-353 and drop the initial ``0'' from Dublin's city code, 01.
</P>
<P>
   Information
</P>
<P>
   - Irish Tourist Board, 345 Park Ave., New York, N.Y. 10154
Telephone: (800) 223-6470. Web site: www.ireland.travel.ie - Dublin
Tourism, Suffolk Street, just off Grafton Street. Telephone:
011-353-669792083.
</P>
<P>
   - Temple Bar Information Centre, 18 Eustace St. 01-671-5717.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
