<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4265 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-SCREENPLAY-RIDE-KANSA     12-09 1405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCREENPLAY-RIDE-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCREENWRITER, AUTHOR SHARE EXPERIENCE OF TURNING BOOK INTO FILM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Screenwriter James Schamus and director Ang Lee steer clear of
best sellers and easy reads when they go looking for material.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood typically buys books with no characters and just a
couple of major plot points and a couple of sex scenes _ and that's
all they need,'' Schamus said during a recent visit to Kansas City
for the regional premiere of their latest effort, ``Ride With the
Devil.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, later on they realize there's nothing there to work
with, and they end up making the same old movie we've already seen
a dozen times before.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the locally shot ``Ride,'' which opened in Kansas
City, New York and Los Angles on Nov. 24 and is now widening to
other major markets. It is most certainly not the same old movie.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Missouri writer Daniel Woodrell's 1987 novel Woe to
Live On, it's a gruesome yet poetic look at the conflict as seen
though the eyes of a teen-aged Confederate guerrilla caught up in
an escalating war of atrocity and revenge.
</P>
<P>
   After the film's debut here, Schamus _ who in addition to
writing and producing movies teaches film at New York's Columbia
University _ and Woodrell, of West Plains, Mo., sat down to discuss
the tricks of turning a novel into a movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ang and I tend to look for the challenge,'' Schamus said,
``for some kind of resistance that says we've got to make a movie
rather than just a filmed book.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Woe to Live On, that challenge was to be found in
the novel's language, a curious blend of down-home phraseology and
florid 19th-century ornamentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were far better writers than people are today,'' said
Woodrell of the Civil War soldiers whose letters and diaries he
studied before writing the novel. ``Their main literary influences
were Sir Walter Scott and Shakespeare. Scott in particular gave the
South plenty of ridiculous romantic notions that they tried to live
up to.''
</P>
<P>
   Schamus praises Woodrell's novel as ``a completely literary work
with unbelievably rich language, and yet it's incredibly cinematic
_ the best of both worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   The trick was to find a cinematic and narrative way of capturing
the book's unique literary voice. The novel is a first-person
account by Jake ``Dutchy'' Roedel, who displays unexpected
eloquence and subtle psychological shadings.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, this paragraph:
</P>
<P>
   We made trash of men and places. At Sweet Springs we found the
houses of two Unionists who had tried to waylay Cave Wyatt when he
had visited his mother there. Both men were unaware of us and smug
_ but not for long. Cave put amens to their miserable existences
after delivering unto them a knotty sermon. Their homes became
beacons.
</P>
<P>
   This weirdly lyrical passage describes with breathtaking economy
the ambushing, torturing (the ``knotty sermon'') and killing of two
enemies, followed by the burning of their houses. Jake's genteel
choice of words distances us _ and himself _ from the horrible
reality.
</P>
<P>
   But how do you put that scene in a movie and achieve the same
effect?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you can't do it,'' Schamus said. ``Film has an
immediacy that hits you in the face. We often found ourselves
toning down the material.''
</P>
<P>
   A filmmaker's vision
</P>
<P>
   The first scene in the book describes how the guerrillas
surprise a family of German immigrants who are staunch Unionists.
The father is lynched, and when the man's 12-year-old son attempts
to cut him down, Jake shoots the boy. We immediately understand
that because his own German parentage raises suspicions among his
colleagues, Jake wants to prove his loyalty through ruthless
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Woodrell explained: ``Redemption is only important if it can be
offered to those who have been down a really ugly trail. I'm not
talking about adulterers and tax cheaters. I'm talking about people
who have done things so bad they can't let themselves think about
it. That's Jake's situation.''
</P>
<P>
   But what works brilliantly on the page may be too ghastly to be
seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you saw that happen on the screen, you would recoil so
badly you'd never recover,'' Schamus said. ``Just seeing it, you'd
never understand why it happened. And you'd never accept Jake as
the protagonist you're to follow for the rest of the film. He'd be
forever tainted as a bad guy.''
</P>
<P>
   An early draft of Schamus' screenplay had Jake shooting the
12-year-old only after the boy picked up a gun and attempted to
attack the guerrillas. That way, at least, the killing seemed less
like the cold-blooded murder of a child.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, the entire passage was dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ang wanted that scene in the movie,'' Schamus said. ``But
could we possibly get away with it? Finally we had to respect the
reality that we couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the film is tremendously faithful to the book in tone. As
much as 70 percent of the dialogue in ``Ride With the Devil'' is
drawn directly from the novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's that good, why mess with it?'' Schamus said.
</P>
<P>
   In numerous instances Jake's thoughts, appearing in the book as
interior monologues, have been converted into dialogue and spoken
aloud.
</P>
<P>
   Woodrell is grateful that his ``linguistic stew'' somehow was
translated to film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really amazed that they could retain it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the novel begins with the guerrilla riders and only
reveals the main characters' histories in piecemeal fashion, the
film takes a straight chronological approach.
</P>
<P>
   Schamus created a prologue _ centering on a wedding _ that
establishes the comfortable lives of the Missouri aristocracy and
how the depredations of raiding Jayhawkers from Kansas drove
Missourians like Jake to join outlawed Bushwhacker bands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studio was anxious that people get a political explanation
up front of where these characters are coming from,'' Schamus said.
``But we found out in our research screenings that the more we
tried to explain the political situation, the less satisfying the
film was to the viewer. So we took a lot of that out. As it is,
people naturally tend to experience this as an ideological film
depending on where they're coming from, on whether they tend to
side with the North or the South.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeds of the American empire
</P>
<P>
   At director Lee's urging, Schamus did create from whole cloth a
long monologue that reflects one of the film's underlying themes.
Lee, a native of Taiwan, had long observed with fascination _ and
some dismay _ that American culture and ideas have colonized much
of Earth, and he believes that the Civil War marked the beginning
of this ``Yankee-ization'' of the planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to find a way to articulate these things that were on
Ang's mind,'' Schamus noted.
</P>
<P>
   His answer was to put them in the mouth of Evans, a gentleman
farmer on whose land the guerrillas hide out during the winter. One
night in his parlor over brandy, Evans reluctantly admits that the
South cannot possibly win because the Yankees, with their notions
of public education and indifference to class, won't be satisfied
until everyone everywhere thinks just like them.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, I figured that dialogue would end up on
the cutting room floor,'' Schamus admitted. ``But people respond to
that. It seems to have hit a nerve.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the inevitable tinkering that takes place between the
printed page and the silver screen, Woodrell describes his
experiences with the filmmakers as overwhelmingly positive. At
various times throughout the production Schamus consulted with the
novelist and sent him drafts of the screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gather from other novelists who have sold books to the
movies that this is not always the case,'' Woodrell said with dry
understatement. ``So my view of the process may not be typical.''
</P>
<P>
   Does Woodrell have any interest in writing for the screen?
</P>
<P>
   ``Only in the same way I'm interested in poetry,'' he said.
``I'm interested in film writing on a kind of fragmentary basis,
but I'll never devote myself to it. Writing novels has spoiled me.
I get to cast them, edit them and produce them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I talk about novelists getting involved in moviemaking, I
like to paraphrase Robert E. Lee,'' Woodrell said. ``It is a good
thing that moviemaking is so terrible, lest we grow to love it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
