<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4266 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-ANIMATION-JAPANESE-KA     12-09 1570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMATION-JAPANESE-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE `ANIME' DARES TO GO WHERE NO ANIMATION HAS GONE BEFORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON BARNHART  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Pokemon'' may be the most successful Japanese cartoon to wash
onto American shores, but it's far from the only one. On Internet
sites such as animenation.com or in video catalogs, you can
purchase hundreds of video titles featuring .MDNM/``anime,'' as
Japanimation is commonly called.
</P>
<P>
   But you may want to think twice before you let some of the most
popular anime films fall into the hands of your ``Pokemon''-loving
kids.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for instance, ``Ghost in the Shell,'' a violent action
movie that was dubbed into English into 1996 and has sold half a
million copies in the United States alone. Like many anime films,
``Ghost in the Shell'' takes place in a not-too-distant but barely
recognizable future. Humans are surgically altered to assume the
qualities of robots. These hybrids are then hooked up to the
Internet so the police can keep tabs on their brains. All is well
in this Big Brother fantasy until one day an evil virus hacks its
way onto the Net and starts erasing people's hard drives ... er,
memories.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is ``Ghost in the Shell'' hard to follow _ one of its
chief intrigues is that one never quite knows where a character's
human nature ends and robotic nature begins _ but there also are
frequent gun battles, female nudity and, in the opening minutes, a
graphic assassination scene.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say there aren't also several best-selling anime
titles appropriately aimed at children. In fact, anime has almost
as many different flavors as ``Pokemon'' has critters. In Japan,
where the average adult reads 200 comic books a year, anime _ which
grew out of Japanese comic book art _ has been a dominant force in
the culture for three generations, with something for every age and
interest. Think of anime almost as a medium rather than a genre and
you get a sense of its breadth and diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Anime also is Japan's MTV, the one entertainment product it can
export seemingly everywhere. In the United States, where anime
videos began trickling onto the market 10 years ago, the genre is
finally starting to go mainstream:
</P>
<P>
   - Cable's Cartoon Network airs a ``Toonami'' anime block weekday
afternoons from 3 to 5, leading off with the half-hour series
``Sailor Moon,'' about a talking cat who turns a group of young
girls into high-kicking warriors for justice. Since last year
``Toonami'' has helped double Cartoon Network's afternoon audience
of 9-to-14-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   - Disney's Miramax Films last month had the premiere of the
English-language version of ``Princess Mononoke,'' the
highest-grossing domestic film in Japanese history. Although it
tells a complicated story set in the Middle Ages, ``Princess
Mononoke'' captivated audiences with its lush scenery and its
unusually graceful motion, the result of 80,000 animation cels
drawn by its venerated creator, Hayao Miyazaki.
</P>
<P>
   - Other anime releases are making their way to theaters for
limited runs. The top distributor of anime in the United States,
Chicago-based Manga Entertainment, is showing ``Perfect Blue,'' a
thriller it expects to be as big as ``Ghost in the Shell,'' in more
than a dozen cities nationwide. (``Perfect Blue'' should arrive in
Kansas City this spring, according to Jerry Harrington, owner of
Tivoli Manor Square Theatre.)
</P>
<P>
   - Hundreds of anime clubs have sprung up in cities and on
university campuses across the United States, where members screen
new releases and swap videocassettes of old favorites. An anime
sales house, Right Stuf of Des Moines, Iowa, has a mailing list of
200,000.
</P>
<P>
   After `Astro Boy'
</P>
<P>
   All of which suggests that anime has come a long way from
``Astro Boy,'' the black-and-white Japanese import that was a
staple of Saturday mornings on American TV in the 1960s. ``Astro
Boy,'' created in 1952 by Osamu Tezuka, the father of anime, was a
crime-fighting machine _ literally. The story went that Astro Boy's
``father'' had built him to serve humanity after the man's own son
had died.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Astro Boy'' and other early cartoons, Tezuka borrowed
from the style of Walt Disney's characters, with their doe eyes and
pencil-line lips. Anime characters have never looked especially
Japanese, but their appearance is distinct to that country's
animation style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still get asked: Why does their hair stand straight up? Why
do they all have such big eyes? Why do they all look like Speed
Racer?'' says Steve Pearl, who chairs the Anime Alliance, a network
of anime clubs in the New York City area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call them `the stupid questions.' The kids who are into
`Pokemon' _ they just accept it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anime's beginnings are found in the economic ashes of postwar
Japan. With little money to support a movie industry, the nation's
creative community instead began producing ``manga,''
cheap-to-print black-and-white comic books. A voracious public ate
them up, and by the 1960s the most popular manga were being turned
into movies. Today half of all movie tickets sold in Japan are for
anime features.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when videos began crossing over to the United States,
something was lost in the translation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when we would screen anime five, 10 years ago, we'd
hear that it looked different, that it was strange,'' recalls Mike
Lazzo, senior vice president for programming at cable's Cartoon
Network.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem was bad dubbing and animation that paled
next to the American product. But anime's soap-opera-like
continuity was also to blame. TV executives would hear complaints
from parents because ``Speed Racer'' _ another well-known '60s
import _ would leave stories hanging at the end of an episode.
American cartoons told a story (and sometimes two) in a tidy half
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Many anime serials are more complex than their American
counterparts, but that may not be the problem TV executives thought
it was. ``Pokemon,'' with more than 150 distinct characters, has
certainly caught on. Still, the ``Sailor Moon'' repeats seen in the
United States feature just five heroines, compared with 11 in the
Japanese version.
</P>
<P>
   Magical girls
</P>
<P>
   ``Sailor Moon'' is typical of the ``magical girls'' genre, as
it's known to anime aficionados. To a female viewer of a certain
age, the magical girls have endless appeal, as was evidenced this
summer at the Comic-Con in San Diego, the world's largest cartoon
and fantasy convention.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of preteen girls had coaxed their parents to bring them
down to the convention center and stand in line to see a
feature-length ``Sailor Moon'' film, a well-traveled 1993
production known on Web sites around the world as simply the ``S
Movie.''
</P>
<P>
   The lead character in ``Sailor Moon'' is an irrepressible
14-year-old Kewpie doll whose path is crossed one day by a
mysterious black cat named Luna. (Why is she blond? ``It
differentiates her character,'' says Pearl.) The cat presents the
girl with a brooch that turns her into a leggy tyro in a miniskirt.
</P>
<P>
   Sailor Moon and her comrades (each named for a planet) eschew
traditional male weaponry, instead sending thunderous kinetic bolts
at their enemies. As the supergirls invoke their respective cosmic
forces, the girls in the audience scream their delight:
</P>
<P>
   ``Moon prism power, make up!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mercury star power, make up!''
</P>
<P>
   (Interestingly, the biggest cheers at this screening were for
the six heroines not seen in the American ``Sailor Moon.'')
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, around the vast Comic-Con exhibit hall, anime was the
hottest thing going, with aisles of vendors selling videos,
paraphernalia, limited-edition cel art and other mementos covering
the whole range of anime. Hundreds of adoring kids showed up for
``Pokemon'' panels. Exhibitors ran out of prizes to give to people
who signed up for their anime clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to account for anime's grass-roots ascent, Cartoon
Network's Lazzo cites the recent success of professional wrestling.
Young boys now stay tuned for weeks to follow a storyline involving
their favorite wrestler. So why not a cartoon character?
</P>
<P>
   Lazzo adds: ``Another thing that complicates anime is that
sometimes a character will be good one week and bad the next week.
But that's something wrestlers do, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Anime and professional wrestling also share a fascination with
buxom, scantily clad women _ big, blond timbers who aren't exactly
native to Japan _ and with violence. Unlike wrestling, some of the
best adult anime are meditations on the senseless and tribalistic
rite of killing, whether the primeval warfare between the forest
gods and humans in ``Princess Mononoke'' or the high-tech terrorism
of ``Ghost in the Shell.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet there's something intrinsically disturbing about the world's
finest animators applying their craft to ever-more exquisite ways
of depicting human bloodshed. Fangoria, a magazine specializing in
horror movies, recently ran stills from the critically acclaimed
``Perfect Blue,'' a movie about a pop star who is stalked by a
murderous fan. One of the images shows a homicide in a blood-rained
elevator, the victim's face so bloody as to make gender
identification impossible. Pornographic would not be too strong a
way to describe it.
</P>
<P>
   It would seem that if there's one thing American mass culture
doesn't need more of, it's gratuitous bloodshed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 1541EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4270 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-MILLENIUM-$AD     12-09 1720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-MILLENIUM-$ADV11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AFTER MUCH CONTROVERSY, BRITS LOOKING FORWARD TO MILLENNIUM
CELEBRATION
 &HT;    (1200&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    EDs: With box information attached to end of story.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Dec. 11 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It's 11:59 p.m. on New Year's Eve. Spotlights
illuminate the four faces of Big Ben. Pulsating at one beat a
second, the spotlights count down the end of 1999. Finally, the
clock strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Several barges unleash 200-foot flares, which sweep down the
Thames, creating what appears to be a long river of fire.
</P>
<P>
   Seconds of pitch-dark calm are then followed by a 15-minute
fireworks display, one of the largest in the city's history.
</P>
<P>
   Oohs and aahs erupt from the crowds. More than 2 million people
go home, duly awed and amazed.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it could be the ``greatest show on earth.'' At least
that's what promoters are hoping. Whether they can pull it off _
after conflicts over everything from the celebration's religious
theme to financing by an American fast-food chain _ remains to be
seen.
</P>
<P>
   But come Dec. 31, just as Rio de Janeiro will have its
beachfront concerts and Edinburgh will have its thousand pipers _
one for every year of the millennium _ Britain will celebrate the
arrival of the millennium with the opening of the $1.2 billion
riverside cupola known as the Millennium Dome.
</P>
<P>
   At twice the size of Atlanta's massive Georgia Dome, the
Millennium Dome is designed to accommodate 35,000 people at a time
and will offer all sorts of highly publicized events beginning Jan.
1.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, London is planning its own New Year's celebration
dubbed Big Time. It will include a ``global village'' along the
banks of the Thames, with street fairs for both adults and children
that highlight the city's diversity.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a 450-foot Ferris wheel on the Thames will
open Jan. 1, offering 25-mile views from 32 enclosed capsules.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair has said it is logical that Britain _
which he proclaimed the ``home of time'' _ should host Europe's
largest millennium commemoration.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it's Greenwich, southeast of London, that's home to
the prime meridian which gave the name to Greenwich Mean Time.
</P>
<P>
   This storied city's plans to ring in the new century has had its
share of skeptics, however.
</P>
<P>
   And nothing has embodied that skepticism more than the
Millennium Dome, designed to showcase Britain in the coming century
and dogged by controversy since its inception five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help that such a huge number of architectural teams _
at least 15 _ were brought in to design the dome, making it
difficult to agree on any one plan.
</P>
<P>
   Crippling delays occurred. Worried sponsors pulled out. On at
least five occasions, plans for the dome were nearly ditched.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, press reports were often scathing.
</P>
<P>
   One, in 1998, said that dome organizers had persuaded media
magnate Rupert Murdoch's satellite television firm to divert $20
million of company money earmarked for investment in Britain's
schools into sponsorship of a carnival ride at the Greenwich site.
</P>
<P>
   Another said that McDonald's had announced its own investment of
$20 million in the project, sparking a national debate as to
whether the dome would really represent the ``Best of Britain'' as
promoters had previously claimed.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't long before The Evening Standard proclaimed it ``the
millennium fiasco.'' The Sun urged Britain to ``dump the dome.''
</P>
<P>
   Promoters boasted that no taxpayer money was being used to build
the dome. The project has been financed with the proceeds of the
national lottery, as well as through private sponsorships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to make everyone happy all the time,''
said Fiona Cline, a spokeswoman for the New Millennium Experience
Co., which is running the dome.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, The Faith Zone, one of the dome's 14 themed
pavilions, was renamed because its title was considered ``too
Christian'' and risked offending other religions.
</P>
<P>
   It will now be known as ``Faith Zone,'' with the definite
article removed, because ``the'' was thought to favor one faith,
Christianity, over others.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Frayling, who oversees the content of the zone, said
it's a very sensitive issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to offend anyone, but how can you make sure
absolutely everyone in the world is included in a project such as
this one?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, controversy has surrounded the role of Christianity in
the government's millennium celebration from the very beginning.
The name of the Faith Zone, for example, had already been changed
early this year from ``Spirit Zone'' after religious groups groused
that it sounded too vague.
</P>
<P>
   Then, under pressure from church leaders to acknowledge the
religious significance of the millennium, the dome organizers
agreed to allocate a sound-proofed room for prayer and meditation
for people of all beliefs. Organizers also agreed to allow the
Archbishop of Canterbury, George Carey, to lead the nation in the
Lord's Prayer in the run up to the dome's official opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have tried to turn the millennium into a secular event,
but we're not going to let that happen,'' said Colin Hart, the
director of the Christian Institute, which supports traditional
family values. ``People have tried to water down every element of
Christianity that can be found in the dome.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite such quibbling, much of the criticism and skepticism
surrounding the dome has now been replaced by anticipation, just
weeks before the dome's gala inauguration by Queen Elizabeth.
</P>
<P>
   The mood began turning around last September, when dome
organizers were able to sell all 2,000 tickets for opening day
within hours, confounding critics who said no one would ever visit
the structure. It wasn't long before the dome was saturated with
corporate logos representing many of Britain's most-important
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Now promoters predict that some 12 million people will visit the
dome during the year 2000, even though the price of an all-day,
adult ticket is a hefty US$32.50.
</P>
<P>
   And they've given the public a clearer idea of what visitors
will find under the dome's 20-acre roof.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will play virtual reality games allowing them to
explore everything from a woman's womb to the earth's atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Faith, the names of other themed pavilions at the
dome will include Play, Money, and Self-Portrait.
</P>
<P>
   In the Body Zone, for example, visitors will explore a
12-foot-high heart, complete with lots of blood and pumping veins.
Promoters claim the exhibit's so realistic that it's not being
recommended for young children. Another room within the Body Zone
explores the nature of beauty, and will allow visitors to adjust
the faces of celebrities using interactive video terminals.
</P>
<P>
   The dome will also house 16 bars, the two biggest cinema screens
in Britain, and Europe's largest McDonald's restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   So these days, much to the cynics' surprise, it appears the dome
could become a lasting, popular tribute to the millennium, as the
government originally intended.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like London will be the center of the world on New
Year's Eve, and I'm very excited about ... the dome,'' said Allison
Humphry, who plans to visit the dome in early January. ``I wouldn't
miss seeing such an important monument.''
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM BOX:
</P>
<P>
   London plans massive celebrations to ring in the new millennium.
And cities across the United Kingdom, including Liverpool,
Manchester and Nottingham, are hosting a variety of concerts, light
shows, and fireworks displays. Here are just a few of the events
planned in London to mark the new year:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The banks of the Thames will be transformed into a giant
``street party,'' with an Elizabethan fair and a huge carnival for
children complete with carousels and other rides. The action starts
at about 11 a.m. on New Year's Eve, leading up to a massive
fireworks display at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The London Eye, a new 450-foot Ferris wheel on the Thames that
promises 25-mile views over the city from 32 enclosed capsules,
takes its first passengers on New Year's Eve, but then closes again
until mid-January so that a ticket office can be built. The ride
will cost US$12 per adult and US$7.50 per child.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Millennium Dome, which includes 14 themed pavilions with
titles like Journey, Faith, and Body, will open Jan. 1. Tickets are
sold out for Jan. 1, but there are some tickets still available the
first week of January. An adult ticket sells for US$32.50. Call
(44-870) 606-2000 to buy tickets and for more information.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Another popular spot will be the Royal Observatory in
Greenwich, just southeast of London, home of the Prime Meridian,
which marks Greenwich Mean Time _ or ground zero of world time. The
observatory can be found in Greenwich Royal Park near the Maze Hill
rail station. It is closed Dec. 31 and Jan. 1. Call (44-181)
858-4422 for more information.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Near the observatory, at the Queen's House, is a millennium
exhibit called ``The Story of Time.'' The exhibit, which runs
through Sept. 24, attempts to explain the meaning of time using an
array of props, everything from the art of Salvador Dali to the
earliest known dated watch. Call (44-181) 312-6565 for more
information.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  St. Martin-in-the-Fields at Trafalgar Square is hosting a
Millennium Day Extravaganza concert at 7:30 p.m. on Jan. 1
featuring the works of Bach, Mozart, and Vivaldi. Tickets go for
US$13 to US$35. Call (44-171) 839-8362 for more information.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Harrod's, London's most famous department store _ visited by
30,000 customers a day _ is spruced up for the holidays, and is
selling everything from millennium coffees to millennium diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hampton Court Palace, southwest of London and one of England's
finest royal abodes, hosts holiday activities from Dec. 27 through
Jan. 3 (closed Jan. 1). They include music, dancing, and cooking in
Tudor kitchens. An adult ticket sells for US$15. Call (44-181)
781-9540 for more information.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For more information on all London millennium events, check
out the following Internet Web sites: www.greenwich2000.co.uk and
www.millennium.gov.uk
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 1547EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
