<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-NORMAL-$ADV12-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T BLAME LIFE'S NORMAL GLITCHES ON Y2K PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Dec. 12) (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If your bank's ATM machine isn't working New Year's
Day, don't assume the high-tech cash machine has been hit by the
Y2K computer jinx.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, recall this aggravating statistic: Up to 3,000 of the
227,000 ATMs in the United States are broken at any given time
under normal circumstances, according to the American Bankers
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The machines go down when they run out of money or are being
serviced by bank personnel or suffer routine computer problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Y2k bug may cause computers to misinterpret the digits
``00'' as 1900, throwing a wicked curve ball at computer systems
that rely on dates. The threat to such computer-based sectors of
American society as electrical power, the air traffic control
system and financial institutions has led to intense efforts by
businesses and governments to cure this problem before the calendar
turns at midnight on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   This may explain why some in the Y2K computer business are just
a bit defensive when they point out that any glitches in the New
Year might not be linked to Y2K but, instead, just part of life's
normal hassles.
</P>
<P>
   Take the electric power-grid for example. It's a near certainty
that at least several hundred people will be with electricity on
Jan. 1. For example, Northern States Power _ an upper Midwest
electricity supplier _ reports that an average of 75 customers lose
power every day among its 1.4 million customers.
</P>
<P>
   This can happen for a variety of reasons like a tree branch
falling on a power line or a vehicle crashing into, and damaging,
an electric utility pole.
</P>
<P>
   ``The failures may not be Y2K related at all,'' said John
Koskinen, the federal government's Y2K czar. ``As we all know,
things don't work everyday.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he'll be the one on the political hotseat over New
Years' weekend, dealing with complaints about any Y2K-related
problems, Koskinen is trying to find out what usually doesn't work
so he will be able to decide whether any problems are worse than
normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to know what the normal background noise is on a
normal weekend,'' he said recently.
</P>
<P>
   Some late 20th century technology isn't vulnerable to a
Y2K-failure. For example, machines like cars and vending machines
do not contain computer chips that are date dependent. The same is
true for microwaves, refrigerators, ovens, coffeemakers and washers
and dryers.
</P>
<P>
   If any of these home appliances fail on Jan. 1, it's just
coincidence and has nothing to do with the date on the calendar.
</P>
<P>
   But it gets tricky when it comes to things like ATM machines,
the air traffic control system and the electric-power grid that are
run by computers with date-dependent chips.
</P>
<P>
   These sectors have upgraded and tested their computers and
expect few, if any, Y2K glitches.
</P>
<P>
   So, if you're on an airliner on Jan. 1 and your flight is
delayed, just remember that up to 500 flights are delayed on a
daily basis, according to the Federal Aviation Administration. The
FAA points out that with more than 55,000 daily landings and
takeoffs, delays amount to less than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Potentially thousands of planes could be delayed on New Years'
weekend if a winter snow or ice storm hits and a similar amount of
people could lose their electricity.
</P>
<P>
   So along with monitoring potential Y2K glitches, Koskinen will
likely keep an eye on the skies to see if any of the blame can be
placed on Mother Nature.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
the e-mail address jennifer &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
