<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4280 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     12-09 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING LIST: THESE BUSINESS BOOKS WERE THE BEST OF 1999
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Happy holidays! If you are a frenzied shopper looking for ideas,
here is my list of the best business books I read in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   For a great management book, take a look at ``First, Break All
The Rules: What the World's Greatest Managers Do Differently''
(Simon &AMP; Schuster, 271 pages, $25).
</P>
<P>
   The authors, Marcus Buckingham and Curt Coffman are employed by
the well-known pollsters, the Gallup Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The heart and soul of this book is based on two sizable Gallup
studies conducted over 25 years. The first asked 1 million
employees what they wanted most out of their company; the second
asked 80,000 managers, identified as talented by performance
measures within their companies, how they manage. Both questions
sought to pinpoint gray areas that hundreds of management books
have attempted to define.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line: ``We had discovered that the manager _ not pay,
benefits, perks or a charismatic corporate leader _ was the
critical player in building a strong workplace,'' they write. ``The
manager was the key. ... People leave managers, not companies.''
</P>
<P>
   If you don't know about zentrepreneurism, beehiving or the
massive immigration of the 1980s, then you better get ``The Future
Ain't What It Used to Be: The 40 Cultural Trends Transforming Your
Job, Your Life, Your World'' (Burkley Publishing Group, 270 pages,
$14.95).
</P>
<P>
   It's written by a group of Minneapolis marketers called
Iconoculture. Their focus is popular culture _ specifically,
American _ and their methodology involves cross-country travel by
car, travel on the Web, reading everything in sight and
``relentless'' TV channel surfing.
</P>
<P>
   After absorbing this material, the group, which consists of Mary
Meehan, Larry Samuel and Vickie Abrahamson, get together to ``make
sense out of the cultural chaos, make key connections, and discuss
the implications for individuals and marketers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These forty cultural trends are literal signs of the times,
guideposts that point the way for you to proactively manage your
future,'' Iconoculture writes. ``Think of signs as territories to
stake with your career, business or brand.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the work force is made up of a mix of generations. How
best to manage that mix is discussed in ``Generations At Work:
Managing the Clash of Veterans, Boomers, Xers, and Nexters in Your
Workplace'' (AMACOM, 280 pages, $) by workplace consultants Ron
Zemke, Claire Rains and Bob Filipczak.
</P>
<P>
   ``At no previous time in our history have so many and such
different generations with such diversity been asked to work
together shoulder to shoulder, side by side, cubicle to cubicle,''
they write.
</P>
<P>
   Given the distinct upbringing and value system of each
generation, this meeting of minds is causing yet another area of
conflict in the workplace, but also the chance to bring even
greater creativity, they contend.
</P>
<P>
   Is Scrooge alive in a Santa suit? Many Americans are overworked,
caught up in a corporate mentality of parties, retreats and other
so-called benefits that encourage longer days at the office.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Arnott, a Dallas Baptist University management professor
and lecturer, sees it pushing us off the edge _ if we aren't
careful. He voices his views in his book, ``Corporate Cults: The
Insidious Lure of the All-Consumer Organization'' (AMACOM, 240
pages, $23.95).
</P>
<P>
   ``Every organization has some degree of cultedness. People join
organizations to accomplish things that they cannot do on their
own, so individuals subordinate themselves to some extent,'' he
writes. ``However, in corporate cults, the organization has become
work, family, and community for the employee.''
</P>
<P>
   Many corporations are pushing their culture to the extreme,
seeing productivity rise with every after-hours party or employee
retreat, Arnott writes.
</P>
<P>
   In an interesting twist, Arnott believes that the companies most
applauded for treating employees well may be the ones hurting their
individual employees' balanced lives the most.
</P>
<P>
   This book will show you how to evaluate your organization and
what to do about signs of danger to your psyche.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, we'll look at some of the best books the economists
put forth in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Professional's Guide to Fitness''
</P>
<P>
   By Lawrence D. Schartz
</P>
<P>
   Taylor Publishing, $12.95
</P>
<P>
   Energy is the one thing nearly everybody would like more of, and
Dallas personal trainer and nutritional adviser Lawrence D. Schartz
has a plan to give it to the pencil-pushers. He encourages readers
to think of the book as a personal coach and tailors much of it to
a professional's busy lifestyle. Schartz says he travels 200 days a
year and still remains in great shape. His guide covers exercise,
nutrition and habits in an inspiring format.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Power of Positive Criticism''
</P>
<P>
   By Hendrie Weisinger
</P>
<P>
   Amacom, $15
</P>
<P>
   Everyone's a critic, especially at work, and although we like to
point out problems in other's presentations, reports or solutions,
few of us like to hear about our shortcomings. Hendrie Weisinger
has spent more than 20 years studying criticism and offers numerous
insights into how to do it effectively without destroying egos. His
tips are helpful for those giving and those taking criticism.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Escape From Voice Mail Hell''
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Lebon
</P>
<P>
   Parleau Publishing, $17.95
</P>
<P>
   In 70 pages, Dallas author and productivity consultant Paul
Lebon shows how voice mail can be your friend, not your enemy.
Although e-commerce may be the future, Lebon says that
``v-commerce,'' or voice commerce, is still a major part of our
infrastructure. Lebon offers Ten Commandments on how to reach voice
mail subscribers effectively.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
