<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIGOLO-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DEUCE BIGALOW, MALE GIGOLO': FISH-TANK CLEANER IN NEW LINE OF
WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes appear at the end of the review.) 
(jt) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Little sex and less humor await audiences for ``Deuce Bigalow:
Male Gigolo,'' whose juvenile comedy targets a gallery of imperfect
women. These include an obese black, a narcoleptic, a victim of
Tourette's syndrome and a giant with a runaway pituitary gland.
</P>
<P>
   The list also includes a woman with an artificial leg, her
sightless roommate and a clerk in a pet fish store who can be
induced to unwittingly wet her T-shirt while scooping snails from a
tank.
</P>
<P>
   Among the males are a stereotypical black pimp and a cuckolded
police detective given to exposing himself while he rails about the
imperfection of his sex organ.
</P>
<P>
   And given that the protagonist of this film is a fish-tank
cleaner and rescuer of goldfish from toilets, the term bathroom
humor is appropriate, especially since his father is a men's room
attendant.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with ``Deuce Bigalow: Male Gigolo,'' whose title
seems intended to evoke memories of ``Ace Ventura, Pet Detective,''
is not its low humor. Low humor has a proud history. The problem
with ``Deuce Bigalow: Male Gigolo,'' directed by Mike Mitchell from
a screenplay by Harris Goldberg and Rob Schneider, is the low level
of its low humor.
</P>
<P>
   The high concept behind this tiny achievement is that Deuce,
played by Schneider, is asked to house-sit for Antoine Laconte
(Oded Fehr), a gigolo who must leave the country on high-priced
business while a valuable fish in his expensive aquarium in his
lavish home is ill.
</P>
<P>
   Leconte gives Deuce two pieces of advice: don't answer the phone
and don't drive the Porsche. Not much time passes before Deuce
violates the rules, because he has managed to destroy the fish tank
and set fire to the premises.
</P>
<P>
   So Deuce decides to try life as a gigolo to earn money to
restore the damage to Leconte's home. And soon he has attracted a
hungry, sloppy, fast-talking pimp, T.J. Hicks (Eddie Griffin), and
the attentions of the angry detective, Chuck Fowler (William
Forsythe), who wants to build a case against Leconte. T.J. also has
some advice for Deuce: don't fall in love with a client.
</P>
<P>
   As Deuce works his way through an assortment of women, learning
that compassion, not sex, is what many need, he eventually meets
the innocent Kate (Arija Bareikis), whose friends have arranged for
his services. And true love begins to run its troubled course.
</P>
<P>
   Among devotees of comedy, ``Deuce Bigalow'' is for the
undemanding.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Deuce Bigalow: Male Gigolo'' is rated R (under 17
requires accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes
simulated sex, foreplay, partial nudity, sexual innuendo, harsh
language and violence.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `DEUCE BIGALOW'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Mike Mitchell; written by Harris Goldberg and Rob
Schneider; director of photography, Peter Lyons Collister; edited
by George Bowers and Lawrence Jordan; music by Teddy Castellucci;
production designer, Alan Au; produced by Sid Ganis and Barry
Bernardi; released by Touchstone Pictures. Running time: 84
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Rob Schneider (Deuce Bigalow), William Forsythe (Detective
Chuck Fowler), Eddie Griffin (T.J. Hicks), Arija Bareikis (Kate)
and Oded Fehr (Antoine Laconte).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
