<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4292 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DICKEY-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     12-09 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DICKEY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CRUX': THE PROSAIC CORRESPONDENCE OF JAMES DICKEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Publication notes appear at the end of the review.) 
(js) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In one of the acerbic letters in this collection, James Dickey
compares New York poets to ``crabs in a bucket: scrambling over
each other, pulling each other down, backbiting, calling each other
names, faulting each other's politics and so on.'' It has ``nothing
whatever,'' he complains, ``to do with poetry.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the reader of ``Crux,'' Dickey is as guilty in
these pages of backbiting, score settling and disingenuous flattery
as the Yankee poets he knocks. Although there are a handful of
passages in this volume that help illuminate Dickey's own work and
attest to his love of books, a distressingly large portion is
devoted to poetic politics: to snide put-downs of other poets,
insider talk about prizes and fellowships, and catty remarks about
rival cliques and claques.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief introduction Matthew J. Bruccoli writes that the
rationale behind the selection of letters was ``to document the
growth of a major writer'' and ``the ways he fulfilled his genius
and advanced his career.'' ``The decision to focus on the
development of Jim's career obviated the life-in-letters
biographical approach,'' he adds. ``These letters do not provide a
systematic biography of James Dickey in his own words. His conduct
as husband and father is only indirectly revealed.''
</P>
<P>
   This is an understatement to say the least. The attenuated
footnotes provided by Bruccoli and Judith S. Baughman not only
appear, awkwardly, at the book's end, where they are not easily
accessible, but they are also perfunctory in the extreme. Dickey's
well-known penchant for telling tall tales is checked only by fuzzy
and unhelpful notations like ``JD often exaggerated his military
record.''
</P>
<P>
   The editors do nothing to illuminate Dickey's ongoing
differences with the poets Robert Bly and Allen Ginsberg, and they
provide little or no context for many of Dickey's more startling
and cryptic statements. Like: ``The main thing that we're faced
with now is my wife's legal situation. If I were to tell you the
full consequences of what is embroiled in her case with various
allegations in different states, it would take a Clarence Darrow to
figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   In the earlier portions of this book, devoted to Dickey's stint
in the Army Air Corps, his service in World War II, his postwar
education at Vanderbilt University and his stumbling efforts to
become a poet while moonlighting as an ad man, the reader is at
least treated to the drama of a young man discovering his vocation
as a writer: his voracious consumption of books, his eager
apprenticeship and his developing sense of philosophy and craft.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time,'' he writes to the poet James Merrill, ``I
have been trying to do two things in poetry, both of which I have
been told one should not do. The first is to get away, by whatever
means, from the idea of a poem as objet d'art, which is a notion I
have always hated, however much it has been drilled into me. The
other is to be able to make statements, one after the other: this
happens, this happens, then this happens. To go with all this, I
have also been trying to assert connections in nature where none
exists: to make the world do what I say, rather than what it
actually does.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickey grew up, he claims, ``in a family in which there was
simply no interest other than in sports,'' and he ``had no more
`talent' for writing poetry, in the beginning, than did Joe
Louis.'' The encouragement he received from the poet and teacher
Andrew Lytle, he writes, made him feel ``like a man who has been
sitting for some time, numbly'' in a cold place, and who then looks
up to see ``that someone has put a table in front of him, and a jug
of milk on that, and bread.'' In later years, when he had long been
a poet and teacher himself, Dickey would often choose to emphasize
his early life as a jock and underscore, like Hemingway, his love
of hunting and the outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   As these letters make clear, however, Dickey was thoroughly a
creature, a self-promoting creature, of the literary world. The
bulk of letters in this volume show him shamelessly cultivating
prospective supporters and dissing gifted rivals. In many instances
he writes savage put-downs of a poet or critic to one
correspondent, then flatters that same poet or critic in a fan
letter.
</P>
<P>
   He denounces Edmund Wilson as ``a tiresome kind of old literary
hack,'' then writes Wilson a letter praising his work. He refers to
John Hollander as ``a literary pimp and time-server,'' then writes
Hollander that ``history is going to have it your way, rather than
the way of the nit-pickers who balk at your poems.'' He assails
Anne Sexton's poems for their ``clever, supercilious'' language and
``parading of mental illness,'' then tells her that she has
``touched a new tenderness in me.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill is dismissed as ``that chocolate-frosting of a poet,''
W.S. Merwin as ``a prettified interior decorator with no subject''
and James Wright as that ``withdrawn, intellectual, ego-guarding,
semi-precious type that one normally associates with the term
`American poet.''' As for Robert Lowell, Dickey acknowledges that
he ``is good,'' but snidely adds that ``his world is so
over-violent it often seems either comical or as though the
violence were just being manufactured, and used here, there, and
everywhere'' _ a curious complaint, given the frequent eruptions of
violence in Dickey's own poems and novels like ``Deliverance.''
</P>
<P>
   So what poets does Dickey like? He has a few good things to say
for Dylan Thomas (``He is very nearly a great lyric poet''),
Theodore Roethke (``He deals with eternal objects and eternal
feeling, and does not throw the sop of temporality or
headline-mongering at the audience'') and Archibald MacLeish (``He
is one of the few American poets to have a sound of his own'').
</P>
<P>
   Of course the poet Dickey likes the best is himself. He ranks
himself as one of the 10 best, along with the likes of Auden and
Pound, and he compares Esquire magazine's rejection of one of his
poems to a rejection of T.S. Eliot's ``The Waste Land.'' ``Humility
is not my forte,'' Dickey writes in one of the more honest passages
in this volume. ``I much more easily run to arrogance and
insolence.''
</P>
<P>
   The reader can only wonder why the editors of this volume would
want to ratify that observation at tiresome length with their
numbing, poorly annotated and repetitious selection of letters,
letters that cast a dark and noxious shadow over the very real
accomplishments of Dickey's career.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CRUX: THE LETTERS OF JAMES DICKEY'
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Matthew J. Bruccoli and Judith S. Baughman
</P>
<P>
   574 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $35.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 1617EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4294 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-TEMPLETON-SUCCESS-NYT     12-09 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEMPLETON-SUCCESS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLDWIDE LAWS OF LIFE:
 SUCCESSFUL PEOPLE START PRACTICING WHEN THEY ARE YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Sir John Templeton, the Tennessee-born billionaire and founder
of the Templeton funds, built his fortune on his legendary ability
to perceive value that others overlooked. In his column, he urges
us to recognize the value of spirituality in life.)
</P>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   (``Success feeds on itself and creates more success.'' --John M.
Templeton)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN M. TEMPLETON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. Templeton Foundation Press &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by N.Y. Times Special Features &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, as we start out in adult life, we may not feel like
much of a success. Our society frequently defines success as the
material goods and lifestyle secured by large amounts of money
earned over a long period of time. We tend to think success is
something that occurs only later in life.
</P>
<P>
   However, this belief may impede us from achieving success even
then. Success takes practice, and successful people start
practicing when they are young!
</P>
<P>
   Think about it for a moment. A musician must practice diligently
to become a virtuoso. A medical doctor studies for many years and
interns for an additional period of time prior to beginning a
viable practice. An athlete trains long hours before becoming a
star.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, it takes practice to experience success in life. If
you want to feel like a success, it is important for you to begin
to acknowledge your successes right now.
</P>
<P>
   Many times the things at which we're naturally gifted are the
hardest for us to claim as a success. We may make statements like,
``If I can do it so easily, why can't everyone else? If I can do
it, it can't be that hard!''
</P>
<P>
   It's important to listen to the acknowledgment we receive from
parents, teachers, employers and friends. Don't brush it off as if
they're just being nice. They may be telling you, ``You are a
success right now!''
</P>
<P>
   Answer with a sincere ``Thank you.'' There is no need to say
anything else. Making disparaging remarks about yourself or your
performance can be false modesty and negates the compliment that
was given to you.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, when a compliment is delivered with some
criticism, you may be tempted to give up. You may feel that since
nothing you do is good enough, why bother to try. Don't give in to
those feelings. Many people, especially your family, may have a
difficult time making it clear that they appreciate your talent and
are supportively behind you. Although they may want you to develop
your skill to the best of your ability, it might be difficult for
them to express this feeling in words.
</P>
<P>
   And if they take time to point out your mistakes, they may be
really saying, ``I know you can do better that this. I care and I
want to help you.''
</P>
<P>
   We are often our own harshest critics, and we have a tendency to
hear only criticism from others and not their praise. It is
important to practice hearing both compliments and constructive
remarks from those who have good advice to offer. As you begin to
recognize and build on the success you're experiencing now, you may
discover that this is a feeling you can create again and again in
various aspects of your living.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever anyone says to you, ``Good work!'' think to yourself,
``Yes, it is good work. I am successful with this.'' A swelled head
is never helpful, of course, but to acknowledge your gifts is not
necessarily self-indulgent, especially if you recognize you
couldn't have achieved success without the support and guidance of
others--like parents, teachers, friends, and co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   If they comment, ``Okay, but you might do better,'' realize you
may have more to give, and receive this advice with an open mind
and heart. Determine to do your best. You are the one who will
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   A story is told about a little boy who called at a house selling
picture postcards for a quarter each. The man who answered his
knock asked the lad what he was going to do with the money he
earned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' he said, ``I'm raising $100,000 for our new church
building.''
</P>
<P>
   The startled customer responded, ``Do you expect to raise it all
by yourself?'' The young man answered with a straight and serious
face, ``Oh, no, sir. There's another little boy helping me!'' This
young man had the spirit of success at an early age!
</P>
<P>
   Knowing right now--feeling inside right now--that you're
successful, whether you're a singer in the church choir, a waitress
in a restaurant, the coach of the softball team, or the budding
mechanic spending every spare moment in the garage rebuilding the
engine of that antique car, can prepare you for greater and greater
success.
</P>
<P>
   Success is not a one-time event. It can be an accumulated series
of wins and other experiences that create a successful life.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Excerpted from ``Worldwide Laws of Life'' by John Marks
Templeton. Published by Templeton Foundation Press)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
