<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4296 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DIAMONDS-FILM-REVIEW-     12-09 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIAMONDS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DIAMONDS': KIRK DOUGLAS PLAYS A GUY WHO LOOKS A LOT LIKE HIM 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes appear at the end of the review.) 
(af) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leading with his famous chin, Kirk Douglas (who turned 83
Thursday), gleefully devours the scenery in ``Diamonds,'' a
simmered-in-schmaltz comedy about a grumpy older man determined not
to go gentle into that good night.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas' character, Harry Agensky, a former welterweight boxing
champion once known as the Polish Prince, is really a pugilistic
stand-in for the star, who is shown slugging it out in the ring in
clips from his 1949 movie ``The Champion.''
</P>
<P>
   When we first meet Harry, who is recovering from a stroke that
has left his speech impaired, he is vigorously practicing mouth
exercises to an instructional video in the Canadian home of Moses
(Kurt Fuller), his favorite of his two grown sons.
</P>
<P>
   By turns feisty, weepy and crazily reckless, Harry clings so
tenaciously to his own boxing legend that on occasion he still
likes to pick fights. And when he puts up his dukes, the years melt
away and he exhibits the stamina of a man 30 years younger.
</P>
<P>
   But such moments are fleeting, and a minute later Harry is just
as likely to crumple into a helpless weeping puddle of
disappointment and confusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diamonds,'' directed by John Asher from a screenplay by Allan
Aaron Katz, is a made-to-order star vehicle that gives Douglas
unlimited rein to flex his acting muscles. And as this bulldog of
an actor struts and pumps and mugs his way through the film he
dominates, you have to admire him for not taking things way over
the top.
</P>
<P>
   The star's courageous performance is the main attraction of a
movie that shamelessly pours on the sentiment (Harry's favorite
song, ``Are You Lonesome Tonight?,'' is played at least two times
too many) while relating a rickety, far-fetched yarn.
</P>
<P>
   For all Harry's spurts of vigor, he has become a burden to his
family, which is gently nudging him toward a nursing home. But
Harry thinks he has the solution. For decades he has claimed that
he was once given 13 priceless diamonds by a mobster named Duff the
Muff for agreeing to throw a fight.
</P>
<P>
   All these years, he insists, the jewels have been hidden in the
mobster's Nevada home. The time has come to retrieve them. But do
they really exist? Only Harry's 15-year-old grandson, Michael
(Corbin Allred), believes his story.
</P>
<P>
   The movie follows Harry; his less-favored, recently divorced
son, Lance (Dan Aykroyd); and Michael, Lance's son, on a wild and
wacky car trip from the Pacific Northwest to Reno to recover the
jewels.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way the travelers suffer predictable mishaps. Harry
insists on taking the wheel and nearly kills them. At the Canadian
border the old man creates such a fuss that the travelers are
ordered out of their vehicle and frisked.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Diamonds'' mechanically reels off standard variations on
the my-father-never-told-me-he-loved-me theme (a theme that has
sunk better movies than this one), the schmaltz comes to a boil.
The parallels between Harry's distance from Lance (a pudgy
fussbudget sportswriter who was never a jock like his father) and
Lance's sniping at his own mildly rebellious teen-age son (he
sneaks cigarettes) are just too pat for words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diamonds,'' which opens Friday in New York City, finally goes
haywire when it takes the three to a brothel where the girls all
have hearts of gold and endless ingenuity and insight. Here Lance
rediscovers the joys of sex, and Michael has his initiation from a
bombshell (Jenny McCarthy) who wistfully compares him to her
high-school boyfriend. Harry meets his soul mate in the
establishment's tough but tender madam, Sin-Dee (Lauren Bacall).
</P>
<P>
   But what about those diamonds? Do they exist? Let's put it this
way: the only thing about the movie that isn't a transparent paste
imitation is Douglas' hard, gleaming performance.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `DIAMONDS'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by John Asher; written by Allan Aaron Katz; director of
photography, Paul Elliott; edited by C. Timothy O'Meara; music by
Joel Goldsmith; production designer, Vance Lorenzini; produced by
Patricia T. Green; released by Miramax Films.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Kirk Douglas (Harry), Dan Aykroyd (Lance), Corbin Allred
(Michael), Kurt Fuller (Moses), Jenny McCarthy (Sugar), Mariah
O'Brien (Tiffany) and Lauren Bacall (Sin-Dee).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   `Diamonds' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying parent or
adult guardian). It has sexual situations and strong language.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
