<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4298 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-SYRIA-1210-COX     12-09 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SYRIA-1210-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HIGH HOPES, ANXIETIES MEET SYRIAN-ISRAEL TALKS
 &HT;    (650&AMP;ADDS)
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV, Israel _ For two decades, Syria has lead the Arab
opposition to Israel. But Thursday, Israeli law clerk Odelia Arad,
28, considered working the country into her lunch plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could go have humus in Damascus,'' Arad said of the Syrian
capital about 130 miles away. ``They are right next door.''
</P>
<P>
   Her appetite for peace got a boost Wednesday when U.S. President
Bill Clinton announced that the two longtime enemies would resume
peace talks next week in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement surprised Israelis, whose opinion will be
crucial. Prime Minister Ehud Barak has promised to hold an
unprecedented referendum on any deal that emerges from the talks.
Syrians, without a democracy, likely won't have that choice.
</P>
<P>
   But, throughout the region Thursday, Arabs and Israelis were
assessing the potentials and perils that could come.
</P>
<P>
   Israel and Syria have been in an official state of war for
decades and have been down the peace-talks path before. The last
formal, and often acrimonious, talks broke off in March 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The new talks, featuring Barak and Syrian Foreign Minister
Farouk Sharaa, could remove one of the great obstacles to peace in
the Middle East. They come amid Israel's parallel talks aimed at
reaching an agreement with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a matter of months now. Not of years. The year 2000 is
going to be, hopefully, the year of peace,'' Israeli Justice
Minister Yossi Beilin said. ``Syria is now the key to comprehensive
peace in the Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   Syria has been arguably the most important hold-out among
Israel's neighbors. Egypt, the largest Arab country, made peace
with Israel in 1982. The Palestinians, though still embroiled in a
torturously slow peace process, officially recognized Israel in
1993. Jordan followed with a peace treaty in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   With about 15 million people and a history of regional
dominance, Syria has lead the so-called ``rejectionist'' front
among Arab states.
</P>
<P>
   For Syria and President Hafez Assad, peace with Israel could
bring a return of the Golan Heights, which Israel captured in 1967.
Though Israel's ownership of the strategic plateau is not
recognized by most governments, it has populated the Golan with
18,000 Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Assad, 71, reportedly wants to reunite Syria before turning
power over to his son. He seeks U.S. aid to fortify an economy that
has suffered since the fall of its former sponsor, the old Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
   But, Assad has to hope that a deal with Israel, seen by Syrians
as an aggressive enemy, will pay off in land and prosperity. While
his people will have little say, Assad will likely want a deal good
enough to strengthen his son's chances for succession.
</P>
<P>
   Syria's official Tishrin newspaper Thursday stated the country,
``will not give up one iota of soil from the Golan. The occupation
must cease from all of the Golan.''
</P>
<P>
   The paper warned that Israel's ``intentions alone, regardless of
how good they appear, do not make a peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Israelis are also pondering the risks of peace with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Many fear that giving up the Golan would allow Syria to use it,
as it did in the 1960s, to launch attacks from the high ground.
They are seeking promises that the Syrian army will not be allowed
back and international monitors will keep watch.
</P>
<P>
   The debate taps into Israelis' visceral wariness. Right-wing
Israeli politicians Thursday alleged that there has already been a
secret deal to give away the Golan. Likud Party leader Ariel Sharon
claimed that Barak had buckled under U.S. pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Another politician, Shaul Yahalom, called the move
``semi-suicide.'' Avi Zeira, leader of the Golan Residents
Committee said Barak ``has abandoned us like we are foreigners.''
</P>
<P>
   But, a deal with Syria could further Israel's quest toward
normal diplomatic and economic relations with its Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Syria controls Lebanon and could reign in the Hezbollah
guerillas now fighting Israel there. That would help Barak fulfill
a campaign promise to withdraw from the unpopular 18-year war in
southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese Prime Minister Salim el-Hoss said Thursday that his
country would enter the talks after the initial round, possibly
becoming the next Arab state in line to accept Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once Israel concludes an agreement with the Syrians, the Arab
world will open up to Israel,'' said Syrian-born political
scientist Walid Kazziha, of the American University in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   As a Syrian native, he bristles at Israeli treatment of
Palestinians and other Arabs and said any peace will likely ``not
be a warm peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep in our hearts, we know that we are making a settlement
because we are weaker,'' he said. ``It is necessary, but I'm not
going to go out and smile and say what a lovely situation it is.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say many of the issues between the two sides were
settled during the talks three years ago. Those agreements were
``deposited'' with American mediators.
</P>
<P>
   Syria has reportedly agreed to have economic ties with Israel
and exchange ambassadors. The two sides have also likely agreed to
keep both their armies out of the Golan and allow some foreign
monitors there.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to not agreeing on the extent of the Israeli Golan
withdrawal, they have not agreed on how long a withdrawal would
take. Israel wants it done over years while Syrian compliance is
watched. Syria wants it done within months.
</P>
<P>
   The have also not agreed on how to split up the Golan's water
supply, which both countries need badly.
</P>
<P>
   (Material from The Associated Press was used in this story.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
