<HEADER>
A4299 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-INTERNET-HISPANICS-12     12-09 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-HISPANICS-1210-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WEBSITE LAUNCHED TO INCREASE HISPANIC VOTER TURNOUT
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics
categories
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hispanic groups launched a new Internet site
Thursday in an effort to swell the ranks of Latino voters to record
levels in next year's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to be a powerful force in the next election,''
said Daisy Exposito (cq.), incoming president of the Association of
Hispanic Advertising, one of the creative forces behind the new
Website.
</P>
<P>
   The site, www.latinvote.org, is designed as a one-stop online
source for Hispanics who want to register to vote or are seeking
information about political issues and candidates at the local and
national levels.
</P>
<P>
   The sponsors launched the site with a multi-media advertising
campaign on television and in newspapers with the theme: ``If you
don't select, somebody else will do it for you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the air support we have needed,'' said Juan Andrade
(cq.) , president of the United States Hispanic Leadership
Institute, and a veteran of door-to-door Latino voter registration
drives. ``This is the most collaborative effort ever ... to insure
that every Latino who is qualified to vote does,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The new Internet site reflects the growing political influence
of Hispanics, already the fastest growing ethnic group in the
United States. They number about 30 million, or 11 percent of the
total population. But by 2050, it is projected that one out of
every four Americans will be of Latino descent.
</P>
<P>
   In next year's election, Hispanics are likely to be a critical
swing vote in the presidential race because they are concentrated
in five states with a total of 166 electoral votes, more than half
of the 270 needed to be elected president. The states are
California, New York, Texas, Florida and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics will play ``a decisive role'' in the election,
predicted Fernando Espuelas (cq.), chairman of StarMedia Network,
an Internet firm that is the principle financial backer of the
site.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 4.9 million Hispanics voted in the last
presidential election, a 16.3 percent increase over 1992. The
www.latinvote.org sponsors hope to turn out 7 million Latino voters
in the 2000 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Website is non-partisan, Andrade cited several
polarizing issues as critical reasons for the new site, including
affirmative action and bilingual education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things that we have fought for are in danger,'' he said during
a news conference at the historic Hay-Adams Hotel near the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the frontrunner for the Republican
presidential nomination, opposes affirmative action. And his
party's congressional leadership has been the leading political
force against bilingual education.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Bush has warned his party against ignoring Latinos
next year. ``In order for our party to be relevant, we better
nominate somebody who understands the Hispanic vote and how to
achieve it,'' Bush said at a ``Politics &AMP; Eggs'' breakfast in
Beford, N.H., last week.
</P>
<P>
   Bush speaks Spanish fluently. And in his reelection campaign in
Texas last year, he received nearly half of the state's Hispanic
vote, a remarkable achievement for a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1976, Republican presidential candidates have received an
average of 28 percent of the Hispanic vote, according to a 1998
study by Andrade's organization. Ronald Reagan did best with Latino
voters, capturing 36 percent in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1988, however, studies indicate that Democratic
presidential candidates have out-polled Republicans by as much as
three to one among Hispanic voters _ a key factor in the campaign
strategy of Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic frontrunner.
</P>
<P>
   (Scott Shepard's email address is scotts(at)coxnews.com).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
