<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Goffstown, N.H.) _ Former President George Bush is
playing a major role in his son's bid for the Republican
presidential nomination, even if the former president has been
rarely seen in the campaign and is almost never talked about. By
R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-GORE (Goffstown, N.H.) _ Republican presidential hopeful
George W. Bush attacks Vice President Al Gore for being ``silent in
Seattle'' during the World Trade Organization's controversial
meeting last week. And he attacks President Clinton for what he
called lax enforcement of drug laws. By R.G. RATCLIFFE and CLAY
ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN-NUKES (Washington) _ Defense experts launch a nationwide
campaign aimed at getting the United States and Russia to remove
their nuclear missiles from high alert, which means they are ready
to launch on a moment's notice. The reason, the experts say, is
that Russian nuclear forces are in such dangerous disrepair that
they could mistakenly launch nuclear missiles at the United States.
By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   DELAY-COMPLAINT (Washington) _ The Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee has filed a complaint with the Federal Election
Commission, accusing Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, of helping
create tax-exempt committees to raise money and aid conservative
causes without having to comply with federal financial disclosure
rules. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SHUTTLE-DELAY (Cape Canaveral, Fla.) _ NASA decides to delay the
launch of the space shuttle Discovery to next Thursday to replace a
dented fuel line. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   STATION-RADIATION (Cape Canaveral, Fla.) _ The National Research
Council releases recommendations to reduce radiation hazards to
crews constructing the international space station. By MARK
CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-CAMPUS (College Station, Texas) _ Two students who carried
a shotgun on the Texas A&AMP;M campus in College Station were never
arrested or charged in connection with an incident in which a
student claimed one of them pointed the gun at him and pretended to
shoot. By KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   VITAPRO-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ The state has won a battle that
will save Texas millions of dollars in a fight over a prison food
contract. The Texas Supreme Court rules that the contract
purchasing VitaPro, a cheap, soy-based food for prison inmates, was
illegal because bids weren't taken. By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ During the 1970s the Republicans
repeatedly attacked what they called the Panama Canal ``giveaway.''
But after President Jimmy Carter signed the canal treaties in 1977,
the Senate ratified them and his polls showed that moderates
supported the deal. Now conservatives are trying to revive the
issue with congressional hearings and dire warnings of disaster as
we finally prepare to turn over the canal to Panama on Tuesday. By
MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   VIEQUES-PROTEST (Vieques, Puerto Rico) _ Weary but determined
protesters have weathered isolation, uncertainty and lashing
hurricanes to block the resumption of naval bombardment on a remote
target range on the Puerto Rican island of Vieques. But now, after
eight months of day-by-day successes that forced an aircraft
carrier battle fleet to go elsewhere for amphibious warfare
training, encamped trespassers are bracing for their greatest
challenge yet: Washington's drive to test the popular campaign to
oust the Navy. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' CATEGORY)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-NORMAL (Washington) _ If your bank's ATM machine isn't
working on Jan. 1, don't assume it's a Y2K problem. As many as
3,000 of them can be down under normal circumstances. On any given
day flights are delayed and people lose their electricity. The
federal government is trying to determine what doesn't normally
work so it won't blame a Jan. 1 problem on the year 2000 computer
glitch when the real cause may be a snowstorm. By JENNIFER CORBETT
DOOREN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-TIPS (Washington) _ with Y2K NORMAL _ While experts say
banks, electricity distributors and transportation companies are
ready for the New Year, they're offering tips to consumers just in
case there are Y2K computer failures. By The HEARST NEWSPAPERS.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   REDISTRICTING-WONKS (Washington) _ Dueling Republican and
Democratic statisticians, cartographers and demographers will play
key roles in the redistricting of the House of Representatives, a
huge political upheaval that occurs once every decade and can
determine which political party controls the House. By JUDY
HOLLAND. (Also to be filed in the ``p'' category.)
</P>
