<SLUG> BC-WEB-CRUMBS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY OFFERS WAY TO ORGANIZE WEB BOOKMARKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Atop the kitschy Buca di Beppo Italian eatery,
the latest Web site craze is taking shape.
</P>
<P>
   It is based on crumbs, as in leaving behind crumbs to find your
way back home through a forest. Except these are digital crumbs,
and the forest is the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Backflip (www.backflip.com ) is a $4 million Internet start-up
company headed by a pair of veterans of Netscape Communications
Corp. The company is hoping Web users are sick of losing their way
while cruising the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Their solution: Keep track of what a Web user visits, then index
that content, plus allow that user to search by keyword through
this worn path.
</P>
<P>
   ``Backflip allows users to create their own personal Yahoo,''
said Backflip co-founder and chief executive Tim Hickman, a former
Netscape product manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``It lets a user build their own search engine and index of the
content they've visited.''
</P>
<P>
   Backflip consists of several components. It creates a
personalized home base Web page that categorizes the pages a user
has visited. It also creates a searchable database of the content
of these pages.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Backflip puts a button on the Web browser that allows a
user to ``backflip'' pages that he or she wants to save. A browser,
such as Microsoft's Internet Explorer or Netscape Communicator, is
software used to view Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   Most browsers already come with a bookmarking feature that saves
the location address of Web pages, but the content of those
bookmarks is not searchable. A particularly enthusiastic bookmarker
can quickly create a confusing and cumbersome list of Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more bookmarks you have, the more difficult it is to
use,'' Hickman said.
</P>
<P>
   Backflip's first investor was Ron Conway of Angel Investors LP,
a group of successful Internet moguls who have ponied up $125
million for Internet start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm betting on the team and the idea,'' Conway said. ``It
solves a big problem for people by acting as their memory of the
Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Backflip plans to generate revenue in part by what it calls a
suggestion engine. Hickman said the site would not actually track
or sell to third parties any individual's Web viewing habits
(thereby avoiding privacy concerns, he said).
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, Backflip will track the Web sites and the
content users view. It will then go out and gather similar content
to suggest to users.
</P>
<P>
   Hickman said this suggestion process takes place within
Backflip's internal computers, disconnected from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers, Hickman said, will have their messages delivered
along with those suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strong privacy assurances are going to make this work,''
Hickman said. ``And we have that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 1639EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4307 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-PRINCETON-HISTORY-ART     12-09 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRINCETON-HISTORY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PRINCETON, HISTORY IS ENTWINED WITH IVY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRINCETON, N.J. _ Is there a college building anywhere in the
United States that can match the storied past of Nassau Hall at
Princeton University, a history that goes well beyond the world of
academe? Built of local stone and capped with an impressive bell
tower, the building served as the college's centerpiece when it was
erected by Presbyterians in 1756.
</P>
<P>
   But in a remarkable seven-year span it twice served as a seat of
government (state and national) and figured in a Revolutionary War
battle. New Jersey's first Legislature gathered at Nassau Hall in
1776 and adopted the state seal. In 1783 Congress met there for
four months with James Madison, a former student, returning as a
representative from Virginia. To walk such historically rich ground
is reason enough to visit Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   The newly arrived will find a pleasant, centrally located hotel
called the Nassau Inn, restaurants, a fine bookstore (Micawber
Books) and no shortage of shops on and around Nassau Street, the
main thoroughfare.
</P>
<P>
   The university lends Princeton an identity that sets it apart
from the commercial and suburban mass continually spreading out
across central New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   F. Scott Fitzgerald, an undergraduate here when the university's
13th president, Woodrow Wilson, was in the White House, snobbishly
described Princeton as ``rising, a green Phoenix, out of the
ugliest country in the world.'' Fitzgerald evoked Princeton in his
first novel, ``This Side of Paradise,'' which he had begun during
his student days here. It is a testament to Princeton's cultural
depth that Fitzgerald is only a single stone in the diadem of
luminaries who have crowned the town with glory, a roster that
includes political leaders, scientists and a breathtaking number of
literary figures, from the Nobel Prize-winning novelist Thomas Mann
to the literary critic Edmund Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Einstein lived here. Two centuries earlier, so too did
Jonathan Edwards, the nation's greatest theologian and the
university's third president, who lies buried here along with his
notorious grandson, Aaron Burr, a Revolutionary War officer,
Jefferson's first vice president and the man who killed Alexander
Hamilton in a duel in 1804.
</P>
<P>
   Princeton can claim George Washington not only as visitor but
also as victor. The general's embattled colonial troops won an
important battle here on Jan. 3, 1777, nine days after they crossed
the Delaware, defeating King George's redcoats and providing a
much-need triumph for the beleaguered revolutionary cause in the
early days of the war. The victory was capped by the surrender of
British troops holed up in Nassau Hall. They succumbed to
Continental Artillery fire urged on by Hamilton, who had better
luck against the British than he did against Burr.
</P>
<P>
   With so much to absorb, where should one start? I recommend
stopping by Bainbridge House, home of the Historical Society of
Princeton, a two-story brick house at 158 Nassau St., two doors
down from the intersection with Washington Street.
</P>
<P>
   Inside is a small but informative display on local history where
one can find everything from pottery created by the Lenape Indians,
the area's pre-European dwellers, to a placard with the Fitzgerald
quotation. The society sponsors a two-hour walking tour of
centrally located historic sites every Sunday afternoon at 2.
</P>
<P>
   On the bright and blustery day I took the tour, an energetic
volunteer guide led a crowd of us on a two-mile loop that stopped
before the quietly impressive Greek Revival exterior of Nassau
Presbyterian Church, paused at the imposing battle monument a
couple of blocks to the south (it was dedicated by President Warren
G. Harding) and took in the sight of Morven, the estate built for
Richard Stockton, who along with Madison's teacher the Rev. John
Witherspoon was a signer of the Declaration of Independence. The
building served as the executive mansion for New Jersey governors
until well into this century.
</P>
<P>
   Our guide pointed out the former house of Mann (now home to
Princeton's Catholic campus ministry), then led us to 112 Mercer
St. for a look at the modest wood-frame house _ still a private
home _ where Einstein lived while at the Institute for Advanced
Study nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the neighbors' nonchalance as they went about taking
out trash and parking their cars, a crowd along the sidewalk was no
cause for remark.
</P>
<P>
   The Princeton Battlefield is about a mile farther down Mercer
Street, a distance I chose to drive on my own, rather than walk.
The site of Washington's victory is a graceful sweep of land,
impressively intact and preserved as an 85-acre state park. On its
southern side stands a late Colonial house built by a Quaker
farmer, Thomas Clarke, that sheltered the wounded American general
Hugh Mercer, who died there several days after he fell in the
battle.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   These days the house is a small interpretative center with
written material and exhibits about the battle. In one display case
a thick telephone book with a hole blown through it for
contemporary demonstration purposes testifies to the destructive
power of an 18th-century musket ball.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone ambitious to learn more about Washington's New Jersey
campaign ought to consider a detour to nearby Titusville, N.J.,
where the 800-acre Washington Crossing State Park commemorates
Washington's crossing of the Delaware on Dec. 25, 1776. His troops
marched to Trenton, defeating Hessian soldiers in a surprise
attack. The visitors' center contains an excellent collection of
Revolutionary War military gear.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to Princeton, to its north, lies another state historic
site, Rockingham, an 18th-century farmhouse on Route 518 in Rocky
Hill, N.J., which was Washington's quarters in 1783 while Congress
convened in Nassau Hall. Hamilton, Jefferson, Madison and others
met with him there. What it looks like inside I never found out, as
I didn't make it past the door, finding the place closed one
afternoon and, on another, busy with a tour for a group of
children.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing barred my way to the Princeton Cemetery, established in
1757 and containing a fascinating record of the town's history.
Owned by Nassau Presbyterian Church but with plots open to a far
wider population, it contains the grave of Grover Cleveland, the
only Democrat elected president between 1860 and 1912. Born in
northern New Jersey, he settled in Princeton after his political
career and became a trustee of the university.
</P>
<P>
   The novelist John O'Hara, the parents of the African-American
singer and actor Paul Robeson, and Sylvia Beach, founder of the
avant-garde Shakespeare &AMP; Company bookstore in Paris, a magnet for
literary expatriates in the 1920's, also lie here. So, too, do most
of the university's presidents, in a plot in the section known as
the Old Graveyard.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, who became president of what was then called the
College of New Jersey shortly before his death in 1758, succeeded
his son-in-law, the Rev. Aaron Burr Sr., president from 1748 to
1757, and the man who supervised construction of Nassau Hall. Their
table-top gravestones bear lengthy Latin inscriptions, as does
Witherspoon's nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Burr, who studied theology before switching to law,
lies at their feet, under an upright stone that briefly notes his
military and political service _ discreetly avoiding mention of his
trial for treason after being charged with plotting to wrest a
chunk of the lower Mississippi Valley from the new republic.
</P>
<P>
   A pamphlet describing the cemetery's history, with a map showing
where to find its famous dead, is available at the historical
society.
</P>
<P>
   Princeton also has a good system of public parks. But the most
interesting space lies on the town's eastern side, where a state
park preserves the old Delaware and Raritan Canal, with a tow path
that makes a quiet place for walking, jogging or bicycling. If you
head north along it, toward Kingston, you skirt the shore of
Carnegie Lake, with ample chance to watch rowing crews at practice.
</P>
<P>
   In a couple of places you may come across a small sign
describing construction of the canal more than 150 years ago by
Irish immigrants. Many of those men, who worked in difficult and
unhealthy conditions, died of disease. It is a sober reminder that
many anonymous hands have gone into shaping Princeton and its
surroundings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
