<SLUG> BC-STATES-SMALL-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SMALL BUSINESS FARED WELL AT WTO, GOVERNMENT SAYS
</P>
<P>
   By Jonathan Lipman
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Dec. 9 -- The tumultuous and unproductive world
trade talks in Seattle last week were actually rather calm and
successful for small business interests, Small Business
Administration head Aida Alvarez said Wednesday. But not everyone
shared her optimism, or even her enthusiasm on the importance of
international trade to the entrepreneurial community.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with States News Service, Alvarez downplayed the
influence of street protests on the delegates to the World Trade
Organization summit and said that trade representatives had an
unprecedented chance to learn about American small business
interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small businesses are all now a part of the international
arena,'' Alvarez said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the trade mission to Seattle, Alvarez ensured that
small business had a voice in the U.S. strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been an aggressive discussion [inside] the
administration for the role of small business in international
issues of any sort,'' Alvarez said. ``We engaged the U.S. Trade
Office. . .and they even contemplated a high level position at
[their office] that would deal exclusively with small business
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   But the National Federation of Independent Business, which did
not send representatives to Seattle, did not share Alavarez' belief
in the importance of international trade to small business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We survey our members pretty regularly and trade doesn't show
up on their list of priorities,'' spokeswoman Mary Crawford said.
``I couldn't tell you why.'' The NFIB's average member company has
six employees, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Chamber of Commerce said that small businesses were
just beginning to get involved in policy debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of small businesses out in Seattle that were
taking an interest in what's going on with the WTO, and I find that
an interesting development,'' said Leslie Schweitzer, Senior Trade
Advisor for the U.S. Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Small Business Committee Chairman Sen. Kit Bond, R-Mo.,
said there could be even more attention paid to that community. In
a letter to U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky, Bond
asked for specific language on small business to be included in any
final agenda that emerged from the Seattle talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt that some productive things happened, but there
certainly is room for more in terms of representing small business
at WTO,'' committee spokesman Craig Orfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez called the letter a sign of the increase in the national
awareness of the importance of small business to international
trade issues. If a trade agenda had emerged, she said, she hoped it
would have had the sort of specific words Bond sought.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that every time there was a discussion of trade barriers,
there would be a question of what it would mean for small
business,'' Alvarez said. She said language would also focus on
intellectual property and e-commerce, two items she said were vital
to small business.
</P>
<P>
   In general, talks on issues important to small business went
smoothly, Alvarez said, and were not suspect to the kind of
divisive sentiments expressed by some small nations inside the
conference hall, and by some protesters in the streets outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a controversial issue, it was positively
received,'' Alvarez said.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to organized labor's demands that working conditions
and wage levels be part of discussions, Alvarez said: ``By and
large small businesses pay minimum wages or more. We don't have
those kinds of issues for small business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now small businesses, the ones I've talked to, they're
interested in _ protection of trademarks and patents,'' she said.
``They're interested in removing barriers to trade. They don't want
to see restrictions to e-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   Discussion on those issues went very well, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But House Small Business Committee Chairman James Talent, R-Mo.,
was less pleased with the outcome of the talks, and felt that so
long as foreign markets in China and elsewhere remain closed, small
farms and technology companies will suffer, according to
spokeswoman, Michelle Dimarob.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was disappointed,'' Dimarob said. ``Not as much attention
was paid to the actual issues, because everything sort of devolved
from what was going on outside the conference.''
</P>
<P>
   The top priority for small businesses at WTO was simply getting
involved with the process, the Chamber's Schweitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of this was working as an educational tool,'' she said.
``There was certainly a lot of exchange, networking, and that is
certainly an important process to occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the increase in national awareness, a new
international focus on small business will help, Alvarez said.
Several national governments are working with the SBA, learning how
to develop their own agencies to serve that community.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they create similar programs, it will be easier for us to
do business,'' Alvarez said. The United Kingdom, Ireland,
Argentina, Egypt, South Africa, and Mexico are all working on
SBA-like programs. The SBA's director of international trade, James
Wilfong, met with WTO delegations from Japan, Europe, Latin
America, and Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very, very busy,'' Alvarez said. ``Once we got there,
we had so many forums to speak about small business. It really was
a fabulous opportunity to get the message out.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez, a former reporter who braved gunfire in Latin American
war zones, was not fazed by the sometimes violent street protest in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a kid of the late sixties,'' Alvarez said. ``When I went
to school the streets were always full of people protesting about
something. I always thought that was our right as American
citizens. It was really unfortunate that it was a really small
group of people who thought that the way to get attention was to be
violent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
