<HEADER>
A4311 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     12-09 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RICK LYMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLIDAY MOVIES, BY THE BOOK
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ The holiday rush of movies, now well upon us, always
includes a fair sampling of book adaptations, both recent best
sellers and time-worn classics. Each comes with its own built-in
audience and predetermined respectability, guaranteed Oscar bait.
And this year's crop is, if anything, a bit bigger than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Before month's end, theaters will be showing adaptations as
diverse as ``Angela's Ashes,'' based on Frank McCourt's Pulitzer
Prize-winning memoir of growing up poor in Limerick, Ireland (with
Alan Parker directing Robert Carlyle and Emily Watson, as McCourt's
parents); ``The Green Mile,'' based on Stephen King's serialized
prison drama (with Frank Darabont directing Tom Hanks, as a Death
Row guard forced to confront _ well, you have to see it); ``Snow
Falling on Cedars,'' based on David Guterson's atmospheric drama
about cultural conflict in the Pacific Northwest (with Scott Hicks
directing Ethan Hawke); ``Girl, Interrupted,'' based on Susanna
Kaysen's memoir of her year in a mental hospital in the 1960s (with
James Mangold directing Winona Ryder and Angelina Jolie); ``Stuart
Little,'' based on E.B. White's children's story (with Rob Minkoff
directing Geena Davis and a computer-generated mouse); ``The
Talented Ripley,'' based on Patricia Highsmith's cold-blooded
thriller (with Anthony Minghella directing Matt Damon and Gwyneth
Paltrow), and ``The Cider House Rules'' based on John Irving's best
seller (with Lasse Halstrom directing Tobey Maguire and Michael
Caine).
</P>
<P>
   And that doesn't even include a couple of adaptations of plays
(Julie Taymor's assertively idiosyncratic take on Shakespeare's
``Titus Andronicus,'' shortened to ``Titus,'' and Matthew Warchus'
adaptation of Sam Shepard's ``Simpatico'') or Martha Fiennes
directing her brother Ralph in ``Onegin,'' an adaptation of
Pushkin's narrative poem.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps none of them faced a challenge quite like Neil
Jordan's. He was charged with finding a way to adapt ``The End of
the Affair,'' Graham Greene's autobiographical story of wartime
love and spiritual anguish. The film opened last week in New York
and Los Angeles to generally positive reviews. Greene's drama is
about a writer, not unlike himself, who is deeply embittered when a
torrid affair with a friend's wife ends inexplicably during the
London blitz. But it's about more than that, also exploring issues
of religious faith and conscience not usually dealt with in
mainstream films, and it tries to explain, at least partly, why
Greene himself became a Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I decided to structure the story, there are a series
of pivotal events that are at the center of the story,'' Jordan
said. He was not so concerned with the specific religious elements
of the story as he was with the way Greene built the plot, in which
the central character (played by Fiennes) completely misunderstands
what is in the mind of his lover (Julianne Moore).
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said he shot some of his pivotal scenes more than once.
One encounter in a restaurant, for instance, is shot once from the
point of view of Fiennes and then, later, after we learn his
lover's secret, from hers, and then yet again from the perspective
of a private detective peering at them through the window. The
scenes play at different times in the movie, and each time the
audience understands a little more about what is really happening.
The point is to show how easy it is to misinterpret what is on
someone else's mind, even someone with whom you are on the most
intimate terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the main reasons I wanted to make the movie,''
Jordan said. ``You read the book, and you get the sense of the
novelist's state of mind, but Greene had a wonderful story in there
with a wonderfully ironic sequence of events, if seen from
different points of view. First we experience what happens with
Ralph, then again with Julianne. By adding these two perspectives
together, yet another perspective emerges, something much more
mysterious.''
</P>
<P>
   He also found it necessary to excise one of Greene's supporting
characters, a rationalist preacher who undergoes a miraculous cure
that he cannot explain. ``In my opinion, the preacher was the least
successful character in the book,'' Jordan said. Yet the character
plays a role in the story's spiritual denouement, so Jordan
inserted a new character, the detective's child, to handle that
chore. ``To me, having a child in that situation just made it all
much more mysterious and believable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ACCENTING THEIR WORDS
</P>
<P>
   Holiday prestige pictures also mean actors' tackling foreign
accents, and this year has a bumper crop. Julianne Moore is not the
only American actress using a British accent; Jodie Foster gives it
a go in Andrew Tennant's ``Anna and the King.'' Michael Caine goes
American in ``The Cider House Rules.'' Tom Hanks tries a Southern
drawl in ``The Green Mile.'' By comparison, the Swedish-born Max
Von Sydow has it easy in ``Snow Falling on Cedars,'' playing a
lawyer who happens to be a Scandinavian immigrant to the Pacific
Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have two situations in my career,'' Von Sydow said. ``Most
of the time in America, I play the foreigner. It's minor parts, the
odd characters. You know: the artist, the doctor. Or the villain,
of course. The foreigner. But in European films, they ask me to do
anything. I play men of authority. They will dub it anyway, so no
matter what, I am not the foreigner.''
</P>
<P>
   Tall, tanned and gimlet-eyed, Von Sydow leaned forward in a
sumptuous upholstered chair in his suite at the Peninsula Hotel in
Beverly Hills. In the film, the character he plays is old and
sickly, hardly able to walk down the street in the snow _ nothing
like the vigorous 70-year-old actor in jeans and running shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This character was really a gift because I felt that I knew
him,'' Von Sydow said. His character acts partly as the film's
conscience, defending a Japanese-American fisherman accused of
murder in the late 1940s. ``He's just an ordinary man,'' Von Sydow
said. ``He's alone. He feels that life is close to the end.
Physically, he is not in very good shape. But he is no enigma to
me. I felt that I knew him. I felt that I had met him.''
</P>
<P>
   Von Sydow said he and his wife had rented numerous films with
important courtroom scenes and had watched them in his trailer
while on location for the film. He also regularly consulted David
Guterson's novel, on which the film is based, ``as a kind of
reference for things about this man'' _ the character he plays _
``that didn't get into the script.'' Mostly, he said, he was
delighted to be asked to play a meaty role in a Hollywood film that
did not require him to be a foreigner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy was wonderful to do because he is a wonderful man,''
Von Sydow said. ``He is someone without any pretenses behind him. I
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   MUTE, EXPRESSIVELY
</P>
<P>
   If Max Von Sydow thought he had an easy time with his accent, it
was nothing compared to Samantha Morton's in Woody Allen's ``Sweet
and Lowdown.'' Of course, the British-born actress had other
problems.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Ms. Morton, perhaps best known in the United States
for the title role in a 1997 television adaptation of ``Jane
Eyre,'' plays a nearly angelic mute laundress who falls in love
with a selfish, philandering jazz musician played by Sean Penn.
Without a single spoken line, she must convey a complex series of
emotions and not let actors like Penn and Anthony LaPaglia,
incessantly chattering Woody Allen dialogue, blow her off the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This film gave me a chance to play somebody who was completely
free of emotional baggage,'' Ms. Morton said. ``It wasn't a
traumatic part; I didn't have to go through some terrible journey;
it didn't require me to go through a nervous breakdown or sexual
revolution. It was almost like playing an angel. I walked away from
work every day feeling very clean, refreshed just from doing the
part.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Morton said she was helped by Allen's script, which she said
was extremely specific about what her character needed to bring to
each scene. ``I didn't have to plot anything,'' she said. ``It was
all there in the script. It wasn't difficult at all. Even though
she never speaks, she does say a lot. I never felt that she lacked
anything. I never even felt the urge to speak, the desire to speak,
and that was a very nice feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Morton has another movie currently in limited release,
``Dreaming of Joseph Lees,'' and she will be seen in the next few
months in three other independent films: ``Jesus' Son,'' a favorite
at the Toronto International Film Festival in September,
``Pandaemonium'' (playing Samuel Taylor Coleridge's wife), and
``The Last Yellow,'' a dark comedy about a pair of misfits. But
mostly, she said, she is waiting to see how people react to the
Woody Allen film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, when this film comes out, some more people will
consider me for their films,'' she said. ``It's very hard to get
scripts, you know, to get auditions. That's just the way things
happen. You know, I was very naive. I thought that you try to do
good work and the scripts come along. But it's also about how much
you're worth and how many people your name can convince to see the
film rather than because you're right for the role.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
