<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JESSE MCKINLEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Interrupted Life, Interrupted Work
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The emotional impact of the death of the director
Mike Ockrent, who died of leukemia on Dec. 2 at 53, was still being
absorbed this week by many who knew him on Broadway. And at the
same time, there were questions about the future of two projects
with which the director was involved at the time of his death.
</P>
<P>
   The more fully realized project was ``The Night They Raided
Minsky's,'' a new musical loosely based on the 1968 William
Friedkin movie about the old days of burlesque, which Ockrent had
been involved with for five years. The show was scheduled to have
its premiere in Los Angeles in July. Those plans are now up in the
air.
</P>
<P>
   One of the show's producers, Rocco Landesman, the president of
Jujamcyn Theaters, said it was simply too early to know what would
happen. ``Mike was not only the perfect director on this show, he
was largely the creative instigator,'' Landesman said.
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was echoed by Timothy Childs, the lead producer.
``Mike had been the heart and soul of this show,'' he said. One
concrete development, however, was news this week that the
experienced producers Richard Frankel and Thomas Viertel (``Sound
of Music'') joined the production.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his bow to burlesque, Ockrent had also joined the
comedian Mel Brooks to adapt another movie about the raffish days
of show business into a musical, Brooks' ``Producers.'' Seth
Gelblum, who represents several parties involved in that project,
said it was still in its infancy but that Ockrent's loss would be
felt. ``Mike and Mel had a special connection,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Ockrent's survivors the show must go on. Word came this week
that the revival of the perennial favorite ``The Music Man,'' to be
directed and choreographed by Susan Stroman, Ockrent's wife, had
secured the Neil Simon Theater for performances beginning on April
3. Rehearsals, with a cast including Craig Bierko, Rebecca Luker
and Ruth Williamson, begin in February.
</P>
<P>
   A Role Change
</P>
<P>
   Considering the under-siege camaraderie that develops among
actors, it is not surprising to see that this month three
successful performers are helping their peers by taking on the role
of producer.
</P>
<P>
   The first up is ``Fully Committed,'' which has done quite well
in its earlier incarnation this year. The one-man comedy about a
beleaguered restaurant clerk was one of the hottest tickets
off-Broadway this fall when it played at the Vineyard Theater. It
is now moving to the Cherry Lane Theater on Tuesday with Mark
Setlock repeating the role of the harried reservations-taker.
Setlock had earlier appeared in ``Rent'' on Broadway with Jesse L.
Martin and Adam Pascal, who have, in turn, signed on to help him
produce his show in its new location.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much good, original material never gets to be seen,''
Pascal said. ``This is a way to give back.''
</P>
<P>
   Another one-man play, ``Another American: Asking and Telling,''
by Marc Wolf, is being produced by the actor and playwright David
Marshall Grant. The drama, focusing on gays in the military, opens
on Thursday at the Theater at St. Clement's.
</P>
<P>
   Grant said he read the script earlier this year and suggested to
friends at New York Stage and Film, a theater company in
Poughkeepsie, N.Y., that they do a workshop of the play. ``I
suddenly realized,'' he said, ``that I'm actually helping produce
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Benched on Broadway
</P>
<P>
   Is Frank Gifford trying to cut in on his wife's territory? Not
quite, but maybe someday.
</P>
<P>
   Kathie Lee Gifford, the morning talk-show host, made her
Broadway debut on Tuesday night in ``Putting It Together.'' Not to
be outdone, her husband, a former New York Giants football star and
sportscaster, auditioned last week for the role of Billy Flynn in
the Las Vegas version of the musical ``Chicago.'' And according to
his lawyer, Ron Konecky, he wasn't half bad.
</P>
<P>
   But Konecky said the rehearsal schedule, and a small window of
performances, made Gifford's participation impractical. Barry
Weissler, the show's producer and a man who has never shied from
salting his shows with celebrities, said he has always idolized
Gifford's football prowess. And his singing? ``Frank is the
greatest football player known to man,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Happy to Be a Lowlife
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that long ago that Fisher Stevens had pretty much
given up on acting, opting out of a television contract on CBS'
science-fiction show ``Early Edition'' and heading back to New York
to concentrate on his budding film-directing and producing career.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Harry Sobel.
</P>
<P>
   Harry, you see, is the central character in Bryan Goluboff's
play ``Shyster,'' a low-rent rake with bad hair whose best trait
may be his uncanny ability for self-delusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I got to play this guy,''' said Stevens, adding with
a grin, ``The thing I like about acting is that it allows me to do
things that I could never do in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Acting and life have often been one and the same for Stevens. He
made his Broadway debut at 18 in ``Torch Song Trilogy'' and quickly
jumped to Hollywood with films like ``The Flamingo Kid'' and
``Short Circuit.'' But the theater and New York remained in his
blood and in 1986 he helped found Naked Angels, a stage company
with several young celluloid stars on its roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shyster,'' a Naked Angels production that opened to critical
praise on Monday and runs through Dec. 19 at the Blue Heron
Theater, may extend if the schedules of its stars, including
Stevens, Annabella Sciorra and the newcomer Charles Malik
Whitfield, can be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
