<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON WHAT'S NEW IN HOME VIDEO 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MUSIC CHOICES AND INTERACTION
</P>
<P>
   Of all the genres migrating to DVD, the long-form, or concert,
music video uses the format as fully as any. One reason is that
unlike videotape, which requires spooling and rewinding to move
around, the disc allows the viewer to pop about instantly and at
random. That gives the music-video audience, often a young one, a
lot to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more potential to engage the fans, get them more
involved with the artists,'' said Kevin Conroy, senior vice
president for worldwide marketing at BMG Entertainment. This fall,
the company, which distributes about 40 record labels, got into DVD
with ```Turandot' at the Forbidden City of Beijing'' and `` 'N
Sync: 'N the Mix,'' a collection of hits and other features by the
pop group.
</P>
<P>
   Puccini's opera, an elaborate $15 million production by BMG
Classics for PBS' ``Great Performances'' series, leans more toward
standard extras like a behind-the-scenes documentary and a chat
with the conductor Zubin Mehta.
</P>
<P>
   The 'N Sync disc keeps the group's teeny-bopper fans busy at the
remote control. Choosing from several menus and six small screens,
each playing clips of content options, viewers can skip about among
songs, a photo gallery, the life stories of 'N Sync's five members,
scenes from tours and video taping sessions, choreography
rehearsals, shots of the group at play and other items.
</P>
<P>
   On ``Lynyrd Skynrd: Lyve From Steel Town,'' with 15 songs
performed by the Southern rock band at a 1997 concert in
Burgettstown, Pa., any song is reachable virtually at any instant,
as is any element of the extra features, which include backstage
scenes, a band history (a long and tragic one), discography and
on-location interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``The viewer spends more time with disc than VHS,'' Conroy said.
In recent years, he added, the concert-length music video has
lagged somewhat, although VHS titles like ``Sarah McLachlan:
Mirrorball,'' a BMG title, and ``Woodstock 99,'' from Sony Music
Video, rank high on current best-seller lists.
</P>
<P>
   BMG has more than 20 titles on disc, among them ``Alabama for
the Record: Live,'' ``Styx: Return to Paradise,'' ``Anthrax: Return
of the Killer B's Video Anthology,'' ``Blondie: VH-1 Live From Town
Hall,'' ``Meat Loaf: VH-1 Storytellers.'' On Tuesday BMG will
release ``The Backstreet Boys'' and ``Time Out With Britney
Spears.''
</P>
<P>
   The McLachlan video, which appeared on DVD in October, includes
an interview with the singer and a ``scrapbook'' with photographs
from her life. Many BMG titles will also be available on tape, but
the emphasis will be on DVD. ``We've spent a lot of time with the
labels educating them on what's required,'' Conroy said.
</P>
<P>
   Some material already released on videocassette may lend itself
to the sharp images and big sound on disc. With their high
production values, concerts shot for television are good prospects.
``Turandot'' and the Alabama, Blondie and Meat Loaf discs are
examples.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever there is an original television production, we
immediately think about DVD,'' Conroy said. Some BMG labels are
shooting material exclusively for DVD. ``In future live concerts
made for DVD then could be a TV show,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   THE GENERAL'S DAUGHTER
</P>
<P>
   To express its opinion of women in the military, Simon West's
film lets an incredibly promiscuous female Army captain (Leslie
Stefanson) make fools of some battle-hardened types before she is
murdered in spectacularly kinky fashion. Brought in to investigate,
the Army detective Paul Brenner (John Travolta) finds the brass
covering up for all its worth.
</P>
<P>
   But good actors are underused in a story that pumps up the
gratuitously ugly side. ``Nobody in this whodunit really seems
interested in the upshot,'' Janet Maslin wrote in The New York
Times. ``All the movie cares about is the deed and the way it is
done.''
</P>
<P>
   1999. Paramount. $107.37; DVD, $29.99. 118 minutes. 117 minutes.
Closed captioned. R. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   BUENA VISTA SOCIAL CLUB
</P>
<P>
   Wim Wenders' documentary mixes music by the ensemble Buena Vista
Social Club with impressionistic glimpses of urban life in
contemporary Cuba. The film springs from an album of 14 Cuban
mambos, boleros and cha-chas performed by musicians from Cuba's
pre-revolutionary old guard and put together by the American
guitarist and producer Ry Cooder. So intense are the joy,
camaraderie and national pride that you ``become convinced that
making music is a key to longevity and spiritual well-being''
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   1999. Artisan. $22.98; DVD, $29.98. 106 minutes. Unrated. Closed
captioned. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   TEACHING MRS. TINGLE
</P>
<P>
   Acting on their misgivings about a nasty teacher named Tingle
(Helen Mirren), three students (Katie Holmes, Marisa Coughlin and
Barry Watson) barge into her house and tie her to her bedposts.
Sneeringly dismissive even when trussed up, Mrs. T. is to recant
unfounded cheating charges against one of them or, or _ or what?
``Maybe we should finish her,'' says one of the students.
</P>
<P>
   Wes Craven's ``Scream,'' written by Kevin Williamson, wouldn't
have needed the suggestion. But all this Williamson movie does is
``prove that Ms. Mirren can outshine a cute teen-age cast with her
hands tied'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1999. Dimension. $104.16; DVD, $29.99. 96 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG-13. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   DICK
</P>
<P>
   At last we learn the truth about Watergate. Late one night at
the apartment complex, two teen-agers, Arlene (Michelle Williams)
and Betsy (Kirsten Dunst), run smack into G. Gordon Liddy (Harry
Shearer), who is monitoring the famous break-in in progress at that
very moment.
</P>
<P>
   Later, a worried Richard Nixon (Dan Hedaya) seeks to buy the
girls' silence by offering them jobs as official walkers of the
presidential dog.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, Arlene develops a crush on Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   But disillusionment sets in when the girls get to messing around
the Oval Office and stumble across some of those infamous tapes in
``an uproariously dizzy satire'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $105.77; DVD, $24.95. 94 minutes.
Closed captioned. PG-13. Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   GRAND ILLUSION. Jean Renoir's antiwar classic, starring Jean
Gabin and Erich von Stroheim, is newly restored and looking fresh.
1937. Home Vision. $29.95. 117 minutes. French with English
subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: A DOCUMENTARY FILM. E.L. Doctorow, Allen Ginsberg and
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani are among those interviewed in Ric Burns'
five-part series about the city, shown recently on PBS. Starting
with the arrival of the English and the Dutch, the story proceeds
through the German and Irish immigrations of the 1800s; the
emergence of Walt Whitman, Frederick Law Olmstead and William M.
Tweed; the mass immigration at the turn of the century; the
contributions of George Gershwin, F. Scott Fitzgerald and Duke
Ellington, and the rise of advertising, radio, magazines and other
mass media in midtown. 1999. Warner $99.92, five cassettes. 120
minutes each. Release date: Dec. 14.
</P>
<P>
   YOURS FOR A SONG: THE WOMEN OF TIN PAN ALLEY. Gershwin and
Berlin ruled the airwaves, but the 1920s, '30s and '40s brought
major contributions by four relatively unknown songwriters: Dorothy
Fields (``On the Sunny Side of the Street,'' ``Big Spender,'' ``I
Can't Give You Anything but Love,'' ``The Way You Look Tonight),
Kay Swift (the musical ``Fine and Dandy''), Dana Suesse (``My
Silent Love'') and Ann Ronell (``Willow Weep for Me''). Betty
Buckley sings and narrates the PBS ``American Masters'' production,
which includes performances by Robert White, Max Morath and Joan
Morris, and interviews and archival clips exploring the songwriters
and their era. 1999. Winstar. $19.98; DVD, $24.98. 55 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 1710EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
