<HEADLINE>
NUMBER CRUNCHERS WILL HELP DECIDE CONTROL OF HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Dec. 12)   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``p'' categories.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dueling computer gurus who crunch statistics for a
living will have a big impact on who controls Congress over the
next decade.
</P>
<P>
   These backroom wonks become key players when, once every 10
years, they are enlisted to redraw the maps of the 435 House
districts.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution requires that House districts be equal in
population and that job ultimately falls to lawmakers in the 50
