Republican and Democratic parties and people like Tom Hofeller.
</P>
<P>
   With a political science PhD and a nimble penchant for
statistics, Hofeller is the Republicans' redistricting czar. When
the Census Bureau delivers its new population data on a computer
disc on April 1, 1991, Hofeller will coach state legislators how to
sketch districts that favor Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the starting pistol on the redistricting race track,''
says Hofeller, a stout fellow with bright suspenders.
</P>
<P>
   If knowledge is power, then Hofeller has huge political clout,
at least once every 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   His work is ``the only legalized form of vote stealing left in
the United States,'' Hofeller says. ``It's the ultimate power sport
in all of politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Working with the state legislatures and incumbent House members
requires plenty of tact.
</P>
<P>
   The process can ``bring out the worst in everybody'' because all
lawmakers assume ``the map will start with their district.''
</P>
<P>
   Emotions run high. Hofeller says he once witnessed a fist-fight
on the floor of the Illinois House in 1981 when the legislators
were considering new boundaries for congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   Hofeller appears amused at the once-a-decade deep bow that House
members make to state legislators when district maps are being
designed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the one time every 10 years that members of Congress
have to go back to the state legislatures and beg,'' Hofeller says.
``It's an awkward position to find themselves in.''
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, as the game plays out, ``the powerful people in each
legislature will be looking to reward and punish people from their
party and other parties,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Gersh, Hofeller's Democratic counterpart, is the head
statistician for IMPAC 2000, the party's national redistricting
project. When it's redistricting time, state legislators sketch new
maps and often submit them for Gersh's review.
</P>
<P>
   He says he must work fast because some states show him 500
different variations of a map and they want quick answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You spend a lot of time tweaking it,'' Gersh says.
</P>
<P>
   But Gersh says he is cautious not to butt in and ``big foot''
state legislators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to make myself helpful,'' Gersh says. ``Where they don't
need us we go on to somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Trained in statistics, accounting and math, Gersh says his
motivation is not primarily political.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an ideological person,'' he says. ``I enjoy the
numbers. I enjoy the process, that's basically what makes it
interesting for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gersh says the most frustrating part of his task is balancing
the Democrats' goal of winning the most seats against individual
interests of lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a lot of very self-centered members who have safe
districts, but they don't want to give up a little bit to make it
possible (for the party) to win another one in an adjacent area,''
Gersh says.
</P>
<P>
   The redistricting competition will begin as soon as the new
Census data is analyzed to determine how many seats go to each
state.
</P>
<P>
   A complex mathematical formula known as ``The Method of Equal
Proportions'' reapportions the 435 House seats so that each state
gets at least one House seat. The remaining 385 seats are divvied
up so that each district has the same number of people.
</P>
<P>
   For example, under the 1990 census allocation, each House
district had about 572,500 people. Because of population growth,
the average district size under the 2000 Census is expected to be
about 637,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The slowly growing states of New York, Pennsylvania,
Connecticut, Ohio, Illinois and Wisconsin are expected to lose
seats, while the faster growing Arizona, Texas, Georgia,
California, Nevada, Colorado and Florida are slated to pick up
seats.
</P>
<P>
   With the House now closely divided _ 222 Republicans, 212
Democrats and one independent _ every seat will count in the 2002
election, the first that will be held under the new map.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Texas, chair of IMPAC 2000, says the role
the redistricting gurus will play is ``very crucial'' although
their efforts are often under the radar screens of most voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The job is somewhat intangible,'' Bentsen says. ``This is the
subterranean election that you're not hearing about in 2000.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Davis, R-Va., who chairs the National Republican
Campaign Committee, says Republicans ``are in better shape then we
have been since the 1920s'' going into redistricting because the
GOP now has greater control in the states.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans control 31 governor's mansions, They control 48
state chambers, compared with 49 for Democrats. Two state houses _
the Washington House and the New Hampshire Senate are tied.
Nebraska only has one state chamber.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
