<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4325 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DIGITAL-DIVIDE-1210-C     12-09 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-DIVIDE-1210-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON SETS GOAL OF BRIDGING 'DIGITAL DIVIDE'
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON President Clinton called Thursday for a ``national
strategy for connecting all Americans to the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   After a Rose Garden speech, Clinton issued a memo directing the
heads of executive departments and agencies to work with the
private sector to make ``computers and the Internet accessible to
all Americans, with the goal of significantly narrowing the digital
divide.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House initiative came as Commerce Secretary William
Daley hosted a daylong meeting aimed at finding ways to increase
minority access to Information Age tools. It brought together
government officials with top communications executives, foundation
chiefs and community leaders, who engaged in a broad review of what
needs to be done to close a widening gap between haves and
have-nots in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted that he had planned to attend the conference
before deciding to go to Worcester, Mass., for memorial services
that honored six firefighters who had died in the line of duty.
</P>
<P>
   In the president's absence, Daley led a 13-member blue-ribbon
panel that, for the most part, approached the ``digital divide''
issue with an air of cautious optimism that positive changes can be
achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Panel members, however, noted continuing problems that stood in
the way of Clinton's professed goal, for which no firm timetable
has been set.
</P>
<P>
   They included fragmented and uncoordinated efforts in dealing
with Internet education issues in poor areas; computer-savvy
teachers being hired away for better-paid industry jobs;
impoverished school districts which lack public funds to train
their disadvantaged students in Internet skills, and a failure on
the part of many large firms to properly target the already hefty
online market potential of African-American and other minority
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know that places that have access to the Internet are
going to be growing faster than those that don't,'' said Zoe Baird,
president of the Markle Foundation, which has pledged to spend $100
million in the next three to five years to ensure that the Internet
meets public needs.
</P>
<P>
   But the real challenge, Baird added, is not only to raise access
to information technology but to offer truly appealing content.
``How can we use this tremendous vehicle,'' she asked, ``to deliver
information in ways that would energize people (and) engage people
to connect them to things that they really need in their daily
lives?''
</P>
<P>
   Following a similar tack, Michael Armstrong, chairman and chief
executive officer of AT&AMP;T Corp., predicted that broadband access to
the Internet, entering the home through affordable interactive
video services, could be the engine of progress that would reverse
the growing information gap within U.S. society.
</P>
<P>
   Most families, including minority ones, Armstrong suggested,
``will have a device at home called a television set that will
connect them with the rest of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Clinton announced that next spring he would join
Armstrong, Daley and other top conference figures on another of his
``New Markets'' tours _ one that will ``focus specifically on the
digital divide out in America.''
</P>
<P>
   His tour, Clinton said, would strike a balance between places
``that have not fully participated in our nation's economic
growth'' and an upbeat note: Publicizing public-private
partnerships that ``can unleash the power of the Internet to link
children and adults to a lifetime of learning, to provide access to
distant medical care, to empower parents, to assist job seekers, to
enhance safety and foster economic development.''
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, some of the key conference participants announced the
creation of an online ``Digital Divide Network'' to coordinate
their joint efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Besides AT&AMP;T, the initial partners include America Online, Bell
Atlantic, BellSouth, Gateway, Intel, iVillage, Microsoft and SBC
Communications. The Benton Foundation will manage the site and
oversee its content, in coordination with the National Urban
League.
</P>
<P>
   The new site may be found on the Web at
www.digitaldividenetwork.org.
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew J. Glass can be reached at andyg(at)coxnews.com).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
