<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4336 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      12-09 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WITNESS PROTECTION': PROTECTOR OR PROTECTED: WHICH IS WORSE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes appear at end of review. Time is for New
York area. Check local listings.) (dw) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to feel much sympathy for Bobby and Cindy Batton, the
central characters in ``Witness Protection.'' Bobby is a third-rate
weasel, a petty mobster who has profited handsomely from crime but
has greedily cheated his own bosses.
</P>
<P>
   When they catch on to his clumsy scheme and order him killed, he
decides to tell all to the feds to save his sorry skin. He
regularly lies to his wife, too, and neglects his children. Cindy
knows what line of work Bobby's in, but she chooses to look the
other way and enjoy the ill-gotten gains. These two deserve each
other, and they deserve whatever unpleasant comeuppance fate tosses
them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, their fate is tough. That's the nub of this film, which
has its premiere Saturday night on HBO. As the title telegraphs,
the Battons and their two children are to be given new identities
and relocated by the federal witness protection program after Bobby
agrees to testify against the first-rate weasel for whom he worked.
</P>
<P>
   The couple, played with riveting intensity by Tom Sizemore and
Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio, as well as their teen-age son, Sean
(Shawn Hatosy), and little daughter, Suzie (Skye McCole Bartusiak),
are spirited into a top-secret government compound, where they are
locked into a duplex apartment and observed via surveillance
cameras. They will live here for five days while they learn to
become new people, under the guidance of their eerily avuncular
tutor, a U.S. marshal named Steve Beck (Forest Whitaker).
</P>
<P>
   This process of forced metamorphosis is both fascinating and
frightening. The drama, while fictitious, comes with an aura of
authenticity. HBO says it was ``inspired by'' a 1996 article in The
New York Times Magazine by a freelance reporter, Robert Sabbag, who
shares credit for the film's story with the scriptwriter, Daniel
Therriault. Although the family described in the article was
different from the Battons in most respects, the wrenching process
is similar.
</P>
<P>
   The film's family has a lot to get used to, and not just new
names and some phony details of their past. Bobby, who is used to
giving orders, doesn't like being told he's going to Seattle, a
city he dislikes because of its rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You either roll with the program or you pack your bags and
leave,'' Steve tells him in his firm and friendly way. ``It's
rainin' whether you like it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   When this kind of persuasion doesn't seem to work, Steve has
boxes full of slides of people who have just met violent deaths:
headstrong dropouts from the government's little school.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to live?'' Steve asks, without waiting for an answer.
``Then embrace your family and learn how to live in the world
legally. Period.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby asks him, ``Why do you care?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care,'' Steve replies. ``It's my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby is a violent jerk, but Whitaker's Steve is the scariest
presence on display. Is he a warmhearted social worker, or is his
smile the frigid expression of a bureaucrat from hell? The film,
directed by Richard Pearce, never allows Steve to reveal the answer
to the Battons or the viewer.
</P>
<P>
   You do get to see what the Battons are made of as they start to
unravel under the pressure of their confinement and their
uncertainty about the future. ``I thought this would bring us
together,'' Cindy says, ``that we'd become a real family.'' Maybe
later. First they become increasingly angry, and all but the little
girl take that anger out on one another, often violently. The film
has a great deal of strong language.
</P>
<P>
   The four actors playing the Battons are convincing. Hatosy and
Ms. Bartusiak have the advantage of portraying innocent victims, so
they can rely on some sympathy from the viewer. Still, these two
young people give nuanced performances that hit a nerve. The adult
Battons, however, are at the story's center, and they are painted
as such venal people that their suffering is kept at a clinical
distance.
</P>
<P>
   You end up feeling like one of the marshals who monitor those
surveillance cameras. You're observing a destructive tragedy, but
it feels as if you're only doing your job.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WITNESS PROTECTION'
</P>
<P>
   At 9 p.m. ET Saturday on HBO
</P>
<P>
   Teleplay by Daniel Therriault, based on a story by him and
Robert Sabbag; Henry Schleiff, executive producer; Howard Meltzer,
producer; Tony Mark and Sue Jett, co-producers; directed by Richard
Pearce; Fred Murphy, cinematographer; Patrizia Van Brandenstein,
production designer; Lisa Fruchtman, editor; Bud McPherson,
technical adviser.
</P>
<P>
   With: Tom Sizemore (Bobby Batton), Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio
(Cindy Batton), Forest Whitaker (Steve Beck), Shawn Hatosy (Sean
Batton) and Skye McCole Bartusiak (Suzie Batton).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
