<HEADER>
A4338 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ROSS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      12-09 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WALLOWITCH AND ROSS: THIS MOMENT' _ 30 YEARS IN PUBLIC AND
PRIVATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes appear at the end of the review.) 
(dw) 
 BY STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Richard Morris' small, tender documentary film,
``Wallowitch and Ross: This Moment,'' peers into a cozy nook of New
York's cabaret world to pay homage to the partnership (personal and
professional) of the prolific songwriter John Wallowitch and his
companion of more 30 years, the dancer Bertram Ross.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, more than a decade after Ross left Martha Graham's
company, where he had been lead male dancer and Graham's male muse,
he and Wallowitch teamed up to create a jolly, informal cabaret act
that mixed Tin Pan Alley nuggets with Wallowitch's own witty
original songs.
</P>
<P>
   Portions of Morris' movie were filmed at a 1998 reunion
performance (attended by this writer) at the Ballroom, the
now-defunct New York club where the pair had made their
professional debut as a team 14 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Moment,'' which opens Saturday at Cinema Village, doesn't
explore the particulars of their relationship, nor are we given a
glimpse into their everyday domestic life on Manhattan's Upper East
Side. Instead the movie interweaves their separate biographies told
through photos, interviews and vintage film clips, then circles
back to their 1998 Ballroom performance.
</P>
<P>
   Artistically gifted in many areas, Ross grew up in Brooklyn and,
after dabbling in the visual arts, joined the Graham company in
1947. His descriptions of its inner workings and of the secretive
nature of its legendary founder are fascinating and a bit chilling.
</P>
<P>
   When he left the company after a blowup, the particulars of
which are not described, he became an important teacher of the
Graham style.
</P>
<P>
   Wallowitch, who was born in South Philadelphia, pursued a career
as a concert pianist while writing pop songs in the Tin Pan Alley
tradition of his idol, Irving Berlin. (Until Berlin's death, he
used to lead a caroling group that serenaded Berlin outside his
Beekman Place home every Christmas Eve.)
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Wallowitch reflects that his two musical lives
conflicted in a way that prevented him from ever writing a Broadway
show, but he doesn't tell us exactly how.
</P>
<P>
   Wallowitch has written more than 1,000 songs. Some are brash,
cheeky novelties like ``I Wish I Had Died at the Altar on the Day I
Married You.'' His best ballads, like the wistful ``My Love Went to
London'' (written when Ross went away on tour), ``This Moment'' and
``Come a Little Closer'' are pearls of homey observation about the
fragility and joy of life's happier moments.
</P>
<P>
   When he says quietly, ``Bertram is my life,'' it's clear that
many of those moments were spent together.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WALLOWITCH AND ROSS: This Moment'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Richard Morris; director of photography, Don Lenzer;
edited by Marsha Moore and Morris; produced by Roberta Morris
Purdee; released by First Run Features.
</P>
<P>
   With: John Wallowitch, Bertram Ross, Dixie Carter and Lynn
Lobban.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 87 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 1733EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4340 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV16-     12-09 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV16-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOOR FLAP PUTS PUBLIC IN PUBLIC ART 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Thursday, Dec. 16.) 
(lh) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ    
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is, of course, not your ordinary door. It's a piece of
sculpture in the shape of a door made out of concrete, weighing
3,000 pounds and lying on its back on a grassy berm. That makes it
art.
</P>
<P>
   The response to such a door depends on the imagination of the
person looking at it. The fact that it is slightly ajar might make
you shiver. Or it might make you smile. It might make you think of
time passing, the end of the century. Or a new one beginning. It's
a personal response, which also makes it art.
</P>
<P>
   The door has caused some flap in Sebastopol, a small town in
northern California. We have people as whipped up as they were in
New York City over a Virgin Mary painting at the Brooklyn Museum of
Art.
</P>
<P>
   The large white slab that looks like a door from a Victorian
house reposes next to the firehouse, across from a church and
kitty-corner from a grade school. It is where kids in yellow
raincoats and red boots meet a crossing guard to cross to go to
school. The setting could be a page in a Richard Scarry kids' book
of Americana with your church, your school, your fire trucks.
</P>
<P>
   But not every small town gets to have public art or artists who
can create it. Some towns have only golden arches for sculptures.
Some towns don't get to debate art. It's causing a wonderful fuss.
People here are reminded of Christo, the artist who came to Sonoma
and Marin counties in the 1970s and said he wanted to run a curtain
across pastures and meadows to the ocean. Some people squawked and
some people were charmed and Christo just took it all in,
explaining that the head-shakers and would-be censors are part of
the process of art.
</P>
<P>
   One of the artists on the collaborative piece in Sebastopol, Ron
Rodgers, said that when he first saw it lying there he worried,
``What if no one notices it?''
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. The unnamed piece has been called everything from
a door to Hades to evil to a creepy thing. Door-haters threw a tarp
over it, wrote letters to the newspapers, complained to City Hall,
badgered the Fire Department for allowing it on public property.
And whether they are compelled by the door or the controversy,
people keep coming by the carload to check it out.
</P>
<P>
   It's supposed to be there for a year, but it's already done what
art is supposed to do _ make people look, scratch their heads and
use their imaginations. Artists don't expect to please everyone.
People stand in line at the Louvre just to see the Mona Lisa and
walk off complaining, ``It's kind of small.''
</P>
<P>
   Towns with artists and art critics are lucky. There is no other
town but Sebastopol right now that has this particular door, and
people who disagree over whether it's a dumb door or a delightful
door or the devil's.
</P>
<P>
   Now it has turned into an evolving art form. After the censor's
tarp was removed someone put a harvest wreath on it, treating it
like a real door. Then someone put up the symbols for Ladies and
Gents and turned it into a restroom door. Artist Rodgers puzzled
over that one and then decided, ``That's clever. Someone sees it as
sleeping in the earth. The door is at rest. Hence, rest room.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently it wears a Christmas wreath, and there's a Santa
decoration beside it.
</P>
<P>
   Critics worry that a door into the earth scares children. But
that would only be if children are taught to fear what's
underground. And maybe it's not leading underground, anyhow, but
out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Why would children automatically fear what's in the earth?
Surely they know that's where tulips get their start. What if Alice
had run screaming from the rabbit hole instead of looking for
adventure?
</P>
<P>
   In this area about the only thing diabolical known to live in a
hole in the ground are gophers. If the artists could create a door
to lock out the gophers they would be popular with everyone. The
sculptors were surprised by the ferocity of their critics, but they
are enjoying the mixed response. Tom Montan said he was surprised
so many people read so much into it, but says it's a testament to
``the power of the ambiguous.''
</P>
<P>
   There is pressure on the City Council to move the piece to a
location where it won't be seen by people who worry about the
devil, but already there is a movement to save the door.
</P>
<P>
   Montan has heard from a group calling themselves Friends of the
Door. They promise to protest any move of the door by holding a
rally where they will play music by The Doors and carry door knobs
as a show of solidarity. They argue that if this door goes, whose
door will go next? Will all doors become suspect?
</P>
<P>
   How will we then know if we're coming or going?
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
