<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4345 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT &LR;      12-09 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PAIR OF WESTWARD JOURNEYS BY MOTHERS AND DAUGHTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUMBLEWEEDS
</P>
<P>
   Janet McTeer, Kimberly J. Brown, Jay O. Sanders, Gavin O'Connor
</P>
<P>
   Directed by O'Connor
</P>
<P>
   PG-13, 100 minutes
</P>
<P>
   One of two greatly similar films now in circulation (the other
being ``Anywhere but Here''), ``Tumbleweeds'' joins Mary Jo Walker
(Ms. McTeer) as she is bailing out of her umpteenth violently
abusive relationship. Shooing her 12-year-old daughter, Ava (Ms.
Brown), into a battered car, Mary Jo heads off vaguely toward
Arizona with a stop in Jefferson City, Mo., where she plans to
snare a man whom she knew in high school. ``Now he finally can have
me,'' she tells her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   A sweet young girl, Ava is appalled, but being deeply attached
to her mother she goes along as gamely as she can. When the
Missouri man is less than advertised, Mary Jo heads for California.
A lusty, good-looking woman with a roving eye, she is fond of
tossing clothing out the car window and yelling, ``Yahoo!'' Near
San Diego, they go swimming and take up housekeeping with Jack (
O'Connor), a conservative, bossy truck driver, and Mary Jo enchants
a school chum of Ava's. ``I love your life and your four marriages,
and I think it's so great,'' the girl exclaims.
</P>
<P>
   The resilient Ava blossoms and wins the role of Romeo in a
school play. Mary Jo drops Jack, and mother and daughter benefit
from a friendship with Dan ( Sanders), a worthy, kindly fellow.
Nevertheless, Mary Jo is itching to head for Arizona, the primary
reason being that she no longer has a boyfriend. But then Ava makes
a stand.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE: Domestic brawls include smashed dishes and a
threatened punch or two, though the men seem more laughable than
menacing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX: An intensely physical woman, Mary Jo is ready to erupt
around any man, but sexual situations are discreet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY: Quite a bit, but fitting given the people and the
stress they often are under. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-10: Older children in this bracket will relate to Ava,
but the film is a little too gamey for very young viewers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11-13: This is a hands-on mother-daughter relationship
between two people who totally and wildly love each other. Children
will be enticed, and, though parents may disagree, language and
sexual situations shouldn't be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14 AND UP: Many girls will be engaged, as will their
mothers.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   ANYWHERE BUT HERE
</P>
<P>
   Susan Sarandon, Natalie Portman, Eileen Ryan, Ray Baker, John
Diehl, Shawn Hatosy, Bonnie Bedelia
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Wayne Wang
</P>
<P>
   PG-13, 113 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Take ``Tumbleweeds,'' make the mother slightly more fragile and
the daughter much more mature, and you have ``Anywhere but Here.''
Ready for a change of men and scene, Adele August (Ms. Sarandon)
packs her 14-year-old daughter, Ann (Ms. Portman), in an old
Mercedes she can't afford and vacates home in Bay City, Wis., for
what she presumes will be a larger, more exciting existence in
Beverly Hills, Calif. Out there, or so the narcissistic Adele
supposes, she and Ann will suddenly be visited by a rosier reality.
</P>
<P>
   Ann, miserable about leaving home and skeptical of her mother's
judgment, has a clearer view. ``You're a crazy, unemployed
middle-aged schoolteacher with a child to support,'' she tells her
mother after life hasn't proved particularly elevating in Los
Angeles. By then the manically impulsive Adele has tired of her job
as a speech pathologist and been badly burned by a smirking
womanizer she meets at the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Being the more adult of the two, Ann hunkers down over the next
couple of years and makes the best of a painful and often chaotic
situation by building solid friendships at school and doing well
enough academically to get into Brown University with a financial
package that is almosate to allow her to attend in the fall.
Almost.
</P>
<P>
   Adele, clinging to her daughter in childish desperation, uses
the expense issue to rule out Ann's getting away from her by going
East. In the end, though, even Adele tries growing up.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE: None.
</P>
<P>
   SEX: Adele gushingly tells the long-suffering Ann about her
experience in bed with her friend from the beach. Ann undertakes
some gentle sexual exploration with a schoolmate, though nothing is
explicit.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY: The usual run of profanity, but not excessive.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTNOTE: It's interesting to watch Ann, who is older and much
less dependent on her mother than Ava is in ``Tumbleweeds,'' try to
sustain a woman who in many ways is more of a child than she is.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-10: No.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11-13: Ms. Portman makes an appealing, competent heroine,
and by this age viewers will be caught up in her problems.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14 AND UP: Many older teenagers will also relate to Ms.
Portman and the scenario.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   LIBERTY HEIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   Adrien Brody, Bebe Neuwirth, Joe Mantegna, Ben Foster, Justin
Chambers, Orlando Jones, Rebekah Johnson
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Barry Levinson
</P>
<P>
   R, 134 minutes
</P>
<P>
   In another of his Baltimore films, Levinson goes back to the
'50s for a story of growing up Jewish in a time and place that
played hob with pat notions of ethnicity. ``Get ready, folks, Jews
are coming,'' says someone in a carload of Jewish youths arriving
at a high school party full of people fresh from a country club
with a sign at the entrance reading ``No Jews, dogs or coloreds
allowed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben (Foster), a smart, cool Jewish boy who dresses up like
Hitler for Halloween just to see the reaction, and his older
brother Van (Brody) take their chances in a rapidly emerging
multicultural society. In one very nice development, and a
horrifying one to their parents, Ben begins a chaste but sexually
loaded friendship with Sylvia (Ms. Johnson), an equally bright
middle-class black girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just kill me now,'' says Ada (Ms. Neuwirth), Ben and Van's
mother, at news of her sons' interethnic adventures. Their father,
Nate (Mantegna), runs a burlesque house and a numbers business,
which provide well for the family until a black drug dealer, Little
Melvin (Jones), hits a bonus bet that wipes Nate out and leads to
criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   But Nate remains ever the gentleman and devoted husband and
father. And through these people an era comes delightfully alive.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE: There is a fist fight, and Little Melvin waves a gun
around after kidnapping Ben and Sylvia.
</P>
<P>
   SEX: Some situations, none graphic, many references, and flashes
of nudity at the burlesque house.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY: Obscenities fly now and then, but they are never
gratuitous.
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 10: Not a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11-13: For all the '50s motif, these are characters for any
era. Many '90s children will thoroughly enjoy this film, but
parents could well object.
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14 AND UP: This is one R-rated film that should get a clean
bill of health.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
