<P>
   FLA-DEATHPENALTY _ Florida lawmakers have called a special
legislative session on the state's death penalty. Foes are gleeful,
saying any attempts by lawmakers to change the rules will lead to
more appeals and ultimately may mean there might not be any more
executions in the state for years. (Date, Palm Beach Post). 18-20.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANES _ The number and intensity of Atlantic storms will
ease next year, but not by much, according to professor William
Gray and his colleagues at Colorado State University in Fort
Collins. In their annual forecast, released Wednesday, they are
predicting a ``moderate'' season in 2000 with 11 named storms,
seven hurricanes and three intense hurricanes. Gray said the
residents along the U.S. Atlantic Coast, including Florida, have a
45 percent chance of being hit by one or more major storms with
winds above 100 mph. (Kleinberg, Palm Beach Post). 8. WITH CHART.
</P>
<P>
   BIBLE-SCHOOLS _ FORT MYERS, Fla._One of the first schools to
propose teaching the Bible as history is in this coastal Florida
community. We visit for an update on the debate and lawsuits the
issue has spawned. (Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
MOVEDSCIENCE/HEALTH
</P>
<P>
   CDC-HIV _ ATLANTA _The CDC Thursday recommended that states
begin tracking people infected with HIV by name, in an effort to
follow the progress of the AIDS epidemic. The federal agency has
long recommended that HIV patients be identified - though not by
name - so officials can track new cases and target prevention
efforts. But new guidelines issued by the CDC call for new
name-based reporting guidelines in all 50 states - an approach that
has been harshly criticized by advocates for people with AIDS, who
say it could compromise medical privacy. (Guthrie, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH _ AUSTIN _George W. Bush campaigns in New Hampshire as new
poll shows him running second to McCain in the crucial early state.
Also today, McCain announces he is suing New York GOP to force it
to loosen up rules that make it real hard to get on primary ballot
statewide. (Heath, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-SOUTH _ WASHINGTON _ If Al Gore wins the Democratic
presidential nomination, it will be because of the South. The Old
Confederacy is his ace in the hole should he stumble in the early
voting in Iowa and New Hampshire. As a consequence, he rarely lets
a week pass without tending to his Southern political supporters _
and especially African Americans. For example, he'll be in Atlanta
this weekend for a meeting with black voters before heading to
Orlando for the Florida state Democratic convention. (Shepard, Cox
News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
