   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SYRIA _ JERUSALEM _ For decades, Syria has been the
Doctor No of Middle East peace, lambasting Egypt for making peace
and firmly maintaining its state of war against Israel. But, by
Thursday morning, Tel Aviv law clerk Odelia Arad, 28, could
seriously state that she hopes to someday ``eat hummos in
Damascus.'' ``I would like to see the place. It is right next
door,'' Arad said. Though attempts at bringing a peace between
Syria and Israel have ended in failure before, this week's
announcement that talks will begin again in Washington next week
raised hopes that one of the toughest obstacles to peace in the
Middle East could finally be removed. We look at key issues,
reaction in Israel and Syria, and what may have lead to the
breakthrough. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 4 p.m. EST.
