<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4354 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-WALKER-COLUMN12-COX     12-09 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Honoring the faith, spirit of Guadalupe
 &HT;    By Ana Pecina Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ On Dec. 12, a substantial number of area
residents will mark one of the most important days of their year.
</P>
<P>
   The larger community may well be unaware of it and that is a sad
thing because it's one of the happiest days for Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   It is the day of the Guadalupes. Most folks in Texas know
someone named Guadalupe. Maybe they're called Lupe or Lupita, if
it's a girl or a woman. But many men carry the moniker, probably
the most common in the Mexican community. It's my first name.
</P>
<P>
   The Fiesta de la Virgen Guadalupe is akin to St. Patrick's Day.
On Dec. 12, all who have even the slightest connection to Mexico
celebrate Guadalupe's day. The event is an official feast day in
the Catholic Church but on the day when ``La Virgen'' is honored,
Mexican people of all faiths claim her.
</P>
<P>
   Her story begins in 1531 in the mountains near Tepeyac, close to
what is now Mexico City. It was a few years after Columbus came to
America and the indigenous people were confused and frightened by
the European invaders that had come to their land. Juan Diego, one
of those native people, saw a beautiful lady one day as he went to
visit his sick uncle. The lady spoke to him and directed him to go
to the bishop and have him build a shrine on the spot in her honor.
She had come to claim the New World and become the caretaker of its
people in the name of Her Son, she declared to him.
</P>
<P>
   The awed young peasant delivered the message several times but
was ridiculed then challenged to bring some proof of this beautiful
lady that he claimed had dark skin like his and a voice like music.
Her clothing was like the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he brought the bishop proof: fragrant Castilian
roses. The blooms cascaded from Juan Diego's tilma, his cloak, as
he presented it to the churchman on that winter day. He had picked
the flowers at the lady's direction, he explained, fresh from the
spot where she had told him they would be.
</P>
<P>
   As the roses spilled out of the tilma, an image of the
dark-skinned lady, La Morenita, was imprinted on the poor man's
cloak. It was neither painted nor drawn on. Nor was it embroidered
there. It just was.
</P>
<P>
   The bishop was convinced. The original basilica of Our Lady of
Guadalupe still stands in the former lake bed outside Mexico City.
Because some years ago the massive structure began sinking into the
soft ground, the thousands who make pilgrimages there are no longer
allowed in for safety reasons. A new basilica was built just a few
yards away from the original and there hangs Juan Diego's cloak
bearing the image for the ``Guadalupanos,'' her devotees, to see.
</P>
<P>
   The devotion she commands is awe inspiring. On any day you can
see bands of pilgrims making their way to the shrine, some on their
knees.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, I bought a book, based on a doctoral
dissertation on Our Lady of Guadalupe's relevance to Mexican
American women in today's American society. The author examines how
Guadalupe's lessons on service, humility and obedience fit into a
society that values assertiveness, self-sufficiency and power.
</P>
<P>
   After pondering that question and the way I was taught as a
young child to revere this icon, then looking at my life today, I
realize the true power such a messenger holds.
</P>
<P>
   Look at her story. It's one of faith, mission, organization,
leadership and getting the job done.
</P>
<P>
   After all, how many women do you know who have the chutzpah to
drop in on a bishop a few days before Christmas and start ordering
him around?
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, me too.
</P>
<P>
   Guadalupe Ana Pecina Walker is managing editor of the Longview
News-Journal. E-mail: awalker(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
