<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Dec. 10, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Large ocean swells were detected Thursday by an offshore buoy
near Los Angeles, prompting heavy surf advisories for parts of the
southern California coast. Heavy surf will prevail Friday as gusty
winds from the northwest develop in the wake of a low pressure
system heading toward the southern Rockies. Winds across southern
California will shift later Friday and Friday evening, blowing from
the north-northeast and thereby helping to import chillier air into
the region. Across middle sections of the Central Valley, winds
will slacken Friday night, raising the possibility of frost.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the disturbance that spawned severe weather Thursday
across the western Gulf states will weaken as it approaches the
central Appalachians and Ohio Valley. As a result, isolated
thunderstorms will develop early Friday. But, given that the system
will steadily weaken, the risk of thunder will diminish east of the
Appalachians across the Virginias and Carolinas by Friday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Areas of rain will develop across the eastern Great Lakes and
western New England states as a potent jet stream disturbance
approaches from the upper Great Lakes. Along the New England
Seaboard, early sun will give way to increasing clouds, but the
arrival of rain will wait until Friday night. By Saturday morning,
the arriving jet stream disturbance will foster a deep low pressure
system over the Gulf of Maine. In its wake, chilly winds from the
northwest will increase to speeds of 20 mph to 30 mph, while rain
will change to snow across northern New England.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: SEVERE STORMS
</P>
<P>
   Severe thunderstorms rumbled across the western Gulf states
Thursday as a potent jet stream disturbance marking a pool of cold
air aloft arrived from the Rockies. In late autumn, evaporation
rates over the Gulf of Mexico subside as water temperatures lower
with the season, lessening the amount of available moisture in the
air. Moreover, with the sun lowering in the sky, surface
temperatures decrease. To compensate for the lack of surface warmth
and moisture that destabilize the atmosphere, a potent disturbance
must provide exceptional cooling aloft to spark severe weather in
December.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
