<HEADER>
A4360 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-RANGERS-RICHTER-N     12-09 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-RICHTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICHTER PUNCHES HIS WAY OUT OF SLUMP 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Before the season, Mike Richter, the Rangers' goalie,
predicted one negative effect of the new rule regarding the goal
crease. Goals would no longer be disallowed when video review
showed the skate of an attacker in the blue paint ahead of the
puck. This would mean trouble, Richter said then.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going to be driving in and out of the crease and
actually hitting you,'' Richter said. ``There's going to be a lot
more disputes. You are vulnerable when you are looking at the puck
and you get blind-sided.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, in a 2-1 Rangers victory in overtime over
Edmonton at Madison Square Garden, Richter and Aleksander Selivanov
of the Oilers presented Exhibit A of this theory. While driving to
the net late in the third period, Selivanov was cross-checked in
the head by Mathieu Schneider, a Rangers defenseman. As he tumbled
toward the net, Selivanov crashed into Richter, knocking the goalie
over before banging into a goal post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have lot of sympathy for him,'' Richter said of
Selivanov. ``He jumped right on top of me.''
</P>
<P>
   So Richter jumped up and began to throw punches at the body of
the prone Oiler, swinging his right arm covered with his big
blocking glove. Players for both sides entered the scrum, and
Richter finally emerged with his helmet and face mask off, his hair
mussed and the back of his shirt pulled up toward the top of his
suspenders.
</P>
<P>
   Richter got only a two-minute roughing penalty. The scene was
memorable for fans of the usually mild-mannered goalie, a senior
Ranger, who joined the team in 1989 and is now 33 years old.
Richter joked that he ``had a few wires crossed,'' but then turned
serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times when forwards take advantage of the goalie,''
Richter said. ``They head to the net, without any regard for the
goalie at all, in fact, trying to take him out. It's happened
enough. The refs can't always call it and certainly haven't been.
You're just vulnerable as a goalie. I think the goalie should have
the leeway to swing back.''
</P>
<P>
   This fracas overshadowed a splendid effort, Richter's best of
the season, the sort he presented in 1994, when he led the Rangers
to the Stanley Cup, and in 1996, when he led the United States to
the championship of the World Cup tournament. Richter made 37
saves, two of them on breakaways, several more on shots from
point-blank range.
</P>
<P>
   He played patiently and alertly inside the crease, remaining
upright most of the time and moving quickly from post to post.
Richter has given up only six goals in the last four games and the
Rangers are 3-0-1, their best stretch of the season, with two of
those victories in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Their record of 10-14-4-1 still puts them in the bottom third of
the 28-team league, but their hope now is that the second quarter
of the schedule will be better than the first. The fans are
chanting Richter's name, which is better than some things they were
chanting earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's trying to kind of renew and start off on a
different foot and try to forget what just happened,'' Richter said
of the 2-9-2 slump that preceded the current streak. ``That's the
hard part. You can get negative. I think we all realized in the
last little while we had to start fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our emotion is definitely more positive than it was. Our
discipline is much better. Our intensity doesn't seem to wane as
much as it did. We're not doing everything right. We can play
better. But we're giving ourselves a chance to win. It's a heck of
a lot more enjoyable to be around.''
</P>
<P>
   As for stopping breakaways against Todd Marchant and Doug
Weight, Richter praised his defensemen for chasing down the racing
forwards and forcing them to shoot quickly without many options.
Regarding his tussle with Selivanov, Richter said his last fight
was in the fourth grade. He threw a half-dozen punches Wednesday.
Did they connect?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Richter said, speculating that he probably hit
two teammates, the referee, the goal post and the ice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
