u i BC-BRITISH-FRANCE-BEEF-5     12-09 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITISH-FRANCE-BEEF-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE REFUSES TO LIFT BRITISH BEEF BAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SARAH LYALL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Britain reacted with fury Thursday to France's surprise
announcement that because of continued fears over so-called mad-cow
disease, it would not, after all, lift its ban on British beef.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their action is completely and totally unjustified,'' Prime
Minister Tony Blair said, warning that he would raise the issue
when he meets the French prime minister, Lionel Jospin, at a
European Union summit meeting Friday in Helsinki, Finland.
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission, the union's governing body, said it had
no choice but to begin legal proceedings against France in an
effort to force it to lift the ban, as the commission has ordered.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the circumstances, there seems to be no alternative but to
proceed with legal action against France in the European Court of
Justice as soon as possible,'' said David Byrne, the European
Union's food safety commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   The commission gave notice last month that it intended to take
France to court if the ban was not lifted, and after weeks of talks
it appeared that France was ready to begin accepting British beef
again.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday the French food safety agency refused to
declare British beef safe from the risk of mad-cow disease, which
causes a wasting of the brain, and Jospin said he would maintain
the ban out of concern for the health of his country's citizens.
</P>
<P>
   France's decision, in defiance of a European Commission ruling
that British beef is safe, was seized by the British government's
political opponents as an embarrassing blow to Blair's efforts to
resolve the dispute through diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much longer must Britain tolerate the humiliating
spectacle of our prime minister dancing like a puppet to Mr.
Jospin's tune?'' asked Tim Yeo, the Conservative member of
Parliament who serves as his party's agriculture spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Blair's position was not helped by the headlines in some
newspapers Thursday. ``Beef: Now It's Humiliation,'' the
influential Daily Mail, which blows hot and cold in its support of
the government, said on its front page.
</P>
<P>
   In a raucous scene in the House of Commons Thursday, Tory
members of Parliament all but drowned out the agriculture
commissioner, Nick Brown, with cries of ``Resign!'' as he rose to
give a statement on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But the government maintained that its ``softly, softly'' policy
had been the correct one, and that it should not be blamed for
France's intransigence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they do need to be reminded that the EU is not like
some sort of Woolworth's pick-and-mix counter where they can choose
some regulations that they agree with and others that they don't,''
Stephen Byers, the trade and industry secretary, said of the
French.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Gill, president of the National Farmers Union, urged Britons
to boycott French goods in retaliation, a tactic Blair has opposed
to prevent the dispute from turning into a full-scale trade war
between two countries that rely heavily on trade with each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would urge consumers to think very carefully when they go
shopping before they buy any French produce and to buy British
instead,'' Gill told reporters Thursday morning. ``We have to send
a very clear message to the French government about what the
British people think of their action.''
</P>
<P>
   Previous calls for a British boycott have not been particularly
successful, although Brown, the agriculture minister, has said he
will not buy French products until the ban is lifted.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some supermarket chains have made cosmetic concessions to
anti-French sentiment by, for instance, more clearly marking what
country food comes from. One chain, Somerfield, has stopped selling
French apples. Another, Asda, announced Thursday it would stop
buying Charlotte potatoes from France, and buy British ones
instead.
</P>
<P>
   Sainsbury's, one of the largest supermarket chains, said that it
had seen no decline in demand for French products and that it had
no plans to remove any. ``We feel it is up to the customer to
decide what they want to buy, and if they want to boycott French
products, that is their choice,'' a spokesman for Sainsbury's said.
</P>
<P>
   In France, officials defended the decision not to lift the ban,
saying consumer safety was their most important consideration. ``If
the British react badly to this, as we fear, then it will be very
damaging for Anglo-French relations and will prevent discussions on
the fundamental issues,'' said Jean Glavany, the agriculture
minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
