<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4364 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-BERMUDATOUR12-COX     12-09 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERMUDATOUR12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hiking just one way to discover Bermuda's beauty
 &HT;    Eds: Emabargoed for Sunday, Dec. 12.
 &HT;    By James D. Smith
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAILEY'S BAY, Bermuda _ Thank goodness for government
boondoggles. Otherwise, Bermuda might not have one of its most
visitor-friendly attractions: the Railway Trail.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one miles of scenic right-of-way is all that's left of
the Bermuda Railway, which operated for only 17 years after earning
the dubious distinction of being the most expensive railway, per
mile, ever built.
</P>
<P>
   After the government sold off the rolling stock and tracks, the
right-of-way property was turned into a series of scenic trails
that provide ideal paths for bicyclists and hikers. Though cars are
not allowed, motor bikes are permitted on portions.
</P>
<P>
   The trail is divided into seven sections. A handy walking guide,
available at most hotels and other tourist sites, provides detailed
maps and commentary on sights along the way.
</P>
<P>
   My wife and I walked the 1.75-mile section from Somerset Bridge
to the bus station in Somerset, stopping off at Scaur Hill Fort
Park and enjoying the scenic panorama from its heights.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, we were greeted by teenagers sneaking smokes on
the way home after school, and we stopped to chat with farm workers
harvesting potatoes in a field. We got to see where Bermudians work
and live, close up, which was a far cry from the confines of the
beach resort where we were staying.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day we had taken a bus to the Bermuda Triangle
Brewery, where we sampled fresh beers direct from the tap, assisted
by a chatty local resident who filled in for the busy brewmeister.
</P>
<P>
   After visiting the brewery, our plan had been to catch the ferry
at Somerset Bridge back to the capital city of Hamilton. But when
we missed the boat by a couple of minutes, we set our feet to the
Railway Trail and discovered the best way to take in this small
island nation, which consists of more than 180 named islands and
islets, only 20 of which are inhabited.
</P>
<P>
   Since rental cars are not allowed, it's good that the largest
island, Bermuda, which also gives its name to this tidy little
nation of small towns and parishes (local governmental divisions
similar to counties), measures about 22 miles east to west and is
rarely more than a mile wide. The public bus and ferry system
travels to all the main attractions. Bicycles, motor scooters,
taxis and walking are other popular ways to get around.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Gert, which brushed Bermuda in September with 110-mph
winds, washed away three miles of its famed Pink Beach and damaged
the Natural Arches on the island's south shore. Otherwise, damage
was limited to downed trees, some localized flooding and power
outages _ nothing permanent.
</P>
<P>
   Other sights worth taking in include:
</P>
<P>
   Bermuda Arts Centre, Dockyard: Meet local artists who ply their
crafts while showcasing their work. Paintings, photographs and
sculpture, as well as jewelry, scarves and quilts are available.
The glass artists are fun to watch. 10 a.m.-5 p.m. daily. Free.
441-234-2809.
</P>
<P>
   Bermuda Historical Society Museum, Hamilton: Par-la-Ville, a
house completed in 1814, abuts a beautiful downtown park of the
same name, originally laid out by the Perot family (apparently no
relation to America's Ross Perot) as its private garden. Cozy
exhibition rooms contain artifacts, including 18th-century Bermuda
cedar furniture that you can examine up close. The living room
retains the original pine flooring imported from the Carolinas.
9:30 a.m.-3:30 p.m. weekdays. Free. 441-295-2487.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal Caves: Caves are not the first things that come to mind
when you think of Bermuda, but there are several, concentrated in
the Bailey's Bay area of Hamilton Parish. Crystal Caves is a
commercial enterprise, complete with walkways, lighting and a
souvenir shop. Several smaller caves, including two at Grotto Bay
Beach Resort and others at Blue Hole Park, are free and open to the
public. 441-293-0640.
</P>
<P>
   Bermuda Government Ferry Service: Boats depart several times
daily from the ferry terminal in Hamilton. We took the
Hamilton-Somerset-Dockyard route ($7.50 round trip, included in our
travel pass) for a waterfront view of the pastel cottages and
buildings that dot the islands like strands of colorful beads. On
the trip back to Hamilton, we learned that our captain was making
his last voyage before retirement. The boat rocked (and veered
slightly off course) as his retirement party took place in the
wheelhouse. 441-295-4506.
</P>
<P>
   Somerset Bridge: Billed as the world's smallest drawbridge, the
32-inch center plank is opened by hand _ just wide enough to allow
a sailboat's mast to pass through. You can see it from the ferry,
which docks nearby at a wharf on the southern end of Somerset
Island in Sandys Parish.
</P>
<P>
   Spittal Pond: Sixty-acre nature park with walking paths and
scenic views of rocky ocean coastline. Twenty-five species of
waterfowl reside here during the winter. Smith's Parish. Open
daily, dawn to dusk. Free.
</P>
<P>
   St. Peter's Church, St. George: A church has existed on this
site continuously since 1620, allowing it to make the claim of
being the oldest Protestant church in the New World. Sited
impressively on a rise above the town's harbor, the pastel gray
with white trim structure contains numerous items of historical
importance, including a complete William of Orange communion set
from 1697. Graveyards to the rear and sides of the church contain
the remains of some of the island's early prominent families as
well as their slaves. Also buried here, with little fanfare: island
governor Sir Richard Sharples and his top aide, Capt. Hugh Sayers,
both slain in 1973 in Bermuda's only notable case of civil unrest.
The killer, Buck Burrows, was hanged in 1977. 441-297-8359
</P>
<P>
   Unfinished church, St. George: A five-minute walk from St.
Peter's takes you to the skeletal stone and mortar remains of a
church begun in 1864 as a replacement for St. Peter's. But a schism
developed in the congregation and eventually the project was
abandoned. The Bermuda National Trust is working to preserve the
remains.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Fly to Bermuda on a sale fare of $269 round
trip with a 14-day advance purchase. Delta offers one daily
nonstop; connecting service is available on American, Continental,
Northwest and USAirways. Travel must be complete by Feb. 17.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Grotto Bay Beach Resort information: Off-season (Nov. 1-Dec.
26 and Jan. 4-April 12) rooms are $94-$99 per night. From April 13
to Oct. 31, $199-$240 per night. You can add breakfast for $15 per
person per day or breakfast and dinner for $48 per person per day.
The all-inclusive plan, which includes three meals a day, bus
passes, taxes, tips, etc., is $230-$240 per person per day during
peak season; $145 per person per day during the off season. Other
plans can be found at www
</P>
<P>
   .netlinkbermuda.com/grottobay/. 441-293-8333.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Bermuda Department of Tourism, 1-800-223-6106.
Good Web sites are www.bermuda-best.com and www.bermudatourism.org.
</P>
<P>
   James D. Smith writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 1800EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4365 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-DUNCAN12-COX     12-09 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUNCAN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-bodyguard goes distance for `Green Mile' role
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 12.
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The biggest new star in Hollywood got there the old-fashioned
way. No acting school. No waiting tables. Not one stage appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Clarke Duncan, former ditch digger and bodyguard, stands
before you now, bigger than life, as Tom Hanks' co-star in ``The
Green Mile,'' and _ at 6-foot-5 and roughly 300 pounds _ this movie
season's Next Big Thing for one simple gonna-make-you-cry reason:
Mama told him to go do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother _ Jean Duncan _ taught me everything,'' Duncan, 36,
says, sitting in the Ritz-Carlton Atlanta during a recent visit
here. ``She loved movies. She had me reading at an actor's pace in
elementary school. I couldn't just read `See Tom run,' I had to
read it as `See! Tom! Run! Run, Tom! Run!' My mother said that's
called reading with feeling. She said, `When you get to Hollywood,
you're going to read scripts like that.'''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan earlier portrayed the leather-wearing, Harley-riding Bear
in ``Armageddon.'' In ``The Green Mile,'' which opened Friday, he
plays John Coffey, a mysterious 7-foot behemoth _ he's big but he's
also afraid of the dark _ sentenced to death row in 1935. Hanks
plays the prison guard who witnesses Coffey's mystical powers and
slowly begins to believe in his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of supporting role Oscar voters have a history of
lapping up. Harold Russell, a disabled World War II veteran who'd
never acted before, won an Academy Award for ``The Best Years of
Our Lives.'' So did the late Haing S. Ngor, a Cambodian who escaped
Pol Pot's regime and starred in ``The Killing Fields.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan has already been nominated for an NAACP Image Award for
``The Green Mile.'' And some are predicting a supporting actor
Oscar showdown between the big, burly Duncan and wee Haley Joel
Osment, the kid who whispers, ``I see ghosts,'' in the box-office
hit ``The Sixth Sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan whispers, too. Like his character Coffey, the actor has a
bull's appearance, but often speaks with a kitten's mew.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a kid I related to John Coffey,'' Duncan says. ``I didn't
have a whole lot of friends growing up, and I was the big guy in
class. Kids picked on me a lot, and I was very sensitive. I was
always getting beat up so I stayed away from groups of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up on Chicago's South Side, Duncan quit school but he
says he later earned a GED and attended Kankakee Community College
and Alcorn State University in Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   He worked as a ditch digger in Chicago for two years and took
various security jobs before becoming the bodyguard of the producer
of the traveling theatrical show ``Beauty Shop, Part 2.'' Later, he
went to Hollywood and was working as a bodyguard when Ice Cube
offered him a role as an extra in 1995's ``Friday.'' That led to
roles in ``A Night at the Roxbury,'' ``The Players Club,''
``Bullworth'' and, ultimately, ``Armageddon'' with Bruce Willis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were doing `Armageddon' and Bruce says to me, `Michael,
I've got the role of a lifetime for you.''' It was ``The Green
Mile.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Go buy the novel and prepare,''' Duncan says. ```Get
inside this guy. You're going to audition. I know you can do
this.'''
</P>
<P>
   After landing the part, one surprise was not getting to work
out. As a bodyguard, Duncan had amassed 22-inch arms but was still
considered too small for the role. ``Green Mile'' director Frank
Darabont ``wanted me to gain weight, but he wanted it to be a more
natural look.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan also had to learn to share screen time with the movie's
smallest character _ a remarkable little mouse named Mr. Jingles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved working with the little mouse,'' Duncan says. ``It was
so nice and sweet. He would come up your shoulder and he could run
from my hand to (co-star) Michael Jeter's hand. I let him go one
time and he went running and went halfway and turned around and
came back to me. And I'm like, `You don't want to be away from me,
do you?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Either that, or Mr. Jingles knows where the spotlight's going to
shine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Green Mile''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Tom Hanks, Michael Clarke Duncan. Rated R for violence,
language and some sex-related material. 3 hours, 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A manipulative but absorbing and deeply satisfying
adaptation of Stephen King's prison novel.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
