<HEADER>
A4369 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-BERMUDA12-COX     12-09 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BERMUDA12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An independent traveler loose in the land of the all-inclusive
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Dec. 12.
 &HT;    By James D. Smith
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAILEY'S BAY, Bermuda _ The coral blue of the Atlantic sparkled
on the horizon, a perfect backdrop for my icy green margarita with
its bright red cherry. Beach music drifted in on the sea breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Spending a week at the Grotto Bay Beach Resort in this
picturesque British dependency was supposed to ensure I didn't have
to fret the small stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Everything _ airfare, airport transfers, room, meals, poolside
drinks, even those pesky gratuities _ had been rolled up into one
convenient all-inclusive tab. All I had to do was kick back and
relax.
</P>
<P>
   That should have been easy at this sprawling 21-acre hillside
resort of pastel lodges overlooking its own slice of beach. In
addition to offering afternoon tea, bingo, croquet, tennis,
boating, snorkeling and swimming, the resort even threw in its own
underground caverns for exploration or swimming.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, Pat, thought this was a perfectly fine way to spend a
vacation _ languishing in the lap of luxury and not lifting a
finger. ``Every vacation doesn't have to be an adventure,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   So why wasn't I having fun?
</P>
<P>
   For starters, my usual style of travel is to jump on an airfare
bargain and make up an itinerary as it happens. That's how we wound
up exploring the ruins of Machu Picchu the previous summer: Cheap
seats to Lima and suddenly I was asking, ``What the heck is in
Peru?''
</P>
<P>
   So, being a frugal traveler, there was the nagging suspicion
that I had probably paid too much for the convenience of having
someone else put all the pieces together.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed for time _ the usual demands of work, plus a house on
the market and a job change looming for Pat _ we went for a
vacation ``off the shelf.''
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the horror stories we had heard about triple-digit
dinners for two at not-necessarily-special restaurants in Bermuda,
and the lure of locking in our costs became more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help matters much, therefore, when I later discovered
room rates on the Web that apparently beat those in our package.
And it added insult to injury when airfares to Bermuda went on sale
shortly before our departure.
</P>
<P>
   But we had opted for the security of knowing that everything was
taken care of and that we wouldn't be in for major financial
surprises.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger problem, however, was that after a couple of days at
poolside, I felt tied down.
</P>
<P>
   For me, going the all-inclusive route was like dining at an
all-you-can-eat buffet: To get your money's worth, you had to hang
out near the food tables and be ready to pounce when new items were
brought out. It's all about quantity, not necessarily quality.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking was the sense of accomplishment we had felt from
discovering a quiet neighborhood cafe on a snowy street in Vienna,
Austria, over Valentine's weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Dining night after night in the same surroundings got old fast _
even though we didn't have to sit at the same table with the same
tablemates as you might do on a cruise. It didn't help that the
staff at Grotto Bay did a masterful job of varying the menu. It was
still the same setting, the same faces.
</P>
<P>
   Though our resort wasn't a gated compound, it was located far
enough from the towns of St. George and Hamilton that casual
contact with locals, other than resort staff, was unlikely. And,
from the mostly American channels on the room TVs to the absence of
local newspapers in the gift shop, the intent seemed to be more at
helping visiting Americans ``feel at home'' than giving us a feel
for Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, it felt much more like being in Florida than in a
separate country with its own history and culture. I itched to get
out, to explore.
</P>
<P>
   By our third day, we were using our Bermuda bus passes (included
in the package) and venturing out on day trips. Although the
resort's luncheon fare was average at best (hot dogs, hamburgers,
chicken nuggets, fish sandwiches or tossed salads _ which Pat
thought were quite good), it irritated me that we were paying extra
whenever we ate meals elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   We also missed out on many of the ``free'' activities that were
part of resort life: nature walks, feeding the fish, volleyball and
shuffleboard competitions. But these were all items that we could
just as easily have done on our own at our own convenience.
</P>
<P>
   An added complication in Bermuda is that you can't rent a car,
which means you have to rely on public transit, taxis or motor
scooters for getting around. Since bus passes were included in our
package, I certainly wasn't about to pay extra for scooters (they
didn't seem a particularly safe mode of transit, either) or taxis.
</P>
<P>
   So, the next time I'm tempted by the lure of an
``all-inclusive'' resort, I'll explore other options. For example,
some resorts offer plans of one, two or three meals a day that
don't lock you into doing all your dining at one site.
</P>
<P>
   Another twist is a dinner plan that allows you to sample the
cuisine at other participating resorts. At least that way, you're
not looking at the same decor and dining companions for your entire
stay.
</P>
<P>
   However, there was one aspect of having spent a week at an
all-inclusive resort that I thoroughly enjoyed: checkout.
</P>
<P>
   There was no tab to tally, no scrutinizing the bill, no pulling
out a calculator to verify that everything added up just right.
</P>
<P>
   Just a smile and a ``hope you enjoyed your stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, that's something to write home about.
</P>
<P>
   James D. Smith writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
