<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4370 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-DATELINE-KUMASI10-COX     12-09 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DATELINE-KUMASI10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia girl finds Ghana liberating
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUMASI, Ghana _ Amid the jumble and clutter of Kumasi, Ghana's
second-largest city, and far, far from the trim lawns of Marietta,
Ga., Anna Mozley feels free.
</P>
<P>
   Anna is 10, the same age as my daughter Jennifer, and Jennie and
Anna used to be best friends. For five years Anna lived in
Marietta, three houses down the hill from us.
</P>
<P>
   Battleview is a clean and quiet neighborhood, orderly and
suburban, bordering the trails and fields of Kennesaw Mountain
National Battlefield Park. Anna and Jennie attended the same
school. Jennie played at Anna's house all the time, and Anna spent
a lot of time at our house, too.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in August, Anna's parents, Mike and Claire, moved to Ghana
to work as missionaries. They swept up Anna, her 6-year-old sister,
Maggie, and their year-old brother, Luke, and moved them off to the
dust and smell and bustle of this teeming African city of 2.5
million people.
</P>
<P>
   Some people might wonder what kind of parents would yank their
daughter out of a good school, away from the whispering pines and
backyard pools, to sit at rude tables in small classrooms and walk
the rutted roads.
</P>
<P>
   Good ones. I hold different beliefs than do Mike and Claire, but
I know of no finer parents anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Don't take my word for it, though. Walk with Anna, as I did,
down some of these roads. See the shine in her eyes. Hear the
excitement in her voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a person that wanted adventure, wanted
Africa, wanted forests, wanted monkeys,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Now she has seen the forests and fed monkeys from her hand. She
lives in Africa. And she's happy.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it has all been easy. There was a time, early on, when
she cried every night. She missed her family. Her grandmother, two
aunts and eight cousins all lived within 30 minutes of her home in
Marietta, and Anna had left that circle.
</P>
<P>
   The unfamiliar odors of Kumasi assaulted her _ the burning
rubbish, the body odor in the marketplace, the sewage that
sometimes runs down street gutters.
</P>
<P>
   The poverty shocked her. She wanted to give away everything she
owned. She did give one girl a special bracelet that a friend in
Georgia had given her as a going-away present.
</P>
<P>
   And she misses my Jennie. ``A lot,'' she said. ``A lot. That was
the hardest. That neighborhood had been home forever.''
</P>
<P>
   A RESPECT FOR CULTURES
</P>
<P>
   We turned a corner and walked up a dusty hill to a tiny shop.
</P>
<P>
   For all the difficulties, Anna has found rewards in Ghana,
deeper ones than patting monkeys on the head. She did that only
once, at a sanctuary in the northern part of the country, far from
Kumasi. The richer rewards are those of everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   We arrived at the shop but, to Anna's dismay, it was out of
FanIce. She had wanted me to taste her favorite treat, creamy ice
cream you suck out of a plastic packet.
</P>
<P>
   Stores here run out of things. And no one store has everything;
there's no Kroger where you can do all your food shopping and no
department store where you can find everything else. A long search
one day through the stalls of an outdoor market resulted in only
one purchase _ yes! _ plastic hangers! The family felt exhilarated.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping here is inconvenient. And it's one of the rewards, too.
</P>
<P>
   You get used to things and you discover the best places to shop.
There is a warren of roadside produce stands not far from the
Mozleys' house that they refer to as Harry's Farmers Market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the best thing is just being able to walk,'' Anna
said, ``and walking to the closest store. In America, I'd ask my
mother, `Can I walk down to the store and get a FanIce?' And she'd
say, `I can drive you to Kroger and get a popsicle.'
</P>
<P>
   ``In America, it would be paved roads and a supermarket. Here, I
feel more close to people.''
</P>
<P>
   The sun poured down. We walked up the street toward another
shop.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few months here have changed Anna. She no longer notices
the smells, no longer notices the goats that cross the road at
random or the chickens that crow about nothing at all.
</P>
<P>
   She is doing well in school; her teacher told me so. There are
good schools, like the one in Marietta, and then there's education.
Anna is learning things in Kumasi she could never learn in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is respect for other cultures. Americans like to
think of themselves as among the most advanced people on earth, but
they can be among the least worldly. Someone who has lived overseas
as a child can never grow up thinking the only valid customs are
American ones.
</P>
<P>
   CHOICES AT EVERY TURN
</P>
<P>
   Anna has learned, too, that happiness does not depend on wealth.
People who live in huts laugh every bit as much as those in
mansions. One time she noticed a bunch of kids singing and dancing.
And it dawned on her: They didn't have nice clothes. They didn't
even have any music.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're dancing,'' she said. ``They're singing. They're having
a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   The sun sank low, chased away by the cool of evening. Anna and I
paused at an intersection, looked around to decide which way to go
and decided to amble home.
</P>
<P>
   On such a day, at such an intersection, a realization came over
Anna: She could take any road she chose. It was up to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm free,'' she thought.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Anna how she would look back on this experience 15 years
from now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifteen years?'' she exclaimed. ``I want to be in Ghana for 30
years!''
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy Kumasi, Anna. It's a wonderful experience for a kid. But
come back after a few years. This country needs people like you.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, sweetheart, Jennie misses you, too. A lot.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
