<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Dec. 12,
1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE stories &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCULPTURE-CITY (subslug) (In the Nevada Desert) _ Michael Heizer
doesn't want you to know where he lives, just that he's in the
middle of nowhere in the middle of Nevada. Heizer has just
completed the first phase of his sculpture ``City.'' The structures
_ which he calls ``complexes,'' using a term archaeologists use for
buildings at ancient sites _ are massive concrete and dirt
mastabas, rectangles with sloped sides. What now exists of ``City''
has got to be one of the most massive modern sculptures ever built.
After nearly 30 years, Heizer has passed the first stage toward
completing what is essentially his own Chichen Itza in the desert.
There are four stages more to go. By Michael Kimmelman. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GREEN-MILE-FILM (Hollywood) _ ``The Green Mile'' will open on
Friday in theaters across the country. Directed by Frank Darabont,
whose first film, ``The Shawshank Redemption,'' drew seven Academy
Award nominations in 1995, it is also based on a Stephen King story
and also set in a prison. In this movie, Tom Hanks plays a Death
Row prison guard in the 1930s who comes to believe that one of his
prisoners, a gentle and somewhat dim giant played by Michael Clarke
Duncan, has supernatural healing powers and may, in fact, be a kind
of angel. By Rick Lyman. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AMADEUS-THEATER (London) _ ``My tongue is stupid, but my heart
isn't,'' remarks the errant genius Mozart in ``Amadeus.'' And a
sprightly genius he proves to be, too, in Peter Shaffer's
metaphysical melodrama, which combines speculative historical
musings with a meditation on divine injustice. Shaffer's play, a
revival, will open Wednesday at the Music Box Theater on Broadway.
By Matt Wolf. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   METROPOLITAN-OPERA (New York) _ Following the Metropolitan
Opera's ups and downs is a prime entertainment for any music-loving
city dweller. Though many call the house's vision dull, its
week-by-week operation offers plenty to chew on. Wagner's ``Tristan
und Isolde,'' now near the end of its limited run, has been a
considerable success. Assembled were Jane Eaglen and Ben Heppner,
two principals who represent the present and the future of an opera
notoriously hard to cast. With them was one of the important Wagner
conductors of the century, James Levine, and a pit orchestra as
good as any in the world. Levine's ``Tristan,'' like much of his
Wagner, is very slow, but it was salutary to surrender to a
different point of view and follow it to a conclusion: a trip worth
taking. By Bernard Holland. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   GRAMMOPHON-CENTENARY-MUSIC (Undated) _ For good reasons,
Deutsche Grammophon's Centenary Collection is heavily concentrated
in the decades after World War II, a period including the history
of the LP and the boom time of the CD. &UR;  &LR; In these years, recording
fidelity started from a high plateau and generally climbed, and
political and social side issues gradually fell by the wayside. The
performers are now better known if not necessarily more
distinguished. &UR;  &LR; Much of the material here will be familiar to
collectors of my postwar generation. By James R. Oestreich.
(Moved).
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LAS-VEGAS-OPERA (Las Vegas) _ What news on the Rialto?
</P>
<P>
   Since spring, they've finished construction on the bridge and
filled the Grand Canal; a few blocks down, a new Paris has its
Opera, Eiffel Tower and Hotel de Ville; and ``O'' has spoiled me
for ``The Ring.'' Greetings from Las Vegas, self-styled
Entertainment Capital of the World, where I have lately landed to
contemplate new frontiers for opera: opera, for the purposes of
this discussion, standing for something greater than itself.
Somewhat to the surprise of observers unattuned to the cyclical
rhythms of cultural history, an art form that within the lifetime
of composers now near their prime was being written off as a
moribund anachronism is experiencing something like a renaissance.
By Matthew Gurewitsch. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCYTHIANS-ART (San Antonio, Texas) _ The story of the Scythians,
how they lived, died and were buried with the things they coveted _
gold, jewels, armor and pottery _ is told in ``Gold of the Nomads:
Scythian Treasures From Ancient Ukraine,'' an exhibition of 171
objects here at the San Antonio Museum of Art, through Jan. 30. The
show was organized by the museum and the Walters Art Gallery in
Baltimore, where it moves in March. By Rita Reif. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   MORIYAMA-PHOTOS (New York) _ Daido Moriyama, 61, was everywhere
in New York this fall. The subject of exhibitions at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art, Japan Society and the Laurence Miller
Gallery; of a handsome catalog on his life and work (from the San
Francisco Museum of Modern Art), and of essays in prominent art
magazines, he has enjoyed scholarly star treatment that no other
Japanese photographer has ever been given in this country. The
reviews were mainly raves. By Richard B. Woodward. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   LOAMY-ART (New York) _ If outdoor earthworks are difficult to
preserve, an ``interior earth sculpture,'' which is how the
conceptual artist Walter De Maria described his 1977 installation
in a Manhattan building, has its own upkeep demands. Twenty-two
years ago, De Maria transformed a desirable 3,600-square-foot piece
of SoHo real estate into something useless. ``The New York Earth
Room'' is 250 cubic yards of earth, piled 22 inches deep. Today,
the work has art historical significance and also provides a
welcome respite from the shopaholics on SoHo's crowded streets.
Some 10,000 people visit the piece annually. One can't walk on it _
a glass barrier contains the earth and keeps people out _ but a
loamy smell definitely permeates the space. By William Harris.
(Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-BECKER (Undated) _ ``He's the most flawed character I've ever
written,'' says David Hackel, proudly, of Dr. John Becker, the
middle-aged lead character played by Ted Danson, the ex-``Cheers''
matinee idol sitcom star. Becker is a politically incorrect
malcontent with no real counterpart in today's youth-obsessed
sitcom world. Positioned neatly at 9:30 p.m. on Mondays on CBS
behind the hit ``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' ``Becker'' the show
regularly finishes in the Nielsen top 20 and has become what
Hackel, 51, a veteran sitcom writer and producer, a bit nervously
calls a ``stealth'' success. By Andy Meisler. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TV-WB (Undated) _ For three years running, the WB television
network has been the favored child of Madison Avenue ad buyers,
media types and teenage-girl America. A trio of freshman shows are
doing well: ``Popular,'' ``Roswell'' and ``Angel,'' the last an
offshoot of WB's flagship, ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer.'' Of course,
none of the new shows have gone above No. 107 in the ratings, but
by WB standards they're hits. Each of the three has growing buzz
and critical support. Each is set in the present day in one of
three WB preferred locations: high school, college or
flunky-job-early-stage adulthood. By Margy Rochlin. (Moved).
</P>
