<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4405 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-WITNESS-PROTECTION     12-09 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WITNESS-PROTECTION-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WISE GUY'S BLUES IN `WITNESS PROTECTION'
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Embargoed until Saturday, Dec. 11. Fact box at bottom.) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dramatically speaking, ``Witness Protection'' is an odd bird.
It's most fascinating in its procedural, by-the-books depiction of
the process through which families who deliver state's evidence are
transformed into completely different entities and shipped off to
completely different environs. But the film also feels the
obligation of providing a semblance of human drama, as well, and
that's where it feels indistinct and formulaic.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by feature filmmaker Richard Pearce (``The Long Walk
Home,'' ``No Mercy''), the movie wastes little time taking off _
mobster Bobby Batton (Tom Sizemore, who plays seedy tough guys as
well as anybody) is almost iced in his home. Once he gets wise to
the fact that it's his own side trying to do him in, he has little
recourse but to turn himself in to the Feds and give up his boss
for a murder. ``I'm not a snitch,'' he insists, but when the choice
is snitch or get snuffed, well, turns out he's a snitch after all.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby and his family _ wife Cindy (Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio)
and two kids _ throw their lives into seven suitcases and are
transported to a high-security flophouse. There, they are given a
mere five days to assimilate reams of information that will help
them assume new, blander identities in a new, safer town (Forest
Whitaker gives a nicely understated, subtly eccentric performance
as the U.S. Marshal who preps them for their new lives). That means
Bobby's going to have to get a real job for the first time since
high school, and it won't pay squat. That means his wife isn't
going to be getting those manicures she likes so much anymore. That
means his son's stellar high school record is for naught _ he won't
be getting into Harvard under his new moniker.
</P>
<P>
   The set-up is endlessly more fascinating than the pay-off. The
requisite conflicts fill the air _ Bobby's wife and son virulently
square off against the family's resident provider and snitch. While
in real life, tensions in such families simmer before exploing, the
confrontations here feel manufactured, and what's supposed to pass
for a hopeful conclusion is simply limp. Sizemore and Whitaker keep
things interesting, but one can't quite shake the feeling that a
more compelling approach to such inherently interesting material
could've been found. &QL; 
____ &QL; 
The show: ``Witness Protection.''  &QL; 
What: Drama about the government's transition of a mob family
turning state's evidence into anonymous pillars of some other
society. &QL; 
The stars: Tom Sizemore, Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio, Forest
Whitaker. &QL; 
Where: HBO. &QL; 
When: 8 p.m. Saturday; also Tuesday, Thursday, Dec. 19 and 24 and
Jan. 3 and 11 &QL; 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
