<HEADER>
A4406 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      12-09 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON THE ART WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Multiple Mysteries
</P>
<P>
   A Cezanne still life with an unusual past sold for $29.3 million
on Tuesday night at Sotheby's in London. ``Pewter Pitcher and
Fruit'' (1888-90) was stolen 21 years ago from Dr. Harry Bakwin, a
child psychologist in New York who was a major Cezanne collector.
</P>
<P>
   The painting was recovered recently after Lloyd's, the London
insurance exchange, approached the Art Loss Register, an
international database for stolen and missing art and antiques.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lloyd's got a vague inquiry from someone who wanted
information about the cost of insurance for shipping the painting
from one country to another,'' said Julian Radcliffe, chairman of
the Art Loss Register in London. He said he did not know who made
the initial inquiry or who stole the painting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the police or the FBI know,'' he said. ``Even if
they had found out, they couldn't make an arrest,'' because the
seven-year statute of limitations for such thefts had expired.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is saying exactly how the painting was recovered, but
once it ended up with members of the Bakwin family, they decided to
sell it. Sotheby's did not identify the buyer, who bid by telephone
through Tobias Meyer, the auction house's director of contemporary
art worldwide. The estimate was $14.8 million to $19.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was the painting one of the artist's finest still
lifes, but Bakwin's collection was also well known, and that
provenance probably helped drive up the price. Another Cezanne from
the collection, ``Young Italian Woman Leaning on Her Elbow''
(1895-1900), was sold to the J. Paul Getty Museum in Los Angeles
last week for a reported $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Also sold on Tuesday at Sotheby's in London was a group of 25
Picassos _ five oil paintings and 20 works on paper _ that had
belonged to Gianni Versace, the Italian fashion designer, who was
fatally shot in Miami Beach in 1997. Like the clothes he designed,
the paintings are all decorative and brightly colored.
</P>
<P>
   The top seller was ``Young Girl With Boat (Maya),'' a 1938
rendering of Picasso's elder daughter, Maya, dressed in a sailor
suit. An unidentified European collector bought it for $6 million,
far above its estimate of $3.3 million to $5 million. A
three-quarter-length 1938 portrait of Dora Maar, one of Picasso's
mistresses, sold for $5.3 million; its estimate was $6.5 million to
$9.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   (Final prices include the auction house's commission: 15 percent
of the first $50,000 plus 10 percent of the rest. Estimates do not
reflect commissions.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The sale was a continuation of what we saw in New York last
month,'' said Melanie Clore, deputy director of Sotheby's in Europe
and head of its Impressionist and modern department in London.
``Many of these works, like the Cezanne, had not been seen for 20
years. It's a discriminating group of buyers. They know what
they're buying, and they don't go crazy.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Asia in Midtown &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since Christie's moved into its new Rockefeller Center
headquarters in May, its old home at 502 Park Avenue, at 59th
Street, has seemed eerily empty. But in January that will change,
at least for 18 months. The Asia Society is renting the building
while its headquarters at 725 Park Avenue, at 70th Street,
undergoes a major renovation and expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Calling its 59th Street quarters Asia Society Midtown, the
institution plans a Feb. 1 opening for its first exhibition there,
``Spiritual Perfection: Hindu, Buddhist and Jain Sculpture of South
and Southeast Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Platt, president of the society, said it had done
minimal work on the old Christie's space, which came with
ready-made galleries.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the society's uptown home, however, are extensive,
involving a $30 million expansion designed by the New York
architect Edward Larabee Barnes. To oversee the project, the
Society chose Bartholomew Voorsanger, the Manhattan architect who
built the garden court for the Pierpont Morgan Library in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a competition but rather brought in a group of
architects to consult,'' Platt said. ``We began with a list of 30
architects, which we narrowed down to 7, then to 3.'' Voorsanger
was chosen because of his experience with the Morgan, Platt said.
</P>
<P>
   Voorsanger's design will double the public and exhibition space
and create galleries on the second and third floors. With its
expansion the society will be able to put its prized Rockefeller
Collection of Asian Art on permanent display.
</P>
<P>
   The first floor will have a redesigned entrance along with a new
glass-enclosed garden court with skylight, sculpture, plantings and
a cafe. The garden court will also be used for special events.
</P>
<P>
   At first plans called for the atrium to be 40 feet high, with an
additional entrance on 70th Street and banners there along with a
glass canopy. But residents on the quiet block of 70th Street
between Park and Lexington objected.
</P>
<P>
   ``This block has often been referred to as `block beautiful,'''
said Barry Schneider, chairman of Community Board 8, which oversees
the neighborhood. ``The major thing was the atrium, which residents
felt was obtrusive. But this has turned out to be community
interaction at its best.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan was changed after Asia Society officials met with their
neighbors. The atrium height was lowered to 24 feet, and plans for
an entrance on 70th Street were dropped, along with the banners and
the canopy. ``The interaction yielded a better project,'' Schneider
said.
</P>
<P>
   The renovation is to begin on Jan. 3 and to be completed by the
fall of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Frick, to Go &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the Frick Collection who don't have time to take its
entire three-hour Acoustiguide can now buy a guidebook based on it.
Available in English, French and German, the book costs $19.95 at
the museum shop.
</P>
<P>
   Modern Times
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Modern Art is adding two viewing days during the
crowded holiday season. Normally closed on Wednesdays, the Modern
will be open on Dec. 22 and 29 from 10:30 a.m. until 5:45 p.m. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 1817EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
