<HEADER>
A4429 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-09 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OLD ISSUE THAT'S STILL A FAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ More than 20 years ago, Ronald Reagan tried to
rescue his failing first presidential bid by stirring up passions
over a pending agreement endorsed by three previous presidents that
would hand control of the Panama Canal to the country through which
the canal runs.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan criss-crossed the land thundering, ``We bought it, we
paid for it, it's ours, and we're going to keep it.'' This
irrational jingoistic message gave conservatives a rallying cry in
the 1976 primaries and President Gerald Ford political heartburn.
Although Ford survived the Reagan challenge, he was so damaged by
the canal issue (and his pardon of Richard Nixon) that he was
defeated in the general election by Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Carter signed two treaties turning the operation of the canal
over to Panama in 1977, and the Senate ratified them by one vote
following an emotional, ideological debate in 1978. President
Lyndon Johnson had agreed to negotiate the transfer in the late
1960s after a bloody rampage indicated anti-U.S. violence might
shut down the waterway; Presidents Nixon and Ford reaffirmed that
position.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, a weary treaty supporter, Senate Minority Leader
Howard Baker, who was soundly trashed by conservatives, sighed, ``I
am tired of behaving responsibly.''
</P>
<P>
   Having caused much of the domestic political fuss, Reagan had no
more use for the issue. Polls showed that most voters who were not
right-wing fanatics accepted the deal as diplomatically necessary
to smooth out relations with Central America and represented no
danger to the principle of U.S. sovereignty. And that was that.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan dropped the subject in his 1980 campaign, and when he
became president, it never reappeared. So much for the dire
long-term consequences that he predicted would result after the
proposed ``give-away.''
</P>
<P>
   Alleged fear of the transfer was always a cynical political
ploy. The action itself was not a genuine national security threat.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue is back, in the glorified memory of Reagan.
Today's conservatives hope that what almost worked for him in 1976
will work for them today. You'd think they'd move on to something
more currently relevant, but no. That's why they are conservatives
_ they like the old thinking.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, former President Carter and Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright will attend ceremonies in Panama marking the
official transfer of the canal to Panama. The event is providing
conservative groups with an irresistible publicity opportunity that
they are already trying to exploit.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, (R-Calif.), predicted ominously that a
``communist Chinese regime that hates democracy ... will dominate
the tiny country of Panama.''
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't this sound familiar? Didn't we hear this apocalyptic
rhetoric about a communist takeover in Nicaragua not so long ago
that led to secret, illegal White House funding of uncontrolled
guerrillas, a huge death toll and an awkward accommodation for
peace when the U.S. stopped funding the killers.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, dear. Let us not do that again.
</P>
<P>
   The new version of the perils inherent in this changeover is
even more gruesome than Reagan's. Witnesses, all selected by
Republican critics of the transfer, testified this week before a
House subcommittee that Panama does not have enough military or
police forces to control the territory. They also charged that the
canal will be vulnerable to outside military pressure as well as
criminal activity and that Chinese plotters will keep our ships
from freely passing through.
</P>
<P>
   A Hong Kong company with Chinese connections, Hutchison Whampoa
Ltd., has been granted a long-term lease to run the cargo ports at
both ends of the canal. Actually, the company, which also runs
Britain's three largest ports, has already been running Panama's
ports under contract for two years, with no apparent political
impact.
</P>
<P>
   But in some conservative circles the Chinese have replaced the
Soviets as the new communist menace that we must rail against, no
matter what the facts. It is also a way of continuing to pound
Clinton over alleged Chinese spying activities and illegal campaign
contributions and for backing China's membership in the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   But this is murky stuff, based on dark suspicions rather than
evidence or even common sense. Many experts say that if China
wanted to sabotage or spy on us, it would not need port facilities
to do so. Nor would it be in China's interest to interfere with use
of the canal since Beijing is its third-biggest user.
</P>
<P>
   Personal connections between the company's leaders and Chinese
investment entities don't prove much of anything either. Former
Secretaries of State George Shultz and Henry Kissinger regularly
advise Chinese clients. There happens to be a business dialogue
going on here, no matter the status of WTO.
</P>
<P>
   Are we scared that Chinese terrorists will plant missiles beside
the waterway or learn our deepest national secrets by bugging us
from a Panama base? Get serious here. Collapse of the Social
Security and Medicare systems _ now that would be a real threat to
the American way of life.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 1843EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
