<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4432 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-2000-HNS &LR;      12-09 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER PRESIDENT BUSH PLAYING ROLE IN 2000 ELECTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOFFSTOWN, N.H. _ Former President Bush is playing a major role
in his son's bid for the Republican presidential nomination, but he
is rarely seen in the campaign and is almost never discussed on the
stump.
</P>
<P>
   As Gov. George W. Bush went on a hand-shaking tour of New
Hampshire cafes Thursday, potential Republican voters such as
William Hunter of Bedford instantly connected with the candidate by
praising his father or his father's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good man,'' Bush told Hunter. ``I'm lucky to have him
as a dad.''
</P>
<P>
   But later, at a Goffstown news conference, another man shouted
to ask Bush what he thought of his father's appointment of David
Souter to the U.S. Supreme Court. Souter's moderate views have been
a disappointment to many staunch conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't talk about my father,'' Bush snapped, but then
attempted to describe for the man how he will pick Supreme Court
nominees.
</P>
<P>
   The man repeated his question. ``I'm not going to talk about
David Souter,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   While his father's 1989-1993 presidential tenure is an immediate
point of reference for voters across the country, Texas Gov. Bush
never introduces the subject of his father on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   Bush often mentions his mother, Barbara Bush, frequently, making
positive comparisons between her and his own wife, Laura. Barbara
Bush also has made several public campaign appearances for the
governor's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But the former president has been noticeably invisible. Early
this year, President Bush hosted a low-profile fund-raiser for his
son in Arizona, and he has made some calls to his old supporters on
his son's behalf. But otherwise he has stayed out of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   When Gov. Bush made his first presidential debate appearance
Dec. 2 in Manchester, N.H., Barbara Bush made a highly publicized
visit to the presidential campaign headquarters in Austin, Texas.
Former President Bush was fishing in Argentina, but the Texas
governor was overheard saying, ``OK, `bye, Dad,'' into his cellular
phone. A spokeswoman confirmed that the former president had called
his son to see how the debate had gone.
</P>
<P>
   The only oblique reference to his father, however, comes in his
stump speech when he says it is a big step between being governor
of Texas and president, ``but I've had some pretty good training.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience always laughs and applauds at the unspoken
connection to this father. But instead of then mentioning his
father, Bush goes on to recite his record as Texas governor as the
basis of his training and qualifications.
</P>
<P>
   In his autobiography, ``A Charge to Keep,'' Gov. Bush reprints a
letter his father wrote last year to him and his brother, Florida
Gov. Jeb Bush. The former president in that letter tells his sons
never to fear politically disagreeing with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is inevitable that the new breed of journalists will have
to find a hook in stories, will have to write not only on your
plans and your dreams but will have to compare those with what, in
their view, I failed to accomplish,'' President Bush wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``That can be hurtful to a family that loves each other. But the
advice is don't worry about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point both of you may want to say, 'Well, I don't
agree with Dad on that point,' or, 'Frankly, I think Dad was wrong
on that.' Do it. Chart your own course, not just on the issues but
on defining yourselves,'' the former president said. ``Read my
lips, no more worrying.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush so far has avoided criticism of his father. After
being heckled Thursday, said he is keeping his father out of his
race because he wants to be judged on his own by voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't I talk about my father? Because I'm (the one)
running for president,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proudly his son. I love him dearly. I'm lucky I have him
as a father,'' the governor said. ``I inherited half his friends
and all his enemies. It hasn't changed for six years.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
