<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Friday, Dec. 10. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
FORBES (Phoenix) - Presidential candidate Steve Forbes on Thursday
defended his aggressive plan to privatize Social Security and said
any financial problems created by a transition period for the newly
revamped program could be solved with long-term bonds.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Arizona Republic editorial board,
Forbes said some of the costs associated with his plan to allow
citizens to invest Social Security funds in their own retirement
accounts could be paid for with bonds. By KRIS MAYES. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AUTO-REVIEW (Phoenix) - Two Volvo wagons shared my driveway
recently, about three feet and 15 years apart. One was considerably
shinier than the other.
</P>
<P>
   The old one _ a silver-gray 240 DL, circa 1986 _ belongs to my
wife. Boxy and funky, reeking of reverse snobbery, her Volvo has
been a loyal and reliable creature since the day we bought it,
used, nearly eight years ago. The new one was Volvo's beautiful new
V40, as stylish and handsome as the 240 is dated and homely. The
V40, and its sedan counterpart, the S40, are Volvo's bid to bring
its cars' prices back down to the entry level.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in the low 20s, they still offer a high level of
sophistication and good driving characteristics, as befitting a
Volvo. By BOB GOLFEN. Story moved in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
