<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4456 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-OIL-PRICE-COX     12-09 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-PRICE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oil firm reps blast Clinton's price caps
 &HT;    By Mike Elswick
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ Representatives of the East Texas oil
business, who have been through the worst of times in the past 18
months, took exception to President Bill Clinton's plans to cap
rising oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration warned Thursday that ``dangerously
high'' oil prices could affect economic growth and said it was
prepared to intervene if costs continue to soar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got some real concerns about him wanting to intervene in
trying to control prices,'' said Denny Bowles Jr. of Longview,
whose family has oil interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been the last three to four months that we've gotten
to the point where we're gaining back some of what we lost last
year when prices were low.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Backwell, co-owner and president of Mas-Tech Inc. in
Kilgore, said Thursday that current oil prices are a product of
world supply, demand and actions of governments far outside the
control of Clinton and the United States government.
</P>
<P>
   ``When prices were down they threw us to the wolves and blamed
it on supply and demand,'' he said. Blackwell said industry
requests for a national oil policy to help bring stability to the
industry have been ignored for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a case of you reap what you sow,'' Blackwell said.
``The administration thought as long as we continued to import oil
the price would stay low.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackwell said the American oil market is ``being manipulated by
things we have no control over.'' These include actions by OPEC and
individual countries like Iraq, Saudi Arabia and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   ``We in the oil industry are victims just as much as the layman
consumer. It just happens this time, for once, we have a little bit
more to gain from it,'' Blackwell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost 40,000 people out of oil field jobs in the last year,
and I've heard numbers of as many as 120,000, but 40,000 is
probably a good, conservative number.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackwell said the economics of oil staying below $15 a barrel
as it did for much of last year and into early this year were
devastating to the American oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need what's going on now with prices just to get healed up
from what's happened the last 16-18 months,'' he said. ``All we
want is a healthy, steady market _ with an emphasis on steady _ I
don't think there's anyone in the business who's been around very
long who wants to see prices go much higher. But steady would be
nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackwell said the industry lost many oil service companies,
along with oil companies, to the last bust.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really hit the service side of the business hard,'' he
said. Blackwell said the oil industry has not asked for aid like
farmers in order to survive and remain competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've asked for for the past 10 years is a national oil
policy and no one will listen,'' Blackwell said. Instead, he said,
the government seems to be ``proud'' of the country's rising
dependence on foreign oil.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
