<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4457 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-WILLINGHAM-COX     12-09 0372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLINGHAM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Another actor turn to politics
 &HT;    By Glenn Evans
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _Television actor Noble Willingham quit his day
job Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He also announced he has laid out the $2,500 filing fee to enter
the race for the District 1 congressional seat from Texas.
Willingham will run as a Republican for the seat held by Democrat
Max Sandlin of Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   No one has filed to challenge Willingham in the March 14
primary. Last May, Longview attorney Brian Hoyle filed as a
Republican with the Federal Elections Commission to run for the
office, but said last week he will not seek the post.
</P>
<P>
   The general election will be held on Nov. 7, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Willingham, who portrays C.D. Parker on the television show
``Walker, Texas Ranger,'' told supporters at Republican
headquarters in Longview Wednesday that his final episode is the
Christmas show. Writers tentatively plan to have his character win
the lottery and take off to see the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a bad idea,'' he said before describing his
departure from the show after seven years. ``We had a mutual deal.
They wanted to know what I thought they should do about it. They
were amenable to me leaving, and they wanted me to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to get to what's really important, and that's this.
I wouldn't want to stretch myself too thin.''
</P>
<P>
   Willingham contrasted himself with Sandlin as, `` ...about like
daylight and dark.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandlin, he said, has veered too far onto the liberal side of
the political spectrum by tying his wagon to that of President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did Mr. Sandlin get too close to Mr. Clinton?'' Willingham
asked. ``I don't know that. I'd rather be in my position than his.
... I'm on the right side of the continuum.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the gentleman who is in there right now _ I don't know
where he falls on the left side.''
</P>
<P>
   Willingham said he would return to his California residence this
week, planning to catch the annual dog show in Indio, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the first of the year we're going to hit it running,'' he
said. ``And we're going to hit it hard, and we're going to have
blood in our eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
