<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4458 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-GORE-HNS &LR;      12-09 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CRITICAL OF GORE, CLINTON ON TRADE, GUN ISSUES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
and CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOFFSTOWN, N.H _ Presidential hopeful George W. Bush took on the
Clinton administration Thursday, accusing Vice President Al Gore of
ducking the free trade issue during last week's meeting of the
World Trade Organization in Seattle and Clinton of loosely
enforcing gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's criticisms on the gun-law enforcement issue were
blunted by Democratic reaction to a Houston Chronicle report that
the Texas Department of Public Safety has for almost four years sat
on information that several hundred felons may be illegally
carrying guns in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican presidential candidate said he believes Gore, a
Democratic candidate, may be avoiding the trade issue because of
his support from labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vice President Gore has been amazingly silent on the issue,
starring in a new movie called `Silence in Seattle,''' Bush said.
``I think he's worried about the political ramifications, but you
need to ask him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said President Clinton did not do enough to promote free
trade during his visit to the WTO meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been disappointed by the administration's reluctance to
promote free trade,'' Bush said. ``They weren't forceful as free
traders.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said, ``Al Gore's view on trade has
been widely known. He has always been a proponent of free and fair
trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehane said Gore supports trade agreements that include labor
and environmental protections as part of main trade provisions, not
as side agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Bush appeared to agree with one argument made by protests at
last week's meeting, saying his ``worry is the WTO conducts itself
in too clandestine a manner. It ought to be more open.''
</P>
<P>
   Violent protests broke out in Seattle at the WTO meeting, as
protesters complained about its secret meetings and its emphasis on
trade ahead of worker and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
   Bush maintains that improved economies in Third World countries
will improve workers' lives and pay for environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, campaigning Thursday in New Hampshire, said Democrats have
tried to take the law enforcement issue away from Republicans and
failed.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, as he has done before, accused the Clinton administration
of being lax in enforcing existing gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to arrest people who illegally carry guns, arrest
people who illegally sell guns. ...This administration has been lax
in enforcing laws, laws on the books,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to keep the guns out of the hands of people who
shouldn't have them. But one way to make society safer is to
enforce gun laws on the books.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan said that prosecutions of
criminal use of firearms had dropped by 46 percent under the
Clinton-Gore administration, according to a report by the U.S.
Senate Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore spokesman responded by taking a jab at Bush over the
Texas guns issue.
</P>
<P>
   Lehane said Bush ``ought to spend more time worrying about
felons who are carrying firearms.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic National Committee Chairman Joe Andrew said Bush was
hypocritical on the gun issue, following the Chronicle story
Thursday about the DPS's lax enforcement of felons illegally
carrying guns in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``His hypocrisy reveals the hollowness of his own commitment to
gun safety,'' Andrew said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party chief said Bush simply ``parroted'' the
position of the National Rifle Association, which opposes more gun
control laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle reported Thursday that the DPS obtained the
information about felons and firearms while screening applicants
for concealed handgun licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Although felons were denied handgun permits, they could have
broken the law merely by getting gun-safety training at a firing
range. Federal law prohibits felons from ever again possessing
firearms.
</P>
<P>
   The DPS didn't refer their cases to federal authorities for
possible prosecution, even though the felons submitted certificates
with their unsuccessful handgun applications showing that they had
completed a gun-safety course.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office said Bush, who appoints the commission
that oversees the DPS, learned only this fall that the felons'
cases were not forwarded to prosecutors. The information will now
go to officials working on a new state program, Texas Exile,
created by Bush and Texas Attorney General John Cornyn to crack
down on gun-law violators.
</P>
<P>
   McClellan said Andrew was ``distorting Governor Bush's proven
leadership of strictly enforcing the tough (gun) laws we already
have on the books in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   McClellan said Bush also had signed laws creating weapons-free
zones around schools, holding parents accountable if their children
gain access to firearms and providing automatic detention for
juveniles who illegally carry guns or use firearms to commit a
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also signed the concealed handgun law in 1995, his first
year in office.
</P>
<P>
   Bush opened a meeting with law enforcement officers at AnnaDel's
Restaurant by asking for a moment of silence for six Worcester,
Mass., firemen who died in a warehouse fire last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad story that people who put their lives on the line
sometimes lose it,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was endorsed by 80 New Hampshire law enforcement officers.
Retired Goffstown Police Chief Stephen Monier said the decision to
back Bush was based on his record of reducing crime, especially
juvenile crime, as governor of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the kind of results that we in the law enforcement
community respect,'' Monier said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush praised the U.S. Supreme Court's decision to review whether
confessions should always be excluded from trial if a defendant has
not been given a Miranda warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``If in fact a voluntary confession has been made, the courts
ought to take a good hard look at if that should be admissible,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
