<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4467 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-WELFARE-WORKERS-ART-2     12-09 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELFARE-WORKERS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 MILWAUKEE: the bill.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the summer of 1998, Garland set out to find a different kind
of caseworker, someone less computer-literate than world-wise,
someone like Steinborn.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Steinborn needed employment planning himself. He
was a 30-year-old, jobless, blue-collar guy with an ex-wife, a
4-year-old son and a pregnant girlfriend. He had dropped out of
college, driven a cab, hung sheet rock, started a business mowing
abandoned city lots and lost it in a fight with his partner. Then
he had sat at home and brooded.
</P>
<P>
   A high school test had predicted he would make a good social
worker, but Steinborn had scoffed. ``I said, `You think I'm going
to be some underpaid, overworked social worker?''' he said. But
over a beer one night, a friend told him that Maximus was hiring,
with annual salaries at nearly $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   He borrowed five dress shirts from his father and swallowed his
pride in his prior avoidance of desk jobs. ``I needed the money,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   THE SUPER WORKER: FROM WALL KICKING TO GLIMMER OF LIGHT
</P>
<P>
   For months, Steinborn had one thought: ``What have I gotten
myself into?'' He had no problem talking across racial or economic
lines. (Both his ex-wife and his girlfriend are black.) But the
policy manual was inches thick, and entering the wrong computer
code could mean a family would not get a check.
</P>
<P>
   He winced at his mistakes and laid awake at night. He dreaded
coming to work so much he kicked a hole in his bedroom wall.
Meanwhile, the caseworker assigned to train him was arrested for
asking clients for kickbacks. (That caseworker was acquitted by a
jury in October.) Steinborn's supervisor caught him filling out an
application for a job cutting plate glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't like putting up dry wall,'' he said. ``You're
messing with people's live.''
</P>
<P>
   Then something strange happened. He entered what he now
self-mockingly calls his ``super Fep'' stage. ``I began to think I
could solve everyone's problems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When a client dragged her feet in applying for a job, Steinborn
drove her to an interview. (She did not get hired.) When a client
needed child care, Steinborn arranged to meet her son at school and
drive him to a day-care center. (She skipped her training program
anyway.)
</P>
<P>
   One day, the mother of a child with cerebral palsy arrived in
his office. By the book, Steinborn was merely supposed to offer her
a list of specialized child-care centers. Instead, he spent three
hours placing calls, until he found a promising lead.
</P>
<P>
   His client never visited the child-care center. But she did
visit a legal aid office, to file a complaint that Steinborn had
failed to appreciate the needs of her child. She dropped it at the
ensuing hearing, saying she had gotten confused. (``I felt sorry
for Michael _ he really did try to help me,'' she said in a recent
interview.)
</P>
<P>
   The planning manual said to teach the poor to solve their own
problems _ to ``empower'' rather than ``enable'' them. Then again,
the theorists had never met the Woman Without a Coat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mi-ii-ke!'' she yelled across the office, introducing herself
on the coldest day of the year. ``Mi-ii-ke, I need a coat!''
</P>
<P>
   She stood too close. She talked too loud. He thought she might
be mentally retarded. When a check of clothing programs turned up
nothing, he ran four blocks through the snow and returned from a
thrift store with a $9 coat.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong size, she complained.
</P>
<P>
   He went back and bought another.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong color, she complained.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, coatless again, she told his supervisor that
no one would help her.
</P>
<P>
   Less offended than intrigued, Steinborn spent months listening
to her rambling monologues _ about God, poetry, the Y2K problem _
until he assembled the outlines of her story. She said she had been
reared by a respected church-going family and lowered to
prostitution by drugs. She said she had been sober, though still
poor and addled, nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
   When she was faced with eviction, Steinborn arranged a special
grant and found a housing counselor to help her. She cursed out the
counselor and told Steinborn's supervisor she had been abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   Steinborn lost it.
</P>
<P>
   When he asked if she was still smoking crack, she said she had
been clean for three days. ``You told me you hadn't used in two
years,'' he screamed.
</P>
<P>
   He urged her to seek treatment, and she angrily refused.
Instead, she and her 8-year-old son moved to a homeless shelter,
and her case was transferred to another agency. He saw her once
more, wandering through the office without her front teeth,
pleading with him for a bus pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``A small part of me knew it the whole time, but my whole heart
really sank into my stomach,'' Steinborn said. ``I felt really
stupid and useless. I felt betrayed, even though it wasn't about
me. I was almost as addicted to helping her as she was to crack.''
</P>
<P>
   He vowed to go back to dry wall.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 1915EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
