<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4470 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DANGER-DANCE-REVIEW-N     12-09 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANGER-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DANGER RUN': AN ABSTRACT PROTEST FROM THE OLD SCHOOL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; NEW YORK _ The choreographer Donald McKayle is of the old school,
which happens to be a valid school. Mainstream modern dance's idea
that movement should go beyond design to express emotions and an
inner reality is still visible in ``Danger Run,'' his latest work
for the Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Yet at its premiere on Wednesday night at City Center, ``Danger
Run'' had a strong contemporary sensibility. If not cutting edge,
it is the most abstract of McKayle's social-protest works since the
1950s. There is a complex piano score by the American composer
Frederic Rzweski, called ``Four North American Ballads,'' and the
choreography, although sometimes diffuse, stays resolutely away
from the literal.
</P>
<P>
   Intelligently and cleverly, ``Danger Run'' emerges as a protest
work that also comments on protest art of the past. Kenneth John
Verdugo has designed a wonderful backcloth-scroll evoking a WPA
mural.
</P>
<P>
   As the scroll, spread across the rear of the stage, moves
upward, the journey from African village to American South and
northern metropolis is revealed in new images that correspond to
phases in the choreography's structure. The African diaspora,
slavery, the civil rights struggle and more come alive in this
assemblage of painted villages, skyscrapers, leg irons, cotton
bales and pickets.
</P>
<P>
   Old union songs and spirituals are likewise embedded in the
richly layered score, played by a brilliant pianist in the pit,
Alan Terricciano.
</P>
<P>
   Rzweski's treatment of folk material, jumbled from the start
with assorted levels of bangs and dissonance, is never without
comment.
</P>
<P>
   A protest piece that is also a gloss on a protest piece does not
suggest the struggle (for equality, in this case) is over. It
suggests only that new ways of expression must be found.
 &UR;  &LR; Whether McKayle has totally succeeded is debatable. His vocabulary
loses a sharp definition as the piece progresses and its repetition
makes for a certain sameness in the ensembles.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, ``Danger Run,'' enhanced by the lighting of William
H. Grant III, has the quality of a tone poem. McKayle's titles for
each section elaborate on the musical subtitles. Rzweski's
``Dreadful Memories'' becomes ``Many Thousand Gone'' and ``Which
Side Are You On?'' is called ``Run Brother Run'' in the second
section.
</P>
<P>
   In the first, Renee Robinson, costumed in a silver bodice on a
brown leotard with a white ruffled skirt by the Nigerian-born
designer Omatayo Wunmi Olaiya, seems to be a Mother Africa spirit.
She weeps and guides. Bahiyah Sayyed, Mucuy Bolles, Linda Caceres,
Briana Reed, Dwana Adiaha Smallwood and Venus Hall pick up her
movement motifs: fluttering hands and crossed wrists.
</P>
<P>
   Their images of captivity are echoed by the men's ensemble,
which enters with a stamping warrior dance. Uri Sands leads Matthew
Rushing, Benoit-Swan Pouffer, Vernard J. Gilmore, Jeffrey Gerodias,
Kevin E. Boseman, Clifton Brown and Guillermo Asca in a dance that
draws partly on Martha Graham's technique. Hence, the love affair
with the ground. For all the leaps and turns, the choreography is
not aerial but weighted, with dancers often dropping to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   McKayle does not draw from African movement but speaks of Africa
in his own idiom. The third section, ``Some Through the Water,''
set to ``Down by the Riverside,'' follows the men's rage with a
duet for two of the company's finest dancers, Ms. Robinson and
Sands. The ruling image, ornamented by lifts, is of the man
enclosing the woman, even by wrapping his leg around her.
</P>
<P>
   The music in the last section, ``Winnsboro Cotton Mill Blues,''
buries its melody in machinelike repetition and is retitled ``They
Keep Coming.'' Sands and Ms. Robinson lead the ensemble, whose
movements are choppier than before and accelerated. Hands are
splayed, and exciting leaps by the men lead up to an enigmatic
image that echoes one from the central duet. Ms. Robinson holds
Sands' foot in her palm.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its weak spots, ``Danger Run'' has a humanity that the
program's opening work lacks. ``Lettres d'Amour,'' by the
French-born choreographer Redha, looks as insufferable as it did
last year. Hell is dancers in an S-and-M battle of the sexes here.
The dancers yank and grovel admirably and the men wear one kneepad
in the interests of self-preservation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
