patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-YELTSIN (Beijing) _ President Boris Yeltsin of Russia, who
is visiting China, responded sharply Thursday to President
Clinton's criticism of Russia's military assault on Chechnya,
reminding the United States that the Kremlin still has nuclear
weapons and warning that Clinton cannot ``dictate how the world
should live, work and play.'' By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Gudermes, Russia) _ Russia plans to return the
flood of refugees who have fled the fighting in Chechnya to
Russian-controlled areas of the republic by the end of the year,
Russia's top official for Chechen affairs said Thursday. By Michael
R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ASSESS (Jerusalem) _ A feeling that change was imminent
swept through Israel Thursday after President Clinton's surprise
announcement on Wednesday that Israeli-Syrian talks would be
resumed after nearly four years. Almost palpably, the national
pulse seemed to quicken _ for some with elation, for others with
anxiety. Even the Israeli right-wing, so uninspired these last few
months, girded up for a real opportunity. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-WORKERS (Milwaukee) _ Lots of people consider themselves
experts on this city's war on welfare, but few have ridden its
highs and lows as intensely as Michael Steinborn. Eighteen months
ago, Steinborn was an unemployed jack of the building trades, down
on his luck and in need of a job. Improbably enough, he is now one
of the system's most popular caseworkers _ and a de facto authority
on the nation's most famous welfare experiment. By Jason DeParle.
</P>
<P>
   KING-TRIAL-ASSESS (Atlanta) _ With key players long dead, with
confessions recanted and altered, and with a vast conspiracy
alleged but not proven, Wednesday's verdict in the civil trial
connected to the assassination of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. may
ultimately do little to demystify the tangle of fact and theory
surrounding one of the century's most traumatic events. By Kevin
Sack.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MARS-OCEAN (Undated) _ Scientists at Brown University
unveiled evidence Thursday that the northern lowlands of the planet
Mars once bore a wide ocean that, until it eventually dried up, had
waves, hidden depths, long beaches _ and perhaps even life. By
William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-FINANCE (Washington) _ John McCain and Bill Bradley,
both insurgent candidates for president, have agreed to step across
party lines and stage an unusual joint appearance in New Hampshire
to highlight their support for overhauling the nation's campaign
finance system, aides to both candidates said Thursday. By Alison
Mitchell. (Developing.)
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENE-THERAPY (Bethesda, Md) _ On the second day of federal
hearings on a death in a gene therapy trial, relatives of patients
plead with the FDA not to halt tests of gene therapy. By Sheryl Gay
Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SPY-ARREST (Washington) _ Developments in the arrest of a
Russian diplomat on spy charges.
