<HEADER>
A4474 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-COCACOLA-NORRIS-COLUM     12-09 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCACOLA-NORRIS-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE CUSTOMERS WON'T PAY MORE, THE CEO DEPARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By   FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do you remember what a two-liter bottle of Coke cost five or 10
years ago? Have prices gone up?
</P>
<P>
   The answers to those questions go a long way toward explaining
why M. Douglas Ivester is leaving his job after little more than
two years as Coca-Cola's &UR;  &LR; chief executive. It's hard to sustain the
stock price of a growth company when the company can't raise
prices.
</P>
<P>
   The government says that in the last decade the price of soft
drinks has risen at a rate of less than 0.9 percent a year. You're
paying less now than you paid back in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   It is a tribute to the wizardry of Coke's management _ not least
the financial management that Ivester personified _ that Coke has
been viewed as a growth company. It persuaded investors to focus on
volume growth, and it emphasized international expansion. But at
bottom it was in an industry with no pricing power.
</P>
<P>
   Consider how Coca-Cola makes its money. It sells concentrate to
bottlers, which add other ingredients, and then package and sell it
to stores and restaurants. Every year, Coke raises the price of
concentrate, usually about 3 percent. But the bottlers have not
been able to pass the costs on to consumers, so their profit
margins have been squeezed. They tried to cut costs and become more
efficient, but there are limits to that, and by the time Ivester
became chief executive in 1997, the limits were being reached.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester tried a strategy of raising the concentrate price and
then funneling more and more money back to the bottlers that needed
it _ as marketing support. That helped the bottlers to report
better earnings, and Coke found a way to minimize the immediate
impact of those payments on its own profits.
</P>
<P>
   The move bought time, but by this year something more was
needed. The bottlers tried to charge more to consumers, only to see
sales fall. Then Coke, trying to bolster its own profits, raised
the concentrate price by far more than it normally does. The
bottlers were not happy.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel Goldman, the longtime Coke watcher who now is at Merrill
Lynch, says he suspects that bottler anger may have prompted
Ivester's sudden decision to retire at the age of 52. But since
neither Ivester nor members of Coke's board are talking, there is
no way to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Coke's lagging stock price played a role. It is down 30
percent from the high it reached in the summer of 1998 and 7
percent since the end of last year. Not since 1979 has Coke's share
price had a down year.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the inability to raise prices was not the only
problem Ivester confronted. Asian sales suffered when that region's
economies imploded. A strategy of growth through acquisitions ran
afoul of European antitrust regulators. The brand's image was
harmed by recalls in Europe. Perhaps a different boss would have
done better, particularly in assuaging Europeans' anger.
</P>
<P>
   Coke's still has a great brand names, but its product has
commoditylike characteristics that keep the company from raising
prices too far above those of competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas N. Daft, Ivester's successor, thinks that can change.
``We believe people will pay more for more,'' he said in a
telephone interview Thursday. ``We build a complex imagery around
our product.''
</P>
<P>
   That image used to drive up the price of Coke stock. But it
hasn't worked as well in persuading consumers to pay more for
Cokes. Changing that reality is Daft's greatest challenge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
