<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4475 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-CDC-HIV10-COX     12-09 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CDC-HIV10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: Use names for tracking AIDS virus, CDC urges
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Using names _ not numbers or other identifying codes _
at the time people are diagnosed with the AIDS virus is the best
way for states to track the epidemic, the U.S. Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention here says.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC made the recommendation for HIV tracking Thursday in its
weekly report. But it gave states a loophole.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is one of 11 states that have no HIV tracking system. To
date, 34 states have developed an HIV surveillance system, while
four others use some combination of numbers, such as Social
Security numbers and birth dates, as identifiers. Washington state
uses a combination of names and numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC recommendation allows for states to use ``unique
identifiers'' instead of names as long as the system meets all its
accuracy and security parameters. It also calls for states to
continue anonymous HIV testing for people who refuse to be part of
the tracking system.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia officials have held hearings over the past year to
receive comments on which system to use, and the Georgia Task Force
on AIDS has recommended that some type of codes, not names, be used
when submitting HIV data to the Division of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said Thursday that they are still researching
the best system to use and that ``security is of paramount
importance.'' It's still too early to say when a decision will be
reached on which system Georgia will implement, said Dr. John
Beltrami, director of AIDS surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   States now track people with AIDS, recording how many are living
with full-blown cases of the disease and how many deaths are
attributed to it. But the federal government needs a better system
of tracking people at the time they are diagnosed with HIV, the
virus that causes AIDS, because better drugs are forestalling the
time when the infection produces the disease.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 297,000 people in the United States have AIDS, and
300,000 to 600,000 are estimated to be HIV-infected, the CDC says.
Since 1981, 21,364 AIDS cases have been reported in Georgia, and
about half of those patients have died.
</P>
<P>
   A national HIV surveillance system will provide a better
understanding of the prevalence of the virus and much-needed data
for public health officials, such as which populations are most at
risk, where they live, at what age people are being infected and
the time elapsed before the disease progresses.
</P>
<P>
   While most agree about the need to track HIV cases, controversy
has swirled around the best way to do so. Many AIDS activists fear
that a name system will lead to breaches of confidentiality and
deter people from getting tested.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 1920EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
