<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4478 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-IOC-BOS &LR;      12-09 1815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS VIDEO LINKUP MARKS NEW ERA FOR IOC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Mitt Romney's favorite cartoon is the one from
the Deseret News that shows him on a billboard hyping
`MittFrugal's', his discount Winter Olympics outlet. ``We're
cheap,'' Romney is proclaiming.
</P>
<P>
   How cheap? The Salt Lake Organizing Committee board members now
pay for their own coffee and doughnuts at meetings. Brochures and
newsletters are printed in two colors, not four.
</P>
<P>
   And when Romney, president of the SLOC, makes his required
status report to the International Olympic Committee's executive
board in Switzerland Friday, he'll do it by video teleconference
instead of in person. ``We'll save $10,000,'' Romney said. ``But as
important is the time savings _ three days going over and back.
Time is of the essence now.''
</P>
<P>
   A year after the scandal that gave Salt Lake City a black eye
and turned the Olympic movement inside out, organizers are
scrambling to make up time and money.
</P>
<P>
   With the 19th Winter Games less than two years away, the SLOC
still has a $148 million budget gap to close, sponsors to sign,
sports venues to complete and test, and volunteers to find and
train _ not to mention millions of still-skeptical Utahns to win
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still an ingrained concern that the Games are very
expensive, and we have a big hole to climb out of,'' conceded
Romney. ``Utah isn't the show-me state, but it could be.''
</P>
<P>
   So Romney, the Boston venture capitalist who was hailed as a
white knight when he arrived here in February, has spent much of
his time selling the Olympics at town meetings, schools, and on a
monthly radio show.
</P>
<P>
   His frankness, energy and optimism are paying off. Recent polls
in the Salt Lake Tribune and Deseret News, the city's two daily
newspapers, found that more than 80 percent of Utahns were
confident that the SLOC would pull off a successful Olympics. But
most of them still expect that the Games will lose money and that
they will get stuck with the bill.
</P>
<P>
   `` `How do you feel about the Games?' is a complicated question
in Utah,'' said Romney, who graduated from nearby Brigham Young
University and whose parents were born here. ``Are you asking: `How
do I feel about how we got the Games and how they were managed
before?' Or are you asking: `How do I feel about them now and
whether they'll be a success?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The joy and pride Utahns felt when Salt Lake City finally won
the Games after five failed attempts turned to anger and shame in
November 1998 when a local TV station revealed that the bid
committee had paid to send the daughter of the IOC member from
Cameroon to college in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The bidders had done considerably more than that. Over seven
years they had secretly spent more than $1 million in payoffs,
scholarships, medical care, lavish vacations, shopping sprees and
an endless cornucopia of gifts ranging from ski parkas to crystal
globes.
</P>
<P>
   When longtime IOC member Marc Hodler of Switzerland said that
bribery and vote-peddling were standard practice in selecting host
cities, it touched off the worst scandal in modern Olympic history.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC expelled six members, pushed four more to resign and
issued warnings to 10 others. This weekend in Lausanne, the ``Lords
of the Rings'' are expected to reform everything from how they
choose members to how they choose Olympic cities.
</P>
<P>
   The US Olympic Committee, which was supposed to oversee the Salt
Lake City bid, was chastised for its laxity by a special
investigative committee headed by former US Sen. George Mitchell
and is undergoing a dramatic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the scandal, SLOC president Frank Joklik and
others stepped down. And when Romney arrived, two days after the
whole mess was detailed in a 300-page ethics report, he was greeted
as a savior and given a standing ovation by the state legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Romney had been told that the situation was a nightmare (``Are
you sure you want this?'' Joklik asked him). It was, he soon found,
even worse. ``When I came in, my guess was that it was an 80
percent public relations problem and a 20 percent fundamental
management problem,'' he said. ``Three weeks later, I realized it
was 20 percent public relations and 80 percent management.''
</P>
<P>
   What he had here, Romney concluded, was the kind of troubled
company he and his colleagues at Bain used to take over and turn
around. ``There are a few basic rules in a turnaround,'' he said.
``Find out how bad things are. Admit it to yourself and everybody
else. Fix the team. And focus, focus, focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without the scandal, the SLOC would have been foundering.
Its revenue projections, which counted on nearly twice as much
sponsorship money ($800 million) than Atlanta had gotten for the
1996 Summer Games, were cockeyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In six months they had only signed one sponsor for $13 million
and every company from Atlanta but one was already in the bag,''
Romney said. ``They gave me a list of 12 they were `close' to
signing. We still haven't signed them.''
</P>
<P>
   Fraser Bullock, the former Bain colleague whom Romney brought in
as chief operating and financial officer, went through the budget
line by line. ``And there were hundreds of thousands of lines,''
Bullock said. When he punched in the bottom line, he found a gap of
nearly $400 million on a $1.5 billion budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``That didn't make the public feel good, but they appreciated
the honesty,'' Romney said. ``They said, at least we're being told
the truth. When things aren't going well, people fear what they
don't know more than the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Romney put on his marketing hat soon after he arrived, visiting
every potential sponsor and hiring five full-time salespeople
(OPUS, the joint USOC/SLOC marketing entity, has signed on IMG to
drum up even more sponsors). Ten new firms are now on board for
$100 million and the SLOC says more are in the queue.
</P>
<P>
   Then Romney and Bullock sliced more than $200 million from the
expense side. Since they've never been to an Olympics, they had the
luxury of asking naive questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been stupid like foxes,'' said Romney. ``A lot of things
didn't make sense to us. When we inquired, we found they didn't
make sense at all. Like the IOC says we're supposed to put out a
daily newspaper during the Olympics. We said, we have two
newspapers here in town. Can't we use them?''
</P>
<P>
   Then isn't now, the SLOC people say. The scandal has changed the
Olympics forever. The way it was is not how it will _ or should _
be. ``We say, tradition isn't necessarily necessity,'' Bullock
said. ``We have three categories in our budget now: must-haves,
nice-to-haves and not-needed.''
</P>
<P>
   The must-haves are written in indelible ink. The nice-to-haves
will happen only if the SLOC can find more revenue. The not-neededs
have already been disregarded. Many of the changes, like the board
members paying for their breakfasts, are symbolic. ``But it
communicates to people, `Hey, we're serious about this,' '' said
Romney. ``Small things multiplied by large numbers become large
numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   The organizers no longer take an entourage to IOC meetings.
Romney and Bullock go by themselves and return the next day. And
when the ``Lords of the Rings'' come for the Games, they'll be
treated like VIPs, not royalty. ``No limos,'' said Bullock. ``It'll
be Blazers and Tahoes and Suburbans.''
</P>
<P>
   The members will stay in the original Little America hotel
downtown, not the $500-a-night ``Grand'' version going up next
door. The IOC president will have a suite, but it won't be lavish.
``It'll be what you'd find at a Marriott or a Hyatt,'' Romney said.
</P>
<P>
   There'll be no lavish reception before the IOC session just
prior to the Games. No floral bouquets. No 24-hour secretary for
each IOC member. And no blocks of prime seats sitting empty just in
case a member decides to show up unexpectedly.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC, eager to change its image as a club of high-livin'
freeloaders, isn't arguing. ``Mr. Samaranch has been extremely open
to any suggestion we have made,'' said Romney. ``He said, anything
you need to cut that doesn't hurt the Games, go ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   The scandal has enabled, if not forced, everyone involved to get
back to basics. ``It's made us stop and rethink,'' admitted Romney.
``What is essential for the Games? What are the Games really
about?''
</P>
<P>
   The Games will be great for the athletes and spectators, Romney
promises, and they will break even. The Utah taxpayers will get
back the $59 million they spent on venues and the state will get
the $40 million sports endowment it's been promised. If they don't,
Romney won't take the $285,000 annual salary he's already
deferring.
</P>
<P>
   There's no free lunch _ or breakfast _ at MittFrugal's. No
embarrassing headlines, either. ``We're making progress,'' Romney
said. ``We're getting more boring. The problem with the Olympics
over the past year is that it was more about bureaucrats than
athletes. If we do our jobs right, we're invisible.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(sidebar) &QL; 
VISITS TO BID CITIES STILL AN ISSUE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While International Olympic Committee members are expected to
approve nearly all of the 50 proposed reforms when they meet at
their Swiss headquarters, they're divided on the one issue that
created the scandal in the first place _ visits to Olympic bid
cities.
</P>
<P>
   Though IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch wants to ban all
trips except for a small site evaluation group, some members insist
that they can't make an informed vote without them. ``If there are
visits in the future,'' said vice president Richard Pound of
Canada, ``my guess is that they'll be extremely tightly
controlled.''
</P>
<P>
   As a compromise, the IOC could organize trips at its own
expense. ``It's what Henry Kissinger calls the `big bus
alternative','' said US Olympic Committee president William Hybl,
who served with Kissinger on the IOC 2000 reform commission. ``Put
'em all on a bus and take them there.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtually everything else in the reform package _ from age
limits to term limits to a nominating and screening process for new
members _ should pass. That would allow Samaranch, who will step
down when his term ends in 2001, to claim that the embattled IOC
has remade itself when he testifies Wednesday before a
Congressional subcommittee in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a lot more movement than anyone expected a year
ago,'' concedes John Hancock president David D'Alessandro, the
IOC's most outspoken critic. ``I think Samaranch has gotten the
most he's ever going to get out of these characters.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Alessandro said it's too soon, though, to decide whether
Hancock will return as a top Olympic sponsor for the next
quadrennium. ``We will probably await the new leadership,'' he
said. ``The key is, can the new leader use these reforms to really
implement change?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
