<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4479 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     12-09 1461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTEWORTHY MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies. (STAR) denotes a highly recommended film
or series. Ratings and running times are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``ALL ABOUT MY MOTHER,'' starring Cecilia Roth, Marisa
Paredes, Antonia San Juan and Penelope Cruz. Directed by Pedro
Almodovar (R, 101 minutes). A whole new order of Almodovar
extravaganza. The antic fizz and theatrical exaggeration of this
filmmaker's earlier work have blossomed into a newly sophisticated
style, one that is far more wise and deeply felt. Lovingly
dedicated to actresses who have played actresses, this film weaves
its own soap opera around ``A Streetcar Named Desire'' and tells of
splendidly resilient women; the filmmaker has aptly described his
material as ``screwball drama.'' Rich and entertaining, this story
celebrates the power of artifice and impersonation to transcend
ordinary truth. The irrepressible Ms. San Juan, a Spanish nightclub
performer, plays a transsexual named Agrado and is the film's
biggest treat (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``AMERICAN BEAUTY,'' starring Kevin Spacey, Annette
Bening, Chris Cooper, Wes Bentley and Thora Birch. Written by Alan
Ball. Directed by Sam Mendes (R, 116 minutes). With heavenly
finesse, Spacey plays a buttoned-down 42-year-old suburbanite who
flips his lid for a teen-age cheerleader. And he never gets it back
on. The midlife crisis motif is familiar, but the stage director
Sam Mendes brings terrific visual flair and dry humor to this
barbecuing of the bourgeoisie. All the actors display coolly expert
timing, especially Ms. Bening as the antihero's grasping wife.
Although the story spreads itself thin among many characters, the
film coalesces for a devastating finale. (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``ANYWHERE BUT HERE,'' starring Susan Sarandon and
Natalie Portman. Directed by Wayne Wang (PG-13, 113 minutes). In a
knowing film adaptation of Mona Simpson's widely praised, if not
often wildly eventful, first novel, Ms. Sarandon is show-stopping
as the 14-year-old heroine's mother and main nemesis. And Ms.
Portman, who proves her mettle in a fully formed dramatic role,
does a terrific job of holding her own in the film's battle of
wills. Even when the material meanders, Wang supplies insightful,
affectionate direction, just as he did for ``The Joy Luck Club.'' A
picture made with feeling and acted with great flair (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``BEING JOHN MALKOVICH,'' starring John Cusack, Catherine
Keener, Cameron Diaz and (of course) John Malkovich. Written by
Charlie Kaufman and directed by Spike Jonze (R, 112 minutes).
Welcome to the fun house: in this exhilaratingly quirky first
feature by a stellar video director, the reigning fears and
obsessions of a technology-crazed, voyeuristic culture are given an
even wilder workout than they got from ``The Truman Show.'' Cusack
plays a discouraged puppeteer who accidentally finds a way into
Malkovich's mind. While the ordinary science-fiction plot might go
downhill after revealing its gimmick, this one's inspired craziness
goes on and on. Originality and cleverness abound (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``BOYS DON'T CRY,'' starring Hilary Swank and Chloe
Sevigny. Directed by Kimberly Peirce (R, 114 minutes). This
stunning debut feature tells the strange and resonant story of
Brandon Teena, who despite being born Teena Brandon went on to
create a charismatic identity as a young man. Brandon's ultimately
wrenching tale may sound tabloid-ready, but on screen it turns into
Theodore Dreiser's idea of American tragedy. The film makes it
hauntingly real and even tenderly romantic, with the astonishing
acting needed to make it work. One of the year's best (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``DOGMA,'' starring Matt Damon, Ben Affleck, Linda
Fiorentino and Chris Rock. Directed by Kevin Smith (R, 130
minutes). Smith's idea of angels in America is the notion of two
cool dudes who take a hair-splitting, legalese approach to Roman
Catholic doctrine and think it would be amusing to nullify all
existence. And nothing in this wildly brazen, unexpectedly devout
comedy is any less outrageous than that. Smith again shows off a
rare gift for fusing his comic-book sensibility with serious
debates and big, big laughs, even if some parts of his film (Ms.
Fiorentino's performance, Rock's and semi-repartee from Jay and
Silent Bob) work better than others (an excrement monster). Making
a gutsy leap into matters of faith, Smith miraculously emerges with
his humor intact and his wings unsinged (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``THE END OF THE AFFAIR,'' starring Ralph Fiennes,
Julianne Moore, Stephen Rea and Ian Hart. Directed by Neil Jordan
(R, 105 minutes). Jordan's intoxicating version of Graham Greene's
1951 novel, in which an illicit affair becomes a far greater gamble
than either lover could have imagined. For this fearlessly eclectic
filmmaker, this is one more intelligent, brooding love story with a
secret twist. Fiennes and Ms. Moore breathe life into this story
with a dreamy, erotic intensity that in no way trivializes the
film's underlying ideas about religious faith. Period detail (the
setting is London in the mid-1940s) is sumptuously heightened by
the inspired costume designer Sandy Powell (``Shakespeare in
Love'') (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``END OF DAYS,'' starring Arnold Schwarzenegger, Robin Tunney,
Gabriel Byrne and Kevin Pollak. Directed by Peter Hyams (R, 118
minutes). The star modestly tackles the role of a new savior who
may just keep mankind free of Satan for the next thousand years.
And that's not even the worst thing about this pointlessly nasty
would-be thriller. The material is so derivative that it amounts to
a tag sale of used parts from better apocalyptic films, with
special credit owed to ``The Exorcist'' for grisly sacrilegious
tricks. Hyams favors a jack-in-the-box approach to delivering shock
value. The star dutifully protects a nice young woman from demonic
forces. But Byrne plays the swaggering embodiment of pure evil and
has the better role (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``FELICIA'S JOURNEY,'' starring Elaine Cassidy and Bob
Hoskins. Directed by Atom Egoyan (PG-13, 116 minutes). In the
brilliantly realized surreal thriller, adapted from William
Trevor's popular novel, Felicia (Ms. Cassidy), a pregnant Irish
girl searching for her boyfriend in the English midlands, is
befriended by Joseph Hilditch ( Hoskins), a catering manager who
also happens to be a serial killer. Egoyan, Canada's most gifted
filmmaker, elevates this cat-and-mouse game into a film that
transcends genre by entering the characters' consciousness and
implying a world of half-discernible connections in which the
weather, the landscape and the chance encounters of strangers
suggest the sense of a grand design (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``FLAWLESS,'' starring Robert De Niro and Philip Seymour
Hoffman. Written and directed by Joel Schumacher (R, 110 minutes).
De Niro is a retired New York City policeman recovering from a
stroke and Hoffman the drag queen upstairs who gives him speech
therapy in the form of singing lessons in this stridently campy
comedy. Their flashy performances can't add dimension to a movie
that is a message-laden duet for two caricatures, a homophobe and
the angry, self-loathing drag queen who gets him out of his
depression (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``THE INSIDER,'' starring Al Pacino, Russell Crowe and
Christopher Plummer. Directed by Michael Mann (R, 155 minutes).
Mann directs this taut thriller about the tobacco industry
whistle-blower Jeffrey Wigand with pulse-quickening panache. And he
illustrates why, in the corporate climate of the '90s,
truth-telling is a riskier business than it was circa ``All the
President's Men.'' While Pacino delivers galvanizing moral outrage
as a producer for ``60 Minutes,'' and Plummer wickedly mimics Mike
Wallace, Crowe movingly captures the complexity of Wigand's
situation. Shaky docudrama ethics cloud the film's take on ``60
Minutes.'' But this is an inordinately well-played thriller, with
Mann's stylistic brio at its best (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``LIBERTY HEIGHTS,'' starring Adrien Brody, Joe Mantegna
and Ben Foster. Directed and written by Barry Levinson (R, 134
minutes). This semi-autobiographical comedy-drama remembering
teen-age life, anti-Semitism and racism in mid-1950s Baltimore is
the fourth movie by Levinson to be set in his native city. A deeply
felt nostalgia trip, the movie adroitly captures the look and
social attitudes of the city 45 years ago. But the screenplay and
performances are too muted for the movie to come to terms with
growing pains cushioned in the nostalgic haze (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``MANSFIELD PARK,'' starring Frances O'Connor and Jonny
Lee Miller. Written and directed by Patricia Rozema (PG-13, 105
minutes). In Ms. Rozema's skillful screen adaptation of Jane
Austen's third novel, the protagonist Fanny Price (Ms. O'Connor)
has been sharpened into a proto-feminist heroine who triumphs over
the materialist, patriarchal values of her wealthy relatives
through a combination of wit, beauty and daring. Without bearing
down too heavily, the screenplay (which incorporates fragments of
Austen's letters and diaries) equates early 19th-century slave
trading with the oppression of women. The message is leavened with
smart humor and warm three-dimensional performances (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``SLEEPY HOLLOW,'' starring Johnny Depp, Christina Ricci,
Miranda Richardson, Michael Gambon, Jeffrey Jones, Michael Gough
and Christopher Walken. Written by Andrew Kevin Walker and directed
by Tim Burton (R, 110 minutes). This ornate visual fantasy,
artfully concocted using a palette that suggests nuclear winter,
has little to do with Washington Irving's story and everything to
do with Burton's macabre vision. Depp makes a dashing hero as the
film's shy detective, but the story (by the writer of ``Seven'' and
``Fight Club'') is determined to put the ick into Ichabod Crane. A
first-rate cast and extraordinary technical talents are
attention-getting here, but so is the film's penchant for sardonic
beheadings. It's possible to admire Burton immensely, for the
secret tenderness and rich imagination of his work, without wanting
to peer at the exposed brain stems of his characters (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``SWEET AND LOWDOWN,'' starring Sean Penn, Samantha Morton and
Uma Thurman. Directed by Woody Allen (PG-13, 95 minutes). In homage
to the kind of jaunty 1930s jazz that has been heard on many of his
other films' soundtracks, Allen imagines a consummate jazz
character: Emmet Ray (played with gusto by Penn), who can play the
guitar as gorgeously as Django Reinhardt but lacks certain
interpersonal skills when it comes to his private life. Borrowing
attributes of various real musicians, the film turns Emmet into
another cad-genius of Allen's and gives him a long-suffering mute
laundress as a sweetheart (Ms. Morton works miracles in her
wordless role). But on the storytelling level, the film remains
flimsy. It's the musical interludes, frequent and lovingly
presented, that keep it alive (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``TOY STORY 2,'' with the voices of Tom Hanks and Tim
Allen. Directed by John Lasseter; a Pixar Animated Studios film (G,
98 minutes). A wonderfully playful sequel, sustaining the first
film's wit and novelty while bringing new sophistication to
computer-generated animation. And here is welcome proof that
Hollywood can still make movies to please audiences of any age or
persuasion. From its opening (a perfectly adorable ``Star Wars''
parody) to its Capraesque conclusion, this is seamless work with
more metaphorical cleverness than that usually found in the toy
bin. Colorful new characters and more adventurous action enhance
the story of how Woody falls into the clutches of a sleazy toy
dealer, experiences newfound celebrity and needs to be rescued by
his old friends (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``TUMBLEWEEDS,'' &UR;  &LR; starring Janet McTeer and Kimberly J.
Brown. Directed by Gavin O'Connor (PG-13, 100 minutes). An
astoundingly vital performance by the British actress Janet McTeer
makes this small, beautifully acted slice of contemporary Americana
a must-see film. Ms. McTeer is Mary Jo Walker, a sexy,
free-spirited woman with four marriages behind her who travels
across the country with her 12-year-old daughter, Ava (Ms. Brown).
Like few other films, this one captures an intimately loving
(though not conflict-free) relationship between a parent and child
without becoming saccharine. The director plays Mary Jo's trucker
boyfriend, who is only the latest in a series of her romantic
disasters (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE WORLD IS NOT ENOUGH,'' &UR;  &LR; starring Pierce Brosnan, Sophie
Marceau, Dame Judi Dench, Robert Carlyle and Denise Richards.
Directed by Michael Apted (PG-13, 128 minutes). This director is
much admired for his ``Up'' series chronicling the lives of former
schoolchildren as they mature. And he has managed to make James
Bond grow up a little, too. Brosnan has grown much more comfortable
with the role of Bond, and most of the other characters are also
more interesting than might have been expected. Ms. Marceau slinks
memorably through the role of a treacherous oil heiress. Ms.
Richards seemed a lot smarter playing high school vixens than she
does as a brilliant scientist here. The itinerary roams from
Scotland to Central Asia. And Apted handles the action as well as
he does the talk (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
