<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-DIVIDE-MEET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIDGING THE `DIGITAL DIVIDE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, executives of technology
companies and representatives of minorities and civil rights groups
announced a series of partnerships and initiatives Thursday to help
bridge the ``digital divide'' between technology haves and
have-nots, so that access to computers and the Internet would
become as common as that for the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   The programs and commitments were announced as Commerce
Secretary William Daley opened his department's first meeting to
address the problem of the widening gap in computer access. About
800 people attended the conference, which was intended to push
government agencies and private companies to do more to narrow the
gap.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech before the meeting, Clinton said he had directed
Cabinet members to take specific actions, like expanding community
technology centers in low-income neighborhoods and helping
low-income workers gain the skills they needed to compete for
higher paying jobs in information technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that we should set a national goal of making
computers and Internet access available for every American,'' the
president said in a memorandum to cabinet members. He directed
Daley to devise a national strategy to achieve that goal.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would use his next ``new markets'' tour of
disadvantaged communities in the spring to highlight the problem
and would then issue several directives intended to increase
government efforts in this area.
</P>
<P>
   During the discussion Thursday, participants noted that efforts
needed to focus beyond getting homes and schools connected to the
Web. Internet content, they said, needed to be developed to serve
the needs and interests of minorities and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's meeting was planned after the Commerce Department in
July released its second report on the issue, which showed a
growing disparity between those who have access to the Internet and
those who do not.
</P>
<P>
   The report found that 47 percent of whites own computers,
compared with 19 percent of blacks. It also said that a child in a
low-income white family was three times as likely to have Internet
access as a child in a comparable black family and four times as
likely as a Hispanic child.
</P>
<P>
   Daley said after the conference that he would work with Congress
to develop programs to address the problem, which could include
increased federal money for specific projects or special incentives
to encourage more private sector involvement.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting also allowed companies to showcase programs and
partnerships they were already planning.
</P>
<P>
   C. Michael Armstrong, chairman of AT&AMP;T, said his company would
donate $1 million to help train workers in technology. AT&AMP;T has
already given $1.4 million to community technology centers.
</P>
<P>
   America Online said it would provide online assistance to the
Leadership Conference on Civil Rights. The partnership would
provide technical assistance and training seminars and would
establish a group of ``circuit riders,'' teachers committed to
promoting Internet use among their students.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 1922EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
