<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4482 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS &LR;      12-09 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT BARKLEY, OLAJUWON, ROCKETS LESS OF A CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Celtics will be guarding against a letdown when
they face the Charles Barkley- and Hakeem Olajuwon-less Houston
Rockets Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am disappointed,'' coach Rick Pitino said Thursday of the
absence of Barkley, whose career ended early when he ruptured a
knee tendon Wednesday night. ``We all wanted to say goodbye to
Charles in the proper way. He has been a great ambassador for the
NBA and we are going to miss his glib way of talking. I think we
would all like to be Charles for a day and be able to say whatever
we feel like saying, without any repercussions, except maybe a fine
from the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard he might go into politics. I'm sure he will stay
around basketball but he is not going to be a coach. He is the
opposite of a coach. We have to say a lot of things that are
politically correct.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pitino is wary of the Rockets. And he is keeping the
Celtics' position in perspective after a 115-90 victory over Denver
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Philadelphia without Iverson,'' Pitino said. ``When
a team loses its bespyer they can be like a wounded tiger and we
are aware of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are good enough to beat Miami but not strong enough to beat
the Bulls, who only have one victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino has used the Celtics' failures to impart lessons and
provide motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``At halftime against the Nuggets we used the Milwaukee game as
an example of how a team can come back,'' Pitino said. ``We wanted
to make sure that didn't happen, because the Nuggets are a great
comeback team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics lost a close one at Philadelphia Saturday night but
have won two of their last three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are still a great team without Barkley,'' center Tony
Battie said of the Rockets. ``You have to prepare for them like
they have Charles. If not, you open yourself up to some surprises.
They will pick it up in his absence. It's the NBA and everyone can
play. Steve Francis is capable of a 35-point game and they are
stacked down low.''
</P>
<P>
   Battie has 40 points, 39 rebounds and 8 blocked shots in the
last three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for consistency from Tony and it's been there
the last three games,'' Pitino said. ``But sometimes he gets into
foul trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Battie, 23, has brought aggressiveness and dynamism to the
center position as a complement for starter Vitaly Potapenko.
</P>
<P>
   I expect to play as hard as I can, bring to the team what I can
bring and help get a win,'' Battie said. ``Lately, I've been doing
some good things. I've been having some good practices and the team
has been having good practices and we've been able to take that
into games.''
</P>
<P>
   Battie leads the team with 60 personal fouls, and he committed
five fouls without blocking a shot or making a steal against
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to pick and choose when to be aggressive,'' Battie
said. ``Sometimes if the team is scoring I want to hawk the ball a
little bit, get some deflections and sometimes that can be costly.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you have six fouls to play with and that should be more
than enough. If I don't have three before halftime I'm fine.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Walter McCarty will play, then have his foot bruise reevaluated.
</P>
</TEXT>
