<SLUG> BC-U.N.-CORPORATE-DONORS-640(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUGE COMPANIES COLLABORATE WITH U.N. TO GAIN GLOBAL MARKETING EDGE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Amoco started drilling for oil in Angola a few years ago,
Exxon and Chevron had already landed some of the richest oil fields
and could easily outbid their smaller rival for others. Lately,
though, Amoco has been the successful bidder on several oil tracts.
</P>
<P>
   Why? The company, which is now BP Amoco, realized that the
Angolan government, torn by civil war, was ready to favor any
company that was also willing to assist with social projects. So in
1997 Amoco offered to spend $800,000 to help local fishermen revive
an abandoned fishing port _ and asked the local office of the U.N.
Development Program to manage the project.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, Amoco and the development program have
helped repair or replace about a dozen boats, equipped them with a
variety of gear, and recruited a local bank to set up a loan
program for the fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know anything about fishing, or managing social
projects,'' said Finda Koroma, then Amoco's director for commercial
development and now a consultant in Houston. ``Companies don't
always understand what the U.N.'s development arms can do for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   They are understanding it more and more. Across the world, huge
companies that once shrugged off the United Nations as a worthy, if
often ineffectually bureaucratic, do-good agency are now viewing it
as a valuable partner. And the United Nations, for a change, is not
only welcoming their help but seeking it out.
</P>
<P>
   United Nations agencies rarely troll for money alone. ``We are
not interested in donations, but in relationships that let us tap
into their expertise,'' said John G. Ruggie, assistant secretary
general for strategic planning.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, companies know that if they help the United
Nations with its pet projects, it will open doors and act as a
valuable buffer between them and the governments of countries in
which they wish to operate. For computer and health care companies,
which along with the oil companies are leading the new trend toward
collaboration, it is also a chance to introduce their brands to
growing markets, while playing up to agencies that routinely buy
their products.
</P>
<P>
   All this a huge change for the United Nations, which a few years
ago was so terrified of losing its patina of impartiality that it
turned down an offer from Coca-Cola to help would-be entrepreneurs
in poor countries sell beverages at sporting events, lest it seem
to be favoring Coke over Pepsi. The United Nations still carefully
guards its neutral image; it does not promote specific companies.
But now it does not turn its back, either. Instead, it solicits
help from all of an industry's players.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can set up a nonexclusive arrangement with a company to
co-finance a project, why not?'' said Mark Malloch Brown, a former
World Bank vice president who has run the development program since
July. ``It's not like we're saying Microsoft gets Botswana, Corel
gets Ghana; we're stimulating competition.''
</P>
<P>
   It is tempting to link the new corporate camaraderie to the
United Nations' much-publicized financing crunch, but it would
probably have come about anyway. What had been a trickle of
private-sector investment in sub-Saharan Africa, Asia, Latin
America and other developing economies has become a flood.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, private sources invested just $43.6 billion in the
developing world. In 1997, some $252 billion of private-sector
money flowed into developing countries, compared with $77 billion
from the World Bank and other public sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the U.N.'s member countries hadn't gotten past their
distaste for foreign investment, we could never have done our own
outreach,'' said Henry Jackelen, director of the development
program's private-sector operation. ``They realize that the
companies are sources of expertise and resources they can't get
elsewhere.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
