<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-RODWIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LLOYD RODWIN, AT 80; PIONEER IN URBAN STUDIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Lloyd Rodwin, a pioneer in the multidisciplinary
approach to the field of urban studies, died of congestive heart
failure Tuesday in Massachusetts General Hospital. He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Rodwin was a retired professor of urban studies at the
Massachusetts Institute Technology and co-founder of the
MIT-Harvard Joint Center for Urban Studies. He was renowned for his
analyses of urban and regional problems in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   He oversaw the organization of one of the most extensive efforts
to design a new city _ Ciudad Guayana _ at the confluence of the
Orinoco and Careen rivers in Venezuela. To plan the city, Mr.
Rodwin led an interdisciplinary team from the MIT-Harvard Joint
Center, which he co-founded with Martin Meyerson in 1959. The
combined efforts of economists, anthropologists, sociologists, and
other social scientists, as well as land-use planners, became a
model for a new kind of integrated planning. Following his 1969
book on this project, ``Planning Urban Growth and Regional
Development,'' his colleagues published seven others that analyzed
the Ciudad Guayana project from diverse disciplinary perspectives.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, MIT professor Bernard Frieden, a student of Mr. Rodwin
and one of his successors as head of the Center for Urban Studies,
said, ``Lloyd really changed the field from city planning to urban
studies. He emphasized research on how cities work and worked with
people outside of planning like Pat Moynihan ( US Senator Daniel
Patrick Moynihan of New York), James Q. Wilson, Oscar Handlin, Alan
Altshuler, and Martin Meyerson. Lloyd made the field much broader,
and extended it to the Third World.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Rodwin was born in Brooklyn, N.Y. He attended City College
in New York City, where he studied with and was deeply influenced
by philosopher Morris Raphael Cohen. He then studied at New School
for Social Research before earning a master's degree in land
economics at the University of Wisconsin and a doctorate in
regional planning at Harvard University in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   His view that social science should complement physical planning
helped change planning education in the United States. While
chairman of the MIT Department of Urban Studies and Planning from
1969-1973, he oversaw a tripling of the faculty. He transformed the
department by introducing new social science faculty and course
work as well as a focus on international comparative studies,
housing policy, environmental policy, and economic development. The
MIT program served as a model for others around the world.
</P>
<P>
   He was the author or editor of 11 books, including a forthcoming
edited volume, with Bishwapriya Sanyal, titled ``The Profession of
City Planning: Changes, Images and Challenges, 1950-2000.''
</P>
<P>
   As a teacher, he trained generations of planners around the
world. He was known for his use of Socratic questioning, a
technique he drew from his studies in philosophy and applied to the
study of complex and controversial issues in planning. In the
classroom, Mr. Rodwin would typically get students to state their
position and then argue the opposite side. When asked what they
learned years later, students often said, ``He taught us how to
think.''
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Nadine Posniak Rodwin of Cambridge; two
sons, Victor G. of New York and Marc A. of Bloomington, Ind.; a
daughter, Julie A. of Groton; a brother, Ted Rosenbaum, and a
sister, Claire Levy of Laguna Hills, Calif.; and six grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 1924EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4486 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-U.N.-CORPORATE-DONORS     12-09 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-CORPORATE-DONORS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: get elsewhere.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Corporate largess to the United Nations is not entirely new, of
course. Ted Turner made headlines when he donated $1 billion of
stock in 1997. And the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation has
earmarked $26 million to help UNICEF wipe out tetanus in infants.
</P>
<P>
   But these were philanthropic gifts spearheaded by individuals
whose money was derived from their industrial activities. The new
trend is for companies themselves to use U.N. collaboration as a
marketing tool, not just a philanthropic one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course we want to help eradicate neonatal tetanus, but we
also want to stimulate the use of nonreusable injection devices,
and to build relationships with ministries of health that might buy
other products from us as their economies develop,'' said Gary M.
Cohen, president of the medical systems unit of Becton Dickinson &AMP;
Co. He is working with UNICEF _ one of its biggest customers for
syringes and other medical devices _ to distribute the company's
patented disposable syringes for the same anti-tetanus program the
Gates Foundation is supporting.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are the companies confining their giving to their own
products and expertise. Many, particularly oil companies, are
contributing to U. N. programs on entrepreneurship and human
rights, in hopes of promoting stability in countries with civil
unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for example, Chevron, which had been drilling oil in
Kazakhstan for five years, contributed $500,000 toward a business
center, run by the U.N. Development Program, that helps
Kazakhstanis set up new businesses. Citigroup's Citibank is in on
the project, too, helping to run an operation that gives
entrepreneurs small loans.
</P>
<P>
   The center, which operates in the same building in the city of
Atyrau as Chevron, has already yielded 19 businesses. It helped a
local doctor set up a private ambulance service, and a
businesswoman rent refrigerators to stock and sell ice cream. Now,
it is helping locals set up a bowling alley in the region, as well
as Atyrau's first supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   ``It boils down to our desire to have a stable economic and
political environment in which to operate, and to stimulate the
local economy,'' said Philip L. Meek, president of Chevron
Munaigas, Chevron's Kazakhstan operation.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, companies could donate products or services without
using the United Nations as a go-between. But in many parts of the
world, the concept of free enterprise is so new that they do not
know where to begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bridge to the community was essential in a country that had
no real grass-roots civil society before 1989,'' said Zoltan
Valcsicsak, who handles community affairs for Levi Strauss in
Europe, the Middle East and Africa. Levi Strauss recently funneled
$40,000 to the development program to help combat AIDS in Poland,
where it has a plant.
</P>
<P>
   Other executives note that U.N. officials understand the
sensitivities of governments that do not want to think of
themselves as backwards. ``The U.N. has been in Russia a lot longer
than we have,'' said John McKeegan, a spokesman for Johnson &AMP;
Johnson, which recently elicited the development program's help in
setting up an educational program for cardiologists in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Reza Ghaffari, who runs Citibank's offices in
Kazakhstan, notes that the development program encouraged local
entrepreneurs to take group loans, on the theory that peer pressure
would go far in encouraging all members to repay their shares. ``We
could have just donated the money without bothering to insist on a
sustainable initiative,'' Ghaffari said, ``but this approach will
have a greater impact on the community.''
</P>
<P>
   And, perhaps the United Nations' most powerful lure of all is
that it provides an administrative backbone for projects that
companies would just as soon not undertake alone. ``Private
industry really doesn't have the expertise to run community
programs,'' said Anne Krisitin Sydnes, a vice president of Statoil,
the big Norwegian oil company, which hooked up with the development
program and Amnesty International last year for a project to train
Venezuelan judges on how to deal with human rights issues.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the United Nations rarely has the expertise to pull
nascent economies into the Internet age. Take the development
program's NetAid project, which was kicked off with benefit
concerts in New Jersey, London and Geneva on Oct. 9. Unlike Farm
Aid and similar fund-raising concerts, NetAid was not a one-shot
deal; the development program persuaded numerous Internet-related
companies that it was to their benefit to help it use the concerts
to publicize www.netaid.org, a Web site the development program
hopes to parlay into a matchmaking tool for corporations and
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems, a major provider of the routers, switchers and
other equipment that powers the Internet, provided much of the
marketing, as well as the technology to enable millions of people
to tap into the concerts online. Cisco, in turn, persuaded the
accounting and consulting firm KPMG, which it partly owns, to
design the Web page. And it persuaded Akamai, a year-old technology
firm, to contribute its expertise in easing Internet logjams. ``It
seemed a terrific way to showcase our technology,'' said an
executive at Akamai, which recently went public.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, high-technology involvement is not ending with NetAid.
Orientation.com, a New York-based company that runs an
advertising-supported network of Internet portals in 20 countries,
is providing material for portals that the development program
wants to run in an additional 31 countries. ``The UNDP gives us
contact with their partners in new countries, and with information
that we can use on our other portals,'' said Tamara Bekefi, a
project manager at Orientation.com.
</P>
<P>
   Corel, a software company based in Ottawa, is contributing a
suite of business-oriented software for the development program to
use in its effort to set up Internet systems in developing
countries. Corel's software runs on the Linux operating system,
which can be downloaded free from the Internet, and it figures that
if Web novices get used to Linux now, they are less likely to flock
to Windows later. Indeed, Corel has thrown Netscape Navigator, a
prime competitor to Microsoft's Internet Explorer, into its
package.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft is still the clear No. 1, and if we can foster brand
loyalty early on, maybe we can level the playing field,'' said
Michael Cowpland, Corel's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Other computer companies have similar aims. Rebel.com, a
Canadian hardware company that Corel partly owns, figures that
computers operated by a free system like Linux are likely to sell
well in poorer countries. ``Our investment is not under the veil of
philanthropy,'' said Michael Mansfield, president of Rebel.com,
which is contributing about $250,000 worth of computers. ``It is
coming out of our marketing budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Such strategic thinking is starting to pervade some U.N.
agencies themselves. Its Population Fund, which distributes
contraceptives in developing countries, is setting up meetings
between drug executives and officials in Egypt and India, in hopes
of helping the companies overcome high tariffs and other barriers
to selling contraceptives there. And the fund expects to set up a
Web-based system eventually, one in which governments can buy
contraceptives at prices the fund has negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't even asking for product donations,'' said Corrie
Shanahan, a spokeswoman for the fund. So why bother? ``If the
companies sell contraceptives to the middle classes in those
countries, it will free up our supply for poor people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
