<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-LEVIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURRAY B. LEVIN, 72; AUTHOR, POLITICAL SCIENCE PROFESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Murray Burton Levin of Newton, a retired professor of
political science at Boston University who published volumes on
America's alienated voters and the political discourse on radio
talk shows, died Wednesday in Brigham and Women's Hospital in
Boston. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
   In Mr. Levin's first book, ``The Alienated Voter,'' published in
1960, he explored what he called ``the widespread belief that
voters feel impotent, believe that all politicians are crooks and
assume that the outcome of elections is meaningless.''
</P>
<P>
   In his follow-up, ``The Compleat Politician,'' in 1962, he
studied how candidates court these alienated voters. In ``Kennedy
Campaigning'' in 1966, he examined the power of big money and the
appeal of what he called ``beautiful people.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Levin explored the McCarthyism of the 1950s in ``Political
Hysteria in America'' (1971) and the dynamics of talk radio and the
emergence of what he called ``peean conservatism in ``Talk Radio
and the American Dream'' (1986).
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Levin estimated he taught more than 18,000 students during
his 30 years at Boston University. He also taught at Stonehill
College and Harvard University Extension School and appeared many
times as a political analyst on the CBS, NBC, and PBS television
networks.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Brookline. He graduated from Harvard College and
earned a doctorate in political science at Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   After his retirement from full-time teaching at Boston
University in 1990, he taught urban politics to high-risk
adolescents for Action for Boston Community Development.
</P>
<P>
   This led to his 1998 book,``Teach Me: Kids Will Learn When
Oppression is the Lesson'' , about what he learned teaching at the
Greater Egleston Community High School, an alternative school in
Jamaica Plain with a student body of youths who had failed to learn
at mainstream schools.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his death he was writing a book with the working
title ``Political Consultants in the Age of Illusion.''
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Helen Jacobson; three sons, Joshua C. of
Newton, Jacob P. Goldstein of Cambridge and Seth Goldstein of
Boston; and a daughter, Jessica Goldstein of Stoughton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 1925EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4491 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BELLSOUTH-GERMANY10-C     12-09 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-GERMANY10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth to join Dutch bid for firm
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth today will announce a $9 billion partnership
with a Dutch phone company to bid for E-Plus, a German wireless
provider, setting the stage for the Atlanta-based company to make
still more inroads in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   With the move, BellSouth is demonstrating a renewed
international interest. The deal pits it against the two biggest
phone companies in Europe, both of which have been mentioned as
possible partners for BellSouth: France Telecom, which had a bid on
the table to buy E-Plus, and Deutsche Telekom, on whose turf E-Plus
competes.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth already owns 22.5 percent of E-Plus Mobilfunk,
Germany's third-largest wireless carrier, and had a right of first
refusal on the rest. The company could have forsworn that right and
forged a pact that permitted France Telecom to take control.
BellSouth also could have blocked France Telecom as part of an
embrace with its archrival Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it chose a third way, jockeying to block France Telecom
while partnering with an aggressive, but smaller player: KPN
Telecom NV. That company is, in some ways, in a similar position to
that of BellSouth: large enough to be ambitious, but perhaps not
big enough to fend off a takeover. Unlike BellSouth, KPN Telecom
has been separating itself into units that might let it find
partners who wouldn't be interested in working with the whole
company.
</P>
<P>
   The complex deal with BellSouth would make E-Plus a joint
venture between the two companies. On Thursday, BellSouth officials
did not specify how big its portion of the $9 billion partnership
would be.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of partnership with KPN Telecom opens the door to the
kind of ties that any U.S. company needs to compete in Europe _ and
vice versa. KPN has a range of businesses, including operations in
Belgium, Holland, Hungary, the Czech Republic and Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
   One ambitious option bandied about as part of the E-Plus deal
was the merger of KPN's wireless properties with E-Plus and
BellSouth's wireless unit in Denmark and perhaps its mobile data
investments in the United Kingdom, the Netherlands and Belgium.
However, it appears that the companies will not go that far _ at
least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   But just bidding for E-Plus is bold for several reasons.
</P>
<P>
   First, it is a fair chunk of change. France Telecom has offered
$9 billion for the 77.5 percent of E-Plus that BellSouth does not
own. Current stake owners Vodafone AirTouch and two German
utilities are selling their shares.
</P>
<P>
   The largest deal BellSouth has made in the recent past was last
year's $3.5 billion investment in Qwest Communications. That bought
10 percent of Qwest, a stake cut in half by Qwest's merger with US
West.
</P>
<P>
   But the most money BellSouth ever dropped on the table was the
failed $100 billion bid to outgun MCI WorldCom at the 11th hour for
Sprint in October. MCI WorldCom came back with a dramatically
higher offer and BellSouth withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth was seen by some as having missed its last opportunity
to find the muscle and reach it needs to compete in what
increasingly is a global market. Analysts whispered of BellSouth's
vulnerabilities, its tacit admission that it needed to make a big
deal.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sprint bid also proved that BellSouth was willing to
move, and the purchase of E-Plus would show that BellSouth has not
been paralyzed by the failed effort to buy Sprint. It also may show
that BellSouth is not afraid of the ever more raucous competition
in a deregulated European market that seems ripe for consolidation,
acquisitions and rapid growth.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, it signals that BellSouth wants to be considered a
global player _ despite the vastly greater size amassed by
companies like AT&AMP;T, British Telecom, MCI WorldCom, SBC and Bell
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth for some time boasted of its three-legged strategy,
splitting its hopes on its Southeast franchise in local service,
its wireless business and its international investments. But it has
been some time since BellSouth added to its presence in Europe, the
most lucrative market outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth is the largest outside investor in Latin America but
has been marginal elsewhere. BellSouth has a wireless unit in
Israel and two operations on the Continent: Denmark, where it owns
46.5 percent of a wireless system, and Germany, the region's
largest economy.
</P>
<P>
   E-Plus has 3.1 million customers, 16 percent of the German
wireless business. The company has revenue of about $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's current interest is worth about $3 billion, based on
the France Telecom bid. Yet KPN Telecom has made arrangements for a
loan of about $13.3 billion, apparently preparing for still more
investments.
</P>
<P>
   Europe, whose telecommunications sectors are currently in the
throes of deregulation, is expected to see rapid growth in
services. Moreover, the region will likely see a slew of
consolidations as national companies are privatized to face
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Among the possible partners is Qwest, which is building a
high-speed network in Europe. As part of that effort, Qwest already
has a joint venture with KPN Telecom.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
