<HEADLINE>
RIVERS URGES BLACK LEADERS TO CONFRONT SEX ISSUE IN AIDS CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WIL HAYGOOD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Rev. Eugene Rivers brought his Boston-based
urban ministry to the nation's capital Thursday and unspooled an
evangelical salvo against black church and political leaders, in
his effort to bring attention to the plight of AIDS in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Believing the crisis _ which has already claimed 12 million
lives in sub-SaharaAica _ to be directly linkedto ``sexual
promiscuity,'' Rivers charged that black American leaders, in and
out of the pulpit, have been reluctant to discuss the role of
sexual behavior in the crisis because of what he called
``hypocrisy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's flush it all out of the bushes, all of this nonsense
about irresponsible sexual behavior being OK,'' Rivers said in a
60-minute address at the National Press Club. He was flanked by a
dozen ministers and activists he has recruited from around the
country for his effort. ``We must get the ministers themselves
right on this issue also. They can't preach one thing on Sunday
then go out abusing women the rest of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivers said he has no doubts that he can connect black America
to the AIDS crisis in Africa. ``Everybody is talking about
globalization, why shouldn't American blacks?'' he said. ``What
happens to the little black girl in Harare is the same as what
happems to the little black girl in Harlem. The little black girl
in Harare listens to hip-hop music produced in Harlem and uses it
as an introduction into a life of sexual decadence and
degradation.''
</P>
<P>
   Many members of Rivers's 21st Century Group _ the intellectual
arm of his 10-point Coalition, which focuses on urban woes _ also
attended.
</P>
<P>
   Rivers released an ``open letter'' Thursday, outlining the AIDS
crisis and calling upon black American leaders to become engaged in
efforts to bring international attention to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Rivers is also calling on each black American church to identify
an AIDS sufferer in either America or Africa, and support that
person ``materially or financially.'' He announced a national
summit on AID to be held in Los Angeles in early 2000 at the West
Los Angeles Church of God in Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Rivers also announced plans to apply diplomatic pressure to
retrieve some of the ``billions'' of dollars corrupt African
leaders have siphoned from their governments and have that money
deposited in a special fund for AIDS victims.
</P>
<P>
   At times in his address, Rivers, dressed in full ministerial
garb, thundered like a Sunday morning preacher who has been absent
from his pulpit too long. He thundered when he announced that he
has every intention to turn the African AIDS crisis into an
election-year issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (Vice President Al) Gore does th right thing, he should be
blessed,'' Rivers said. ``If he doesn't, he should be held
accountable for his sins. The same goes for (Texas Governor) George
W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Ronald Clifton Potter of Jackson, Miss., was one of the
ministers who spoke with Rivers at the Press Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we take this challenge of promiscuity seriously,'' Potter
said, ``we take the old prophecy of `can these bones be saved?' The
question comes back, `Lord, only you know.' Well, let us be part of
that answer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Amen,'' came the loud chorus led by Rivers.
</P>
</TEXT>
