<SLUG> BC-VITAPRO-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS WINS LEGAL BATTLE OVER PRISON FOOD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Montreal) 
 
By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The state has won a legal battle that could save
taxpayers more than $30 million in a prolonged contractual fight
over an unpopular prison food.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Supreme Court ruled Thursday that the prison system's
massive purchase of VitaPro, a soy-based product that was dished
out as a cost-saving meat substitute from 1994-96, was illegal
because competitive bids weren't sought.
</P>
<P>
   If the ruling stands, Texas won't have to pay the Canadian
company that provided the food in a controversial arrangement that
led to the indictment of the company's owner and a top prison
official.
</P>
<P>
   After inmates and guards claimed that the food _ served in main
dishes such as casseroles, enchiladas and meatless loafs _ made
them ill, prison officials stopped serving VitaPro in mid-1996 and
began feeding it to livestock.
</P>
<P>
   At least 200,000 pounds of the food pellets were delivered to
the prison system under long-term contracts that initially called
for delivery of up to 39 metric tons a month, with a projected
total cost between $33 million and $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   The latest ruling was based on a finding that the food pellets,
made from processed soybeans, dehydrated vegetables and flavoring,
were not an ``agricultural commodity'' or raw material that might
have been exempt from bidding requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Purchase orders for VitaPro that were construed as contracts are
not binding, the state's highest civil court determined in its
unanimous opinion. It reversed a 1998 decision by a Texarkana
appellate court, which said a trial was warranted to further
scrutinize the contracts, and it upheld a 1996 ruling in the
state's favor by a Huntsville district court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed in the decision. We thought the Texarkana
court of appeals had it right when they said there were issues for
a jury to resolve,'' said VitaPro attorney P. Michael Jung of
Dallas. ``We're still evaluating our options'' regarding appeals,
he added.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996 decision, state District Judge Bill McAdams decided
that the state was not obligated to pay the full amount of the
purchase orders because the official who issued them was not
authorized to do so without approval of the Texas Board of Criminal
Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Although purchase orders totaled more than $33 million, only
$3.3 million was paid to the producer, VitaPro Foods Inc. of
Montreal. No refund is being sought on the amount already paid.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal investigators subsequently said the official
who ramrodded the five-year deal, former prisons director James A.
``Andy'' Collins, was on VitaPro's payroll _ before and after he
left the top job at the Institution Division of the Texas
Department of Criminal Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said records indicated Collins agreed to accept
$20,000 from VitaPro a month before he resigned under fire on Dec.
31, 1995. The money was transferred to Collins after he left the
state job, when he became a $1,000-a-day consultant to VitaPro for
a short time, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1998, Collins and VitaPro president Yank Barry were
indicted by a federal grand jury in Houston on multiple counts of
conspiracy, bribery, money laundering and other charges. Collins is
scheduled to stand trial on Jan. 25 before U.S. District Judge Lynn
N. Hughes. Barry's trial is set for February.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
