<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-PEACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELIS DEBATE PROSPECT OF PEACE WITH SYRIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV _ Israelis woke up Thursday to the prospect of peace
with Syria, perhaps their most bitter enemy, and quickly began
debating the price they are willing to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   In the cafes and crowded streets of downtown Tel Aviv, people
read morning papers headlined with Wednesday night's announcement
that Israel and Syria would reopen talks for the first time in
three years by holding unprecedented high-level, face-to-face talks
in Washington next week aimed at clinching a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an insane risk. It's not worth it,'' said Shai Krel, 28,
who during his three years in the Israeli Defense Forces was
stationed along the border with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Sipping espresso outside the tobacco store he owns on Ibn Givrol
Street, he added, ``Peace is not in the land, it is in the mind. .
. . I've never been convinced that Syria really wants peace with
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Odelia Arad, a 28-year-old law student, pulling hard on a
Marlboro Light before taking a set of final exams, was thrilled
about the possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be having humus in Damascus,'' she said, adding that
she trusted Barak to ensure Israel's safety in any possible deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel feels safe in his hands,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   How Israelis feel about Wednesday's stunning diplomatic
breakthrough is more than just an excercise in gauging public
opinion. The whole process could hinge on a unique voter referendum
in Israel which will be held in the aftermath of any agreement that
is reached.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to an agreement will not be easy. Even if all the
generals and all the heads of state work out every technical aspect
of security and demilitarization of the border. Even if Israel
gives up the strategic Golan Heights which it captured from Syria
in 1967 and held onto in bloody fighting in 1973. It will still all
come down to a vote in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak was elected in part on the
promise that he would bring to a vote any final agreements on the
Syrian track and on the for-now bogged down Palestinian track, and
he says he is going to stick by it.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, quoted Thursday in Israel's mass-market daily Yediot
Ahronot, said a ``decisive and sweeping'' majority of Israelis
would back him up in the referendum.
</P>
<P>
   The referendum would be the first of its kind in Israel's 50
years, and is an experimental form of of diplomacy by consensus
that has only rarely been tested before in other parts of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Minister Yossi Beilin, one of the architects of the
original peace process begun six years ago with the Palestinians
and five years ago with Syria, said at a meeting with reporters
Thursday, ``We will have to deal now very intensively with
preparations for a referendum. Without a referendum there won't be
any implementation of an agreement between Syiria and ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Yehuda Ben Meir, a senior researcher at Tel Aviv University's
Jaffee Center and an expert on public opinion and the peace
process, said the result of the referendum would depend on more
than just the final agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition to technical security measures, the Israeli people
will be looking for gestures from Syria that convince them there is
a genuine change. When (slain Egyptian President Anwar) Sadat came
to Ben Gurion Ariport and then the Knessett, Israelis saw that he
was serious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take a dramatic gesture like this,'' said Ben Meir,
referring to Sadat's historic visit which paved the way for the
historic 1979 Camp David agreement between Egypt and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Beilin said that if an agreement is reached, ``This will be the
end of slogans. We have to give up something and they have to give
up something. And that is our test. This is again subject to the
referendum, with both the Syrians and the Palestinians, we will
have to go back to the people and get them to allow us to sign.''
</P>
<P>
   The government of Syrian President Hafez Assad has long insisted
that any agreement is impossible without Israel's return of the
Golan Heights to borders that existed before the 1967 war when
Israel seized the military high ground that looms over much of
northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Some 18,000 Israelis live in the Golan, where wineries and
cattle ranches dot the countryside. The heights are a crucial water
resource in a region where water is as precious as life. It is the
main source of the Jordan River and borders the Sea of Galilee, two
sources which provide more than one-third of Israel's drinking
water.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has said since he was elected five months ago that he was
willing to consider returning Golan territory, but with strict
security conditions, a dismantling of Syria's massive military
presence along the border, and control over water resources.
</P>
<P>
   Already the political lobbying for the referendum has begun.
</P>
<P>
   Legendary hawk and opposition Likud party leader Ariel Sharon
scoffed at Barak's assertion that he is going into the talks
without any agreements on what it would give up to Syria, saying
the talks were a ``total surrender'' to Syrian demands.
</P>
<P>
   Uri Heitner, a spokesman for the Golan Residents Committee, said
giving back the heights would be bowing to the ``the dictates of a
Syrian tyrant'' and said the right-leaning members of Barak's
coalition government would battle him tooth and nail on any
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   At the talks in Washington Assad will be represented by his
foreign minister, Farouk al-Sharaa, and Barak will himself attend.
The meeting between a prime minister and foreign minister would
seem diplomatically awkward, but Israeli and US officials Thursday
insisted that Sharaa was handling the talks because of the
practical concerns over the health of the ailing 69-year-old Assad.
</P>
<P>
   Assad's regime was busy doing its own shoring up of public
opinion Thursday. Syrian newspapers carried banner headlines and
large photographs of Assad and Clinton, with Barak noticeably not
featured. A commentary in the official Tishrin daily said Syria
would not give up ``one iota'' of the Golan.
</P>
<P>
   How the reopening of the Syrian track of negotiations could
affect the stalled talks between Palestinians and Israelis was an
issue of concern on the streets of Palestinian areas in East
Jerusalem, the West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat made public pronouncements of
his pleasure at the opening of the talks with Syria. But privately
Palestinian officials confirmed that the bad blood between Arafat
and Assad, which dates back to Lebanon's long civil war, is no
secret. And one Palestinian official said that there are private
concerns that Barak will ignore the more difficult stages of the
Palestinian talks, which are stalled on the issue of settlement
expansion, to focus on Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Amnon Lipkin-Shahak, the former military chief of staff and
current tourism minister in Barak's cabinet, has played key roles
in earlier negotiations on both the Palestinian and Syrian tracks.
He dismissed the notion that the two tracks could not progress in
unison and offered the negotiations with neighboring Jordan which
were clinched in 1996 while the Palestinian peace process also
unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did it then and we can do it now,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 1931EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4497 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-NASA-EDIT-AZR &LR;      12-09 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-EDIT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA NEEDS PUBLIC'S SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX A $165 million loss is hard to swallow. But the gag
reflex over what happened to the Mars Polar Lander shouldn't choke
off funding or support for NASA.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency's gee-whiz days of taking men to the moon may
seem as far away as the Red Planet. But the potential for great
accomplishments remains, and the importance of a healthy space
exploration program is as real as the coming millennium.
</P>
<P>
   NASA taught us more than the average person can comprehend about
outer space. But that knowledge did not come without failure.
Today's failure can lead to tomorrow's insights and improvements.
</P>
<P>
   But NASA can't do great things as the timid, angst-ridden
whipping boy of a disenchanted public. It needs the brash, can-do
attitude of its glorious past to overcome today's setbacks. Public
support can help it re-create that powerful Big Man on Campus
mind-set. The loss of public support can lead to NASA's complete
failure and enduring defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there's room for soul-searching, and there's plenty of
reason to demand explanations. It's not just the Mars missions that
are troubled. The space shuttle Discovery's journey to rescue the
Hubble Space Telescope has been delayed as NASA ponders what to do
about a badly dented fuel line.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's ``faster, cheaper, better'' approach may need
rethinking, as Fred DeJarnette, founding director of the Mars
Mission Research Center at North Carolina State University, said.
</P>
<P>
   But the source of that strategy is likely the budget cuts that
NASA has suffered in Congress. In an opinion piece in today's
``Republic,'' physics professor and author Robert L. Park points
out that those cuts fall disproportionately on NASA's science
program because Congress is pushing the $100 billion International
Space Station.
</P>
<P>
   Charges that NASA's three Mars mission failures are due to
mismanagement or incompetence should not be dismissed. But it's
worth asking whether the mismanagement is at the agency or
congressional level.
</P>
<P>
   After vainly straining its most sophisticated electronic ears
for communication from the Mars Polar Lander and its separate twin
miniprobes, NASA has given up on hearing anything.
</P>
<P>
   But despite chuckling at Jay Leno's NASA-inspired barbs, the
public should not give up on the space agency. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
