u f BC-STATES-OIL-NAT     12-09 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-OIL-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        OIL PRICES TOO HIGH, ENERGY SECRETARY SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Alex Canizares  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Dec. 9 - Department of Energy Sec. Bill Richardson
said oil prices are ``dangerously'' high and said he would consider
contingency options to stabilize prices if they continue to climb
in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``As any secretary of energy I am prepared to recommend to the
president any steps are necessary to protect the American consumer
and the American economy,'' Richardson told reporters after
speaking at an energy security conference. ``I want to see what
happens in the next few weeks to determine what further action we
might take.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to explain what action this would be and refused to
name specific price levels that would trigger a move. But the
secretary said that $27 per barrel, the nine-year-high for crude
reached last month when Iraq cut off shipments in disagreement with
a United Nations plan -- was ``a little high.''
</P>
<P>
   Oil analysts dismissed the likelihood that the United States
would cut prices by taking oil from the country's Strategic
Petroleum Reserve, a crude oil stockpile reserved only for
emergency domestic shortages. The Energy Department has opposed
tapping the 572 million barrels of oil reserves to ease prices in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   Crude oil for delivery in January fell 64 cents, or 2.4 percent,
on the New York Mercantile Exchange after Richardson's comments
this afternoon, Bloomberg reported.
</P>
<P>
   Although Richardson affirmed that markets should dictate energy
prices, he said the administration should be ready to take some
sort of action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our policy is to let the market correct these disruptions and
that is my hope.''
</P>
<P>
   But John Saucer, an energy analyst with Salomon Smith Barney in
Houston, said to be wary of reading too much into Richardson's
comments. He said the secretary's comments were ``mostly
political'' responses to concerns from congressmen from the
northeast who are worried about their constituents paying a lot for
heating oil this winter. Compared to 1986, when the price was also
$27 per barrel, Saucer said current prices aren't dangerous and
markets would eventually bring them down. The national economy is
stronger now, he said, and can weather high oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Government intervention to dampen prices would be bad for
domestic producers struggling to attract investment, said Scott
Espenshade, vice president of economics at the Independent
Petroleum Association of America, a trade association representing
independent oil and gas producers. He cautioned against a use of
the strategic oil reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was set up for extreme supply problems, not price
fluctuations,'' Espenshade said. ``Prices were at 25 or 26 dollars
in 1996, and it didn't hinder economic expansion then.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said that although the American economy is strong,
the department would be ``extremely concerned'' if oil prices rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``The markets have corrected many of these problems in the past,
they are cyclical, but it's reaching the point because of several
geopolitical factors that I think we need to be prepared,''
Richardson said, likely referring to concerns over Iraq's
withholding of oil in a dispute with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson this afternoon met with Saudi Arabian oil minister
Ali I. Al-Naimi to discuss oil prices and U.S. plans to ready extra
reserves for the year 2000 turnover. A Department of Energy
spokesman said to his knowledge the two did not discuss the
American strategic oil reserves in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Nizam Sharief, director of energy research at Hornsby &AMP; Co. in
Houston, said he predicts prices will go higher - perhaps up to $30
a barrel - due to worsening shortages. At a point where producers
hit minimum operating level, Sharief said, OPEC would probably
produce more, making any U.S. government action unnecessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
