<HEADER>
A4505 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ITALY-TV-HOLYYEAR-NYT     12-09 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-TV-HOLYYEAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JESUS, SUPERSTAR OF ITALY'S JUBILEE, SHARES SPOTLIGHT WITH PINUPS
AND SITCOMS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Italy, the country that perfected housewife striptease
quiz shows, is better known for pizazz than for piety on
television.
</P>
<P>
   But on Dec. 25, a Roman Catholic Holy Year, or Jubilee, begins,
one that coincides with what most Christians view as the 2,000th
anniversary of the birth of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 20 million pilgrims expected to flood into Italy
to visit St. Peter's and other shrines, millions of Italians, and
especially tourist-phobic, traffic-fearing Romans, are planning to
stay indoors. But even on television, there will be little respite
from the Jubilee celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Turn-of-the-millennium specials, Holy Year documentaries, lives
of the saints, Bible stories and even sitcoms promoting spiritual
values are programmed on almost every channel. A foretaste, a
two-part mini-series entitled ``Jesus,'' ended on Monday on RAI,
the state-controlled network.
</P>
<P>
   The heavily promoted international production, which starred
Jacqueline Bisset as Mary and the American actor Robert Sisto as a
sunny, laid-back Jesus, drew 33.9 percent of viewers Sunday night.
The film won generally good reviews, but some critics complained
that the bloody crucifixion scene was too violent for younger
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of other New Testament shows are planned. They come on
top of the special programming of RAI, the official Holy Year
broadcaster, which is committed to 200 hours of live Jubilee
programming, including live coverage of 80 events _ everything from
the opening of the Holy Door of St. Peter's on Christmas Eve, to a
papal Mass in May dedicated to scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Even Mediaset, a private network owned by Silvio Berlusconi, who
was prime minister of Italy in 1994, has joined in. Mediaset is the
company that in the 1980s introduced Colpo Grosso, ``The Big
Coup,'' a game show that had contestants stripping off their
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   For next year, Mediaset has commissioned its own life of Jesus,
starring yet another foreign actor, an Australian, Nicholas Rogers.
The two main networks also have dueling versions of the life of
Padre Pio, a mystic friar who was beatified this year and who has a
large following in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Mediaset is putting its own inimitable stamp on religious
programming with a series called ``Friends of Jesus'' concentrating
on the more sensational followers of Christ _ Mary Magdalen, played
by Maria Grazia Cuchinotta, a buxom brunette who played a Bond girl
in the latest 007 movie; St. Thomas, the doubting apostle, and
Judas, the betrayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the more conflicted characters; they lend themselves
better to drama,'' Francesco Nardella, head of dramatic production
for Mediaset, explained.
</P>
<P>
   But there are people who find the sheer number of Jubilee
specials excessive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a massive overdose _ Rome is turning into Tehran,''
complained Giovanni Negri, a member of the Lay Observatory of the
Jubilee, a watchdog group of lay citizens that monitors the
planning. ``It could have a boomerang effect. The Holy Year could
give rise to a new wave of anticlericalism among the young.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the staggering amount of Jubilee programming on
Italian TV is simple proximity to the Vatican. Jubilees, or Holy
Years, were introduced in 1300 by Pope Boniface VIII, borrowing an
ancient Hebrew tradition of forgiving debts every 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the Catholic Church called a Jubilee every 25 years, and
in Rome they are 12-month extravaganzas that involve not just the
church, but the state, city officials, museums, concert halls,
hotels, restaurants and souvenir vendors. In Rome, everything from
Vatican ashtrays to parchment papal blessings are for sale. (It is
a sin to sell papal blessings, and the Vatican fine print explains
that the fee, between $14 and $39, goes for covering the printing
and dealers' selling costs. The blessing itself is offered for
free.)
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to spare the sensibilities of religious pilgrims, the
city government has shut down sex shops and banned prurient
advertising near the Vatican. The Castello, an X-rated movie house
close to St. Peter's, has been turned into a Jubilee media center
by the government agency organizing the Year 2000 events.
</P>
<P>
   Television is not immune to the zeitgeist.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent panel discussion on RaiUno, RAI's first channel,
about whether there is too much sex on television, Carlo Rossella,
head of a Mediaset television news program ``Verissimo,'' proposed
a moratorium on racy shows during the Holy Year. But he may have
forgotten to inform his own network. Silvia Levato, a producer of
``In Bocca al Lupo'' _ a top-rated Mediaset evening game show,
whose name is an expression for ``Lotsa Luck'' and that is best
known for its scantily clad dancing girls _ grew indignant at the
suggestion that the program should clean up its act.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the show _ how could we possibly change it?'' she
said. ``We are already a serious show. The dancers aren't naked,
after all.''
</P>
<P>
   Religion has even sneaked into Italy's highly competitive sexy
calendar competition. For the first time, priests in Macerata, in
central Italy, introduced their own calendar: entitled ``Priests,''
each month features a different priest. All are fully dressed, but
Father February plays volleyball, and Father December playfully
straddles a playground rocking horse.
</P>
<P>
   Raoul Bova, the handsome young actor Mediaset chose to play St.
Francis of Assisi, brought out his own cheesecake calendar this
month, but said he rejected full frontal nudity and also tried to
convey his innermost thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see my body, sure,'' he told the newspaper La Stampa.
``But I hope one can also see my point that we have to free
ourselves of the ties imposed by society.''
</P>
<P>
   Major Vatican events, like the Christmas Midnight Mass at St.
Peter's, have been broadcast live worldwide by satellite since
1974. There was live coverage of the last Jubilee, an extraordinary
one called by John Paul II in 1983. But the year 2,000 has a far
greater resonance, and technology allows for saturation coverage.
</P>
<P>
   RAI will broadcast the main events. SAT 2,000, a new satellite
TV network run by the Italian Bishops' Conference, will also
broadcast them in their entirety, as well as all Jubilee events,
even ones where the pope does not intend to appear. The network
also offers religious talk shows, news bulletins, a serial drama,
``Ciao Domani,'' that follows the tribulations of young women in a
boarding house in Rome. SAT 2000 will keep a camera on 24 hours a
day outside St. Peter's, interviewing pilgrims on the air.
</P>
<P>
   All the networks seem to be searching for a new sense of
propriety in the year 2000. But old habits die hard. Last week,
viewers of RaiUno were startled one morning by an R-rated Western,
``Hard Bounty,'' featuring a topless Kelly Le Brock, at 10:00 a.m.
Once alerted to the mistake, RAI hurriedly pulled the film off the
air and apologized to its viewers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 1935EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
