<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWENTIETH CENTURY KEEPSAKES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   By far, the item most nominated as a 20th century endangered
object is the slide rule, an engineering-student accessory for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other modern marvels destined to mystify future
generations: the automobile crank ( &UR; Jack Riggs &LR; ), paper tape reader
for computers ( &UR; Howard Matis &LR; ), disposable flashbulbs ( &UR; Shari
Bland &LR; ), roll of film ( &UR; Deborah Burstyn &LR; ), black-and-white TV set
( &UR; Kenyon Wills &LR; ), colored plastic to turn that TV set colored
( &UR; Linda Beltran &LR; ), the carburetor ( &UR; James Buxton &LR; ), clock with
hands (so ``clockwise'' and ``counterclockwise'' will become
meaningless, says  &UR; Paula Kleinfeld &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   And for the office, consider the ditto machine, already ``gone
the way of the dodo,'' writes  &UR; Nathan Ballard &LR; , ticker tape
( &UR; Arkie &LR; 
 &UR; Koehl &LR; ), Eaton's Corrasable paper ( &UR; Joan Fisch &LR; ), steno notebook
filled with scribblings in Gregg shorthand ( &UR; Vera Torres &LR; ),
circular typewriter eraser with green brush attached ( &UR; James &LR; 
 &UR; Carley &LR; ), typewriter correction tape ( &UR; Sharon Ulrich &LR; ), typewriter
correction shield ( &UR; Oliver Atchison &LR; ) and the little tubular metal
thing with a ball embedded in the end that fits on a pencil and can
be used to dial a phone ( &UR; Carol Jones &LR; ). Note that this category
includes many items for fixing mistakes, which will never go out of
style (see below).
</P>
<P>
   In the closet, the buttonhook ( &UR; Gertrude Bernesque &LR; ), diaper pin
( &UR; Marion Brackett &LR; ), darning egg to place inside socks ( &UR; Ray &LR; 
 &UR; Clayton &LR; ), spats ( &UR; Bob Wieder &LR; ), zip-on extension to turn
