<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4507 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-BOS &LR;      12-09 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS ATTEMPT TO RESTORE NORMALCY TO CONQUERED CHECHEN AREAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZNAMENSKAYA, Russia _ Khava Kumarova still cries whenever she
hears the thunder of outgoing artillery, which unfortunately
happens very often.
</P>
<P>
   Kumarova, 8, is one of more than 100 refugee children from the
Chechen capital of Grozny who have been integrated into the classes
in the school in Znamenskaya. As the smiling pupils pose for
visitors outside the newly repaired school building, Major General
Vladimir Kovrov, the Russian military commander of northwestern
Chechnya, smiles back and hands out treats.
</P>
<P>
   But the school in this northwestern town in Chechnya is so close
to a Russian firing range, that every time the heavy guns let loose
with a new salvo, Kumarova shudders and begins to weep.
</P>
<P>
   As Russia presses ahead with its effort to reimpose its rule
over Chechnya, the army has embarked on a parallel campaign to show
how it is restoring life to normal in parts of the breakaway
Caucasus republic it has brought under its cotrol.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the veneer of friendly gestures, the Russian effort seems
more than a bit contrived, especially in contrast to the army's
darkly worded ultimatum to civilians trapped in Grozny, 30 miles to
the west.
</P>
<P>
   The school is part of Kovrov's guided tour of Znamenskaya,
intended to show visitors how well he has prepared for the influx
of refugees expected to arrive from Grozny before the military's
deadline for civilians to leave the city.
</P>
<P>
   Also included in the tour is an orphanage and a tent camp built
to accommodate new arrivals from the beseiged Chechen capital. The
facilities are clean and equipped with gas stoves, large washing
areas, and even a sauna. Built in 10 days, the tent city provides
stark contrast to the miserable conditions endured for the past two
months by tens of thousands of refugees from the fighting in the
neighboring Russian republic of Ingushetia.
</P>
<P>
   The camp in Znamenskaya is still empty _ even though the
military, in leaflets dropped on the city, warned civilians to
leave the capital by Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Kovrov, whose command includes the escape route for Grozny,
bristles at the idea that the lack of refugees so far is in any way
connected with the actions of Russian troops, who have not let up
in their bombardment of an estimated 3,000 to 6,000 separatist
militants holed up in Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who wants to leave can leave,'' Kovrov said. ``There is
no ultimatum. We are providing a corridior for safe passage.''
</P>
<P>
   Kovrov's theory is that most civilians have left Grozny. Other
Russian officials, however, say that as many as 45,000 people, many
of them aged, ill, or with small children, could still be hiding in
the capital's basements.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Russian officials, Kovrov predicted a quick end to
the conflict in Chechnya, and said Chechen citizens will get help
from Moscow to rebuild their war-shattered homes and lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to work,'' Kovrov said. ``They are tired of war,
and that's why federal forces will prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   A visit to the strategic hamlets along the route leading from
Znamenskaya toward Grozny, a muddy road dotted with checkpoints
manned by heavily armed troops, found some Chechens who shared
Kovrov'sew.
</P>
<P>
   Many expressed disappointment that the de-facto independence won
after a 1994-1996 war with Russia did not turn into a better life.
Some blamed the separatist government of President Aslan Maskhadov
for its inability to restore Chechnya's economy, but many more
fingered rival gangs whose kidnapping and banditry paralyzed the
republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Chechens had high hopes, but they disappeared in a wave of
lawlessness,'' said Aisha, a vendor at a food market in the village
of Lakha-Nevre. Wary of two Russian policemen nearby, she asked not
to give her last name.
</P>
<P>
   Others quietly expressed anger at Russia for again bringing war
into their homeland. Moscow invaded the region in response to a
wave of apartment bombings and attacks on neighboring regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They blame the Chechens for banditry, but the biggest bandits
are the Russians,'' said a man who gave his first name, Musa.
``They can occupy us, but they cannot defeat the Chechen spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   It was time to visit the next stop on Kovrov's tour: a burning
oil well that he said fleeing Chechen rebels set ablaze, even
though early in the conflict, Russian commanders said their
warplanes had specifically targeted oil wells and refineries.
</P>
<P>
   Kovrov said it will take three months to cap the blaze, which is
wasting 1,400 barrels of oil a day and ruining the local
environment. As he spoke, two Russian Su-24 jets streaked overhead
on their way to bomb Grozny. A helicopter gunship prowled a nearby
ridge, and machine gun fire echoed across the valley below.
</P>
<P>
   The last stop on the tour was the orphanage, where the children
sang Russian pop songsad danced across the spartan facility.
Someone asked the director, Benlan Kasayeva, to tell her visitors
how one boy's parents were killed by a radical Islamic group among
the rebels. She willingly obliged, even though the visibly
distraught boy was listening. Then she complained the Kovrov's
administration had yet to find money for the orphanage's staff.
</P>
<P>
   Kasayeva's complaint got at the heart of the problem of Russia's
plans for the reconstruction of Chechnya. Orphanage staffs do not
get paid in Russia proper. Nor do teachers, retirees, and others,
at least not on time. If Chechnya has suffered from crime and
unemployment during its three years of independence, the standard
of living in the neighboring republic of North Ossetia, which has
been loyal to Moscow for two centuries, is not much better.
</P>
<P>
   If Russia's battle for the hearts and minds of Chechnya is to
succeed, it will have to work better here than in Russia itself.
Kovrov seemed to recognize that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The end of the military campaign is near,'' he said. ``But
that is only the beginning of our work here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
