<SLUG> BC-OIL-SPILL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURERS TO PAY $10 MILLION TO SETTLE R.I. OIL SPILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Insurance carriers for a barge that caused one of the
worst oil spills in New England history have agreed to pay $10
million to Rhode Island lobstermen, fishermen and business owners
who claimed the 1996 accident near Point Judith damaged their
livelihoods for years afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, subject to court approval, would resolve a
federal lawsuit filed by 114 individuals and businesses against
Eklof Marine Corp. of New York, whose barge North Cape spilled
800,000 gallons of home heating oil along the Rhode Island coast
when it ran aground.
</P>
<P>
   Though Eklof already has been fined a state record $8.5 million
in connection with the North Cape accident, lobstermen and
fishermen had been frustrated in their effort to get compensation
for marine resources destroyed in the spill. Point Judith
lobstermen reported catches dropped by up to 50 percent in the year
after the spill.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can never fully compensate all the lobstermen for all of
their losses, but this is a good settlement and a fair
settlement,'' said Thomas Cole, the attorney at Kirkpatrick &AMP;
Lockhart who represented the lobstermen, fishermen and
fishing-related businesses in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The North Cape split open on Jan. 20, 1996, near one of southern
New England's most important fishing ports after the tugboat that
was towing it caught fire and had to be abandoned. Dead lobsters,
starfish and other animals washed ashore by the thousand as the oil
slick spread.
</P>
<P>
   Eklof agreed to pay huge fines to settle criminal charges after
investigators learned that the tugboat did not have proper
firefighting equipment despite a history of fires on the vessel. In
addition, the captain sailed despite forecasts of rough seas.
</P>
<P>
   However, the settlement did little for people whose livelihoods
were damaged by the spill. Reforms adopted by Congress after the
1989 Exxon Valdez oil spill were supposed to make it easier for oil
spill victims to negotiate damages, but the North Cape victims said
talks stalled over the issue of long-term impacts of the spill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cruel paradox is that the settlement process envisioned by
Congress proved to be more grueling than protracted litigation and
that's why we were forced to go to the courthouse,'' said Holt.
</P>
<P>
   Under Thursday's settlement, the plaintiffs will divide $10
million from Eklof's insurance companies for damages since 1997.
They have already been promised more than $2 million from insurers
as well as an oil industry fund to cover 1996 damages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 1939EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4515 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TURNER-DIGITAL10-COX     12-09 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURNER-DIGITAL10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New buildings to house growth, attract top talent for Turner
Broadcasting
 &HT;    Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Turner Broadcasting plans to begin a $90 million
construction project early next year at its downtown Atlanta campus
that will add two new office buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The development is aimed at accommodating the company's rapid
growth and is helping recruit top talent to the company's
entertainment channels, which are based at the site, as well as
signaling the company's commitment to the city.
</P>
<P>
   The project calls for Turner Broadcasting to retool its site
into a suburban-style office campus in the heart of the city.
Company executives hope this type of work environment will attract
top people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to promote Atlanta as a great place to work and
live,'' says Alec Fraser, president of Turner Properties, who is
leading the $90 million project.
</P>
<P>
   The rapidly expanding television programming business is based
primarily in New York and Los Angeles. Turner Broadcasting has
always had to work harder than its competition to attract talent to
its Atlanta headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Broadcasting's site is already densely settled with four
office buildings housing the operations for the company's TNT, TBS,
Turner Classic Movies and Cartoon Network channels.
</P>
<P>
   The site abuts Georgia Tech on Techwood Drive between 14th and
10th streets. About 1,400 employees work at the site and that
number is expected to grow.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, the company launched its newest channel, Turner
South, from the Techwood site. The next addition to the Techwood
campus will be a $35 million studio, expected to open early next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Also in 2000, the company plans to launch Boomerang, an offshoot
of Cartoon Network that will feature cartoons 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   The new buildings will total 330,000 square feet of office
space. They will be built on top of the two parking lots that now
flank the front of the site's cornerstone building, a white
columned brick mansion, the original home of CNN. A fountain now in
front of the mansion will become a courtyard. Parking will be built
under each building. The idea is to preserve the leafy and hilly
campuslike feel of the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to protect the two hills that are on the site,
keep the best of the environment and maximize the use of land,''
says Fraser. ``There will be no parking decks to block the view of
our neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   As designed by local firm KSP Group, the buildings will be built
of brick, stone and glass. The idea behind the design is a
contemporary look that incorporates a touch of the original
mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The style is a cross between the classical and the modern,''
says Fraser.
</P>
<P>
   Both buildings will be constructed by Turner Construction, which
built the new studio. The builder is no relation to either Turner
Broadcasting or its founder, Ted Turner.
</P>
<P>
   The first building is largely a technical facility. It will be
designed to incorporate the latest in digital television
transmission technology, including high definition technology. Only
the top two floors of the building's six stories will house
offices.
</P>
<P>
   The second building, five stories high, will house the company's
network operations employees.
</P>
<P>
   Said Fraser, ``the two buildings will be highly visible from the
street and should make quite an impression.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 1943EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
