   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Gudermes, Russia) _ Russian officials vow to
return the flood of refugees in Ingushetiya back to
Russian-controlled areas of Chechnya by the end of the year. The
reverse migration of potentially hundreds of thousands of people
appears intended to demonstrate that Russia is making process in
stabilizing Chechnya and that talk of a human disaster is
overblown. By Michael R. Gordon. (We plan to move the story by 8:30
p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Reefer to CHINA-YELTSIN; story inside.
</P>
<P>
   Top center:
</P>
<P>
   2-column photo reefer to MASS-FIREFIGHTERS.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: See also SPOT-BUDGET-BOS for a list of related stories
and photos from Worcester, Mass.)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-FINANCE (Washington) _ John McCain and Bill Bradley,
both insurgent candidates for president, have agreed to step across
party lines and stage an unusual joint appearance in New Hampshire
to highlight their support for overhauling the nation's campaign
finance system. By Alison Mitchell. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m.
ET in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   Reefer to REPUBS-BUSH; story inside.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-WORKERS (Milwaukee) _ Lots of people consider themselves
experts on this city's war on welfare, but few have ridden its
highs and lows as intensely as Michael Steinborn. Eighteen months
ago, Steinborn was an unemployed jack of the building trades, down
on his luck and in need of a job. Improbably enough, he is now one
of the system's most popular caseworkers _ and a de facto authority
on the nation's most famous welfare experiment. By Jason DeParle.
(The report has moved in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Special Report; 2,900 words. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   DIALLO-TRIAL (New York) _ With the most closely watched police
trial in a decade set to begin next month, a look at the evidence,
including new details. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a''
news file.) 2,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ASSESS (Jerusalem) _ Analysis: A feeling that change was
imminent swept through Israel Thursday after President Clinton's
surprise announcement on Wednesday that Israeli-Syrian talks would
be resumed after nearly four years. Almost palpably, the national
pulse seemed to quicken _ for some with elation, for others with
anxiety. Even the Israeli right-wing, so uninspired these last few
months, girded up for a real opportunity. By Deborah Sontag.
(Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MARS-OCEAN (Undated) _ Scientists at Brown University say
they have found tantalizing evidence that the northern lowlands of
Mars once bore a wide ocean that, until it dried up, had waves,
hidden depths and long beaches. The findings are hailed as making
the best case yet for the existence of a sea on primordial Mars. By
William J. Broad. (The story has moved in ``a'' news file.) 1,100
words.
</P>
<P>
   KING-TRIAL-ASSESS (Atlanta) _ With key players long dead, with
confessions recanted and altered, and with a vast conspiracy
alleged but not proven, Wednesday's verdict in the civil trial
connected to the assassination of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. may
ultimately do little to demystify the tangle of fact and theory
surrounding one of the century's most traumatic events. By Kevin
Sack. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 1,300
words.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   LINUX-IPO (San Francisco) _ Internet mania reach new levels of
frenzy as investors pay huge multiples on an initial public
offering, giving a tiny company with powerful competitors, little
revenue and no expectation of earnings in the foreseeable future a
market value of almost $10 billion. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.) 1,100 words.
</P>
