<HEADLINE>
GROUPS ANNOUNCE CAMPAIGN TO `DE-ALERT' NUKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A coalition of defense experts, lawmakers and
liberal organizations launched a nationwide campaign Thursday aimed
at getting the United States and Russia to remove their nuclear
missiles from high alert _ that is, ready to launch on a moment's
notice.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition's effort to get both nations to ``de-alert'' their
weapons is surfacing because it believes that after years of
neglect Russia's early-warning radars are in such disrepair and the
troops that guard intercontinental ballistic missiles are so
demoralized that the missiles could be accidentally or purposefully
launched at the United States.
</P>
<P>
   One possible nightmare scenario is that faulty Russian radars
will relay inaccurate information to Kremlin leaders saying that
they are under nuclear attack and Moscow will respond with a volley
of nuclear missiles at the United States. Another feared scenario
is that Russia will plummet into political anarchy and troops,
demoralized after a decade of economic chaos, will wrest control of
a few missiles from civilian leaders and make an unauthorized
launch against the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Blair, a Russian nuclear weapons expert at the nonpartisan
Brookings Institution here, says the dangers are increasing daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main current threat to our mutual survival stems from the
growing risk that weapons on a hair-trigger alert will be fired
illicitly or accidentally because of technical failure, human error
or internal military and political disintegration,'' he said at a
news conference announcing the de-alert campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This campaign believes that keeping nuclear arsenals on high
alert makes little sense in the post-Cold War era, that it runs
inherent safety risks and that these risks are growing as the
result of the deterioration of Russian control and early warning,''
Blair said.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign was announced by Blair, the Center for Defense
Information (CDI), a liberal think tank, and Rep. Edward Markey,
D-Mass., sponsor of a congressional measure signed by 83 other
lawmakers to de-alert U.S. nuclear missiles. Also joining the
effort are the Takoma Park, Md.-based Institute for Energy and
Environmental Research, the Snake River Alliance in Idaho and the
Federation of American Scientists here.
</P>
<P>
   Activists in the campaign are distributing videotapes about the
perceived nuclear dangers and are circulating a grass-roots
Internet petition (www.DEALERT.org) that asks the political leaders
of both countries to ``stand down our weapons of mass
destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   The activists are seeking the removal of the missiles' warheads
and guidance systems or the covering of silos with large amounts of
dirt that would have to be removed before a launch. In this way, it
would take hours to prepare a missile for flight. While Presidents
Clinton and Boris Yeltsin of Russia signed an agreement in 1994 not
to aim missiles at each other's country, the weapons remain loaded
with nuclear warheads and could be activated in minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The nuclear policy of both sides is still pegged to Cold War
hostilities with Moscow and Washington maintaining the ability to
launch their respective atomic arsenals minutes after detecting a
nuclear attack from the other side. The idea is to fire a
retaliatory salvo before the incoming missiles strike. It is known
as the ``use them or lose them'' strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States needs to take the leadership on this issue
and take the first step,'' said CDI's director, former Democratic
Arkansas Sen. Dale Bumpers. ``We will have the moral and political
basis on which to ask Russia to reciprocate.''
</P>
<P>
   Markey said in a statement that the ``weapons should not sit
like cars at a drag race with revved engines waiting for the start
light to turn green.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Central Intelligence Agency said it doubts Russia
will launch a preemptive strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We judge that an unauthorized or accidental launch of a
Russian strategic missile is highly unlikely so long as current
technical and procedural safeguards are in place,'' said Robert D.
Walpole, a nuclear expert at the agency.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still, because of concern that Y2K computer glitches in Russia
could result in an accidental missile launch, the governments of
the two nuclear powers have set up a joint command center at
Peterson Air Force Base near the Rocky Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   While officials from both countries stress the likelihood is
remote for such a deadly exchange, the command post has a simple if
important mission: assure Russia _ where aging military computers
haven't been upgraded for years _ that a U.S. attack is not under
way if Moscow's early warning system malfunctions and indicates an
imminent strike.
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
eric &LR; hearstdc.com
</P>
</TEXT>
