<HEADLINE>
NFL MATCHUPS FOR WEEK 14 
</HEADLINE>
  (A graphic of these matchups has been sent electronically to NYT
graphics clients. Call 888-603-1036 for information.) 
(jt) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAME OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Detroit (8-4) vs. Tampa Bay (8-4)
</P>
<P>
   The Lions and Bucs are rejuvenated, Detroit spurned by balance
and commitment and Tampa Bay by the league's top-ranked defense.
Detroit plays defense, too. Last season it created 21 takeaways; it
already has 24 (10 interceptions, 14 fumble recoveries) this year.
The Bucs rookie quarterback, Shaun King, vs. the Lions defense, led
by end Robert Porcher, gives Detroit an edge. Detroit coach Bobby
Ross is 6-3 vs. Tampa Bay and his counterpart, Tony Dungy, is 2-6
vs. Detroit. Incentive for both _ the divisional lead with three
games left _ is supreme. Detroit wins the battle of wills.
</P>
<P>
   Lions, 21-16.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY, 1 P.M. GAMES
</P>
<P>
   Arizona (6-6) vs. Washington (7-5)
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago Arizona was a lousy team, scratching its head
and demoralized. Now the Cardinals are refreshed. They have won
four straight and no Cardinals team has done that in 11 years. Jake
Plummer has resurfaced after a painful start. In his last two games
he has completed 32 of 55 passes for 304 yards with 3 touchdowns.
The Redskins have been a yo-yo team _ brilliant one week, ordinary
the next _ all season. It is time for brilliance after a collapse
at Detroit last week. It does not look like, however, the Redskins
have it in them.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals, 31-28.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore (5-7) vs. Pittsburgh (5-7)
</P>
<P>
   This is the Pittsburgh's fifth consecutive divisional game. It
lost the last four. Mike Tomczak starts at quarterback again for
Pittsburgh and he finds a team not prepared to rally around him.
Pittsburgh is close to losing its heart for this season and its
hope. A victory is crucial to salvage an even more severe tailspin.
Can Pittsburgh run at Baltimore with Jerome Bettis? It meets a
Baltimore defense that ranks first in the AFC allowing an average
of 80.8 yards per game. Baltimore has not allowed a 100-yard rusher
this season. Look for that streak to continue as well as the
big-play production of Baltimore quarterback Tony Banks.
</P>
<P>
   Ravens, 25-20.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina (5-7) vs. Green Bay (7-5)
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers were smoked by the Rams last week, ripped for 34
points and shoved aside as a team with more holes than strengths.
It could get ugly at Lambeau Field. Green Bay is beginning its
playoff drive with a resolve and focus that could take it far.
Certainly past the Panthers. Green Bay's rookie running backs _
Basil Mitchell and De'mond Parker _ provide quickness and a spunky
change of pace. Green Bay has won three straight by a combined
score of 81-39. That's an average score of 27-13 per victory.
</P>
<P>
   Packers, 27-13.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland (2-11) vs. Cincinnati (3-10)
</P>
<P>
   Just when the Bengals looked like a dog team headed for a 1-15
season, they won two straight and started blowing up defenses like
their fans thought they could all season long. In their last three
games, the Bengals have averaged 34 points per game; in their first
10 they averaged 13 points per game. What happened? Jeff Blake
began throwing deep downfield once again, Bruce Coslet loosened his
coaching reins and let the Bengals create. This is a common trend.
The Bengals are lousy for three months and then fly in December
when all hope for the playoffs is lost. They are 8-4 in December
games under Coslet and he is 3-0 vs. the Browns. There is little
chance he will survive this latest Bengals stretch of mediocrity,
so, as a parting shot, he makes it 4-0 vs. the Browns. Bengals,
30-17.
</P>
<P>
   New England (7-5) vs. Indianapolis (10-2)
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots beat the Colts, 31-28 in September. It was a game
where New England trailed 28-7 at halftime. New England will be
hard-pressed to duplicate that comeback. Indianapolis has gained
confidence in beating nearly all comers, especially in its
dramatic, last-second victory last week at Miami. That road victory
gave the Colts all they needed in psyche to roll the rest of the
way toward their divisional crown. Players like Peyton Manning,
Marvin Harrison, Cornelius Bennett and kicker Mike Vanderjagt (a
league-most 114 points) provide the rest in production.
</P>
<P>
   Colts, 27-21.
</P>
<P>
   Giants (6-6) vs. Buffalo (8-4)
</P>
<P>
   Rested but perhaps rusted, the Bills tackle the Giants new,
one-game, high-rolling offense. Will it sputter and clank in the
cold of Buffalo? Maybe not. The Giants will give the ball again to
back Joe Montgomery and the new play-calling and emphasis on
breaking old tendencies will work in the Giants favor. Expect Kerry
Collins to outplay Doug Flutie and the Giants defense to overwhelm
the Bills' defense. The Giants should start quickly while the Bills
work through their one-week layoff. This game could be won in large
part in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Giants, 24-23.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia (3-10) vs. Dallas
</P>
<P>
   Dallas has produced a season much like Washington's with extreme
highs and lows, with sparkling play followed by a breakdowns both
mental and physical. Dallas lost the first one to Philadelphia
13-10 back in October but won't make the same mistake. It must have
this game to keep pace with the Giants and Cardinals and maybe will
catch Washington. Often the Eagles are their own nemesis. How can a
team that leads the NFC in takeaways have a turnover differential
of Zero? Easy. It kicks the ball around as much as it recovers it.
Dallas will exploit that this time.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys, 17-9.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis (10-2) vs. New Orleans (2-10)
</P>
<P>
   Mike Ditka, the Saints coach, met this week with Saints owner
Tom Benson. Benson left that meeting saying that after this season
he would do whatever he could to ensure winning Saints football.
Notice the words ``after this season.'' The season is shot. It
began with the promise and glow of Heisman Trophy winner Ricky
Williams. It spun out of control with Williams often hurt and with
the Saints in disarray. As this woeful season ticks away, it is
apparent this one is Ditka's last one in New Orleans. The Rams
provide another painful punctuation mark.
</P>
<P>
   Rams, 33-16.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
