u s BC-FBN-MATCHUPS-2NDTAKE-     12-09 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MATCHUPS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: Rams, 33-16.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNDAY, 4 P.M. GAMES
</P>
<P>
   Miami (8-4) vs. Jets (4-8)
</P>
<P>
   How can the Jets have a plus 10 turnover differential and be a
4-victory team and the Colts have a -2 turnover differential and be
a 10-victory team? Oh, we could forever count the ways. The biggest
problem is offense and touchdown and point production. The Colts
have it; the Jets do not. But last week, the Jets defense fell
flat, too, in a 41-point Giants offensive showing. This game spells
trouble for the Jets. Two teams heading in totally opposite
directions. Miami toward the playoffs; the Jets to an offseason of
depression.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins, 13-9.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego (5-7) vs. Seattle (8-4)
</P>
<P>
   Jim Harbaugh has quarterbacked the Chargers with a steady hand
and has given his team a jolt. But the Chargers need so much more.
They often find themselves standing rather than creating, chasing
rather than being chased, trailing rather than leading. The
Chargers tackle a team that is smarting, especially after the
Raiders cut them and carved them last week. Momentum is slipping
for Seattle, but Seattle recaptures it with a solid game where
every phase of its team contributes.
</P>
<P>
   Seahawks, 30-17.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta (3-9) vs. San Francisco (3-9)
</P>
<P>
   Both the Falcons and the 49ers find their offenses finally
improving, showing life, scoring points. The good news for Atlanta
is its defense is making that good for something. The bad news for
San Francisco is its defense is not. The 49ers scored 30 points,
Jeff Garcia threw for 437 yards and three touchdowns, Jerry Rice
caught two scores, Terrell Owens caught nine passes for 145 yards _
and the 49ers still lost to the Cincinnati Bengals. The Bengals
torched the 49ers for 44 points. How many will Atlanta get? Enough
to win.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons, 20-17.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota (7-5) vs. Kansas City (7-5)
</P>
<P>
   Cris Carter is Minnesota's leading receiver. Tony Gonzalez at
tight end is the Chiefs' leading receiver. That tells you plenty
about the differences in these two offenses. The Vikings sprint,
the Chiefs plod. But Kansas City, especially at home, has a way of
making offenses crawl. The Chiefs at home and in a special night
affair start the game with big, bruising hits and then continue
throughout the night. They will attempt to pulverize the Vikings
offense into submission. A tall task. So, the Chiefs will need help
from their offense and especially from quarterback Elvis Grbac to
keep pace. The Chiefs surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs, 24-22.
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Denver (4-8) vs. Jacksonville (11-1)
</P>
<P>
   This game in recent years has been for huge stakes but now it
has fizzled because Denver collapsed early this season and could
never get up. It fought, but adversity and poor play and a less
cohesive team unit helped doom this team to an unfamiliar and
draining bottom-rung position after consecutive Super Bowl titles.
Jacksonville arrives ready to dump more dirt on Denver. These
franchises have testy history between them including a touch of
envy and a general dislike. Jacksonville can run it up as much as
it likes. It won't stop for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Jaguars, 36-20.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
