<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4528 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BARR-GUNS10-COX     12-09 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARR-GUNS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barr calls for probe into HUD's part in suit against gunmakers
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Rep. Bob Barr is calling for an investigation into the
federal government's plan to take part in a suit against gunmakers.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Barr wants to know whether a Housing Department
lawyer lied to Congress about taking such legal action.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Gail Laster, counsel at the Department of Housing and
Urban Development, told a House panel that the department ``does
not plan to bring any action on its own against the gun industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr, a board member of the National Rifle Association, contends
that Laster's statement amounts to ``misleading, if not lying'' to
the House Government Reform's panel on criminal justice.
</P>
<P>
   Barr has asked the chairman of that panel, Rep. John Mica
(R-Fla.), to investigate whether Laster acted on her own or whether
this is part of a ``department policy to lie to Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a perfect example of the way the Clinton
Administration works,'' Barr said on Thursday. ``These people come
up here and they are basically thumbing their nose at Congress.
They're saying: `We're going to tell you whatever we want. We're
not going to tell the truth, and then we're going to go back and do
whatever we want.' That is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The Housing officials have a starkly different memory of
Laster's April 4th testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Laster did tell the panel that the federal housing
agency had no plans to file suit against the gun industry. But she
did not rule out that a suit would be filed by one of the some 3
million people who live in public housing developments across the
country or by a local housing authority.
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly what is expected to happen when the federal
action is finally filed. The suit will be brought by a small band
of public housing residents or a group of individual housing
authorities and it will have the support of the federal agency,
according to HUD.
</P>
<P>
   In filing a lawsuit against gunmakers, the Clinton
administration is attempting to support the 29 cities and counties,
including Atlanta, across the country that have sued the gun
industry in hopes of winning monetary damages for the cost of
gun-related violence.
</P>
<P>
   The gun debate on Capitol Hill is expected to unfold again in
January with both chambers drafting legislation aimed at curbing
gun violence. The momentum for gun legislation came from a series
of recent shooting sprees in California, Colorado and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control advocates applaud the Clinton administration's
action, saying it is time to hold the gun industry accountable in
the same way that the tobacco industry has been taken to task.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Barr's protestations of this lawsuit are as ludicrous as
they are predictable,'' said Adam Eisgraw, director of federal
relations for the Center to Prevent Handgun Violence, a nonprofit
organization based in Washington, D.C. ``The notion that Americans
should not use the judicial branch to address a problem as severe
as guns is preposterous.''
</P>
<P>
   The gun industry is lobbying lawmakers on Capitol Hill and in
state legislatures to prevent more lawsuits from being filed.
Already they have convinced 14 states, including Georgia, to pass
legislation preventing local governments from taking legal action
against gunmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel the lawsuits are wrongheaded,'' said Bill Powers,
director of public affairs for the NRA. ``Who's next? General
Motors for causing drunk driving?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
