<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4529 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-DELAY-COMPLAINT-HNS &LR;      12-09 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELAY-COMPLAINT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS ACCUSE GOP LEADERS OF VIOLATING FEDERAL CAMPAIGN LAWS  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democrats accused House Majority Whip Tom DeLay and
other Republican leaders Thursday of violating federal campaign
laws by funneling money into several independent groups in order to
avoid campaign donation and spending limits in next year's
elections.
</P>
<P>
   In a complaint filed with the Federal Election Commission,
lawyers for the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee
asserted that DeLay, R-Texas, and the National Republican
Congressional Committee had devised an illegal ``scheme'' to create
and fund ``a web of organizations'' that are not required to
disclose their donors or how they spend their money.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, the complaint said, would allow Republican donors to
contribute more to the NRCC than the $20,000 limit by giving to the
outside groups. It would also make it easier for NRCC to spend more
``soft money'' on campaign advertising and get-out-the-vote drives
than allowed by law.
</P>
<P>
   By off-loading ``huge segments of its own activities to groups
that play under more permissive rules,'' the Democrats said the
NRCC will be able ``to do what it may not do on its own'' under
current law governing how much the parties can spend on advertising
and get-out-the-vote drives funded by so-called ``soft money''
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint, which urges the FEC to investigate and seek a
court order prohibiting the NRCC from working with the groups, also
alleges that the organizations involved are actually controlled by
DeLay and run by his former aides and political associates,
including his former chief of Staff Ed Buckham.
</P>
<P>
   ``The web of DeLay operatives and NRCC consultants running these
operations all point to an ongoing relationship and the creation of
an entity affiliated with the NRCC,'' the complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   As the third-ranking GOP leader in the House, Delay has become
one of the most influential lawmakers on Capitol Hill. By wielding
his political power and strong conservative credentials, he has
also emerged this year as the GOP's top fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   So it's no wonder that he has become an ``easy target,'' his
aides say, for criticism from Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay spokesman Michael Scanlon called the Democratic complaint
``absolutely false'' and accused the Democrats of pulling a
political ``publicity stunt'' designed to make Republicans, and
DeLay in particular, look bad to the voters.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Mattoon, the NRCC deputy chairman, also said in a statement
that there was nothing illegal about the committee giving to
``pro-family groups.``
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand what the law is and the NRCC always complies
with the letter and spirit of the law,'' Mattoon said, calling the
Democratic charges ``baseless.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic complaint to the FEC was prompted by an article
earlier this week in the Capitol Hill newspaper Roll Call, which
reported that the NRCC had given $500,000 to U.S. Family Network,
one of three independent, non-profit groups associated with DeLay
and run by his former aides or political consultants.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Family Network has reportedly applied to the Internal
Revenue Service for tax-exempt status as a non-profit social
organization. The other two groups are the Republican Majority
Issue Conference, which many Republicans acknowledge is a
DeLay-NRCC fund-raising arm, and Americans for Economic Growth,
which is also a non-profit, tax-exempt organization.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear whether the NRCC has given money to the RMIC or
AEG. But both groups make no secret of the fact that they rely on
DeLay and other Republican leaders for help in their fund-raising
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   In the complaint, the Democrats allege that all three groups are
nothing more than surrogates of the NRCC and should be forced to
register with the FEC and abide by federal election laws that
govern political parties and their affiliated organizations.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans argue that neither DeLay, nor NRCC Chairman Tom
Davis, R-Va., are involved in deciding how the organizations should
spend the money they receive, despite their obvious ties to the
directors of the groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom has no involvement in their decisions,'' said Scanlon.
``That's just not true.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the FEC declined to comment directly on the DCCC
charges. But as with most complaints it receives, FEC officials
will likely ask DeLay and the NRCC to respond to the charges within
the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter the response, Meredith McGehee, legislative
director for the public interest group Common Cause, says the FEC
is ``not going to do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   She called the agency charged with enforcing campaign laws ``a
toothless tiger'' in a political system awash in huge amounts of
money with very little accountability about how it's spent and
little impetus to actually strengthen the laws.
</P>
<P>
   Although she noted that a case could easily be made that
Democrats use outside groups themselves to skirt campaign finance
laws, she said the DCCC complaint indicates that Republicans have
all but dropped any pretense of trying to stay within the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's very clearly here an effort to exploit this enormous
amount of soft money flowing into the system ... DeLay is at the
center of many these efforts,'' McGehee said, citing DeLay's
leadership position in Congress and his strong connections with
Washington lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is obviously a money king-pin in the system,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Scanlon called McGehee's comments ``inflammatory,'' saying
``that doesn't help anything.'' He suggested that Common Cause
``ought to be trying to create a more respectable discourse'' on
campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
