<SLUG> BC-KING-CASE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING DECISION BRINGS COMFORT TO FAMILY, DOES LITTLE FOR CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS _ Beneath the motel balcony where a sniper's bullet
killed the Reverend Martin Luther King Jr., a granite plaque has
long borne a Biblical passage that hints at one of his family's
gravest beliefs: His assassin did not act alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behold, here cometh the dreamer,'' the inscription says. ``Let
us slay him. And we shall see what will become of his dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   The civil rights leader's dream of justice was alive Thursday,
members of his family said, because a jury on Wednesday accepted
their premise that King's assassination was not the solitary work
of James Earl Ray, a petty thief convicted of the killing, but the
heinous product of a vast conspiracy masterminded and covered up by
the Mafia and government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all its blockbuster potential, the civil jury's verdict
appeared destined to languish as a footnote in history. Beyond
providing vague confirmation for what many Americans already
suspected, the jury's finding was expected to represent little more
than final consolation for King's widow, Coretta Scott King, and
the couple's four children as they end their quest for the truth in
the 1968 tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   King's survivors said they will not push for dional action,
depte plans by some of their closest allies to seek afuller
inquiry. State and federal prosecrs said they will not reopen
criminal investigations because of the verdict. And at the site of
King's assassination, now the National Civil Rights Museum,
officials said they will add only a sentence about the verdict, if
that, to the story of the martyred leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are prepared now to move on with our lives,'' Mrs. King
said at a news conference in Atlanta. ``We hope that other people
will join us so the nation can move on with the healing that is so
necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Family members, with a trace of bitterness, said the verdict had
even sqeulched their interest in a Justice Department inquiry into
a possible conspiracy to kill King _ an investigation that Mrs.
King had personally lobbied President Clinton to open last year.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder said Thursday the 15-month
inquiry will be completed in the next few weeks, although he
downplayed expectations that the limited investigation would break
significant new ground. ``It's not a very broad-based look at all
the possibilities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, Dexter King said, ``We don't care what the Justice
Department does . . . We believe this case is over. We know what
happened. This is the period at the end of the sentence.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he described the alleged conspiracy as ``the most
incredible cover-up of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   The verdict, issued after a month-long trial in a county court
in Memphis, is likely to invigorate conspiracy buffs who have been
frustrated f decades by what they perceive as the government's
failure to fully investigate a number of potentially explosive
cases, most notably the assassinations of King and President John
F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   The jury of six whites and six blacks found that Loyd Jowers,
73, who owned Jim's Grill a floor below the rooming house from
which Ray allegedly shot King on April 4, 1968, helped ``others,
including government agencies'' assassinate King and frame Ray. The
verdict came in a civil suit the Kings filed against Jowers after
he said publicly that he hired King's unnamed killer as favor to a
Mafia figure who was his friend.
</P>
<P>
   In his closing argument, William Pepper, a lawyer for the Kings,
said the US Army had a sniper squad poised to shoot King if the
Mafia operative failed. And he asserted that the FBI, CIA, Army
intelligence, and Memphis police helped to cover up the conspiracy.
All the government agencies have denied playing any role in King's
death or a coverup, and none of their representatives was called to
testify in the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Pepper once represented Ray, who pleaded guilty to the
assassination in 1968 and received a 99-year sentence. Ray quickly
recanted his confession, but he died in prison in 1998 after
failing eight times to receive a jury trial on the murder charge.
</P>
<P>
   Pepper has drawn considerable criticism for his conspiracy
theory of King's death, which the King family embraced though much
of it is based on second-hand and third-hand assertions. There also
is scant evidence direct linking the government agencies to the
assassination.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the paucity of evidence, the jury accepted Pepper's
theory after Jowers's lawyer, Lewis Garrison, acknowledged his
client may have played a limited, indirect role in a conspiracy to
kill King.
</P>
<P>
   To some scholars, the evidence the jury used to reach its
verdict was too weak to require a rewriting of history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe the evidence was there of a conspiracy,'' said
Kenneth W. Goings, chairman of the history department at the
University of Memphis. ``It seems the King family, like many
Americans, just can't believe that one very insignificant
individual could create such havoc in their lives and the nation's,
so they keep looking for other forces that could have brought about
that kind of change. But it looks like they're wasting their
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet conspiracy theories for King's murder have long flourished,
and the verdict will likely do little to diminish them. As she sat
facing the balcony where King was killed, Jacqueline Smith, a
former resident of the motel, echoed the reactions of many
Americans to the jury's erdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not news to me,'' Smith said. ``It just confirms what
I've thought all along. He was the victim of a conspiracy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
