<HEADER>
A4544 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-HANCOCK-DEMUTUALIZE-B     12-09 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANCOCK-DEMUTUALIZE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS OK'S HANCOCK DEMUTUALIZATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ State regulators gave an expected nod Thursday to John
Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co.'s plan to convert to a Wall
Street company, removing the last major hurdle facing the Boston
insurer as it prepares to issue first-time stock to the investing
public next month.
</P>
<P>
   The approval by the Massachusetts Division of Insurance came as
the agency roundly rejected strident criticisms from a small group
of consumer advocates and policyholders upset about Hancock's
highly-complex plan.
</P>
<P>
   In a 30-page decision signed by insurance commissioner Linda
Ruthardt, the agency said it was ``not persuaded'' by complaints
that the nation's 13th-largest life insurer had misled customers
about various aspects of its conversion from a mutual firm owned by
policyholders to a stoccpany owned by shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is positive news for our policyholders, and we are
encouraged by Commissioner Ruthardt's decision,'' said Stephen L.
Brown, Hancock's chairman and chief executive, in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The division also said Hancock's highly-publicized inability to
find 400,000 missing policyholders had not raised red flags that
negatively affected the agency's consideration of Hancock's plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we stress the importance of Hancock's continuing efforts
to locate policyholders, we find that. . . the absence of votes
from the still-missing policyholders does notrender the
(conversion) notice and policyholder vote unreasonable or so
prejudicial to policyholders or the insuring public as to compel
disapproval of the Plan,'' the decision said.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock has 3.3 million policyholders, of which 2.9 million are
eligible for cash, stock, or beefier policies in the new company.
About 94 percent of 1.1 million policyholders voted in favor of the
conversion last month, giving Hancock the internal approval it
needs to issue over $2 billion in stock on Jan. 27.
</P>
<P>
   While Hancock plans to allow AWOL customers to come forward and
claim compensation up to seven years after the stock offering,
critics argue that the missing should be given the right to vote
belatedly. The division said Hancock had not sent bills to missing
policyholders or contacted them through agents since 1985, when it
stopped requiring premiums for the small policies, known as
industrials, owned by such customers.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock initially lost track of 800,000 customers, or one
quarter of its total customer base.
</P>
<P>
   Rebutting criticisms raised at a division-sponsored publicearing
last month on Hancock's conversion, the agency also said Ruthardt
was not required ``to determine that the plan is in the best
interests of each and every policyholder, a standard that would be
impossible to attain.'' It rejected arguments by Boston lawyer
Jason Adkins that the division did not give critics or
policyholders enough time to assess the conversion's merits.
</P>
<P>
   And the division said Hancock's complex formula allocating
compensation to policyholders based on their past and future
profitability was fair. The agency noted that it approved a similar
formula for Worcester-based State Mutual Life Insurance Co. of
America when it converted to Allmerica Financial Corp. in 1995.
Critics argue the formula shortchanges policyholders because they
become less profitable to an insurer the longer they own policies.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts regulators also rejected complaints that Hancock
was cheating policyholders by not allowing them subscription rights
in the initial public offering, andsaid such a plan would be too
complex and costly.
</P>
<P>
   Unusual in the insurance industry, Hancock has made cash the
automatic compensation unless policyholders specifically choose
stock.
</P>
<P>
   The division said the move to cash out smaller policyholders was
practical, since the administrative cost of servicing millions of
small shareholders, at $15 per person, was too high. ``In light of
Hancock's expected earnings of $2 per share, Hancock and its
financial advisor, Morgan Stanley, concluded that the expenditure
of nearly half that amount in shareholder servicing costs would be
excessive,'' the division wrote. Hancock said the figure was based
on projectionbut declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock had not intentionally reduced its life insurance
business or violated state laws, the division wrote _ even though
the number of individual life policies Hancock wrote from 1989 to
1997 declined 33 percent, compared with 22 percent for other
insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock plans to create a ``closed block'' protecting
policyholder dividends in its new company, to be known as John
Hancock Financial Services Inc. The division will monitor the block
and require annual reports on its status for at least three years.
</P>
<P>
   Under its plan, Hancock must remain headquartered in
Massachusetts and keep the majority of its employees in-state for
at least four years.
</P>
<P>
   New York regulators, who are upset about New York insurer Mutual
of America's complaints that Hancock has reneged on reinsurance
contracts, must still give their blessings to Hancock's conversion.
``We expect they will do this,'' said a Hancock spokesman, Stephen
Burgay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 2005EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
