<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4545 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-OPENING-NIGHT-2TAKES-     12-09 1380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPENING-NIGHT-2TAKES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAGIC OF OPENING NIGHT ON BROADWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Matthew Broderick canceled at the last minute and
Katie Couric didn't show. There was only one camera crew, and
several audience members failed to come in black tie. But there was
electricity in the air nonetheless as limousines pulled up and
people crowded the sidewalk under the marquee for opening night of
``Kiss Me, Kate.''
</P>
<P>
   Opening night on Broadway isn't what it used to be. The critics
no longer come all at once to that first official performance,
running up the aisles as the curtain falls to rush back to their
typewriters and tap out reviews for tomorrow's papers. (Now the
critics spread themselves out over the last few previews to write
their notices under less time pressure.)
</P>
<P>
   Television pays hardly any attention to opening night anymore.
Where once the invitations were engraved by Tiffany's and everyone
came in black tie, the evenings have grown more casual, with few
calling for formal attire. While the parties afterward, if they
happened at all, used to be intimate affairs at restaurants like
Sardi's _ where the cast members made grand entrances and were
greeted with applause _ now the events are large, costly, heavily
produced extravaganzas that are considered a pro forma perk for
investors.
</P>
<P>
   These developments may have taken some of the urgency and
elegance out of opening night, but some people in the theater
business say the experience is as magical as it always was.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, there's no finer evening,'' said Aubrey Reuben, who
takes photographs for Playbill magazine and has practically not
missed an opening night in 20 years. ``I go every night with
anticipation and hope.''
</P>
<P>
   The elements of opening night include everything from planning
the party to deciding which VIP trumps which VIP for a prime
orchestra seat on the aisle and sending gifts to the cast and crew.
There is also the Gypsy Robe ceremony before the show, a 50-year
tradition under which the chorus member who has appeared on
Broadway the most puts on a good-luck cape that has been passed
from one Broadway production (flops as well as hits) to another.
</P>
<P>
   A close look at one Broadway opening offers a window into the
hectic, happy, sometimes heartbreaking rituals leading up to and
through a show's biggest night. More than any other period in a
production's life, opening night signifies that rare, fleeting
moment of promise, celebration and good will. In just a short time
the sun will rise, bringing with it reviews, and reality will
descend. But for the next few glittering hours, at least, anything
is possible.
</P>
<P>
   THE PUBLICISTS
</P>
<P>
   It is noon on the biting November day before the revival of Cole
Porter's ``Kiss Me, Kate'' is to open at the Martin Beck Theater on
West 45th Street. Chris Boneau and Amy Jacobs of the theatrical
publicity firm Boneau/Bryan-Brown are standing outside with Elie
Landau, the associate company manager of ``Kate,'' talking about
traffic flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to stay on the street,'' Boneau explains. ``We
want them to keep moving.''
</P>
<P>
   They decide to angle the police stanchions in an attempt to
direct people into the theater and discourage them from socializing
on the sidewalk. They do this knowing it's largely futile; people
come to opening night to socialize on the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Boneau, who started his company 10 years ago, plans to have as
many as 15 people from his office present during arrivals.
</P>
<P>
   Time was, Boneau says, when he would have to flip from channel
to channel to catch all the reviews on the 11 o'clock news. Now if
Hollywood pays a visit to Broadway _ as Woody Harrelson did this
season in ``The Rainmaker,'' and Kevin Spacey did in ``The Iceman
Cometh'' _ the cameras show up. Otherwise, they tend to stay away.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the office, Boneau and Ms. Jacobs get down to the
sensitive business of seating the celebrities, theater executives
and journalists they have invited.
</P>
<P>
   He and Ms. Jacobs start out by considering ``who needs an
aisle.'' These, they decide, include Isabelle Stevenson, chairman
of the board of the American Theater Wing; Jed Bernstein, president
of the League of American Theaters and Producers (who always wears
his opening night bow tie for good luck); Al Hirschfeld, the
theater caricaturist, and John McDaniel, the musical director for
Rosie O'Donnell, whose talk show has become an important
promotional tool for Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Taye Diggs, who was featured in ``Rent'' and has since had a
successful film career with ``Go'' and ``How Stella Got Her Groove
Back,'' is expected to attend. ``He's a movie star,'' Boneau says.
``We should really take care of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Boneau and Ms. Jacobs talk about who will be ``happy to sit
upstairs,'' meaning in the mezzanine. ``Jules Feiffer can go
upstairs,'' Boneau says of the cartoonist. ``I hope he doesn't
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're actually very good seats,'' Boneau explains. ``It's
just that stigma of saying, `I'm going upstairs.'''
</P>
<P>
   Among those for whom the publicists make sure to find seats in
the orchestra are the actors Tony Roberts and Laura Linney and the
writers Betty Comden and Adolph Green. Stockard Channing bumps the
director Stanley Donen (``Singin' in the Rain''). Three or four
pairs of seats are always reserved for emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   THE PRE-SHOW
</P>
<P>
   It is about 4:30 p.m., nearly two hours before show time. Even
though the critics no longer need an early curtain, the tradition
of a 6:30 start has remained. Inside the theater the cast members
have gathered in the orchestra seats to warm up their voices with
the musical director, Paul Gemignani, a k a Paulie. Gemignani sits
on the edge of the orchestra pit in a plaid shirt and jeans, taking
them through the opening number, ``Another Op'nin' Another Show.''
</P>
<P>
   The cast then presents its group gifts to the director, Michael
Blakemore (a Mont Blanc pen); the choreographer, Kathleen Marshall
(Tiffany earrings), and Paulie (tequila).
</P>
<P>
   ``What did you need to do this for?'' Gemignani asks. ``You have
the job already.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' answers one chorus member, ``but we want the next
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Berlind, the producer, who had wanted to do ``Kate'' since
the 1980s, hasn't arrived at the theater yet, so his partner, Roger
Horchow, says a few words, concluding with, ``Break a leg.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Berlind _ some have taken to calling them ``the Rogers''
_ put up and raised the $6.5 million it took to produce the show.
``I hope it will recoup,'' Horchow says with his typical Texas
understatement.
</P>
<P>
   After a group picture, the cast gathers in a circle onstage to
hear Terry Marone, guardian of the Gypsy Robe, talk about the
history of the ritual, how it started nearly 50 years ago when a
chorus member in ``Gentlemen Prefer Blondes'' sent a good-luck
dressing gown to a friend in ``Call Me Madam,'' who added a cabbage
rose from Ethel Merman's costume and sent the robe to a friend
opening in ``Guys and Dolls.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Marone announces the ``Kate'' winner, JoAnn M. Hunter, to
whoops of congratulations. Ms. Hunter puts on the robe and runs
three times around the circle, touching all the cast members as
they in turn offer her kisses, cheers and applause. She then visits
every dressing room, in keeping with tradition.
</P>
<P>
   In these dressing rooms the transformation from present-day
actors to 1940s hoofers begins. Amy Spanger, who plays Lois Lane
and gets to sing such classics as ``Always True to You (in My
Fashion),'' has been on Broadway before but in shows that were
already up and running: ``Sunset Boulevard'' and ``Fosse.'' This is
her first opening night. ``It's like the calm before the storm; all
week we've been on eggshells,'' Ms. Spanger says.
</P>
<P>
   In his dressing room next door, Michael Berresse, who plays Lois
Lane's gymnastic beau, Bill Calhoun, is trying to finish the cards
meant to accompany his opening-night gifts to the rest of the cast.
``I am so freaked out,'' Berresse says. ``No matter how prepared
you are, it's always more love than you can handle. Everyone wants
this thing to land.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   THE PERFORMANCE
</P>
<P>
   Outside, the audience is starting to arrive. The square of
bright light under the marquee quickly becomes a crush of fur
collars and strong perfume. Berlind and Horchow stand side by side
near the doors, greeting family members, friends and fellow
producers. (``I've heard wonderful things,'' says Miles Wilkin of
SFX Theatrical.)
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Morison, the original Kate, arrives wearing black,
radiating an ethereal elegance. ``I'm a little nervous,'' she says.
``I know how they're feeling. I so want it to be wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   As more people arrive, Ms. Morison lingers outside among them,
greeting other members of the original cast, making herself
available for interviews. (``Make sure they spell Morison with one
R,'' she says to Boneau.)
</P>
<P>
   Ross Perot arrives, a guest of Horchow. Fran Weissler, the
Broadway producer, shows up with Tommy Tune towering over her. Tune
says that without the critics in the audience anymore, ``opening
nights are like Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   THE PARTY
</P>
<P>
   The coat check is on the left. Suzanne Tobak, Broadway's busiest
party planner, is on the right, coordinating the three-ring circus
that is an opening night party at Tavern on the Green. `` ``How's
seating?'' she asks into her headset.
</P>
<P>
   All this took military-style planning, from the chocolate kisses
decorating the tables (it is ``Kiss Me, Kate'') to the banners with
appropriate song titles hanging around the room (``Wunderbar''
behind the bar, ``Too Darn Hot'' over the dance floor) to the
Shakespeare glossary on fake parchment headed ``Brush Up Your
Shakespeare.''
</P>
<P>
   For ``Annie Get Your Gun'' last season, Tavern on the Green
became what Ms. Tobak called a ``Western blowout,'' with a haystack
outside, a country-western band, an archery range, stagecoaches and
toy guns, in addition to the chicken-and-ribs cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the party for ``Epic Proportions,'' the comedy
about shooting a ``Ten Commandments''-style movie in the 1930s, was
at the Copacabana and featured a live Cleopatra.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes shows have party favors but there are some shows, Ms.
Tobak says, for which such efforts would seem inappropriate. ``I
wouldn't theme into `Death of a Salesman,''' she explains. ``Nor
did I last year. We simply did an elegant evening.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Tobak declines to discuss the cost of an opening
night party, some producers put the range at $50,000 to $100,000.
Ms. Tobak will say she never pays full price for a party; through
bartering and sponsorship, she gets a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   For ``The Iceman Cometh'' last season, Ms. Tobak enlisted Vox
vodka as a sponsor and used their bottles as centerpieces and had
special vodka bars.
</P>
<P>
   The subtext at these parties is the reviews _ particularly the
one in The New York Times. Now that the newspaper is printed in New
Jersey and Queens, publicists say, they miss the thrill of walking
to the Times building on West 43rd Street to get the review hot off
the presses and take it back to the party.
</P>
<P>
   But theater insiders generally say not getting the reviews at
the party makes a better party. ``If the reviews were bad, your
emotions went through the biggest drop you can imagine, right down
into a ditch,'' said James Freydberg, a Broadway producer. Even if
those in the know tried to keep their bad news to themselves, the
feeling seeped out and killed the spirit. These theater veterans
say the cast and crew deserve at least one night of pure joy, no
matter what they may be in for the next morning. As a result, some
producers have insisted that the reviews do not come near the
party.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Kiss Me, Kate,'' however, Boneau gets the Times review
off the Internet at close to 11 p.m. and brings it to the party. He
and Ms. Jacobs then excitedly run through the mirrored corridors of
Tavern on the Green, searching out the Rogers. When they find the
producers, they pull them into a quiet place: the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Boneau does not read the review or reveal that he has it folded
in his breast pocket; he just gives the producers what he knows
they want to hear, that the Times' chief theater critic, Ben
Brantley, generally loved the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time since I've been to one of these,''
Boneau says, ``when it was all about pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   THE MARKETING PLAN
</P>
<P>
   It is 10:30 on the morning after opening night, and the
marketing machine that has grown increasingly sophisticated on
Broadway is in full swing for ``Kiss Me, Kate.'' Coffee, Danish and
fruit are served in the conference room at the offices of Serino
Coyne, the theater ad agency. Boneau, Ms. Jacobs and Polk of
Boneau/Bryan-Brown have taken their seats at the table, along with
several members of the marketing and management teams and, of
course, the Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   The mood is remarkably restrained, given that each person at the
table is sitting in front of a thick stack of rave reviews from
newspapers all over the region, and that everyone present has been
through the opposite experience, when they strained to cull a
positive quotation from a sea of pans.
</P>
<P>
   They do have champagne, which is unusual for an ad meeting.
</P>
<P>
   After writing a radio ad, which immediately goes on the air, the
group discusses which of the gushy lines to lift for the huge
advertisement to appear in the next week's Arts &AMP; Leisure section
of The New York Times, among them: ``Enter musical comedy
paradise'' (Dennis Cunningham, CBS-TV). ``A knockout'' (The
Star-Ledger of Newark).
</P>
<P>
   They also debate whether to go for broke, running three
consecutive full pages instead of two. Wendy Orshan, the show's
general manager, argues against this extravagance, recalling how
theater people felt when Garth Drabinsky, of the now-defunct
Livent, used ostentatious ads for ``Ragtime.'' ``When Garth did
that, didn't we all say, `Who does he think he is?''' Ms. Orshan
says.
</P>
<P>
   The group gathers for a photo in front of the ad they've
designed, now printed out and pinned to the wall. They have just
become part of Broadway history: a hit show that is likely to keep
all of them busy for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   They consider whether to put another block of tickets up for
sale, and everyone agrees it is better to wait. ``We should keep
this,'' Boneau says, ``the hottest ticket in town.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
