<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4548 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AIDA-REVIEW10-COX     12-09 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDA-REVIEW10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A new look for Aida
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Goodbye, pesky pyramid; hello, epic romance. Next
stop: Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aida,'' which left many of its initial mistakes in Atlanta
(including that famously malfunctioning chunk of Egypto-junk) is so
improved that it's a good 80 percent ready for the Great White Way.
The pop musical opened Thursday night at the grandly restored
Cadillac Palace _ itself celebrating a debut _ and performances in
New York are to begin in February.
</P>
<P>
   In making wholesale changes, the Disney producers were shrewd
enough not to throw out the baby with the bathwater. The elements
of ``Aida'' that were so impressive, drawing record crowds to
Atlanta's Alliance Theatre in fall 1998 _ the energizing score by
Elton John and Tim Rice (``The Lion King''), leading ladies Heather
Headley and Sherie Rene Scott _ are still in place and better than
ever. They're enhanced by more sophisticated dialogue (David Henry
Hwang of ``M. Butterfly'' fame) and sets (Bob Crowley,
``Carousel''), and dynamic direction and co-authorship by Chicago's
own Robert Falls, arguably the hottest stage director in America
(``Death of a Salesman'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Aida'' is big, slick and glitzy, yes, but beneath its shiny
pop plating there now thumps a real heart.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for the company, Michael Eisner _ the Disney chairman
who takes a hands-on role in the company's stage work _ agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael saw the show the other night and was very
enthusiastic, which he was not in Atlanta,'' said Rice, sipping a
Diet Coke at the intermission of a recent preview. ``It's a whole
new show, really _ very exciting. I don't expect major changes
before New York.''
</P>
<P>
   True, there is a lingering air of weirdness and confusion at the
top of the show, prompting audience whispers such as, ``What's
going on?,'' ``Where is this taking place?'' (ancient Egypt, but
costumer Crowley throws in gypsies and Klingons, too) and, ``Why is
the Pharaoh wearing a giant ice bucket on his head?'' Falls'
inexperience at handling a singing-dancing chorus, or staging
musicals at all, is most glaring in the first 20 minutes. But then
his showmanship takes hold and the timeless tale of a doomed love
triangle comes into focus and builds in intensity to the final
chord.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Bernhardt, the Alliance board chairman who saw a recent
preview with a contingent of Atlantans, was delighted by the
revamped ``Aida.'' He also was delighted by the line on the
program's title page that credits the Alliance for presenting the
1998 premiere (the credit was harder to find for the Alliance's
Broadway 1997 transfer of ``The Last Night of Ballyhoo.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a terrific shot for the artistic reputation of the
Alliance _ and a financial shot as well,'' Bernhardt said. The
Alliance's royalties are
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) Please see AIDA, F3
</P>
<P>
   expected to be $5,000 to $10,000 a week for the two-month
Chicago engagement, with a comparable revenue flow for the Broadway
run. Though it's a fraction of Disney's share (including exclusive
movie rights), the Alliance royalties are an important windfall for
a nonprofit theater with an accumulated deficit of $1 million. The
Alliance took national criticism for what was seen as an
all-too-commercial partnership with the Mouse, but artistic
director Kenny Leon says the royalties will subsidize his more
adventurous, meaty fare that is not always supported at the box
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aida'' (shortened from its Alliance title, ``Elaborate Lives:
The Legend of Aida'') is based on the myth that inspired the 1871
Verdi opera: the forbidden love of a Nubian princess, Aida
(Headley), and the Egyptian commander Radames (Adam Pascal), who
vanquished her people and is already betrothed to an Egyptian
princess, Amneris (Scott). Those who come listening for for Verdi's
grave splendor will be disappointed. Then again, opera purists are
not the target audience here. In Disney's take, sexpot Amneris
(Scott) is cheekily saluted by a slave as, ``First in beauty,
wisdom and accessories.'' She mocks her own fashion mania and
I-enjoy-being-a-girl narcissism in ``My Strongest Suit,'' which
sounds like Elton's affectionate sendup of sock-hop songs, a la
``Crocodile Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney is aiming for the elusive 18-to-35 market, reawakened by
1996's ``Rent'' to the allegedly mummified art form of musical
theater. The casting of Scott and Pascal (vastly more dynamic than
his Atlanta predecessor, Hank Stratton), who were both in ``Rent,''
is probably not coincidental. Even the dagger-shaped marquee of the
Cadillac Palace (the car sponsorship makes it sound like a Texas
dance hall, but it's actually a magnificent 1900s theater) has the
look of a hip nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish-born Crowley, the reigning genius of designers (even
his sets for the failed ``Capeman'' were astounding) is a key to
``Aida's'' new cool quotient. He specializes in elegant visual
tricks from the subconscious, but on an Imax scale. He shows us an
overhead view of a swimming pool with swimmers zooming through
space; a huge hieroglyphic eye whose pupil can be a blazing sun; a
line of silhouetted palm trees, growing out of their own reflected
image in a shimmering Nile, used in the magazine ads for the
Broadway production (interestingly, those ads mention Disney in the
tiniest print, presumably so that theatergoers in their 20s won't
be scared away by visions of dancing animals).
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Disney wildlife, Headley's New York debut was as
Nala in ``The Lion King,'' but it's as Aida that she displays a
true lioness spirit. If this musical can ever be said to match
Verdi for operatic grandeur, it's when her Aida _ serving as
Amneris' slave but planning to lead a prisoners' revolt _ stands in
the spotlight and sings furiously to the gods about her conflicted
passion and duty. Safe prediction: Headley will be a star.
</P>
<P>
   With due respect to Pascal, who does a fine job on his end of
the romantic duets (including ``Written in the Stars,'' sung by
Elton and LeAnn Rimes in the breakout single from the
all-star``Aida'' CD), Headley's verses are the evening's high
points.
</P>
<P>
   In an even more moving duet, the lovers sing of their
``Elaborate lives ... extravagant times,'' and their aching search
through war for ``a little peace and truth.'' It's a striking
linkage between antiquity and our own danger-filled, millennial
moment. Rice said, ``Yes, I wanted a modern resonance, a relevance,
if that doesn't sound too pompous.''
</P>
<P>
   For a man who sometimes seemed a mere glib assistant to Andrew
Lloyd Webber, Rice now brings a maturity, even a touch of poetic
depth to his lyrics, matched by Elton's more soulful sound. These
qualities were partially drowned out in Atlanta by the pyramid
buzzing, flimsy character development and other problems, but are
now allowed to sing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aida''
</P>
<P>
   Through Jan. 9. 7:30 p.m. Wednesdays-Thursdays; 2 and 8 p.m.
Fridays-Saturdays; 2 and 7:30 p.m. Sundays. $32.50-$75. Cadillac
Palace Theatre, 151 W. Randolph St., Chicago. Tickets: 312-782-1600
(box office) or 312-902-1500 (Ticketmaster).
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
