<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4550 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      12-09 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE BOOK ON GEORGE W. 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   During his first presidential debate, George W. Bush volunteered
that he was reading a book about postwar international policy. It
is possibly a bad sign that we now feel compelled to examine what
he meant by ``read.''
</P>
<P>
   Our leading Republican candidate has been plagued by speculation
that he's not all that deep a thinker. ``I read books all the
time,'' he told the debate audience in New Hampshire, a tad
defensively. ``I'm reading a book on Dean Acheson right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides said the book in question was ``Acheson: the Secretary of
State Who Created the American World,'' by James Chace. Weighing in
at 512 pages, it describes Acheson's work overseeing the
establishment of NATO and the World Bank, and the financing of the
Marshall plan.
</P>
<P>
   How many people out there think that Bush:
</P>
<P>
   A) really read the book
</P>
<P>
   B) really read some of the book
</P>
<P>
   C) was really briefed by an adviser who is reading the book
</P>
<P>
   D) purchased the book and was carrying it around in his suitcase
at the time of the debate.
</P>
<P>
   We don't want to be hyper-critical. Many of us believe that, for
the purposes of dinner party conversation, paying for a book and
hauling it from one hotel room to the next counts as reading it.
Now that I have skimmed two reviews of ``Acheson'' and talked to
the author on the phone for 10 minutes, I feel qualified to assure
you it is one really fine piece of work, and to discuss it at
social events with great authority.
</P>
<P>
   However, the bar gets raised a bit when a presidential candidate
goes on TV and claims to have an impressive-sounding tome on his
night table in order to demonstrate he's not a superficial,
underprepared, overentitled Quayle clone. I think I speak for all
of us in saying that under those circumstances, the alleged reader
should at least prepare a few pithy comments demonstrating that he
knows what the book was about.
</P>
<P>
   A few days and another debate later, Bush was asked, rather
cruelly, what lessons he had learned from his study of the Acheson
era. The flummoxed governor started out with a caution that the
United States should not ``retreat within our borders.'' He put in
a good word for free trade, quoted a speech he gave at the Citadel,
and concluded this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``The lessons of Acheson and Marshall are _ is that our nation's
greatest export to the world has been, is, and always will be the
incredible freedoms we understand in the great land called
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Bush said it was hard to give a full book review ``in a
minute's time,'' but more time was the last thing he appeared to
need. In fact, he looked like a ninth grader had who forgotten to
do his homework, desperately free-associating and hoping the bell
would ring.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush was telling the truth about the Acheson book, he is
apparently capable of reading 512 pages of material and coming away
from the exercise without a single new thought. Even if he's only
made his way through the first few chapters, he should have been
able to answer the debate question by saying he had learned that a
man can become a successful public servant after being a C student
at Yale.
</P>
<P>
   If he was fibbing, the problem is even worse. An American
president meets dozens of heads of state every year, virtually all
of whom have written books, most of them unreadable. How would
President Bush, the Sequel, react when one of them fishes for a
compliment about a recent literary effort? We don't necessarily
need a great reader in the White House, but we do need somebody who
knows how to fake it under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Bush never tried to pass himself off as an intellectual before.
When you've got charisma, who needs a Phi Beta Kappa key? But the
shock of the early debates has been how charmless he's appeared. If
Dan Quayle looked like a deer caught in the headlights when he was
in front of the cameras, Bush sometimes resembles a possum cornered
in the garage _ hunched over, tense, eyes darting worriedly.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in response, his campaign has been trying to upgrade his
image as a thinker. By recent accounts of the Bush team, over the
last few weeks he's devoured approximately 2,000 pages of
nonfiction, including a 774-page biography of John D. Rockefeller
and a 476-page work on Chinese-American relations.
</P>
<P>
   Big books. Deep man.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
