<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4549 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-KIDS10-COX     12-09 0393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-KIDS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Book list for youngsters chock-full of old favorites
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another Y2K-themed ``best of'' booklist is making the rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Scholastic Books has released ``200 for 2000: Literature for the
Millennium,'' a list of great books for younger readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to celebrate the millennium, and also get a
conversation going over how people felt about the old classics and
the new classics,'' said Francie Alexander, a vice president for
the New Jersey-based publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike previous lists for best books, movies and TV shows that
have created controversy, Scholastic didn't rank the books from top
to bottom. Instead, the list simply groups works by age
appropriateness and genre.
</P>
<P>
   Among the better known books for younger readers are
``Charlotte's Web,'' by E.B. White; ``Sylvester and the Magic
Pebble,'' by William Steig; ``The Snowy Day,'' by Ezra Jack Keats;
and ``Goodnight Moon,'' by Margaret Wise Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The work of Theodore Geisel, aka Dr. Suess, makes the list not
for a single book but for his entire goofy-but-wonderful
</P>
<P>
   oeuvre.
</P>
<P>
   For older readers the list includes ``Anne Frank: Diary of a
Young Girl,'' by Anne Frank; ``Stuart Little'' by E.B. White;
``Tales of a Fourth Grade Nothing,'' by Judy Blume; and ``The
Yearling,'' by Marjorie Kinnan Rawlings.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, the wildly popular Harry Potter books by J.K. Rowling
made the list, too.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander said the project started in May when company editors
introduced a 100-book list during a conference, and then posted it
on the company's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden we had hundreds of responses asking, `How
could you leave out such and such?''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander gathered a panel of five independent librarians to
sort through the reponses and to make suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while we realized we couldn't get it down to a
hundred,'' Alexander said. ``We had a hard time narrowing it down
to 200, and there were still hundreds more that didn't make the
cut.''
</P>
<P>
   WEB SITE
</P>
<P>
   For Scholastic Books' entire list of great books for younger
readers, ``200 for 2000: Literature for the Millennium,'' see
www.ajc.com/booklist
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
