r e BC-AIDA-TIMELINE10-COX     12-09 0281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDA-TIMELINE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aida timeline; tracking the show
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE LEADS
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta: Heather Headley as Aida and Sherie Rene Scott as
Amneris were excellent; Hank Stratton as Radames was as plastic as
a Ken doll.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago: Headley and Scott are better than ever. Adam Pascal
(Roger in ``Rent''), the dynamic new Radames, strikes romantic
sparks with Headley.
</P>
<P>
   THE LOOK
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta: Ancient Egypt goofily crossed with ``Star Trek.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago:Sets by Tony Award winner Bob Crowley (``Carousel'')
have dreamlike elegance on an Imax scale.
</P>
<P>
   THE BOOK
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta:
</P>
<P>
   Linda Woolverton's dialogue sounded like it was geared toward
teens, and not even smart ones.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago:
</P>
<P>
   Co-writers David Henry Hwang and Robert Falls (also director)
add a whole new flashback narrative frame, even some wit and
character depth.
</P>
<P>
   THE MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta:
</P>
<P>
   Elton John and Tim Rice's score was already first-rate.
Flavorings of gospel and soul linked vanquished Nubians to today's
African-Ameri-cans; victorious Egyptians were party-rockers.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago:
</P>
<P>
   A new song, ``Not Me,'' adds little, but the score is better
showcased by the overall production.
</P>
<P>
   THE SET
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta:
</P>
<P>
   Pyramid refused to glide, spin or unfold; it buzzed at the worst
possible moments during the romantic duets.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago:
</P>
<P>
   No pyramid, but a levitating tomb falls 15 feet, slightly
injuring Headley and Pascal during an early preview. Latest tomb
stays a nice safe 4 feet off the floor.
</P>
<P>
   _Compiled by Dan Hulbert for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
