<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4554 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-GETAWAY-OPELIKA10-COX     12-09 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY-OPELIKA10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alabama town decks itself out in memory of Victorian era
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OPELIKA, Ala. _ Jan Jones is sneaky.
</P>
<P>
   One night, several Christmases ago, the local artist secretly
placed life-size Santas and angels, carousel horses and teddy bears
on the porches of more than 30 Victorian homes in her historic
North Opelika neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Word got out and people from around the area flocked to admire
her elaborately dressed figures.
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, more than 10,000 visitors are expected in this
east Alabama town for Victorian Front Porch Christmas, which runs
Thursday through Sunday. Carolers, musicians and neighbors in
Victorian attire add to the fun. For the first time, three
storytellers will be positioned on various porches to tell about
the history of the houses and the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The costumes and figures are breathtaking,'' says resident
Nita Guthrie. ``Everyone has such fun and it brings the community
together.''
</P>
<P>
   The free tour is open to automobiles and walkers from 6-9 p.m.
Dec. 9-12. From 6-9 p.m. Saturday, the streets are closed to cars
so carolers, neighbors and visitors can experience the spectacle on
foot.
</P>
<P>
   The walking tour begins at North Eighth Street and Second Avenue
at the Heritage House, a bed-and-breakfast. Folks can stroll up to
Seventh Avenue, then come back down Eighth Street to Fifth Avenue
and turn right and go to North Ninth Street. Then, they can take a
left onto Third Avenue and walk back up Ninth Street.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Victorian Front Porch Christmas event,
Opelika offers plenty of Southern hospitality via its inviting
antiques stores and gift shops,
</P>
<P>
   To say nothing of a princely Croak-A-Lika Frog.
</P>
<P>
   In the heyday of trains, Opelika was a transportation hub and
had many railroad tracks. The section of track that crossed was
held together by metal frogs _ devices for keeping train cars on
the right rails at intersections. Artistic license has been taken
with the word frog by the Christmas artist Jones, who makes amusing
papier-mache frog collectibles and dresses them in a variety of
clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, trains chug through Opelika on historic Railroad
Avenue, which is home to a variety of shops in refurbished
buildings. It's also the perfect place to park your car and stroll
the sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some engineers blow their horns all the way through town,''
said Joanne Woodall of Southern Crossing, a gift shop on Railroad
Avenue. ``Others just give a short beep. But after awhile, you
don't pay any attention to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodall and five other women have owned the shop, a former
hardware store, for four years. Each does her own buying, and the
mix includes everything from the frogs and painted furniture to
jewelry and antiques. ``For six women, we all get along and have a
good time,'' Woodall said with a laugh. ``When we have a difference
of opinion, we vote and whatever the consensus, that's what goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Another neighbor on this historic avenue is the two-story shop
the Gallery. Built in 1865, the building was originally a saloon
but for the past 20 years has housed frames, prints, European
garden ornaments, accessories and gifts. Owner Deborah Purves said
there's ``a whole new beat going on'' in downtown Opelika. ``Thank
goodness, people are revitalizing.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the tracks, but still on the avenue, is High Cotton, an
eclectic gift shop located in an old cotton warehouse. Items range
from Vera Bradley's patterned soft luggage to Vietri Italian
pottery and Mississippi artist Vicki Carroll's hand-painted china.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Friday, two friends from Baton Rouge, La., Sally
Pareti and Debbie Sikes, were shopping for Christmas gifts, and,
for themselves. The two had stopped on their way to Atlanta to
visit relatives. ``There's a charm about Opelika,'' said Pareti,
who was looking for something ``I can't find at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Opelika derives its name from the Creek Indian words Opila for
swamp and laka for large or big, thus meaning Big Swamp. Since
Opelika is actually the highest elevation between Atlanta to New
Orleans, why the name Big Swamp? Historians say the streams and
creeks throughout the area that were being fed by the lakes caused
the Indians to choose swamp as a descriptive term.
</P>
<P>
   Like many smaller towns, downtown Opelika, incorporated in 1854,
has had its retail ups and downs. ``In the early '70s, streets were
closed off and monstrous steel awnings were put on storefronts,''
said Sherri Sumners, president of the Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vacancies were running 40 percent. It was a ghost town. The
city fathers saw that something had to be done. They refurbished
the train station, which now houses the arts association,
demolished some buildings to build a park and took down those
awnings. Between 1989 and 1999, $22 million in capital investment,
both public and private, was pumped into Opelika.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, there's 5 percent vacancy in the area and the town of
28,000 is working to build loft apartments in the century-old
buildings _ to attract people to live downtown.
</P>
<P>
   One shop that's been a constant in town in Winston Smith T
Hardware on Railroad Avenue. For more than 60 years, this store,
which is in a turn-of-the-century building, has been selling
everything from building supplies and mail boxes to tools. ``I have
an old invoice book from '44, which lists transactions,'' said
Dozier Smith T, grandson of the original owner Winston. ``Now I
have the sons and daughters of those customers as my customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's what separates our store from the other boys. We
know each customer by name.''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Getting there
</P>
<P>
   Take I-85 south to Exit 62. Follow U.S. 280 (toward Birmingham)
into town. It's about 100 miles from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Hours
</P>
<P>
   From 6-9 Friday night, retailers on Railroad Avenue will treat
shoppers to holiday treats, hot wassail and live music. Kids can
ride a miniature train and meet Santa and Mrs. Claus. Typically,
most shops are open 10 a.m.-6 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays; however, some
close early on Wednesdays and Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   Information
</P>
<P>
   Opelika Chamber of Commerce, 601 Ave. A. 1-800-673-5452; or go
online at www.opelika.com.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Venable's has lace curtains at the window and Miss Martha as
the gracious hostess-owner who whips up pure comfort food. If you
want light fare, try the cold plate: chicken salad, raspberry
congealed salad, fresh fruit and deviled eggs ($6.75). For heartier
appetites, go for the Southern sideboard buffet, which might
feature chicken pot pie, meat loaf, mashed potatoes, black-eyed
peas and broccoli casserole plus yeast rolls and corn bread muffins
($7.25). Save room for banana pudding or coconut cream pie ($2.95).
Hours: 11 a.m.-2 p.m. weekdays. 913 S. Railroad Ave. 334-745-0834.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Other recommendations: Try soul food at Made from Scratch, 124
S. Eighth St. (334-742-2676). It's chicken fingers at the Breezeway
, 213 S. Eighth St. (334-749-5167), and continental specialities at
Warehouse Bistro, 105 Rocket Ave. (334-745-6353).
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Heritage House: The innkeeper is Opelika Mayor Barbara
Patton, who with her son Richard, oversees an elegant 1914 home in
a historic neighborhood. It's minutes from downtown, championship
golf at the Grand National Robert Trent Jones Golf Course and
Auburn University. Each of the five rooms has a private bath.
$70-$95 (includes full breakfast). No smoking or pets. 714 Second
Ave. 334-705-0485.
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
