r e BC-MOVIES-MCTEER10-COX     12-09 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MCTEER10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McTeer hones maternal instincts once again for `Tumbleweeds'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago, British actress Janet McTeer riveted Broadway
audiences and won the Tony Award for best actress in ``A Doll's
House,'' playing a conventional 19th-century mother gathering the
strength to leave her stuffy marriage. Now she's turning heads at
the multiplex with her electric performance in ``Tumbleweeds,''
playing another kind of mom, a Southern hellion who drags her
preteen daughter cross-country in search of a new life.
</P>
<P>
   The two projects are connected. ``Tumbleweeds'' co-writer and
director Gavin O'Connor first saw McTeer on ``The Charlie Rose
Show'' during the Broadway run, and saw in her the movie's rowdy
Mary Jo, based loosely on his then-wife's mother. ``I have no idea
how he saw Mary Jo in me,'' McTeer says from her London home,
brewing an afternoon cup of tea. ``I think it has to do with being
uncompromising. I had very short black hair at the time, and I
certainly wasn't looking girly.''
</P>
<P>
   One challenge of shooting ``Tumbleweeds'' was playing most of
her scenes opposite 13-year-old Kimberly Brown, co-starring as Mary
Jo's daughter. ``We just sort of clicked and became great
friends,'' McTeer says of the process, which required the two to
improvise some scenes as they filmed. ``We were very keen not to
treat her as a kid. She and I were the two leading actresses, so we
discussed everything. We questioned her and challenged her. It
wasn't about my leading and having her follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Another challenge of the shoot: nailing a Southern accent. She
took a couple of lessons with a voice coach. ``We could only afford
about two, because we didn't have much money,'' McTeer says. She
watched movies like ``Coal Miner's Daughter,'' visited North
Carolina and tried out her accent on taxi drivers.
</P>
<P>
   McTeer recently returned to North Carolina on business, shooting
the period film ``Songcatcher.'' But her accent work didn't help:
In that movie, opening next year, she had to perfect a
turn-of-the-century Boston accent. Now, having shot four movies in
the past 18 months, she's glad to take a break in London for the
holidays. But New Line, the distributor of ``Tumbleweeds,'' is
keeping her in the spotlight, lobbying for year-end award
nominations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it very much,'' she says of the attention. ``It's
very odd. Some of the people I've met have been very nice. But
sometimes it's a little bit daunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm not sure I'm particularly interesting enough to write
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
