<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4556 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-RAGE10-COX     12-09 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAGE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rage cranks sonic assault to critical praise
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the first acts to really make something out of the
rap-rock template, Rage Against the Machine might be the most
influential band in business right now. For better or worse, the
Los Angeles group perfected the testosterone-rich formula that
dominates late-'90s rock, where jagged, dissonant guitar heroics
meet hip-hop beats and phrasing.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of the bands it's inspired, however, Rage Against
the Machine exploits the hybrid musical style with an ambitious
sense of scope, and an agenda that puts it in the grand American
tradition of social protest that links Woody Guthrie to Public
Enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``At last, radical rockers who actually sound as earthshaking as
the MC5 were supposed to 30 years ago,'' writes critic Eric
Weisbard in the January issue of Spin, which named Rage its band of
the year and placed its latest album, ``The Battle of Los
Angeles,'' second in its Top 20 list of 1999 pop albums. Tracks
such as ``Calm Like a Bomb'' and ``Guerrilla Radio'' accurately
describe the band's concept, which feeds on the tension between
guitarist Tom Morello's innovative fretwork _ with its fusillades
of disorienting sonic effects _ and vocalist Zach de la Rocha's
passionate raps, which target everything from oppressive regimes in
Central America to police violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're one of the best bands I've ever worked with,'' says
Brendan O'Brien, the Atlanta-based producer who directed Rage's
breakthrough 1996 album, ``Evil Empire'' as well as ``Battle.''
``And live, they're one of the best if not the best performing acts
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Fan and label mate Emily Saliers of the Indigo Girls counts Rage
as one of her favorite acts. ``They're an incredible band, one of
the greatest,'' she says. ``I saw them at the Masquerade once, and
they were mind-blowing.''
</P>
<P>
   The band's unabashedly leftist politics have prompted its
critics to take pokes: Rolling Stone magazine compared Rage's
lyrics to the hyperventilated dogma of a religious tract, and
references to ``pigs'' and ``devils'' can seem like a throwback to
'60s revolutionary lingo that may be lost on the kids roiling in
the mosh pit.
</P>
<P>
   But Morello insists that the band's message is getting across.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's difficult for folks outside of it to adjust to
the fact that 435,000 people could go out in one week and buy a
Rage record, and if they do get it, that's kind of threatening,''
Morello says. ``Our audience is an intelligent one. It's not that
our message is that well hidden, it's there in every song, on every
T-shirt, in every video.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up being a fan of bands _ my first favorite band was
Kiss, and they were loathed by all reviewers,'' he continues.
``That set my barometer. We've made the album of our career. We've
got a sold-out arena tour of the U.S. It's awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard-educated Morello may be one of the most articulate
lead guitarists in contemporary rock, the child of activist
parents, who hails from an Illinois town with a perfectly Norman
Rockwell name: Libertyville. He traces his political awakening to
childhood. ``Growing up brown-skinned in a predominantly white
town, issues come up early and often on the playground,'' he says.
``I realized early on that the history I had learned at home was
very different than the one I learned at school, and when pressed,
the teachers weren't so sure about party lines.''
</P>
<P>
   The band's success has helped rewrite rock history in one
important, though complicated way. ``When we started, there was
white music or black music and you had to choose,'' says Morello.
``So Rage seemed destined for oblivion. The curse of having a
multiethnic band. At that time, if you had a black guy in your
band, there was no way you'd be taken seriously as a rock band, and
if you had a white guy you were never viable in the hip-hop
community. And a guy of Chicano descent? There's no room for that
in the spectrum.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Rage Against the Machine'' (1992, Epic).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Evil Empire'' (1996, Epic).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Battle of Los Angeles'' (1999, Epic).
</P>
<P>
   IN CONCERT
</P>
<P>
   Rage Against the Machine
</P>
<P>
   With Gang Starr. 8 tonight. $25 (tickets still available).
Philips Arena, 1 Philips Drive N.W. 404-249-6400.
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
