<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-WINTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX SEEKING PITCHING AT WINTER MEET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As is his custom, Red Sox GM Dan Duquette is shedding
little light on the team's plans entering baseball's five-day
winter meetings, which open Friday in Anaheim. The word from his
office Thursday was that the GM was in, but not ``available.''
</P>
<P>
   This much is certain: Unlike White Sox GM Ron Schueler, who is
staying home and letting his lieutenants conduct his team's
business at the meetings, Duquette is planning to head up the Sox
delegation, which is expected to include top aides Eddie Haas and
Lee Thomas and big-league scout Frank Malzone, among others.
</P>
<P>
   This much is also as obvious as the new scar on Bret
Saberhagen's shoulder: The Sox come into the meetings in search of
more pitching to bolster a starting rotation looking rather thin in
December.
</P>
<P>
   The high-end help that could resolve the Sox shortage has little
appeal to Duquette, according to some of his earlier public
pronouncements. The Anaheim Angels, for example, elected to let
free-agent lefthander Chuck Finley walk this week rather than offer
him salary arbitration. Signing Finley, therefore, would not cost
the Sox any draft choices in compensation, but the asking price for
the 37-year-old Finley is expected to be at least $25 million for
three years.
</P>
<P>
   A ludicrous sum for a pitcher who has averaged just 12 wins in
the last three seasons? If you are among those answering in the
affirmative, you have company in Texas Rangers owner Tom Hicks, who
wasn't speaking about Finley directly but complained this week that
some of his colleagues are spending like ``drunken sailors,''
citing the $12 million one-year deal the Yankees gave pitcher David
Cone this week. And Duquette has said that Finley is too rich for
his blood, and the same probably holds true for such free agents as
Aaron Sele, Kenny Rogers and Darren Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   Even a free-agent righthander like Steve Trachsel, offered
arbitration by the Cubs this week, reportedly is seeking a
three-year deal in the neighborhood of $6 million to $7 million a
year. This, after going 8-18 with a 5.56 ERA last season, when he
won four of his last six decisions to avoid becoming a 20-game
loser.
</P>
<P>
   Free-agent righthander Omar Olivares, a 15-game winner last year
in a season split between the Angels and A's, is an intrigiung
possibility, but his agent, Scott Boras, said the 32-year-old
Olivares wants a four- or five-year deal. The budget-conscious A's
offered Olivares arbitration, but probably did so only to ensure
they'll get something in return when someone else coughs up the
cash.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox could look at some cheaper free-agent alternatives, like
Bobby Witt or ex-Rangers rigfhthander Joihn Burkett, but neither
was effective last season. Witt was just 1-9 in the season's last
two months to finish 7-15, while Burkett, 35, was just 9-8 with a
5.62 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   The pickings may be just as slim in the trade market. The Sox
have talked with the Dodgers about Ismael Valdes and Darren
Dreifort and have inquired about Padres lefthander Sterling
Hitchcock, but a deal with either club would require Duquette to
part with prospects he's disinclined to give up, including
shortstop Adam Everett and left-handed power hitter Dernell
Stenson.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants have some pitching for whom they might be willing to
listen to offers, including righthanders Kirk Rueter and Shawn
Estes, the Yankees would consider parting with righthander Hideki
Irabu, a relative bargain at $2 million for next season, and the
Devil Rays are expected to field offers for righthander Rolando
Arrojo. But it's a seller's market, and Duquette may find few
takers for the players he'd be willing to move, including third
baseman John Valentin and second baseman Jeff Frye.
</P>
<P>
   There's little question that the Sox, who went through a
league-high 13 starting pitchers last season, will have new names
to audition come next spring. Whether Duquette lands any of those
pitchers this weekend remains to be seen, and the new acquisitions
may be just as nondescript as last winter's pickups, Mark Portugal
and Pat Rapp.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings may not produce a blockbuster to rival last month's
Shawn Green-Raul Mondesi deal between the Dodgers and Blue Jays,
nor a free-agent signing to rival that of first baseman John Olerud
by the Mariners earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, those names will pale by comparison if the
Mariners succeed in dealing Ken Griffey Jr., with the Cincinnati
Reds still the team most likely to land Junior if a trade is
consummated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
