<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ISRAEL-REACT-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ISRAEL, SOME ARE EBULLIENT, SOME WARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: MIDEAST-ASSESS, MIDEAST-ARABS-REACT)  
(lh) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The news that Israel is sitting down to peace talks
with Syria galvanized opposition and government forces alike
Thursday, with Likud Party leader Ariel Sharon mobilizing
resistance to the expected surrender of the Golan Heights and
center-left parties rallying behind Ehud Barak, their suddenly
ebullient prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a government that was born to make history,'' crowed
Yossi Sarid, head of the leftist Meretz faction, which was lately
devoting much of its energy to carping at Barak's economic
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Even the long-stagnant Tel Aviv stock market seemed giddy,
jumping 4 percent on the news.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the Israeli prime minister and foreign minister,
virtually all political leaders here were caught off guard by
President Clinton's announcement Wednesday that Barak and Syria's
foreign minister, Farouk al-Sharaa, will begin talks in Washington
next week.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday they scrambled to embrace or denounce the decision, as
commentators noted how the prospect of peace with Israeli's last
belligerent neighbor had instantly transformed the political
climate here.
</P>
<P>
   In a Tel Aviv meeting Thursday with members of his own Labor
Party, who in a gathering just a week ago had shouted bitter
complaints about his budget plans, Barak was greeted with sustained
cheers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years ago as foreign minister I saw and sat one person
away from Farouk al-Sharaa at lunch given by the King of Spain, but
we couldn't speak with him,'' Barak told his party colleagues. ``It
was impossible to conduct a dialogue, and today we are able to
conduct a dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon, meanwhile, who had been frustrated in his efforts to
unite the right behind his own dispirited Likud party, greeted the
announcement as a gift: Here was a fundamental issue clearly
separating his allies from Barak's coalition partners.
</P>
<P>
   In gatherings Thursday of Likud activists and other opposition
leaders, Sharon blasted the Barak plan as a capitulation both to
President Hafez Assad of Syria and President Clinton. ``American
internal interests don't have a thing to do with vital Israeli
interests,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon, especially relishes the prospect of a national
referendum on any peace deal with Syria as an opportunity to undo
the last election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talks are not dangerous,'' Sharon told a state radio
interviewer Thursday. ``What is dangerous is the content of the
talks, and the commitment of Prime Minister Barak to a full
withdrawal from the Golan Heights, despite the denials still being
issued by the prime minister's office.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big victory for Syria,'' Sharon said. He asserted
that officials in Damascus contend that Barak communicated a
willingness to withdraw to the shoreline of the Sea of Galilee,
Israel's border with Syria before their 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   David Levy, the foreign minister, disputed that assertion. ``We
will not go into an agreement that means the line of Galilee,
period,'' he said. ``I reiterate the government position that
everybody knows, that there is no return to the line of Galilee or
to June 4, 1967.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Syria peace talks disclosure also prompted an unusual public
commentary by former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling in Paris, Netanyahu was quoted as saying that Assad
had secretly agreed to his demand for continued Israeli control of
Mount Hermon _ the peak of the Golan Heights _ but that talks had
foundered when Israel refused to withdraw back to pre-1967 borders.
Netanyahu had been largely silent on his own unsuccessful pursuit
of a Syrian peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, never lacking for confidence, claims he is succeeding
where his predecessor failed because he has delivered on promised
land-for-peace concessions to the Palestinians. ``I promised to
advance the negotiations with the Palestinians, and the
negotiations advanced,'' the prime minister said in an interview
published in Israel Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In the Golan Heights, Israeli residents held emergency meetings
Thursday to plan their response. Though Israeli peace advocates
envision accords under which Israel could retain water rights in
the area and full access for military surveillance purposes, almost
every scenario assumes the evacuation of Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most residents of the Golan, and all the Golan leadership,
oppose leaving the Golan Heights,'' said Eli Malca, chairman of the
Golan Heights Settlements Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as Barak often reminds his adversaries, he won 56 percent of
the Golan vote last May on a platform that made peace with Syria a
top priority. Yoav Tzur, who heads a pro-Barak ``Golan with Peace''
group, said Thursday that the prime minister received ``a clear
mandate from the public, including the Golan residents, to move
towards peace. With this mandate he is going forward, and
justifiably so.''
</P>
<P>
   But surveys show that even liberal Israelis are wary of a pact
with an aging Syrian dictator who has invaded their country twice
in their lifetime.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a poll released Thursday by Tel Aviv University, but
conducted before Wednesday's announcement, a surprisingly strong 47
percent plurality of Israelis pronounced themselves ``greatly
opposed'' to a peace with Syria that required withdrawal from the
Golan Heights. Only 23 percent said they were either ``greatly'' or
``somewhat'' in favor of such a tradeoff. Yet just a small minority
of the same group of Israelis surveyed oppose plans for a
land-for-peace deal with the Palestinians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
