<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLPREVIEW10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cards, Bucs work their way back into contention
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Cardinals and Buccaneers seemed dead more than a
month ago. Now, both teams are scratching their way back into the
NFL playoff picture.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona, which had a 2-6 record on Nov. 7 and trailed Washington
by three games in the NFC East, can tie the first-place Redskins
with a victory at Washington on Sunday. The Cardinals have won four
games in a row _ their longest streak since 1988 _ and are 5-2
against teams in their division.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona has been sparked by the return of quarterback Jake
Plummer, who missed more than a month with a broken ring finger.
But the Cards' defense has been the difference. Arizona is allowing
only 17.3 points a game over the past four.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense has carried this team,'' Cardinals wide receiver
Frank Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona will have to slow down the Redskins, who have the NFC's
No. 2 offense at 368.3 yards per game. Washington has scored 347
points in 12 games, second only to St. Louis' 400. The Cardinals
have scored 183 points this season, fewest in the NFC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hope Washington wouldn't score a lot of points against
us,'' Cardinals coach Vince Tobin said. ``But they certainly have
the firepower to do that and have done it against almost everyone.
Regardless, we have to be more efficient offensively. We have to be
able to utilize our weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buccaneers, who have won five games in a row, haven't been
very efficient on offense, either. But first place in the NFC
Central is on the line when the Lions travel to Tampa Bay on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in crunch time,'' Bucs defensive lineman Brad Culpepper
said. ``We're in December. If you look at the past with (Bucs
coach) Tony (Dungy), we've always done pretty well in December. It
means the most. You hate to say one game means more than the next,
but the month of December is when championships are built. There's
no way there's a letdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Buccaneers rookie Shaun King, who beat the Vikings in his first
NFL start last week, has won his past 15 games, including a perfect
12-0 season at Tulane last year. King's last loss came at
Mississippi on Nov. 15, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   _ Divisional matchup: The Patriots will be fighting for their
playoff lives when they travel to Indianapolis. New England is
three games behind the Colts in the AFC East. A loss would all but
knock the Pats out of the postseason. ``It looks like we need to
win the rest of our games,'' New England quarterback Drew Bledsoe
said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Grudge match: The Eagles stunned the Cowboys 13-10 on Oct. 10,
when Philadelphia quarterback Doug Pederson threw a 28-yard
touchdown to Charles Johnson with 1:07 left. Dallas has won its
past seven games at home, including all five this season.
</P>
<P>
   _ Upset opportunity: The Patriots have their backs against the
wall. Bledsoe has torched the Colts in the past, throwing for 15
touchdowns in his past six games vs. Indianapolis. Youth will catch
up with the Colts at some point, won't it?
</P>
<P>
   _ Fantasy play: Falcons quarterback Chris Chandler had six
touchdown passes the past two weeks. He should have his way with
San Francisco's secondary, which has been a revolving door this
season.
</P>
<P>
   _ Individual matchup: New England cornerback Ty Law will cover
Colts receiver Marvin Harrison, who needs only five catches to
break Marshall Faulk's club record of 86 in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
