<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4567 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-FILM-GREENMILE-SPI &LR;      12-09 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GREENMILE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS A RICHLY TEXTURED THRILLER, `GREEN MILE' GOES THE DISTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It wasn't that many years ago that any movie that operated off
an occult theme was automatically considered to be exploitation
fodder. Adaptations of Stephen King's more ghoulish novels, in
particular, were invariably low-budget affairs with third-level
stars and no press screening.
</P>
<P>
   But in the '90s, the occult has joined the mainstream, a trend
that should continue with the mega-success of last summer's ``The
Sixth Sense.'' In fact, there are darn few movies these days that
don't accept the existence of ghosts, angels, demons, aliens,
prophecies, miracles, or some other unearthly being or unseen
energy.
</P>
<P>
   So it is no huge surprise that one of our decade-ending holiday
movie season biggies is a three-hour adaptation of a Stephen King
occult thriller that boasts arguably Hollywood's biggest male star
_ Tom Hanks _ and is played in the kind of leisurely-paced, low-key
manner that we normally associate with serious-minded, ``prestige''
Hollywood dramas.
</P>
<P>
   Told in flashback (with an opening and closing that recalls
``Saving Private Ryan'' perhaps a bit too deliberately), it's the
story of a kind-hearted security guard (Hanks) who runs the death
row _ the ``Green Mile'' of the title _ of a Mississippi prison in
the bleak Depression year of 1935.
</P>
<P>
   One day, the Mile gets a new prisoner: a gigantic
(seven-foot-plus, 300 pounds), seemingly simple-minded man (Michael
Clarke Duncan) who has been convicted of the unspeakably brutal
rape-murder of two small children but is _ paradoxically _ gentle,
deathly afraid of the dark and in possession of miraculous powers
of healing.
</P>
<P>
   So the film becomes an occult thriller, as the guard gradually
comes to grasp the full extent of the man's power; a detective
story, as he struggles to ferret out the facts behind the man's
alleged crime; and an intense prison drama, with internal feuds,
political maneuvering and other parallels to such classics of the
genre as ``The Last Mile'' and ``Birdman of Alcatraz.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone going into the film expecting a typical King thrill-fest
is bound to be disappointed, and possibly even bored. To be sure,
gory elements _ rape-murder, ghoulish executions, much prison
brutality _ are present in spades, but they're not really staged
for titillation, and the tone and style are far removed from the
grab-you-by-the-throat horror of ``Cujo'' or ``The Shining.''
</P>
<P>
   The film is much more character-driven, and is handled in a more
classic filmmaking style by director-writer Frank Darabont, who is
never afraid to take the time he feels is necessary to establish
secondary characters and a complex web of relationships. The film
is even more textured and less gratuitous than ``The Shawshank
Redemption,'' Darabont's 1994 adaptation of another Stephen King
prison story.
</P>
<P>
   The supporting cast is especially strong. Duncan is wonderfully
tortured and sympathetic as the Christ-like healer; veteran
character actor Dabbs Greer gives an engaging, career-topping
performance as the elderly version of the Hanks character; and
James Cromwell, Bonnie Hunt, David Morse, Michael Jeter, Patricia
Clarkson and Doug Hutchison are all memorable.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Hanks holds all these elements together with his own
effortless magic. As he grows older and more jowly, he seems to be
settling ever more gracefully into his star persona, secure enough
to allow his character to be flawed, generous enough to give much
screen time to his supporting players, so completely appealing that
it's becoming harder and harder to dispute the contention that he's
Jimmy Stewart's replacement as Hollywood's great Everyman.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Mile. Directed and written by Frank Darabont. Cast:
Tom Hanks, Michael Clarke Duncan, David Morse, James Cromwell,
Bonnie Hunt. Warner Bros. 180 minutes. Rated R for horror, prison
violence, and language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
