<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4569 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-MOOKIE10-COX     12-09 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MOOKIE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Blaylock in exile, no happy homecoming
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's a homecoming of sorts tonight at Philips Arena
for Mookie Blaylock. Seven years the Hawks' point guard, Blaylock
is the floor general for the beleaguered Golden State Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   He is looking forward to seeing some of his old teammates, but
don't expect him to be nostalgic about facing the Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Blaylock was most excited about returning to Atlanta to
see his dog, a golden retriever. Blaylock, 31, talked more fondly
of giving ``Digger'' his nightly walk and splashing around in a
nearby river than he did about seeing old cohorts. ``He calls me
every day,'' Blaylock said about Digger. The dog lives with a
house-sitter in the home that the 6-foot-1 guard still maintains in
suburban Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Blaylock plans to live here after he retires from the game. But
his allegiance to the Hawks ended after he was traded in June to
Golden State for the No. 10 pick in the draft, Jason Terry; Bimbo
Coles; and the since-released Duane Ferrell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some good years here,'' Blaylock said, ``but I'm the
type of person that couldn't care less about the Hawks now.''
</P>
<P>
   He named Dikembe Mutombo and Alan Henderson as teammates
remaining on the club that he was the closest to. For all the
criticism Blaylock received for a game that deteriorated to a
barrage of 3-point shots, his departure hit some of the players
hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to believe (the trade) when it happened,''
Mutombo said. ``It'll be hard to look at him in a different
uniform. He was a really special teammate.''
</P>
<P>
   Blaylock, averaging just 8.7 points on 33 percent shooting,
wonders how the fans will receive him. Earlier this week, he
watched teammate John Starks get a rousing standing ovation during
his first return to New York against the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might hear some boos,'' he said. ``It was great what John
got in New York. To get what he got lets him know the people really
appreciated what he did for the team. You have to respect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Blaylock might not have played well all the time, but he
certainly put out the effort, which left an imprint on the Hawks.
He earned their respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mookie did a great job for us,'' coach Lenny Wilkens said. ``I
know last season was tough on him because he didn't shoot the ball
as well as he'd like. But he always gave 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Warriors saw that. They had playoff aspirations, and they
deemed Blaylock the point guard to lead them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can he shoot? Yeah,'' coach P.J. Carlesimo said when Blaylock
was acquired. ``Can he make free throws? Yeah. Can he get to the
rim? Yeah. Can he run the pick-and-roll? Yeah. Can he guard other
guards? Yeah. He's got a lot of yesses in his portfolio. That's the
thing I like most about him.''
</P>
<P>
   That despite Blaylock's subpar season last year in which he shot
just 38 percent _ 31 percent on 3-pointers _ with just 5.8 assists
a game. Not even Blaylock could deny he was far from his best.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a great year; it could have been better,'' he said.
``Instead of relaxing and going out and playing, I put a lot of
pressure on myself. That kind of threw me off.''
</P>
<P>
   He must really be thrown off now, for the Warriors are in a
shambles. Blaylock never experienced the kind of hopelessness he
faces now in his first season with Golden State. A checklist of
trouble as long as a Blaylock 3-pointer marks the Warriors, a team
mired in an 11-game losing streak that has threatened the job
security of Carlesimo.
</P>
<P>
   They face the Hawks as the Pacific Division's cellar-dweller at
2-16. They have not won a game in nearly a month. They have a
former All-Star in Starks, unhappy with his role as a reserve and
slowed by an ankle injury. Centers Erick Dampier and Tim Young and
small forward Donyell Marshall are on the injured list. Forwards
Terry Cummings and Chris Mills are battling bad ankles and might
not play tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the Warriors are last in the NBA in field-goal
percentage, 25th in free-throw shooting and 25th in scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Worse of all, a loser's mentality seemingly has set in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until you can sustain some success,'' Starks said, ``it's
always in the back of your mind that you're going to end up
losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Forward Jason Caffey said: ``It doesn't make sense for us to go
out and play hard and, when it's closing time, you chicken out. It
doesn't make sense to play hard and then not believe in
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Warriors have trouble scoring and defending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basic defense,'' Blaylock said. ``We're not really playing
that. In high school, what does the coach say? `Ball, you, man.'
That's high school stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of talk does not bode well for Carlesimo. Neither does
it when general manager Garry St. Jean says: ``Here's where it's
at. Anybody who's watched us so far has a right to be upset, and we
understand that. You can't use alibis in this league. Injuries are
part of the game, and we've been hit. That's the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a tough way right now.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
