<HEADER>
A4572 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-STATION-RADIATION-HNS     12-09 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATION-RADIATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA URGED TO BETTER MONITOR RADIATION LEVELS AT SPACE STATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ NASA should quickly improve its ability
to monitor and forecast the radiation levels that pose a health
risk to spacewalking astronauts as they build the U.S.-led
international space station, the National Research Council reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The research council urged the space agency to equip the outside
of the orbital outpost with radiation monitors as soon as possible.
It also called for better use of the radiation level information
already gathered by existing satellites to avoid spacewalks during
the periods of greatest risk.
</P>
<P>
   Though not immediately life-threatening even in worst-case
estimates, episodes of high radiation could equal the equivalent of
several hundred chest X-rays, increasing an astronaut's risk of
cancer later in life, said George Siscoe, the Boston University
space physics researcher who chaired the council's 10-member panel.
</P>
<P>
   With monitors on the exterior of the station that constantly
relay radiation levels on the station to NASA's Mission Control
Center and better use of satellite information about solar storms,
NASA flight directors would have greater flexibility in the
scheduling of assembly missions as well as spacewalks to lessen the
exposure, the panel reported.
</P>
<P>
   NASA has referred the report's findings to the agency's Johnson
Space Center, where the recommendations will be reviewed by medical
experts, said John Ira Petty, a spokesman for the facility.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the space agency observes Occupational Safety and
Health Administration guidelines for 30-day and one-year exposure
limits. But unanticipated exposures could limit the number of
spacewalks astronauts could participate in during a single flight
as well as their availability for assignments on subsequent
missions, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The limits for eye and skin are rather small, and these are
the things that can affect the timing and the decisions that flight
directors have to worry about,'' said Siscoe.
</P>
<P>
   The Earth's magnetic field furnishes a natural barrier to much
of the harmful radiation that streams from the sun and deep space.
</P>
<P>
   Started in late 1998, the construction of the new orbital
outpost nonetheless will correspond with the maximum period of
activity during the 11-year solar cycle.
</P>
<P>
   The assembly will require at least 43 more spaceflights through
at least 2004. During construction, at least 161 two-astronaut
spacewalks are planned, placing astronauts outside the safety of
the space shuttle or the station itself for more than 1,700 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Based on its assessments of radiation fluctuations during the
most recent solar cycle, there is a 100 percent chance that at
least two future station assembly missions will coincide with high
solar radiation levels and a 50 percent chance that five of the
flights will, the research council said.
</P>
<P>
   The first two modules of the new station were joined in orbit
last December by spacewalking astronauts. The station's first crew
module is to launch early next year, with the first resident crew
to follow in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
