<HEADER>
A4581 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-WORCESTER-SCENE-BOS &LR;      12-09 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORCESTER-SCENE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROSS-SECTION OF SOCIETY HONORS BRAVERY OF SIX FIREFIGHTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ The silence inside the Worcester Centrum
Thursday resonated loudly. Somber, riveting and reflective, the
church-like quiet from 15,000 people carried gratitude and awed
respect for six brave firefighters who died last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Grown men dabbed at their eyes, family members clung to one
another, and mourners from all ranks of society focused with
profound attention on the tributes delivered by speakers from
President Clinton to Worcester Fire Chief Dennis Budd.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is overwhelming, but it doesn't surprise me,'' said Brian
Borneman, a firefighter in Merrimack, N.H. ``Fighting a fire is the
closest thing to combat there is. You see people at their worst,
and you see people at their best.''
</P>
<P>
   The memorial was a rich, moving spectacle. Praise for public
service, tributes for the unhestitating courage of the dead
firefighters, and reminders that the unheralded often perform the
most remarkable deeds were combined in a service that acknowledged
a city's grief with a celebration of the best of human nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hero is an average citizen who does something extraordinary
to help someone in need,'' said Worcester Mayor Raymond V. Mariano.
``A hero is a firefighter.''
</P>
<P>
   The solemn pageantry inside the arena, where a sea of white
gloves snapped to attention in a show of expressive symmetry, was
also evident on the city's streets. For more than two hours,
firefighters from all across the country and several foreign
nations saluted their Worcester comrades as they marched in
dignified cadence past the Central Station.
</P>
<P>
   There, weary men who have scoured the rubble of the Worcester
Cold Storage and Warehouse Co. for nearly a week, stood atop fire
trucks parked outside the crepe-fringed bays of the station.
</P>
<P>
   Hats off, but still wearing soot-soiled clothing, the Worcester
firefighters gazed with grim but grateful expression as their
far-flung brotherhood passed by. The remains of four firefighters
still lie hidden in the charred remnants of the warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   After 13,000 firefighters filed into the Centrum, an equal
number filled the streets around the arena to follow the service
via remote broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   One of those was former Brockton fire chief Edward Burrell, an
85-year-old ex-firefighter haunted by long-ago memories even as he
honored the six men who died last week.
</P>
<P>
   More than most, Burrell understands the horrific loss that has
touched so many in this small-town city. He recalls the rain-soaked
memorial for nine Boston firefighters killed at the Hotel Vendome
in 1972, the trip to New York City to honor 12 firefighters who
perished in a blazing store in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   But the terrible night of March 10, 1941, even now, is never far
from his thoughts. For in the early morning of that frigid day,
Burrell lost 13 of his comrades from the Brockton Fire Department
as the snow-laden roof of the burning Strand Theatre collapsed upon
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you hear about lives lost, your mind reverts to what
we went through,'' Burrell said. ``It was devastating, especially
being young. Everything went through our minds, thinking of all the
families. Several of those who were killed were young fellas with
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Burrell walked the entire 1 1/2-mile processional route
Thursday. ``Hell, there's nothing to it,'' he said. ``You just put
one foot in front of the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Benoit of Paxton stood by that route to pay silent
respects to all the firefighters who marched Thursday, including
her husband, Michael, who battled the fatal fire last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are everyday heroes who are not recognized,'' Benoit
said. ``People might look to sports stars, but these are the real
heroes. You have firemen and policemen who risk their lives all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph O'Brien, a New York City firefighter stationed in Spanish
Harlem, agreed that tragedy is often a catalyst that renews respect
for his profession. O'Brien drove a car to Worcester for the
service, a sign of brotherhood with six men he never met.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien shrugged off any resentment about the ``respect'' issue.
``It's the same with any job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the public confidence that is routinely placed in
firefighters helps explain the humbled respect that filled the
Centrum. Dignitaries and public servants alike, high-ranking state
officials to rookie firefighters, showed by their rapt attention
and unmoving posture that these men _ Paul A. Brotherton, Timothy
P. Jackson, Jeremiah M. Lucey, James F. Lyons, Joseph T. McGuirk,
and Thomas E. Spencer _ lived worthy lives.
</P>
<P>
   The evocative strains of ``Amazing Grace'' _ first from a lone
bagpiper, then from an ensemble and chorus _ brought many in the
arena to tears. Wives and children of the slain firefighters
embraced, wept, and grieved for a loss they can never replace.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, Burrell reflected on how his life was spared in the
Strand Theatre blaze, only because the roof collapsed minutes
before his company had planned to attack the building.
</P>
<P>
   Only three men are still alive who battled that fire, he said,
but still they gather every March 10 to recall the sacrifices made
in what remains the single greatest loss of life in Massachusetts
firefighting history.
</P>
<P>
   Burrell, like his Worcester comrades, says he regrets nothing.
The rewards, he explains, are ``rescuing people and protecting
them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was our job,'' Burrell says, ``just like those fellas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
