<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4583 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-GENE-THERAPY-NYT &LR;      12-09 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GENE-THERAPY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS EXPERTS LISTEN, FAMILIES OFFER SUPPORT FOR GENE THERAPY TRIALS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Md., Pa., Calif., N.J.)   (jw) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHESDA, Md. _ Paul Gelsinger, his voice quivering but his
composure intact, stepped to the microphone in a crowded auditorium
here at the National Institutes of Health.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite three months ago, Gelsinger's 18-year-old son, Jesse,
became the first person killed by gene therapy. Thursday, Gelsinger
addressed the hundreds of scientists gathered here this week to
examine the experiment that cost Jesse his life.
</P>
<P>
   Gelsinger, a handyman from Tucson, Ariz., asked the members of
the audience to reach into their pockets and take quarters.
Throughout the hall, the rustling of purses and the jingling of
coins could be heard. He noted the language on the coin: ``In God
we trust. You don't see that too much in government anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   He then told how Jesse, a clerk in a supermarket, had taken
unpaid leave to participate in the experiment at the University of
Pennsylvania, even though it was not intended to benefit him but
rather babies with a fatal form of the rare metabolic disorder from
which he suffered.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these people who participated in this trial did a
wonderful thing,'' said Gelsinger, who has said that in dying, his
son taught him how to live. ``They came in with the same intent my
son had. It doesn't get any purer.''
</P>
<P>
   Gelsinger's speech, which was greeted with lengthy applause,
provided a moment of humanity on the second-day of a three-day
meeting of the Recombinant DNA Advisory Committee, the National
Institutes of Health panel that oversees gene therapy research.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to examining the experiment in which Jesse Gelsinger
died, the committee was considering the safety of adenovirus, the
weakened cold virus that was used as to deliver healthy DNA to the
patients in the Pennsylvania study, and was also debating rules
that would force scientists to make public more of their safety
data.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering has been marked by acrimony between scientists at
the University of Pennsylvania, whom Gelsinger has said he
supports, and officials of the Food and Drug Administration, who on
Wednesday held a news conference to accuse the scientists of
several lapses, including improperly admitting Jesse into the
study, altering the informed consent form given to patients and
failing to immediately report safety data that could have put a
stop to the clinical trial.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, however, the talk was toned down, as the Penn
investigators, led by James Wilson, director of the Institute for
Human Gene Therapy at the university, and FDA officials gave
lengthy presentations of their findings.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson and his colleagues pointedly apologized to the agency for
specific failings, and Wilson reiterated what he said on Wednesday
in response to the agency's charges: ``At no time during or prior
to this trial did we in any way expect to see what we saw in Jesse
Gelsinger.''
</P>
<P>
   FDA officials delivered only muted criticism Thursday, noting
the lapses by the researchers in bland, bureaucratic language while
they presented the preliminary results of their inquiry into the
death.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Siegel, the agency official who supervises gene therapy
reviews, noted that the experiment had been monitored closely; the
FDA, he said, reviewed 20 amendments to the original protocol, and
the two sides communicated either by telephone or fax 50 times
during the course of the two-year clinical trial.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, W. French Anderson, a gene therapy expert at the
University of Southern California who is regarded as the father of
the field, hinted that some kind of agreement had been reached.
``There was a realization that this had gone too far,'' Anderson
said, referring to the FDA. ``Yesterday they were blasting Penn.
Today they basically accepted Pennsylvania as dealing with them in
good faith.''
</P>
<P>
   There were a few interesting scientific facts to come out of
Thursday's meeting. The Penn scientists are still not certain why
Jesse Gelsinger, who suffered from ornithine transcarbamylase
deficiency, suffered an reaction to the adenovirus that was so
severe that it killed him.
</P>
<P>
   Autopsy findings discussed Thursday offered a possible
explanation: Jesse's bone marrow had abnormalities that might have
existed before the therapy, suggesting that, unbeknownst to the
researchers, he might have been infected with a second cold virus,
parvovirus.
</P>
<P>
   Were that the case, Anderson said, the parvovirus could have
triggered the reactions _ jaundice, a blood-clotting disorder,
kidney failure, lung failure and ultimately brain death _ that
Jesse experienced after receiving the adenovirus.
</P>
<P>
   With their ability to infect cells, viruses are useful in gene
therapy because doctors can use them to deliver healthy DNA to
patients. More than 300 gene therapy experiments have been
conducted since 1990, and the adenovirus has been used in more than
a quarter of them. But now, its usage may be limited. Researchers
said Thursday that it seemed clear that patients who received
adenovirus tolerated it well up to a certain point, but once the
dosage passed that threshold, the side effects became significant.
</P>
<P>
   In the Penn study, 19 patients with ornithine transcarbamylase
deficiency were divided into three groups, each receiving a higher
dose than the last. Investigators expected to see a gradual
escalation of side effects, Wilson said, so that the study could be
stopped before any patients were hurt.
</P>
<P>
   But more than science, Thursday was a day for patients,
including the mothers of children with the deficiency, a disorder
that, even when not fatal in infancy, often causes coma, brain
damage and death. As did Gelsinger, the mothers pleaded with the
committee to allow the research to continue, saying it was their
only hope for a cure.
</P>
<P>
   As Claudia Mickelson, the committee's chairwoman, fought back
tears, Mindy Rosen, of Cherry Hill, N.J., told the committee what
her 17-year-old son said Thursday morning as she kissed him goodbye
before leaving for the meeting: ``Mom, please tell them I want to
have gene therapy. I hate being sick.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
