<HEADER>
A4584 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-WORCESTER-COMMENT-BOS     12-09 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORCESTER-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE BROTHERHOOD, NO CHOICE BUT TO CARRY ON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ Long after the flow of official words ran dry
Thursday, long after the last strains of ``Taps'' melted into the
rafters, thousands of firefighters found themselves drawn to the
place they know best: the nearest firehouse.
</P>
<P>
   They ate homemade American chop suey off paper plates. They
drank Pepsi from the can. And some of the more curious drifted
upstairs and gazed across the vast, communal bedroom that
firefighters Paul Brotherton and Jeremiah Lucey used to call home.
</P>
<P>
   It's nt much to look at, really, with its scratched linoleum
floors, fded bege wallpaper, and long rows of twin metal beds. But
it explains something more.
</P>
<P>
   It explains this concept of brotherhood so frequently mentioned
in this city these last tortuous days. It explains the sea of tears
shed by brawny men. It explains why upwards of 30,000 firefighters
from across the country and around the world arrived to pay final
respects to six men they didn't know. ``It's like family,'' Jay
Olson, a lieutenant from Portland, Ore., was saying of the men in
his company. ``You prepare meals together. You eat at the same
table. You're sleeping in the same room.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know everything about everyone else's business,'' he
added. ``The gifts they're buying for Christmas, their marital
problems, their kids' grades at school. The outside world, they
don't understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 17 had their fathers taken away in last Friday's fire. A
city mourns. And an entire profession is once again brought to its
collective knee.
</P>
<P>
   The last heroes, firefighters are often called. They may well be
that and more. In a nation obsessed with every blip in interest
rates, at a time in our history when courage is seen as a $10
million-a-year outfielder playing with a sore shoulder.
firefighters provide a link to a more purposeful, more glorious
past.
</P>
<P>
   They are a different breed. They work in long shifts that often
extend through the night. They rush into burning buildings for
$50,000 a year. They pass their jobs from father to son. And
precious few of them ever leave to do anything else.
</P>
<P>
   So six of them die in Worcester, and countless thousands of
their brethren put themselves in their emmpty boots.
</P>
<P>
   Take Bill Fuller of Ashland, Mass., who sat inside the Worcester
Centrum Thursday to pay tribute to the fallen six. His grandfather
was a firefigther. His father was a firefighter. He retired as a
firefighter two years ago. And his son is a firefighter now.
</P>
<P>
   ``You leave your wife and kids every day and go spend your time
with your second family,'' he said. ``It's in the blood.''
</P>
<P>
   They are bitten early by the g. They see the gleaming firetruck
scream down their streets. They watch as tough men in rubbery
uniforms transcend fear. They are seduced by the phscal, aggressive
nature of the work.
</P>
<P>
   They develop, quite literally, a blind trust in each other's
abilities. They trundle into smokey buildings in pairs, unable to
see more than a foot ahead. They eat each other's cooking, watch
ballgames together on threadbare chairs. They share bathrooms,
lockers, and beds.
</P>
<P>
   Standing outside the Centrum, Lieutenant David McCourt recalled
falling through a weakened floor a few years back in a house fire
in his native Medford, Mass. He clung to a wooden beam above a
swirl of flames until another firefighter came by and pulled him
up.
</P>
<P>
   That other firefighter was his father. ``He told me not to ever
let that happen again,'' McCourt said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the stationhouse, they form bonds that even the hottest
flames can't burn away. They talk, they joke, they pull pranks. The
universal rule of firefighters: Never, ever, let your brethren know
what bothers you, or you'll live with it for the rest of your
career.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighter Henry Cullen of North Providence, R.I. recalls a
particularly fastidious lieutenant who demanded once too often that
the firehouse be cleaned. So his troops hid a vacuum cleaner under
his bed and strung a series of extension cords along the wall. When
they turned it on at 4 a.m., a whole group of men were there to
watch their fearless leader bolt from his bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It breaks the monotony,'' said Cullen. ``Sometimes 't
stop moving for 20 hours, but sometimes you don't move at all for
10.''
</P>
<P>
   Another North Providence firefiter bragged too much about the
gas mileage of his new car, so his colleagues began covertly adding
fuel to his tank while he was keeping track of his miles. A couple
of weeks later, they began siphoning gas out and listened
sympathetically as he expressed confusion about his falling
fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   How many beds have been moved to the roof? How many buckets of
water dumped on each other? How many foul casseroles hanged in
effigy from a kitchen pipe?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing this 21 years and I see new and amazing things
every day,'' said Mark Simmons, a battalion chief from Tempe, Ariz.
``You do everything you can to humiliate and annoy and haze
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the scene of a fire, there are no jokes. The often ragtag
collection of men _ and he rare woman _ suddenly become symphonic
in their actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a guy on the hydrant, you have an apparatus guy, you
have someone else on the hose,'' said Rick Woerth, another
firefighter from Tempe, Ariz. ``And the captain is the quarterback,
running the play.''
</P>
<P>
   It was like that last Friday evening at the Worcester Cold
Storage and Warehouse Co. Firefighters entered the burning building
in pairs, and they died in pairs. As six of them were missing in
treacheous flames and smoke, their brethren had to be restrained
from plunging in anew.
</P>
<P>
   It's different than it used to be. The equipment is better these
days, more sophisticated. But because of that, firemen tend to take
greater risks. Buildings are more laden with sythetic materials,
which tend to burn hotter and faster than wood.
</P>
<P>
   And death lurks every night on every call, in places where they
least suspect it. Places like vacant arehouses.
</P>
<P>
   So now, firefighter at two stations here will eventually have to
clean out the lockers of the dead _ Lucey and Brotherton, Thomas
Spencer, James Lyons, Timothy Jackson and Joseph McGuirk.
</P>
<P>
   They'll fold their sheets. They'll walk uneasily past their
favorite easy chairs in the station lounge. They'll mourn the
casseroles that won't be baked, the pranks that will never be
plotted, the half-cocked dreams left unrealized.
</P>
<P>
   And eventually, the survivors, this city, and the entire
profession will summon the strength to carry on. For firefighters
and their families, too often there is no choice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Brian McGrory is a Globe columnist. His e-mail address is
mcgrory(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
