<SLUG> BC-BUSH10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush scoffs at recent poll result
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOFFSTOWN, N.H. _ Gov. George W. Bush responded Thursday to a
poll showing him trailing Arizona Sen. John McCain in New
Hampshire, while McCain expressed support for a threatened lawsuit
against the New York State Republican Party seeking to get him on
that state's ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the most recent poll has him wondering if he'll lose
the Feb. 1 New Hampshire primary, Bush, campaigning in the state,
laughed and said: ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are polls,'' he said at a morning news conference.
``There was one that showed me plus 14. There was one that showed
me even, plus five, minus whatever you just said. People are making
up their minds. That's what this is all about. And I've got a lot
of work to do, and I'm looking forward to doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   An American Research Group poll released Wednesday found McCain
leading Bush for the first time here. McCain was ahead 37 percent
to Bush's 30 percent. That further solidified reports of McCain's
steady rise in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Bush responded to reporters' questions on the second of a
two-day spin through the state. On Wednesday, campaigning with
Netscape founder Jim Barksdale and Jesse Devitte, former state
chairman for Elizabeth Dole and chairman of the Software
Association of New Hampshire, Bush spoke to employees at a Nashua
software company, held a town meeting in Bedford and, later, had a
``high-tech town meeting'' at FIRST, a Manchester nonprofit
organization that works with children on science and technology.
</P>
<P>
   Bush concluded his visit in Goffstown, where he received the
endorsement of more than 80 law enforcement officers and took a
walk down the town's quaint main street before boarding his
campaign bus and heading home.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed to analyze McCain's rise, Bush attributed it to the
vagaries of presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the people of New Hampshire take a good, hard look at
who they want to see as their president, and that's what's taking
place,'' Bush said. ... That's what elections are all about. I look
forward to the contest. John McCain's a good man. I just think I'll
do a better job.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York on Thursday, McCain joined former Bush supporter and
State Island Borough President Guy Molinari, who announced he will
sue the New York State Republican Party in an effort to get McCain
on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Molinari, who earlier switched his support from Bush to McCain,
said the state GOP makes it too hard for candidates to win a place
on that state's ballot. GOP candidates must gather signatures in
all 31 congressional districts, among other rules that Molinari
called unconstitutional, because, he said, they place an ``undue
and overwhelming burden'' on presidential candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has campaigned aggressively in New Hampshire and is
familiar to voters here while Bush has faced criticism for skipping
a handful of GOP forums and not working hard enough to win support.
This week, Bush said over and over again that he enjoys the
hand-shaking, the ``retail politics,'' of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   That went only so far with people like Liz Vincent, who heard
Bush speak in Manchester Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, I tell you, the verdict's still out,'' she said. ``When
you listen to (Bush) talk, it's , `This is the way we do it in
Texas.' I tell you, I don't want New Hampshire to become Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
