<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4591 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-ASSESS-ART-2T     12-09 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ASSESS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: A GALVANIZING MOMENT IN THE MIDDLE EAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MIDEAST-ISRAEL-REACT, MIDEAST-ARABS-REACT) 
(ART ADV: Photo _ NYT5 _ is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In the Middle East, negotiations come and
negotiations go and everyone has learned to be guarded, even jaded,
about the possibilities for agreements, much less real peace.
</P>
<P>
   But a feeling that change was imminent swept through Israel on
Thursday following President Clinton's surprise announcement that
Israeli-Syrian talks would be resumed next week after nearly four
years. Almost palpably, the national pulse seemed to quicken _ for
some with elation, for others with anxiety. Even the Israeli
right-wing, so quiet these last few months, girded up for its first
real combat.
</P>
<P>
   Why did everyone get ahead of themselves? Supporters and
opponents alike talked as if the resumption of negotiations, which
are bound to be difficult and crisis-ridden, was tantamount to an
agreement. Many were already asking whether voters would approve
the accord in a referendum and whether Syria would get American
financing to modernize its old Soviet-equipped army.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was because there is a deep-seated sense that the
stars are aligned for a deal to be realized. All three leaders _
President Clinton, President Hafez el-Assad of Syria and Prime
Minister Ehud Barak of Israel _ are hungry for a success,
determined to prove that they can resolve this 32-year-old conflict
once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we have this time is not artificial deadlines,
but real ones,'' said Stephen P. Cohen, the senior policy adviser
of the Center for Middle East Peace in New York. ``There is the
deadline of biology and the deadline of the decline of political
power, or its potential, for the three principals.''
</P>
<P>
   For Assad, this year in which two important Arab leaders of his
generation have died _ King Hussein of Jordan and King Hassan of
Morocco _ has been a reminder of the physical limits of power. The
69-year-old Syrian is believed to be in ill health, plagued by
chronic and debilitating disorders including diabetes and, it is
thought, some form of cancer. To retrieve the Golan Heights, the
strategic plateau he lost to Israel in the 1967 war, would close a
circle and provide neat borders to his rule.
</P>
<P>
   Also, experts on Syria believe that Assad wants to ensure that
the reins of power will be smoothly handed to his son Bashar, 34,
and that to accomplish this he needs to consolidate his own
position. By taking on peace with Israel, the major issue facing
Syria, Assad seeks to prove that he is willing to finish something
that he started eight years ago at a conference in Madrid. To walk
away from the table this time, without the Golan Heights, would be
seen as a defeat and would undercut his authority at a critical
time. Like the Israelis, after so much talk, the Syrians are
impatient to see results.
</P>
<P>
   And from a Syrian point of view, Barak is an attractive
negotiating partner; he grounds his concept of peace in a view of
Israeli national security and does not stress economic
normalization, an idea that reportedly frightens Assad. That the
Syrians are willing to send their foreign minister, Farouk Shara,
to meet directly with Barak increases both the public risk they are
taking and the prospects of success.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was lacking until now was the political will on both
sides to come to closure,'' said Itamar Rabinovich, president of
Tel Aviv University, who previously headed Israel's negotiations
with Syria. ``A lot of the basic work has already been done. There
is a legacy to the negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the Syrians and the Israelis realize that they can only be
guaranteed of Washington's focused support in the immediate future,
before the American presidential campaign moves into full drive. In
Washington, Clinton clearly wants to secure a major accomplishment
in a region where he has invested so much energy, and time is
running out.
</P>
<P>
   Barak feels time to be of the essence, too. He is a great
believer in momentum, which is why he set a peace deadline for
himself shortly after taking office in July. In 15 months, he said,
more or less, he would achieve peace with the Palestinians, peace
with the Syrians and withdraw Israeli troops from southern Lebanon.
His targets set the agenda for the region, pressuring the other
leaders to move quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But Barak also faced political fall-out at home, too, when his
peacemaking did not take off as quickly as he originally planned.
He was encountering his first real disenchantment at home as
anxieties rose that he would not be able to live up to his
diplomatic ambitions. But with the announcement that talks would
resume, his political profile changed almost overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until last night, Ehud Barak was a prime minister under
siege,'' wrote Yossi Verter in Thursday's Haaretz newspaper. ``But
last night was a long time ago, before Hafez Assad enlisted to help
him. The sudden breakthrough in negotiations with Syria restored
the color to Barak's wan cheeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Next week, the first handshake between high-level Israeli and
Syrian officials is bound to produce a ripple throughout the Middle
East, a sense that the defining tensions are starting to shift.
Barak declared on Thursday that everything can be sewn up quickly,
within a few months. His certainty set the tone, and encouraged
Israelis to leap far forward in their thinking. With remarkable
precision, Channel Two television on Thursday night predicted a 58
to 41 Parliament approval of the eventual agreement.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the detailed negotiations that follow are bound to be
tortuous. They will take place in the region, possibly in Amman,
Jordan's capital.
</P>
<P>
   In concept, the Israelis and the Syrians would seem to be close
at the outset. Like other leaders before him, Barak is prepared to
concede the Golan Heights in exchange for security guarantees and
greater normalization of relations. But the border lines are key.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis will propose withdrawing to borders agreed to
internationally in 1923. The Syrians have insisted on the borders
of June 4, 1967, before the Golan Heights were occupied by Israel,
which would give Syria access to the Sea of Galilee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is a few miles, and for Americans, with their
expansive continent, it seems pathetic,'' Rabinovich said. ``But
this is the proverbial olive tree. For the Syrians, to be or not to
be on the water's edge is critical.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis are likely to urge the Syrian leaders to engage in
a kind of public diplomacy they may not be prepared to undertake.
That would mean sending clear messages to their people that Israel
is no longer the enemy, and making sure that Israel's northern
border is free of violence as Israeli troops began to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli-Egyptian peace deal, born at Camp David 20 years ago
with a framework agreement between former Prime Minister Menachem
Begin and the late President Anwar Sadat, will shadow the talks.
The Syrians will push to extend beyond the international borders
just as the Egyptians pushed for getting Taba in addition to the
Sinai. If the Israelis insist on maintaining a presence in an early
warning station on Mount Hermon, the Syrians are likely to point
out that they completely exited the Sinai.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assad cannot do a worse deal than Sadat,'' said Dore Gold,
Israel's former ambassador to the United Nations. ``He has to try
to do a better deal.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise his people will say, ``Why did you wait 20 years?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
