<HEADER>
A4593 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-TEACHERS-CHEATING-     12-09 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TEACHERS-CHEATING-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION QUESTIONS INVESTIGATOR'S FINDING ON TEACHER CHEATING
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York City teachers' union Thursday called an
investigator's finding that dozens of teachers had helped students
cheat on standardized tests exaggerated and unfair, and officials
at the Board of Education suggested that the report was aimed at
undercutting Chancellor Rudy Crew while his future is being
decided.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the United Federation of Teachers said the report
unfairly implied that cheating was rampant in the city's 1,100
schools, and they asserted that some of the 43 teachers charged
with cheating appeared to have been wrongly accused. At a news
conference, Randi Weingarten, the union's president, announced that
the union had hired its own investigators to study the report's
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Board of Education officials stoked the debate by questioning
why Edward F. Stancik, the special investigator for New York City
schools, released the scathing report in the weeks before Crew and
the Board of Education must decide on whether to extend his
contract. One official even called a reporter to point out that
Stancik had briefed Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's staff on the report,
before publicly releasing it, but had not informed Crew.
</P>
<P>
   Some allies of the chancellor theorized privately that Giuliani,
who stopped expressing confidence in Crew after the two men battled
over school vouchers last spring, had directed Stancik to release
the unflattering report now in hopes of convincing Crew to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Questions have been raised about the timing of this,'' said
Karen Crowe, a spokeswoman for Crew. ``The chancellor, though,
assumes there was no premeditated decision on when to release this
report.''
</P>
<P>
   Stancik and aides to Giuliani angrily insisted Thursday that
City Hall never interfered in Stancik's investigations of the
school system. Deputy Mayor Joseph Lhota confirmed that Stancik had
briefed mayoral aides on the report before publicly releasing it
but added that Stancik frequently did so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mind-boggling that anyone would say this report was timed
to hurt Rudy Crew,'' Lhota said. ``Nothing could be further from
the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   In a morning news conference, Ms. Weingarten said she had hired
the corporate investigations company of Thacher Associates to look
into the cheating allegations and recommend strategies to prevent
cheating in the future. Ms. Weingarten said that while some cases
described appeared to be ``clear instances of conspiracy and
fraud,'' others were questionable.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Ms. Weingarten said, she had doubts about the
charges that students were given practice tests with actual answers
from the impending tests on them. Students frequently take practice
tests modeled after the official exams, she said. She said she was
also concerned about a number of charges based solely on interviews
with young students, including some cases in which teachers
interviewed by the investigators had disputed the children's
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children's allegations make up the body of the report, and
the denials are buried in the footnotes,'' Ms. Weingarten
complained. ``I don't want to trample on children, but there is a
sweeping indictment here of the entire system that we don't think
is borne out by the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that some teachers had been calling the union
headquarters ``in tears'' to say they would ``never, never, never
in a million years resort to the practices described here.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, though, Ms. Weingarten stressed that she
abhorred cheating and said that if the charges proved correct, she
would consider them ``appalling'' and press for the culprits to be
punished. As the school system puts more emphasis on standardized
tests, she said, the Board of Education should develop strategies
and clear-cut protocols for administering the increasingly
high-stakes exams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to not only get to the bottom of this,'' she said,
``but to create some solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Stancik said that the union had every right to
investigate the charges. But he added that he suspected that the
investigation would be biased on behalf of the accused teachers.
``Randi has made it very clear to me that she thinks highly of many
of the people named in the report, without having investigated it
at all,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Toby Thacher, who will lead the union's investigation, is the
former inspector general of the New York City School Construction
Authority. He left that job in 1996, after developing an
anti-corruption program that was praised by legal experts as a
national model. Thacher would not discuss how he planned to
investigate the report Thursday, but he said that he would present
any findings to the union. The union could then forward the
findings to the Board of Education, which must decide whether to
bring disciplinary charges against the accused teachers.
</P>
<P>
   William Thompson Jr., the board president, said Thursday that he
took the charges seriously but that he believed that ``the vast
majority of our teachers and supervisors do not engage in
cheating.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani vigorously defended the report at his daily news
conference, going so far as to call Stancik ``one of the most
effective investigators ever in the history of the city.'' In
discussing the findings, he did not offer any support for Crew.
Instead, Giuliani said that the school system ``doesn't work'' and
that he should be in charge of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Board of Education system doesn't work to serve children
well,'' Giuliani said. ``So you have to change the system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
