<SLUG> BC-EMAIL-AVOID10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    10 steps to e-mail sobriety
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ E-mail addicts: The first step is admitting you
have a problem. After that, follow this 10-step program. It
probably won't break you from e-mail, but it will give you a little
breathing room to last well into the next millennium:
</P>
<P>
   1.Try getting away from e-mail just one day a week. Sunday is a
good time to start.
</P>
<P>
   2.Go on a vacation and don't take your laptop or Palm Pilot with
you. Let your e-mail program respond with an automated message
while you're gone.
</P>
<P>
   3.Spring clean your e-mail: Trash all those outdated folders,
respond to any lingering threads and feel good about your tidier
``inbox.''
</P>
<P>
   4.Unless your job depends on it, don't leave your e-mail open
all day. Check it once every hour or two, then close it and get
back to your work or play.
</P>
<P>
   5.Take a weekend drive or a hike and get as far away from your
mailbox as possible.
</P>
<P>
   6.Forgive all those who have sent you spam and hokey e-mail in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   7.Resolve to send no spam or hokey
</P>
<P>
   e-mail if you can help it.
</P>
<P>
   8.Stop giving your e-mail address to people you never want to
hear from.
</P>
<P>
   9.When in doubt, face-to-face communication is best.
</P>
<P>
   10.Accept the higher power of your e-mail administrator.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
