u l BC-EMAIL10-COX     12-09 2186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMAIL10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Type E personalities: E-mail addicition
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Subject: e-mail addiction story
</P>
<P>
   Date: Mon., 29 Nov 1999 15:54:02
</P>
<P>
   From: Omar L. Gallaga, Technopolis Writer
 &QL; ogallaga(at)statesman.com &QR;
</P>
<P>
   To: Gretchen Heber, Technopolis Editor  &QL; gheber(at)statesman.com &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen,
</P>
<P>
   Finishing up the story on e-mail addiction. What I'm finding out
from the people who've responded is that a lot of people use e-mail
so much that they aren't able to differentiate their work life from
their home life. I'm forwarding some of the messages so you can see
them _ one person, a systems administrator, says he checks his
e-mail and responds nearly 24 hours a day depending on his work
schedule. I also received some information from an Austin company
that specializes in Web-based
</P>
<P>
   e-mail. They had some interesting things to say and some
research to back it up.
</P>
<P>
   I got your messages about WeeWeb and Link. I'll fix those as
soon as I get a chance to look at them.
</P>
<P>
   Does it seem weird to you that we're
</P>
<P>
   e-mailing back and forth like this when you sit less than 10
feet away?
</P>
<P>
   It's probably just me.
</P>
<P>
   I'll e-mail you as soon as the story's done.
</P>
<P>
   omar
</P>
<P>
   Subject: e-mail addiction story
</P>
<P>
   Date: Mon, 29 Nov 1999 15:59:12
</P>
<P>
   From: Omar L. Gallaga  &QL; ogallaga(at)statesman.com &QR;
</P>
<P>
   To: Gretchen Heber, Technopolis Editor  &QL; gheber(at)statesman.com &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Gretchen,
</P>
<P>
   This is the e-mail that got me interested in the story. It's
from a friend who I've known for about two years. I don't really
talk to her much anymore on the phone, but she'll e-mail me every
now and then:
</P>
<P>
   Subject: FWD: RE: Help on a Technopolis Story
</P>
<P>
   Date: Wed, 03 Nov 1999 17:32:15
</P>
<P>
   From: eileen(at)ideality.com
</P>
<P>
   I can relate. My clients no longer call me to tell me something
important _ they e-mail me. If I don't check my e-mail at least
three to four times every HOUR, I miss something. And it's usually
very urgent and very important. Honestly, the rhythm of our day has
drastically changed.
</P>
<P>
   I feel like I'm in a William Gibson novel gone Similacra. When I
unplug at 6 or 7 p.m., I still sneak looks at the e-mail to make
sure they don't need something. One night I was e-mailing until 1
a.m. Were they at work? No. Was I? No. But we were still working.
Thank you 24/7. Now where's my life?
</P>
<P>
   Subject: Story opening
</P>
<P>
   Date: Mon, 29 Nov 1999 16:30:46
</P>
<P>
   From: Omar L. Gallaga  &QL; ogallaga(at)statesman.com &QR;
</P>
<P>
   To: Gretchen Heber, Technopolis Editor  &QL; gheber(at)statesman.com &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Here's how I think I'll open the story:
</P>
<P>
   About three words into a sentence, a real work-related sentence,
and a little flashing icon on the upper right hand side of the
screen begins to blink. It will blink forever if you let it,
looking for attention greedily from now until the y10k bug brings
it down. It doesn't speak (this isn't AOL), but it means the same
thing. ``You've got mail.'' Stop what you're doing. Look at me.
Read me, respond to me, wait for me to return.
</P>
<P>
   The Web, with its sparkly new ways of selling you things, is not
the biggest entanglement in this happy high-tech life. It is the
591 billion e-mail messages folks in the U.S. will send this year
alone.
</P>
<P>
   But lest you think our growing obsession with e-mail has to do
with volume, the real change is not only how much we're using
e-mail, but how we're using it. Genevieve Van Cleve, who works for
HushMail, an Austin company that provides encrypted e-mail service
on the Web, said she uses e-mail to avoid the nagging call of a
ringing phone. ``To screen calls openly is kind of rude; to choose
to answer or not answer e-mail provides a bit more privacy to the
user and recipient,'' Van Cleve said. ``I don't quite know if I'm
convinced myself, but I like typing instead of getting stuck
talking.''
</P>
<P>
   And Steven Phenix, who works for WorldNet Box Office Inc.,
confides _ via e-mail _ that his girlfriend won't let him have
e-mail at home because she knows he will check it constantly. ``I
only live seven blocks from work. So on weekends, I sneak up to the
office before she wakes up. In the evenings, if I run to the store
for milk, I can't resist dropping by the office to log on.''
</P>
<P>
   For Cleve and Phenix, e-mail may be essential for their jobs in
marketing and public relations.
</P>
<P>
   But their lives, full of unanswered e-mails, online address
books and subject headers where once there were stamps and licked
envelopes, are becoming more typical.
</P>
<P>
   There are 95 million e-mail users in the U.S., according to
Cambridge, Mass.-based Forrester Research Inc. About 97 percent of
people who go online use it.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond those numbers is a culture where computers have
successfully infiltrated the home and new e-mail enabled appliances
_ everything from smart cell phones to e-mail-friendly toys like
the Sega Dreamcast to the past and future incarnations of the Palm
Pilot organizer _ will be able to say ``you've got mail,'' (not out
loud _ this still isn't AOL) whether you're in front of the TV, in
the car or (Bill Gates save us) using the restroom.
</P>
<P>
   The result is people who run and run and run like the Energizer
Bunny with no ``OFF'' switch. Like the highly touted new high-speed
Internet services, we are always ``ON,'' checking e-mail again and
again, whether it's the crucial information for a business proposal
or an e-mail with an attachment of your best friend's ultrasound
pictures.
</P>
<P>
   We live and GET MAIL and GET MAIL again until we sleep.
</P>
<P>
   And then: ``On several occasions I have had dreams in e-mail,''
Phenix said. ``While I'm sleeping, a little icon pops into my head
that chimes, 'You have dreams!' I click on the icon and the dream
begins.''
</P>
<P>
   Subject: E-mail addicts
</P>
<P>
   Date: Tue, 30 Nov 1999, 12:21:57
</P>
<P>
   From: Omar L. Gallaga  &QL; ogallaga(at)statesman.com &QR;
</P>
<P>
   To: austin.internet (an Internet
</P>
<P>
   discussion forum)
</P>
<P>
   Hi _ I'm working on a feature story and looking for folks who
would characterize themselves as addicted to e-mail. That means
people who, for whatever reason, can't do without it and find
themselves checking their mail compulsively.
</P>
<P>
   If you are that person or know somebody, please drop me a line
(via e-mail of course).
</P>
<P>
   Responses:
</P>
<P>
   Ron Yokubaitis of Texas.Net: ``I keep my mail client open 24
hours a day. I am such an addict, I have had a dedicated Internet
connection to my home. I get up from my bed when I hear the 'beep'
of e-mail being delivered.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Landt, who works for IBM, but who makes it clear his
views are his and not the company's: ``My last job did everything
by e-mail even though there were only 15 employees and all were
within 20 yards of each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Lou Marco, a system administrator at Jump.Net, who says he gets
at least 500 e-mails a day: ``Except for the four hours of actual
sleep I get each night, I check e-mail constantly at work (always
an open window) and every 5-10 minutes at home (on a dedicated
connection). ``
</P>
<P>
   Ron Tosch, a manufacturing supervisor at Solectron Texas who
says he spends at least two hours a day on e-mail: ``I check it 20
times a day. It's probably more, but I'd deny it. I get 50-120
personal messages and about 60 work-related messages a day. It's
vital to work and seemingly vital to my personal life.''
</P>
<P>
   Subject: psychiatry
</P>
<P>
   Date: Tue, 30 Nov 1999, 12:21:57
</P>
<P>
   From: Omar L. Gallaga  &QL; ogallaga(at)statesman.com &QR;
</P>
<P>
   To: Gretchen Heber, Technopolis Editor
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen,
</P>
<P>
   I called a psychiatrist, a woman named Jan Parker who has a
doctorate and teaches at National University's La Jolla, Calif.,
campus. It was a little strange speaking to her on the phone. I've
gotten very used to asking questions over e-mail. It was an
adjustment speaking to a live voice.
</P>
<P>
   She said that there hasn't been much published research on
e-mail addiction. But she said there is anecdotal evidence that
overuse of the Internet can strain relationships and, of course,
take time away from other activities.
</P>
<P>
   One interesting thing she said _ e-mail is one of those perfect
things that can feed into obsessive compulsive behavior pretty
easily.
</P>
<P>
   For people who already have those personality traits, ``This is
a really convenient one for them to get that way about.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker said another group of people (and who among us falls into
this one?) have an unmet need for contact. I imagine there's a
whole population of tech workers who use e-mail to combat
isolation.
</P>
<P>
   She said, ``They're the kind of people that wear out their
friends and call people all the time if they have a problem. Now
they can do it this way and it's not as obvious. They're less
likely to get rejected.''
</P>
<P>
   I wondered aloud to her what might happen if people who rely on
e-mail for that fulfillment don't get what they need. ``The
function of e-mail is so the person feels connected,'' she
answered. ``Anything that threatens that sense of being connected
is going to produce anxiety.''
</P>
<P>
   Write back as soon as you get this. I need to know what you
think.
</P>
<P>
   Omar
</P>
<P>
   Subject: Can't sleep
</P>
<P>
   Date: Wed, 01 Dec 1999, 03:04:11
</P>
<P>
   From: Omar L. Gallaga  &QL; ogallaga(at)statesman.com &QR;
</P>
<P>
   To: Barbara  &QL; babsbun(at)okdaily.net &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Hey. It's 3 a.m. and I can't sleep.
</P>
<P>
   And I know that you're asleep now and this won't get to you
until tomorrow, but it felt important to say that I miss you and
that I'm sorry we haven't talked in so long. I woke up and I
realized I couldn't remember what your voice sounded like, even
though you're one of the most important people in my life. That
scared me and I panicked.
</P>
<P>
   And now I'm writing.
</P>
<P>
   It's been so long. All we do is e-mail, and even though I'm
connected to the people in my life, it really doesn't feel like it.
</P>
<P>
   It feels, instead, like a substitute, and a cheap and easy one
at that.
</P>
<P>
   It's like comparing an IV drip to a meal. Like measuring the sky
against a Kinko's copy of a photo of the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Why do I feel so disconnected? And if the real thing is so much
better, why do I keep clicking on ``Get Mail,'' hoping against hope
that something wonderful will arrive?
</P>
<P>
   Good night,
</P>
<P>
   Omar
</P>
<P>
   Subject: Technopolis story
</P>
<P>
   Date: Fri, 05 Nov 1999, 10:29:42
</P>
<P>
   From: Jerry Amundson (technology consultant)  &QL; jerrya(at)onr.com &QR;
</P>
<P>
   To: Omar L. Gallaga  &QL; ogallaga(at)statesman.com &QR;
</P>
<P>
   ... there is also the issue of timing. What does it mean to
respond within two hours vs. the next day? As far as I am concerned
it means nothing, but to you, my timing may be pregnant with
meaning. The questions go on ... what does Jerry mean by those
asterisks around words? Maybe he doesn't know how to emphasize
words any other way.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe compulsion in e-mail is a reflection of a person's general
approach to life _ are we experiencing anxiety in general? Do we
worry too much about what other think about us if we don't respond
quickly (or at all)?
</P>
<P>
   I had the compulsion, but went over the top. I got overwhelmed
by too many e-mails and take them less seriously. I've been using
my famous disclaimers for a year now (see attached).
</P>
<P>
   I could go on, but I must see if anyone sent me e-mail while I
wrote this. . .
</P>
<P>
   Attached Disclaimer _ Since e-mail has a limited ability to
express the full meaning of a message, please take this message at
face value. If you have any doubts or questions or strong emotional
reactions to this message, please call by telephone immediately.
Response _ Please do not interpret a slow response as anything
other than a slow response. If you desire a quick response to an
e-mail message, I would appreciate a telephone call.
</P>
<P>
   Subject: Technopolis story ending
</P>
<P>
   Date: Thu, 02 Dec 1999, 10:12:21
</P>
<P>
   From: Omar L. Gallaga  &QL; ogallaga(at)statesman.com &QR;
</P>
<P>
   To: Gretchen Heber, Technopolis Editor
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen,
</P>
<P>
   The story is just about done. It's hard to draw conclusions
about e-mail addiction because really, where do we draw the line
between addiction, compulsion and enthusiastic use?
</P>
<P>
   Everyone I talked to who uses the Internet said that e-mail is
important, and vital to them at least in their work. And many of
them bemoan the fact that they get so many e-mails, including
useless spam. But most of them agree that with a little patience,
you can control how much you let it take over your life.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't want to check your e-mail every two minutes, then
don't. If you can't respond to all of your messages at once, put
them aside and devote a half hour later in the day to
correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   If you rely on e-mail for your happiness, you probably need to
reexamine your priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, I counted how many times I checked my e-mail, from
the time I woke up to bedtime. I checked about 47 times.
</P>
<P>
   I think I may follow some of the helpful, solicited advice.
</P>
<P>
   I think we all could do that.
</P>
<P>
   Read the story when you have time and respond anytime, when you
have the chance.
</P>
<P>
   No rush.
</P>
<P>
   Omar
</P>
