A4600 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      12-09 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND: PREMIER ENTERS BUGGING CASE
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bertie Ahern, calling the bugging of a car used
by Gerry Adams a serious matter, said he would raise the issue with
Prime Minister Tony Blair at a meeting in Finland. Adams, leader of
the Sinn Fein political wing of the IRA, questioned whether recent
peace talks would have succeeded if the device had been found while
the talks were going on. Adams says British agents planted the bug.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: MASS PORNOGRAPHY RAIDS
</P>
<P>
   In a huge effort to thwart the increasing use of the Internet to
traffic in child pornography, police officers in 20 areas of
England, Wales and Scotland made early-morning raids on 27
locations to confiscate computer equipment. The police said the
raids followed a six-month investigation.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: NEW INQUIRY ON EX-AIDE
</P>
<P>
   Former Finance Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn, who resigned
last month because he was under investigation in a corruption
scandal, is facing a second investigation. The scandal involved
allegations that he received as much as $100,000 in legal fees for
fictitious jobs. Now investigators will look into charges that
documents he provided seeking to prove he had done some work were
forgeries.
</P>
<P>
   SWITZERLAND: QUESTIONS ON BANK
</P>
<P>
   A prosecutor is investigating whether the Union Bank of
Switzerland continued to shred Holocaust-era documents after a 1997
law banned such destruction. The law was passed after a guard
rescued records and turned them over to Jewish groups. A report on
Swiss wartime banking activities said auditors found the bank had
destroyed documents three more times after 1997. A bank spokesman
expressed regret but said the bank felt the documents fell outside
the law in question.
</P>
<P>
   LATVIA: LANGUAGE LAW PASSES
</P>
<P>
   To the dismay of a large Russian-speaking minority, Parliament
voted to require that most public communications by the government
and businesses be published in Latvian. The law is aimed at curbing
the influence of hundreds of thousands of Russians settled in
Latvia by Soviet rulers; 48 percent of the population is Russian,
and tensions with Latvians have long run high.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA: COALITION FORMING
</P>
<P>
   More than two months after the right-wing Freedom Party came
second in elections, the ruling Social Democratic Party began to
form a coalition without the Freedom Party. The process has been
bogged down because the center-right Austrian People's Party
refused to take part after it came in third, and neither group
wanted to be aligned with the Freedom Party. The breakthrough came
when the People's Party said it was ready to start talks.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: BANKER FLEES
</P>
<P>
   A banker facing prosecution in a notorious fraud case, Angel
Isidoro Rodriguez Saez, disappeared after bodyguards blocked the
police from arresting him, the attorney general's office said.
Rodriguez, the former chairman of Banpais, SA, also escaped from
the police in 1995. He fled to Spain, but was extradited to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: 11 DIE IN JAIL SHOOTOUT
</P>
<P>
   A shootout between rival gangs in Bogota's main jail has left 11
prisoners dead, several visitors wounded and an estimated 200 still
in hiding. The overcrowded jail, whose 4,500 inmates include
left-wing guerrillas and drug traffickers, had been opened for
visits by prisoners' relatives when the gunfire erupted.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: PARTY EXPELS A LEADER
</P>
<P>
   The Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata party expelled Kalyan
Singh, a leader of the middling peasant castes in Uttar Pradesh,
after he criticized Prime Minsiter Atal Behari Vajpayee for
abandoning the party's commitment to seeing that a Hindu temple was
built on the site of a destroyed mosque. The party had removed
Singh as chief minister of the state after the party's dismal
showing in parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: TAJ BY MOONLIGHT
</P>
<P>
   The Taj Mahal, the white marble monument raised by the
17th-century Mogul emperor Shah Jehan, will be opened for moonlight
viewings beginning Dec. 22 for the first time in 15 years. Tourists
will be allowed to gaze at the Taj until midnight for five moonlit
nights a month, according to the tourism minister in Uttar Pradesh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
