<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4602 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-PORK-PANTS10-COX     12-09 0265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORK-PANTS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Police arrest suspected pilferer of pork chops
 &HT;    By John Lynch
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ A Pittsburg, Texas, man faces a felony theft
charge after he was accused of trying to smuggle 48 pork chops out
of a Longview supermarket, stashing them in his pants, according to
police reports.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fitzgerald Cooper, 33, was nabbed after suspicious
employees at a Super 1 Foods saw him putting packages of meat into
his pants shortly after midnight Friday, according to arrest
reports. He was in the Gregg County Jail on Thursday on $2,500
bond.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper spent some time in the store, the report said, wandering
around and picking up items, eventually paying for a bottle of
orange juice. When the store manager stopped him as he attempted to
leave, Cooper handed over three packages, containing 48 pork chops
and valued at $40, the report said. He then attempted to flee, but
was restrained by employees, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, Cooper, who listed his employer as Pilgrims Pride
Corp. of Pittsburg, would have faced a Class C misdemeanor charge
for theft less than $50, but the charge was enhanced to a state
jail felony theft because of a previous conviction, the report
said. Cooper had an outstanding warrant for evading arrest in Camp
County, but the details of that incident weren't available.
</P>
<P>
   A state jail felony is punishable by 180 days to two years in a
state jail; a Class C misdemeanor carries a fine of less than $500.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
