<HEADER>
A4603 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-ARABS-REACT-N     12-09 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ARABS-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDERCURRENT OF EXCITEMENT IS SEEN THROUGH USUAL CAUTIOUS REACTION
TO TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: See also MIDEAST-ASSESS and MIDEAST-ISRAEL)  
(DW) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUWAIT CITY, Kuwait _ The Syrian government and its Arab allies
spoke with customary caution Thursday even as they welcomed the
planned resumption of peace talks between Syria and Israel. But
across the Arab world, there were also rare hints of haste to learn
whether the breakthrough might really bear real fruit.
</P>
<P>
   In Lebanon the powerful speaker of parliament, Nabih Berri,
reflected that enthusiasm by saying his government, too, was ready
to seize the opportunity for peace. Berri said Lebanese officials
would join their Syrian counterparts in discussions this month, as
soon as the talks with Israel move from an opening session next
week in Washington to further meetings in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon and Syria are the last of Israel's neighbors to remain
technically at war with Israel, and the prospect of three-way
negotiations could offer an opportunity for the final settlement
along their disputed borders, an accord that has eluded them for
half a century.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, which made its peace with Israel in 1994, described the
planned Syrian-Israeli talks as ``a step in the right direction''
and said it hoped Lebanese-Israeli talks would also begin soon.
</P>
<P>
   In Egypt, which has been at peace with Israel since the Camp
David accords of 1979, President Hosni Mubarak was described by a
top deputy as being ``very happy with the progress that has been
achieved.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, there were deep rumblings of concern
that a new international preoccupation with Syrian-Israeli issues
might allow Israel to relegate talks with the Palestinians to the
back burner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The momentum must remain on the Palestinian-Israeli track,''
said Ayman Majali, a deputy prime minister of Jordan. Majali said
it was vital that the so-called final-status issues not be
neglected: future Israeli-Palestinian borders, the status of
Jerusalem and the fate of Palestinian refugees. Arab governments
see these as being at once the most intractable and the most
important of the disputes that divide Arabs and Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   The location of any long-term Syrian-Israeli talks has not been
disclosed, but one candidate is Jordan, whose young monarch, King
Abdullah, served as a key intermediary earlier this year in passing
messages between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   In Syria Thursday morning, just hours after President Clinton
announced in Washington that Syria and Israel had agreed to renew
talks, government-controlled newspapers announced the news with
front-page headlines and prominent portraits of Clinton and
President Hafez al-Assad.
</P>
<P>
   Citing an official statement issued late Wednesday in Damascus,
the newspapers reported that Assad and Clinton, in a telephone
conversation, had ``expressed their determination to exert all
possible efforts to achieve a comprehensive and just peace in the
region.''
</P>
<P>
   But newspaper commentaries, which reflect government opinion,
also cautioned Syrians against expecting too much from Israel,
which still occupies then Golan Heights, captured in battle in the
1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intentions alone, regardless of how good they appear, do not a
peace make,'' the official newspaper Tishrin said in an editorial
that urged Israel and Prime Minister Ehud Barak to back up words
with action.
</P>
<P>
   Under the formula used by Clinton, Israel and Syria have agreed
only to resume negotiations ``from the point where they left off''
nearly four years ago. That careful phrasing is intended to
sidestep a dispute about whether Israel ever agreed, as Syria
claims, to a formula under which Israel would withdraw fully from
the Golan to the borders that existed before the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   But the editorial in Tishrin suggested that Syria was still
unwilling to negotiate that point. Saying Syria ``will not give up
one iota of soil from the Golan,'' the newspaper declared, ``The
occupation must cease in all of the Golan.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, reports from the region made clear that Syrian officials
were moving into high gear in preparation for next week's talks, at
which Foreign Minister Farouk al-Shara will meet with Barak in the
highest-level meeting yet between Syrian and Israeli delegations.
</P>
<P>
   Assad telephoned President Emile Lahud of Lebanon, while Shara
spoke with the Lebanese prime minister, Salim Hoss, apparently in
an attempt to coordinate positions. Syria, which maintains about
15,000 troops in Lebanon, is the dominant power there, and each
nation has said that neither will make peace with Israel alone.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon was not invited to the talks in Washington, but U.S.
officials have made plain their hope that Lebanese officials would
join later discussions. Thursday David Satterfield, the U.S.
ambassador to Lebanon, met with Lahud, Hoss and Berri to brief them
about next week's talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
