603-1036.)
</HEADLINE>
  
 McCAIN AND BRADLEY PLAN JOINT APPEARANCE   
(ART ADV: Photo NYT11 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)(lh) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ John McCain and Bill Bradley, both insurgent
candidates for president, have agreed to step across party lines
and stage an unusual joint appearance in New Hampshire to highlight
their support for overhauling the nation's campaign finance system,
aides to both candidates said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   While the Republican and the Democrat threatening their parties'
front-runners, disagree about how the current system should be
changed, both have put the fight against special interest money at
the center of their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Each has taken a strong stand against the unlimited, unregulated
donations to political parties known as soft money that were at the
center of the campaign finance abuses in the 1996 presidential
race.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said they expect the two to make a joint pledge next week
that if they became their party's nominees, they would call on
their parties not to accept soft money.
</P>
<P>
   While still working on logistics and details, the two sides were
planning the appearance for next Thursday and were examining
whether it could take place in Claremont, N.H., where President
Clinton and then Speaker Newt Gingrich held a wide-ranging,
conciliatory debate at a senior citizens center in 1995, a few
months after the Republicans took control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Gingrich shook hands on a pledge to create a
commission to study an overhaul of the campaign finance and
lobbying laws. But the agreement soon dissolved in partisan
acrimony, making that handshake the symbol of the broken promise of
reform.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One official planning the event said the candidates might still
have to find another location in New Hampshire because advance
teams were not sure they could find a large enough site in
Claremont on such short notice. Scores of reporters packed into an
outdoor tent to cover the encounter between Clinton and Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The meeting could be officially announced as early as Friday.
``John McCain and Bill Bradley both want this to happen,'' said Dan
Schnur, McCain's communications director. ``So we are doing
everything we can to try to make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to hold a joint appearance comes at a time when
McCain is beginning to pull ahead of Gov. George W. Bush in New
Hampshire according to new polls. Bradley, meanwhile, is running
neck and neck with Vice President Al Gore in the nation's first
primary state.
</P>
<P>
   The shared spotlight should provide both candidates with a burst
of publicity and serve to distinguish them further as fighters
against the status quo. It would also give each a bipartisan sheen
at a time when voters are turned off by partisan attacks.
</P>
<P>
   For Bradley in particular a Thursday, Dec. 16, event could give
him maximum publicity and momentum going into a scheduled debate
against Gore the next day in Manchester, N.H. Gore is vulnerable on
the campaign finance issue because of his fund raising in 1996,
including one event at a Buddhist temple.
</P>
<P>
   One question about a joint appearance is how it would sway
independent voters. Bradley and McCain are each trying to draw
support from independents in New Hampshire. But strategists for
each campaign say most independents already lean toward one party
or the other, creating little risk for the two in appearing
together. In New Hampshire independent voters can cast a ballot in
either party's primary.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of changing the finance law were ecstatic Thursday.
``We just haven't had two serious presidential candidates making
campaign finance reform a centerpiece of their campaigns before,''
said Fred Wertheimer, the president of Democracy 21, a nonprofit
group advocating change in the way campaigns are financed. ``Now
they're talking about creating a very dramatic symbolic moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The two campaigns have been sporadically discussing such an
event since last July, when Bradley called for a sweeping overhaul
of the campaign finance system including free television time for
candidates and public financing of congressional campaigns. He also
said, ``If I'm the nominee of the Democratic Party, the first thing
I'll do is invite the Republican nominee to join me in a compact.
We will direct our parties not to raise or spend soft money in the
general election.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Ludecke, a spokeswoman for Bradley, said Thursday: ``He
issued that challenge and an interesting thing happened. Tony
Coelho attacked him and John McCain accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   Coelho, the campaign chairman to Vice President Al Gore said in
July that Gore too favored a change in the campaign finance law.
But he went on to say Bradley's stance would leave Democratic
candidates to ``fend for themselves while George W. Bush and the
Republican money machine try to buy the election.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   McCain, who is the main Republican sponsor of legislation to ban
soft money said, ``I welcome another voice to the fight to take our
government back from the special interests and big dollar
contributors.'' McCain shares with Bradley an interest in promoting
free television time, but he does not support public financing of
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately after Bradley's speech in July, the McCain
campaign approached the Bradley camp with the suggestion of a joint
re-enactment of the Claremont handshake _ this time with a pledge
against soft money. But negotiations were desultory.
</P>
<P>
   An adviser to McCain said that the Bradley campaign became wary
of the idea when the former senator from New Jersey started rising
in the polls. Then the McCain campaign itself became distracted by
other issues, including questions raised about McCain's temper.
</P>
<P>
   Recently both sides started negotiating seriously.
</P>
<P>
   A somewhat similar, though far less showy and substantive moment
in recent presidential history came in 1980 when Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass., who was challenging President Jimmy Carter made a
joint appearance on Capitol Hill with John B. Anderson, R-Ill., who
was mounting an independent candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   The two men were not promoting a particular issue, however.
Instead Anderson implied that he would consider withdrawing his
candidacy if Kennedy became the Democratic nominee instead of
Carter. Carter won the nomination, then lost to Ronald Reagan.
Anderson drew just 6.5 percent of the vote in his third party run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 2101EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
