<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4606 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-KING-TRIAL-ASSESS-2TA     12-09 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-TRIAL-ASSESS-2TAKES(TRIMS)-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERDICT NOT LIKELY TO ANSWER QUESTIONS SURROUNDING KING
ASSASSINATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT-3 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By KEVIN SACK with EMILY YELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When a jury ruled in a wrongful death trial in Memphis
on Wednesday afternoon, it became the first judicial panel to hold
someone responsible for playing a role in the assassination of the
Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. on April 4, 1968.
</P>
<P>
   But with key players long dead, with confessions recanted and
altered, and with a vast conspiracy alleged but not proven,
Wednesday's verdict in the civil trial of Loyd Jowers may
ultimately do little to untangle the knot of fact and theory
surrounding one of the century's most traumatic events
</P>
<P>
   The jury in Memphis declared Jowers liable, purportedly for
hiring a now-deceased Memphis police officer as part of a vast
conspiracy to kill King, after a four-week trial that was notable
for the passivity of the defense, for the prevalence of second-hand
and third-hand witness accounts and for the propensity of the judge
and jurors to nod off during testimony. At one point, James E.
Swearengen of Shelby County Circuit Court allowed unsworn testimony
from a 1993 mock television trial of James Earl Ray to be
introduced as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the unusual nature of the Memphis trial, King's widow
and children exulted Thursday in the verdict, saying it vindicated
their nearly three-year effort to revive the investigation into
King's killing. In February 1997, the family began pushing for a
new trial for James Earl Ray, the career criminal who pleaded
guilty in 1969 to killing King, received a 99-year sentence, and
then quickly recanted and argued that he had been duped by a
shadowy figure named ``Raul'' into playing a patsy for the real
killer. While Ray never faced a jury, his conviction was upheld
repeatedly by appellate courts and a congressional committee
concluded in 1978 that he was the killer, although he may have had
help.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings had been convinced by William F. Pepper, Ray's lawyer,
that the assassination had been planned and executed by a
government conspiracy, reaching from the FBI and the CIA to Lyndon
B. Johnson's White House. The federal government, Pepper maintains,
feared King's growing denunciations of the Vietnam War and his
threats to clog Washington with massive protests by the poor.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1998, Ray died in prison of liver disease. Several
months later, with Pepper as their lawyer, the Kings filed their
wrongful death lawsuit against Jowers, who had said in a 1993
television interview that he hired a man to kill King at the behest
of a Memphis grocery owner named Frank Liberto. Pepper maintains
that Liberto was working for a Mafia boss in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference here Thursday, seated at a table with a
view of King's crypt, the civil rights leader's widow and children
made it clear that they now consider the case closed. The ``most
incredible coverup of the century,'' said Dexter Scott King, one of
King's four children, has now been exposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what happened,'' King said. ``This is the period at
the end of the sentence. So please, after today, we don't want
questions like `Do you believe James Earl Ray killed your father?'
I've been hearing that all my life. No, I don't, and this is the
end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, where Justice Department investigators have been
reviewing aspects of the assassination at the request of the King
family, officials said Thursday that the Memphis verdict was
unlikely to alter their review. Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder
said the Justice Department's report was nearly complete, and said
that criminal charges were not likely to be brought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not expect that there would be any criminal
prosecution out of our report,'' Holder said.
</P>
<P>
   Dexter Scott King said that his family, which asked for and
received $100 in damages from the jury in Memphis, does not care
what the Justice Department does next. ``We did not do this to
force their hands,'' he said. ``I doubt seriously they would indict
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the trial, which began on Nov. 15, the jury was presented
with sometimes contradictory and often confusing details of an
elaborate plot to kill King. Many of the approximately 70 witnesses
appeared in person. But others, including the ailing 73-year-old
Jowers testified only through depositions or unsworn audiotaped or
videotaped accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Often, lawyers introduced long and tedious videotaped or written
accounts, seemingly more to create an official record than to sway
the jury. For instance, Jowers' lawyer devoted a day and a half to
having a 300-page 1995 deposition of Ray read into the record. When
the reading was finished, members of the jury clapped in relief.
</P>
<P>
   Many times, jurors could be seen nodding off and Swearengen, who
is due to retire at the end of this year, was seen napping in court
as well. Opinions by members of the King family about the testimony
of witnesses were presented to jurors without objection from the
defense.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Judge Joe Brown, who presided in criminal court
over the last attempts by Pepper to win a trial for Ray, testified
as an expert witness in ballistics. Brown, who presides over both a
real courtroom and a television court in Hollywood, used his
extensive layman's knowledge of guns to maintain that Ray's rifle
was not the weapon that killed King.
</P>
<P>
   And Pepper also presented videotape from a staged mock
television trial. In the mock trial, which was broadcast on HBO in
1993, Earl Caldwell, a former New York Times reporter who was at
the scene of the assassination, said his editor had sent him to
Memphis in 1968 to ``nail Dr. King.'' That videotape was used to
bolster one of Pepper's main contentions, that the news media was,
and still is, controlled by the CIA and the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   The trial was also notable for what was not presented to the
jury, including changes in Jowers' story and various
inconsistencies alleged by Memphis prosecutors between his accounts
and those of other witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 report by the Shelby County District attorney General
said that Jowers originally claimed he hired a ``black man'' from
Memphis to kill King. But the Kings and Pepper maintain that Jowers
later suggested that a white police officer named Earl Clark, now
deceased, was the shooter. ``That's the killer,'' Dexter Scott King
said Thursday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; (MORE)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The same report by the district's attorney general concluded
that the inconsistencies created such a lack of credibility that
the conspiracy theory involving Jowers ``can be dismissed
outright.'' Jowers' lawyer, Lewis K. Garrison Sr., who did little
cross-examination of the plaintiff's witnesses, presented that
voluminous report to the jury during closing arguments and asked
them to read it, but did not offer guidance on its findings. It is
doubtful the jurors studied it during deliberations that lasted
about an hour.
</P>
<P>
   John Campbell, a Memphis prosecutor who reinvestigated the King
case and doubts Jowers' claims scoffed at the evidence presented in
the civil trial, where the standard of proof is lower than in a
criminal case.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I tried to put that kind of proof in front of a criminal
jury, I could lose my law license,'' he said. ``The trouble with
Pepper's theories is he quotes sources he never names and if you do
not agree with him you are part of the conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Posner, an author who concluded in a 1998 book that Ray
was King's assassin, predicted that the Memphis trial ``will be a
footnote, at best'' to the history of the slaying. ``The defense in
this trial was so lethargic it raises the question of its
sincerity,'' he said. People want to embrace the sweeping
conspiracy theory, he said, ``because it matches the stature of the
man and somehow gives even more meaning and power to his death.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 2107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
