<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4609 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     12-09 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SAMARANCH WON'T FACE A SUBPOENA 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has come to this: Before the head of the world Olympic
movement testifies before Congress, he first brokers an agreement
that he will not be slapped with a piece of paper on the steps of
the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   How the mighty have fallen. Juan Antonio Samaranch is coming to
America next Wednesday, direct from this weekend's meeting in
Lausanne, Switzerland. He is expected to brandish a mandate for
reform of the very same International Olympic Committee that he has
led for nearly 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI also wants to discuss some of the dealings between crass
officials of the 2002 Winter Games in Salt Lake City and
sticky-fingered delegates.
</P>
<P>
   So many Olympic officials are worried about being questioned
that there is talk of an IOC meeting, scheduled for Colorado
Springs in February, being shifted out of the United States to keep
Olympic delegates from being served subpoenas.
</P>
<P>
   At least Samaranch does not have to worry next week. Thursday he
agreed to speak with the feds, but at some later date.
</P>
<P>
   The man who brought professional athletes and huge corporate and
television money into the former haven of ``amateur sports'' is
coming to Washington on Wednesday to testify before the House
Commerce Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations, whose
chairman is Rep. Fred Upton, R-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody loves the Olympics,'' Upton said Thursday in a
telephone interview. ``I remember watching the Americans win the
hockey gold medal in 1980, one of the great moments in sports
history. Now I go to my 8-year-old's soccer practice and the coach
puts his finger in my chest and says, `You've got to straighten out
these Olympics.'''
</P>
<P>
   Upton has already voted to impeach President Clinton during the
Monica Lewinsky episode. Now he has invited the man called His
Excellency to a special hearing while Congress is on recess.
</P>
<P>
   ``We contribute to the Olympics as taxpayers and as private
citizens,'' Upton said. ``America foots most of the bills from
television and corporate support. We can't have this.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the delegates ousted so far have come from so-called
Third World countries, but the givers are as guilty as the takers.
When that smug little corner of the world, Salt Lake City, tried to
compete for the Winter Games, its leading sports and business
officials acted from craven instinct and tried to buy off the IOC
delegates, many of whom were quite available.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got involved, I thought maybe Salt Lake City was an
aberration,'' Upton said Thursday, adding that his subcommittee's
diligent prodding of Atlanta officials only showed how widespread
the bribery was.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a culture of corruption,'' Upton said. ``Jobs, visas,
cash, sex. There wasn't anything that wasn't available. It just
makes you sick.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not an American disease, by any means. Halfway around
the world, Sydney used blatant payoffs and the specter of civil
rights abuses in China to defeat Beijing by two votes for the right
to be the host of the 2000 Summer Games. Having procured those
Games by hook and by crook, the Sydney officials showed their own
sleazy instincts by hiding as many as 800,000 tickets, to be sold
at exorbitant prices to friends and corporate patrons. Many of
those tickets have now been made available to the public, but the
Sydney officials seem alarmingly unabashed.
</P>
<P>
   And still Juan Antonio Samaranch holds onto his job. When he
appears before the subcommittee with the presumed reform package,
His Excellency can expect to be treated respectfully but not
necessarily gently. A trace of haughtiness just might touch off a
representative who has flown back from the home district.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch has had a charmed career, starting as one of the rare
Catalan natives to prosper under the Franco regime in Spain, then
as Spanish ambassador to the Soviet Union and now for 20 years as
the leader of the Olympic movement.
</P>
<P>
   He has raised the Olympics into a wealthy pageant, and he has
also used the Games to make the biennial plea for an end to
violence, particularly toward ``the children of the world.'' For a
long time, there was the buzz, undoubtedly from within the IOC,
that Samaranch might be considered for a Nobel Prize.
</P>
<P>
   That talk has ended since somebody looked at the goodies being
exchanged under the table in Salt Lake City, but at least Samaranch
will not be publicly hounded by the FBI. This is not a tradeoff
that Juan Antonio Samaranch ever thought would happen. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
