<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GUNS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS FAILS TO REPORT APPARENT GUN LAW VIOLATIONS FOR SEVERAL
YEARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JACK DOUGLAS JR. 
And R.A. DYER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   State officials have known for years about hundreds of convicted
criminals who may have violated gun laws in Texas, but none of
those cases were sent to prosecutors until Thursday, a spokeswoman
for the Department of Public Safety said.
</P>
<P>
   The possible violations involve 750 to 800 people with criminal
pasts who candidly acknowledged in gun license applications that
they had used a firearm, DPS spokeswoman Tela Mange said.
</P>
<P>
   It is against federal law for a felon to ever use, or even
possess, a gun.
</P>
<P>
   The cases were sent Thursday to prosecutors in Austin who are
assigned to the ``Texas Exile'' project. The project was recently
formed by Gov. George W. Bush and state Attorney General John
Cornyn to bear down on gun-law violators through implementation of
penalties available under federal law.
</P>
<P>
   It was a ``complete coincidence,'' Mange said, that the cases
were transferred on the same day that news broke about the state's
years-long delay in considering whether laws were violated.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats quickly accused Bush, the front-running Republican
candidate for president, of failing to back up his campaign's
support of strong gun-law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's being a hypocrite here, and it reveals how hollow his
rhetoric is,'' said Rick Hess, spokesman for the Democratic
National Committee. ``Bush can't have it both ways. He can't say
the answer to gun safety is better enforcement, when he's not
enforcing the law himself,'' Hess said.
</P>
<P>
   Nina Butts, a lobbyist for Texans Against Gun Violence, said
Bush should be held at least partly responsible for the DPS'
failure to immediately report the gun-law violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we know is that there are a lot of dangerous people out
there right now, and they have their hands on guns. ... And under
Bush's leadership, nothing was done to prosecute them,'' said
Butts, whose open-records request first revealed the ignored
violations.
</P>
<P>
   But Scott McClellan, a spokesman in Austin for the Bush
campaign, said it was the governor's ``leadership that prompted the
DPS'' to transfer the files to Texas Exile prosecutors. ``The
governor's office called the DPS'' about the cases, McClellan said.
</P>
<P>
   The DPS began learning of the violations in 1996 while
conducting background checks on people who had applied for a
concealed handgun license, Mange said. As part of that written
application, she said, a person has to show proof of taking a ``gun
proficiency'' training class.
</P>
<P>
   The applicants must also note whether they have ever been
convicted of a felony.
</P>
<P>
   In the cases sent to prosecutors yesterday, applicants showed
proof of taking a training course, which requires using a gun, and
they also noted that their past included a criminal conviction,
Mange said.
</P>
<P>
   She said licenses were denied to anyone with a felony
conviction, but that the state did not go a step further and notify
proper authorities that a felon may have illegally used a gun _
even if it was only in a training class.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never tried to forward it on. We held on to the records,''
Mange said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the DPS did not have the ``resources'' to pass on the
information, and ``normally, prosecutors expect to have more ...
than just that we think a felon touched a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Several leading advocates of gunowners' rights said the DPS
should have immediately contacted prosecutors. But they did not
blame Bush for the oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the governor's place to do the research if DPS has
found out that someone is unqualified to have a ... concealed
handgun license,'' said Randy Gibson, executive director of the
Texas State Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson said the association does not support stricter gun laws,
but that those already on the books should be enforced.
``Otherwise, why have the law?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A right-to-carry advocate whose parents were killed in a mass
shooting, state Rep. Suzanna Gratia Hupp, R-Lampasas, said she
found it ``quite maddening'' that the cases had not been referred
to prosecutors earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really bothers and offends me that so many people are
screaming for stricter gun-control laws, when we're not enforcing
the ones that we have,'' Hupp said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
