<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MASS-FIREFIGHTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A TOUCHING TRIBUTE IN WORCESTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Dec. 11:
</P>
<P>
   At a moving memorial service attended by thousands of
firefighters from around the country and several foreign countries,
President Clinton paid tribute Thursday to the six firemen who
perished battling the inferno-like blaze that broke out at an
abandoned warehouse in Worcester, Mass., last Friday. Fittingly,
the president also took the occasion to pay homage to the nation's
entire family of firefighters _ the men and women whose willingness
to risk injury and death in order to protect others, Clinton noted,
is too often taken for granted.
</P>
<P>
   The Worcester blaze, and the courage shown by the firefighters
who battled it with lethal results amid unbearable heat and
blinding smoke, was a reminder of the risks routinely faced by
firefighters everywhere when they answer an alarm. So far this year
100 firefighters have been killed in the line of duty in this
country, a death toll roughly comparable to that suffered by
crime-fighting police during the same period. In New York City
alone, 13 firefighters have lost their lives since 1995, according
to Fire Department records. Many more have been injured.
</P>
<P>
   At the ceremony, President Clinton quoted from Benjamin
Franklin's salute to firefighters contained in an essay, ``Brave
Men at Fires.'' ``Neither cold nor darkness will deter good people
from hastening to the dreadful place to quench the flame,''
Franklin wrote. All these years later, battling flames remains what
it has always been _ an honorable, necessary and extremely
dangerous job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
