<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-PERSONAL-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEM ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 12) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn.)   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Lure of Free Food In the Conference Room &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Too bad you are not reading this at the office, where you could
be nibbling a bagel and sipping coffee provided free each day, or
where you could be burning calories at the company gym.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent national survey of 129 companies, Ceridian Employer
Services of Minneapolis found that 65 percent believed that ``work
perks'' helped to attract and retain employees.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular were casual-dress policies, offered at 82
percent of the companies; flexible hours, 60.5 percent; personal
development training, 49 percent; entertainment and product
discounts, 40 percent; and free food and beverages, 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Diane McNutt, director of human resources at Ceridian, said the
survey showed that employers were trying to differentiate
themselves in a competitive job market and to create a culture that
appealed to their employees.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, such perks don't cost much, she added, and they
can help create loyalty among existing employees while attracting
new recruits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This confirms that we need to be extremely creative in the
types of environments we create,'' Ms. McNutt said.
</P>
<P>
   _Mickey Meece
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 2114EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
