<HEADER>
A4620 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-FLA-DEMS10-COX     12-09 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-DEMS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Education tops Florida Democrats' agenda
 &HT;    By Marcia Gelbart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Stressing that their party has shed its
discord from a year ago, House and Senate Democrats rolled out a
unified 2000 agenda Thursday that focuses on public education,
health care and gun safety.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, announced one day before the start of this weekend's
Democratic State Convention in Orlando, calls for 10 percent salary
increases for teachers and the infusion of 10,000 teachers into
Florida's public schools. The price tag: $840 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the agenda is limited because Republicans control both
chambers, by a margin of 75-45 in the House and 24-15 in the Senate
(one special election will occur in January to replace Sen. Al
Gutman, R-Miami).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Party is simply riding the wave of success of
this governor,'' said Senate Democratic Leader Buddy Dyer of
Orlando, flanked Thursday by 18 of his colleagues at a Capitol news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic leaders believe the new agenda, which also pushes
for the use of gun safety locks and patients' rights to sue
insurance companies and health maintenance organizations, unifies
the party and will boost their election chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago when Republicans took over, we went through a
confusing time,'' said Rep. Lois Frankel (D-West Palm Beach), who
is leading House efforts in the 2000 campaigns. ``But this past
year, we've seen the `for sale' sign on public policy and we are no
longer confused.''
</P>
<P>
   Repeating the slogan, ``We're on Your Side,'' they singled out
Republican-sponsored measures last year that they say benefit
``wealthy special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, they mentioned a $1.1 million tax break for
country club members, later vetoed by Gov. Jeb Bush, and a new law
that allows people with concealed weapons permits in other states
to carry their guns in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans point to the school voucher plan and 10-20-Life
law, which targets violent criminals who use guns in felony crimes,
as proof of their pro-family record.
</P>
<P>
   It's ``greedy lawyers and teachers'' who support the Democratic
initiatives, said House Majority Leader Jerry Maygarden
(R-Pensacola).
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the GOP agenda mirrors that of ``Florida's working
parents, children and our seniors, and our growing numbers are
proof of that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
