<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4621 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-BIGGIO-HNS     12-09 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BIGGIO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The Astros placed a bold check mark next to Item No. 1 on their
offseason list of things to do, signing second baseman Craig Biggio
to a three-year contract extension worth $28 million Thursday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The agreement eliminates the risk of losing Biggio as a free
agent after the 2000 season and locks up the seven-time All-Star
through 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Biggio will receive a $7 million signing bonus to be paid in $1
million installments in each of the next four years, with a $3
million payment due in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old second baseman will earn base salaries of $6
million in 2001, $7 million in 2002 and $8 million 2003. He already
was under contract for $5 million in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   With an average annual salary of $8 million, Biggio joins
Cleveland's Roberto Alomar as the highest-paid second basemen in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Craig has established himself as one of the best players in
the game,'' general manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``No single
player has meant more to this franchise since its inception than
Craig Biggio.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is on track to become the first (career) Houston Astro to
be elected to the Hall of Fame when his career is completed. We
targeted this as our most important move of the offseason.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are the only organization for which Biggio has played
since being drafted in the first round in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being able to spend just about your entire career with one
organization is a great feeling,'' the native New Yorker said. ``In
this day and age, it just doesn't happen very much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was an East Coast kid, 21 years old, and I survived 13 years
in Texas. Now, I have a few more, and you couldn't ask for a better
situation. I couldn't think of a better time to be wearing an
Astros uniform.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio debuted with the Astros toward the end of their success
in the late 1980s and was around for some lean years in the early
1990s. He and first baseman Jeff Bagwell formed the backbone of a
team that has won the National League Central Division title the
past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The contract extension allows Biggio to help the Astros make
another run at the postseason without uncertainty regarding his
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't have bothered me to go through the entire season
without getting a deal done,'' he said. ``But it's just nice to
know that management thought enough about me that they wanted to
get it done beforehand.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio hit .294 with 16 home runs, 73 RBIs, 28 stolen bases and
a club-record 56 doubles in 1999 as he became only the sixth player
to have at least 50 doubles in back-to-back seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the best leadoff hitter in baseball,'' manager Larry
Dierker said. ``It's such a dynamic spot in the lineup, and it's
been such a tremendous strength for our team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's continually trying to get better. His offense speaks for
itself, but his defensive accomplishments are just as important _
if not more important _ as the things he does with his bat and on
the bases. He's a complete player, and it's hard to find complete
players at the major-league level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many players who had success in the minor leagues were able to
do almost everything, but when they get to the majors, if there's a
weakness, it will be exposed. At this stage in his career, we have
a guy who has no discernible weakness. This was the most important
step we could take this winter.''
</P>
<P>
   With Biggio secured for four years, the Astros can turn their
attention to center fielder Carl Everett and lefthander Mike
Hampton, both of whom can become free agents after the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker hopes to sign each to a contract extension, but the
general manager has acknowledged that players who are not signed
beyond the 2000 season are candidates to be traded _ perhaps at the
winter meetings, which commence today in Anaheim, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   After the coming season, the Astros will face a similar
situation with Bagwell, who is signed through 2001. By then,
Bagwell might be in position to demand a salary in excess of $15
million a year, leading some to wonder if Bagwell will end his
career in an Astros uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management has been able to do some unbelievable things
here,'' Biggio said. ``If you lose Baggy, you're going to be losing
a tremendous part of your ballclub. You can't lose a guy like that.
If anyone can get it done, (owner) Drayton (McLane Jr.) will get it
done. I'm not really concerned about that, because I know it will
get done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
