<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4630 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-JOBS-$ADV12-NYT &LR;      12-09 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-JOBS-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST A COUPLE EXTRA ZEROS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 12) 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Short precede may be italicized. The (AT) word should be
replaced with the symbol) 
(af) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   So many people had such good stories about expense accounts and
the mischief they inspire that a second column on the subject
seemed to be merited. Without further ado, here is an accounting: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Talk about confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Lynn Porter of Larchmont, N.Y., tells the story of an
executive who, early in his career, was transferred to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told his boss he needed a Blazer `because of all the
snow,''' says Ms. Porter, senior executive vice president of the
Sidney Frank Importing Co., importers of Jagermeister and Grey
Goose vodka. ``His boss said, `O.K.' and told him to buy one.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went out and bought his wife a Chevy Blazer and put the
expense on his expense report,'' Ms. Porter continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``When his boss saw the expense, he was shocked at the thousands
of dollars and asked what it was.''
</P>
<P>
   The executive explained that he had bought a Blazer automobile
as discussed and approved previously.
</P>
<P>
   ``His boss told him he had meant `one with three buttons.'''
</P>
<P>
   (The expense was approved.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I once put in for lunch with a horse,'' writes Steve Zousmer
of Scarsdale, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at the Kentucky Derby as chief writer for `Good Morning
America' in 1978, the year of the great Affirmed-Alydar rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Churchill Downs representative had been assigned to the
television staff, but there was a limit to how many people could
plausibly claim to have taken him to every meal every day. So I
alleged that I had gained editorial perspective in an $11 lunch
with `Derby insider Raymond Earl.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Raymond Earl, with his conveniently human but unrecognized
name, did indeed run in the Derby, and as far as I know, he's still
running. But I finished in the money. If challenged, I would have
claimed $6 for my hamburger and $5 in oats for the big fella.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Some years ago, I had a new sales manager who made frequent
trips to Philadelphia, presumably on company business,'' writes
Richard Carlton of White Plains, who was then the executive vice
president of a television syndication production company. ``His
expense sheets were fairly normal and aroused no suspicion.''
</P>
<P>
   One day, Carlton's assistant mentioned that the manager ``had a
unique way of solving his laundry problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Her comment went right by me, but knowing that he was single
and lived alone, I thought about it the next time he went to
Philadelphia,'' Carlton says. ``Sure enough, the expense sheet had
a revelation: Laundry _ $8.50.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since it was a one-night stay, it seemed odd, so I sent for
the past expense sheets, and for the first time examined the hotel
bill. Every one had laundry running upward of $8 on overnight
stays.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlton says he then realized how the manager solved his laundry
problems: ``Pack a bag with dirty laundry, check in for an
overnight, send the laundry down for express service and _ bingo! _
problem solved.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about it, Carlton recalled, the manager ``tried to
make light of his unusual technique, but the game was over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A quick check with his accounts in Philadelphia ended the
story. They hadn't seen him in months, but he did call once in a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   It was then goodbye to the manager. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dick Smyster, the founding editor of The Oak Ridger, a daily
newspaper in Oak Ridge, Tenn., recalls that in the paper's early
years, one of the sundry jobs of the small news staff was to
conduct tour groups, usually children, through the plant.
</P>
<P>
   He writes that after one such tour, one staff member submitted
the following expense claim:
</P>
<P>
   ``Three peppermint candies (AT) 2 cents each in order to cover
up odor of Friday lunch beer before taking Girl Scouts through
office on tour.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``As part of my introduction to expense account policies at a
company I had just joined, I was told that everyone in the company
flew coach class on domestic flights,'' writes Ronald J. Rakowski
of Bethel, Conn., a former human resources vice president for a
major corporation. ``However, first-class travel was OK if coach
seating wasn't available.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I didn't consider the policy particularly onerous, one
of my fellow department managers didn't think the policy applied to
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd often boast that he would simply lie on his expense
account about the availability of coach seating and fly first
class.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it soon came to an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``While attending a Chicago meeting with my boss, he received a
call from our Denver division asking us to come out and handle a
labor problem at one of its operations. So we detoured to Denver
and, after addressing the local labor problem, booked passage back
to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we threaded our way back to our seats in the nearly vacant
coach section, whom should we spot perched in first class sipping a
free drink? Yep! My fellow department manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``My boss was outraged. During the rather long flight home, he'd
settle down for a while before breaking out with another diatribe
on the importance of honesty and following company policies. He
usually avoided drinking alcohol on flights, but he had a couple
that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what my boss said to the manager after we landed,
but the guy resigned shortly thereafter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 2121EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
