<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR FRIDAY, DECEMBER 10
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Friday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Dec. 7)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Dec. 7,
about the promotion of a woman, Rasha al-Sabah, by the Kuwait
ministry of higher education misstated her new title. She was named
acting minister of higher education, not under secretary of
education; she has served as under secretary of higher education
for many years. The report also referred incompletely to Yusif
Muhammad al-Ibrahim's posts. In addition to being the education
minister, he is the minister of higher education.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MILITARY-GAY-SLAYING-NYT (Moved on Wednesday, Dec. 8)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Dec. 8,
about the conviction of an Army private, Calvin Glover, in the
murder of Pfc. Barry Winchell and about Hillary Rodham Clinton's
criticism of the ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy of the military
misstated the number of gay service members discharged last year
because of the policy. The number was 1,149; discharges from the
Army account for 312.
</P>
<P>
   Because of an editing error, the article about Mrs. Clinton's
criticism of the policy also misstated its legal basis. President
Clinton agreed to legislation allowing homosexuals to serve; he did
not issue an executive order.
</P>
<P>
   BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Nov. 30)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Nov. 30,
about a campaign appearance by Vice President Al Gore in New
Hampshire rendered a passage incorrectly in a comment he made about
the contamination of Love Canal. Mr. Gore said: ``I found a little
place in upstate New York called Love Canal. I had the first
hearing on that issue and Toone, Tenn. But that was the one that
started it all.'' He did not say ``But I was the one that started
it all.''
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-LLOYD-JONES (moved on Tuesday, Dec. 7)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Donald J. Lloyd-Jones, sent by the New York
Times News Service on Tuesday, Dec. 7, misstated the date of his
death. It was Nov. 29, not this past Monday.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CYBERSQUAT-LAWSUIT-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Dec. 8)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Dec. 8,
about lawsuits seeking Internet addresses held by others referred
incorrectly to the effect of international rules on addresses
registered by Network Solutions Inc. before Jan. 1, 2000. Beginning
on Jan. 3, those addresses will be subject to the rules intended to
protect trademark holders. The addresses will not be exempt from
them.
</P>
<P>
   BC-VH1-FASHION-NYT (moved on Monday, Dec. 6)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on moved on Monday,
Dec. 6, about the VH1/Vogue fashion awards show misidentified the
principal designer of the set. He was Keith Ian Raywood; Isaac
Mizrahi was a consultant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 2123EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0349 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4632 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-BOOKS-ART-$ADV12-     12-09 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOKS-ART-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIPS ON THE POWER PLAY, FROM A PAST MASTER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 12) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By HUBERT B. HERRING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Machiavelli as role model? Machiavelli as business guru at the
cusp of the you-know-what? Niccolo Machiavelli, symbol of all
that's calculating and cold-blooded?
</P>
<P>
   Are they kidding?
</P>
<P>
   No, the Prince of Expediency has been having his own renaissance
of late, his name gracing the cover of one book after another, from
``The New Machiavelli: The Art of Politics in Business'' to ``The
Machiavellian Manager's Handbook for Success'' to ``What Would
Machiavelli Do?'' And, lest nonprinces feel left out, ``The
Princessa: Machiavelli for Women'' and ``A Child's Machiavelli: A
Primer on Power.''
</P>
<P>
   That last one (Penguin Studio, $14.95), by Claudia Hart, is an
odd specimen indeed: It has the look of a children's book _
snippets of cuddly text meandering alongside cute drawings. But you
might think twice, at least, about reading those words at the
frilly bedside of your 8-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   A sampling: ``Either be really nice to people or kill 'em.''
``If you wanna give presents to people, make sure it's other
people's stuff.'' ``People who cheat are always more successful
than people who are honest.'' ``You have to destroy everything'' _
this with a drawing, a la ``The Little Prince,'' of a planet as
rapidly deflating balloon.
</P>
<P>
   Who could this book possibly be for? A little rib-tickling
stocking-stuffer for the corporate princes on your list? The jacket
copy, so kindly, acknowledges the book's ``tongue-in-cheek
concept.'' Oh, so that's it.
</P>
<P>
   Tongue practically punctures cheek, meanwhile, in ``What Would
Machiavelli Do?'' (Harper Business, $21), by Stanley Bing. The
cutely outrageous tone is set in the dedication: ``I'm going to do
what Machiavelli would tell me to do, and dedicate this book to
myself.'' No, it's actually set on the dust jacket: ``So start
reading. Or get out of here. You're beginning to get on our
nerves.''
</P>
<P>
   Bing, a Fortune columnist with a (sort of) secret life as a
television executive, sprinkles in modern-day case studies of a
sort, like everyone's favorite gold-plated, high-rise ego on
wheels: ``Donald Trump would be a failed real-estate agent if he
didn't have the world's biggest need to tell everybody how great he
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Lying for a good business reason, Bing writes, is now called
``positioning, and people get paid good money to do it, lucky for
me.'' (A little hint about Bing's day job.)
</P>
<P>
   But mainly he indulges his flamboyant outrageousness: ``Don't
like it? Get over it, you sniveling tree hugger.'' ``You have
enormous selfishness within you. Let it out. Let it flower.''
``You'll have to find, cultivate, and celebrate your insanity if
you have any hope of ruling others.'' On the Dalai Lama: ``I hear
he can get really cranky when they screw up his reservation at
Spago.'' It wears thin before long.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Machiavellian Manager's Handbook for Success'' (Libey
Publishing, $14.95), by L.F. Gunlicks, plays it a little
straighter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lest the title lead you to think it's a how-to manual, you are
encouraged to use the book as ``an entertainment source,'' perhaps,
or ``to identify the Machiavellian Manager to avoid the carnage he
eventually causes.''
</P>
<P>
   And to shatter any hint of doubt, this disclaimer: ``I am not
advocating Machiavellian behaviors _ I detest and deplore them.''
</P>
<P>
   Gunlicks sums up: ``Although I have slightly exaggerated parts
of the descriptions of Machiavellian Managers, the beasts are out
there. If you don't believe me, just look around _ or in a
mirror.'' Gotcha.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Machiavelli'' (John Wiley &AMP; Sons, $16.95), by Alistair
McAlpine, also goes for serious analysis: ``The point is not that
Machiavelli advocated evil-doing; rather that he accepted that all
human activity, and especially politics, will involve evil-doing.''
</P>
<P>
   There are whimsical touches. ``Clearly,'' he writes, ``it is not
possible at the turn of the 20th century to behead managing
directors.'' But the tone is mainly earnest: ``Courage, honor,
energy, ability, perseverance and, above all, dedication are the
ingredients of success.''
</P>
<P>
   And: ``Machiavelli would find the last years of the 20th century
a strange world, for much has changed since the 15th century, not
least the attitude of women towards men who would beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes. Women. That's where ``The Princessa'' (Doubleday, $22),
by Harriet Rubin, comes in. Citing everyone from Cordelia to
Scheherazade, she strives to define a distinctly feminine type of
power. Unlike the prince, ``the princessa cannot cripple the
enemy,'' Ms. Rubin writes. ``She must make her opponent an
unwitting ally.''
</P>
<P>
   Her one-liners are tasty: ``I have found a way for a woman to
become the artist of her anger and her desire.'' ``Women are the
fiercer sex. The Greek poets and philosophers trembled before
women.'' ``Why fight like Machiavelli when we can fight like
Machiavella?''
</P>
<P>
   She even quotes E.M. Forster, about ``enlarging the space in
which you may be strong.''
</P>
<P>
   By her rules, Hillary Rodham Clinton doesn't cut it. In the
health care fight, she tried to keep control, but a true princessa,
Ms. Rubin writes, ``makes her war others' war too.''
</P>
<P>
   So what to do with these books? Most are petite, sized just
right for bizarre little gifts _ if you can just figure out who
deserves them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 2124EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
