<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida Gov. Bush fights to reduce death row delays
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Ready to spend millions more taxpayer
dollars to do so, Gov. Jeb Bush on Thursday called a special
legislative session to pick up the pace at which Florida kills its
condemned murderers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, House Speaker John Thrasher and Senate President Toni
Jennings agreed to discuss shortening the time for death row
appeals, lessening the influence of jury recommendations in capital
cases, limiting the options available to state-paid death row
lawyers and making lethal injection the primary method of execution
_ all in two and a half days in January.
</P>
<P>
   The most ambitious of the changes, so-called ``parallel
tracking'' of death penalty appeals, is modeled after the system in
Texas, where Jeb's older brother, George W. Bush, is governor.
Texas leads the nation in executions each year.
</P>
<P>
   Because about half of all death sentences in Florida are
overturned by the state Supreme Court in the first round of
appeals, Bush's new plan would mean half of the secondary appeals,
which would be done simultaneously, would be wasted effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will cost a little more, but I think it's worth it,'' Bush
said, conceding that he didn't yet know how much more but that
staff members would produce the numbers in time for the Jan. 5-7
session.
</P>
<P>
   Civil liberties groups and defense lawyers predict some of the
proposed changes will backfire, ultimately delaying executions with
lengthy court challenges over their constitutionality _ changes,
for example, such as limiting state-paid death row lawyers, but not
privately paid lawyers, to one appeal in each state and federal
court.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Spalding, an American Civil Liberties Union lobbyist, said
lawmakers, in their rush to write and pass complicated laws in just
a few weeks, would undoubtedly give defense lawyers vast new areas
to explore. ``They haven't been able to get it right yet,'' he
said. ``I'm reasonably comfortable that they won't get it right
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The session was requested originally by Attorney General Bob
Butterworth to stave off a pending U.S. Supreme Court review of
whether using Florida's electric chair constitutes cruel and
unusual punishment. Florida is one of only four states that uses
the chair as its sole means of execution.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea of a special session has grown to encompass more
than a dozen separate ideas, going far beyond a mere switch from
electrocution to lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   Butterworth asked Bush and lawmakers to pass a law before Jan.
10 _ his deadline for filing his brief with the high court _ to let
him ask the court to declare the electric chair's constitutionality
moot.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, though, made it clear he would not call a special session
unless the bill it produced did something to reduce the current
14-year average stay on death row before inmates are put to death,
a figure he said has increased from eight years in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``These statistics point to a system that's not working,'' Bush
said. ``It's wrong. Justice delayed is justice denied.''
</P>
<P>
   QUESTIONS OF CONSTITUTIONALITY
</P>
<P>
   Marty McClain, a former state-paid appeals lawyer whose efforts
have put the electric chair under the eye of the U.S. Supreme
Court, said the new changes would in turn bring their own legal
challenges and, hence, even more delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons for all the delays is the legislature every
couple of years makes changes and it takes a couple of years for
the courts to rule on the constitutionality of those changes,''
said McClain, now a capital-case public defender in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the commission appointed by the Supreme Court to
shorten appeals delays, meanwhile, questioned how Bush and
legislators could want to prohibit an inmate from taking newly
discovered evidence to state courts if the inmate has already been
through his state appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's proposal bars all such appeals with the exception of DNA
evidence that might not have been available during the inmate's
original trial.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH CLAIMS AMPLE PROTECTIONS
</P>
<P>
   Susan Schaeffer, chief circuit judge in Pinellas County, said
such a blanket prohibition would apply, for instance, to three
eyewitnesses who independently realize they've made a mistake after
seeing the real killer on a ``America's Most Wanted''-type
television program.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they really think about it, they would not want to deny
actual evidence,'' Schaeffer said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal's defenders say inmates with new evidence can still
make a case in federal court. ``We have ample protections for
people on Death Row,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
