<SLUG> BC-WORLD-SKATE-LIPINSKI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIPINSKI BLOSSOMS AS AN ARTIST ON SKATES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Switzerland, France, Ukraine, Texas)   By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When she was in seventh grade, Tara Lipinski burst
into big-time figure skating, a 12-year-old jumping jack long on
athleticism but, understandably, undeveloped artistically.
</P>
<P>
   The last five years have brought huge success and change. At 14,
she became figure skating's youngest world and youngest U.S.
champion ever. At 15, she became the sport's youngest Olympic
champion ever. Now, as a 17-year-old professional, she can still do
the jumps beautifully, but the artistic parts of her skating have
indeed become artistic and not just links between jumps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be the best jumper,'' she said in an interview
Thursday. ``I want to become the best skater.''
</P>
<P>
   She may be that already. She has an opportunity to confirm that
Friday and Saturday nights in the Metabolife world pro
championships at the MCI Center. Competing in these championships
for the first time, she will oppose Oksana Baiul of Ukraine, the
1994 Olympic champion; Surya Bonaly of France, three times the
world silver medalist; 36-year-old Denise Biellmann of Switzerland,
the 1981 world champion, and Tonia Kwiatkowski, a member of the
U.S. world team.
</P>
<P>
   The most notable absentee is Michelle Kwan, the American who was
upset by Lipinski for the 1998 Olympic gold medal. Kwan is
retaining her eligibility for the 2002 Olympics in Salt Lake City
by passing up such events as this outside the jurisdiction of the
International Skating Union. Under that body's convoluted rules,
Kwan, ostensibly an amateur, can earn as much money as Lipinski,
and the money is considerable.
</P>
<P>
   After her Olympic triumph, Lipinski turned pro and earned
between $1 million and $2 million for four months on the Stars on
Ice Tour. She will make a similar 70-stop tour starting next month,
and competitions, commercial endorsements and other appearances
bring her perhaps an additional $1 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Lipinski says she likes life much more as a pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy it all, including the tour,'' she said. ``There's not
a lot of pressure. Even though there are a lot of stops, I get home
more often. I used to compete and tour and train and there was
little time for anything else. I still train every day, but it's
not as strenuous, and that helps avoid injuries. I have more time
and no injuries, so I'm doing a lot of competitions.''
</P>
<P>
   She is also doing many things any other 17-year-old would do,
including studying. She is in 12th grade at River Oaks Academy in
Houston, near her family home in Sugar Land, Texas. A tutor travels
with her, and she spends four hours a day studying. She has a
straight-A average.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 feet 1 inch, she weighs 98 pounds and, she says, eats well
and intelligently. At home, she drives her own Corvette. With an
autobiography, a contract as a television actress and appearances
as a favorite television guest, she is a celebrity beyond sport,
but she still seems almost taken aback by public recognition.
</P>
<P>
   People come up and ask, ``Are you Tara Lipinski?'' She responds
with a nod and smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real flattering,'' she said. ``They want an autograph or
just want to say hi.''
</P>
<P>
   The young idealist in her bonds easily with her admirers. The
audience is happy because she is accessible, and it helps that she
is unbeaten in her four major competitions since she turned pro.
Her success, on and off the ice, almost seems a case of too much
too soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' she said. ``Some people can't handle it. I think my
parents prepared me for it. They taught me how to react to people.
If I couldn't handle it, I think my parents would tell me to come
home and go back to school full time.''
</P>
<P>
   Her popularity makes her the female equivalent of Scott
Hamilton, the dynamic 1984 Olympic champion who has become the
darling of figure skating crowds everywhere. She enjoys the
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'll be remembered for breaking records, for being the
youngest to win some championships,'' she said. ``But I want to be
like Scott. Audiences all over the world love him. I'd like them to
love me like that.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
