<HEADLINE>
PINCAY TIES SHOEMAKER RECORD WITH 8,833 CAREER WINS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Panama, Calif., Ill . , Ky.)   By KEN GURNICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Laffit Pincay Jr., riding a horse that had
not won in 11 career starts, reached the winner's circle and the
record books Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay, 52, joined Bill Shoemaker atop the list of thoroughbred
racing's winningest jockeys with victory No. 8,833. He won the
fourth race at Hollywood Park aboard the 3-year-old gelding I Be
Casual, who is trained by Jack Van Berg, a fellow member of the
sport's Hall of Fame. Shoemaker had held the record alone since
supplanting John Longden 29 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very proud,'' Pincay said. ``I just need one more win
and my dream will come true.''
</P>
<P>
   Pincay rode in three other races on Thursday's card, finishing
no better than fifth. He has five mounts scheduled for Friday and
six for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   I Be Casual, the 6-5 favorite in the field of nine $25,000
maiden claimers, prevailed by a head in a stretch duel with A J
Flyer. Omar Berrio, riding the runner-up, waved his whip in
celebration of the accomplishment by his fellow Panamanian. Berrio
narrowly defeated Pincay two races earlier.
</P>
<P>
   A mob scene awaited Pincay in the winner's circle. He was
carried to the scales for the postrace weigh-in on the shoulders of
his fellow jockeys. He was handed a Panamanian flag by Berrio for
the winner's circle photo with his family and the wheelchair-bound
Shoemaker, who watched the race on a monitor in the jockeys room.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the greatest, in my opinion,'' Shoemaker said. ``He's
climbed to the top of the mountain, but he's got one to go to be
there by himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoemaker had held the record since passing Longden with winner
No. 6,033 in 1970. Pincay passed Longden in 1985 and has been
chasing Shoemaker ever since. Shoemaker set his record with 40,350
career rides compared with 44,630 for Pincay.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Day, 46 and still one of the top riders, is third on the
career list with 7,608 winners. He could eventually pass Pincay.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay, who turns 53 on Dec. 29, rode his first winner in his
native Panama aboard Huelen on May 19, 1964, and was brought to the
United States two years later by the horse owner Fred Hooper to
ride in Chicago. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
