u p BC-REPUBS-BUSH-800(2TAKE     12-09 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-BUSH-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME IN GOP UNEASY OVER BUSH IN DEBATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Many prominent Republicans have concluded that Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas is an unimpressive debater, but they
disagreed over how much that should be a cause for deep concern
among his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans expressed fears that Bush would be no match for
Vice President Al Gore or Bill Bradley in a general election, while
others argued that all that mattered was that the governor not make
any humiliating blunders.
</P>
<P>
   But in interviews among Republicans who have endorsed Bush or
who are neutral in the primary thus far, there was overwhelming
agreement on this point: the governor's performance was lackluster
in the debates this week and last week. Even two of Bush's foreign
policy advisers _ speaking anonymously _ expressed concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has not been the Michael Jordan in the debates,'' said Rep.
John Kasich of Ohio, who withdrew from the presidential race and
endorsed Bush this summer. ``He's not been himself or as
effervescent as he is capable of being. My advice to George Bush is
to keep studying, keep learning, be yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   In the primaries, Kasich said, all that matters is that Bush
avoid a big gaffe. But, counseling that Bush needed some polishing,
he said, ``I have said all along that Al Gore is not to be
underestimated.''
</P>
<P>
   The critiques are among the first serious questions that have
been raised about the political dexterity of Bush, the Republican
front-runner. Many Republicans had argued that Bush's affable
personality would come across well on television and give him a
crucial advantage over Gore or Bradley should he win the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, many said that Bush appeared uncharacteristically
awkward on television and that the events raised questions about
his command of the issues. These Republicans also said that Bush's
performance raised questions about whether he had suffered because
of his lack of national campaign seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania, who is neutral in the race,
said it was ``a terrible mistake'' that Bush did not emerge from
Austin early and begin campaigning and debating. ``I think he took
his lead for granted and that was a mistake,'' Specter said.
Contending that Sen. John McCain of Arizona had appeared more
steady, Specter said, ``McCain's been through a lot of fire. In the
Senate, we make speeches all the time and are in all sorts of
debates. That experience level is an automatic reflex. Governor
Bush doesn't have that.''
</P>
<P>
   Specter, who ran unsuccessfully for the Republican nomination in
1996, said that Bush needs to loosen up in front of the cameras.
``Cramming is not good,'' he said. ``I don't think he ought to have
his head full of facts and figures and statistics. It's more
important to be relaxed and cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Fabrizio, who was Bob Dole's pollster in the 1996
presidential race and is neutral this time, said he was deeply
worried about Bush's debate skills. ``I'm concerned more for the
general,'' he said. ``Anybody who thinks that Gore is going to be a
pushover in the debates is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   In the debates so far, he said, Bush ``was very repetitive.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I understand that benefit of repeating a message.
But to where it's just rote? You've got to be a little deeper than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the many Republicans interviewed, almost no one was greatly
impressed by Bush. ``Did he score a grand slam home run? No,'' said
Steve Duprey, the Republican chairman in New Hampshire. ``But I
don't think he needed to. What he needed to do was not make a big
error.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher DePino, the Republican party chairman in
Connecticut, described himself as a ``Kool Aid drinking Bushie.''
But he said the affable, charming candidate he knows was not
reflected on television. ``There's a side of this man that is
completely different from his television persona,'' he said. ``In
my opinion, he's very humble. But that does not come across
sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning on Thursday in Goffstown, N.H., Bush brushed aside
questions about whether he knew enough to be president. ``I'd
rather be underestimated than overestimated,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   At a breakfast here with reporters on Wednesday, Karl Rove,
Bush's chief strategist, dismissed criticism about his candidate.
``You don't get elected governor unless you've got some great
communication skills,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that before last week Bush had only taken part in two
debates _ one when he ran for governor in 1994 and another when he
sought re-election in 1998 _ Rove quipped, ``In the last five days,
Governor Bush has doubled his debate experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Rove conceded that Bush's one-on-one appeal does not
always convey well on television. ``Does he come across better when
he's sitting two feet away from you?'' he said. ``You bet. That's
just the nature of what television is all about.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Two of Bush's foreign affairs advisers were less charitable,
saying that the candidate is not at his best in debates. ``He's
better as a natural guy than in these stylized settings,'' one
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another adviser put it this way, ``He really relates to people,
and he's clearly at his best when he's dealing with small groups.''
The adviser said that Bush needs to figure out whom he is talking
to when he is in a debate.
</P>
<P>
   Don Sipple, who for years was a media consultant for Bush, said
the debates have been ``a learning experience'' for the governor
and that he will no doubt improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The format and the stilted nature of these events is something
he will grow accustomed to,'' Sipple said. ``He's got a lot of
strength, a lot of personality traits that will come through as
time goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Bush supporter, Rich Bond, a former chairman of the
Republican National Committee, said, ``George is playing error-free
ball. And if you're behind in New Hampshire, that's a cautious
strategy. I am not urging boldness upon George at this point. But
if it gets a little more dire between John and he then he may have
to sharpen his message.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans said that although they were not impressed with
Bush's debate skills, they insisted that would not pose an
insurmountable problem for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is not an Adlai Stevenson, intellectually, but neither
was Ronald Reagan, not his father, not even Dwight Eisenhower for
that matter,'' said David Hess, a state representative in New
Hampshire who will back either Bush or McCain. ``The American
people are suspicious of the four-point-0, straight-A guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Sutherland, a Republican national committeeman from
Kansas who is neutral in the primaries, said Bush could never
``live up to his dad's credentials'' and needs ``to get hard-nosed
_ he's going to have to get aggressive going after Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, he was optimistic about the governor. ``He's not
Aristotle's philosopher-king,'' Sutherland said. ``But he did a
perfectly workmanlike job. He answered the questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Specter said that Bush only has to meet expectations that are
already low. ``He doesn't have to be a super star,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 2130EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
