<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4645 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-TRUMP-ASSESS-ART-2TAK     12-09 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUMP-ASSESS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: A QUESTION TRAILS TRUMP ... IS HE REALLY A CANDIDATE? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Pa., Conn., Fla., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT26 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There was the taping with Jay Leno, the late
dinner at a restaurant bustling with celebrities, the visit to a
Holocaust memorial trailed by an invited pack of television crews,
and the paid speech to 17,000 people at a ``motivational
conference'' in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   There was even a political event on the itinerary of Donald
Trump, here to present himself as triumphant developer, new book
author, and the potential next leader of the free world. It was a
cantankerous meeting with leaders of the California Reform Party,
whose support Trump would presumably like should he run for
president. For many, the most memorable moment came when someone
asked if Trump supported the Reform Party platform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Trump responded loudly, ``Nobody knows what the Reform
Party platform is.'' As a swell of boos rippled the crowd, a man
stepped forward to offer Trump a copy of the document.
</P>
<P>
   Trump's two-day trip to the West Coast was an exploratory
campaign trip by an exploratory candidate. Yet the visit did little
to settle what has emerged as the fundamental question around his
potential candidacy for the Reform Party nomination: Is he serious?
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, Trump has taken a few steps that would suggest
this is something more than an exercise in self-promotion. He has
begun meetings with Reform Party leaders, including the one here on
Monday night, as well as meetings in Pennsylvania, Connecticut,
Florida and New York. He has placed on retainer two
signature-gathering companies, which he would need to get on 29
state ballots and become an official contender for the Reform Party
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   He has offered a plan to cut taxes, is preparing his own
proposal to provide universal health care and is considering naming
a running-mate early next year.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Trump has yet to do the kind of political spade work
that a candidate for office, or even a potential one, would
customarily have done by this point. His meeting in Beverly Hills
was the only real political event on his short schedule here.
Indeed, Trump suggested that his invitation by Leno and the
$100,000 he was paid for his motivational speech were the real
incentive for flying his black-and-gold private Boeing 727 across
the nation and back.
</P>
<P>
   Trump has yet to hire a campaign staff, and while he says he has
commissioned some polls, he has declined to say who is doing them.
</P>
<P>
   Trump's political travels happen to coincide with a release of a
book, and what at first glance appears to be a campaign pamphlet
turns out, on closer inspection, to a promotional leaflet for the
book.
</P>
<P>
   And as Trump's performance with the Reform Party leaders here
suggested, the developer's command and interest in the details of
running for president sometimes seemed tenuous. Asked to discuss
the idea of a national sales tax, Trump responded: ``How do I feel
about sales tax? I try to avoid paying it whenever possible. But
the idea is an idea that a lot of people like very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Denouncing U.S. trade policy, Trump promised to appoint himself
as the nation's trade representative, saying he would have no
trouble serving both in that post and as president. He then
attacked the current holder of the job, Charlene Barshefsky. ``Who
is she?'' demanded Trump. ``I never heard of her!''
</P>
<P>
   And Trump offered an unusual analysis of why he would be a
strong candidate. ``In a three-person race, we need 33 1/3 percent,
a little more, figure 34,'' he said. ``So it's not a very large
percentage in a three-person race.'' In fact, while the analysis
may be correct as a matter of theoretical mathematics, the history
of three-person races suggests that they are never so evenly
divided, with the ultimate winner getting closer to 45 to 50
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The one issue on which Trump was firm was restrictions in
immigration. ``I'm opposed to new people coming in,'' he declared.
``We have to take care of the people who are here.''
</P>
<P>
   But difficulties with the details aside, Trump, a man accustomed
to attention, is luxuriating in what he sees as a cross-country
shower of interest in his potential presidential ambitions. He
raises his hands in a victory salute as he charges onto the set of
the Jay Leno show to the sounds of ``Hail to the Chief.'' He beams
in the glaring television lights as he walks through the solemn
hallways of the Holocaust exhibit in Los Angeles, and camera crews
_ whom he invited to attend _ climb on top of the exhibits to
photograph him.
</P>
<P>
   As he makes his way through the Ivy restaurant, he stops to say
hello first to Rod Stewart and then to Michael Bolton. In arguably
unusual behavior for a White House candidate, he remarks, while
taking questions at the motivational conference, on the clothing
and physical appearances of several women, all young and
attractive, whom he called on for questions.
</P>
<P>
   And, narrating his own voyage, he makes sure to point out how
much attention is being paid to him. ``By the way the camera is `60
Minutes,''' Trump said at the Reform Party meeting here. `Don't
worry about them. It's just a small program on television.''
</P>
<P>
   When Leno inquired how it was going, Trump, responding with
characteristic exaggeration, said: ``Oh, so much press. So much
press out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in his dressing room after the interview, Trump
described himself as serious and dismissed the suggestion that this
was a self-promotional lark. ``I'm looking at it seriously,'' he
said. ``Very, very seriously. And a lot of people think I'm pushing
the book. But just remember, I had three No. 1 best sellers. So I
believe this will be a No. 1 best seller, or very close to it, even
if I don't do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Should Trump run, he is in a strong position to win the
nomination. The Reform Party is racked by infighting, which Trump
says could allow a newcomer like himself to gain quick advantage.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, party rules permit almost anyone who requests a
ballot to vote on the party's presidential nominee, which Trump's
main adviser, Roger Stone, argues would allow Trump to draw much
support from the clients he has assembled in his gambling and real
estate businesses over the years.
</P>
<P>
   And in a party that is anything but conventional, the notion of
a Trump candidacy is stirring some interest. In New York, Trump has
won the support of the chairman of the New York chapter of the
Reform Party, Jack Essenberg. ``He's a very interesting guy,''
Essenberg said. ``He certainly impressed me with the seriousness of
his candidacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Trump is leaving nothing to chance, attacking, in
particularly brutal terms, his main opponent for the nomination,
Pat Buchanan. (Trump was presumably unaware of the provision in the
Reform Party platform enjoining against attacking opponents.)
</P>
<P>
   Trump said he would only run if he could win, and there are few
professional politicians these days who believe there is much
chance of that. But the New York developer asserts that if he
decides to run, he is prepared to spend $100 million of his own
money _ and while that might not make him president, it could
certainly change the outcome of a three-way race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to toot my own horn, but everybody says two
things about Trump: He's very competent, and he's very rich,''
Trump said. ``That's not so bad. If you have to have two traits, I
mean you might as well have those two.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
