<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4647 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-FOR-ME-$ADV12-NYT     12-09 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-FOR-ME-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POP GOES THE CLASSROOM  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 12) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz.)   (af)  
 By MARIANNE M. JENNINGS and STEPHEN K. HAPPEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oprah Winfrey and her beau, Stedman Graham, teach a course at
Northwestern University's Kellogg Graduate School of Management.
Michael Milken has been a guest lecturer in finance courses at
UCLA's Anderson School of Management. There can be little doubt
that Ms. Winfrey, a woman who parlayed her television success into
extensive business interests, and Milken, the king of junk bonds,
have great war stories. They are the stuff that MBAs dreams are
made of.
</P>
<P>
   But while TV stars and tycoons have their place in business
classrooms, they also have their limitations when it comes to
educating students. We have no personal knowledge of what goes on
in their classrooms, but we wonder whether Ms. Winfrey ever
discusses the failure of her last movie, ``Beloved''?
</P>
<P>
   Does Milken discuss the public policy, ethical and corporate
governance issues related to the losses shareholders suffered from
1980s greenmail?
</P>
<P>
   As business school professors for more than two decades, we
confess to a bit of self-preservational wincing over celebrity
faculty members. But we also fear that higher education is being
reduced to little more than a talk-show format.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when Ms. Winfrey and Milken would have raised
eyebrows as classroom guest speakers. Now, as the distinction
between pop culture and higher education has become increasingly
muddled, they are conducting class.
</P>
<P>
   As professors, we have witnessed the dumbing-down of the
curriculum, as well as the elimination of general studies,
mathematics and science requirements for a degree. Nowadays, Ms.
Winfrey's MBA course, called ``Dynamics of Leadership,'' sounds
like serious learning next to courses like ``Rock Journalism'' and
``Star Trek and Religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Paralleling trends in elementary and secondary schools, higher
education has moved from rigor to fuzziness in teaching techniques.
In the sage-on-the-stage vs. guide-on-the-side debate, the guide
has won, and it is now unchallenged that students learn better from
one another in groups as faculty stroll among them. Yet imagine
Milton Friedman teaching a class in which students form discussion
groups while he just ambles about, asking whether there are any
questions.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, higher education is taking on characteristics that are
very familiar to Generation X and their baby brothers and sisters,
the Echo Boomers. Much like the dragons and dungeons encountered in
these students' video games, higher education has become an
obstacle to be bypassed.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to find a way to morph to the next world, complete
with credentials, so that you move directly to the bonuses and
rewards without enduring the challenges of the present.
</P>
<P>
   Business schools are making that morphing easier. Taking Peter
Drucker's ``universities without walls'' to the max, they are
becoming clearinghouses for self-generated studies and stages for
star appearances. They offer cyberspace and satellite courses. They
grant credit for life's work. Soon, deans will be able to hawk
their business schools as if they were selling cars: ``I can grant
that degree in 180 days or the fee's on me.''
</P>
<P>
   But a classic education takes time _ and demands creativity. The
ability to plug models into a computer is not the same as the
ability to develop the model itself. That requires creativity,
innovation and training to outlast trends.
</P>
<P>
   Through all their new shortcuts, including the granting of
credentials for communing with the Internet, business schools may
indeed ease the path for students who have spent a lifetime in
front of some form of screen. And who better to grace the screen
than a TV star with great stories?
</P>
<P>
   Pop culture and education are one; the morphing will soon be
complete. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marianne M. Jennings and Stephen K. Happel are professors at the
College of Business at Arizona State University. Submit your
account of struggling or succeeding as a worker, consumer, investor
or entrepreneur to My Money, Money &AMP; Business, The New York Times,
229 West 43rd Street, New York, N.Y. 10036, or by e-mail to
mymoney(AT)nytimes.com. All submissions become the property of The
Times. They may be edited and may be republished in any medium.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
