u w BC-NAVY-SHIPYARD-NYT &LR;      12-09 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAVY-SHIPYARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AILING SHIPYARD ON GUAM PROMPTS CLASH BETWEEN NAVY AND CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Md., Hawaii, Ill., Iowa, Guam)  (lh) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Four years ago, Congress agreed with the Pentagon
and a federal base-closing commission to shut a Navy shipyard in
Guam to save $172 million by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Now many lawmakers from both parties and even some Navy officers
fear that they may have made a big mistake, one that could
ultimately cost the United States control of a vital repair site
strategically situated near areas of potential trouble in Asia like
East Timor or Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The cost-cutting move seemed smart in 1995 because it would keep
in sync with a shrinking post-Cold War Navy, but its unintended
consequences have drawn sharp fire on Capitol Hill. Members of
Congress and officials in Guam say the Navy is undermining a plan
to help preserve jobs on the island and protect U.S. interests,
carried out by leasing the shipyard to a private American operator
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether the Navy is circumventing a law requiring
that U.S. ships be repaired in U.S. shipyards, including Guam,
except in emergencies. Navy officials say its five ammunition and
supply ships operating out of Guam are exempt from the law and can
be overhauled at cheaper, more convenient shipyards in South Korea
or Singapore. Without that work, however, the Guam shipyard may be
forced to close or surrender its lease to a foreign rival.
</P>
<P>
   Facing that prospect, an unusual alliance of pro-labor Democrats
and Republican defense hawks are pressing the Navy to reverse
course and comply with the law as the lawmakers interpret it. Their
ranks include Reps. David Bonior of Michigan, the second-ranking
Democrat in the House, and Robert Ehrlich, R-Md., who is a close
ally of Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois. Joining them are some
powerful Democrats on the Senate Appropriations Committee,
including Daniel Inouye of Hawaii and Tom Harkin of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Harkin recently wrote Navy Secretary Richard Danzig, saying that
his visit to the island last August underscored ``the unique
strategic role Guam may play as a forward deployment option for the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Regrettably,'' he added, ``current policies being implemented
by the Navy are inhibiting, rather than promoting, this
possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of this fight is Adm. James Lyons Jr., a
blunt-spoken retired commander of the Pacific Fleet who is the
chief executive of Guam Industrial Services, which runs the
shipyard. Lyons is lobbying his broad network of connections in the
Navy and in Congress to save his financially troubled company.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the uncertainty in China and Korea, the Navy is doing
everything they can to close us down,'' Lyons said. ``The
difference here is a few million bucks to keep open an important
strategic facility.''
</P>
<P>
   The Navy agrees, up to a point. ``We do need a repair capability
there,'' said Michael Hammes, deputy assistant secretary of the
Navy for ship programs. ``It's a question of how much capability.''
</P>
<P>
   When the United States closed the Subic Bay military base in the
Philippines in 1992, the Navy lost its premier shipyard in the
Western Pacific and Indian Ocean, leaving the 100-acre shipyard in
Guam as its westernmost repair site in the Pacific. It formed a
part of a major military installation that now includes an air
base, a Navy ammunition depot, a hospital and a support unit for
Navy special operations teams. As one of Guam's largest private
employers, the shipyard has had a work force as high as 325 people
since the Navy pulled out; it now hovers at around 150.
</P>
<P>
   Navy warships undergo repairs at U.S. shipyards at the end of
their six-month sea tours. But more than 30 support ships operated
by the Military Sealift Command deploy for nearly a year at a time,
and must be able to steam into foreign ports for repairs rather
than make the time-consuming trips back to the United States, Navy
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, the Navy does not assign the support ships to a
domestic home port, calling them simply ``forward deployed,'' a
technical but important distinction because the ship repair law
covers only those vessels formally based on Guam or in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Harkin complained that the Navy's interpretation ``is contrary
to both the letter and spirit of the law, and must be reversed.''
</P>
<P>
   Navy officials say they have gone out of their way to help
smooth Guam's transition from a government shipyard to a private
one. The Navy agreed in 1997 to steer $25 million in work over two
years to help the shipyard get on its feet.
</P>
<P>
   But to break even, the shipyard needs about $20 million of work
a year, Lyons said. When it comes to attracting the commercial work
to make up the difference, Guam has several disadvantages. For one
thing, it is off the beaten path of major shipping lines. Repair
costs in Guam, while in line with those on the West Coast, are 25
to 70 percent higher than at Asian shipyards.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons is trying to overcome perceptions that the shipyard has
failed to market itself aggressively. But Guam officials are
threatening to lease the shipyard to another company if it cannot
sustain a large enough work force.
</P>
<P>
   Navy officials say they are in a bind. ``Guam is a pivotal
location and a hedge against the future,'' Adm. Thomas B. Fargo,
commander of the Pacific Fleet, said in a telephone interview.
``It'll take a mixture of Navy and commercial work to sustain it at
a steady state level.''
</P>
<P>
   But Navy budget experts are wary of pouring more subsidies into
a financially shaky shipyard, even if it has a strategic mission.
``They need a graceful transition, but we've provided two years of
that already,'' said Hammes, the Navy's ship programs official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
