<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4659 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-OPTIONSIDE-OPTIONSIDE     12-09 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPTIONSIDE-OPTIONSIDE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Firms Leery of Getting Paid With Paper  &HT;     By Sam McManis 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The story has taken on almost mythic status among advertising
agencies in San Francisco. Some of the wilder rumors are
exaggerated but, yes, Black Rocket agency once had a chance to get
pre-IPO stock options in Yahoo at what its CEO calls ``extremely
favorable prices.''
<P>
   But Black Rocket turned down the offer, opting for cash up front
to handle Yahoo advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regrettably, that's true,'' John Yost, head of Black Rocket,
said. ``I wish I'd been able to see clearer, but at that time, we
were just getting started and we needed computers and desks more
than we needed options on somebody's stock.''
</P>
<P>
   For every Yahoo that offers options in lieu of payment to
advertising agencies, landlords, executive recruiters, accountants
and even caterers, there are many Internet startups whose options
turn out to be worthless.
</P>
<P>
   Equity-based compensation is a risk many businesspeople can't
afford to take. Others see it as something of a barter system.
</P>
<P>
   Erik Cederblom, an executive recruiter in San Rafael, says he is
willing to work for stock options provided the company's prospects
look promising. But Cederblom said he, too, has options so
worthless they could be used for scratch paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking options in lieu of cash is a gamble,'' he said. ``There
were three companies I did that with that didn't make anything. In
two of the cases, the companies didn't get funded. The other one
just didn't work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Cederblom said it makes sense, sometimes, for executive
recruiters to take options in lieu of cash because it makes the
recruiter a quasi-employee of the startup.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I've done these projects, it's like retaining a permanent
adviser, knowing I've got a vested interest in that company,'' he
said. ``I'll get them a VP of marketing, but I'll also introduce
them to (an) ad agency and other executives. I've got five deals
like that pending.''
</P>
<P>
   Other businesses find the risk-to-reward ratio too heavy on the
risk.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney Buechert, director of the Leagas Delaney advertising
agency in San Francisco, says he often turns down option offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that we're against stock options,'' Buechert said.
``We do have arrangements, but it's under a very judicious policy.
We have to have faith in their business model, financing and
executive group. You're not buying into a company when you accept
options; you're buying into the possibility of a company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We insist our costs are covered with cash, actual American
currency. ... But I am willing to take a certain percentage of
profit margin in stock option, taking a flier when it seems
right.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the option deals Leagas Delaney has entered into has
paid off _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because the companies are so young,'' Buechert said.
``It remains to be seen. But if it hits, the upside is tremendous.
Everyone in the industry knows about the Yahoo-and-Black-Rocket
story. Lurking in everyone's head is, if just one company with
options becomes a success, it makes all the risks worth taking.''
</P>
<P>
   Yost of Black Rocket says his agency has only accepted stock
options with one Internet client.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much uncertainty in it,'' Yost said. ``It's hard to
pick which will be the winners and losers. Sometimes, the most
interesting advertising clients are not necessarily the hottest
IPOs. But then, there are cases like Yahoo. We don't have any sour
feelings about not taking options with Yahoo. We're just delighted
to get the account. It's been a good partnership.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
