u s BC-OLY-REFORM-MEETING-NY     12-09 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-REFORM-MEETING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFORMS ARE ON IOC AGENDA, BUT BIG CHANGES ARE NOT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ Even if the International Olympic
Committee enacted all 50 of its proposed reforms at meetings here
this weekend, many Olympic observers do not expect the group to
change in more than an incremental way in the aftermath of the Salt
Lake City bidding scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The seriousness of the scandal, which was disclosed a year ago,
was underscored Thursday when Juan Antonio Samaranch, the IOC
president, said through a spokesman that he would agree to a
``voluntary interview'' with the U.S. Justice Department sometime
after he testifies before Congress in Washington on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, by agreeing to later questioning, Samaranch avoided
the embarrassment of being subpoenaed when he arrived in
Washington. The continuing Justice Department investigation has so
far resulted in two indictments related to a sham job arranged by
Salt Lake City bidders for the son of a prominent IOC member from
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   This will be an important weekend for Samaranch, who is certain
to face hostile questioning on Capitol Hill about IOC business
practices if he cannot show proof of significant reforms when he
appears next week before the House Commerce Subcommittee on
Oversight and Investigations, chaired by Rep. Fred Upton, the
Michigan Republican. The IOC is being threatened with a loss of its
tax-exempt status and the withholding of television rights fees
unless it enacts major reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be damaging if it falls apart,'' said Anita DeFrantz
of the United States, a vice president of the IOC. Speculation that
Samaranch would resign after this weekend's reform package was
pushed through has persisted, but he has said that he will fill out
his term, which ends next year.
</P>
<P>
   DeFrantz defended the IOC's reform movement, pointing to the
creation of an ethics commission and a worldwide doping agency, to
the opening of meetings to reporters and to the public issuance of
financial reports. ``We had a crisis and we took the opportunity to
make much-needed changes,'' DeFrantz said.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the IOC meets to consider reforms, however, questions
continue to be raised about how much DeFrantz knew about the
bidding practices in Salt Lake City and corruption within the IOC.
A copy of a report written by Salt Lake City bid officials after
they attended an IOC meeting in San Juan, Puerto Rico, from Aug. 25
to Sept. 1, 1989, stated that one of the officials, Bennie Smith,
had spoken with DeFrantz.
</P>
<P>
   ``She suggested we not base everything on what Ganga says,'' the
report said. ``Ganga is very political and he is the kind of guy
that wants to know how his hand will be greased. He is not
trustable.''
</P>
<P>
   The report was written a full decade before Jean-Claude Ganga of
the Congo Republic was removed from the IOC this year after
accepting more than $250,000 in illicit support from Salt Lake City
bid officials. One of those officials, Dave Johnson, has insisted
publicly that DeFrantz knew about the scholarship program and other
inducements, but she has vehemently denied it.
</P>
<P>
   She said she had no recollection of making such remarks to
Smith. ``I wouldn't have said that,'' she said. ``What nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the IOC proposals to be voted on this weekend are not
what they seem. For instance, term limits for its members are not
term limits at all. It is proposed that IOC members be limited to
eight-year terms, but those terms would be renewable by peer
election to the age of 80 for current members, and to 70 for
members elected in the future. Depending on how the 102 current
members vote, any future IOC president could remain in office for
up to 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Term limits that are infinitely renewable are not term
limits,'' said Jeff Benz, a San Francisco lawyer who served on the
panel headed by the former Sen. George Mitchell that investigated
the Salt Lake City bribery scandal. ``I am convinced they are only
willing to do the minimum necessary to get through the current
crisis and that the real proof will be in how they implement those
reforms they are considering.''
</P>
<P>
   There is the potential chance for fireworks among committee
members this weekend if a revolt occurs against the most
controversial proposal favored by Samaranch _ that members not be
allowed to visit cities bidding on the Winter and Summer Games. A
panel of experts would assess the bids, which would be put to a
vote by the membership.
</P>
<P>
   Salt Lake City officials plied visiting members and their
families with millions of dollars in cash payments, scholarships,
medical treatment, and shopping sprees in its effort to secure the
2002 Winter Games. Ten IOC members were removed or quit as the
scandal unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   Another part of the reform package to be voted on this weekend
concerns the issue of doping. The IOC has caused much skepticism
with its doping reform package. It is proposing to throw out of the
Olympics any sports that do not comply with worldwide testing and
punishment standards. However, sports such as soccer, tennis and
cycling have long ignored IOC guidelines. In recent weeks, the
track and field federations in Cuba and Jamaica have declined to
suspend athletes who have tested positive for cocaine and the
steroid nandralone.
</P>
<P>
   The World Anti-Doping Agency, which the IOC recently set up,
raised questions about its legitimacy with the appointment to its
board of Hein Zerbruggen, president of the International Cycling
Union, which has become one of the most discredited sports
federations in the wake of the Tour de France doping scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Yesalis, a Penn State professor who is an expert on
performance-enhancing drugs, said that if the IOC eliminated drug
use, sponsors and fans may not be interested in watching races in
which records were no longer being broken. Yesalis and many others
have criticized the IOC for being decades and tens of millions of
dollars behind in anti-doping research. The IOC's current proposals
are ``smoke and mirrors,'' Yesalis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminds me of putting wax on Lenin's body,'' Yesalis said.
``It's pretty well decayed.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 2150EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0368 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4661 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-SPACE-SETBACK-1     12-09 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-SPACE-SETBACK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN DROPS ROCKET PROJECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (CORRECTS rocket name to `H-2' sted `H-II' thruout) 
 (rk) 
 By CALVIN SIMS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ In the latest setback for the Japanese space program,
the space agency said Thursday that it would abandon its troubled
H-2 rocket project, the cornerstone of the program, after a series
of costly failures.
</P>
<P>
   The decision will delay the launchings of almost all Japanese
satellites for about a year and follows the failed launching last
month of the No. 8 H-2 rocket, which plunged into the Pacific
shortly after takeoff because of engine trouble. In developing the
rocket, Japan sought to free itself from the restrictions that came
with relying on the United States for rocket technology, and to
compete in the commercial satellite-launching market.
</P>
<P>
   But the National Space Development Agency said it would
immediately halt production of the No. 7 H-2 rocket, which is 90
percent complete at a cost of $160 million. The No. 7 rocket, which
despite its designation was the last in the H-2 series, had been
scheduled for launching with a communications satellite next year.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said it would focus on the next generation of rocket,
H-2A, which it said would benefit from past mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has invested $4.14 billion in the H-2 program, which
began in 1986, including $2.7 billion for development and $180
million for each launching.
</P>
<P>
   An aerospace analyst, Fujio Nakano, said the decision to shift
focus to the H-2A was a good idea. ``With the past H-2 launches,''
Nakano said, ``we have already accumulated much valuable
information that can be used in designing the new rocket model.
Considering that this is an investment toward the next-generation
rocket technology, 16 billion yen is a small loss.''
</P>
<P>
   That total equals $160 million.
</P>
<P>
   The credibility of the space effort was severely damaged on Nov.
15, when the No. 8 H-2 rocket, carrying a government satellite,
plunged into the ocean after the first-stage engine stopped firing.
That was the second H-2 rocket failure in two years.
</P>
<P>
   The lost rocket and satellite were valued at $340 million. The
agency has not determined the cause of the failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we are still investigating the accident, we decided,
considering the cost involved, that we should cancel the No. 7 H-2
and apply the savings and what we learn from the investigation to
ensuring a successful launching of the H-2A,'' said a spokesman for
the agency, Yasukuki Fukumuro.
</P>
<P>
   Fukumuro said the agency would save $30 million by devoting its
efforts solely to developing the H-2A, which he said has a more
advanced engine and more power than its predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   The agency had planned the initial H-2A launching for early next
year. But its debut will be delayed for a year to conduct
additional ground tests, the agency said. The postponement, along
with the cancellation of the No. 7 H-2, will push back the
launching of almost every satellite for at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said it planned to launch the first and second H-2A
rockets, which are scheduled to carry a European Space Agency
communications satellite and Japanese military satellite, in the
summer and winter of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Fukumuro said if the initial H-2A launchings were successful,
the agency hoped to transfer the technology to the private sector
to fulfill the long-term goal of launching commercial satellites.
To be competitive, the Japanese plan to offer customers steep
discounts on launchings and build a reputation for reliability.
</P>
<P>
   The highly competitive launching industry is dominated by three
major players, Boeing's Delta rockets and Lockheed Martin's Atlas
rockets, both from the United States, and Ariane rockets made by
Arianespace, the European consortium. Russia and China have small
parts of the market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
