<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEC BEGINS INQUIRY INTO TYCO'S ACCOUNTING
</P>
<P>
   Tyco International, a conglomerate that has grown rapidly
through acquisitions, said the Securities and Exchange Commission
had begun a ``nonpublic informal inquiry'' into its merger
accounting practices. The SEC is seeking all supporting documents
relating to charges and reserves taken by Tyco over the last six
years, a period in which it has made more than 120 acquisitions. L.
Dennis Kozlowski, the company's chairman and chief executive, said
the company welcomed the inquiry in light of the recent drop in its
stock price. The company's shares fell 24 percent in heavy trading.
</P>
<P>
   SALTON IN DEAL FOR FOREMAN'S NAME
</P>
<P>
   Salton, a maker of housewares, said that it would pay $137.5
million in cash and stock for the rights to use the name and image
of the former heavyweight boxer George Foreman to sell
food-preparation products. The company had been paying Foreman a
percentage of the profits on products bearing his name.
</P>
<P>
   GM SEEN BUYING 20 PERCENT OF FUJI
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to help its business at home while building its tiny
market share in Asia, General Motors is expected to announce that
it will pay $1.4 billion for 20 percent of Fuji Heavy Industries,
the Japanese maker of Subaru vehicles, people close to the talks
said.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ HAS RECORD-BREAKING DAY
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index rose 8.09 points, to 3,594.17, an
all-time high, as 1.76 billion shares changed hands, setting a
volume record. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 66.67, to
11,134.79, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 4.23, to
1,408.11.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ CONVERSION PLAN PROCEEDS
</P>
<P>
   The board of the National Association of Securities Dealers
agreed to a preliminary plan to convert the Nasdaq stock market to
a private for-profit company. Also, Nasdaq and Wall Street's
largest brokerage firms reached a preliminary agreement to provide
electronic trading of Big Board stocks.
</P>
<P>
   STRENGTH AT SEMICONDUCTOR MAKER
</P>
<P>
   National Semiconductor reported quarterly earnings that exceeded
analysts' estimates. The company, which got out of the PC
microprocessor business, benefited from strong sales of analog
devices, which are used in cell phones and consumer electronics
products. It was the second quarterly profit after a string of
losses. The company's shares closed up $5, or 11 percent, to $51.
</P>
<P>
   IRIDIUM GETS $20 MILLION IN FINANCING
</P>
<P>
   Iridium, the troubled global satellite telephone venture, said
that a group of investors led by Motorola had agreed to commit $20
million so that the company could continue operating through early
next year.
</P>
<P>
   QUICK, CALL THE WASHING MACHINE
</P>
<P>
   With the free-spending Christmas shopper as the target audience,
an Italian appliance maker put on sale the Margherita2000.com, a
washing machine that uses wireless telephone technology and a modem
to communicate with the manufacturer and the owner. In the future,
it will also be able to chat electronically with other appliances
around the house.
</P>
<P>
   BARNES &AMP; NOBLE AND IBM IN DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Barnes &AMP; Noble said it had struck an agreement with IBM to
provide print-on-demand equipment for its distribution centers,
which will allow the bookstore chain to quickly convert digital
books into conventional print versions one at a time. At the same
time, Random House said it was also preparing to invest in
state-of-the art equipment for its national distribution center.
</P>
</TEXT>
