A4664 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-WEISEL-WEISEL_SFCHRON     12-09 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEISEL-WEISEL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Weisel in Talks to Sell Stake _ $100 Million  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Thomas Weisel Partners, the San Francisco investment bank started a
year ago by the former chief executive of Montgomery Securities, is
in talks to sell a 10 percent stake to a major financial
institution for $100 million, people with knowledge of the matter
said.
<P>
   The investment by the unidentified partner would value the firm
at $1 billion, twice its initial worth and not far from the $1.3
billion Weisel got for Montgomery Securities, a firm it took him
nearly three decades to build before he sold it to North Carolina's
NationsBank in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Talks are said to be advanced, but no information was available
on when an agreement might be announced.
</P>
<P>
   The new investor has also agreed to put as much as $1 billion
into several private investment funds organized by Weisel Partners,
according to the online business news service TheStreet.com, which
first reported the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts called the $1 billion value for Weisel Partners, a firm
with $65 million in capital and projected 1999 revenue of $150
million, astronomical.
</P>
<P>
   The high price for the stake in Weisel Partners, which sells
securities for and provides merger advice to fast-growing companies
in technology and other sectors, reflects intense buyer demand for
securities firms that have a strong position in the superheated
Internet and technology initial-public-offering market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The price is mind-boggling,'' said Michael Flanagan, an
independent securities industry analyst based in the Philadelphia
area. ``Valuations are skyrocketing, reflecting the dearth of
investment banks`` with good technology franchises.
</P>
<P>
   Insiders will still control more than 80 percent of Weisel
Partners' equity after the deal and the firm intends to stay
independent, a person close to the firm said. A spokeswoman for the
firm declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Weisel Partners is one of the last remaining independent
investment banks in San Francisco. During a selling frenzy over the
past three years, almost all the city's home-grown firms were taken
over, including Montgomery, Robertson Stephens and Hambrecht &AMP;
Quist.
</P>
<P>
   Another independent San Francisco firm, Volpe Brown Whelan, is
reportedly near an agreement to sell out to Prudential Securities
for an undisclosed price.
</P>
<P>
   The $1 billion valuation of Weisel Partners is just under seven
times the firm's projected 1999 revenue. By contrast, Chase
Manhattan Corp. is paying $1.35 billion to buy Hambrecht &AMP; Quist,
about eight times revenue. But that price includes a premium for
taking control of the firm.
</P>
<P>
   In the nine months ended in September, Weisel Partners completed
51 public or private stock offerings and advised on six merger
deals, worth a total of $13.5 billion. It ranked 21st among
investment banks nationwide in public stock offerings.
</P>
<P>
   The firm started in January with $30 million in capital
contributed by partners and $35 million from outside investors. The
outside investors got a 7 percent stake, giving the firm an initial
value of $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
