director of the Center for Science in the Public Interest, in his
office earlier this month. ``Some companies are making outrageous
claims that probably don't provide any benefit other than to their
shareholders'' Jacobson said. More and more food and drug companies
are rolling out so-called functional foods, but the question
remains: are they worth it or are they rip-offs? (Jusitn Lane/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) MILWAUKEE -- Dec. 9, 1999 -- WELFARE-WORKERS -- Michael
Steinborn feeds his 16-month old son Christian as his partner Jai
Marin works in the kitchen. Lots of people consider themselves
experts on this city's war on welfare, but few have ridden its
highs and lows as intensely as Steinborn. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WORCESTER, Mass. -- Dec. 9, 1999 -- MASS-FIREFIGHTERS-7
-- The helmet, medal and U.S. flag of James Lyons on the stage
during a memorial service on Thursday for him and five of his
colleagues who were killed last Friday. The streets of this
grief-stricken city became a winding stream of mournful bagpipes,
as nearly 15,000 firefighters from near and far led a 3-mile long
