<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0373 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4666 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-BRADLEY-NYT &LR;      12-09 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BRADLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWLY AGGRESSIVE GORE FOLLOWS CLINTON MODEL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Texas, Fla., N.Y., N.H.)   (jw) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore tells audiences these days,
``I want to fight for you,'' and boy, does he mean it.
</P>
<P>
   He is fighting every day, around the clock and through the news
cycles, with his Democratic rival, former Sen. Bill Bradley. Gore
rips him in speeches, flames him on the Internet, denounces him in
editorial interviews, attacks him even in a little hand-drawn
chart, calling his health-care plan a budget-buster, warning that
he wants to scrap Medicaid and shouting that on top of it all,
Bradley will have to raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   This is partly the new Alpha Gore at work, sculpted by seasoned
campaign warriors like Bob Shrum and Carter Eskew. But it is also
the old Bill Clinton. It seems like centuries ago, but it was just
seven years back when the somewhat apolitical, seemingly morally
superior Paul Tsongas _ a figure not unlike Bradley _ was winning
plaudits as the low-key, authentic candidate, the one who was above
the fray, who appealed to independents and seemed like a refreshing
alternative to politics as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Until Clinton bared his claws.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton campaign did to Tsongas what Democrats usually do to
Republicans _ assert that he would undermine Medicare and cut
Social Security. That did it, especially with old people in
Florida, where the Clinton campaign unleashed its most blistering
criticisms. Tsongas hardly knew what hit him.
</P>
<P>
   Gore seems to have the Clinton playbook on his bedside table.
And like Tsongas, Bradley seems a little dazed by the relentless
assaults. The most he has been able to muster is that Gore is being
dishonest and is distorting his record. He is fighting back in his
own low-key way, but to some this is little more than a cry in the
woods reminiscent of that of another wounded candidate, Bob Dole,
who snapped in 1988 when the anchorman Tom Brokaw asked him if he
had anything to say to his rival, Vice President George Bush.
``Yeah,'' Dole growled into the camera. ``Stop lying about my
record!''
</P>
<P>
   What Tsongas and Dole have in common, of course, is that they
both lost. The Gore campaign is obviously hoping to consign Bradley
to the same fate. The question is whether Gore can villify Bradley
without alienating voters and coming across as a bully.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president is getting awfully, awfully close to the
edge of demagoguery,'' said Stephen Hess, a presidential scholar at
the Brookings Institution. ``As long as he's allowed to get away
with it, he'll be fine. But it's time for this to stop working.
Mean is out.'' This is evident on the Republican side, where the
front-runners, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., are all smiles to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hess acknowledges the exigencies of politics and the long
list of unsuccessful candidates who have failed to fight back. And
he said that Bradley might be taking an even greater risk by not
defending himself _ even if doing so undercuts his image as a
nonpolitician.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Bradley is sort of moseying around, and that's been
attractive, but now he's got to fight back,'' Hess said. He said
Bradley's so-far muted response suggested a campaign that was not
ready for prime time. ``There is still something a little
amateurish about the Bradley campaign, which has its charms, but
they better get some professionals.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley supporters are appalled by the turn of events. Clark
Rasmussen, who was the Clinton-Gore campaign director in Iowa in
1996 but now supports Bradley, summed up the frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Gore is doing on the health care, the Medicare-Medicaid
issue, is just abominable,'' Rasmussen said. ``And people see
through that. That's a core value for Democrats. To think that our
vice president would be attacking Bradley for coming out with such
a forward-looking health-care plan on such a core value is
incomprehensible to Iowans.''
</P>
<P>
   Those supporters see another risk in the Gore assault. If Gore
wins the nomination, the pounding could hurt his ability to attract
Bradley supporters.
</P>
<P>
   But to Gore advisers, the risks seem minimal and the benefits
tangible. Gore has halted his slide in the polls and is pulling
back even with Bradley in states like New Hampshire and New York,
where he was trailing. Pounding Bradley on his proposals, Gore
advisers say, is a way for Gore to distinguish himself from a
fellow Democrat with whom he is ideologically in sync and allows
him to assert himself.
</P>
<P>
   Some advisers were worried that Gore began his assault on
Bradley with an overly negative tone. In September, the vice
president started taking him on directly and accusing him of being
a bad Democrat for voting for the Reagan budget cuts and
``quitting'' the Senate with his retirement in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   That revved up Gore supporters but was viewed internally in the
Gore camp as too divisive. Now Gore has dropped that personal
reference. ``Everyone's very happy with this, as long as we stay on
the issues,'' said one.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, Gore's press secretary, justified Gore's approach
this way: ``These are serious issues, this is a presidential
campaign, and people want to know that you're going to fight for
them on issues they care about.'' Lehane added that Bradley's
laid-back approach raised a serious question about him. ``If you
are not willing to fight for your ideas in a campaign,'' he asked,
``when will you?''
</P>
<P>
   James Carville, the architect of Clinton's successful 1992
strategy, sneers at those who question Gore's approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must be on a different planet than everyone else,'' Carville
said, ``but why would you put out a comprehensive plan and not
expect it to be the topic of discussion or attack? That's politics.
That's discourse. The real risk in a democracy is to let people do
something and then just accept it on its face.''
</P>
<P>
   Carville dismissed any notion that Gore might be coming across
as too negative. ``This is all wimpy, press, editorial goof-ball
mush,'' he said. ``I'm nauseated with the sort of goo-goo pristine
idea that you can't question someone's proposals.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's combativeness has been evident in the past, as in his
debates with Dan Quayle, Ross Perot and Jack Kemp, and he is not
uncomfortable in this mode. After all, he was the candidate who in
1988 first raised the issue of prison furloughs in Massachusetts,
laying the groundwork for Vice President Bush to seize on the image
of Willie Horton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
