s f BC-BIZ-PROFILE-ROBINSON-     12-09 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-ROBINSON-ART-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVANCING ON A GLOBAL POWER GRID  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 12) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore.)   (Eds: Please note a correction on last week's profile at end of
this article)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Ian Robinson, the chief executive of Scottish Power
PLC, likes to tell how a young man from a modest background _
himself _ discovered the world's widest horizons.
</P>
<P>
   As an engineering graduate in his early 20s, he was offered a
job in the copper mines of Zambia, then the British colony of
Northern Rhodesia. The son of a railroad worker from northeastern
England, he had never flown before.
</P>
<P>
   When his airplane developed engine trouble over Uganda, he was
grounded for three days until a replacement engine arrived from
London. He spent those days in a swank hotel on Lake Victoria,
partying with the flight crew until the plane was repaired.
</P>
<P>
   The tyro engineer and the reveler, may be difficult to discern
in the solid, silver-haired executive who is now 57 . But the
appetite for new horizons seems undiminished. He has built his
company into Britain's biggest power and water utility and is
leading a charge into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 30, Scottish Power completed the $6.5 billion
acquisition of PacifiCorp, based in Portland, Ore., the first
British acquisition of an American utility.
</P>
<P>
   Since arriving at Scottish Power in 1995 as chief executive, he
has built its customer base from 1.8 million to 7.5 million _
including the 2 million American customers of PacifiCorp. In
Britain, he has added gas, water and telecommunications companies
to the corporate portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   But after mining the deregulation of British utilities for
growth, he sees the United States _ with its fragmented utility
business also going through deregulation _ as ripe for similar
alchemy.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, he sees the world's utilities market as headed for
consolidation into just a handful of global players. ``Scottish
Power has to be one of them,'' he said at the company's new London
offices.
</P>
<P>
   So why focus on the United States when Europe's new single
market is on his doorstep?
</P>
<P>
   ``Europe is way behind in the process of deregulating power and
other utilities,'' he said. ``So we think that the U.S. has a lot
of potential for us.''
</P>
<P>
   When he talks about the United States, he speaks from
experience. He lived there for four years among the 22 he spent
working for American engineering companies. In 1986, he became a
managing director of John Brown Ltd., a British engineering
company. He rose to become chairman in 1992 of the engineering
division of its parent company, Trafalgar House PLC, controlling
projects in more than 80 countries.
</P>
<P>
   He lives in Glasgow, where the company is based, with his wife,
Kay; they raised two childeren there. He travels extensively.
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts say Robinson has been able to court political
leaders and pursue expansion because he has granted substantial
day-to-day authority to talented aides.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of utilities in Britain are characterized by having a
very strong individual at the top,'' said Simon Flowers, an analyst
at Merrill Lynch in Edinburgh. ``What Ian Robinson has created is a
really strong team.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson expects to travel more than ever to rally his forces.
``I regard myself as the leader of the team and part of my job is
to ensure that we get the best out of the team when we work
together.''
</P>
<P>
   He also has a penchant for cultivating his political connections
face to face. The night in late November when he received word of
approval of the PacifiCorp deal by Utah regulatory authorities, he
had dinner with Scottish members of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson may cast himself as an exemplar of the market-driven
1990s, but Scottish Power is itself protected from predators by a
so-called golden share _ in effect, the power to veto a takeover _
held by the Scottish authorities. He has cemented his ties to the
government of Prime Minister Tony Blair by running its high-profile
welfare-to-work program for young people.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of restructuring _ and the downsizing that comes with
it _ political connections provide useful protection against
criticism of job losses. Robinson freely acknowledges that, as it
has expanded with acquisitions, Scottish Power has shed some 5,000
jobs. But he sees that as a price of efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The company says 3,000 other jobs have been created, largely by
a telecommunications subsidiary called Thus PLC, which had its own
initial public offering last month. With the PacifiCorp merger, the
company now employs 24,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, clearly proud of Scottish Power's success, recently
provided a diary of a typical week to a British newspaper. He
listed a 60- or 70-hour routine. And he often works weekends,
leaving not enough time for golf. (His handicap is 15.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the job, and have a passion for the job,'' he said.
It's a passion that Americans will be seeing a lot more closely.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A profile last Sunday about Paul Sagan, president of Akamai
Technologies, misstated the year that a former colleague, Peter
Landis, began working with him at New York 1, the cable news
station. It was 1995, not 1991; Landis did not take part in
starting the station.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
