CANDIDATES-ECON-PUNDITS -- Lawrence B. Lindsey, of the American
Enterprise Institute, in his office during an interview last week.
Lindsey, a former Federal Reserve governor, is now George W. Bush's
chief economic adviser. Lindsey sees himself as a mere technician,
helping to turn the Republican presidential candidate's vision into
nuts-and-bolts programs. (Shana Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Dec. 9, 1999 - OPENING-NIGHT -- Brian Stokes
Mitchell greets Betty Comden at the opening night party for ``Kiss
Me, Kate'' earlier this week. Opening night on Broadway isn't what
it used to be. The critics no longer come all at once to that first
official performance, running up the aisles as the curtain falls to
rush back to their typewriters and tap out reviews for tomorrow's
papers. Where once the invitations were engraved by Tiffany's and
everyone came in black tie without being asked, the evenings have
grown more casual, with few calling for formal attire. (Sara
Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- Dec. 9, 1999 - ADV. FOR SUN, DEC. 12 -
FOODS-TASTE - Some of the nutrional products, known as functional
foods, made by Novartis. More and more food and drug companies are
rolling out so-called functional foods, but the question remains:
are they worth it or are they rip-offs? (Richard Perry/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
