in the line of duty last Friday. Thousands of firefighters and
citizens led by President Clinton mourned the loss of the six men
who died battling a warehouse blaze that still smoldered eerily on
Thursday. (Bill Greene/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WORCESTER, Mass. -- Dec. 9, 1999 -- MASS-FIREFIGHTERS-4
--Firefighters from across the world march under a U.S. flag on
Thursday during a memorial march for six firefighters killed in
Worcester. The six firefighters were killed Friday after two became
lost in a burning warehouse looking for homeless people and the
other four went in to save them. (Jim Davis/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WORCESTER, Mass. -- Dec. 9, 1999 -- MASS-FIREFIGHTERS-3
--President Clinton during a memorial on Thursday for six
firefighters killed last Friday. Clinton urged Americans to
remember their own public servants as thousands gathered for the
memorial service for the firefighters who perished in the line of
duty. On Clinton's lapel is a pin bearing the portraits of the
fallen firefighters. (David L. Ryan/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WORCESTER, Mass. -- Dec. 9, 1999 -- MASS-FIREFIGHTERS-2
--Firefighters from across the world march under a U.S. flag during
a memorial march for six firefighters killed in Worcester on
Thursday. President urged Americans to remember their own public
servants as thousands gathered for a memorial service for the
firefighters who perished in the line of duty. (Bill Greene/The
