</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ATLANTA -- Dec. 9, 1999 -- BUYER'S-EDGE-COX -- Margie
Perry wraps a Christmas gift at Rich's at Greenbriar Mall earlier
this week. The professional wrapper has been wrapping gifts at
Rich's for 26 years, and last year she won a $500 consolation prize
in the 3M Scotch Tape wrapping contest in New York. (Jean
Shifrin/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ATLANTA -- Dec. 9, 1999 -- KING-FAMILY-COX -- Coretta
Scott King, center, wife of slain civil rights leader Martin Luther
King Jr., and her son Dexter King, are interviewed by Leon Harris
on Cable News Network on Thursday. Mrs. King said that a Memphis
jury's verdict that a conspiracy led to the death of her husband
was ``a great victory for America.'' (John Spink/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Dec. 9, 1999 -- OBIT-GREENFIELD -- Margaret
A. Greenfield, a founder and officer of the Independent Journalism
Foundation and a dealer in art, antiques and real estate, died
Wednesday at her home in Manhattan. The foundation, which she
started with her husband, James L. Greenfield, and Donald M.
Wilson, a former vice president of Time Inc., teaches citizens of
former Communist countries in Central and Eastern Europe about
working as journalists in newly democratic societies. Mrs.
Greenfield, who was 74, died of cancer. (File Photo, Undated/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- Dec. 9, 1999 -- OBIT-KRATTER -- Marvin
Kratter, the New York real estate investor whose holdings once
included the home of the Brooklyn Dodgers and Ebbets Field. His
wide-ranging business interests also included ownership or part
ownership of the Boston Celtics basketball team, a brewery and a
pharmaceutical company. Kratter died of pancreatitis on Oct. 24 at
a hospital in Encinitas, Calif. He was 84. (File Photo, 1963/The
New York Times)
</P>
