<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4672 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BIBLE-SCHOOLS09-COX     12-09 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIBLE-SCHOOLS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Changes deflate Florida county's Bible course
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ As a high school elective here, the Bible
just can't compete with home economics or shop.
</P>
<P>
   Brought forward by Christian activists, a controversial Bible
class similar to the one that will be debated today by the Georgia
Board of Education was offered in January 1998. More than 150
students enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   But the day before the class started, a federal court blocked
Lee County's original proposal.
</P>
<P>
   What's left in this Gulf Coast community is a course based on a
college textbook written by a Stetson University professor.
</P>
<P>
   The case remains the legal watermark for districts that want to
incorporate Bible courses into their curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   But just 23 months after all eight of Lee County's public high
schools offered the class, no one is teaching it.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? Not enough students signed up.
</P>
<P>
   Some seniors don't want to risk their grade-point averages by
taking a college-level course, which the Bible class is, said
Douglas Whittaker, executive director of curriculum for the Lee
County school district.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're saying is, `I'm going to take ceramics,'''
Whittaker said. ``This wasn't a Sunday school class. This was a
rigorous academic class.''
</P>
<P>
   But even more critical in the enrollment drop-off has been the
court-mandated recording of the courses. Watchdog groups monitor
the video and audio tapes, making sure instructors don't stray into
proselytizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students were just very uncomfortable taking a class that was
under glass like that,'' said Mike McNerney, principal at Mariner
High School, the last school in the county that taught Introduction
to the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the course really ever had a chance because it
was political in nature,'' McNerney said, ``and that spelled defeat
from the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, Board of Education member Bruce Jackson has said
state School Superintendent Linda Schrenko and others gain
political capital from the Bible proposal, ``whether we approve it
or not.''
</P>
<P>
   At Lehigh Senior High, across the county in this southwest
Florida community, Principal Pete Folaros said the history
instructor who volunteered to teach the class felt apprehensive
because of community scrutiny. Reached Wednesday, the teacher
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought he might face personal damages,'' Folaros said.
``Even though the district would go to bat for him'' there was no
guarantee a teacher might not become the subject of a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The issue first surfaced in 1996 when a citizens group asked for
a high school Bible course. The five-member school board approved
the idea 3-2, creating a committee to design a legally acceptable
Bible class.
</P>
<P>
   The committee met for 1 1/2 years but fractured into two groups:
a minority that favored a secular presentation of biblical events
and a majority that advocated material from the North
Carolina-based National Council on Bible Curriculum in Public
Schools.
</P>
<P>
   Local Christian activists supported the North Carolina material.
</P>
<P>
   However, U.S. District Judge Elizabeth Kovachevic barred the
group's New Testament course because it might violate
constitutional bans against teaching religion in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Kovachevic, in her ruling, expressed constitutional reservations
over the presentation of Christ's resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   According to the judge, ``the only reasonable interpretation of
the Resurrection is a religious interpretation.''
</P>
<P>
   School districts debating Bible courses should tread cautiously
in light of what's happened in Fort Myers, advised Whittaker, the
Lee County curriculum chief.
</P>
<P>
   Kovachevic ``is very conservative and tends to align herself
with the political right _ and she found that curriculum
untenable,'' Whittaker said. ``You're probably going to end up in
court if you choose to use it. It's a prescription for failure.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, two years after the debate started, Bible class
opponents spent $14,000 on election advertising and voted out two
school board members who supported the North Carolina curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves just one school board member who favors the more
evangelical course.
</P>
<P>
   Self-described Christian conservative Lanny Moore, a member of
the committee that recommended the original class material, was
elected to the Lee County school board after it approved the idea
of a Bible course.
</P>
<P>
   Moore said most of the committee's time was spent arguing over
whether a class should be taught at all. He's distressed the North
Carolina curriculum was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any vestiges of the Christian influence basically has been
expunged from the social studies and history classes in our
district,'' Moore said. ``If you can't teach history as it happened
in an academic setting, where can you teach it? You can't teach
Christianity, and you can't allude to it. Where's your academic
freedom?''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Wayne Robinson, whose Unitarian Universalist Church of
Fort Myers was a primary opponent of the course, argued that the
material originally proposed was little more than an extended
Sunday school class.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debate in the media made it seem like an issue of faith,''
Robinson said. ``I really think it was misunderstanding of our
Constitution. ... We respect all religions and minorities. But
we're not to establish a religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
