u a BC-NTSB-CHALLENGES-NYT &LR;      12-09 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NTSB-CHALLENGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSPORTATION BOARD HURT BY `SERIOUS OVERLOAD,' STUDY FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD    
 c. 1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The National Transportation Safety Board is facing
increasing doubt, from inside its ranks and from outside aviation
experts, about its ability to investigate complex aviation
accidents as it attempts to re-structure itself and cope with a
variety of high-stakes investigations.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report released Thursday by Rand Corp., requested
by the safety board officials last year, the board is ``coping with
serious overload.'' Rand researchers reported having ``encountered
a consistent uneasiness regarding the ability of the NTSB to
generate timely, accurate results.'' And among the staff and board
members, aviation veterans are raising questions about the quality
of the board's work.
</P>
<P>
   Two principal authors of the $400,000 study declined to identify
specific cases. But within the five-member board and among its
staff, there is dissatisfaction with, for example, the
investigation into a fire on board a Federal Express DC-10 flying
from Boston to Memphis in September 1996. The plane made an
emergency landing in Newburgh, N.Y., and the five crew members
barely escaped with their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The safety board found evidence that a bio-medical device on
board had been improperly carrying a flammable fluid, and some of
the investigators thought that was the cause of the fire. But the
board decided there was insufficient evidence to isolate that
device as the probable cause of the accident, which destroyed a
$30-million aircraft, partly because the staff could not say how
much of the liquid was present before the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't nail the facts down,'' said one board member, who
asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that the time needed to complete major
investigations was ``climbing alarmingly.'' The September 1994
crash near Pittsburgh of a Boeing 737 operated by USAir, which
killed all 132 people on board, took more than four years to study.
The explosion of TWA Flight 800 off Long Island in July 1996 is
still under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The report comes as the board restructures itself, struggling
over who should release information on accidents _ and when _ and
over its public image.
</P>
<P>
   In October, without meeting, the board quietly approved a new
order on media relations that bars a board member from staying at
the scene of a crash for more than five days without the permission
of the board chairman. Board members say the vote was a reaction to
the TWA 800 crash, in which Robert T. Francis, the vice chairman,
stayed on Long Island for weeks, appearing at joint briefings with
the FBI and the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman, James E. Hall, has also broken the regular pattern
of sending board members to accidents according to a rotation
system; for the crash of John F. Kennedy Jr.'s plane and the
Egyptair 990 crash, he went himself, although it was not his turn
to go.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Hall has instituted stricter controls on travel,
following inquiries about travel expenses by members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The various changes have produced some resentment within the
board.
</P>
<P>
   The board is also struggling with the flow of information.
Long-time board officials say they are stunned at the growing
intensity of media interest after high-profile crashes, from that
of TWA 800 to those of Kennedy's single-engine plane in July and
Egyptair in October.
</P>
<P>
   The Rand study released Thursday also called for changes in the
``party'' system, in which the board works with groups like the
airline, the airplane and engine manufacturers and the pilots'
union during investigations. The study said that the system was
prone to the appearance of conflict of interest problems.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
