<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-EWING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING READY TO START, BUT HE'S NOT EXACTLY SMILING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ A glowering Patrick Ewing stepped out of a side
door to the gym Thursday and made a direct line to a driver waiting
for him in a Lincoln Navigator, never breaking his loping gait to
confirm an end to the drama. Moments earlier, Coach Jeff Van Gundy
had announced that Ewing would start Friday night against
Philadelphia at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   It will mark the first playing time for Ewing since he partially
tore his Achilles' tendon on June 1, during Game 2 of the Eastern
Conference finals. Instead of expressing relief that his long wait
was over, Ewing profanely declined to comment on his return as he
left the team's practice facility at SUNY-Purchase.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Ewing was fined $10,000 by the National Basketball
Association for refusing to grant the news media accessibility this
week. This afternoon, the team fined him (the amount was believed
to be $10,000) for failing to make himself available after practice
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The penalties probably serve only to further irritate Ewing.
This season, he has been reclusive in a locker room full of
teammates who do not treat him with reverence, angry at an
organization that has provided him with a $68 million deal while
trading or cutting his friends, and upset at how his Achilles'
tendon partially tore when team physicians assured him it would
not.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the ways Ewing's edginess has manifested itself, members
of the organization and teammates believe he has been wrestling
with the reality of being on the decline as a superstar. In
October, Ewing began training camp by saying that he would not
return ``until I feel that the pain is gone, and I can play the way
I'm accustomed to playing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't be me if I'm playing hurt,'' he said. ``When I can't
be me, I'm going to retire.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Ewing expects instant results. His coach and teammates
understand that he has missed 88 regular-season games over the last
three seasons and do not expect a miracle performance from him
against Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect him to get better over time,'' Van Gundy said
Thursday. ``I expect him to probably struggle for a couple of
weeks. The big thing is, I want him to enjoy these last X-amount of
years he has to play. I'm concerned with that. He has had a great,
great career. He's won a lot of games and helped two teams get to
the finals. He's a top-50 player and Hall of Famer. I just want him
to enjoy the last two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Larry Johnson could be Ewing's example. As Johnson has
experienced, there comes a time when helping the team win is just
as enjoyable as being able to carry it. Not to the extent of Ewing,
but Johnson was once an All-Star go-to man before injuries limited
his impact in the box score.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, I just put all that stuff out of my mind and said
`Win,''' Johnson said. ``It was so sweet last year. Everyone has a
role, and what you do is understand your role, accept your role and
enjoy playing your role. There's a difference in accepting your
role and playing your role. When you enjoy it, and you win ... How
can you not have fun winning?''
</P>
<P>
   A lot depends on how Ewing adjusts to Latrell Sprewell and Allan
Houston, how they adjust to him and how other players respond to
having their minutes decreased. Instead of answering questions
surrounding the date of Ewing's return, others will pop up in their
place for Van Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   None of the Knicks knew about Ewing's decision to return. He
told only Van Gundy after practice and never said a word to his
teammates. For more than two weeks, Ewing has practiced without
pain but had given no indication when he would be ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing the TNT commentator John Thompson, Ewing's former
coach at Georgetown, announce before a television audience
Wednesday night that a ``little bird'' told him the Knicks' center
would be back on Friday, Van Gundy approached Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked Patrick about that before practice,'' Van Gundy said
Thursday, referring to Thompson's comments. ``He said he hadn't
made up his mind. But after practice, I talked to him and he said
he is going to play tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an uncomfortable position for Van Gundy, knowing that
Ewing had apparently let Thompson in on his plans first. ``I'm more
happy that he's back than disappointed in the other,'' Van Gundy
said.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy embraces the chance to have Ewing on the floor again,
in whatever capacity. The team is woeful in rebounding, ranked 25th
in the league. And they have not had a consistent low-post threat
all season.
</P>
<P>
   Although the team is finally healthy and intact, Van Gundy is
not expecting Ewing's impact to be the cure-all for a team with a
so-so record of 11-9.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick may not be able to add anything tomorrow,'' Van Gundy
said. ``I don't know. You put your best players out there when
they're coming back, you let them play, you see what they can do
and go from there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
