<SLUG> BC-TEN-MEN-CHANGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATP OVERHAULS TOP EVENTS AND RANKING SYSTEM
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATP Tour officials announced a marketing makeover Thursday that
they believe will offer a bolder and more structured look to men's
tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted fans to know more than just four times a year that
something important in tennis is happening,'' said Mark Miles, the
ATP Tour's chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   The ATP has repackaged the Super 9, its nine premier
tournaments, into the Tennis Masters Series, which features four
tournaments in North America, five in Europe and concludes with the
season-ending Tennis Masters Cup, formerly the Grand Slam Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The tour has created a new ranking system for 18 tournaments _
the ATP Champions Race 2000 _ which starts with each player having
zero points at the start of each year. The ranking replaces a
hard-to-follow system in which points were constantly rolled over
on a 52-week cycle. Miles said the system is designed to encourage
the best players to enter more tournaments and to build up
rivalries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public is totally baffled by our current ranking system,''
Miles said. ``Pete Sampras can beat Andre Agassi in the final of
Wimbledon, and at the conclusion of the match have Andre Agassi
pass him to be the No. 1 player on the board. That won't happen
with the race.''
</P>
<P>
   The ATP has sold the television, sponsorship and licensing
rights to the nine Tennis Masters tournaments and the Tennis
Masters Cup to ISL Worldwide, a global marketing firm, for $1.2
billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tennis has always suffered from fragmentation in the
marketplace,'' Miles said. ``Each tournament sold its own
television, sponsorships and licensing. Now we'll control
production and distribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the arrangement, Miles said, ISL Television will spend
three times as much as the networks have spent on producing the
tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   The ATP is also paring from 212 to 15 the number of sponsors of
the Masters Series and Masters Cup. Now, Miles said, the smaller,
centralized group of sponsors ``will have an interest in promoting
the series.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
