<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TYCO-SEC-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYCO STOCK FALLS 23 PERCENT AFTER COMPANY DISCLOSES SEC INQUIRY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tyco International's stock price fell 23 percent Thursday,
trading at its lowest price in more than a year after the company
disclosed that the Securities and Exchange Commission is looking
into Tyco's merger accounting practices.
</P>
<P>
   Tyco said that the SEC staff had begun a ``non-public informal
inquiry'' related to charges and reserves taken in connection with
acquisitions made by Tyco, a conglomerate that has grown rapidly
through mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In light of the recent market activity in our stock, which is
not justified by any development at the company, we welcome the
opportunity to respond to this request,'' said L. Dennis Kozlowski,
the chairman and chief executive of Tyco. ``We remain confident of
our accounting methodology, our public disclosures and the
continuing strength of our business.''
</P>
<P>
   A Tyco spokesman, J. Brad McGee, said that the SEC had sought
all supporting documents relating to charges and reserves taken by
Tyco during the last six years. During that time, it made more than
120 acquisitions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tyco shares fell $8.25, to $28 in New York Stock Exchange
trading, on volume of 114 million shares, the largest daily volume
in the company's history. Thursday's low of $22.50 was the lowest
price for the stock since October 1998 and was less than half the
prices realized in July when Kozlowski raised $170 million by
selling shares and Mark Swartz, the company's chief financial
officer, sold $108 million of his shares.
</P>
<P>
   Tyco's stock price peaked Oct. 8 at $53.875, adjusted for a
subsequent split, but fell after the company's accounting was
criticized by David W. Tice, an analyst and money manager whose
newsletter, ``Behind The Numbers,'' is followed by many
institutional investors. Tice said that the large charges Tyco had
taken after it made takeovers had inflated later reported profits.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 29, a column in The New York Times reported that two
companies acquired by Tyco had taken big writeoffs just before
being acquired, making later comparisons look better than they
would have otherwise been. The column said that Tyco had not fully
disclosed those writeoffs in filings with the SEC, though Swartz
said that the information had been provided to analysts who
requested it.
</P>
<P>
   The company said that all the criticisms were unfounded, and
emphasized that the SEC had not challenged its accounting when it
reviewed filings made in connection with numerous deals.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's Tyco announcement indicated that while the SEC was
seeking a vast amount of information, it had not begun a formal
investigation. An SEC spokesman declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Tyco employees Thursday, which the company
released, Kozlowski said that ``Tyco will emerge from this episode
even stronger than before,'' he wrote. ``All things considered,
this is very exciting time for Tyco and I am confident in our
future.''
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the October criticisms of the company's
accounting, the share price fell to as low as $35. It then rallied,
as many Wall Street analysts said the company's accounting was
proper and recommended the stock. It climbed back to more than $45
before beginning to slip during the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, with the share price again around $35, Kozlowski
issued a statement saying that Tyco ``remained on target to meet
expectations for the quarter and year for sales, earnings and cash
flow.'' McGee said that the company received the SEC's request for
information on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Tyco retains considerable support on Wall Street. Phua Young, an
analyst at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., issued a report Thursday
reaffirming his buy rating on Tyco. ``While this investigation puts
a further cloud on the stock,'' Young wrote, ``we believe that the
company will receive a clean bill of health from the SEC regarding
its accounting policies, which could put an end to all the rumors
and accusations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
