<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0390 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4690 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DUTCH-PHONE-DEAL-NYT &LR;      12-09 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUTCH-PHONE-DEAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELLSOUTH JOINS WITH DUTCH IN $20 BILLION GERMAN WIRELESS DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)   (af)  
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ BellSouth Corp. upset the chessboard of
European mobile communications Thursday, teaming up with the Dutch
phone company KPN to take control of E-Plus Mobilfunk, Germany's
third-largest wireless telephone network, in a transaction worth
nearly $20 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Under the unusual deal, BellSouth will not put up any of its own
cash. Instead, it will exercise options to buy full control of
E-Plus Mobilfunk but transfer the shares to KPN, which will put up
about $10 billion in financing.
</P>
<P>
   As envisioned, BellSouth will retain its 22 percent stake in
E-Plus but will get half the seats on its board and have veto
rights over significant decisions, including on any future mergers
or partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth will also have the option to convert its E-Plus stake
after 18 months into a 19-percent stake in KPN. At the Dutch
company's current market price, such a stake would be worth about
$6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, BellSouth said it would lend KPN $3 billion for
additional wireless investments in Europe in exchange for
additional warrants for KPN shares.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is a financial coup for the Atlanta-based BellSouth,
because its stake in E-Plus is likely to be worth more as a result
of its expanded control. It is also a victory for KPN, giving it a
key position in Germany, the largest economy in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   F. Duane Ackerman, BellSouth's chairman and chief executive,
said, ``We think we've got a good partner, a nimble partner, and we
get to preserve options for ourselves about what we might want to
do in Europe in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   But the plan was a significant setback for France Telecom, which
thought it had reached its own deal to pay $9 billion or so for
more than 60 percent of the stock in E-Plus being sold by Vodafone
AirTouch of Britain and two German utility giants, Veba and RWE.
France Telecom's shares have dropped more than 7 percent since
rumors of a BellSouth move appeared on Tuesday in The Financial
Times.
</P>
<P>
   France Telecom had hoped to use E-Plus as a staging area for
competing against Deutsche Telekom AG, Germany's dominant phone
carrier. The French and German phone companies broke up a
longstanding partnership earlier this year, after Deutsche Telekom
infuriated the French by making a surprise bid for Telecom Italia.
</P>
<P>
   But although France Telecom reached agreements to buy out the
E-Plus stakes held by Vodafone, Veba and RWE, BellSouth retained
rights of first refusal on those same shares, which means it had
the right to purchase them before they could be offered for sale to
others. BellSouth was one of the founding partners in E-Plus in
1993, paying about $150 million for its 22 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   The deal negotiated Thursday underlined the enormous gambles
taking place in Europe's booming mobile communications industry.
The biggest competitors are all scrambling to build pan-European
wireless networks, spending the equivalent of tens of billions of
dollars to acquire businesses in such large markets as Britain,
Germany and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone is in the midst of a hostile takeover attempt against
Mannesmann AG, which controls wireless networks in Germany, Italy
and now Britain. The value of that deal has steadily risen with the
ascent in Vodafone's shares and is now worth an estimated $147
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom recently spent $11 billion to buy Britain's
smallest mobile phone company, One 2 One, and it remains on the
prowl for other international acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   In Amsterdam Thursday, speculation about a possible deal drove
shares of KPN up 8.9 percent to a record high of 68.15 euros, or
$69.62. KPN's American depository receipts, each representing one
common share, rose $4.50, or 7 percent, to $68.875. BellSouth
gained $1.21 in New York, closing at $47.25.
</P>
<P>
   KPN, once a government-owned monopoly, is now majority-owned by
shareholders and its stock is traded on the Amsterdam, New York,
London and Frankfurt exchanges. The Dutch government still owns 43
percent.
</P>
<P>
   KPN has about 3.2 million subscribers in the Netherlands, or 54
percent of the market. E-Plus has about 3.1 million subscribers, or
16 percent of the much larger German market. E-Plus is the youngest
of the three German wireless telephone networks, and has grown
rapidly since it began offering service less than four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Germany, with a population of more than 80 million, is poised
for continued rapid growth in mobile phone services. Though the
share of adults with cellular phones has climbed to 25 percent from
17 percent in the last year, mobile cellular phones use is still
less pervasive than in several Nordic countries and in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the merger impulse in the mobile phone business has been
driven by an effort by the companies to spread their costs over a
broader base of customers. By establishing cross-border networks,
providers can lower or even eliminate the ``roaming'' charges they
impose on customers from other countries _ a potentially big
marketing advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The European companies are also spending heavily on advanced
wireless-data technologies, which make it possible to tap into the
Internet over mobile devices and transmit data faster than over
ordinary fixed telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone was forced to sell its stake in E-Plus after it
acquired AirTouch Communications of San Francisco in January.
AirTouch had a big minority stake in Mannesmann's D2 mobile
network, and Vodafone would be prohibited from owning stakes in two
rival networks. Veba and RWE are in the midst of big mergers with
other power companies, and eager to solidify their resources on
those markets.
</P>
<P>
   The KPN deal for E-Plus is likely to intensify this urge to
merge among European telecommunications companies, particularly in
mobile communications.
</P>
<P>
   France Telecom is now in the position of having to look again
for paths to expansion, though officials refused to comment
Thursday night on BellSouth's deal with KPN. When the French phone
company announced its plan to take control of E-Plus, executives
characterized the move as merely the first of many steps to roll
out a broad array of telecommunication services across Europe.
</P>
<P>
   By any measure, those plans have now been delayed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
