<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4708 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-COKE-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      12-09 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW COCA-COLA CHIEF SAYS HE PLANS NO ABRUPT CHANGE
</HEADLINE>
   (With COCACOLA-NORRIS-COLUMN) 
(rk) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three days after his surprising selection as the next chairman
and chief executive of Coca-Cola, Douglas N. Daft got on the
telephone with reporters Thursday and talked about, among other
things, his feelings upon being asked to lead the soft-drink giant.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've tended to range from shock to surprise to sorrow to
elation,'' Daft said. And then there is pride, he added, ``pride in
the company and pride in being asked to take this position.''
</P>
<P>
   The overtures to reporters and the discussion of his emotional
life are two signs of the difference between Daft's style and that
of his predecessor, M. Douglas Ivester, who stunned the business
world by announcing on Monday that he would step down.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems that Coca-Cola will not operate so differently
under Daft. His mentors, he said, were Roberto C. Goizueta, the
chairman and chief executive who died in 1997, Ivester and Donald
R. Keough, the former president who now works for Allen &AMP; Co., the
investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   He stands by the large price increases Coke recently instituted
for the concentrate it sells to bottlers in the United States, even
though many of them are irked. And he said he was committed to
increasing the number of cases sold by 7 percent to 8 percent and
earnings growth by 15 percent to 20 percent, even though many on
Wall Street doubt the company can pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   The company whose corner office he will inhabit is tarnished
from a year of unprecedented regulatory difficulties, a racial
discrimination lawsuit filed by four current and former employees
and the biggest product recall in its history. The share price has
fallen 7 percent this year, and earnings have disappointed for the
last six quarters. Coca-Cola earns 75 percent of its profits
overseas; many of those markets have been gripped by recession or
monetary crises for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have said we are in a period of readjustment,'' Daft said.
``The October and November results were ahead of the third quarter;
2000 is the year of the recovery for the world, and obviously our
business will be part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts question whether Coca-Cola can grow at twice the
industry average. ``We've advised investors to wait out this period
of uncertainty, and we're waiting to get comfortable that Doug Daft
is not just going to keep the status quo,'' said Bill Pecoriello, a
beverage analyst for Sanford C. Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   The issues facing Coca-Cola, he said, include figuring out how
to make the global bottler system profitable after a long period of
consolidation, as well as how to successfully sell Coke in regions
like Latin America, Eastern Europe and parts of Asia where cheaper
brands have chipped away at Coca-Cola's market share. And Coca-Cola
might be better off lowering expectations, which would affect share
price in the short term but redefine what growth means at the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester was known as a brilliant tactician who preached an
aggressive growth plan and once made a speech before an industry
group in which he compared Coca-Cola to a wolf among sheep and
declared he wanted the entire soft-drink market, not just a share
of it. Part of his strategy included urging bottlers to consolidate
and exhorting ``anchor bottlers,'' the biggest, to invest heavily
in vending machines, production facilities and other equipment.
</P>
<P>
   In many parts of the world, Coke's big bottlers have poor
returns on their invested capital because local fiscal crises have
cut demand for pricier American soft drinks. The bottlers in
trouble include Coca-Cola Beverages, based in London and operating
in Eastern Europe and Italy; Coca-Cola Amatil, based in Sydney and
operating in much of the Far East, and Pan American Beverages,
known as Panamco, which paid close to $1 billion for a bottling
company in Venezuela, soon before a major economic downturn there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to make the bottler network sustainable,''
Pecoriello said. ``It can't be the Coca-Cola Company winning at the
expense of its bottlers.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he needed to mend fences with bottlers, whose
displeasure at the concentrate-price increases _ at 7 percent,
twice the typical rate _ likely did not go unnoticed by Coca-Cola's
board, Daft said he thought the situation had been overstated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have extremely strong relationships with all our partners
everywhere,'' he said. As for the price increases, he added: ``I
was well aware of the strategy in the U.S. and well aware of the
thinking behind it. And I totally agree with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola has been in the business of making huge support
payments to its bottlers. Its largest bottler, Coca-Cola
Enterprises in Atlanta, received just less than $1 billion last
year, without which the publicly traded bottler would have finished
the year in the red.
</P>
<P>
   Market support to bottlers will continue, Daft said, although he
did not give specifics. ``The market support is a critical part of
the relationship,'' he said. ``Each of the bottlers will continue
to get that support, and the level will depend on the local market
and local needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Daft told of meeting with Ivester last Friday night, in what he
thought was just a routine conversation with his boss. ``He called
me into his office and said to me, `Remember when we talked about
making life decisions?''' Daft said, adding that he had made one of
his own some six months earlier. ``And then he told me, `I've just
made one.' And he told me what it was.''
</P>
<P>
   What followed was ``sorrow and discussion,'' he added. ``And on
Sunday, he said to me, whatever happens I'm your friend. Both of us
were very emotional.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
