<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-VIRUS-CASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN PLEADS GUILTY TO CREATING WIDELY SPREAD MELISSA VIRUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ A New Jersey man pleaded guilty Thursday to state
and federal charges that he created the most widely spread,
disruptive and costly computer virus in history, but he insisted
that he had had ``no idea'' that his Melissa virus would replicate
itself exponentially as it swept through more than a million
computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in a Monmouth County courthouse Thursday morning, and
being described later by his lawyer in U.S. District Court here,
the man, David Lee Smith of Aberdeen Township, was portrayed as the
creator of an innocuous program that did not destroy computer
programs and hardware or steal money, but simply disrupted those
systems. ``I did not anticipate and expect that amount of damage,''
said Smith, 31, as he answered questions from Judge John A.
Ricciardi in state Superior Court in Freehold. ``I had no idea that
there would be such profound consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's lawyer, Edward Borden Jr., said that while his client
was ``profoundly remorseful,'' his goal had simply been to
circulate ``a harmless, joke message.'' But law enforcement
officials assembled in the two courtrooms were not laughing. They
said that Smith had caused at least $80 million in disruption, lost
commerce and computer downtime as the virus made its way through
1.2 million computers in one-fifth of the country's largest
businesses, and even into the electronic mail systems of the Marine
Corps and NATO in Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Far from being a mere nuisance, Melissa infected computers and
disabled computer networks throughout North America,'' said Robert
J. Cleary, the U.S. attorney for New Jersey. The New Jersey
attorney general, John Farmer, called the case the ``single most
significant Internet prosecution in the nation to date'' and an
indication of how aggressively law enforcement would pursue such
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Borden said the determination of prosecutors to try his client
in both federal and state courts led to Smith's guilty plea, under
which some lesser state charges were dropped. Smith faces up to 10
years in prison and a $150,000 fine on the state charges when he is
sentenced on Feb. 22, and up to five years and a $250,000 fine on
the federal charges when he is sentenced in federal court on May
15.
</P>
<P>
   Peter S. Tippett, vice chairman of ICSAnet, a computer security
firm, told reporters outside the federal courthouse that the
company had research pointing to multiple Internet personalities
for Smith, including a record of five years of virus writing and
determined disruption. Tippett, whose firm helped law enforcement
officials quantify the virus' damage, said that in one persona
Smith was the virus writer ``VicodinEs,'' who bragged in the
cyberunderground about ``creating a ruckus'' in computer systems.
But he also surfaced as ``Doug Winterspoon,'' a free-lance
cyberdetective who offered people advice over the Internet on
detecting and debugging viruses, Tippett said.
</P>
<P>
   Borden denied that his client was also ``Doug Winterspoon,'' but
would not discuss whether Smith was ``VicodinES.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
