<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRIDIUM-BANKRUPTCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTOROLA STEPS IN TO KEEP IRIDIUM GOING 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Iridium LLC, the troubled global satellite
telephone venture, said Thursday that a group of investors led by
Motorola Inc. had agreed to commit $20 million so that the company
could continue operating through early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in
August, said the money would allow it to operate through
mid-February and give its executives more time to develop a plan
for restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our existing investors have stepped forward to provide for
ongoing operations while we continue to have discussions with
potential new investors,'' John Richardson, the chief executive of
Iridium, said in a statement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have expressed an interest in taking a huge
stake in Iridium, based in Washington, is Craig O. McCaw, the
cellular telephone pioneer, who has been interested in gaining
control of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Iridium officials would not say who the potential investors are
and McCaw, who is a large investor in Teledesic LLC, the so-called
Internet in the Sky global satellite service that expects to begin
operating in 2004, was unavailable for comment Thursday. A month
ago, however, McCaw agreed to raise $1.2 billion to lift ICO Global
Communications, another global satellite telephone service, out of
Chapter 11.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts said the announcement Thursday suggested
that Motorola and others continued to believe that Iridium could be
revived.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means that Motorola is holding out some hope,'' said Armand
Musey, an analyst at BancAmerica Securities. ``They could have
pulled the plug.''
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, which helped develop the Iridium system, has continued
to back the venture despite criticism from some analysts earlier
this year and huge charges against earnings in recent quarters
because of financial commitments to the satellite system.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Motorola officials said they remained confident about
the viability of Iridium. ``Motorola is very encouraged by the way
Iridium LLC and its board of directors is working together to find
new investors that can help Iridium achieve a successful financial
restructuring,'' the company said in a statement. ``We hope today's
action will provide Iridium with the time it needs to complete that
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Motorola, however, said the company would stand by
its earlier statements about not committing significantly large
sums of money unless Iridium comes up with a convincing plan to
reorganize.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not make any more significant contributions unless
there is a sound business plan and a sound management team and
appropriate financial participation by the other investing
partners,'' said Albert R. Brashear, a Motorola spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Brashear also said Motorola would suspend operations of the
satellite service on Feb. 15 if a reorganization plan was not in
place. Motorola has been operating the service at no charge for
months, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Iridium also warned investors that once its
reorganization plan was announced, its shares might be worthless.
Shares of Iridium, which traded as high as $70 in May 1998, dropped
to about $3 after the bankruptcy filing.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the shares have been delisted by the NASDAQ stock
market and now trade off the market in what is called the pink
sheets, a bulletin board for stock quotations operated by the
National Quotation Bureau Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Trading has soared recently on speculation that McCaw could take
a stake in the company, but Iridium executives say that the
reorganization may not raise the value for shareholders because the
company has more than $4 billion in debt and legal priorities
related to the bankruptcy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
