u a BC-N.Y.-AIDS-MINORITIES-     12-09 0379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-AIDS-MINORITIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL SAYS AIDS PROGRAMS FOR MINORITIES NEED MORE MONEY
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A state AIDS panel is urging leaders in Albany to
spend more money on AIDS and H.I.V. programs and services aimed at
minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-member AIDS Advisory Council, which advises the governor
and the Legislature on policy, also said in a report distributed at
its monthly meeting on Wednesday that more money was needed to pay
for better programs aimed at minorities, which have been
disproportionately affected by the disease in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government had allocated $156 million for programs
that would specifically help minorities with AIDS or H.I.V., the
virus that causes AIDS, and more money would be added next year.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention,
which distributed $250 million to state and local health
departments for AIDS prevention programs, required those
departments to allocate their portion of money in a way that
paralleled the disease. In other words, if 50 percent of a city's
AIDS patients are African-American, 50 percent of that city's money
from the C.D.C. must go to programs that serve those individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials have said that new cases of H.I.V. are
dangerously high among minority gay men and heterosexual women,
especially minority women.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, for instance, Hispanics make up more than one
third of all AIDS cases, according to a report by the Latino
Commission on AIDS. While death rates from AIDS have slowed
nationally, those rates have fallen much more slowly among blacks.
In New York City from 1995 to 1998, AIDS deaths among white men
fell 83 percent but the rate declined by 75 percent among black
women.
</P>
<P>
   Groups that aim services at minorities are clamoring for a
larger proportion of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some time now, there has been a lot of people bringing
concerns to us about how the epidemic has shifted so much to men
and women of color,'' said Allan Rosenfield, chairman of the
Columbia University School of Public Health and a member of the
advisory council. ``We need to focus our efforts on the group that
makes up the highest risk at the present time.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 2240EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4722 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DAFT-INTERVIEW10-1STL     12-09 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAFT-INTERVIEW10-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1ST LEDE
 &HT;    EDs: Updates throughout.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Daft's priority: Long-term growth
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Douglas Daft, the new president of Coca-Cola, said
Thursday that his greatest challenge will be to leave an indelible
mark on the company like his predecessors did _ and enjoy himself
at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   But first, ``I have to get through the next couple of days,''
Daft joked during his first round of media interviews since
becoming president and chief operating officer earlier this week.
The promotion was prompted by Chairman M. Douglas Ivester's
decision to retire in April, when Daft will take over that job.
</P>
<P>
   Daft, 56, reassured investors that the Atlanta-based beverage
giant is committed to building shareholder value over the long
haul.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't concentrate on the short-term swings in the (stock)
market,'' said the former head of Coca-Cola's Middle East, Far East
and Africa operations. ``The company is committed to its long-term
growth goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have questioned those goals, saying they are
overly ambitious and cannot be sustained. The goals include annual
average increases in global case sales of 7 percent to 8 percent,
as well as earnings-per-share growth of between 15 percent and 20
percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Coca-Cola has been able to meet those goals
fairly consistently, propelling huge profits for its long-term
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   But recently, the company has failed to hit those targets _
depressing its stock _ largely because of troubled economies in
parts of Asia, Latin America, Russia and Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   While some of those economies have improved, Daft said, they
still have not fully gotten back on their feet.
</P>
<P>
   When they do, he is convinced the good ol' days for Coke
shareholders will return.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunities haven't changed,'' he said. ``We are
perfectly positioned to benefit'' from economic rebounds around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   In his new job, Daft said he will follow the advice of the
company's late chairman, Roberto C. Goizueta, who stressed the
value of focusing on a ``short and critical agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   He will be developing that agenda after discussing key issues
with other senior executives, as well as by remembering a central
lesson he learned during his three decades with the company:
``Don't lose your intuition.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the key issues he will be dealing with is whether to
appoint a president when he becomes chairman in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's a critical issue, but it's too early to
comment,'' Daft said.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester had been criticized by some analysts for not having a
No. 2. Some have said that a dispute over the issue with board
members may have prompted Ivester to retire.
</P>
<P>
   Daft emphasized the importance of building relationships. Some
analysts also have criticized Ivester for not doing enough of that,
saying that may have aggravated some of the company's recent
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put a high value on people and relationships,'' Daft said.
``People are critical to my success. ... The consumer is king.''
</P>
<P>
   Daft also said building stronger ties with bottlers and
retailers will be an essential part of his job. He doesn't plan any
changes in the company's recent decision to raise the price of
concentrate it sells to bottlers to make soft drinks. That decision
caused bottlers to raise prices, especially in supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   The stock of the company's largest bottler, Coca-Cola
Enterprises, has been taking a pounding lately. On Thursday, it
fell to another 52-week low before closing at $16.93 3/4, down
$1.06 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's stock, meanwhile, rose $1.62 1/2, closing at $62.12
1/2.
</P>
<P>
   The shares got a boost from analyst David Goldman of Banc of
America Securities, who raised his rating to ``buy'' from ``market
perform.'' He predicted the shares will reach $75 within 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
