<SLUG> BC-SOC-NCAA-MEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN MEN CLOSE IN ON SOCCER TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ In the early 1980s, the University of
Connecticut men's soccer team was a powerhouse. It won the national
championship in 1981 and reached the semifinals the next two years.
For the next 13 years, though, UConn was unable to even get past
the first round of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   This season, UConn again has an elite program. The Huskies
(19-4) will enter Friday's Final Four matchup of the College Cup
against Santa Clara (15-3-3) riding a 12-game winning streak. Eight
of those victories have been shutouts, and the offense has scored
27 goals.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana (19-3), the defending champion, will take on UCLA
(19-2), the winner of the NCAA title two years ago. The games will
be played at Ericsson Stadium in Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Ray Reid, who led Southern Connecticut State to three
Division II titles between 1990 and 1995, has revitalized the
Huskies' program in his third season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no pressure on us from the school to do what
the men and women did in basketball,'' Reid said Thursday. ``The
only pressure we have is what we've put on ourselves. The school,
in fact, has given us great support.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies rallied to eliminate Hartford, 2-1, in four
overtimes in the first round; defeated Yale, 3-0; and then had to
come back twice to defeat Furman, 3-2, in the quarterfinals last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't panic when we were down, and that's a testament to
our players,'' Reid said. All of UConn's victories came at home at
Storrs.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Clara, making its second consecutive appearance in the
semifinals, opened the season with 11 victories, nine by shutout.
The Broncos may have an advantage over Connecticut because they
have played all their tournament games on the road. They eliminated
Stanford, top-ranked Duke and Alabama-Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing every game on the road has certainly been challenging
for our team,'' coach Mitch Murray said. ``But we survived and our
team is in high spirits because we feel we have a lot of soccer
left to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid said: ``Santa Clara is very well organized defensively, but
I don't expect them to sit back and play low pressure. Their
defense will be difficult to break down. We'll have to neutralize
them in transition.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid's team, led by Luis Arauz and Daren Lewis, has the speed to
do damage. Arauz has scored 13 goals and Lewis has 10.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana, which eliminated Santa Clara in the semifinals last
year before beating Stanford in the championship game for its
fourth national title, struggled against Kentucky in the first
round before eliminating Washington and Penn State to reach the
semifinals for the 13th time under coach Jerry Yeagley.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA, coached by Todd Saldana, is making its 10th appearance in
the semifinals. The Bruins have captured three titles and were
runners-up three times. They reached the semifinals this season by
defeating San Diego at home and St. Louis and Virginia on the road.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
