<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRISH PARADE IS LATEST ISSUE FOR FIRST LADY
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wading into one of the more complicated political
issues here, Hillary Rodham Clinton said Thursday that she would
like to march in the St. Patrick's Day parade in March, an event
that many Democrats have boycotted because the organizers exclude
gay groups.
</P>
<P>
   The remark threatened to dampen the enthusiasm that Mrs. Clinton
had fostered this week among an important New York voting bloc when
she announced her support for gays serving openly in the military.
Later, the spokesman for her U.S. Senate campaign seemed to
backpedal, suggesting that the first lady's presence in the parade
was not guaranteed and that she hoped it would not exclude anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton made the comment as she sought to please
Irish-American political and community leaders, who surrounded her
at a news conference Thursday at a midtown restaurant. They took
note of her four trips to Ireland as first lady, and she promised,
if elected, to push for more aid to Northern Ireland as it moved
toward peace.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she planned to march in the parade, which Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, her presumed Republican rival, has faithfully attended,
she beamed and replied, ``I would hope so.'' The remark drew
applause from the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I've got a lot of good company,'' she continued,
turning again toward the smiling group, ``I would certainly go
marching in the St. Patrick's Day parade.''
</P>
<P>
   The second-floor lounge erupted in cheers, but Mrs. Clinton's
remarks appeared to take her aides by surprise. It also left other
Democrats and gay leaders wondering if she had stumbled on a land
mine.
</P>
<P>
   The parade is a magnet for politicians of all stripes, but in
recent years, several Democrats have boycotted it, because the
Ancient Order of Hibernians, the Roman Catholic fraternal group
that organizes the parade, forbids gay organizations to march under
their own banners.
</P>
<P>
   After Mrs. Clinton's news conference, when reporters pointed out
the parade's political turmoil, her spokesman, Howard Wolfson,
said: ``It wasn't a firm commitment that she made. I think she said
she hoped to, and we will revisit the issue when we get closer to
St. Patrick's Day. We'll deal with Christmas first.''
</P>
<P>
   In a later telephone interview, he said Mrs. Clinton indeed
wanted to march but added that she hoped that the parade would be
inclusive.
</P>
<P>
   Gay leaders said they would seek to persuade Mrs. Clinton to
work with them to have gay groups included or, failing that, to
skip the parade.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Thomas Duane, a Manhattan Democrat who is gay, said,
``I think she probably does not know the depth of feeling
surrounding New York's St. Patrick's Day parade and its history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
