<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CANCER-CLUSTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK IS FIRST STATE WITH CANCER-RATE MAPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ New York Thursday became the first state to
produce maps showing the rates of some cancers, county by county,
but the maps were quickly dismissed as useless by some of the
people who conceived of the project.
</P>
<P>
   As envisioned by cancer survivors' groups and the Legislature,
the maps were to show cancer rates at a neighborhood level,
alongside known sources of serious air, water and soil pollution.
The idea was to identify possible environmental causes for ``cancer
clusters'' so that scientists could investigate and determine
whether there was a connection. Nothing like it had ever been
tried, except by amateurs at a local level.
</P>
<P>
   The maps released Thursday by the state Health Department do not
supply either half of the equation; they do not show sources of
pollution and do not show cancer rates at the local level, where
clusters might turn up. Dr. Antonia Novello, who became state
health commissioner this year, said the department would include
such information in future maps, though she could not say when.
</P>
<P>
   The data included in the maps is also not new. The department
has published county-level cancer rates for years, though officials
said that data had required some polishing before the maps could be
published. The maps can be viewed on the department's Web site, at
http://www.health.state.ny.us.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've spent 18 months repackaging what they had before they
started, and they're dragging their feet on the important part,
which is the environmental risk factors,'' said Assemblyman Richard
Brodsky, the author of the legislation that commissioned the maps.
``What they've produced is useless, and it can't be accidental.''
</P>
<P>
   The project is controversial among scientists. Many believe that
there is no such thing as a residential cancer cluster, that
neighborhood variations are essentially random. Others contend that
such clusters do exist, though they are exceedingly hard to prove,
and that detailed maps can be a start down that road. (Some
occupational cancer clusters, like those among asbestos workers and
coal miners, are well documented.)
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki's administration has been uncomfortable with
the project from the start. Administration officials have voiced
fears that detailed maps could prompt people to leap to conclusions
about cause and effect. Real estate interests and corporations
responsible for significant pollution have lobbied against the
effort, fearing that it could result in lawsuits or reduced
property values.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1998, the Legislature mandated the maps and included
money for them in the state budget, but Pataki vetoed the spending
item. Then, in the face of criticism from cancer survivors' groups,
he ordered the Health Department to proceed with the effort. The
Legislature renewed the mandate in this year's budget, which the
governor signed.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Department has long operated a cancer registry,
collecting information on people who get cancer diagnoses.
Advocates of the mapping project assert that maps comparing that
information, by ZIP code, with known major sources of pollution
could be completed in a matter of days or weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Novello said Thursday that the cancer registry data, which
was a few years old, needed updating and that duplications had to
be eliminated before maps could be made. But the same data included
in the maps issued Thursday was posted on the department's Web site
early this year.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Cornell University researchers, using the state's data,
posted a county-level breast cancer map of the state early this
year, which can be seen on their Web site,
http://www.cfe.cornell.edu/bcerf. This week, the National Cancer
Institute published a set of county-by-county cancer mortality maps
covering the entire country, which are posted on the institute's
Web site, http://www.nci.nih.gov.
</P>
<P>
   The maps released Thursday show rates of breast, lung, and colon
and rectal cancers, among the most common types, from 1992 through
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Breast cancer has become a potent political issue on Long
Island, where its incidence is relatively high. But the state's
data showed that the highest rate, nearly 30 percent above the
state average, was in Rockland County. Rockland is high in many
known risk factors for the disease: it is affluent, has a heavy
Jewish population, and women there tend to begin having children at
a later age.
</P>
<P>
   The highest rates of lung cancer and colon and rectal cancer
were in mostly rural counties in central and northern New York, a
pattern officials said they could not explain. New York City had
below-average rates for all three groups, though in each case,
Staten Island had above-average rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
