<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-SUBARU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM SAID TO BE READY TO BUY STAKE IN PARENT OF SUBARU 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Seeking to help its business at home while building
its tiny market share in Asia, the General Motors Corp. is expected
to announce that it will pay $1.4 billion for 20 percent of Fuji
Heavy Industries, the Japanese maker of Subaru vehicles, people
close to the talks said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which could be announced as early as Friday, would
allow GM to share Subaru's expertise in all-wheel-drive systems for
small cars, its engineering work on car-based sport utility
vehicles and its technology for continuously variable
transmissions. In addition, GM might tap into Fuji's distribution
system in Japan, where it has struggled to sell cars for years.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts shrugged off the deal as a minor one for GM. ``It would
be a rounding error for GM in terms of the cost, in terms of the
earnings effect and in terms of the effect on their business,''
said David B. Healy, an analyst with Burnham Securities. ``It could
give them a source of engines and maybe save them some development
costs and maybe give them a toehold in the Asia-Pacific market.''
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, GM's market share in the region was 4.6
percent. In the first nine months of this year, GM's revenue in the
Asia-Pacific region was $2.25 billion, and it lost $195 million on
the business. Those figures are dwarfed by GM's nine-month revenue
of $112.63 billion and net income of $4.86 billion.
</P>
<P>
   GM acknowledged late Thursday that it had been negotiating with
Fuji about ``a strategic alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been considerable momentum with those talks, but
there is nothing firm to announce at this point,'' Anthony Cervone,
a GM spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fuji deal may not be the last for GM, or for other
automakers looking for more business in Asia. With the recovering
Japanese economy helping regional economies rebound across Asia,
Detroit's carmakers are busy trying to forge links through
investments and other alliances.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a Ford Motor executive traveled to South Korea to
meet with bankers there. GM has spent 22 months negotiating with
Daewoo, the country's No. 2 automaker, over whether to take a stake
in the company, which is in financial difficulty. But the bankers
asked Ford whether it was interested in Daewoo.
</P>
<P>
   Ford told the bankers ``we are always interested in subjects
under the right conditions,'' W. Wayne Booker, a Ford vice
chairman, said in an interview Thursday night. He cautioned that
Ford had yet to hold talks with Daewoo. ``We haven't made any
proposals to anybody,'' Booker said.
</P>
<P>
   Like GM, Ford has looked to alliances with other automakers to
try to increase its market share in the Asia-Pacific region. Ford
will not disclose its country-by-country 10-year goals, but GM has
said it wants to increase its market share in the region to 10
percent by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   GM has not broken off its talks with Daewoo. Ford's interest
could force a decision on the matter soon if it does not derail the
GM talks. GM signed a memorandum of understanding with Daewoo in
February 1998 that laid the groundwork for discussions about a
deal, with a second memorandum of understanding signed in August.
</P>
<P>
   GM's long discussions with Daewoo have run aground because GM
wants to avoid acquiring any of Daewoo's enormous debt burden.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan also owns a 4 percent stake in Fuji, and is negotiating
whether to sell that stake to GM, people close to the deal said.
</P>
<P>
   The GM deal to buy a fifth of Fuji would be just the latest in a
wave of cross-border alliances in the auto industry. Last year,
Daimler-Benz of Germany bought the Chrysler Corp., the smallest of
Detroit's Big Three. Earlier this year, Ford bought Volvo of
Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   GM itself last year raised its stakes in Isuzu Motors Ltd. and
the Suzuki Motor Corp. to 49 percent and 10 percent, respectively.
In the coming months, GM may also buy the piece of Saab it does not
already own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
