<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4733 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-PENGUINS-BROOKS-N     12-09 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PENGUINS-BROOKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROOKS REDUX IN PITTSBURGH WITH A NOD TO THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty winters ago, when Herb Brooks was on top of the world, he
was a man ahead of his time. He had a global perspective on hockey
and the imagination to make it fun to play and to watch. He coached
the U.S. Olympic team that upset the powerful Soviet Union and went
on to win the gold medal at Lake Placid.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Sports Illustrated rightly judged the unlikely
triumph of Brooks' American team to be the greatest moment in 20th
century sports. Greater than Louis over Schmeling or DiMaggio's
hitting streak or Roger Bannister's four-minute mile or anything
offered by football, basketball, tennis, golf or horse racing.
</P>
<P>
   Push the fast-forward button now to the season of 1999-2000.
After coaching the Rangers for four years, the Minnesota North
Stars for one and the Devils for one, Brooks had been working as a
scout for the Pittsburgh Penguins. He served as coach of France, a
second-tier Olympic team, in the 1998 Winter Games in Japan. At age
62, he seemed to be putting in his time until retirement, sometimes
edgy and maybe a little bitter about the way both amateur and
professional hockey have evolved in North America. He was due to
resurface in a few weeks only for another round of interviews on
the Olympic anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   And, suddenly _ do you believe in miracles? _ Brooks is back
behind a National Hockey League bench for the first time since
1993. The Penguins named him to replace Kevin Constantine, and
Brooks coached Thursday night in Pittsburgh against Washington. He
has an important job with a troubled franchise. The team lost its
previous three games and was 8-14-3. After enduring a year of
bankruptcy, the Penguins were bought by Mario Lemieux, their former
star, who took control mainly to recover about $30 million owed to
him. Penguins attendance is down and payroll limitations have
forced a few personnel moves.
</P>
<P>
   The hiring of Brooks suggests many things, including
desperation. What if Brooks, two decades removed from his great
triumph, proves himself to be behind the times? Some of his new
players were toddlers that memorable week in Lake Placid.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks was hired by General Manager Craig Patrick, his assistant
coach on the American Olympic team. A skeptic can speculate about
cronyism and panic. But a romantic can hope that this is the
perfect move at the perfect time.
</P>
<P>
   In a league plagued by boring, defensive strategies, Brooks
takes over a team filled with Europeans schooled in puck skills and
playmaking. Forwards such as Jaromir Jagr and Aleksei Kovalev could
discover a coach who reminds them of their ``trainers'' in Europe.
A successful team in Pittsburgh, with a dynamic style under a
legendary coach, could help produce the shift in personality that
the league needs as it enters a new year, decade and century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Herb is a perfect fit for what we are trying to achieve
here,'' Patrick said in a telephone interview Thursday. ``I know
his hockey mind. He is always at the cutting edge of what is going
on in hockey. He always will be. He has a brilliant hockey mind.
Lots of teams are finding ways to beat the trap. I know him. He
will be able to.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks promised his team will play ``an up-tempo, dynamic
game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ice out there, not blacktop, wood or dirt,'' Brooks said
at the midday news conference to announce his hiring. ``The first
thing is to get back to even and play a type of game that fits into
the abilities of the players we have here.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux did not attend the news conference, held across the
street from team offices. But he approved Patrick's decision. And
more fresh ideas could come from the 34-year-old owner.
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux suggested that a cure for empty seats and low television
ratings might be to use an international-sized rink, 100 feet wide
instead of 85, the kind used in the Olympics and in Europe. More
space could mean more creativity. But might some owners not wish to
remove seats for a bigger playing surface?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, if you look around the league, there's not too many
teams selling out every game,'' Lemieux said. ``So, to make our
product better, if we have to take some seats out and, by doing
that, selling out most of the buildings, it makes more sense. All
I'm trying to do is make the game more fun for the players, the
fans and for the viewers on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   What a concept. It is the kind of talk heard 20 winters ago,
when Herb Brooks was golden and hockey hoped to make its great leap
forward.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
