<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4734 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EUROPE-GADGETS-NYT &LR;      12-09 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-GADGETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALIANS INTRODUCE `SMART' WASHER WITH THE INTERNET IN MIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Now, for the homemaker who truly has everything _
cyberlaundry.
</P>
<P>
   With the free-spending Christmas shopper as the target audience,
an Italian appliance maker Thursday put on sale a washing machine
that uses wireless telephone technology and a modem to communicate
with the manufacturer and the owner, and hat will in the future be
able to chat electronically with other appliances around the house.
</P>
<P>
   The vaguely retro-looking whitewasher, the Margherita2000.com,
is the product of Merloni Elettrodomestici S.p.A., which ranks
alongside Whirlpool of the United States as Europe's third-largest
appliance maker, after Electrolux of Sweden and Bosch-Siemens of
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction of Margherita, a front-loading model that
retails for as much as $1,400, is Merloni's attempt to get a head
start on its big international rivals.
</P>
<P>
   As the use of the Internet and wireless phones spreads through
Europe, the Continent's consumer electronics makers are hustling to
create so-called smart appliances that can join the chatter. Last
month, Electrolux announced a joint venture with Ericsson, the
Swedish company known for cellular phones, to develop smart
appliances and the home networking they require. Electrolux plans
to have its first smart appliance, a refrigerator that can order
groceries through the Internet and is known as the Screenfridge, on
sale by next year. Siemens-Bosch has linked up with Sun
Microsystems to pursue similar plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excitement and white goods used to be an oxymoron,'' said
Francesco Caio, the former chief of the Olivetti computer group who
is now Merloni's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   After Thursday's introduction in Italy, Margherita is to be
offered in the spring in Britain and later in the year in France,
Spain and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the push toward smart appliances are clear.
Three years ago, when Caio took over at Merloni, the European
appliance industry was burdened by stagnant sales and enormous
overcapacity, despite the opening of fresh markets in
post-Communist Eastern Europe. Electrolux soon announced an
ambitious five-year plan to cut 12,000 jobs and close 25 factories,
mainly in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   European energy and water prices are high, and smart appliances
operate efficiently. They also put less of a strain on the
environment. But what attracts manufacturing executives like Caio
is the potential ability to create an array of related information
services around smart appliances and the networks that link them,
enabling the appliance makers to increase their revenue beyond what
they collect on the appliances themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Giorgio Mosca, Merloni's director of innovative product
development, taps keys on his wireless phone to ask Margherita when
it has been set to begin the wash cycle. If he puts in too much
detergent, or sets the temperature too high for the cashmere he is
washing, the machine sends a warning message over the Internet to a
manufacturer's Web site, where Mosca can use a code and a password
to call it up. If Margherita's internal sensors note that one of
the components is about to go out, the machine informs a customer
service center so that timely repairs can be made.
</P>
<P>
   Using his cell phone, Mosca can now do little more than start
and stop the machine and tell it to change the preset starting
time. That is because the controls on Margherita are still
conventional analog controls, which consumers prefer.
Future-generation machines will be designed to respond to a broader
array of commands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a work in progress,'' Mosca said.
</P>
<P>
   And Margherita has other talents. Sensors in the tumbler measure
the conductivity of the rinse water, enabling the machine to shut
off the rinse cycle as soon as all the detergent is dissolved.
Fuzzy logic enables the microchips to tell fabrics apart _
distinguishing, say, between cotton and wool, and to know whether
the right amount of detergent or water softener was used.
</P>
<P>
   By midday Thursday, though, Merloni had sold none of its
machines, though some people who browsed were clearly impressed.
</P>
<P>
   Giovanna Cecchi, an accountant in her 30s, said she liked the
idea of operating the machine remotely by cell phone. ``If you
leave wet wash in your machine all day,'' she said, ``it comes out
with a funny odor.''
</P>
<P>
   The price, she acknowledged, was ``a bit above the average,''
but the convenience for a working homemaker who uses the Internet
anyway she found ``pretty interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Merloni, which does not sell appliances in the United States,
says it sees a market for its software package among American
appliance makers, who are expected to offer their own lines of
smart appliances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't seen huge interest yet,'' said Jill Notini,
spokeswoman for the Association of Home Appliance Manufacturers in
Washington. But she added, ``We'll see; give it another year. I
think you have a first here.''
</P>
<P>
   Per Grunewald, president of Electrolux's new joint venture with
Ericsson, said that ``potentially, the United States is one of our
first markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Notini conceded she was unsure just how American consumers
would take to a machine that evaluated its owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd kill it,'' she said. ``How dare an appliance talk back?''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Cecchi said she liked the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a grandmother, telling you how to do the wash
better,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 2256EST &QL; 
