<SLUG> BC-FORBES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORBES OFFERS UP SPECIFICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phoenix - Presidential candidate Steve Forbes on Thursday
defended his aggressive plan to privatize Social Security and said
problems created by a transition period for the newly revamped
program could be solved with long-term bonds.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with ``The Arizona Republic'' editorial board,
Forbes defended his plan to allow citizens to invest Social
Security funds in their own retirement accounts and said some of
the costs associated with introducing the plan could be paid for
with the bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you need to issue bonds to pay benefits, those bonds could
be financed at 4.4 percent long term, amortized over 40 years, and
still make the thing work,'' Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has been criticized by other GOP presidential candidates,
most vocally Gary Bauer, for failing to adequately explain how his
plan would be funded.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the bonds, the new system would be paid for with
gains in worker productivity and spending caps, according to
Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have any kind of decent economic policy, the monies are
there to aggressively phase in this new system,'' Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   In a wide-ranging interview, Forbes also said the problems
associated with illegal immigration should be laid at the doorstep
of the Immigration and Naturalization Service, and he called for
increased border operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need to use the military, you just need to have the
INS get its act together,'' Forbes said, referring to the call by
some conservatives to use the military to stanch the flow of
illegal immigrants across the border.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent Arizona poll, conducted for ``The Republic,''
Texas Gov. George W. Bush led Arizona Sen. John McCain, 40 percent
to 36 percent, with Forbes in third place at 7 percent. The survey
had a margin of error of 3.4 percentage points. Despite his
third-place position, Forbes is competing heavily in the state's
primary, which he won during the 1996 presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
   As he has throughout the campaign, Forbes sought Wednesday to
put daylight between his proposals and those of the front-runner,
Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine publisher critiqued Bush's education proposal,
which would require states to establish minimum testing standards
to be reviewed by the federal government, as too bureaucratic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long after Mr. Bush takes that office, if (he) takes that
office, bureaucracies will take on a life of their own,'' Forbes
said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Forbes, his own plan to send education block grants
to states that agree to offer school choice is the more
conservative approach.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes also defended his recent support of allowing schools to
post the Ten Commandments, which he called ``the core of Western
civilization.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a particular religion,'' he said of the Bible tenets.
``It's the core of who we are and what we are.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 2258EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
