<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PINCAY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINCAY TIES SHOEMAKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Riding a horse named I Be Casual past the
finish of Thursday's fourth race at Hollywood Park, narrowly a
winner for a record-tying 8,833rd time, Laffit Pincay waved his
whip overhead left-handed and called out to the beaten jockeys, ``I
got it! I got it!''
</P>
<P>
   What happened next is even more rare than a flashy expression of
personal triumph by the normally stoic Pincay.
</P>
<P>
   Omar Berrio, riding the runner-up, raised his whip overhead. Pat
Valenzuela, aboard the third-place finisher, lifted his. And with
arms aloft, the three jockeys faded into the distance _ the one in
gold and green galloping into history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy for (Pincay),'' Berrio said later, explaining why
he celebrated after losing a hard-fought race by a head after
leading yards from the wire. ``When I was a little boy, watching TV
in Panama, Laffit was my idol.''
</P>
<P>
   It seemed as if everybody in the small but noisy crowd at
Hollywood Park felt like the fawning Berrio on the cool, clear
afternoon when Pincay, 52, equaled Bill Shoemaker's mark for
lifetime riding victories, setting the stage for a possible
tie-breaker today.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay got a hero's welcome as he jogged I Be Casual back to the
winner's circle while an Olympian fanfare blared from the
loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hot damn, that was exciting!'' fellow Hall of Famer Chris
McCarron said, sprinting out from the jockeys' room to greet Pincay
with a shout of ``All right, Laffit!'' and a pat on the hip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congratulations, Laffit!'' growled Jack Van Berg, I Be
Casual's Hall of Fame trainer, offering a handshake. Pincay beamed
and stroked the horse's mane.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Hollywood Park jockeys stormed out of their
locker room as the fans in the weekday crowd of 5,578 pressed
against the rail above the winner's circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laffit, you're the best athlete in the world!'' a man in the
crowd yelled as the winner's circle photographs were snapped,
Pincay and I Be Casual surrounded by his family, rival jockeys and
the horse's owners and handlers.
</P>
<P>
   Dismounting, Pincay was scooped up by the other jockeys and
carried to the scale to weigh in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they were going to throw me in another cake,''
Pincay said later, referring to a past occasion when the jockeys
dumped the fanatical dieter in a huge sheet cake.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was back to the winner's circle for a formal ceremony
that included the wheelchair-bound Shoemaker.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Park president Rick Baedeker congratulated Pincay ``on
behalf of all the racing fans here.''
</P>
<P>
   Baedeker unveiled a $10,000 check, a donation by racetracks to
the Shoemaker Foundation, established following the jockey's 1991
auto accident to aid injured horsemen.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay's agent, Bob Meldahl, fought back tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gotten to the top of the mountain, but he needs one more
to be up there by himself,'' Shoemaker said into a crackling
microphone. ``I'm rooting for him. Go get 'em, Laffit!''
</P>
<P>
   Pincay answered: ``I just (tied) the record of the greatest
rider who ever lived.''
</P>
<P>
   How much sweeter can it get when Pincay actually breaks the
record?
</P>
<P>
   It could happen today, when he's scheduled to ride in five of
Hollywood Park's eight races, although none of his horses is
favored on the morning line. It could happen Saturday, when he has
mounts in six of the nine races.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay tied the record by posting a single winner for the fifth
straight day, this time with a swooping rally from sixth aboard I
Be Casual, a gray 3-year-old gelding who'd been winless in 11
previous races under other jockeys. Whipping left-handed, he pushed
his horse's head in front of Berrio's AJ Flyer a few strides from
the finish.
</P>
<P>
   The winner, bet down from a 2-1 morning line, paid $4.40. This
was the 44,640th ride of Pincay's career; Shoemaker had 40,350.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to win easy,'' Pincay said of the moment
when he angled I Be Casual out from behind other horses at the top
of the stretch. ``That other horse kept fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   The win came on the second of Pincay's five tries Thursday. He
picked up a promising mount, Bob Baffert-trained De Witt at 2-5
odds in the second race, after Emile Ramsammy complained of an
upset stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics grumbled that the publicity-conscious Baffert
orchestrated the switch, but their speculation was moot after De
Witt finished second. A good thing, perhaps, because Pincay's wife
and children hadn't arrived at the track yet.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay finished sixth, seventh and fifth in three later tries.
The real celebration awaits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 2300EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991209.0411 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4737 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-MUSIC-ENRIQUE-HNS &LR;      12-09 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ENRIQUE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENRIQUE IGLESIAS: MAKING A CONNECTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOEY GUERRA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Enrique Iglesias is running late _ very late.
</P>
<P>
   That may not be an earth-shattering surprise in a celebrity's
world of late-night concerts, autograph sessions and interviews,
but this Latin crooner has a legitimate excuse.
</P>
<P>
   Iglesias was en route to Paris recently to promote ``Enrique,''
his first English-language album, when the flight he was on
unexpectedly took a disaster-movie turn for the worse. And we're
not talking turbulence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The front window _ the cockpit window _ broke,'' said Iglesias
when he finally called from his safe hotel room in Paris. ``We were
at 35,000 feet. Emergency landing! Emergency landing!''
</P>
<P>
   Iglesias comes to Houston on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Iglesias' last local appearance was in March during the Houston
Livestock Show and Rodeo, where more than 56,000 people swooned to
his lush love songs. Some were so overcome by Iglesias' presence at
the Astrodome that they dived over guardrails and chased the singer
as he was leaving the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was hilarious. You should've seen the bulls. Suddenly you
felt like the bulls were the audience,'' Iglesias said, recalling
the stampede.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute I jumped in the truck, there were already hundreds
of girls running all over the place and holding onto the truck.
Cops running all over the place. ... And the girls are actually
punching the cops.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a reaction is typical at this entertainer's concerts, which
rely more on raw emotion and personal connection than the
prepackaged spectacle of Ricky Martin, Latin music's current king.
</P>
<P>
   The teary-eyed hysteria suits Iglesias just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the worst thing a girl can do? They're going to
scratch you? Give me a break. They're my audience,'' Iglesias said.
``They're not going to kill me. Thank God that happens. The day I
have to worry is the day that doesn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old singer and songwriter won't have to worry about
fans losing interest anytime soon. Since the release of his first
Spanish-language album in 1995, Iglesias has sold more than 14
million albums, scored more than a dozen No. 1 singles, and earned
a Grammy and an American Music Award.
</P>
<P>
   This year brought the flamenco-flavored ``Bailamos,'' his first
English-language chart-topper, on the ``Wild Wild West''
soundtrack. It resulted in a fierce bidding war that incited
interest from Maverick, Madonna's record label.
</P>
<P>
   Iglesias eventually signed a $40 million multi-album deal with
Universal/Interscope. He completed his ``Enrique'' album in a mere
two months, and no expense was spared on the glittering collection.
</P>
<P>
   It features credits from such big-league players as producers
Mark Taylor and Brian Rowling, David Foster, songwriter Diane
Warren and Whitney Houston, who joins Iglesias for a duet, ``Could
I Have This Kiss Forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Arista Records (Houston's label) president Clive Davis suggested
the collaboration to Iglesias after Houston said she loved the
song, too. Because of conflicting schedules, the song was recorded
over the phone using Integrated Services Digital Network
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was in Germany, and I was in L.A. I never met her, but
I've seen her on TV,'' Iglesias said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Iglesias co-wrote five tracks on his album, including the
sensual first single, ``Rhythm Divine.'' The video is in heavy
rotation on MTV, and the album entered Billboard's charts at a
modest No. 42.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's stupid, but it's what I call a happy album,''
Iglesias said. ``The songs I wrote, they're pretty positive. They
leave you in a good mood.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the best moments on the album is Iglesias' hushed version
of ``Sad Eyes,'' a song originally featured on Tracks, Bruce
Springsteen's collection of outtakes and rarities. Interscope
president Jimmy Iovine, who has produced Springsteen, brought the
song to Iglesias' attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew I was a big Bruce Springsteen fan,'' Iglesias said.
``I listened to the song, and I fell in love with it. I'm like,
`How am I going to do a Bruce Springsteen song?' But I went into
the studio with a bunch of great musicians I liked, and I produced
it with a friend of mine (Lester Mendez). I did it kinda my way.''
</P>
<P>
   While the label ``crossover'' has been slapped on every artist
with the slightest Latin appeal, Iglesias isn't afraid to label his
accessible sound as pure pop. His influences _ Springsteen, Billy
Joel, Lionel Richie, the Police _ reflect that.
</P>
<P>
   Producers Taylor and Rowling, known collectively as Metro,
ushered galloping dance beats and pop smarts into four tracks on
Iglesias' album. (They are also responsible for ``Believe,'' Cher's
techno-tinged comeback.)
</P>
<P>
   ``What I did in Spanish was mainstream,'' Iglesias said.
``That's where my focus was on this album. I wanted to do a
mainstream pop album in English. I'm Latino _ that's what makes it
Latino. Anything that has Jennifer, Ricky _ they even stuck
Christina Aguilera in it _ it's really pop. You cannot be No. 1 in
the United States if you're not mainstream. It all comes down to
that.''
</P>
<P>
   With Iglesias aiming for U.S. stardom, he'll be going
head-to-head with Martin and Marc Anthony, who beat him to the
male-heartthrob punch with full-length albums earlier this year.
Iglesias concedes, however, that there is room for everyone on the
charts and in the hearts of music listeners.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's only a few of us out there, it's just going to be a
trend,'' Iglesias said. ``But at the end, what I love about it,
what matters, is the album. People don't get in their cars, turn on
the radio and say, `Oh, it's Latino time; let's buy that song.' If
a song is good, it will do good.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides a slate of radio promotion shows and TV appearances,
Iglesias isn't planning a full-scale tour any time soon. His
worldwide ``Cosas del Amor'' outing wrapped up in May, and he won't
hit the road again until next September, when more singles will
have been released from his English-language album.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, he should have plenty of time to prepare himself for
any potential outbreak of frenzied fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love my audience. I feel so protected when I'm around
them,'' Iglesias said. ``You can't really explain what you feel.
That's what pushes you. That's when you say, `All the work, all the
traveling, all the interviews, all those sleepless nights, all
those hotels, all that _ it's all worth it as long as you feel
that.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
