<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MCTEER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH ACTRESS DRAWS CRITICS' PRAISE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine you are a respected British actress, well known on
English television and the stage, and a Broadway Tony Award winner.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine you land a good leading role in an American movie _ a
low-budget independent film, to be sure, but still ... You shoot
the movie, and it's about to arrive in theaters.
</P>
<P>
   So, what do you most not want to hear?
</P>
<P>
   Well, how about this? Just before your movie, ``Tumbleweeds,''
is to be released, another movie will come out with a similar plot
and theme.
</P>
<P>
   And this other movie, ``Anywhere but Here,'' is a big-budget,
highly advertised Hollywood production.
</P>
<P>
   And the role parallel to the one you play is handled in the
other movie by Susan Sarandon, not only a star but also one of the
most respected performers around.
</P>
<P>
   If actress Janet McTeer fretted at all about this seeming
misfortune, she's fretting no more. Not only has ``Tumbleweeds''
and her performance gotten better reviews than ``Anywhere but
Here'' and the estimable Sarandon, but McTeer is also widely
considered a strong dark-horse contender for an Oscar nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times called her work as an American Southern mom
who runs away from relationships ``not a performance at all but a
kind of spontaneous alchemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Time magazine said she is ``a wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Luminous, haunting, electrifying,'' Rolling Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   As you might guess, McTeer finds this overwhelming response
quite gratifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh God, yeah,'' she said. ``Poof. You kidding? I thought they
were going to laugh me off the screen. Some silly British actresses
doing a silly voice. I'm delighted.''
</P>
<P>
   McTeer, 37, was calling from her home in London. She had just
returned there from a busy U.S. visit and sounded relaxed. In fact,
in the middle of the conversation she interrupted herself to say,
``I'm now lying down on the sofa,'' and giggle, ``If you hear a
little pause, I've fallen asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, she sounds not at all like her ``Tumbleweeds''
character, Mary Jo Walker, who hails from North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   And let's take this moment to say, with gratitude, that her
Southern accent in the movie is subtle, not the heavy-syruped
unreal drawl of so many actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``America's a very large place, but in actual fact they have
very few accents. Whereas England is a tiny, tiny place, and we
have many, many, many accents. I grew up in York, and five miles
away the accent's different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I now live in London, and there are four different London
accents. When English people are children, their ear becomes
attuned to many different accents. That's my latest theory.''
</P>
<P>
   Though she has worked mainly in England, McTeer made an impact
here in 1997, when her Broadway debut in ``A Doll's House'' won the
Tony Award and several other drama prizes. She earned additional
honors in England when the play was staged in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tumbleweeds'' is about a mother-daughter relationship between
Mary Jo and her teen-ager, Ava (played by Kimberley Brown). Of the
two, Ava is definitely the more stable; she yearns to stay in one
place and form friendships.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jo, however, is an emotional, free-spirited but confused
adult with a talent for picking the wrong men. The idea that she
might have a relationship with a man and be friends with him, too,
is outside her comprehension. When things turn uncomfortable in an
affair, she's out the door and on the road, dragging Ava along.
</P>
<P>
   The film is directed by Gavin O'Connor, who plays one of Mary
Jo's bad choices, and written by O'Connor and his former wife,
Angela Shelton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story is inspired by Angela's life,'' McTeer said. ``She
went across the country (as a child) with her mum. Eleven times, in
fact.''
</P>
<P>
   McTeer did some serious, and not so serious, preparation for
playing the part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked a lot to Angela and her mum. I went to North Carolina
and stayed with some of Angela's relatives, who were wonderfully
hospitable. Lovely people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent time going around, talking to people and watching
everybody, observing. I read some Southern novels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must have watched `Coal Miner's Daughter' and `Sweet Dreams'
and `Bastard Out of Carolina' at least 6 million times.''
</P>
<P>
   But she came to the decision that playing Mary Jo as a
Southerner was not the most important part of the role.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's universal,'' McTeer said. ``People are people are people
across the world. We all really want the same things: to be loved,
to be understood, to find peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The struggle of being a mother who is trying to bring her
daughter up and trying to have a life at the same time is totally
universal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 2310EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
