<SLUG> BC-OUTOFPRINT-BOOKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING TO PUT `OUT OF PRINT' BACK IN PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two of the nation's leading book industry players
announced separate plans Thursday to invest in new instant printing
technology that will resurrect out-of-print titles and lead toward
more electronic books.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes &AMP; Noble said it had struck an agreement with IBM to
provide print-on-demand equipment for its distribution centers,
which will allow the No. 1-ranked bookstore chain to quickly
convert digital books into conventional print versions one at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day, Random House Inc. _ the largest trade book
publisher in the United States and a unit of Bertelsmann _ said it
was also preparing to invest in state-of-the art equipment for its
national distribution center in Westminster, Md., that will begin
operation in March or April. But unlike Barnes &AMP; Noble, it has not
yet struck a deal with any of the major manufacturers of the
equipment like Xerox or IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Book buyers may not immediately notice the impact of the
equipment, but ultimately it means that the depth and selection of
titles will increase because publishers will be able to maintain
titles economically in digital form, printing titles out in short
runs according to demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are roughly 1.3 million titles considered in
print, and some 90,000 books are put out of print each year,'' said
Stephen Riggio, vice chairman of Barnes &AMP; Noble. ``We think that's
a travesty. The technology enables us to declare that the words
`out of print' should be obsolete.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes &AMP; Noble has a business tie to The New York Times, selling
books through links from the newspaper's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Riggio said the company expected to start offering a range of
services to publishers early next year. It has already been working
with a pilot group of five small and large publishers to identify
titles, said Riggio, who added that the company was ``not ready to
talk about'' whether there would be a price for such services.
</P>
<P>
   Random House is going through the first round of examining its
out-of-stock titles, which could be brought back to life in digital
form and printed with the new technology, said Erik Engstrom,
president and chief operating officer for Random House.
</P>
<P>
   The company has a backlist of more than 20,000 titles, but
estimates that there are as many as 50,000 titles that are no
longer in stock that could be revived, Engstrom said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of this will be invisible to the reader,'' he added.
``The only thing a reader is interested in is whether they can find
a book or not. With this equipment, we'll have the ability to print
any book in our database whenever we want it. When we have this new
printer, we'll also have the ability to turn everything around
faster.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 2312EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
