<SLUG> BC-FOREMAN-SALTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALTON INC. PAYS $137.5 MILLION FOR GEORGE FOREMAN'S NAME
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (rk) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It looks as if George Foreman's association with hamburger
grills will last longer and pay better than his last comeback as a
prizefighter.
</P>
<P>
   Salton Inc., a maker of housewares, said Thursday it would pay
$137.5 million in cash and stock for worldwide rights to use the
former heavyweight boxing champion's name and image to sell
food-preparation products, including indoor and outdoor grills. The
company said it would give Foreman and two business partners shares
of Salton worth $23.5 million and five annual cash payments of
$22.75 million.
</P>
<P>
   Foreman will receive about 75 percent of the payout, which is
structured as a long-term capital gain to reduce the sellers' tax
liability, said Peter Schaeffer, an analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette. He estimated that Foreman's total income from his
association with Salton will exceed $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   Foreman, who started out as a scowling sourpuss in the ring, has
carved out a lucrative second career as a large, lovable pitchman
since he returned to boxing in 1987 after a 10-year hiatus. After
34 more fights, including an improbable victory in a world
heavyweight title bout when he was 45, Foreman, now 50, retired
again two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, he has appeared in TV ads for Meineke mufflers
and Pepsi, as well as infomercials for Salton's Lean Mean Grilling
Machine. ``He's not fighting, but he's a pretty popular guy,''
William Rue, Salton's president, said. ``He's been very
instrumental in the company's growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The line of products Salton sells under the Foreman name has
become the company's biggest source of revenue, said Leon Driemann,
Salton's chief executive. As part of the agreement, Foreman will
``continue to assist us in our marketing effort,'' Driemann said.
</P>
<P>
   Driemann said he expected the agreement to add ``significantly''
to the company's earnings because Salton will no longer have to pay
60 percent of the profits from the sale of Foreman appliances to
Foreman and his partners. Driemann said that under the agreement,
which is expected to close in the first quarter of 2000, the
company, which is based in Mount Prospect, Ill., will not pay
royalties on sales of the Foreman products starting last July.
</P>
<P>
   Salton's earnings will get a lift this quarter when the company
reverses more than $16 million in expenses it booked last quarter
for royalties on the Foreman products, Schaeffer said. In addition,
not having to pay royalties on sales during the holiday season
should add $20 million more to Salton's operating profit this
quarter, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schaeffer, the analyst, said that sales of the Foreman grills
started slowly in 1995 and amounted to only about $5 million in
1996. Then they soared to $200 million in 1998, making them one of
the best-selling lines of small kitchen appliances on the market,
he said. He estimated that they account for about 37 percent of
Salton's sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 2312EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
