<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4863 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EMAIL-AD-COLUMN-2TAKE     12-09 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMAIL-AD-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: RUSH TO CAPITALIZE ON INTERNET ADVERTISING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You usually don't want to stand in the way of
agencies rushing to complete deals before the end of the year. That
is even more true this month because the urge to capitalize on the
frenzy for interactive advertising, marketing and media is spurring
deal makers to finish up in, well, Internet time.
</P>
<P>
   That is being demonstrated by three agreements to make
investments in e-mail marketing services, interactive agencies and
software by two agency giants, Interpublic Group of Cos. in New
York and Cordiant Communications Group in London.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail marketing deal brings together E-Dialog in Lexington,
Mass., founded in 1996, with Interpublic, the world's No. 1 agency
company in billings at $37.7 billion, according to the trade
publication Advertising Age, and No. 2 in revenue at $4.3 billion.
E-Dialog, which specializes in digital direct marketing services
like sending commercialized e-mail messages _ some with e-commerce
capabilities _ to consumers and businesses, is forming a strategic
partnership with Interpublic.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership is to be announced formally Friday morning by
Philip H. Geier Jr., chairman and chief executive of Interpublic,
at a presentation at the 27th annual PaineWebber Media Conference
in midtown Manhattan. Interpublic will act as a venture capitalist,
making an unspecified investment in E-Dialog along with two venture
capital firms, Commonwealth Capital and One Liberty Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for us to pair up with agencies,'' said John
Rizzi, president and chief executive at E-Dialog, because ``it's a
way to differentiate us from other e-mail marketing providers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our future,'' he added, ``is not just our relationship with
our clients,'' which include CDNow, Doubleday, Lycos, Major League
Baseball and the National Football League, ``but to add to our
business through agencies.'' Interpublic agencies include
Carmichael Lynch, Draft Worldwide, the Lowe Group and the
McCann-Erickson World Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll put E-Dialog together with our agencies,'' said Gil
Fuchsberg, vice president for new media and technology at
Interpublic, ``when clients tell us: `My Web banner ads are not
working. What other ways are there to get response?'''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail marketing is booming despite complaints from some
computer users and privacy advocates who denounce the practice as
disseminating spam, or unwanted e-mail. To counter that, many
advertisers send e-mail ads only to consumers who agree to receive
cyberpitches, a process known as opt-in e-mail or permission-based
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Permission is important,'' Rizzi agreed, ``but our focus is in
precision, sending mail from some company you have an affinity or
relationship with, so you're delighted to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Rizzi cited a campaign last summer for
Ticketmaster/CitySearch, a unit of USA Networks Inc., centered on
sending a series of three unsolicited e-mail messages to people who
bought tickets to Bruce Springsteen concerts in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first e-mail was to thank you for your order,'' Rizzi
said, ``the second provided directions to the arena and your seat,
and the third, sent the morning after the concert, included the
playlist from the night before _ with every song a link to buying
the CD on which the song appears, plus show merchandise for sale
like T-shirts and programs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty-seven percent of those who opened the mail clicked to
something,'' he added, ``and in the best scenarios, 20 percent of
them bought something.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal in the realm of interactive agencies also involves
Interpublic, which is bundling many _ but not all _ of its
interests in shops devoted to online advertising, design and
consulting services into a unit named Zentropy Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Zentropy is starting with almost 500 employees at 11 offices in
five countries handling accounts with annual revenue estimated at
more than $50 million from clients like Coca-Cola, General Motors,
Johnson &AMP; Johnson, Lucent Technologies and Microsoft. The name
comes from Zentropy Inc., an interactive agency in Los Angeles and
New York in which Interpublic took a minority stake in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   To form Zentropy Partners, Interpublic is now taking a majority
stake in Zentropy Inc. and folding in two other interactive
agencies it acquired last year. They are Digital Cafe in
Minneapolis and MDEO in Lyon, France, and Paris. That will make
Interpublic the owner of what Barry Linsky, senior vice president
for planning and business development at Interpublic, described as
``a substantial majority'' of Zentropy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zentropy will be independent,'' he added, ``but closely
aligned with Interpublic.'' Zentropy will work with McCann-Erickson
in areas like international expansion plans.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Zentropy resembles Communicade, a unit formed by
the Omnicom Group in New York to manage the minority and majority
stakes it owns in interactive agencies like Agency.com and
Razorfish. And trade publications have reported that Interpublic as
well as Omnicom may be considering initial public offerings of
Internet operations.
</P>
<P>
   But there is an important difference: the interactive operations
of several Interpublic agencies are also becoming part of Zentropy.
By comparison, the interactive units of Omnicom agencies like the
DDB Worldwide Communications Group are not part of Communicade.
</P>
<P>
   The units joining Zentropy are Anderson &AMP; Lembke Interactive in
San Francisco; Hill, Holliday Interactive, part of Hill, Holliday,
Connors, Cosmopulos in Boston and New York; Shandwick Interactive
in London, Minneapolis and St. Louis, part of Shandwick
International; and Thunder House in Frankfurt, Germany, and New
York, part of McCann-Erickson.
</P>
<P>
   John Connors III, 32, senior vice president and managing
director at Hill, Holliday Interactive, will be chief executive at
Zentropy, which is based in Cambridge, Mass. Ryan Magnussen,
co-founder of Zentropy Inc., will be president at Zentropy.
</P>
<P>
   The formation of Zentropy was reported Thursday by The Wall
Street Journal. But in a description of the scheduled Interpublic
presentation in a booklet distributed on Monday by PaineWebber, the
list of speakers identified Connors by his Zentropy title rather
than by his title at Hill, Holliday Interactive.
</P>
<P>
   Oops!
</P>
<P>
   Not all Interpublic interactive interests are being included in
Zentropy, Linsky said, because ``we're not dictating `One size fits
all' or saying everyone has to avail themselves of it.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, the interactive unit of Lowe Lintas &AMP; Partners, a
division of the Lowe Group, will remain separate from Zentropy. The
unit, bearing the interim name Lowe Lintas Interactive, is being
formed by the merger of the digital operations of two Interpublic
agencies that themselves have already merged: Ammirati Puris Lintas
and Lowe &AMP; Partners Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe Lintas Interactive _ the result of the combination of Lowe
Interactive and APL Digital _ will be led by Dan Goodman, 26, as
managing director; he had been director of Lowe Interactive. Lowe
Lintas Interactive will have 43 employees in New York and San
Francisco working on accounts with billings for 2000 estimated at
$50 million from clients like Eddie Bauer, Heineken, Lego, Mapquest
and Unilever.
</P>
<P>
   Also remaining separate from Zentropy is Icon Medialab
International in Stockholm, Sweden, in which Interpublic owns a 20
percent stake. Icon is the largest independent Internet services
and consulting company in Europe and agreed last month to acquire
Nicholson NY, an electronic business development company.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to the deal involving Cordiant, that agency company,
which owns shops like Bates Worldwide, is acquiring Interactive
Edge in New York, which develops software for marketers like
Colgate-Palmolive, Johnson &AMP; Johnson, Nabisco and Warner-Lambert.
</P>
<P>
   Cordiant is paying a combination of cash and stock valued at
$6.1 million for Interactive Edge, whose software enables sales
forces to present data to retailers in ways intended to help
stimulate sales of name-brand packaged goods. The deal calls for an
additional payment of up to $19 million in stock considerations
based on the financial performance of Interactive Edge.
</P>
<P>
   Interactive Edge, which will become an autonomous unit of the
141 Worldwide division of Cordiant, has about 20 employees. Zel
Bianco, 44, will continue as chief executive.
</P>
</TEXT>
