<SLUG> BC-MASS-FIREFIGHTERS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORCESTER MOURNS FALLEN FIREFIGHTERS  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada, Ind., Conn.)  (CORRECTS number of widows and children in 10th graf) 
 (See related stories from The Boston Globe:
WORCESTER-MEMORIAL-BOS, WORCESTER-SC-BOS, WORCESTER-COMMENT-BOS,
WORCESTER-TRAGEDY-BOS. For questions about these stories, call
Frank Perrotta at the Globe, 617-929-2597.) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT5-10 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ The streets of this grief-stricken city
became a winding stream of mourners Thursday morning as thousands
of firefighters led a three-mile procession to honor six of their
own, killed last week while battling a fire in an abandoned
warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   The sky was cloudless, but smoke still billowed from that
windowless building.
</P>
<P>
   Even as President Clinton and a host of politicians eulogized
the firefighters at a service in the Worcester Centrum, an arena in
the heart of downtown, dozens of firefighters and search dogs
continued to sift through the rubble of the warehouse for the
bodies of four of the firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your men are ours,'' Clinton told those at the service. ``Our
whole country honors them and you. We grieve with you, and we will
stay with you.''
</P>
<P>
   A homeless couple, who the authorities believe may have
accidentally started the fire when they knocked over a candle, are
being held on $1 million bail; both have pleaded not guilty to
charges of involuntary manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   In this blue-collar city, where nearly everyone seems to have
some connection to a firefighter, the tight fraternity of
firefighters was on full display. The streets, lined deep on both
sides with an estimated 25,000 spectators, were eerily quiet, the
silence broken only by the dirge of bagpipes and snares.
</P>
<P>
   Parents propped their children on their shoulders. A long row of
construction workers stood at the end of the procession route,
yellow hard hats tucked under their arms. The Boston Fire
Department led the procession, bearing flags of Ireland and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters came from as far as Halifax, Nova Scotia, and Fort
Wayne, Ind., and an Amtrak train full of firefighters arrived from
Connecticut early in the morning. Some came to march in their dress
uniforms, others to fill the memorial service in the Centrum, still
others who could not get in to watch the service on big-screen TVs
inside the pubs lining Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope by our collective presence we will speak louder than
words and say your tragedy is ours,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, the six firefighters left five widows and 17
children.
</P>
<P>
   While struggling with their grief, many city residents expressed
compassion for the two squatters who fled from a burning building.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when cities nationwide have imposed new measures
against the homeless, there was little clamor here for punishment
of the homeless in general, or the accused couple in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made a mistake,'' said Fred Stone, 43, a telemarketer who
had come to watch the firefighters dig through the rubble late
Wednesday night. ``They're not responsible for the deaths of six
firefighters. You have to put yourself in a homeless person's body.
You're going to find a place to go and you're going to build a
fire. It's the nature of people to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a few here seemed to know the pair. Thomas S. Levesque, 37,
rolled a shopping cart every day, foraging for cans. His
girlfriend, Julie S. Barnes, 19, is three months pregnant,
according to her lawyer. Both volunteered at a soup kitchen called
the Mustard Seed, and Levesque tried repeatedly to find jobs,
recalled another volunteer, Michele Sampson. On Thursday Ms.
Sampson, who is also homeless, said she planned to write to the
couple in jail and offer to care for the baby they are expecting.
</P>
<P>
   Worcester, once a hub of textile plants and wiremaking
factories, has been struggling to reinvent itself. Its population
has declined steadily in the last three decades to about 166,000
today. Its gleaming downtown has a new outlet mall and the Centrum
arena. The old railroad station, with its elaborate white domes,
has been renovated. But just on the edge of downtown is the swath
of old warehouses and narrow streets lined with auto repair shops
and butcher shops _ still busy with daytime traffic but also
natural resting place for the homeless at night.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. John A. Coonan, the pastor of St. John's Church, a
stone's throw from the abandoned warehouse, says pointedly that
only after nearby Union Station, a once dilapidated train station
where dozens of homeless slept every night, closed for renovations
did buildings like the warehouse where the firefighters died,
Worcester Cold Storage, become regular dormitories for the
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   The roughly 1,000 shelter beds in the city have all been
occupied since summer. ``I believe to the core of my being that we
are all responsible for that fire,'' said Coonan. ``Worcester has
not seriously taken on the challenge of homelessness.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It was well known that homeless people squatted in the Worcester
Cold Storage building. That is why firefighters raced in on Friday
night, thinking someone might be trapped inside. No one was. The
homeless couple fled the building and failed to report the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Some had little sympathy for the couple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to hear no excuses,'' fumed Dian Germain, 40, a
waitress who stood in front of the Central Fire Station Thursday
morning for the procession. ``That's all they had to do _ say there
was nobody in the building.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, firefighters have repeatedly said in recent days that
their job was not to pass judgment against the people who are
accused, but to find the bodies of all those who perished. In the
last few days, as food and drink has poured into local fire
stations, some of it has been passed on to homeless shelters.
</P>
<P>
   So far, firefighters have retrieved only the bodies of Timothy
Jackson, 51, and James Lyons, 34. Still missing are Paul
Brotherton, 41, Jeremiah Lucey, 38, Joseph McGuirk, 38, and Thomas
Spencer, 42.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Thursday evening, a visibly exhausted deputy chief of the
Worcester Fire Department, Gerry Dio, said the search had yielded
no new clues. Fire officials said they had combed through about 50
to 60 percent of the five-story brick building, a thickly insulated
catacomb where cattle carcasses and hamburger patties were stored.
They vowed to find the other four bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like Day One because everyone's not out,'' said Jim
Sweeney, a firefighter from nearby Auburn, who has helped with the
search since Friday. ``We're trying to get closure. Everyone's got
to come home.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For them, a fire truck parked near the Cold Storage building has
been transformed into a shrine, literally shrouded with bouquets of
mums and carnations, poems and letters. All day and all night, it
has drawn visitors and it has reduced burly men to tears. There is
a collage with painted hearts and sad faces, a wreath from the
Worcester AIDS project and a framed Fire Wife's Prayer.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is this deeply personal letter from a
sixth-grader named Laurencia. She writes of a father she has not
seen since she was 5. ``At least I do know he is alive, she writes.
``But still I feel like I have lost my father too just like those
15 children.''
</P>
</TEXT>
