<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DON'T-ASK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: REJECTING `DON'T ASK, DON'T TELL' 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Dec. 10:
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton was exactly right when she told a gay
audience at a fund-raiser in New York City this week that
homosexuals ought to be able to serve openly in the U.S. military.
That is the position her husband held when he campaigned for
president, promising to issue an executive order to end the
Department of Defense's ban on homosexuals in the armed forces. But
in 1993 the new president allowed opposition in Congress and the
Pentagon to drive him to an ill-conceived compromise, the ``don't
ask, don't tell'' policy.
</P>
<P>
   In her remarks on Tuesday, the first lady said her husband's
policy had been a failure, and that is an understatement. ``Don't
ask, don't tell'' has led to increased harassment of homosexuals
and doubling in the number of discharges of gay service members. It
has also turned barracks life into a grotesque trap for many gay
men and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing brings that fact into harsher focus than the murder of
Army Pfc. Barry Winchell of the 101st Airborne Division at Fort
Campbell, Ky., in July. For weeks, while his company sergeant
looked on and did nothing, Winchell endured daily sexual taunts and
harassment from his barracks mates. When he finally beat his chief
tormentor in a fistfight, that man, Pvt. Calvin Glover, retaliated
by beating him to death with a baseball bat two nights later as he
slept in his bunk.
</P>
<P>
   As in other cases when Mrs. Clinton has criticized her husband's
policies, the politics here are plain. Her prospective opponent in
the 2000 Senate race, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, has been critical of
the Pentagon policy. To continue to support the failed policy would
have hampered her ability to compete with Giuliani for New York
City's influential gay voters. In an odd campaign twist, Mrs.
Clinton may have subsequently damaged her standing with those same
voters by saying Thursday that she would march in the St. Patrick's
Day Parade. That event is shunned by many Democratic politicians
because the parade's organizers exclude the Irish Gay and Lesbian
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the parade remark turns into a serious gaffe, the
clarity of Mrs. Clinton's new position on the ``don't ask, don't
tell'' policy is encouraging. So was the verdict of the martial
jury at Fort Campbell, which on Wednesday found Glover guilty of
premeditated murder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
