</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BINGHAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT BINGHAM: YOUNG, RICH, TALENTED AND HIGHLY COMBUSTIBLE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky., R.I., Mass.)   By TINA KELLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Robert Bingham's wedding six months ago, like his
life, was a mixture of two worlds. When the heir of the
well-chronicled, contentious Southern newspaper family married
Vanessa Scharven Chase at a historic farmhouse in Princeton, N.J.,
the understated fragrance of taste and privilege prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the reception. ``Everyone ambled over to the barn, and
the next thing you knew you were in the middle of an incredible,
spontaneous rock show,'' said Henry P. Davis, 34, who was the best
man for his friend from boarding school. The rock band Pavement
played, with other musicians joining in. Bingham and Dean Wareham,
from the band Luna, sang ``Sweet Child o' Mine'' to the bride.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, Wareham sang that Guns 'n' Roses song, alone, at
Bingham's memorial service on Park Avenue. A promising fiction
writer whose first novel is scheduled for publication by Doubleday
Broadway in May, he died Nov. 28 in his loft in TriBeCa, after what
one law enforcement official said apparently was a heroin overdose.
He was 33.
</P>
<P>
   From the accounts of friends and partners in his artistic
pursuits, Bingham lived hard, wrote hard, and was admired for
sharing the benefits of his birthright with the city's artistic and
literary community and with other philanthropic projects around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   His life was full of adventures that almost begged to be written
about: spilling secrets about family campaign contributions during
a martini-drinking contest, distributing $100 bills after a
Kentucky Derby tip paid off, sleeping from Sunday night until
Tuesday after reporting about the wedding of a Khmer Rouge
general's daughter in the riskier reaches of Cambodia. His
interests ranged from archaeology to tennis (played fiercely) to
collecting Zippo lighters.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath, there was a sadness fueling his creativity: the death
of his father when the writer was 4 months old, the loss of the
chance to lead the family business, a battle with alcohol and
addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was always such a struggle for Robbie,'' Thomas Beller,
co-editor of Open City, a literary magazine Bingham published, said
at the memorial service at Calvary Episcopal Church. ``But it was
exhilarating to be around that struggle. It was perplexing, but it
was also somehow inspiring, because I always felt that part of what
he was wrestling with was the truth, the truth about people and
society and himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bingham lived just a few blocks from John F. Kennedy Jr.,
and some cannot help but see similarities between their families.
Alex S. Jones, who chronicled the Bingham family's epic
disagreements and eventual decision to sell their newspapers, The
Courier-Journal and The Louisville Times, called the family the
Kennedys of Kentucky, in that they were liberal, glamorous,
powerful and public spirited.
</P>
<P>
   Bingham continued that tradition and apparently redirected his
disappointment in the papers' sale into a more artistic,
philanthropic career. Besides backing the literary magazine, he
published a book of David Berman, a poet whose work he admired, and
was known for supporting innovative performances, Web sites and
documentary films.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, he wrote stories with vivid descriptions of the
lives of privileged, dissolute people his age. Comparisons were
made to F. Scott Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of Tom and Daisy Buchanan's offspring, but with more
than two wits to rub together,'' said Geoffrey Wolff, a fiction
writer, about ``Pure Slaughter Value,'' Bingham's 1997 collection
of short stories.
</P>
<P>
   Bingham was the son of Worth Bingham, assistant publisher of the
family papers, who died at 34, hit in the head by the surfboard he
was carrying in a convertible, during a drive with his family.
Robert Bingham's mother, Joan Bingham, is executive editor of
Grove/Atlantic Press, the New York publishing house. He grew up in
the Dakota apartment building in Manhattan, attended Dalton and St.
Bernard's.
</P>
<P>
   He worked as an intern at The Courier-Journal while in high
school, and is remembered there for his inquisitiveness and humor,
and for getting arrested for urinating on the bushes in front of
the police station. He headed to boarding school.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff, who taught Bingham in a writing class at Brown
University, remembered one tender autobiographical essay from
Bingham's senior year. ``He wrote about his family with wide-open
candor, but without anger or contempt,'' he said. ``He was, by God,
courageous, recklessly courageous on the page.''
</P>
<P>
   He also was known for taking other kinds of risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robbie always went one step closer to the edge,'' his sister,
Clara, said at the memorial. ``He hated the false, the easy, the
conventional. Robbie was fearless of the scary things in life, but
in his deepest heart he was vulnerable and afraid. He was tormented
by our father's death and by his own struggle with addiction.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, after brief stints at The New York Post and
The Tennesseean, he traveled frequently to Cambodia, where he
worked for The Cambodia Daily as the newspaper was setting up shop
in the attic of a hotel.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 26, Bingham's first piece of short fiction was
published in The New Yorker. In it the narrator, a man in his 20s
who has yet to discover what to do with his life, attends a funeral
for his young first cousin, who had apparently died of a drug
overdose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I, for one, had not died yet, and I felt good and healthy
driving down a safe street on a beautiful day in the shelter of
suburban Far Hills,'' he wrote. After the wake, the narrator goes
off in the woods with a bottle of Jack Daniels, some pot, and his
cousin's sister. They drink. They smoke. They kiss. Everyone goes
home.
</P>
<P>
   His collection of stories skirt between moral vigilance and
self-destruction. In them, rich Hamptonites try to seduce their
maid, a honeymooning couple decides to kill an obnoxious skier, and
people dress in the clothes of their dead relatives.
</P>
<P>
   After the collection's publication, New York magazine published
a profile of Bingham, saying, ``word for word he may be New York's
finest writer about New York.'' In it, he told the interviewer: ``I
think everyone has to manage their death drive, their will to
destroy themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Bingham threw late-running parties at his loft,
where people had to buy a copy of the magazine for admission.
``They were always incredibly fun, and incredibly populated,'' said
Elizabeth Schmidt, senior editor with Open City magazine. ``He was
a draw for so many people.''
</P>
<P>
   In between trips to Cambodia and beyond, he wrote his novel,
even though working on it felt like ``standing at the starting line
of a marathon, smoking,'' he wrote to one friend.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Vanessa Chase, found Bingham dead on the floor of
their bathroom the Sunday after Thanksgiving. A couple of empty
glassine envelopes were found next to him, the police said. The
medical examiner has yet to rule on the exact cause of death.
</P>
<P>
   Those who worked with Bingham professionally said that anyone
with a serious drug problem could not have written, revised or
edited as well and intensively as he did.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they spoke of an open-hearted and charismatic man.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went a very wrong way, and he knew he was in trouble, you
know, recently,'' said Jesdale, Bingham's high school coach, who
had kept in contact with him. ``You know Rob, for me, will always
be this wonderful kid who had this incredible burn to be excellent,
and was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
