<HEADER>
A4878 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a `LOSTSQUADRON'STORYASNOW     12-09 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 `LOST SQUADRON' STORY A SNOW JOB  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE WILSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a frigid tale fit for a nippy day across Arizona. It's
about the ``Lost Squadron,'' a group of eight American planes lost
in a storm over Greenland during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   As told by Robert Balling, an Arizona State University climate
expert, the story would seem to debunk claims of global warming and
melting ice in the Northern Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   I'd describe it as something else: a good snow job.
</P>
<P>
   On July 15, 1942, U.S. pilots were flying two B-17 Flying
Fortresses and six P-38 Lightnings from Greenland to England when
bad weather forced them to ditch the planes on Greenland's icecap.
All 25 crewmen survived, but the planes were lost.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, several expeditions searched for the aircraft,
estimating they would be found below about 40 feet of snow and ice.
But when they were finally located with the help of subsurface
radar in 1988, the planes were 268 feet below the surface. With the
help of hot water cannons, one of the P-38s, dubbed ``Glacier
Girl,'' was brought up piece by piece in 1992 and is being
restored.
</P>
<P>
   If reports of global warming and shrinking ice sheets are true,
Balling asks in a Web site article, why were the planes buried so
deeply?
</P>
<P>
   ``If those planes were sentient, they would find it hard to
believe all these apocalyptic stories about melting icecaps,'' he
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He goes on to cite temperature records for that area of
Greenland that show a cooling of 2.25 degrees Fahrenheit during the
50 years before the P-38 was recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike much of Balling's work, this story was not published in a
peer-reviewed journal, and for good reason. As he concedes, a large
inland accumulation of ice and snow over a half-century doesn't
prove anything about the overall state of Greenland's ice sheet.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, global warming theory predicts more precipitation as
temperatures rise, and recent studies have found significant
melting in the Great White North. The evidence includes:
</P>
<P>
   A report by Norwegian researchers in the journal Science using
satellite data that show Arctic ice diminished 14 percent in the
past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   A study relying on sonar data from nuclear submarines that found
the floating ice cover in the Arctic Ocean was 40 percent thinner
than 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   An article in the current issue of Science that examined five
different sets of data and concluded that sea ice in the Northern
Hemisphere declined 7 percent in the past 46 years.
</P>
<P>
   A finding by the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
that several edges of Greenland's ice sheet have lost 3 to 6 feet
in thickness per year since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   One of the nation's best-known global warming critics, Balling
has published 103 peer-reviewed articles, including dozens on
greenhouse gases and warming. The ``Lost Squadron'' story, however,
was written for the Greening Earth Society, a creation of the
Western Fuels Association. Both organizations dispute that fossil
fuels have harmed the global environment.
</P>
<P>
   Because much of his work has been funded by fossil-fuel groups,
Balling has been called a rent-a-scientist who's in bed with the
industry. He says none of his work has been compromised and notes
that his largest current grant, $500,000, came from the National
Science Foundation. He disagrees that government-funded research is
more pure than industry-funded research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, it all goes through peer-review, and anything
industry-funded is likely to be held to a higher standard,'' he
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Balling correctly warns that people shouldn't leap to
conclusions based on any single study. He points out that ice
masses are constantly thinning and thickening, and the net change
isn't easy to measure. Any warming, he contends, could be the
result of increased solar output just as likely as human activity.
</P>
<P>
   We should be skeptical of ``bold, simplistic pronouncements
about global warming,'' Balling says, and he's right.
</P>
<P>
   We should be no less skeptical of glib anecdotes from Greenland
more likely to mislead than inform. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
