<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-REVIEWS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIZMOS GALORE GIVE `GADGET' A CARTOON FLAVOR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `INSPECTOR GADGET'
</P>
<P>
   Disney hasn't just been remaking its '60s hits (``The Parent
Trap,'' ``That Darn Cat,'' ``101 Dalmatians''). It's also been
cobbling them for re-inventions.
</P>
<P>
   The gizmos and guffaws of its ``Merlin Jones'' movies are what
propel ``Inspector Gadget'' _ along with '80s cartoons of the same
name, which in turn took the premise of the '70s TV show ``The Six
Million Dollar Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Broderick plays the title character, a cop wannabe who's
injured in an explosion. To repair his body, he's fitted with a
wild array of crime-fighting gadgets, enabling him to fly, stretch
his arms and spew streams of icky toothpaste as a public protector.
</P>
<P>
   What ensues is a bigger barrage of computer effects than were in
evidence in ``The Haunting.'' ``Gadget'' is as close to a
live-action cartoon as it gets _ even to the point of having
animated stars swirl around a guy who's knocked on the noggin.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the performances are broad, the dialogue is corny
(``Oh, for crying out loud!''), and the humor hinges on slapstick
stunts.
</P>
<P>
   While this fanciful fun is kid-geared at the expense of adults,
Gadget also is afflicted with a taint of today's pop culture.
</P>
<P>
   That is to say, kids are mature and sophisticated, while adults
behave like kids _ or do you truly think the stars of ``Ally
McBeal'' and ``Friends'' are acting their ages?
</P>
<P>
   Heck, even the bickering barristers of ``The Practice'' would
rather engage in infantile shouting matches (often sounding like
``Did not!'' ``Did, too!'') than exchange ideas.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``Gadget,'' its only real kid is Michelle Trachtenberg
(``Harriet the Spy'') as Broderick's sensible niece.
</P>
<P>
   His love interest and the gadgets' inventor is Joely Fisher, who
looks uncannily like Broderick's real-life wife, Sarah Jessica
Parker.
</P>
<P>
   Broderick is earnest, warm and bland as our hero. He's far more
fun as Gadget's evil clone, a wild man with capped teeth.
</P>
<P>
   But Rupert Everett is wasted as the dapper villain, merely aping
his looniness in ``Dunston Checks In'' (a better kid flick).
</P>
<P>
   Here, he's so hammy you expect to hear oinks, and he also adopts
the film's witless childishness. If anything, Everett is the
biggest kid of all.
</P>
<P>
   At least the film has clever opening credits _ and some
surprises for those who stick around for the end credits. At only
78 minutes, even an adult's attention span should allow that.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 1/2 stars.
</P>
<P>
   1999, PG, Disney, CC, VHS $24.99, DVD $29.99
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`A MIDSUMMER NIGHT'S DREAM' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rupert Everett fares a bit better in this latest adaptation of
Shakespeare's romantic comedy _ a bit, but not much.
</P>
<P>
   He's among an outstanding cast, along with Kevin Kline, Michelle
Pfeiffer, Stanley Tucci and David Strathairn. (As for Calista
Flockhart, she's out of her league.)
</P>
<P>
   But for all its visual splendors (with early-1900s Italy the
setting) and its sprinkling of fairy dust, this tale is choppy and
ponderous, with an ensemble of stars who don't really gel.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 stars.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; 1999, PG-13, Fox, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $34.98
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DVD DOINGS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Disney and Pixar made the right call with ``Toy Story 2.''
Unlike animated sequels to ``The Lion King'' and ``Pocahontas,'' it
went straight to theaters _ not video _ where it's setting
box-office records.
</P>
<P>
   But the franchise's picture still looks bright on video, where
the original ``Toy Story'' has sold 22 million copies on tape.
</P>
<P>
   The oddity is that it's still not on DVD, unlike Pixar's ``A
Bug's Life,'' which followed ``Toy Story'' in theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually (''Toy Story``) will be on DVD,'' said director
John Lasseter, who also helmed the sequel and ``A Bug's Life.''
``But we're really adamant about the digital transfer being just
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Seems like they could have been ``really adamant'' about ``Toy
Story'' for DVD before ``A Bug's Life.'' At any rate, Lasseter says
Pixar is busy ``restoring'' it for a digital transfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toy Story'' does exist on the fading laserdisc format, where
it has what Lasseter calls ``a wonderful deluxe edition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Bug's Life'' also just got such an edition on DVD, adding
many more extras than its first DVD release. The latter costs
around $24, with the deluxe edition around $35.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``Toy Story 2,'' it could reach tape, at least, as early
as April. ``A Bug's Life'' appeared on tape and DVD last April,
after opening in theaters the previous Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   In other Disney news, ``The Jungle Book'' and ``The Little
Mermaid'' arrive on DVD for a suggested $39.99.
</P>
<P>
   (Does anyone pay such a price? You can find them online for
under $24.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`LOVE' REDUCED &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare in Love'' drops to $22.99 this week on VHS and
gains a deluxe DVD edition for $39.99.
</P>
<P>
   Also on disc are two vintage horror flicks from Elite: 1972's
``Tower of Evil'' and 1973's ``Horror Hospital,'' both $24.95. The
latter has Michael Gough, now in ``Sleepy Hollow.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
VIDEO RATINGS &QL; 
4 stars _ Excellent &QL; 
3 stars _ Good &QL; 
2 stars _Fair &QL; 
1 star _ Poor &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
