A4885 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a WITNESSESPLEADFORFALA     12-09 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
TER'S LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 WITNESSES PLEAD FOR FALA (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 By JERRY KAMMER 
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  Phoenix - Former co-workers, rela
tives and friends implored a judge Thursday not to end Scott
Falater's life, which they said was exemplary until that bizarre
night in 1997 when he stabbed his wife to death.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``He was the most compassionate, caring boss that I've ever
had,'' said Wyvaughna Mullins, a shipping clerk at Motorola, where
Falater was an electronics engineer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always the calm, level-headed one,'' said Michael
Vines, who befriended Scott and Yarmila Falater 20 years ago when
the couple were living in Illinois. ``He just had the greatest
heart of any man, I think, I have known.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullins and Vines were two of 11 witnesses who testified on the
first day of a sentencing hearing for Falater, who was convicted in
June of first-degree murder. The 44-year-old father of two faces
the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-member jury rejected the defense claim that he was sleep
walking when he stabbed Yarmila dozens of times, dragged her into
the backyard pool and held her head underwater.
</P>
<P>
   Now, his fate is in the hands of Judge Ronald Reinstein, who is
weighing the circumstances of the crime before deciding from three
options: the death penalty, life with no chance for parole, or life
with the possibility of parole after 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Juan Martinez is attempt ing to convince Reinstein
that the murder meets the state death penalty standard because it
was ``especially heinous, cruel or depraved.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, defense attorneys Mi chael Kimerer and Lori Voepel
argue that the ``mitigating circumstances'' in Falater's life
should persuade Reinstein to impose the least severe sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez launched the hearing by guiding a county medical
examiner through a graphic description of the 44 stab wounds that
punctured Yarmila Falater's upper body with a hunting knife.
</P>
<P>
   The attack was so fierce that two of the wounds penetrated to
the hilt of the 5-inch blade, according to the testimony of Dr. Ann
Bucholtz.
</P>
<P>
   Bucholtz, spoke in calm, clinical terms, holding up autopsy
photos and explaining that the cause of death was ``multiple stab
wounds with asphyxiation.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez attempted to establish the attack's cruelty by arguing
that Falater left his wife to die while he returned to the house,
washed the blood from his hands and arms and stashed his crimsoned
clothes in the wheel well of his Volvo.
</P>
<P>
   After Bucholtz's testimony, defense attorneys began questioning
their 20 witnesses. The testimonials about Falater's character will
resume Mon day.
</P>
<P>
   All expressed bewilderment about the killing and disbelief that
Falater acted consciously that night, after having what his two
teenage children said at trial was a calm dinner at home. All urged
the judge to spare the life of a man whose son and daughter have
already lost their mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael and Megan adore this man, and they need him desper
ately,'' said Cheri Allen, who knows the family through Mormon
Church activities. She described Falater as ``a kind, devoted,
loving father.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez challenged all the defense witnesses. Some had only a
superfi cial acquaintanceship with the Fala ters, he said, and none
could truly understand what happened inside the Falater home.
</P>
<P>
   He said Falater was responsible for the suffering of Megan and
Michael, who were described by Falater's mother as ``devastated''
in the kill ing's aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said Thursday that the placid surface of the Falater
home concealed tensions and turmoil seething beneath.
</P>
<P>
   He described Yarmila as a strong-willed, independent woman who
re sented a church to which her hus band was devoted. He suggested
that Yarmila was weighing a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   But the defense witnesses said they saw no indication of
domestic stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was crazy about her,'' Allen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
