<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-09 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4886 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-JACKSON-NYT &LR;      12-09 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-JACKSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM JACKSON DIES AT 80; LAWYER WITH WIDE CLIENTELE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Eldred Jackson, a New York lawyer with an international
clientele that included Nelson Rockefeller, Jacqueline Kennedy
Onassis, the king of Morocco and Baron Hans Heinrich
Thyssen-Bornemisza, died on Saturday at his home on the Upper East
Side of Manhattan. He was 80 and also had a home in Cold Spring
Harbor, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was throat cancer, a family spokesman said. He said
Jackson had continued to go to his office until last week.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson came to the law as a personal assistant to his father,
Robert H. Jackson, an associate justice of the Supreme Court
appointed by President Franklin Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Jackson, a native of Jamestown, N.Y., was first in
his class at St. Albans School in Washington and graduated Phi Beta
Kappa in 1941 from Yale University, where he was vice chairman of
The Yale Daily News. He was an editor of the Harvard Law Review and
got his LL.B there in 1944.
</P>
<P>
   He then was a lieutenant in the Navy until 1946. William Jackson
followed Robert Jackson to Germany when his father, on a leave of
absence, was America's chief counsel for the prosecution at the
Nuremberg trial of major Nazi war criminals. As a staff member,
private secretary and law clerk, William Jackson took part in the
interrogation of Hermann Goering, Rudolf Hess and Albert Speer. He
was co-editor of the eight volumes of trial evidence printed by the
American government.
</P>
<P>
   In 1947, he joined the Wall Street law firm of Milbank, Tweed,
Hadley &AMP; McCloy, specializing in civil litigation, including
arbitration, as well as antitrust actions and international legal
disputes. He became a partner in 1954 and was a consulting partner
at his death.
</P>
<P>
   He was the personal lawyer for Gov. Nelson Rockefeller of New
York in 1974, when President Gerald Ford picked Rockefeller as his
vice president after the Watergate scandal; he counseled
Rockefeller at his confirmation hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson represented Mrs. Onassis in her negotiations with the
Onassis estate after the Greek shipping magnate, Aristotle, her
second husband, died in 1975. He also advised Baron
Thyssen-Bornemisza, the Swiss industrialist, in the intricate
international bargaining before he moved his fabled art collection
into its own museum, a stone's throw from the Prado Museum in
Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Jackson won two landmark Supreme Court cases for
the New York Stock Exchange that established guidelines for class
action cases in the securities industry. He was a past vice
chairman of the International Court of Arbitration in the
International Chamber of Commerce in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is survived by his wife of 55 years, Nancy Dabney
Roosevelt Jackson, a granddaughter of President Theodore Roosevelt;
five daughters, Miranda Hook of Fairfield, Conn., Melissa Morgan of
Cold Spring Harbor and Melanie Jackson, Melinda Kessler and Marina
Jackson, all of Manhattan; and five grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
