<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANDELA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANDELAS CHALLENGE THE NEXT GENERATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH SCHUBERT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Robed in black university gowns and topped with mortar
boards, Nelson Mandela and Graca Machel Thursday answered to the
next generation.
</P>
<P>
   In a convocation held at Seattle University, high school and
college students from around the region asked Mandela tough
questions about his support of Libya and Iran, his opinion of the
World Trade organization and his endurance through 27 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela, the former president of South Africa, and Machel, his
wife, stood on a dais flanked by college and university presidents
as they addressed a crowd of about 1,100.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at the end of the century and the millennium,'' Mandela
said. ``For those of us who have come (through) a long part of this
century, there is much cause for disappointment about what we
haven't been able to achieve. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``For you, the youth, the future beckons. It is now in your
hands to make the next century one in which the best of the human
spirit can truly triumph.''
</P>
<P>
   In his long struggle against apartheid in South Africa, Mandela
endured 27 years in prison, much of it in solitary confinement,
after being convicted of sabotage and conspiracy to overthrow the
government by revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Even in prison, however, Mandela worked to educate fellow
prisoners and maintained contact with the African National
Congress. He was released from jail in February 1990, to a hero's
welcome, was elected president of the Republic of South Africa in
1994 and went on to win the Nobel Peace Prize.
</P>
<P>
   Machel, the former minister of education in Mozambique, brought
the plight of children in war to the world's attention through a
groundbreaking report presented to the United Nations. She recently
became the first woman and first black to lead the University of
Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela and Machel were each presented with honorary associate
of arts degrees from Seattle Central Community College and
doctorates from Seattle University.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Seattle Central announced a $30,000 endowment, and
the University of Washington a $50,000 endowment, for new
scholarships named after Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   ``Couldn't you just feel the electricity in that room?'' said
Kirsten Anderson, a junior at Pacific Lutheran University, after
the convocation.
</P>
<P>
   With a nod of agreement, her friend Lindsay Daehlin added: ``It
was really great that he wanted to talk to the students.''
</P>
<P>
   For about 40 minutes, Mandela and Machel responded to prepared
question from students. Following are some of their comments:
</P>
<P>
   Mandela on why he's not special: ``It is a mistake to think that
I'm the only person who spent a long time in prison, in an
apartheid prison. There were many men and women, some of them who
deserve more credit than I do.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as becoming the first black to be elected president of
South Africa, it never occurred to me that one day I would have
that position. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the product of a collective leadership. It had no
significance to us who held a particular position because we were
placed there by a team of men and women who, under very difficult
circumstances, had triumphed to become a pathfinder in a new South
Africa. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I did did not generate from my brain or from my
spirit. It was something in which we all contributed.''
</P>
<P>
   Machel on AIDS: ``We need vaccines and we need to make vaccines
available to everyone. But we need to look at reality. Before
vaccines can be approved and tested, we have to get the message
across, because time is running against us. ... While the vaccine
doesn't come, please share your knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandela on the World Trade Organization: ``There are many
organizations in the world that have emerged which are an
expression of globalization. It is a process no country can avoid,
because today the things that take place in the People's Republic
of China immediately have an effect on South Africa, Morocco,
Seattle, and in other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The WTO) is an organization we all must support because it
has many advantages. But of course, we must take account of
reality. Power today is still monopolized by the West, and their
moral fabric leaves much to be desired. They use world trade in
order to make a maximum profit, not for humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandela on Cuba, Libya and Iran: ``There is no country anywhere
_ and I'm tempted to exaggerate and to say no force whatsoever in
the universe _ that can dictate to South Africa what it must do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The enemies of the United States are not our enemies, and if
the United States thinks they can dictate to South Africa, they are
living in dreamland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apart from the apartheid movement and certain far-seeing and
bold-minded Americans, the government of the United States
supported our oppressors, the apartheid regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuba, Libya and Iran gave us enormous support. It would be a
tragedy if, ... now that we are free, we are advised by the friends
of our former enemies to break all allegiance with those who helped
us when we were all alone. No proud freedom fighter will ever do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Machel on when it's time to rest: ``Since the time I was a young
girl in my village (in Mozambique), there are many things that have
changed for the good ... but there are so many other things which
are exactly the same as when I was born. How can we rest? ... How
can one afford to think that I have the right to rest?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
