<SLUG> BC-HKN-CANADIENS-ISLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENOUGH'S ENOUGH, CANADIENS TELL ISLES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JENNY KELLNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ It may be difficult to fathom, but in one
sense the Montreal Canadiens came into Thursday night's game at the
Nassau Coliseum in more desperate straits than the Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a marginally better record, the Canadiens had lost to
the Islanders twice, accounting for fully one-third of the Islander
victories this season.
</P>
<P>
   That must have been two too many for the Canadiens, who jumped
all over the Islanders' special teams Thursday night and emerged
with a 4-2 victory before 6,861 fans, stretching the home team's
losing streak to five games.
</P>
<P>
   It was also a record sixth straight home loss for the Islanders,
who have won two games in the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadiens, playing without Saku Koivu and Brian Savage, who
are both injured, jumped out to a 2-0 lead, courtesy of the first
of two goals from Martin Rucinsky, at 7 minutes 55 seconds, and the
first goal of the season by Benoit Brunet, at 11:24.
</P>
<P>
   With Mariusz Czerkawski in the penalty box for
obstruction-holding, Rucinsky skated across the blue line and took
a shot from 40 feet out that skipped off goalie Felix Potvin's
glove for the score, Rucinsky's 12th goal of the season. Brunet
made it 2-0 when he ferreted out the puck from a pile of Islanders
in front of the net and nudged it past the sprawled Potvin.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders did not get a shot off on their lone power play
chance of the period, but Tim Connolly kept them alive with a nice
play near the end of the period. Coming down the left side,
Connolly picked up the rebound of his own shot, scooted around the
back of the net and made a beautiful pass to the waiting Brad
Isbister, who put the puck in at 19:41 to cut the lead to 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadiens made it two of three on power-play opportunities
at 2:37 of the second period, with Sergei Zholtok scoring off the
odd-man rush for a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Orszsagh then brought the Islanders to within a goal
again at 10:06, coming up behind Josh Green as goaltender Jeff
Hackett kicked away his shot, picking up the rebound and neatly
putting the puck behind Hackett to make it 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders had two great chances to score early in the third
period, but Czerkawski's dead-on shot on a breakaway bounced
harmlessly off Hackett at 2:25 and Zdeno Chara's hard shot hit the
left post a minute later.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadiens put the game out of reach at 12:21 on Rucinsky's
second goal, scored past Potvin on his glove side after Shayne
Corson dug the puck out from the right corner, took it behind the
net and fed it to Rucinsky.
</P>
<P>
   With the win, which snapped a four-game streak without a
victory, the Canadiens extended their record to 10-17-2. The
Islanders, who went 0 for 5 on power plays, fell to 6-16-3.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-09-99 2342EST &QL; 
